<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-MAVERICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS BEAT MAVERICKS, 100-93 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Under the pressure of the moment, Allan Houston
revealed an unshakably smooth release with the Dallas Mavericks'
Michael Finley right in his whiskers down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Houston scored 31 points, including 8 on four consecutive
baseline jumpers in the last three and a half minutes of the game,
to give the Knicks a 100-93 triumph at Reunion Arena on Thursday
night and their fifth straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   As explosive as Houston was on offense, his energetic sidekick
on defense was Marcus Camby. He earned every one of his 34 minutes
by scoring 17 points, blocking 5 shots and grabbing 13 rebounds. In
the process, he took the burden off a languid Patrick Ewing, who
finished with 14 points and seemed a step behind most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   After three blocks in two minutes by Camby, topped off with a
3-pointer at the shot-clock buzzer by Latrell Sprewell, the Knicks
looked as if they were on their way to an easy finish to their
brief western swing. But the Mavs made a furious push in the end
with the help of some big rebounds to go on an 8-0 run and cut the
Knicks' lead to 86-84. That was when Houston turned on his touch
and hit four straight jumpers, three of which came over the tight
defense of Finley, who scored 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks won despite a 1-for-10 night from Larry Johnson and
just 15 points by Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was part of a first unit that was too lethargic in the
first quarter to keep up with the frenetic pace the Mavericks
established from the opening tip. It took the instant energy
provided by Camby and Chris Childs off the bench to keep the Knicks
in the game and tied with the Mavs at halftime, 43-43.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off his frisky performance in Houston on Tuesday, a flat
Ewing sat out most of the first half. After seven minutes of
watching Gary Trent spin by him in the lane, after seeing Ewing too
late to jump out on the perimeter and defend Dirk Nowitzki's
jumpers, Coach Jeff Van Gundy took him out and put Camby in.
</P>
<P>
   Camby never left the floor again in the first half. While
Sprewell was unable to stop Finley's fall-away jumpers and the
7-foot-6-inch Shawn Bradley was busy swatting Johnson's layups to
leave the Knicks' low-post threat 0 for 9 in the first half, Camby
and Houston were the only ones left to save the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Camby's feisty attitude was contagious. He was the catalyst to
the Knicks' second-quarter comeback. After the Knicks had fallen
behind by 31-20 with 9 minutes 52 seconds left in the half, Camby
became the focus of the offense as he scored 11 points in three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Childs, relieving a slow-footed Charlie Ward who could not keep
up with the driving Robert Pack, found Camby cutting to the basket
for layups. Camby had three consecutive driving layups as a part of
his offensive flurry in the second quarter that left him with 13
first-half points to go with 7 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   This was the best Camby had looked in more than a week. Over the
past seven days, he had wondered aloud about the minutes crunch
that would result from Ewing's return. And when Camby had been on
the floor, he had been in foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Camby was earning a long stay on the court.
Van Gundy did not let his loyalties to Ewing stop him from leaving
Camby in for 17 first-half minutes. With one minute to go in the
second quarter, Ewing approached the scorer's table to check into
the game. As the clock wound down on the half, Ewing retreated to
the bench with 7 minutes, 2 points and 3 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing's demeanor in the second half was a little more lively, as
was the body language of his teammates _ especially Sprewell. After
a pump fake that left Hubert Davis reaching for air, Sprewell flew
through the lane and put down an emphatic dunk to give the Knicks a
58-55 lead with 6:27 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With the Knicks clicking, Ewing was left in the game and Camby
came in for Johnson. Camby made his mark, grabbing an alley-oop
pass from Ward and coming away with a dunk to give the Knicks a
7-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   But for every flashy moment the Knicks unearthed, they made a
mistake. A flagrant foul by Johnson, who whacked Pack on the way to
a dunk, led to a 3-point possession for the Mavs. And a turnover by
Ward in the backcourt gave Dallas an easy layup to cut the lead to
71-68 with just under two minutes to play in the third quarter. The
Knicks, who converted a nice last-second fast break when Camby
found Johnson alone under the basket for a layup, led after the
period, 75-70.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing played the whole third quarter and looked much better. He
scored 8 points and was a contributor side by side with Camby.
</P>
</TEXT>
