<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 MAN CALLED PHILADELPHIA CRIME CHIEF INDICTED WITH 13 OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Merlino, identified by prosecutors as the head of the
principal organized-crime family in Philadelphia, has been indicted
on federal charges of running a fencing operation that sold
bicycles, baby formula and other goods stolen from a waterfront
shipping port.
</P>
<P>
   Merlino, 37, was charged with 13 other men in two separate but
related indictments announced Thursday by the U.S. attorney's
office in Philadelphia. The indictments were handed up by a grand
jury there on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Merlino, who is known as Skinny Joey and has homes in
Philadelphia and Margate, N.J., was arrested in June and has been
in custody since then on federal cocaine-distribution charges that
were repeated in Wednesday's superseding indictment, said Barry
Gross, an assistant U.S. attorney. The others were freed on bail in
amounts ranging up to $100,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Merlino was being held Thursday in a federal prison in Fairfield
Township, N.J., said his lawyer, Joseph Santaguida. Santaguida
declined to comment on the new charges, which were brought under
the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act.
</P>
<P>
   As for the cocaine charges, he said, ``Joey never had anything
to do with drugs, and they were totally against drugs.'' Asked who
``they'' were, Santaguida said, ``Joey and his friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Between July 1997 and August 1998, Gross said, Merlino and four
other members of his crime family, La Cosa Nostra, received
$405,871 worth of goods that had been stolen from a CSX freight
yard and Ameriport container shipping port in Philadelphia. The
other men, all of Philadelphia, were identified as Frank Gambino,
68; Ralph Abbruzzi, 50, also known as Ralphie Head; Steven
Frangipani, 37, also known as Snitch, and Anthony Accardo, 39.
</P>
<P>
   Gross said the goods were stolen by nine other men, including
several who are involved in the trucking industry and one who was a
CSX security guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started with a shipment of ceiling fans in July 1997,''
Gross said. They were accused of receiving 13,000 women's
sweatsuits, a container of bicycles and a container of baby formula
and nutritional supplements. He refused to say where the goods were
sold.
</P>
<P>
   The nine men not identified as members of La Cosa Nostra are
accused of stealing more than $1.3 million worth of goods from the
port.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Griffin, a lawyer for one of the men, Wesley DiDomenicis,
38, of Voorhees, N.J., the president of BMX Trucking Co. in
Philadelphia, declined to comment on the charges.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Merlino was acquitted of threatening a federal agent
during his arrest in June, and Santaguida said the latest set of
charges was no more likely to stick. ``Joey is used to that,'' he
said. ``Any crime anyone commits, they always say, `He's behind
it,' or, `He orchestrated it,' or, `It wouldn't have happened if
they didn't get his OK.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
