<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS ARE HURTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clippers, who have no reference point for the
concept of livin' large, have another big problem:
</P>
<P>
   They're livin' even smaller than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Tuesday's Laker catastrophe has become the exclusive
province of talk radio, the prevailing dilemma was the challenge
created by back-to-back ankle injuries for Derek Anderson and Brian
Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The walking wounded don't look good,'' Coach Chris Ford said
of the 6-foot-5 Anderson and the 6-9 Skinner, whose wounds make
walking require crutches. They are expected to be goners for two
weeks. ``Both of their ankles are still swollen.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson rolled his ankle in the first quarter of Monday's
victory over Vancouver. Skinner did his damage in the opening
quarter versus the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   This means 10 relatively able-bodied Clippers will suit up
tonight against the Golden State Warriors at Staples Center. It
also means 7-3 Keith Closs, who has been so far down the bench that
he makes a beeping nose while backing up, will be the first big guy
off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his opportunity,'' Ford said of Closs.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative would be hiring a temp from the CBA, but Elgin
Baylor, the team's vice president of basketball ops, said the minor
league is not exactly a bonanza of tall hoop talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were that good,'' Baylor pointed out, ``they wouldn't
be in the CBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, for now, prefers to go with the Terrific 10, but doesn't
eliminate the possibility of adding a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that we may bring one body in,'' said Ford,
leaving us to assume it would be a body with a pulse. ``Unless it
was a trade, anyone we bring in would not leapfrog over anyone we
already have.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast breaks: Lamar Odom's sore hip didn't prevent the rookie
forward from participating in Thursday's practice, but he did
request a leave of absence from posting up during a controlled
scrimmage. ``He's gotta get healthy and he's gotta knock down some
shots,'' Ford said of Odom, who scored just 8 points against the
Pacers and Grizzlies and just 2 vs. the Lakers. ``Other teams have
scouted him. They're not letting him beat them off the dribble; he
has to make them pay by taking the shots they're giving him.'' ...
Golden State went into Thursday night's game with Detroit just 1/2
game ahead of the Clippers (5-17) in the struggle to escape the
Pacific Division cellar. The Warriors defeated the Miami Heat
Tuesday in Oakland. ... The Clippers have promoted Rob Raichlen to
the rank of Director of Communications. Raichlen replaces Jill
Wiggins, who took a similar job with Portland's new WNBA franchise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
