<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-WIZARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS FALL TO WIZARDS, 108-104 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The night started so well for the New Jersey Nets.
They drained 3-pointers like layups, had a 7-point halftime lead
over the Washington Wizards and received praise from President
Clinton, who attended the game as a guest of Lewis Katz, the Nets'
principal owner.
</P>
<P>
   But a fourth-quarter collapse, which almost mirrored the Nets'
performance against the Wizards two weeks ago, turned an enchanted
evening into just another hellish experience for the mystifying
team with the see-saw play.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring only two field goals in the final six minutes, being
outrebounded by 41-28 and allowing the Wizards to shoot 59.5
percent from the field, the Nets lost, 108-104.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss, they dropped to 6-17, and, after a one-game
hiatus, back into the Atlantic Division cellar.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who led by 9 points early in the fourth, were
outscored by 32-24 in the final period and victimized by a
game-turning 19-6 run that saw the Wizards surge from a 7-point
deficit to a 6-point lead, 105-99, with 52.8 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's charge included some baffling miscues by the Nets,
including the two times when Jamie Feick was stripped of the ball
after grabbing defensive rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who shot 53.7 percent through three quarters but only
42.1 percent in the fourth, moved within 105-104 on a 3-point play
by Stephon Marbury with 15.6 seconds left, and had a chance to tie
the score in the final moments.
</P>
<P>
   Down by 2 points after Rod Strickland made one of two foul shots
with 13.8 seconds left, the Nets called a timeout and decided to go
to Kerry Kittles, despite the fact that he had scored only 2 of his
12 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles got open on the left wing and flew past the Wizards'
defense along the baseline and threw up an off-balance reverse
layup that hit the backboard but missed the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Van Horn, who led the Nets with 23 points, fouled Juwan
Howard while going for the rebound, and Howard's ensuing two free
throws sealed the outcome for the Wizards, who won for only the
second time in their last nine games to improve to 7-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wide open when I got the ball,'' Kittles said. ``It was
just a bad shot. I didn't feel comfortable while shooting it. The
play happened so quickly that I can't tell you what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' late-game crumble was reminiscent of their 85-78 loss
to Washington on Nov. 30, when they gave away a 15-point
third-quarter lead by being outscored, 26-11, in the final quarter.
Coach Don Casey compared the game with the Nets' 71-69 loss to the
woeful Chicago Bulls last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's similar to Chicago in that Washington made the big plays
and we floundered at the end,'' Casey said. ``We were like lost
souls out there. A lot of teams are having career nights against
us. We're resurrecting careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey was referring to the stat line of Washington's center,
Jahidi White, who scored a career-high 19 points and grabbed 8
rebounds in the first start of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, who has been having a poor season, led everyone with a
season-high 28 points, 15 above his average, and Mitch Richmond,
who has also struggled this season, scored 22. Strickland added 17
points and 14 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their strong shooting in the first three quarters,
which included an awesome 9-of-11 3-point shooting effort in the
first half, the Nets shot 50.7 percent. Marbury followed Van Horn
with 20 points and 11 assists, while Kendall Gill hit three
3-pointers in scoring 19 points and making 4 steals. The Nets'
finished 11 of 20 from 3-point range. Their early 3-point barrage
left the president lauding them at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing well tonight, very impressive,'' said the
president, who sat with Katz in a lower-level loge. ``They have a
lot of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Nets looked to be headed for their fifth
victory in six games. They were winning what looked like a
1970's-style shootout in the first half. Washington was unconscious
in the first quarter, making an incredible 78.9 percent (15 of 19)
of its field-goal attempts. Such hot shooting would typically be
the beginning of a blowout, but the Nets were nearly as accurate,
shooting 63.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Five players connected from long range in the quarter as the
Nets made their first 6-of-7 3-point attempts in the first quarter.
Marbury, Gill and Kittles each canned triples in the first three
minutes to build an early lead, and the Nets went on to hit their
next three before finally missing.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when the Nets took their 59-52 lead into the locker room,
the president and everyone else was impressed. Of course, even the
most powerful man in the world could not forsee how badly the Nets
would fold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
