<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1634 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MILLENNIUM-ABC-980(2T     12-17 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-ABC-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ABC NEWS, RUSH TO YEAR 2000 WILL SEEM LIKE A MARATHON
</HEADLINE>
   (With MILLENNIUM-NETWORKS) 
(rk) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Don't offer Peter Jennings a cup of coffee anytime in
the next two weeks. He is abstaining, on doctor's orders, so a
sudden surge of caffeine will really pack a wallop on Dec. 31, when
he'll be on the air, virtually nonstop, for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings will anchor ABC's all-millennium, all-the-time
broadcast, from 5 a.m. on the last day of the old year until 5 a.m.
on the first day of the new. Fittingly, he will broadcast from the
network's new studio in Times Square, ground zero for the world's
year 2000 celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, 61, has not pulled an all-nighter in a very long time,
coming closest when he was on the air for 15 hours during the Gulf
War and 12 hours after the Challenger disaster. His daughter, a
college sophomore, has offered an array of remedies popular on
campus during exam week. He hopes Starbucks does the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings is not alone in looking for ways to keep from nodding
off somewhere between midnight in New Zealand and midnight in
Western Samoa. The executive director of ABC 2000, Roger Goodman,
has also sworn off coffee, and alcohol, until the big day. And he
plans to take a sleeping pill the night before to ensure a full
eight hours of rest and is considering a dose of Ritalin to stay
focused during the hectic broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is promoting the broadcast as a historic undertaking _ the
First, the Biggest, the Best. Advertisements on bus shelters
trumpet ``24 Hours, 7 Continents, 1 Network.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing will ever compare to this,'' Goodman said with
unabashed hyperbole. ``I can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   The staff in the War Room on West 66th Street, where the
broadcast is being planned, say the proof is in the numbers. There
will be 30 correspondents stationed around the globe, along with
225 producers, 485 engineers, 32 satellites, 72 tape machines, 80
ABC cameras, 400 more from a consortium of cooperating stations
worldwide and three backup control rooms (in case the main one at
1500 Broadway suffers year 2000 disruptions). More than 300 people
will work in the Times Square studio, napping in shifts on a dozen
cots, stoked by a catered buffet and rewarded for their efforts
with commemorative fleece jackets and fatter-than-average
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   But a note of historical caution is in order, said Lawrence K.
Grossman, the former president of NBC News and PBS and author of
``The Electronic Republic.'' Grossman, who will spend a
television-free New Year's Eve at the New York Philharmonic,
applauds ABC for ``an enormous and awesome undertaking.'' Yet he
urges this generation of television journalists to see the 24-hour
broadcast in context.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you say which is more difficult or ambitious or a
greater achievement?'' Grossman asked, citing ``monster efforts''
of earlier decades, like the first live broadcast seen on both
coasts, the first live political convention, or the first satellite
broadcast, all of which set the stage for what is possible today.
</P>
<P>
   But the news division at ABC, a subsidiary of the Walt Disney
Co., is in no mood for modesty. At an all-hands meeting earlier
this week, David Westin, president of ABC News, reminded staff
members that the event could have fallen into the hands of the
entertainment division. ``It's a huge undertaking and we stepped
forward and said we wanted to own it,'' he said, sounding every bit
the football coach preparing his team for the big game.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate conference room was standing-room only, with
people pressed against the walls, perched on window sills and
seated cross-legged on the floor. Far-flung correspondents and
producers listened in by remote hook-up.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings stayed in the background during Westin's pep talk and
remained there while producers laid out the grueling timetable
between now and the big day: when taped segments would be screened,
when the ``Good Morning America'' set would be dismantled, when the
correspondents would be dispatched to their posts.
</P>
<P>
   Looming large was the story board, a patchwork of color-coded
segments, with every minute of every hour accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Patches of red indicated live entertainment: Billy Joel, the
Kirov Ballet, Aretha Franklin, the Sydney Opera, Bonnie Raitt.
Orange was for segments prepared in advance: essays on subjects
like spirituality, science, sports and warfare. Purple represented
the hourly cascade of midnight celebrations. Gray was for local
news segments. Pink was for video feeds from the worldwide
consortium.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings scowled openly at the huge multicolored chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks so scrunched, like the program is already done,''
Jennings complained. ``The great joy of this should be spontaneity.
You must push us to get something on that's not on the board. If
you have something great, I promise it will get on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the roomed buzzed with a more potent stimulant than
caffeine: the adrenaline rush of beating the competition, even when
the competition sits in the office next door.
</P>
<P>
   Because the story board was a mere backup plan, each
correspondent _ Barbara Walters in Paris, Cokie Roberts in Rome,
Charles Gibson in London, Morton Dean in Moscow, Lynn Sherr in
India, to name but a few _ was on notice to find moments of
celebration, reflection or suspense, get a producer on the phone
and sell their story hard enough to push someone else off.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, to be sure, is not immune to the thrill of having his
face on the screen, his observations the viewers' road map. He says
he will not leave the anchor chair on New Year's Eve for more than
about 10 minutes at a stretch, during local news breaks, lest he
miss a news development requiring his signature commentary. That
means he will forgo showers and naps, freshening up with just a few
shirt changes.
</P>
<P>
   He says he will also leave the studio, with its bullet-proof
windows, to wander Times Square. ``I wouldn't want the century to
go by entirely on the other side of the glass,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of the 24-hour broadcast extend beyond uplinks and
down time. ABC also must see to the comfort of its staff, not just
pampered stars like Jennings but all the anonymous technicians and
gofers. The technical people will work two shifts of 12 hours each,
while the production team and Jennings will be on duty throughout.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of year 2000 disruptions or terrorist violence
went unmentioned at the staff meeting, and Jennings scoffed at the
notion that Times Square on New Year's Eve was a dangerous posting.
``We've been in worse places, like the Middle East,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also insisted that he had no stake in whether the broadcast
included dramatic breaking news _ a certain ratings bonanza. He
would be delighted, Jennings said, with an uninterrupted reflection
on where the world has been for the past 1,000 years and where it
is going.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not to say the network hasn't made elaborate plans
for any eventuality. The three backup control rooms _ one at
corporate headquarters on West 66th Street, one in Washington and
another in London _ will each have their own anchors ready to take
over for Jennings if he is forced off the air. And the New York
Police Department has promised a clear corridor to 66th Street if
the crew at Times Square needs to leave that studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every system has been checked,'' said Neil Patterson, the
executive in charge of production. ``Every chip has been looked at.
As redundant as we can be, we are. But if the satellites go down,
we'll all be sitting around drinking Champagne.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing left to chance is what Jennings will wear for the
occasion. Until 11:45 p.m., Eastern Standard Time, expect a sleek
coat and tie. But as midnight approaches in the city that
celebrates like no other, he may disappear for a costume change.
``I'm asking everybody's opinion,'' Jennings said. ``Do you think I
should wear a dinner jacket?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
