<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-NETWORKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTHER NETWORKS SKIP WORLD COUNTDOWN  
(WITH MILLENNIUM-ABC)
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While Peter Jennings is announcing that the New Year
has arrived in Djibouti, anchors at the other networks will be
taking things a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 31, CBS' ``Early Show'' will be co-anchored from Sydney
and New York. Later, CBS's prime-time coverage will originate from
the entertainment division in Los Angeles, with news coverage
limited to the evening news and one-minute updates from numerous
correspondents after Dan Rather anchors the news.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's New Year's Eve coverage, like ABC's, will begin at 5 a.m.
There will be live hourly updates on New Year's observances and any
year 2000 developments. Tom Brokaw will be amply supplemented by
dozens of NBC reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Couric and Brokaw will anchor an expanded edition of
``Today,'' which will run in each United States time zone from 7
a.m. to 10 a.m. And Brokaw will anchor the evening news live from
Times Square beginning at 6:30 p.m. A special edition of
``Dateline'' _ on what Americans can expect from the next
millennium (apart, evidently, from endless news broadcasts) _ will
be shown from 8 p.m. to 9 p.m. The network will continue to cover
any breaking news until 3:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC's live coverage will also continue for 30 hours, featuring
a team of computer and utility experts who will follow any year
2000 news.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fox network, the plans are more modest, with a 90-minute
special from 11 p.m. to 12:30 a.m. Brit Hume and Paula Zahn will
report live from Times Square, Tony Snow from the federal year 2000
center in Washington and John Walsh, of ``America's Most Wanted,''
from the command center in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast will also include taped celebrations from London,
Moscow, Bethlehem, Las Vegas and New Mexico and live concerts in
progress. Only in the event of a large-scale news development does
Fox intend to interrupt its regular programming earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of No-Doz ought to concentrate their marketing
efforts on the staff of CNN. CNN will offer continuous coverage
beginning at 5 a.m. on New Year's Eve, through Tuesday morning,
Jan. 4, with anchors from around the globe and reports from 60 CNN
correspondents, for a total of 100 hours of live programming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
