<HEADLINE>
CUBAN BOY AT CENTER OF ANOTHER DEBATE _ ON NEW YEAR'S PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (mk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 6-year-old Cuban refugee whose fate has sparked
heated debate in Havana, Washington and Miami became the center of
yet more polemic Thursday when Mayor Rudolph Giuliani suggested
that the boy might be invited to attend the New Year's Eve
celebration in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy exchange with reporters at City Hall, Giuliani said
the question of whether the boy, Elian Gonzalez, should be returned
to Cuba _ as Fidel Castro and the boy's father have demanded _
``plays out in a very dramatic way the purpose of America.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy has been staying with relatives in Miami since he was
rescued last month off the Florida coast during an ill-fated voyage
from Cuba that took the lives of his mother and stepfather and nine
others.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Spencer Eig, a lawyer representing Elian, said that
the boy and his family had not received an official invitation.
``It is a kind and caring suggestion,'' he said, but he added that
the family had not decided whether Elian would participate.
``Midnight is kind of late for a 6-year-old,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The possible invitation was first reported Thursday by The Daily
News. In discussing it, Giuliani spoke about the boy's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``My views are that he should be given the benefit of asylum
protection, and whatever argument his father has should be made in
an American court,'' the mayor said. ``The very dramatic act of his
mother, in giving up her life in order to obtain freedom and
democracy for her child, is a very powerful thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
