<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARDSON MEANS TROUBLE FOR UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ DePaul All-American forward Quentin Richardson
isn't suffering from the sophomore jinx so much as the sophomore
nag _ a series of nagging ailments that, until recently, have
limited his practice time and tempered his production.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, whose No.19 Blue Demons face UCLA on Saturday at
Pauley Pavilion, missed three practices last month because of an
ingrown toenail. Then, thinking he needed a filling replaced,
Richardson instead had a molar removed and missed more practice
time. Finally, he strained his shoulder lifting weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very bright kid, and he sees what's happening,'' DePaul
coach Pat Kennedy said. ``He didn't practice for three days before
the Duke game. But now he seems to be 100 percent. He's getting
himself back on course.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson averaged 17.9 points and 8.6 rebounds in the Blue
Demons' first eight games _ superb numbers for anyone but the
nation's top sophomore. But improved performance has accompanied
improved health. Tuesday, before two dozen NBA scouts, Richardson
had 26 points and 12 rebounds against St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he takes aim at UCLA, and the Bruins are bracing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to have a collective awareness of where he is,''
Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``He can beat you in so many ways.
That's why the pros think he's a top-five pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Prepping the defense: At 6-6 and 225 pounds, Richardson is a
difficult matchup _ too big for guards, too quick for forwards.
He's accurate from 3-point range, he can score off the dribble, and
he has an array of low-post moves.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore guard Ray Young is UCLA's best chance; he's strong and
athletic. But it's unrealistic for Young to defend Richardson
effectively for 30 minutes, avoid foul trouble and have much
success offensively. Most likely, guard Earl Watson and two
forwards, Rico Hines and Jason Kapono, will help Young.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Bruins probably will play zone defense to
protect their big men, Jerome Moiso and Dan Gadzuric, from foul
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``DePaul will be equally, if not more challenging than
Gonzaga,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: The Blue Demons (7-2) are without starting point
guard Rashon Bruno, who strained a knee ligament against St. John's
and will miss three to five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement is senior Kerry Hartfield.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting cast: DePaul's 7-foot freshman center, Steven Hunter,
has been as impressive as the Pac-10's best rookies _ Arizona's
Gilbert Arenas and Jason Gardner, Stanford's Casey Jacobsen, Cal's
Joe Shipp, and Kapono.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, who wasn't heavily recruited, is averaging 12.8 points
and scored 21 against Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the degree he played in the Duke game, I think he has
surprised everyone,'' Kennedy said. ``He has NBA potential and
wasn't recruited at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter is DePaul's No. 4 scorer, behind Richardson, forward
Bobby Simmons and guard Paul McPherson, a junior college transfer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
