<HEADER>
A1650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CHANCELLOR-GAFFE-N     12-17 0279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHANCELLOR-GAFFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS CHANCELLOR CRITICIZED FOR REMARK ABOUT COUNCILMAN'S
HEIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A gibe by Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew that an
obscure freshman city councilman was ``too short'' to demand his
resignation _ and should come back when he's taller _ set off a
storm of criticism Thursday during one of the most challenging
periods in the chancellor's career.
</P>
<P>
   Some dismissed the remark as humorous in a city of much
diversity, including in height, but others criticized Crew for
serving as a poor role model for children. Thirty of the 51 City
Council members called on him to apologize. His remarks emboldened
his critics and led to new calls for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The dustup began Wednesday when Stephen Fiala, a councilman from
Staten Island, blamed Crew's management for recent cheating and
attendance scandals and called on him to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, cornered by reporters, Crew retorted: ``He's too
short to talk to me about that.'' Then, with a slight laugh, he
added, ``He can call for my resignation _ till he's taller.'' Crew
is about 6 feet tall; Fiala, according to his driver's license, is
5-foot-6.
</P>
<P>
   Crew said Thursday that he felt no need to apologize because he
had been misunderstood. He said he had been using an expression
that his father used to describe someone as short-sighted, and was
not referring to Fiala's height.
</P>
<P>
   The ruckus has come as Crew has been publicly and privately
agonizing over whether to accept a job offer in Seattle and as his
relationship with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a former ally, has grown
strained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
