<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX LAW MUST ADJUST TO INTERNET COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The debate over taxing Internet transactions
took a constructive turn this week when an e-commerce advisory
panel focused on the need to simplify the nation's crazy quilt of
sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Levying Internet taxes in the context of today's system defies
the most basic principles of taxation. As Adam Smith admonished in
his Wealth of Nations, taxes should be convenient to pay and not
cost more to collect than they generate in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional mail-order tax model is catalog shopping, which
has posed tax-collection problems for as long as catalogs have been
a significant part of the retail scene. The Internet challenge is
the catalog problem writ larger.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the difficulty is the Constitution. Twice since the
'70s, states have been on the losing side of Supreme Court
decisions concerning imposition of taxes on out-of-state
businesses. Beyond the legal barriers, though, are more daunting
practical considerations.
re are thousands of U.S. taxing jurisdictions applying
different rates and exemptions on certain products. Rationalizing
these myriad tax situations is possible with sophisticated computer
programs, but such programs might be more expensive and unwieldy
than small Internet entrepreneurs can afford or are capable of
dealing with.
</P>
<P>
   The Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce, a 19-member
public-private panel chartered by Congress last year to study
Internet taxation issues, came to grips with this problem at its
San Francisco meeting this week by exploring systemic reform. One
expert witness told the group ``radical simplification'' of
existing sales taxes in exchange for stronger enforcement
mechanisms might provide the basis for compromise among sharply
divided members.
</P>
<P>
   The enforcement problem is critical because Internet sales taxes
under the current system are likely to generate a lot more hassle
and expense for many taxing jurisdictions than potential revenues
could ever justify.
</P>
<P>
   An e-commerce expert who helps large companies develop online
sales programs says sales taxes are an anachronism. Raul Fernandez,
head of Proxicom, recently told Investor's Business Daily that
``the sales tax is a relic of the old economy, and has no place in
the new global economy. It is backward thinking to apply something
designed for the physical world in the virtual world.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be, if observers such as Fernandez are right, that the
new-era economy demands new methods to fund government's needs.
Perhaps the sales tax is on its way to becoming a
revenue-generating dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it's not fair to expect Main Street retailers to
continue to be tax collectors while increasing numbers of
cyberrivals sell their goods taxless, and thus more cheaply, and
with less government meddling.
</P>
<P>
   This reality leads to the question of whether government has a
divine right to profit from the sale of goods and services. Almost
nobody much questions this right, even though the sales tax is
generally conceded to be one of the most regressive methods of
taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Economic relationships are undergoing profound changes, and
governments must adjust if they are to adequately and fairly serve
the needs of all their constituents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 0036EST &QL; 
