<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-CANADIENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS EDGE CANADIENS BEHIND MCKAY, OR WAS IT HOLIK? 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Just two days after scoring seven goals, their
largest production of the season, the New Jersey Devils barely
mustered two goals Thursday night. But that was still enough for a
2-1 victory over the lowly Montreal Canadiens, who have had more
injuries this season than any other team in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Randy McKay, who assisted on Jay Pandolfo's goal, which tied the
score early in the second period, was credited with the winning
goal. It came with 20.9 seconds left in the game when McKay jumped
in front of Montreal's goaltender, Jose Theodore, and appeared to
deflect home Bobby Holik's shot from the right circle.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Robbie Ftorek said that it was Holik's goal and that the
Devils would pursue having the official scoring changed. But Holik
was not upset that the goal belonged to McKay. ``If he didn't touch
it,'' Holik said with a laugh, ``it went through his aura, and
that's enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had touched Holik's shot, McKay said: ``I still
don't know. I hope I touched it. I jumped and the shot came.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second consecutive victory on the road for the Devils
(17-10-3). They are 5-7-1 on the road this season after setting a
league record for road victories last season with 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big win on the road for us and it makes us feel good,''
goaltender Martin Brodeur said. ``You worry a little after scoring
seven goals, but tonight we played a tight game, the way we're
supposed to on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, who took 32 shots at Theodore, tended to lose the
puck in their zone, especially during the early going, but they
were saved by Brodeur, whose only lapse was a short-handed goal by
Craig Darby, which opened the scoring 9 minutes 38 seconds into the
game. It was only the second such goal allowed by New Jersey this
season. But that was it for Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes into the game, Brodeur, who has missed just one
start in the last 22 games, alertly came off his line to narrow the
angle on a shot by Martin Rucinsky during a breakaway. Brodeur used
his left skate to deny Rucinsky, the Canadiens' leading scorer, who
tried to deke him with a left-to-right move.
</P>
<P>
   Just 47 seconds after the first intermission, Pandolfo took a
pass from McKay from the left side and beat Theodore over the glove
from the slot. It was Pandolfo's third goal of the season and it
tied the score. McKay's next point in the game was the game-winning
goal. Or maybe it was Holik's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
