<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKE-MESSAGE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIP MORRIS EXECUTIVE IS TAKING COMPANY'S NEW MESSAGE TO PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ With the fervor of an evangelist, Steven C.
Parrish, a Philip Morris Cos. Inc. senior vice president, is
crisscrossing the land, telling how the company that purveys
tobacco and alcohol also sells food products and is doing its part
to help Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dramatic change from the company's previous stance on
communicating with the public and the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long, we've been perceived as being bad and only about
tobacco,'' said Parrish, who visited Kansas City, Mo., last week
and made similar stops recently in Denver and Tulsa, Okla. ``And a
lot of that was our fault. The media would call and all they got
was a `no comment.' They had no idea of what we were doing for the
community, if anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Parrish said, the company is much more than Marlboro
and its other tobacco brands.
</P>
<P>
   Few people know that Philip Morris owns Kraft, the largest food
company in the United States, or that it owns Miller Brewing Co.
</P>
<P>
   Or that:
</P>
<P>
   - It spends millions each year on programs to prevent children
from smoking and to encourage people to ``Think When You Drink.''
</P>
<P>
   - It annually donates millions of dollars worth of goods to food
pantries.
</P>
<P>
   - Bottling plants in areas hit by floods stop bottling beer and
start bottling drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   - It supports numerous shelters, facilities and programs to help
battered women.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those efforts, some still perceive Philip Morris as
hypocritical for supporting such programs while it sells products
that contribute to societal ills.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a study released this week found a strong link
between the use of alcohol and physical abuse in homes. The study
found more than three times the risk of domestic violence when
husbands or male partners abuse alcohol or drugs, go in and out of
jobs, or break up with their partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study offers the strongest evidence so far that links
alcohol abuse by the male partner with domestic violence,''
Demetrios N. Kyriacou of Olive View-UCLA Medical Center, the lead
researcher, told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish acknowledges that there is a link between alcohol abuse
and domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to me that's an additional reason why Philip Morris should
be involved in programs to end domestic violence _ when people
consume too much of one of our products and violence results,''
Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the efforts to stop youths from smoking, Parrish says Philip
Morris takes the stand that people shouldn't make the decision to
smoke until they're adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, it's a dangerous product,'' Parrish said, ``And two,
society has decided _ and I agree _ that for dangerous products
like cigarettes, the decision is more appropriately made after
you're an adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Parrish says that he has been asked many times why the company
continues to sell controversial products and that the answer mostly
has to do with money.
</P>
<P>
   In the company's most recent quarter, tobacco and beer
constituted 67 percent of its sales and 73 percent of its profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, these products are a big, big part of Philip
Morris,'' Parrish said. ``But there are other products and issues,
too. I mean we sell Jell-O, Philadelphia Cream Cheese, Post Raisin
Bran, Maxwell House _ some of the best-known brands in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gustav Carlson, author of the recently published Total Exposure:
Controlling Your Company's Image in the Glare of the Business Media
Explosion, credits Philip Morris for trying to get its message out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like nature, the public and media abhor a vacuum,'' Carlson
said. ``If you don't fill it with your own message, others will do
it for you, and I think that's what's happened with Philip Morris
for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The company currently is trying to get its message out through
four television commercials. All the commercials carry the same
theme line: ``Working to make a difference. The people of Philip
Morris.''
</P>
<P>
   One features a woman who had been battered by her husband. One
night, he threatened her with a knife and barely missed their son.
</P>
<P>
   Another features folks in Elba, Ala., who had been flooded out
of their homes. A nearby beer bottling plant stopped bottling beer
and started bottling water.
</P>
<P>
   The third shows an older woman who recently had been sick and
ended up having to rely on a food pantry for goods.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth is aimed at showing Philip Morris' commitment to stop
underage smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you agree their products are dangerous or not, I think
it's courageous of them to come out and tackle some of the
problems,'' Carlson said. ``If they came out with some sort of
image campaign with puppies and butterflies, trying to separate
themselves from their products, that would be stupid _ people are
too smart to buy into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Parrish acknowledges that his mission is sometimes stressful.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when it's frustrating, when I get
disappointed, but mostly I feel upbeat because I really do think
we're doing the right thing in talking about some of the difficult
issues that are tied to some of our products,'' Parrish said.
```But you're right _ it's not always easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
