<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGES HEAR ARGUMENTS OVER RELEASE OF DOCUMENTS IN GM LIABILITY
TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The documents are precious to Kenneth and Steven
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   In them, the Bakers see proof that General Motors did little to
prevent cars from catching fire. Their mother died in 1990 while
riding in a Chevrolet Blazer that went up in flames after a wreck.
</P>
<P>
   GM values the documents, too, and the company says they deserve
the sacred legal protection of attorney-client privilege. No jury
in the Bakers' liability case should ever view them, GM says.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel on the U.S. Court of Appeals heard from both
sides in St. Louis on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The document dispute will help shape the longest-running product
liability lawsuit in Kansas City's federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1973 document, GM employee Edward Ivey suggests that it
would be cheaper for the company to settle liability lawsuits than
spend more than $2.20 per car to prevent potential fires. The
document has already been made public.
</P>
<P>
   In February, U.S. Magistrate Sarah Hays in Kansas City ordered
GM to turn over other documents that plaintiffs say show that the
company knew of Ivey's analysis.
</P>
<P>
   A liability trial is on hold until the judges decide GM's appeal
of Hays' ruling. That could take several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a fishing expedition,'' Kenneth Chesebro, one of
the Bakers' attorneys, told the judges on Thursday. ``There is no
other way to get access to these facts.''
</P>
<P>
   GM disputes the plaintiffs' claims, saying the documents don't
pertain to the Bakers' case. The company also notes that Ivey has
testified that GM knew nothing of the cost-benefit study.
</P>
<P>
   While plaintiffs say the internal documents merely repeat facts
already public, GM argued that they reflected the thinking and
opinions of attorneys and should stay privileged.
</P>
<P>
   GM repeated its argument that the plaintiffs' attorneys are free
to question Ivey in court and don't need the documents.
</P>
<P>
   GM attorney Jay Lefkowitz argued Thursday that upholding Hays'
ruling would have grave implications for attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Her ruling would ``literally obliterate'' the privilege and
alter the attorney-client relationship ``for all time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Judge David R. Hansen questioned Lefkowitz's ``doomsday
arguments,'' noting that other judges have waived the privilege in
certain cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky hasn't fallen,'' Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the stakes are high for GM.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a Florida judge ordered GM to hand over some
of the same damaging documents. A jury eventually awarded $33
million to the family of two children who died in the fiery crash
of an Oldsmobile station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer watchdogs are closely monitoring the Baker case,
speculating that a plaintiff victory could expose GM to a wave of
liability suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``On an interest-level scale of 1 to 10, the Baker case is a
10,'' said Clarence Ditlow, executive director of Ralph Nader's
Center for Auto Safety, in an interview on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to the case,'' he added, ``is the documents.''
</P>
<P>
   In her ruling, Hays said trying to protect potentially damaging
documents is an ``abuse'' of the attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The privilege is generally untouchable except in cases where a
party has used it to commit a crime, such as perjury or obstruction
of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Hays wrote that the document dispute ``has consumed endless
amounts of time and has effectively sidetracked this litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baker case already has reached trial once.
</P>
<P>
   At that trial, the plaintiffs' attorneys argued that a fuel pump
continued to feed gasoline into the engine after the collision
involving the Bakers' mother, Beverly Garner of Bevier, Mo. That
caused the fire, they said.
</P>
<P>
   GM says Garner was dead before the fire even started.
</P>
<P>
   Before the case even reached a jury, U.S. District Judge Joseph
E. Stevens in 1993 declared the pump defective to punish GM for not
turning over documents. A jury awarded the Bakers $11.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   But an appeals court, ruling that Stevens' punishment was too
harsh, threw out the judgment and ordered a new trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 0047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
