<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1662 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-RUSH-KAN &LR;      12-17 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL FRAUD, CONSPIRACY STATUTES COME INTO PLAY IN RUSH
SUSPENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ JaRon and Kareem Rush, two of the best prep
basketball players ever to come out of Kansas City, have been
suspended by the universities they play for after a federal grand
jury questioned JaRon and investigators talked to Kareem.
</P>
<P>
   The universities say it's possible National Collegiate Athletic
Association rules have been violated. But such violations are not
necessarily a crime. So a lot of people are wondering: What does a
federal grand jury have to do with college athletics?
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the probe, a source familiar with the legal
theory in play told The Kansas City Star on Thursday, is the novel
application of federal fraud and conspiracy statutes often used in
public corruption cases.
</P>
<P>
   The source said prosecutors would argue that an athlete who
falsely certified to a university that he was amateur could be
guilty of defrauding the school. Each year, athletes sign a letter
verifying their amateur status, saying they have taken no money for
playing their sport.
</P>
<P>
   But the athletes would not necessarily be the focus of such a
probe. Those who paid the athletes and endangered their amateur
status could be under scrutiny under federal bribery statutes, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legal theory being tested, should the athlete lose his
amateur status, and his eligibility to play college sports, the
university would have been deprived of his ``good and faithful''
servicesd the university be sanctioned by the NCAA, damages
could be measured in the form of lost ticket sales, tournament
revenues and unpaid television money.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors would have jurisdiction over such a case
because the U.S. government funnels millions of dollars in grants
to public and private universities each year.
</P>
<P>
   The source declined to speak specifically about the current
probe, citing grand jury secrecy. It was unclear what prompted the
probe or how wide its scope is.
</P>
<P>
   The Rush brothers have declined to comment since their
suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   West Coast press reports have said JaRon Rush, who attends the
University of California-Los Angeles, acknowledged to investigators
accepting ``considerably less than $500'' from Los Angeles sports
agent Jerome Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley has denied making the payments.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Rush reportedly acknowledged accepting a pair of shoes
and $50 in cash on one or more occasions from his summer basketball
coach, Myron Piggie, before entering college. Such payments for
expenses are allowed under NCAA rules, and sources told The Kansas
City Star that an expedited University of Missouri-Columbia
investigation could clear the way for Kareem Rush to return to the
team by a Dec. 30 game against Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Kareem Rush's situation is less serious than that of his
brother because there are no reports that he was ever involved with
a sports agent. Under NCAA rules, accepting anything from an agent
is a clear violation.
</P>
<P>
   Piggie, a former consultant for the Nike Corp., has acknowledged
paying for the athletes' meals and providing each with a pair of
shoes, but denied giving they anything that would jeopardize their
college eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Law professors said the government's legal theory is unusual,
though not unprecedented, and wonder if it will hold up through the
actual filing of charges, should that ever happen.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Mitten, director of the National Sports Law Institute in
Milwaukee, said a better solution to policing college sports would
be to write state laws allowing universities to sue if an athlete
misrepresents his eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, he pointed out, already has a law allowing
universities to sue athletes and their agents in such a case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this such a big pervasive thing that there's such harm that
it justifies federal criminal prosecution?'' Mitten asked. ``I
would say I don't think it's appropriate for, in essence, a
violation of NCAA rules to constitute a federal crime. If we're
going to do it, there should be more laws that would more directly
apply.''
</P>
<P>
   Roscoe Howard, a professor of criminal law at the University of
Kansas, found more merit in the government's approach, though he
agreed it was an unusual reading of the statutes.
</P>
<P>
   He also was more willing to give federal prosecutors leeway in
determining what issues in their areas deserve the attention of
federal criminal code.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will vary from jurisdiction to jurisdiction,'' Howard said.
``A lot of time you'll find the federal government jumping into a
problem that the local jurisdiction can't handle.''
</P>
<P>
   A crucial element of a sports fraud case would be the annual
statement signed by each athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Every athlete at NCAA-affiliated schools is required to sign the
``Student-Athlete Statement.'' That document, provided by the NCAA,
is the athlete's written acknowledgement that he or she is eligible
for collegiate competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's designed to protect the institution,'' said Jim Epps,
senior associate athletic director at Kansas State University. ``It
puts the athlete on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The amateurism part of the statement clearly notes that athletes
are ``not eligible for participation in a sport if you have ever
taken pay, or the promise of pay, for competing in that sport.'' It
also states that athletes are not eligible if they used their
athletic skills for pay ``in any form.''
</P>
<P>
   The athletes are required to sign the statement before the first
competition of his or her respective season. The athletes must
re-sign them every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Institutions are supposed to know whether their athletes are
eligible,'' said Athena Yiamouyiannis, a director of membership
services for the NCAA. ``They need help from the student
athletes.''
- The Star's Steve Rock and Howard Richman contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
