<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Pervomaiskaya, Russia) _ Desperate civilians
fleeing the blistering Russian bombardment of Grozny say they had
to run a gantlet of gunfire in the ``humanitarian corridor'' set up
by the Russian army. Refugees interviewed at a checkpoint six miles
from the outskirts of Grozny said a bus full of refugees was
riddled with machine-gun fire. Mortars exploded as elderly
civilians, women and children huddled in a ditch for hours before
making the long, chilly walk to Russian-controlled Chechnya. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Washington) _ Behind the hard-line talk, a
willingness to talk. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-ABORTION (Rome) _ Furor in Itay over the legal case of
13-year-old retarded girl in Sicily who is pregnant and whose
parents are seeking an abortion. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-IRAQ (Paris) _ France, which has delayed a vote in the
Security Council on a new arms-inspection system for Iraq until
Friday, is hoping for an agreement that all five permanent council
members can support. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-MINORITIES (New York) _ A hugely disproportionate number of
minorities represent new AIDS cases, yet blacks and Latinos have
not had front and center positions in AIDS policy making.
Mainstream black groups have shied away from the issue, and
minority groups devoted to it have had trouble getting money. But
slowly, that is all changing, as more minorities find themselves in
powerful positions in the advocacy and policy front, and state and
federal dollars are starting to be newly appropriated in
recognition of where the disease now hits home. By Jennifer
Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-SERVICE (Undated) _ The thrill of shopping online is that
it replaces the shopping cart with a vehicle that has the power and
responsiveness of a fighter plane. But more and more this holiday
season, Internet users are finding that the sophisticated online
shopping machinery can malfunction under actual battle conditions.
And when it does, companies often become distressingly mute when
customers write or call with problems. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
