   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-DALLAS (Dallas, Texas) _ The words and music have stuck
in my mind for 40-odd years, because they seemed so apt. Frank
Loesser wrote them for a musical called ``The Most Happy Fella,''
and they stopped the show every time. ``You're from Big D I can
guess,'' a brassy dame sang, ``by the way you drawl and the way you
dress. You're from Big D, my, oh yes. I mean Big D, little a,
double l, a, s. And that spells Dallas, my darlin', darlin' Dallas
... where every home's a palace, 'cause the settlers settle for no
less.'' Big money, big hair, big talk. Such is the lingering
stereotype of this city. It occupies a sizable spot in the national
consciousness as the home of the big, bad Dallas Cowboys, of J.R.
Ewing and Miss Ellie and all the gang at Southfork, and of the
little guy with the big ears and bigger ambition, H. Ross Perot,
who was a billionaire before he turned 40. And for those old enough
to recall the events of November 1963, it occupies an especially
dark corner of memory, as the cursed place where John F. Kennedy
was shot. Yet Dallas and its smaller sibling, Fort Worth, an
unmatched pair if ever there was one, amount to much more than
that. Together with the little cities that cluster around them like
pilot fish, they constitute the largest metropolitan area in the
nation's second largest state. They boast the largest collection of
major corporate headquarters outside of New York and Chicago. By
R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   TEXACO-OPERA (New York) _ Opera has long been saddled with the
perception that it is a pricey art form for elitist audiences. But
it is hard to make the elitism charge stick when for 60 years the
Saturday matinees of the Metropolitan Opera have been broadcast
live across the United States and Canada, sponsored by Texaco.
``The Texaco-Metropolitan Opera International Radio Broadcasts,''
as the series is officially called, represents the longest
continuous commercial sponsorship in broadcast history. (Met
performances were first heard on radio nine years earlier.) The
broadcasts have also been carried live in Europe since 1990.
Australia, New Zealand and Hong Kong were added later, and this
year the network was extended to Brazil. When the current radio
season ends on April 22 with Wagner's ``Gotterdammerung,'' Texaco
will have sponsored the broadcasts of 1,192 live performances of
142 operas. It is estimated that 10 million listeners tune in each
season. What other art form has been made so available to so many
people for so long? By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   WINGS-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Noel Coward's ``Waiting in the
Wings,'' with Rosemary Harris, at the Walter Kerr Theater. Reviewed
by Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has ben sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MET-DESIGN-EXHIBIT (New York) _ Proving once again that it can
mount a boutique of a show with the same panache as a five-alarm
blockbuster, the Metropolitan Museum has unveiled an exquisite
sampling of 20th-century design objects from its own collection. A
salute rather than a full survey, ``A Century of Design, Part I:
1900-1925'' is installed in several intimate galleries in the
20th-century wing. It displays more than 50 examples of furniture,
metalwork, glass, ceramics, textiles, jewelry and drawings, from a
fanciful Pompeiian-style dressing table of bronze and basalt by the
French designer Armand-Albert Rateau to a silver claret jug with
sinuous curves and flyaway thumb-piece, the work of the English
craftsman Archibald Knox. By Grace Glueck.
</P>
