<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ BLASTS REFS AGAIN AFTER LAKERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shaquille O'Neal's jump shots bounced as wildly as his
free throws, his scrums with Dikembe Mutombo knocked his rhythm
off-kilter, and the flurry of fouls that followed eventually
knocked him off the floor entirely.
</P>
<P>
   But stopping the Lakers' winning streak proved as difficult as
stopping O'Neal from trashing the officials. Both efforts were
pointless.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers did win Thursday night, riding Kobe Bryant's
season-high 30 points to a 95-88 victory over the Atlanta Hawks at
Phillips Arena. It was their fourth consecutive win, 11th in their
last 12 games, and pushed their NBA-best record to 19-5.
</P>
<P>
   And O'Neal did vent afterward, following a frustrating night in
which he made four of 15 shots, scored just nine points and fouled
out with 5 minutes, 54 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to hold back _ ``I'd rather save my money, it's
Christmastime,'' he said _ but then...
</P>
<P>
   ``Three refs out there, six fouls _ one guy called five fouls,''
O'Neal said, referring to Monty McCutchen. ``That should tell you
something about these (bleeping) idiots that they got calling the
game. They suck. They stink. They need to get some new ones.''
</P>
<P>
   And about that Christmas money going to pay another NBA fine?
``Don't care. I don't give a (bleep).''
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least O'Neal kept his composure until he reached the
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   The same couldn't be said for Isaiah Rider, the Hawks' volatile
guard. Rider led Atlanta with a team-high 33 points, but he missed
13 of 24 shots and drew the wrath of a fan on his way off the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Rider engaged him in a shouting match, which reached its low
point when Rider _ held back by security staff _ yelled to the man,
``Stay right there _ I got some boys that will come see you.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they'll be available to help him defend against Bryant
next time too. Rider and Bryant did most of the on-court jousting
for the evening, trading jump shot for jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant hit 10 of 19 field goals and made 10 of 11 foul shots to
win the battle, and prove the Lakers can win, on the road, even
without a 30-point night from O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if anything it will build character,'' Bryant said,
``because there's certain times when he might get in foul trouble
or I might get in foul trouble, and we have to step up as a unit
and do it together.... (The win) will build confidence, maybe not
for tomorrow night but later on, in April, in May.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes a village to replace an MVP candidate, and the Lakers
found a few willing citizens. John Salley filled in for O'Neal and
contributed seven points in 20 minutes. Derek Fisher pitched in 10
points off the bench, and Rick Fox, seven.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice's 11 points were second only to Bryant's, but he
missed 12 of 17 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo had a bit to do with the Lakers' 40 percent shooting. He
blocked four shots, misdirected several others and, of course,
eliminated O'Neal as a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Lakers built a double-digit lead in the third
quarter, holding Atlanta to 18 points, and maintained their cushion
throughout the fourth, despite 13 points from Rider.
</P>
<P>
   ``(O'Neal) started off with Mutombo getting a couple blocks that
probably should have been fouls that weren't called,'' coach Phil
Jackson said, ``and it just kind of grew from there. One thing led
to another and I think that ultimately he wasn't even given a
chance to play in the last part of the game. Everything seemed to
be a foul, whatever he did. ... Some nights are going to be like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, since O'Neal only played 28 minutes, he saved
his energy for the three games the Lakers play in the next four
days. And they got away with a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means we're a pretty good team,'' O'Neal said. ``We just
have to maintain our pace and just get better. We're going to be
fine. I like the way this team is playing now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
