<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1684 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-Kearse-HNS &LR;      12-17 1841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kearse-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Titans' Kearse takes the league by storm as a rookie
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN McCLAIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Jevon Kearse might be the best rookie
defensive player to enter the NFL since Lawrence Taylor in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse, the Tennessee Titans' No. 1 draft choice, has 11{ sacks,
one behind the league's rookie record shared by Leslie O'Neal
(1986) and Simeon Rice (1996).
</P>
<P>
   Kearse, who plays the left side, leads the NFL with nine forced
fumbles and has a team-high seven tackles for losses. Kearse's 76
tackles are more than any lineman on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jevon plays as hard as any lineman I've seen in a long, long
time,'' Titans coach Jeff Fisher said. ``He does the kind of things
that can't be coached, things that make you go, `Wow.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that if Jevon keeps the same work habits and
stays healthy, he can be as good as he wants to be. And he wants to
be the best. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``The Freak'' by his University of Florida teammates
because of his extraordinary athleticism, the 6-5, 255-pound Kearse
ran the 40-yard dash at the Indianapolis scouting combine in 4.41
seconds. He has an 86-inch wingspan, and his hands seem as large as
manhole covers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he'd be very productive, and I expected him to make
a lot of plays as a rookie, but not this many,'' Fisher said. ``I
expected him to be a factor in the passing game, but there were
questions about how physical he would play against the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``His production in the running game has been the most
surprising. He's very instinctive, and he plays the same way
against the run as he does the pass. He can explode off a
double-team block, where most guys his size would have been crushed
and buried.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the No. 1 song on Sundays at Adelphia Coliseum is Le
Freak. The fans freak out every time Kearse makes a play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jevon's so explosive going to the ball,'' Fisher said. ``He
has unbelievable change of direction and closing speed. And his
up-field speed is as good as you'll find in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Kearse could become the first rookie defensive end
from the AFC to make the Pro Bowl since the merger in 1970. After
the regular season ends, Kearse is expected to be named NFL
Defensive Rookie of the Year. He has been named Defensive Rookie of
the Month two times.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Kearse's accomplishments even more impressive are the
almost unimaginable hardships he overcame while growing up in Fort
Myers, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse was one of seven children reared by a single mother
because his father was murdered a few months before he was born. An
older brother, J.J., is serving time in prison. A younger brother,
Jermaine, was shot to death at 17 outside the family's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse has used his family's misfortune as motivation on and off
the field. He's hoping his story will inspire others.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm on the field, I tell myself that the guy lining up
across from me could be the guy that shot my brother,'' he said.
``Sometimes, I ask myself what my life would be like now if I'd
grown up with a father. Maybe my younger brother would be alive.
Maybe my older brother wouldn't be in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then again, if I had grown up with a father, I may not have
pushed myself to be where I am right now. Maybe I wouldn't need to
play football because my mom and dad would have jobs, and I'd still
be in college working on my degree. By not having a father and
wanting to help my family be financially stable, I guess that's
motivated me to be the kind of person and player I am today.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what kind of person and player is Kearse? His teammates,
coaches and friends say he is shy, humble, polite and
well-mannered. He is the only member of his family to graduate from
high school. He needs one semester to earn his degree from Florida,
where he was a member of the National Honor Society.
</P>
<P>
   But Kearse is still a football player first, one whose
incredible speed, quickness and agility that combined with
unbridled enthusiasm have helped put the Titans one victory from
clinching a playoff berth for the first time since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Former defensive end Sean Jones, who was one of the league's
premier pass rushers for the Raiders, Oilers and Packers, was a
member of that 1993 team that finished 12-4, won the AFC Central
and lost in the second round to Kansas City in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came into the league, he could have been Lawrence
Taylor or Aundray Bruce,'' said Jones, an agent who tried to sign
Kearse as a client. ``So far, he's been L.T.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Tennessee drafted Jevon, I asked (general manager) Floyd
Reese what they were going to do with him. Floyd said, `Hey, Bo,
we're just going to drop him down and tell him to go.'
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that makes Jevon so good is he's relentless. He gets
blocked, but he plays with a great motor and he continues to make
plays. Some guys get blocked at the point of attack, and you can't
find them the rest of the game. Jevon gets blocked, but he sheds
and chases down plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many rookies who wear down as the season progresses,
Kearse has improved each week. Despite being double-teamed most of
the time, he has at least one-half sack in the last seven games.
During that period, he has 8{ sacks, 39 tackles and seven forced
fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jevon wants to be as good as there's ever been,'' Titans
defensive coordinator Gregg Williams said. ``As long as he stays
healthy and keeps that humble drive to be the best, he has the
ability to be the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid's just amazing. There are four or five plays a year
where no matter how intense a fan you are or how intense a coach
you are, you have to just watch and wonder at some of the things
he's done athletically.''
</P>
<P>
   To beef up the pass rush, the Titans hired University of Houston
defensive line coach Jim Washburn, drafted Kearse and defensive
tackle John Thornton in the first two rounds and signed veteran
free agents Jason Fisk and Mike Jones.
</P>
<P>
   With three games left, they have 46 sacks one season after
registering 30. They have a chance to break the team record of 52,
set in 1993 when the Buddy Ryan-coached defense led the NFL in
sacks and run defense.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse is the catalyst. His unrestrained exuberance is
contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very competitive, and I'm never satisfied with a
performance or with a play,'' Kearse said. ``I had three sacks in
the first Cleveland game, but I wasn't satisfied. I'm the same way
off the field, whether it's fishing or playing video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my competitiveness comes from not having anything when
I was growing up. With seven kids, we had to reach out and grab
something if we wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearse is reaching out and grabbing quarterbacks and running
backs in impressive fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches don't make the game too complicated,'' he said.
``They don't make me play like a robot. They let me use my talent.
They let me play my game.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, if I'm going against a 350-pound tackle, I know
he's slower than me. I'm not going to sit there and take him on.
I'm going to run around him and soften him up. You run around him a
couple of times, you beat him at an angle. If you go back door,
he'll start softening up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some players take on blocks by using good hand strength. I'll
do that when I have to do it. But if I don't have to do it, I'm
going to run around them and try to make a play in the backfield or
on the other side of the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearse left Florida after his junior year. He was supposed to go
high in the first round, but he lasted until the Titans selected
him with the 16th pick. He's working hard to prove a lot of teams
made mistakes by passing him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they just didn't want to take a chance on taking a
`tweener' like me,'' Kearse said. ``I was moved around a lot in
college. I think other teams saw me as just a big, athletic guy.
Some thought I had to play outside linebacker. Others thought I was
just a pass rusher and not an every-down player. Teams didn't want
to take a chance, and that motivated me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team that passed me up may not play us, but they can
pick up the paper, see our record and my stats.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Kearse played so many positions at Florida, scouts
didn't get a solid look at his performance against the run. When he
read that he was a one-dimensional player, Kearse found even more
incentive.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the day I was drafted, I worked out by myself back home
in Florida,'' he said. ``I worked on good run technique. I knew I
had to get stronger to play the run in the NFL. I got in the weight
room and got stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I got to camp, I was playing the run better than I
was rushing the quarterback. I'd put a lot of anger in falling in
the draft, and I tried to justify it by telling myself that they
(scouts) said I couldn't play the run. It took a while for me to
stop the run and pass rush the way I'm capable.''
</P>
<P>
   The coaches say watching Kearse on game film is similar to
watching former Detroit running back Barry Sanders. Kearse does so
many things instinctively he doesn't realize it until he sees the
film, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Kearse said, ``they (teammates and coaches) say,
`Man, how did you do that?' It just comes naturally. Sometimes, I
can't believe it myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, neither can his coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendously prideful kid,'' Williams said. ``Jevon
doesn't want to be recognized as a finesse player. The complete
player has to be a physical football player to play in the
trenches. A lot of it has to do with Jim Washburn, a coach who's
making a whole group of players more physical and aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jevon has such great flexibility in his hips that he's able to
dip and get faster on his third, fourth and fifth steps. To be a
complete player, he has to learn how to take speed to power, and he
needs to learn how to take speed and be able to work it back
underneath. He's just now starting to scratch the surface on those
things, and that's scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he gets those things down and adds a little more body
weight, he can be as good as anyone who has ever played on that
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearse had such problems keeping weight on that Fisher got a
nutritionist to prepare meals for him to make him gain weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been as low as 245, and I'm hoping to be 265 or 270 in
the future,'' Kearse said. ``I want to be stout at the point of
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The more success Kearse has, the more attention he draws.
Opponents are using a tight end to help the tackle double-team him.
They also are keeping in a running back to chip-block Kearse. The
coaches have been countering lately by moving him to the other
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that idea,'' he said. ``It works best for the team
because it frees me up or frees someone else up. It doesn't matter
to me who makes the play. The only thing that matters is that we
win. This season has been a lot of fun. Those teams that passed me
up can see I'm having the time of my life in Tennessee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 0202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
