<HEADER>
A1685 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN--NBA-HNS &LR;      12-17 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--NBA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Faster-paced NBA packs plenty into still-young season
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MICHAEL MURPHY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The NBA season is only at the quarter pole _ or thereabouts _
and we've already had more action than in all of last season's
lockout-squeezed schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have forced an All-Star team of talent to miss large
portions of the season, and two coaches have bitten the dust for
one reason or another.
</P>
<P>
   Word around the Alamo City is the Spurs have gone from
contenders to contenters, playing without the fire and enthusiasm
that typified their charge to the 1999 NBA championship, the first
in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   And their opponents in the Finals, the New York Knicks, are once
again a case study in family dysfunction. The Portland Trail
Blazers, everyone's preseason darlings, won't go 82-0, even though
there were some who (almost) jokingly hinted they might.
</P>
<P>
   There have been the requisite surprises (Danny Ainge walking
away from a talent-rich Phoenix team? Miami one of the top-scoring
teams in the league? Seattle nine games over .500? Philadelphia at
.500 despite playing without Allen Iverson for 10 games?) and
disappointments (Minnesota at 7-12? New Jersey 6-17? Detroit 11-12?
Washington 7-17?).
</P>
<P>
   But at least it's been fun to watch, unlike last year's root
canal of a season.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to rule changes, scoring is way up, and (almost) everyone
wants to run. Phil Jackson is adding a few more decimal points to
his win percentage, only this time with the 19-5 Los Angeles
Lakers. Shaquille O'Neal, who has finally added rebounding and shot
blocking to his duties with the Lakers, is looking like the next
Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, though, we've said goodbye to Charles Barkley,
who blew out a tendon in his knee, ending a storied, but ringless,
career.
</P>
<P>
   But on the plus side, we haven't had to deal with Dennis Rodman.
Yet.
</P>
<P>
   It's been interesting, hasn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Especially for New York and San Antonio, last season's Eastern
Conference and Western Conference champions, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Patrick Ewing, the Knicks are again the city's most
popular dope opera. Ewing, who had missed a big chunk of the season
recovering from the torn left Achilles' tendon he suffered in last
season's Eastern Conference finals, finally returned to the lineup
last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Ewing wants to be the star of the show, not a supporting
player, causing a rift on the team. And when the media ask him
about it, Ewing gets churlish about everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just tired of it, so tired of all the garbage here,''
Ewing said. ``With everything that's happened the last couple of
years, maybe I've overstayed my welcome here. Some days I think
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed playing in New York. I've given my heart and soul to
this team. I've got a lot of basketball left in me. But I'm tired
of all the other stuff that goes with playing here.''
</P>
<P>
   The intrigue is just as thick in San Antonio, where the Spurs
have struggled, despite their 17-7 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our biggest problem is the adjustment period,'' said
David Robinson of being the defending champs. ``We're not trusting
each other and we're not helping each other. So a lot of our
problems are just reading each other and trying to play together.
As we watch the tape, it becomes more increasingly obvious that
we're not trusting each other yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can trust us. Here are the hottest topics around the
league at the quarter pole:
</P>
<P>
   Trade rumors _ The NBA's trade season opened Wednesday, but
there wasn't a flurry of activity. Yet. But everyone's talking, and
some of the names being discussed are interesting:
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who needs a power forward who can knock down the
16-foot jumper, would love to get the grossly overpaid Juwan ``Dr.
Do Little'' Howard from Washington. Going to Washington would be
the usual Lakers CARE package of Glen Rice, Robert Horry and Travis
Knight to offset Howard's $15 million salary.
</P>
<P>
   Rice will be asking for $14 million next year, and few teams
think he's worth it, but they don't want to alienate David Falk,
Rice's agent, by refusing to grant the rich extension.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls would love to unload Toni Kukoc, who apparently has
medical history's first recorded case of terminal back spasms.
Kukoc, who hasn't played since Nov. 9, is rumored to be waiting for
this season to end so he can head back to Europe and not have all
these NBA demands placed on him. Like play defense. And they say
Scottie Pippen couldn't take following in Jordan's footsteps. At
least Pippen sat out only 1.8 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves have fallen off the NBA map despite the
presence of Kevin Garnett and Terrell Brandon, losing seven
straight. So the T-Wolves (in sheep's clothing) are looking to dump
Brandon, who signed a $54 million extension last season. Brandon is
on the outs supposedly because he provides little, if any,
leadership. Interested parties include the Raptors, Warriors and
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics are willing to part ways with ``Employee No. 8'' _
Antoine Walker, perhaps packaging him with Vitaly Potapenko.
Nobody's interested in having Walker punch their time clock,
however, given his tough-guy behavior and a shooting touch that is
less accurate than Barkley's drives on the local fairways.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst-kept secret in the league, Philadelphia is shopping
Larry Hughes. The perception is Sixers coach Larry Brown can live
with Iverson or Hughes, but not both. Rumored offers include the
Raptors' Tracy McGrady (who turned down a contract extension) and
the Nets' Kerry Kittles, who practically has a blue light flashing
beside him _ that's how eager the Nyets are to get rid of him and
his bum knees _ or Kendall Gill, depending on who's reporting the
rumor.
</P>
<P>
   But talk is the wish list Brown sent to Santa has the Mavericks'
Michael Finley at the top. And you know Mavericks coach/general
manager/guru Don Nelson could do something that stupid.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks would be willing to part with Charlie Ward or Chris
Childs, perhaps even both. Brandon is the apple of the Big Apple's
eye, but Minnesota general manger Kevin McHale wants shooter deluxe
Allan Houston in return. The Knicks have politely declined.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State, which got a ``no thanks'' when they offered Mookie
Blaylock to Minnesota for Brandon, is shopping Donyell Marshall. A
possible destination is New Jersey for Kittles or Gill, who has one
year left on his contract. Some reports have Gill, apparently the
``Zelig'' of trade talks, headed to Cleveland for Wesley Person.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks are interested in moving Isaiah Rider, even though
he's been playing the best ball of his career. Rider, in the last
year of his current deal, wants a fat extension, hence the solid
play. But the Hawks, wary of Rider's troubled history, believe if
they give him the new deal, he'll go haywire again.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested? Yep, the Nets, who are offering _ who else? _
Gill, who must be in the Greensheet.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries _ How about a roster that includes Iverson (broken
thumb), Kobe Bryant (broken hand), Barkley (knee), Hakeem Olajuwon
(hernia), Ewing (Achilles' tendon), Tim Hardaway (knee), Brian
Grant (knee), Paul Pierce (ankle) and Kukoc (back yeah, right)?
</P>
<P>
   Those are just the biggest names that have taken the pause for
the gauze.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers have taken a big hit by Zydrunas Ilgauskas'
continuing foot problems, the Golden State Warriors are waiting for
Erick Dampier to get back from a knee injury and the Heat only
recently got Otis Thorpe back from his broken right thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Rod Williams still hasn't played for the Mavericks because
of his bad back and Hersey Hawkins had his streak of 527 straight
games played end last Friday when he tore his left calf muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches in the crosshairs _ Danny Ainge stepped down in Phoenix.
Brian Hill was stepped on Thursday in Vancouver. Who's next?
</P>
<P>
   Don Casey in New Jersey, who would no doubt pay his own way out
if that rumored trade for Rider goes through. All you need to know
about Casey's chances are the Nets now have Yankees boss George
Steinbrenner as a partner. Yeah, Casey's packing his bags right
now.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' Chris Ford, who watched his team score three
points in the second quarter against the Lakers this week, an
NBA-record low. Three points? If he wasn't fired after that, then
Ford has to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Carlesimo in Golden State. Heck, the owner probably will
choke him if the Warriors keep losing the way they have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 0204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
