<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1686 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-L     12-17 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC'S PLAUSIBLY LIVE SUMMER GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Question 1 of the Great American TV Quiz: When NBC
combines forces with cable partners CNBC and MSNBC next September
to televise the Sydney Summer Olympic Games, they'll force upon the
good ol' USA a staggering 435 hours of coverage. How many of them
will be as-it-happens live?
</P>
<P>
   a) 435.
</P>
<P>
   b) 201.
</P>
<P>
   c) None.
</P>
<P>
   The correct answer, of course, is...
</P>
<P>
   Did we mention this was (begin ital)NBC(end ital) doing the
event?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is, of course, zilch.
</P>
<P>
   Not because there's an impossible time difference to deal with.
Los Angeles is 18 hours behind Australia _ meaning if it's 8-to-11
p.m. prime-time window here, it's 2-to-5 p.m. the next day with the
sun ablazin' there.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the peacock will drop the goose egg, as NBC Olympics
co-chairman and long-time network sports TV exec Dennis Swanson
tried to explain Thursday, is because it makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   To advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't do any good to take the major events in an
Olympics and run them in hours when no one can see them,'' said
Swanson, who flew in to L.A. from New York for NBC's announcement
Thursday at the Western Cable Show at the L.A. Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time shifting can put the most visible and desirable sports at
the peak of prime time, when most can get in front of a TV. There's
a reason why the World Series isn't in the afternoon anymore. Prime
time is where they have the biggest audience.''
</P>
<P>
   And...
</P>
<P>
   ``And advertisers want maximum viewership,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the World Series is live.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC, which forces its way into 71 million homes, and MSNBC,
limping along in another 51 million homes (but hopefully more after
this announcement), will combine for 172 hours of ``original''
programming over 18 days. Please note, it's the first time coverage
of an Olympic Summer Games will be on cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   And because MSNBC will carry preliminary rounds of the men's
soccer match on Wednesday, Sept.13, it'll mark the first time
American TV coverage of an Olympiad will begin on cable.
</P>
<P>
   Since MSNBC will also show 101 hours of repeat broadcasts from
midnight-to-7 a.m. on weekdays and midnight-to-6 a.m. on weekends
(or when it's prime-time in Sydney). That makes 273 hours of cable
filler to go with 162{ hours on NBC's over-the-air channel.
</P>
<P>
   True, it does mean viewers from the '96 Games in Atlanta who
felt slighted by overlooked coverage of the entire boxing
competition as well as all the games of the U.S. women's softball
and soccer teams will be appeased this time around.
</P>
<P>
   It just won't be... do we have to say it again?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a time and distance discrepancy that I don't think
bothers the viewers as much as it seems to bother the newspaper
writers who devote so many column inches to this issue over the
year,'' said Jim Lampley, hired back by the network to host MSNBC's
Olympic studio show. (Live, we should add).
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole time-frame issue is something viewers are quite
accustomed to making accommodations for, either to watch the event
knowing what already happened, or as something that helps them
maintain a willing suspension of disbelief.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Pat O'Brien, the former long-time CBS Sports employee who
returns to host the CNBC side of it: ``I think people accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of things in life we accept, true.
</P>
<P>
   Death, taxes and tape-delayed Olympics on NBC will always be a
threesome.
</P>
<P>
   No loyalty oath required: Neither Lampley nor O'Brien envisioned
they'd be working on an Olympic event again, but all of the sudden,
the two who used to work together at KNX-Channel 2 about 10 years
ago (O'Brien as a news anchor and Lampley as the sports guy) are
sharing a summer down under.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some Olympics done without me, but not enough
of them,'' said Lampley, the current HBO boxing broadcaster who'll
undertake his 10th Olympic assignment. He was the late-night
co-host for NBC's past two Olympics (Atlanta and Barcelona) and
worked for ABC (on five Games, including Los Angeles), CBS
(Albertville) and Turner Sports (Nagano).
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the last thing I expected after my contract with NBC
dissolved a few years ago,'' he said. ``I knew NBC had the next 12
years of Olympics and because I'd be at HBO, I figured that'd be
the end of that. Now, out of the blue, I'm back in it. I'm sure
Juan Antonio Samaranch was saying, `We've got to find a way to have
him involved.'''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said he'd planned to go to Sydney anyway with ``Access
Hollywood.'' He says putting on an NBC blazer after all his years
at CBS won't creep him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even sure NBC people wear blazers, but if they do,
I'll wear it,'' said O'Brien, who hosted CBS' entertaining
late-night studio show from Albertville in '94. ``This is a great
way to come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
