<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALLEY MAKES CONTRIBUTION FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's generally accepted as fact that the Lakers won't
go far without acquiring a bruising big man to back up Shaquille
O'Neal. John Salley thinks they've already got one.
</P>
<P>
   Salley seemed to prove his point Thursday, ably filling in for
the foul-plagued O'Neal and holding the Lakers together long enough
to pull out a 95-88 victory over the Atlanta Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a season-high 20 minutes in relief, Salley scored seven
points and contributed a blocked shot, two rebounds, four fouls and
some nifty passing out of the high post.
</P>
<P>
   Unspectacular, but effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felt like I'm worth my money now,'' Salley quipped. ``I had to
make up for that Houston game (when O'Neal was suspended and Salley
started).''
</P>
<P>
   Salley can't give the Lakers what O'Neal does, but he sees his
role simply: ``Make something happen. Get a tip, get a rebound, get
a pass, foul hard, block a shot, score when the opportunity's
there. Play basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   And for those who believe the Lakers desperately need another
big man?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are called critics, and I don't pay attention to
critics,'' Salley said. ``Phil (Jackson) knows. Basketball people
know what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Good eye: Derek Fisher had a contact lens knocked out of his
right eye when he caught a Dikembe Mutombo elbow and had to play
the last 1:59 of the game with one contact.
</P>
<P>
   He managed to make one of two free throws and grab a steal
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely split vision _ one good eye, one bad eye,'' he
said. ``But I had to go to the free-throw line and at least make
one of those free throws.''
</P>
<P>
   He shot with both eyes open, creating some blurred vision,
rather than shoot one-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it, but I figured I have a better chance with
(both eyes), a 75 percent chance of going in, instead of just 50.''
</P>
<P>
   Dispute: Lakers second-year guard Tyronn Lue is one of 16
defendants named in a $30 million lawsuit filed by agent Eric
Fleisher, according to a report in the Rocky Mountain News of
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher is accusing a former business associate, agent Andrew
Miller, of essentially poaching his clients to start his own firm.
Lue, a Miller client, is one of six NBA players named in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Miller called the allegations ``absolute fiction.'' Lue declined
to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Lue, on the injured list with a sore left knee,
said he's feeling better, and he expects to begin practicing again
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Travis Knight will be eligible to be activated from the
injured list after tonight's game, but Jackson said that's
unlikely, barring an injury to another Laker big man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
