<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1690 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MAGNOLIA-MOVIE-LADN     12-17 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGNOLIA-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD GETS IT WRONG IN `MAGNOLIA'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Dennis McCarthy  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If ever a movie should come with a neon warning label, it's the
film ``Magnolia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Warning _ if you've believed all the hype and think you're
about to see a movie depicting real life in Los Angeles' San
Fernando Valley for the vast majority of people who live here _
turn around, go home, and watch a rerun of the `Brady Bunch'
instead.''
</P>
<P>
   They're both about as realistic, you'll save $7, and at least
you won't feel like you need a shower after watching the ``Brady
Bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolia'' bombed big time with the people I took to see it
Wednesday night at a screening at Warner Bros. studios _ the people
who know the real Magnolia Boulevard and North Hollywood areas
better than anyone because they're out there on those streets every
day.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Bogart, a Los Angeles police patrol officer from North
Hollywood Division; Guy Weddington McCreary, who grew up in North
Hollywood about 10 miles north of downtown Los Angeles and is the
great grandson of the man who developed the area; and Lori Dinkin,
president of the Valley Village Homeowners Association, near North
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   They all take serious issue with the film's director, Paul
Thomas Anderson, who told Los Angeles Daily News Film Critic Bob
Strauss that he wanted to make ``the epic, the all-time great San
Fernando Valley movie.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. Not even close. It's a three-hour root canal. A minus
four stars, these people say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that picture is supposed to represent the vast majority of
life in the Valley _ heaven help us all,'' McCreary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are people who will think it is great, but I
walked out of the theater thinking, Whew, thank God my life isn't
like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like that'' is a steady stream of life's losers bombarding the
audience for three hours with reams of perfunctory, loud profanity,
cocaine snorting, women hating and a little child abuse thrown in
just for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   It makes Anderson's last movie, ``Boogie Nights'' look like
``Toy Story.'' Trust me. You don't want to take Grandma to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Bogart took his grandmother Wednesday night. I've
never seen a person squirm that much outside of a dentist's chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw `Boogie Nights,' so I knew the director's work, and told
my grandmother it might not be a good movie for her to see,''
Bogart said. ``She wanted to go, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very uncomfortable throughout the whole movie, and so
was she. She asked me after the movie if people really talked like
that, and I told her no, that was the extreme, and it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (police officers) deal with a lot of tragedy, death and
destruction on the streets, but nothing like the kind of personal
tragedy this movie tried to portray in its characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was magnified 10 times from any kind of reality,'' he said.
``It's certainly not the Magnolia Boulevard I work on everyday as a
police officer.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is what angers these people more than anything. The
movie may have excellent acting, may even carry a message, if you
want to wade through a three-hour headache and frogs' guts to find
it. But, in the end, it's a fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's being sold as the Valley's movie, and that's an insult to
everyone living here,'' said Dinkin, president of the Valley
Village Homeowners' Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of young and old people, all generations, living
here, and nobody even remotely close to them was portrayed on the
screen. Where were the normal people?
</P>
<P>
   ``The director showed only the worst of the losers. Maybe that's
the only people he knows, but it's not the people we all know, not
the Valley I see out on my streets everyday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movie wasn't about the Valley, it was about the ugly side
of life anywhere in this country,'' she said. ``It's three hours of
pure garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   A downer, McCreary calls it. ``It would be pathetic if that
really was the Valley.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there will be those who will read this and think we
just don't get it, but that's the sad part,'' McCreary said. ``We
do get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This picture is a sad, sick commentary on our society, and who
wants to spend $7 and waste three hours to see that?''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 0213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
