<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 03:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1711 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-USC-WRITETHRU-LAD     12-17 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S LOSS ANGERS BIBBY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH _ USC coach Henry Bibby was so disgusted after the
Trojans' 76-66 loss to Long Beach State before 2,739 at the Pyramid
on Thursday night, he made the team drive back to Los Angeles
immediately after the game and watch films of the setback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys didn't play,'' Bibby said. ``Sam Clancy played and David
Bluthenthal played for a half and that's it. We didn't play smart
or with structure. It was incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   USC (5-5) led 39-37 at halftime, but scored just 27 points in
the second half and shot 24 percent in the final 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Brian Scalabrine scored just four points, 12 below his
average, and fouled out in only 27 minutes of action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a downer for us,'' Bibby said. ``We had come
off a couple good wins. I thought we didn't want to win. You can't
just show up.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an ideal situation for the Trojans to play such a dud,
considering the game was televised on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Even USC's leading scorer, Clancy, struggled. He scored 19
points but was 5 for 18 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I couldn't make an outside shot,'' Clancy said. ``We
seemed out of sync the whole night. They just wanted it more than
we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss is particularly damaging because the Trojans don't seem
to be getting much better than they were at the start of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   They were unable to stop Long Beach's frontcourt, as 6-foot-11
center Mate Milisa had 15 points while forwards James Williams and
Antrone Lee each scored 14.
</P>
<P>
   USC's bench was also an issue. Bibby used it sparingly, but the
reserves scored only two points.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby acknowledged that the Trojans were in a near no-win
situation before the game the Trojans played like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough game to play,'' Bibby said. ``They have
everything to gain from a win. It's not an automatic win. We have
to go down and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Bibby added, ``It's a must game for us too.''
</P>
<P>
   Bluthenthal scored a career-high 19 points for USC, but only two
in the second half. He supplied most of the offense for the Trojans
in the first half, scoring 17 points, including three shots from
3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the Trojans were not nearly as effective in the
first half. Clancy scored eight points but made just 3 of 9 shots.
Shooting guard Jeff Trepagnier made 3 of 8, and had six points.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a 36-29 lead, the Trojans were outscored by Long
Beach 8-3 over the final 4:11.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans led by as many as nine points twice in the half.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Bluthenthal paced USC, hitting two 3-pointers
and scoring eight points as the Trojans took an 18-11 lead with
12:17 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   His tip-in and two free throws then gave the Trojans a 22-15 as
he scored 12 of USC's first 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby did not substitute until 10 minutes into the game, when he
inserted point guard Rashad Jones. But Jones lasted only one minute
after committing a foul and turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the game, Bibby set four goals for the Trojans: ``I
want to see us play better defense, rebound the basketball, make
free throws, execute the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: USC forward Jarvis Turner, who is out with a stress
fracture in his foot, will see a doctor next week, but is not
expected to begin practicing until Christmas. That would mean the
earliest he could return is Dec. 29 against Northwestern, USC's
final game before Pac-10 play begins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
