<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BELTRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT: DODGERS WON'T LOSE BELTRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A television report late Thursday said the Dodgers
would be fined for signing third baseman Adrian Beltre, but the
club would not lose him to free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports News said an announcement would come Monday from
Major League Baseball stating the Dodgers wouldn't lose the
20-year-old Beltre, signed at 15, because the statute of
limitations expired. Beltre was signed more than five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But that rule may come down to an interpretation. A rule states
a player has one year to file for a grievance after the claim is
made, baseball officials said. According to representatives of the
player's association, that date was in late March when Beltre and
his agent, Scott Boras, first discovered Beltre was signed
illegally. Players must be 16 to sign a contract.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone nor Boras could be
reached for comment. Dodgers officials said Thursday evening they
hadn't heard a ruling from the commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   If Beltre isn't declared a free agent, Gene Orza, the associate
general counsel for the players association, said he expects the
union to file a grievance. Boras echoed those sentiments numerous
times.
</P>
<P>
   The issue would move in front of an independent arbitrator,
which could take until late January to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said regardless of what the ruling was, the Dodgers would
move forward based upon it and not worry about appeals or
grievances.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, executive vice president of baseball operations
for the commissioner's office, is handling the investigation. He
said during the weekend that all interviews were finished, but he
still needed to talk with commissioner Bud Selig about the issue.
Selig will make the final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre hit .275 with 15 homers, 67 RBI and 18 stolen bases in
his first full season with the Dodgers. If he's declared a free
agent, he could make as much as $550 million over seven years,
industry insiders believe.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were fined $200,000 during the season after an
investigation led to a pair of Cuban-born Dodgers minor-leaguers
being declared free agents because the club broke baseball rules in
signing them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
