<P>
   Russia's most popular personality these days is Putin, who was
handpicked for the job by Yeltsin four months ago. His name is not
on the ballot Sunday, but his mark will be all over the results.
Putin's strong image as a leader invested wholly in the war in the
breakaway Chechen republic has altered the contours of Russian
politics. A decent showing among pro-Kremlin parliamentary
candidates Sunday could solidify his advantage in the presidential
sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six political parties and some 2,400 candidates _ from
Marxist ideologists to former gangsters, capitalist tycoons to
alleged criminals seeking immunity _ are vying for the Duma, the
lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a bitter battle, heightened by the significance of
the upcoming presidential race. The make-up of the parliament is
important, but it pales in comparison to the immense power of the
presidency under Russia's current constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's opponents had hoped the parliamentary election
results would reflect a resounding rejection of Yeltsin's failed
reform policies and his erratic leadership. The country's deep
economic distress and the taint of Kremlin-involved banking
scandals, they hoped, would pave the way for a new populist party
formed earlier this year and mean greater gains for the leading
opposition party, the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Chechnya foiled that game plan. It altered the
campaign agenda from economics and corruption to war and
patriotism. Virtually every leading politician backed the Chechen
offensive and those who dared to question it were publicly
denounced as disloyal.
</P>
<P>
   If the polls hold true in Sunday's balloting, the new Duma will
look much like the current one. The Communist Party will win retain
its leading but not controlling bloc of about 140 seats, faring as
they did in the 1995 elections with about 20 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kremlin may emerge with something equal, according to
some polls. The Unity Party was literally invented by the Kremlin
just a few months ago and stocked with an odd assortment of
candidates. From nowhere, it has drawn its popularity by
association with the tough-talking Putin and his war against
Chechnya's Muslim separatists.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive in Chechnya has dominated the news and restored a
sense of national pride after Russians suffered a humiliating
defeat there in the 1994-96 war. It also turned Putin from an
unknown into an idol, with a job approval rating was near 80
percent among Russians. This, for a man whose name barely
registered in August.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Putin's public approval ratings are the highest of any
Russian politician since those his boss, President Yeltsin, in his
heyday in 1991, when he led the democracy drive that helped topple
the Soviet regime. Today, however, Yeltsin is mired in the single
digits amid the economic turmoil, corruption scandals and his
chronic health lapses.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Kremlin party's gains have come at the expense of two
other presidential aspirants, former Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov and Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov. They teamed up earlier this
year to form the Fatherland-All Russia bloc, who in most polls has
dipped to third place.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Primakov was the leading prospect for president,
based on polls. But he and Luzhkov have taken a beating from
pro-Kremlin media owned by a group of wealthy tycoons _ known as
the oligarchs _ who helped Yeltsin defeat his Communist rival,
Gennady Zyuganov, in the 1996 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Primakov, 70, was targeted by a vicious ad
campaign suggesting he was past his prime. The billboards and
leaflets wished the able-bodied Primakov a happy birthday, but
showed only a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov, a popular mayor with extensive and shadowy business
ties, has been portrayed as corrupt _ including a suggestion that
he was linked to the murder of a prominent American businessman,
Paul Tatum, who was gunned down in a dispute over the control of a
luxury hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Both Primakov and Luzhkov have accused Yeltsin's aides of dirty
tricks, including attempted bribes to Fatherland-All Russia Party
members to withdraw from the election.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, it was widely assumed that the Fatherland-All
Russia Party would offer voters an attractive third way _ not the
old policies of the Soviet-era Communists, and not the unbridled
capitalism of Yeltsin ``reformers'' that has made the vast majority
of Russians poorer than they were a decade ago. Just a month ago,
it was even with the Communists in polls, with about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If Sunday's results mirror the pre-election surveys, analysts
say the Kremlin will have achieved just what it wanted _ derailing
Primakov's presidential bid before it ever got started and assuring
that the Communists remain the key, but still ineffective,
adversary in the Duma.
</P>
<P>
   But measuring the political temperature in Russia is not so
simple. And a Kremlin victory in Sunday's elections may not mean
much in January is Russian troops become bogged down in Chechnya,
or suffer heavy losses such as the more than 100 soldiers
reportedly killed in an unsuccessful assault on Grozny last week.
</P>
<P>
   Putin and Primakov are proof that a lot can change in four
months.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Primakov's high popularity ratings were said to be
a sign of the country's need for a ``father figure'' and a steady
force amid the traumatic changes Russia has endured in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Putin's popularity _ three separate polls show him leading
his nearest rival by an almost 3-to-1 margin if the presidential
race were held today _ stems from the notion that the nation likes
a ``strong hand'' pressing a war that many Russians feel is
necessary to bring order to its southern border, and to show the
world that it will not bow easily to international pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the mercurial results reflect a weary Russian
electorate disenchanted with democracy and an ailing, out of touch
president. They are hungry simply for a solid leader that will
actively guide the nation through troubled times.
</P>
<P>
   In the Duma races, despite the large number of parties seeking
seats, only a handful will gain a place in parliament. Under
Russia's election laws, half of the 450 seats are set aside for
candidates running in individual districts while the other half are
allocated to national party lists based on how the parties finish
in the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   To gain a place in parliament, a political party must receive at
least 5 percent of the overall vote. Only four parties qualified in
the 1995 elections.
</P>
<P>
   If opinion polls prove correct, the Communists should lead the
way, with the pro-Kremlin Unity Party and the Fatherland-All Russia
Party roughly dividing the seats that had been held by the 1995
pro-Kremlin party, Our Home is Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Reform-minded liberals from the established Yabloko Party of
Grigory Yavlinsky and the newly formed Union of Right Forces should
gain a small number of seats, but manage to cross the 5-percent
threshold.
</P>
<P>
   No single party will hold a 226-seat majority, and how a ruling
Duma coalition may be aligned is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   There has been little debate over the issues, but the major
parties generally agree on the need to simplify the tax code and
none _ not even the Communist Party _ is advocating printing money
to get Russia out of its current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are witnessing a war between forces that differ very little
in their views and programs,'' said Yevgeny Yasin, an analyst and
former economic minister.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Russia's fledgling democracy remains primitive and its
election process is flawed.
</P>
<P>
   However, amid the dirty campaign tactics and political disarray,
there are positive signs, say analysts. Foremost, is the mere fact
that free parliamentary elections are taking place for the third
time in eight years after the collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most remarkable event is that this vote is not a
remarkable event,'' said Michael McFaul, a Russian scholar at
Stanford University. ``This is the longest-standing electoral body
in 1,000 years of Russian history.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
