<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-UGA-EVANS18-COX     12-17 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-EVANS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dogs' Evans quells doubts
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ According to Georgia coach Jim Harrick, only about
15 percent to 20 percent of junior college transfers contribute
significantly in their first season in a Division I-A basketball
program. Fewer than that make what is considered an impact on their
new team.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick shared that theory with Anthony Evans in their first
conversation upon the forward's arrival on campus from Neosho
County (Kan.) Community College this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me which percentage did I fall into _ the ones that
take a year or the ones that make an impact?'' Evans said this
week. ``I told him, `I can make an impact.' There wasn't any doubt
in my mind about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not in Evans' mind, but there was considerable doubt among
many others, Harrick included. While no one seemed to question
whether Evans would be a useful player in the SEC and ACC, few
predicted the overwhelming success that he has experienced his
first two months at Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's game at Marshall, the 6-foot-7, 265-pound
forward from Decatur is the Bulldogs' second-leading scorer (16.9
points per game) and top rebounder (10.3). With 18 points and 11
rebounds in Georgia's 68-67 upset victory against Wake Forest last
Saturday, Evans recorded his fifth consecutive ``double-double'' in
points and rebounds. He also leads the team with 10 steals.
</P>
<P>
   Evans' numbers are not the product of soft competition. They've
come against Wake Forest, Georgia Tech, Louisville, Kansas and
North Carolina State. What's more, Evans is putting them up against
defenders who usually stand 3 to 6 inches taller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea we were getting what we got,'' Georgia's Harrick
said. ``He's exceeded all my expectations. I've always felt junior
college players needed a year before they really contribute.
Watching him in practice, I knew he could do it against our guys.
But he's been able to do it against everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans' scoring knack is the product of three attributes: great
hands, strength and quickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he could make millions of dollars in the NFL as a
tight end,'' said Jeff Guiot, Evans' junior college coach at Neosho
County. Indeed, Evans was a favorite target of Georgia quarterback
Quincy Carter while the two were at Southwest DeKalb High. But
Evans injured a knee and gave up the sport after his junior season.
</P>
<P>
   What Evans lacks in height, he makes up for in strength and
girth. He's the consummate wide body and he knows how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Guiot did a good job of teaching me how to use my body
and seal off,'' said Evans, whose NBA idols include Charles Barkley
and Larry Johnson. ``He used to bang me with these pads. He'd push
me just as I would go up for a shot. He told me I was always going
to be going up against 6-9, 6-10 guys, night in and night out, so I
might as well get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans does everything quickly on the court _ moving his feet,
getting off his shot, jumping for rebounds, throwing the outlet
pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a special knack, a special talent,'' Harrick said.
``He's got great hands. He's very quick with the release on his
shot. And he's got the greatest outlet pass of anybody I think I've
ever coached. He can rebound the ball and throw the outlet pass to
the guard in one motion. Our team is starting to sense that and
reacting to it pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans' outlet pass was best displayed against Wake Forest. His
half-court pass after a Demon Deacons basket with 3.8 seconds set
up the winning 3-point shot by Adrian Jones.
</P>
<P>
   With Georgia's trip to Marshall, Evans' basketball career has
come full circle. Had Evans qualified for freshman admission after
high school, he said he likely would have signed with the
Thundering Herd, who gave him his first in-home visit. Marshall,
Mercer and Georgia State were his most vigorous pursuers at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   But after his two seasons at Neosho, Evans was holding
scholarship offers from Arizona State, Kentucky and Tennessee as
well as Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew coming in people had doubts about me, about my
height,'' Evans said. ``But I always believed in my heart I could
play in the SEC, ACC, anywhere in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, everyone else is starting to believe, too.
</P>
<P>
   THE ANTHONY EVANS FILE
</P>
<P>
   Full name: Anthony Maurice Evans
</P>
<P>
   Born: Oct. 9, 1978, Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Raised: Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   High school: Southwest DeKalb
</P>
<P>
   Junior college: Neosho County Community College, Chanute, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   College: University of Georgia
</P>
<P>
   Height, weight: 6 feet 7, 265 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Position: Forward
</P>
<P>
   Accomplishments: Averages 16.9 points and 10.3 rebounds.... Has
recorded five consecutive double-doubles in points and rebounds....
Was chosen the National Junior College Athletic Association (NJCAA)
Male Student-Athlete of the Year for 1999.... Had 3.80 grade-point
average while averaging 23.7 points and 9.1 rebounds at Neosho.
</P>
