<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1805 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-LATHAM-COLUMN18-COX     12-17 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   No one seems to want to have fun with the Y2K bug
</P>
<P>
   By Phil Latham
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ Gee, what with this Y2K thing, nobody has a
sense of humor anymore.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, I've been working on the local manager for
Southwestern Electric Power Company for some time now. All I want
him to do is, exactly one minute after midnight on Jan. 1, 2000,
flick the lights for a couple of seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Would that be a hoot, or what? And yet, for some reason, he
absolutely refuses to consider my request.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, those stick-in-the-muds at the financial institutions
won't hear my suggestion that, a few minutes after midnight, they
set some of their ATMs to begin spewing $1 bills. Would that really
cost much compared to the fun it would produce? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think that the ``bug'' in the Y2K was affecting our sense
of humor, not a computer chip. Do we all lose the ability to laugh
in the coming millennium? I hope not, because I have a feeling that
laughter is going to be more important in the days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to chuckle, think of Y2K as God's little joke on
humans to show us that we aren't quite as smart as we think we are.
In the span of roughly 40 years computers entered our lives, took
them over our to the point of becoming indispensable, then almost
became obsolete because of the ticking clock.
</P>
<P>
   How's this for funny: One hundred years ago, give or take, the
highest technology for getting water was a hand pump drawing it
from a well. With all our amazing technology, though, if the Y2K
bug isn't fixed, we'll be wishing for hand pumps and buckets.
</P>
<P>
   So I say we all lighten up. Bug or no bug, there isn't much
likelihood that anyone is going to die of thirst or hunger, even if
every computer on the face of Earth refuses to work on Jan. 1,
2000. High blood pressure from stress and worry, though, that's
another matter.
</P>
<P>
   So even if we can't get the electric utility to cut the power _
and we probably won't get city to turn off the main water tap,
either _ we can all have a little fun of our own, right?
</P>
<P>
   So at that New Years' Eve party, you can locate the breaker box
yourself and give everyone a quick charge of darkness at the
appointed time.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about going to the host in a not-so-quiet voice and
asking him, ``Why in the heck won't your toilet flush and who's
been taking Metamusel?'' The host might even pay you to do that if
he wants to clear out his guests.
</P>
<P>
   The fun goes beyond the scatological.
</P>
<P>
   If you happen to be going to one of those parties where people
drink too much, I suggest going out on lawn just after midnight,
pointing to the sky and shouting, ``They are here! They are here!''
</P>
<P>
   If the people are really drunk you could just wobble around and
ask if anyone else is feeling the earthquake. Better make sure the
toilets really are working before you try that one.
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Day, take a bunch of bananas back to your grocer
and tell him that they can't be peeled and are obviously not Y2K
compliant. Spouses who don't want to cook can say that the can
opener no longer works. Don't want to do the cleaning? Simple, have
you checked the mop to see if it is Y2K compliant? I'm guessing
that it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   The only way I'm going to be upset on Jan. 1 is if I discover
that my pink recliner isn't Y2K compatible. I've already done
extensive testing, but I intend to do much, much more.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (Texas) News
Messenger. His e-mail address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
