<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deaths spell injustice
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In 20 years of working with battered women, Nancy
Grigsby has never seen anything like it.
</P>
<P>
   Nine Miami Valley women have been murdered since June 1998,
suspected victims of domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   The Artemis Center for Alternatives to Domestic Violence has
lost five clients. ``What's going on here?'' asks Grigsby, the
agency's director. ``We've seen a huge escalation in domestic
violence homicides.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzie Thompson's murder by a Warren County Jail inmate
mistakenly let out for Thanksgiving furlough is only the most
outrageous example, Grigsby says, of what she sees every day: the
failure of the criminal justice system to protect battered women,
even against offenders with a long history of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of our mission is to change the community in which our
clients live, and I don't think we have done that,'' Grigsby says.
</P>
<P>
   William Chapman served time in a state prison for domestic
violence. He was jailed again after making harassing phone calls to
Thompson, violating his parole. Even though state parole officers
ordered him kept behind bars, he was granted a one-day furlough
after Warren County Sheriff Tom Ariss failed to tell Judge Dallas
Powers about the hold order.
</P>
<P>
   It gets worse. For most of the six days Chapman was on the
loose, nobody bothered to look for him.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson called the jail Nov. 29 to report that Chapman was
harassing her again. She was told that Chapman was still in jail.
(The computer system failed to tag him as absent.)
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 30 _ the day before Suzie Thompson died _ a deputy filed
an escape charge in Lebanon Municipal Court. But even then,
according to court documents, a perfunctory phone call was the only
attempt to bring Chapman back to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Unbelievable?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a more direct version of the homicides we see every
day,'' Grigsby says. ``The common thread is the failure to perceive
danger, to see things through the eyes of the potential victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Armanthua Beckwith, mother of six, was slain Nov. 1 after coming
off her shift as night custodian at Wogaman Elementary School in
Dayton. Her accused killer, Eric Fleming, is being held in lieu of
$1 million bond. When it might have mattered _ when it might have
saved Beckwith's life _ Fleming got every break in the book.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Fleming threw Beckwith to the ground and threatened her
with a knife. Despite four witnesses to the violence, the
prosecutor reduced the charge from a first-degree to a
fourth-degree misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day Fleming was sentenced in that case, he was
arraigned on charges stemming from a Sept. 14 stabbing during which
he threatened to kill Beckwith. He was sentenced to 30 days,
including time served, in the first attack, and his bond was
reduced from $25,000 to $2,000 in the stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you have three people who didn't get it _ the prosecutor
who reduced the case, the judge who didn't reject the plea, and
another judge who reduced the bond,'' Grigsby says. ``They missed
every opportunity to make sure he was in custody.''
</P>
<P>
   Grigsby is disheartened: ``After all these years of convening
task forces, writing protocols, relationship-building, and training
our butts off, and here we sit, looking at a list of dead
clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Ginsburg of Artemis Center puts it more bluntly: ``Here
we have victims saying, `Hello?' This guy is going to kill me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When are we going to listen?''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Thompson and Beckwith are concerned, never.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
