<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I'd write a longer letter if I weren't so modest
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Folks:
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's time again for the annual report on adventures and
accomplishments of the Minter family, which I know all of you have
been anxiously awaiting.
</P>
<P>
   It also is easier and cheaper than addressing Christmas cards
and licking all those stamps you have to stand in line at the post
office and spend half a Social Security check to get.
</P>
<P>
   We would have a lot more to tell if we hadn't spent so much of
the year in international travel. The Marco Polo lady was able to
find a real bargain on a tour of Australia, New Zealand, the Fiji
Islands, a stop in Hawaii, and a few other places I can't recall.
Not counting all the nifty made-in-China souvenirs we bought in
Australia, the trip didn't cost all that much more than our first
house.
</P>
<P>
   Because we were in the air for several days and about 100,000
miles, we earned so many Frequent Flier points we may never be able
to spend more than two nights at home in the next several years.
Thanks to our massive accumulation, Mrs. Christopher Columbus was
able to arrange a bonus trip to France in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   You won't believe this, but we actually made money on that one.
Thanks to our hard-earned Frequent Flier points, we had to pay only
$39 each for our tickets. Shortly after we got home, the airline
sent both of us a $100 voucher, along with apologies, for the three
hours we spent at Charles de Gaulle Airport in Paris waiting for
Curley and Moe to change a tire. That put us $122 ahead, although I
think we spent more than that on the bribes we had to pay to use
restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   We're real proud of all those stamps from different countries we
can show off when we match passports with fellow travelers, or swap
itineraries with friends in Peachtree City and North Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The technical highlight of my year was learning to use e-mail.
I'm sure lucky I never got serious about golf, because I wouldn't
have time. Answering e-mail takes seven or eight hours a day, not
counting the 30 or 40 minutes it takes to get hooked up to wherever
it is you have to get hooked up to. When you get on e-mail,
everybody you know and even total strangers send you dozens of
jokes about Bill and Hillary, philosophical essays, excerpts from
books and how to enjoy better sex. According to estimates of some
experts, e-mail has cut productivity in this country about 89
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Our in-house fat control officer discovered a great new magazine
on healthy living. We now know 50 secrets of how to fight bulges
without dieting; how to stop the aging process by eating grape seed
and pine bark; how to drop cholesterol 100 points in 21 days by
eating Chinese red yeast and butter made from yogurt; and how to
live happily with an overactive bladder, even when you are
traveling in France.
</P>
<P>
   Although I violated a direct order and planted a rather large
garden, our marriage seems to have bumped through another year,
saved by the weather. A windstorm blew down most of the Silver
Queen just when it was ready to be frozen and put up for the
winter. Thanks to the drought, a lot of butterbeans didn't fill
out, and wilt reduced the tomato crop so much that canning never
became an issue.
</P>
<P>
   We enjoyed another season following the Georgia Bulldogs and
their exciting victories over Central Florida, Vanderbilt, LSU and
either Idaho State or Utah State, I forget which. Even though
Florida beat us again, it's always nice to spend an afternoon in
Jacksonville getting drenched in a warm tropical rain. The Tech
game was a bit of a disappointment, but I think we could have won
if either the officials or the coaches had stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   In October I celebrated another birthday I didn't really expect
to have. We also survived numerous trips to Atlanta and down to
Macon on Interstate 75 without being run down and crushed by an
18-wheeler trying to break the sound barrier. We didn't have any
more stray cats to take up with us.
</P>
<P>
   Our granddaughter, going on 15 and looking forward to her
learner's license, is still the prettiest, smartest, best-behaved
teen-ager we know. In fact, our entire family is just super smart
and successful, not to mention being real modest. Since we might
make other parents feel bad, we try not bring up all the fantastic
accomplishments our boys continue to enjoy in their personal and
professional lives.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, 1999 was another great year, in spite of drought,
tomato wilt, an army of Japanese beetles, a record infestation of
fire ants, 120-degree heat in the Australian Outback, a flare-up of
arthritis in my left knee, nasty telephone calls from Georgia Tech
fans, Chinese yeast, yogurt butter and French restaurants that
won't let you use the restroom without ordering a five-course meal
and a bottle of wine.
</P>
<P>
   We hope you and yours have enjoyed an equally good year, and are
looking forward to many, many more _ as I am now that we're stocked
up on grape seed and pine bark.
</P>
<P>
   Until next year. ...
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
