<SLUG> BC-PROTEIN-DIET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giving customers what they want: Restaurant servers get wise to
the ways of popular high-protein regimens
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The customers order 14-ounce filets and salads loaded
with blue cheese dressing. But as soon as they say ``no croutons,''
Jennifer Wooten knows they're on a diet.
</P>
<P>
   Not a carrots-and-Fresca kind of diet, but one of those
high-protein diets.
</P>
<P>
   For Wooten, a waitress at the upscale Lenox Square steakhouse
Prime, knowing the ins and outs of high-protein dieting is key to
success on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are deciding what to order, I can tell right away
they're on the Atkins diet,'' Wooten says. ``I'll ask them, and
nine times out of 10 it's that one or another.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as Protein Power.
</P>
<P>
   Such as the Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Such as Sugar Busters.
</P>
<P>
   Although these fad diets differ in their particulars, all have
the same basic message: ``yes'' to proteins, sometimes ingested in
Conehead-esque excess, and ``no'' to carbohydrates, sometimes
prohibiting even a bite of carrot, a pinch of sugar or a lonely
crouton. Nutritionists, despite their reservations, admit that the
diets can effectively peel away the pounds in the short run.
</P>
<P>
   And, strangely enough, these weight-loss programs have been a
boon to the high-end restaurant biz, eager to supply all the prime
steaks, chops and cheese a high-protein dieter could hope for.
</P>
<P>
   Wooten guesstimates that ``someone's doing that diet at just
about every other table _ perfect, skinny little Buckhead ladies
and big businessmen who can't eat sushi because they're watching
their figures. It's definitely the buzz; everyone's talking about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooten knows exactly how to steer these diners _ toward plain
sashimi rather than rice-sullied sushi, away from salads that have
sugar in the dressing _ and she hustles the bread basket away
before the dieters can give in to temptation. ``They're all pretty
happy when a waiter or waitress knows what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   All over town, the cream of Atlanta's service corps is hip to
the protein diet. ``It's pretty easy to detect,'' says Ryan Turner
at Food Studio in Atlanta. ``When I hear `Can you sub the mashed
potatoes for something else?,' I'll ask them if they're on
Atkins.''
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Elder at Canoe in Vinings has heard the no-mashed-potatoes
request ``so many times'' that he's lost count. ``They ask for a
steak with just sauteed greens or asparagus.''
</P>
<P>
   David Abes, chef at Insignia in Sandy Springs, Ga., knows the
steak-and-spinach order well, and he notes that his customers are
``cutting out a lot on the bread.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the prototypical high-protein diet has been around
for years _ Robert C. Atkins originally published ``Dr. Atkins'
Diet Revolution'' in 1972 _ it wasn't until he rejiggered it in
1997 (``Dr. Atkins' New Diet Revolution'') that it became a
national phenomenon and spurred a host of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans, where a group of doctors first published ``Sugar
Busters!'' several years ago, restaurants have long been keen to
diners who want their steaks sans potatoes. Places as tony as the
Grill Room at the Windsor Court Hotel offer menu items specially
sanctioned by ``Sugar Busters!''
</P>
<P>
   But in Atlanta, it wasn't initially so easy for Mary Sorrel to
eat out when she brought the diet back from New Orleans in
mid-1998. Sorrel, a partner in an Atlanta public relations firm,
says, ``I'd get a strange look from the waiters at Mick's when I'd
order a hamburger without the bun.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past six months, though, the diets have picked up so much
steam that even chain restaurants now pose no problems.
</P>
<P>
   John Magnuson, a specialty food and wine wholesaler on the
``Protein Power'' plan, recently tried to navigate the menu at
Houston's. The waiter immediately recognized that he was on a
high-protein diet and steered him away from the balsamic
vinaigrette dressing, which contains sugar.
</P>
<P>
   But Magnuson says he doesn't feel deprived on the diet. ``Last
night we had dinner at McKendrick's and had a huge strip steak,
bibb lettuce salad with Maytag blue cheese dressing and a copious
quantity of red wine,'' he recalls with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a definite shift,'' says Wooten, the waitress at
Prime. ``It's bring on the steak. Bring on the cream. Bring on the
bearnaise.''
</P>
<P>
   And even among regulars. ``There's this one woman who's very
prominent in Atlanta,'' says Wooten, ``who went suddenly from just
eating low-fat carbs to all sashimi and steak and salad with the
dressing on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Has she lost any weight?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' laughs Wooten, ``She's just the same, but she seems
happier.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
