<SLUG> BC-PROTEIN-DIETSIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fad or find? Books detail diets
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Heart Association has issued a statement
criticizing high-protein diets. Nonetheless, they top the charts of
the diets in vogue. Here are books about the most popular versions.
</P>
<P>
   Though high-protein diets have been criticized by the American
Heart Association and other health groups, they top the charts
among diets in vogue. Some books describing the most popular
versions:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dr. Atkins' New Diet Revolution'' by Robert C. Atkins (Avon
Books). Unlimited amounts of protein and fat, severe restriction of
all carbohydrate-containing foods.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sugar Busters!'' by H. Leighton Steward, Morrison C. Bethea,
Sam S. Andrews, Ralph O. Brennan and Luis A. Balart (Ballantine
Books). Less restrictive than Atkins in carbohydrate intake, as
long as all white starches and sugars are avoided. More restrictive
caloric intake.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Zone'' by Barry Sears with Bill Lawren (HarperCollins).
</P>
<P>
   All meals and snacks based on 40 percent carbohydrate, 30
percent protein and 30 percent fat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Protein Power'' by Michael R. Eades and Mary Dan Eades
(Bantam Books). Similar to the Atkins program: very low in
carbohydrates and very high in protein. Works in two phases.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Chris Rosenbloom, American Dietetic Association
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
