A1810 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD18-COX     12-17 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New joinery book helps the woodwoker get it together
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Joinery Shaping &AMP; Milling,'' another new book from
The Taunton Press, is one that deserves a place in every student
woodworker's library alongside the same publisher's classic ``Tage
Frid Teaches Woodworking'' series.
</P>
<P>
   The 202-page softcover book is no more than a collection of
articles from Fine Woodworking magazine, but the whole is far more
than its parts.
</P>
<P>
   I see it alongside Frid's books, which any longtime reader knows
I revere, because it compliments them.
</P>
<P>
   It updates the techniques to include new tools and new
techniques, and elaborates on many of the standard ones.
</P>
<P>
   The book begins at the beginning of any woodworking project _
getting the stock square. An excellent article discusses means of
dealing with every defect known to a plank. It's followed by
articles on jointing edges on a jointer or a table saw, and
flattening a board by hand with a jointer plane and a scraper.
</P>
<P>
   The article on resawing on a band saw, especially the section on
setting up and tuning the saw, is the best I have read on the
subject, and it concerns itself entirely with the saw most of us
have _ the 14-inch Delta.
</P>
<P>
   The long section on curved wood is comprehensive. It spends
plenty of time on the standard methods of steaming and bent
lamination, but it also goes very thoroughly into coopering, using
a vacuum veneer press, and even bricklaying segments to build up a
hollow circular frame. There is a fascinating article by one fellow
who uses a common drug store heating pad and a wet towel instead of
a steaming tube to prepare wood for bending.
</P>
<P>
   The latter half of the book is devoted to shaping and joinery.
There are extensive articles on using the biscuit joiner and the
router for almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   A long section has articles on every method known for making the
mortise and tenon joint, certainly the most important joint in
woodworking. Every kind of mortising machine is discussed, and
there is even a fine article on making your own mortise miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joinery'' is part of the publisher's ``Essentials of
Woodworking'' series, and I would certainly agree that it's
essential. It is, of course, handsomely designed and lavishly
illustrated with photographs and drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Its companion this fall in the same series is ``Finishes &AMP;
Finishing Techniques.'' For those who make a big thing out of
finishing, it is no doubt excellent, especially in its evaluation
of new water-based finishes. I checked to make sure it includes
something on the type of finish I use _ an oil varnish variety _
and let the rest of it slide.
</P>
<P>
   However, after almost 200 pages of chemistry and technique,
there's a one-page article that makes a pretty good case against
any kind of finish.
</P>
<P>
   These books sell for $17.95 each, a distinct bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
