<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday and Sunday, Dec. 18-19, 1999
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   FOR SATURDAY:
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ Gee, what with this Y2K thing,
nobody has a sense of humor anymore. (Latham, Marshall News
Messenger) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Dear Folks: Well, it's
time again for the annual report on adventures and accomplishments
of the Minter family, which I know all of you have been anxiously
awaiting. (Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ In 20 years of working with
battered women, Nancy Grigsby has never seen anything like it. Nine
Miami Valley women have been murdered since June 1998, suspected
victims of domestic violence. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FOR SUNDAY:
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ As anyone who once bought an
eight-track tape player can attest, predicting the future of
technology is not for those who embarrass easily. Still,
forecasters keep looking down the road, doing their best to guess
where the new century will take us. While they differ about what
specific tools and toys will shape our tomorrows, prognosticators
do seem certain about one thing: Whatever we have, we'll have more
of it. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution), 22.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ There is much urgent mulling going on at high
levels and low over the prospect of applying state and local sales
taxes to ``remote'' retail trade _ that is, to catalog and Internet
commerce _ just as they are applied to store sales. This is a
no-brainer. There is simply no good reason not to charge routine
sales taxes. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Just when I thought I was fully Y2K
compliant, I found out I wasn't. It was while writing a check to
the cable company that I noticed that the space for the date
concluded with 19; as in 1999 or 1901. I don't know about you, but
I order checks by the bale, printed with my name, address and part
of the date on it. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News
Service.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ Doctors are griping about health care plans that
jilt their patients to satisfy stockholders. By working in concert,
some doctors say, they would stand a better chance of putting
things back in sync. But that would break the antitrust laws. Some
politicians agree it's time to right the balance. (Andy Glass is a
columnist for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED
THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
