health. (Lee Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes two
6-pica color photos of book jackets and 1 6-pica color illustration
of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   CYSTIC - Every night, Bill and Jerri Chesney tap their
children's chests, over and over again, to keep them from drowning.
Courtney, 8, and Taylor, 5, have cystic fibrosis (CF), a disease
that tricks the body into producing excess mucus, which coats the
pancreas and the lungs, inhibiting digestion and breathing. The
phlegmy superflux must be expelled daily, or the children will be
left gasping for air, like fish on dry land. (Browning, Palm Beach
Post) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LAMB-COLUMN - Even modern technology does not give without also
taking away. With every car, television and computer, humans have
moved farther away from the tribal societies and extended families
that once gave us a sense of belonging to a group. Every month,
some medical researcher expresses astonishment at how much a
person's social support has to do with his health and lifespan.
This essential ``connectedness'' refers to both the number of
relationships and the satisfaction they bring, but it boils down to
how much we share our lives with others. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   PROSTATE-MOBILE - DAYTON, Ohio - Thor Industries has begun a
national tour in a custom-built recreational vehicle to deliver
free prostate cancer screenings to 10,000 men older than 40 in
upcoming months. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
