and art books; photographer Chris Verene; and filmmaker Ruth
Leitman. (Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   RAGE - Pop music column looks at Rage Against the Machine, and
the relationship between politics, partying and the appropriation
of funk. With notes from their concert. With staff photo shot at
12/9 concert, hopefully. (Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
23. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   CRACKER-AUTHOR - BAXLEY, Ga. - Writer Janisse Ray, whose first
book, ``Ecology of a Cracker Childhood,'' is winning praise from
environmentalists and reviewers, grew up in a Baxley junkyard in a
family cramped by poverty, mental illness and fundamentalist
beliefs. Her world widened when she went away to college and
graduate school, became an environmental activist and writer,
taught school in South America, lived in a hippie-style commune and
bore a child. Now, Ray and son Silas, 11, are back in Appling
County while she finishes her second book on rural communities.
They live in a rustic, 80-year-old farmhouse built by her
grandparents, often feeling lonely and isolated. While Ray and her
son struggle with the limits of a lifestyle she rejected, the move
back has allowed her to reach rapprochement with her father, who
caused much of her childhood pain.(Davis, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 75. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WALTONS-CD - This Christmas, fans of ``The Waltons'' can get
even closer to the cast of the 1970s show with the CD ``A Walton's
Christmas.'' It was produced by Jon Walmsley, who played the gangly
Jason, andfeatures 19 tracks of holiday favorites, warm-fuzzy
recitations and chitchat betwn the actors, right down to the
mandatory bedtime mantra ``Good night 'Liv, good night John, good
night grandma, good night Erin, good night Ben . . .'' (Longino,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WINNERS-QUIT - WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Most folks, at some point
or another, have wanted to take their jobs and shove 'em. Tough day
at the plant, terse words with the boss, too much to do in too
little time. But what if you're a pampered pop star, admired
athlete or sitcom sensation? A beloved leader, respected writer or
lauded corporate bigwig? Would you be willing to chuck it all -
top-notch talent, tons of money, the world by the tail - if you
weren't happy? Or if you knew - even though you were at the top of
of your game - that it was time to bow out? (Grantham, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   PROTEIN-DIET - High-protein diets are now so popular that
waiters are hip to the needs of diners. (Kessler, Atlanta
journal-Constitution). 20. MOVED.
</P>
