<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1817 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-LAMB-COLUMN18-COX     12-17 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAMB-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Strong social relationships important to good
health
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Even modern technology does not give without also
taking away. With every car, television and computer, humans have
moved farther away from the tribal societies and extended families
that once gave us a sense of belonging to a group.
</P>
<P>
   Every month, some medical researcher expresses astonishment at
how much a person's social support has to do with his health and
lifespan. This essential ``connectedness'' refers to both the
number of relationships and the satisfaction they bring, but it
boils down to how much we share our lives with others.
</P>
<P>
   Social connection is as important for doctors to measure as
weight, cholesterol and blood pressure, says Dr. Brooks S. Edwards,
medical editor of the Mayo Clinic Health Oasis Web site. ``The
strength of our relationships has great bearing on how well we age,
how well we deal with life's challenges and how well we survive
serious illness.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject most often involves the elderly, partly because
one-third of Americans older than 65 in private homes are living
alone and partly because the impact of connectedness is so dramatic
at their age. It's hard to ignore a five-year study of 1,400 heart
patients showing people who don't have a spouse or confidant are
three times more likely to die than those who do.
</P>
<P>
   But connectedness is also important for the young. When a
middle-school child's increased academic and peer pressures
converge with a torrent of hormones, stress levels soar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feeling connected just makes people feel more at ease,'' says
Ray Messer, a psychotherapist. ``You're OK. You don't feel as
anxious or worried, or get angry as much because you know you're
OK. That in itself relieves stress, and there are scientific
studies that show relieving stress strengthens the immune system.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Vonnegut, the acutely observant novelist, uses the term
``folk society deficiency'' for the ongoing outbreak of people who
lack a sense of connection or belonging. He compares it to vitamin
and mineral deficiencies, saying people waste away from FSD as
surely as scurvy patients lacking vitamin C.
</P>
<P>
   Often, he says, they ``become a member of an artificial extended
family.'' That isn't a huge problem if the symptom is wearing a
Cleveland Browns jersey to the fridge for the quick sandwich that
has replaced traditional Sunday dinners. But some artificial
extended families connect with each other by burning crosses on
front lawns or wearing black trenchcoats to school to conceal their
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Random violence occurs in part due to a lack of social
conscience,'' Messer says. ``Social conscience derives from social
commitment. Social commitment comes from the sense of belonging to
a group.''
</P>
<P>
   Messer got to thinking about the subject this fall, when his
seventh-grade daughter was moved out of the cluster of students who
had been grouped together in sixth grade and otherwise kept
together this year.
</P>
<P>
   In questioning the move unsuccessfully, he was bewildered that
the pleasant school officials he talked to had no apparent idea
they were discussing a significant problem with a simple solution.
Some kids naturally sink in the sink-or-swim environment of large
secondary schools, he says. ``But if kids are grouped with teams of
about 50 to 100 kids throughout their educational journey, there is
a stronger potential for interpersonal connection and group
loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence among older adults shows those with good social
support are more likely to have optimum blood pressure and lower
rates of common colds, mental illness and age-related memory loss.
The support is believed to lower stress levels and to give people
more motivation to live healthfully.
</P>
<P>
   Connectedness deficiency is not something modern medicine is
equipped to treat, however. Doctors often worry that technology is
usurping humanity in their field, even as Hollywood movies
substitute special effects for character development.
</P>
<P>
   Even among psych professionals, it's hard to get past the
reality that reaching out to others is often quite stressful for
those who most need to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Web site: The Mayo Clinic has a social support assessment and
information on building support systems at
www.mayohealth.org/mayo/9907/htm/social/socialq.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
