<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1818 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PROSTATE-MOBILE18-COX     12-17 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-MOBILE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Medical RV to spread word about prostate cancer
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Thor Industries has begun a national tour in a
custom-built recreational vehicle to deliver free prostate cancer
screenings to 10,000 men older than 40 in upcoming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I'm alive today is because I was able to catch
the disease early enough to eradicate it,'' says Wade F.B.
Thompson, Thor's chairman and a prostate cancer survivor. He called
it ``the most difficult experience of my life'' and established
``The Drive Against Prostate Cancer'' to educate men and their
families about the importance of screening.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 180,000 American men are diagnosed each year with
prostate cancer and nearly 40,000 die. But it is virtually 100
percent curable if detected before it has spread from the prostate.
</P>
<P>
   The tour is targeting RV owners at RV shows and other public
forums, Thompson said, ``since so many RVers are over 40.'' Thor is
the second-largest manufacturer of RVs and the largest midsized bus
manufacturer in North America.
</P>
<P>
   All men 50 and older will be offered the screenings, as will
those 40 and older who are black or have a family history of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-foot Airstream medical vehicle has two private screening
rooms, where the 10-minute process will include a digital rectal
exam and prostate-specific antigen blood test from trained medical
staff.
</P>
<P>
   The tour's schedule of at least 15 cities is still being
assembled. Sponsoring partners are the Cancer Research Institute,
Endocare, Bayer Diagnostics and UroCor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
