<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1819 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WINNER-QUIT18-COX     12-17 1682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINNER-QUIT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Choosing to quit the start of a new life for some
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Most folks, at some point or another,
have wanted to take their jobs and shove 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Tough day at the plant, terse words with the boss, too much to
do in too little time.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you're a pampered pop star, admired athlete or
sitcom sensation? A beloved leader, respected writer or lauded
corporate bigwig?
</P>
<P>
   Would you be willing to chuck it all _ top-notch talent, tons of
money, the world by the tail _ if you weren't happy? Or if you knew
_ even though you were at the top of of your game _ that it was
time to bow out?
</P>
<P>
   Geri Halliwell, better known as Ginger Spice, recently released
a book that claims, among other things, fame ain't what it's
cracked up to be. You'll recall that she made the globe (or at
least a lot of pre-teen girls) gasp when she dumped the Spice Girls
last year in search of serenity and a solo career.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, who some argue had a decade of hoops left in
him, said in his retirement speech in January that he was leaving
pro ball ``to enjoy watching my kids grow up.'' This time, no
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   And last month, Julianna Margulies, head nurse Carol Hathaway on
``ER'' for six years, walked away from a $27 million contract _
landmark cash for a television actress _ to work in film and
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Quitting, my friends, is in.
</P>
<P>
   Not when you're about to get the gold watch and goodbye sheet
cake, but while you're still vibrant and/or young enough to revel
in your success and try something new.
</P>
<P>
   Or do nothing at all. Even if folks think you're nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very serious trend across the board, whether it be
entertainers, athletes or executives,'' says Boston-based author
Mark Albion, whose book, ``Making a Life, Making a Living:
Reclaiming Your Purpose and Passion in Business and in Life,'' is
due out next month.
</P>
<P>
   (He also runs a support group for, get this, folks 30 and under
who've made at least $500 million, ``mostly dot-com money.'' There
are 12 men and two women, all filthy rich but unfulfilled.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Geri Halliwell was one of the unbelievable few who reached the
top of the mountain. But what you have to ask is, `Is this the
right mountain?' Sometimes you can only make that decision when
you're high enough to look down at the rest of your life and figure
out what's really important to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider actress Dolores Hart, who frolicked alongside George
Hamilton in ``Where the Boys Are'' in 1960. Three years later, she
canned Hollywood to join a convent in Bethlehem, Conn. Or running
back Jim Brown, third highest all-time rusher in the NFL, who _ at
age 30 with plenty of time left to play _ quit the Cleveland Browns
in 1965 to go to Hollywood. Predictably, his flicks flopped. But at
least Brown, who was inducted into the Football Hall of Fame in
1971, was brave enough to follow his bliss.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people sometimes have a challenge understanding is just
because you're working hard, doing well and making a lot of money,
that doesn't necessarily mean you love what you do,'' says Bob
Burg, motivational speaker and author of ``Winning Without
Intimidation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nor does it mean that you don't love what you do. But you may
reach a point where your decisions are based on different
criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as redefined values, the need for a new challenge and the
realization that even the Sultan of Brunei's megabucks don't make
him immortal.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, money can't buy happiness. What it can buy, though,
is the freedom to quit so you can hunt elsewhere for it.
</P>
<P>
   And here, experts say, are the top three motivations for making
a change:
</P>
<P>
   _ A shift in values, such as putting family first or
volunteering to support a cause.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Barnes _ head of PepsiCo's North American beverage
business and one of America's highest-ranking female execs _
startled colleagues in 1997 with her eyebrow-raising move to become
a full-time mom to her three kids. And then there's poised Colin
Powell, the retired four-star Army general who was begged to accept
a GOP presidential bid after his stellar leadership during Desert
Storm. He decided, however, to forgo the White House for his own
house, where he sifts through stacks of mail bins deciding which
volunteer effort to endorse. Powell also has launched a lucrative
speaking career, in which he commands as much as $40,000 an
appearance. No desk, no daily hassle.
</P>
<P>
   Even Halliwell has hopped on a soapbox to promote, among other
issues, breast-cancer awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always wanted to do something good with my public
standing,'' she writes in ``If Only,'' her autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   Some claim that the book is a cop-out, a whiny ``I had to find
myself'' excuse to deflect criticism that Halliwell was greedy and
self-absorbed. Perhaps. But she insists the price of fame was
``turmoil, insecurity and constantly being on display.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is about compassion and goodness and having a clear
conscience. Without these things it doesn't matter whether you're a
household name or a housewife because life will leave a bad taste
in your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Career experts chuckle that celebrities oftentimes deem the
``price of fame'' too high after they've banked several million.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it still reflects a shift in values and goals,'' insists
Sharon Linzey, a sociologist in Newberg, Ore. ``From paycheck to
personal growth.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The need for a new challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan immediately comes to mind. What more could he strive for
after leading his team to six NBA titles? Sure, he still hawks
Hanes briefs, Ball Park franks, Nike shoes and the cologne that
bears his name, but there's nothing left for him to prove on the
basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Same with legendary boxer Rocky Marciano, who left the ring in
1956 after eight years with a perfect 49-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know from a career standpoint I have accomplished everything
that I could as an individual,'' Jordan said in January after
shedding his Chicago Bulls jersey for the second time. (The first
time was in 1993 during a one-season stint at pro baseball.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I feel great. Mentally, I am exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Joel Wilkinson, a consultant for careerexperience.com:
``One of the major reasons people quit at the top of their game is
that what they're doing no longer holds meaning for them because
the excitement and passion are gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, someone like Michael Jordan still has a passion for
sports, but if the challenge is gone, the thrill is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, however, that passion keeps athletes toiling for too
long, fans grouse, citing Muhammad Ali; Cal Ripken, still with the
Baltimore Orioles after a record 2,632 consecutive games; and
hockey great Wayne Gretzky, who finally called it quits in April
after two decades on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Thing is, the decision to split rests solely in the hands of the
athlete or actor or company president. Public opinion, harsh though
it may be, is no reason to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's arrogant of others to judge when people are performing
past their prime,'' says Dr. Bruce Saltz, a Boca Raton
psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there are more losses than wins or fewer goals scored or
not as many No. 1 hits, but that doesn't mean that person enjoys
playing the game any less or performing a song any less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does anybody quit anything? When the pain of doing it
outweighs the pleasure. To people on the outside, your choices may
seem ridiculous or incite ridicule. It takes enormous courage to
make decisions based solely on your own perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Take ``Catcher in the Rye'' author J.D. Salinger, who spent a
decade creating his 1951 classic. Then, he all but vanished in New
England, continuing to write but _ much to many perplexed fans'
dismay _ only for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishing was a vicious, vicious thing,'' he once said.
``There is peace in not doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The realization that life doesn't last forever, no matter how
rich and famous you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is when people come to grips with the fact that none of
us is sure how much time is allotted,'' says Sally Haver, president
of the Ayers Group, a New York-based human resources firm. ``They
think they can make a Tarzanlike swing from vine to vine and this
to that, and then, they go klunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as actress Shelley Long (Diane), who left ``Cheers'' in
1987 to raise the bar of her career, so to speak. Movies! Broadway!
Her own show! KLUNK.
</P>
<P>
   And actor David Caruso (Detective John Kelly), who blew off
``NYPD Blue'' in 1994 for the bright lights of Tinseltown. He made
two movies: ``Jade'' and the aptly titled ``Kiss of Death.'' KLUNK.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they were bored or greedy or egomaniacs or all of the
above. Regardless, career experts say, you gotta give them credit
for taking the leap.
</P>
<P>
   After all, there are always infomercials.
</P>
<P>
   Says Albion: ``At the point you realize you're mortal, you also
come to understand that we're all born with little marching orders
in our pockets. Sometimes you have to stop in your tracks _ let go
of your addiction to success and outward fulfillment _ to find out
what those orders are.''
</P>
<P>
   And what force put them there.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to what Burg calls today's ``spiritual
revolution,'' which he says is in direct proportion to baby boomers
getting older.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there really is, gulp, a heaven. And it isn't within a $50
million mansion, a new Mercedes-Benz or a movie studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is when people start to ask if there's more meaning to
life than just money. They slow down, they focus on different
things, they take a breather _ even at the height of their careers
_ because that's when the maturity comes.''
</P>
<P>
   That and the common sense.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he quit after one of his most successful seasons,
Patsy Hendren _ England's top cricket player in the 1930s _
replied: ``I'm going while you still ask why. I'm not waiting till
you ask `why not?'''
</P>
<P>
   If only Wayne Newton were so wise.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
