 HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Friday, Dec. 17, 1999 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6320.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (All slugs include the ``HNS'' tagline.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (`a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-TRIAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ This city braces for the
emotionally charged trail of four New York City policemen accused
of killing an unarmed man in the Bronx. A state appeals court ruled
that New York City-area media coverage had made it impossible to
pick an impartial jury in the trial of four white police officers
accused of murdering a West African immigrant. By MELISSA GRACE.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown's
landslide victory in Tuesday's mayoral election wasn't cheap. With
an unprecedented $2.4 million in independent spending by business,
labor and Democratic groups on top of more than $3.1 million
directly donated to his campaign, Brown surpassed all previous
election spending records. In the six-week runoff race alone, Brown
and his supporters shelled out $100 for every $14 spent by opponent
Tom Ammiano. By ERIN McCORMICK and SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-CROSSINGS (Austin, Texas) _ With an eye on traffic
congestion at international crossings, the Texas Transportation
Commission gave the go-ahead to development of eight centralized
state inspection stations at five cities on the border. BY PEGGY
FIKAC.
</P>
<P>
   DUMB-SUSPECTS (San Francisco) _ Cops are calling these robbery
suspects dumb, dumber and dumbest.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, investigators cannot decide who is the dumbest.
``These guys sure made our work easier,`` said Lt. Bruce Marovich,
head of the San Francisco police robbery detail. ``These guys don't
think. They just do it impulse and go. I don't know if they have
half a brain between them.`` By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL (San Francisco) _ Electronics giant Motorola and Research
in Motion, a New York based wireless data company, are pushing two
nifty, but imperfect, devices that will let e-mail addicts get
their fix just about anywhere. Both devices Motorola's PageWriter
2000X and RIM's Blackberry are pager-like devices with tiny
keyboards that send and receive e-mail messages via radio signal.
They also include some simple but useful software that keeps track
of a user's calendar, phone messages, memos and other personal
information. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   SF-HOUSING (San Francisco) _ The skyrocketing cost of home
ownership made housing the second most important concern for Bay
Area residents, according to an annual poll. As it has for years,
transportation remained the top concern in the region, listed by 38
percent of respondents down from 40 percent last year.. By RYAN
KIM.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTMENT-OUTLOOK (Colonie, N.Y.) _ Investors will be able to
make money investing in the stock market next year, but will have
to make their stock picks more carefully, noted investment
authority Hugh Johnson is predicting. ``Stock prices will continue
to rise through 2000, but stay tuned,'' said Johnson, chief
investment officer at First Albany Corp. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-ANNA (Undated) _ ``Anna and the King'' is a story of
a love that cannot be. Tragic pairings are often the kind that make
the best movies. Sadly, the pairing between Chow Yun-Fat as the
king of Siam and Jodie Foster as British schoolteacher Anna
Leonowens is only a tragic mess. The truly gripping story of
ill-fated lovers in ``Anna and the King'' is the screen-stealing
subplot between the king's concubine Tuptim and her peasant lover.
BY JESSICA BARBARO.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DALLAS-SPELLMAN (Irving, Texas) _ Seven months ago, Alonzo
Spellman sat on the edge of his bed one night and wondered how life
became so painful. It was like, 'Man, what's next?'`` said
Spellman, remembering what he calls the lowest point of his life.
It was at that moment that everything became brighter, his worries
faded and his road to recovery began. ``That's when God walked into
my life and said, 'I'm what's next, because you don't have a what's
next.' Everything else changed from there.`` By TOM OSBORN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Tom Ammiano's most satisfying
time may still lie ahead: some day after Jan. 1, when ``soft
money`` campaign contributions must be reported to the state. It
will be then that the Board of Supervisors president gets a good
look at just how much fear he struck in the hearts of San
Francisco's rich and powerful. Given what we've already seen, the
revelation could be the biggest ego boost a left-leaning
``outsider`` has ever received. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
