<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES DEFT AT NEGOTIATING CYBERSPACE ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Yours,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah admonished Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas during the first of the Republican
presidential debates earlier this month, ``is not user friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   As political zingers go, it might have been a bit lame. But that
Hatch would use precious air time to criticize an opponent's Web
site as ``pretty tough to use'' is only one indication of how the
presidential candidates are confronting the Internet and technology
generally, both as substantive issues and as pervasive cultural
forces.
</P>
<P>
   They are raising money over the Internet. They are raising money
from people who have grown rich from the Internet. They are
debating how best to nurture the potential of the Internet while
shielding children from pornography and consumers from potential
misuse of data about them. And in the early stages of the first
Internet-era national election, they are eager to let voters know
they are as comfortable with a mouse as the next guy is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace of candidate education is nearly as rapid as the pace
of technological development,'' said Rep. Christopher Cox,
R-Calif., who is one of the few true techies in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore long ago dropped his paternity claim to
the Internet. But Gore, who can sometimes be spotted with a Palm
Pilot clipped to his belt, dropped into the CyberStop Cafe in
Washington last week and with reporters and photographers watching
sent an e-mail message to Bill Bradley, his rival for the
Democratic presidential nomination, questioning his opponent's
stand on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has held electronic town-hall meetings. And the
Republican candidates have gone back and forth about technology
issues regularly during their debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``In not very many years, politics has moved from a lot of
smoke-filled rooms and ward bosses giving out turkeys to
constituents to dueling e-mails,'' said Sen. Ron Wyden of Oregon, a
Democrat with a strong interest in technology issues. ``This is an
extraordinary transformation in politics. To reach the swing,
independent voters who are going to decide about the 2000
elections, you've got to talk about these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The most politically charged of the issues may be whether and
how to apply sales taxes to electronic commerce, and it is shaping
up as a test of the candidates' views on the Internet in the
economy and society.
</P>
<P>
   Most governors and many local government officials are worried
that as business migrates from Main Street and the mall to
Amazon.com and eBay, state governments will face a fiscal crisis,
since online retailers for the most part are not required to
collect sales taxes, the primary revenue source for states.
</P>
<P>
   But in Washington, there is support in both parties for making
the Internet a permanently tax-free shopping zone. A government
commission studying the matter seems headed toward a deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is particularly tricky for Bush, who is trying to
establish his anti-tax credentials but shares the concerns of other
governors that revenue losses from a shift to tax-free Internet
shopping could leave states in a bind and hurt traditional
retailers. Bush favors extending a moratorium against Internet
taxes while the issue gets further study.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's unwillingness to come out definitively against Internet
sales taxes is being exploited by his rivals, who are suggesting
obliquely that Bush is soft on taxes and may be a bit of a Luddite
to boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet should not be taxed,'' Sen. John McCain of
Arizona said. He extolled the Internet as ``the greatest thing
that's happened to the world,'' and compared its impact to a
combination of the printing press and the industrial revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governors are incredibly short-sighted when they want to
tax this baby in its cradle,'' McCain said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hatch said it was ``far overblown to think that the fact that
people buy over the Internet is going to reduce Main Street USA.''
</P>
<P>
   But the politics of technology can be complicated. Despite his
message to Washington to ``keep the government's mitts off'' the
industry, Hatch has been a supporter of the federal antitrust case
against Microsoft Corp. He has been raising campaign funds from
executives at some of Microsoft's rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, by contrast, says the Microsoft case is a waste of
time and money, because the pace of change in the software business
will render moot any court judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The scramble to raise money from technology companies almost
guarantees that candidates will continue to pay attention to the
issues on the industry's mind.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had raised $1.73 million from people affiliated with
technology and communications companies through Oct. 15, while Gore
had raised $1.54 million from them, Bradley had raised $770,000,
and McCain $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidates seem fascinated and intrigued by the
technology's potential to affect the world, not just dot-com
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Defending his support for bringing China into the World Trade
Organization, Bush cited the Web's potential to communicate
democratic values even in the face of opposition from a repressive
regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if the Internet took hold in China,'' Bush said.
``Imagine how freedom would spread.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-12-99 2010EST &QL;
</P>
