<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-ECOMMERCE-WRONG-P     12-17 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ECOMMERCE-WRONG-PRICES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE WEB, PRICING ERRORS CAN BE COSTLY IN MORE WAYS THAN ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When traditional retailers mistakenly label an item the wrong
price _ for instance, marking a $99 item $9.90 _ they might have to
apologize to a customer and give a quick lesson in decimals to a
clerk. On the Internet, they have to be prepared either to lose
face or to part with a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com is the latest Web site to confront this problem.
Early last week, it received a slew of visits from people who read
newspaper advertisements listing a Toshiba DVD player for $199.99.
When customers saw the actual retail price listed on the site,
$249.99, Amazon faced a no-win situation: Either honor the
advertised price and lose money, or explain the mistake and risk
losing the customers.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon ultimately decided to sell its stock of DVD players at
the advertised price, limiting customers to two per order. ``What
else can you say _it was an error,'' said Paul Capelli, an Amazon
spokesman. Capelli declined to say how many players the company
sold or how much money it lost in all. ``What's important is we're
taking a customer-centric approach to the solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet retailers are coming to grips with the notion that
pricing errors can be far more costly online than in traditional
stores. Thanks to chat rooms, e-mail and shopping ``bots,'' or
automated robots, like MySimon and DealTime, which survey prices on
products offered at thousands of sites, such mistakes rarely remain
a secret for long. What is more, Web merchants have made a habit of
slashing prices to startling levels to attract customers, so those
same merchants cannot appeal to the reasonable expectations of
their customers when a pricing glitch happens.
</P>
<P>
   Buy.com ran afoul of those expectations earlier this year when
it listed a $588 Hitachi computer monitor on its site for $164.
Buy.com began taking the orders, but after realizing the error, the
company agreed to sell only what it had in stock at the time to the
first customers who ordered at the lower price, then refused to
honor the other orders placed. The company is now in the midst of a
class-action lawsuit based, in part, on its handling of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   A more innocuous version of this happened to Ashford.com, a
seller of luxury goods, which earlier this month posted five
watches for sale priced at $0.00 _ with free shipping, no less. The
company said consumers understood Ashford.com's decision not to
give away the timepieces, given their combined value of $11,332,
but the resulting bad press did little for the start-up's image.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mary Lou Kelley, Ashford.com's vice president for
marketing, the pricing mistakes were the result of a system used to
set up its merchandising pages before they were published on the
site. Under that system, which has since been scrapped, items were
given $0.00 prices until the correct number was entered.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kelley said the company posted a disclaimer on its site,
stating that it was not responsible for pricing errors, but she
added that the company would evaluate such situations case by case.
``We'll do whatever we can to make customers happy, short of giving
watches away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is it more costly for Internet retailers to make such
mistakes than their off-line counterparts, but Web merchants are
far more prone to commit such errors, said Erik Brynjolfsson, a
professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Sloan
School of Management. Brynjolfsson recently completed a study of
Internet pricing, and found that Web merchants changed their prices
``much more frequently'' than brick-and-mortar stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much easier to change prices on the Net, and the benefits
are much greater, because of shopping bots,'' Brynjolfsson said,
noting that even 1 cent price reductions can give companies greater
exposure on price comparison sites. ``But that presents a big
opportunity for mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   However _ and this news will not endear him to bargain hunters _
Brynjolfsson said that pricing errors would decrease with time,
``as pricing technologies and systems get more accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the short run,'' he said, ``these companies have to
discover the kinds of really stupid things they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Anthony, chief executive of Brookstone, said the company
relied on a team of ``four to five people'' to verify prices on its
site, in the company catalog and in Brookstone's stores. ``It also
helps that we have one price on our items, no matter how you buy
them, so there's less of a chance of a mixup,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When a pricing error does occur on his site _ a situation that
has yet to happen _ Brookstone ``will appeal to the reasonable
expectations of our customers,'' Anthony said, adding that ``most
people are reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he said, ``there are so many crazy pricing schemes
on the Internet that a lot of people wouldn't be sure what is a
reasonable price, so we'd have to look at each situation
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the concept of reasonable pricing on the Web has all but
disappeared with the advent of free computers, free Internet access
and merchants who have not been compelled by Wall Street to focus
on profits. That, in turn, has made it more difficult for consumer
advocates to deal with such cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission generally occupies itself with
unfair business practices like so-called bait-and-switch pricing
and cedes issues of pricing errors to state jurisdictions. State
contract laws, meanwhile, typically protect merchants who make a
genuine error in pricing.
</P>
<P>
   But other watchdog organizations may set higher standards. The
Better Business Bureau Online, for instance, is drafting a new set
of standards for Web merchants who want to post the organization's
seal of approval on their sites. The current version of the draft
requires merchants to ``comply with all commitments,
representations, and other promises made to a consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that statement would require a merchant to sell a DVD
player for $100 as a result of an advertising error, however, is an
open question. ``We're open to feedback on this one,'' said Russ
Bodoff, the Better Business Bureau Online's chief operating
officer. ``It's a difficult issue, because the Internet presents
real questions around this area of consumer expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-12-99 1647EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
