<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A FILM NOT QUITE FIT FOR A KING 
</HEADLINE>
 FILM-REVIEW-ANNA   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JESSICA BARBARO  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Anna and the King'' is a story of a love that cannot be.
Tragic pairings are often the kind that make the best movies.
Sadly, the pairing between Chow Yun-Fat as the king of Siam and
Jodie Foster as British schoolteacher Anna Leonowens is only a
tragic mess.
</P>
<P>
   The truly gripping story of ill-fated lovers in ``Anna and the
King'' is the screen-stealing subplot between the king's concubine
Tuptim and her peasant lover.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is a new take on the old tale of a Victorian widow and
Mongkut, the king of Siam. She has come, saddled with her tidy
little take on imperialism (``India is British _ that's what
colonization is all about''), to educate the king's brood of 58,
from his 23 wives.
</P>
<P>
   With every crinkle of his sexy crow's feet and his sleek black
hair (yes, he has hair), Chow is every bit a king. Although this is
just his fourth American film, Chow is a veteran of more than 70
Hong Kong action movies. His screen presence is magnificent, but
Foster, for her part, swishes along opposite him like a wet mop in
a dress.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment she minces off the boat, she refuses to follow
protocol in Siam in a way that seems more petulant than purposeful.
The king has reneged on his promise of a house of her own in which
to raise her son, Louis (Tom Felton).
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that there is a Burmese death squad roaming the
country pillaging villages and massacring, she wants a proper
British household. After she harps at him enough, he grants her
wish, but not before he has told her he finds her demeanor ``most
unbeautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, Anna grows to appreciate the culture and even to admire
the king's devotion to progress. In time, the viewer grows to wish
she would fall off an elephant already.
</P>
<P>
   In Rodgers and Hammerstein's 1956 musical ``The King and I,''
another look at this famous pair, Deborah Kerr as Anna managed to
inject a sense of playfulness into a woman of purpose. Foster
spends most of the movie looking more harassed than in the throes
of love.
</P>
<P>
   While this yawner of a courtship is unfolding, treachery lurks
within the palace. The film treats us to a ferocious bad guy,
complete with deep facial furrows, which is how we recognize him as
the bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   He does not appreciate the king's devotion to progress, and the
conflict that ensues is filled with big, Hollywood action scenes in
which things blow up.
</P>
<P>
   Director and co-writer Andy Tennant _ of the charming Cinderella
story ``Ever After'' and the Matthew Perry vehicle ``Fools Rush
In'' _ does a fine job with this sweeping palette. The scenery
alone, rich with monsoon-swollen foliage and exotic landscapes
captured by cinematographer Caleb Deschanel, is worth the price of
admission.
</P>
<P>
   The king's wives and children are a bouquet of rich Asiatic
flowers in contrast to Anna's prim Victorian getups.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of Foster, hers was not the best female part in this
movie. The screenwriters gave Tuptim the hankie-grabbers, like ``If
love was a choice, who would ever choose such exquisite pain?''
</P>
<P>
   Tuptim is the daughter of a wealthy tea merchant who has given
her to the king as a gift. She first appears atop a golden
procession, weeping like a child for her impossible love. Her
doomed paramour, a man unhinged, reaches desperately for her and
cries out that he will never, never forget her as she is borne
behind the palace gates into the arms of a king.
</P>
<P>
   Tuptim (played by the Chinese actress Bai Ling) owns the screen.
Her face is a pool channeling the fury and desolation of her life.
We see her shackled and filthy, her head shorn, like a lightning
rod railing to the gods. We see her transformation from fear to
perfect peace, and it is as if the Buddha is resting serene behind
her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Anna and her king make a diplomatic decision for the good of
both their worlds. But we do not ache for them that they must part.
She just isn't fit for a king.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1881 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f INVESTMENT-OUTLOOK &LR;      12-17 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BANKING EXEC SEES SLOWDOWN IN `HIGH-FLYING' TECH STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
 INVESTMENT-OUTLOOK   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ Investors will be able to make money investing
in the stock market next year, but will have to make their stock
picks more carefully, a noted investment authority said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stock prices will continue to rise through 2000, but stay
tuned,'' Hugh Johnson, the chief investment officer of First Albany
Corp., told the Albany-Colonie Regional Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The banking executive sees prices coming down on some of the
``high-flying'' technology stocks next year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of seeing stocks trade at price/earnings ratios of 28 or
29 to 1, as is currently the case with the Standard &AMP; Poors 500,
Johnson expects a ratio closer to 24 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate earnings will remain strong, he said, but stock market
prices are inflated in many cases, he said. The prices will adjust
downward in the first quarter, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Investment returns, Johnson said, will be ``more normal,''
closer to 8 percent to 10 percent a year, he said. Some investors
have seen returns of more than 20 percent in recent years, though
more than 60 percent of the stocks in the New York Stock Exchange
declined in value this year, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   So next year will still be a time to ``be aggressive'' in buying
stocks, he said, but the performance of individual stocks will
depend more on earnings and are less likely to climb just because
some other stocks are climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Economic growth is slow in 2000, probably to a rate of 3.2
percent, compared to 3.9 percent this year, Johnson said. And
growth will be slower in the first quarter, when businesses will be
adjusting to any after-effects of the Y2K computer conversion, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Johnson warned, the economy is starting to show
hints of inflation: higher short-term interest rates and energy
costs. Those elements could prove dangerous for consumers carrying
plenty of debt, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-term interest rates should be fairly stable,'' Johnson
said. So companies deciding when in 2000 to borrow money can
probably wait until the latter part of the year and still get good
rates, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
