<HEADLINE>
CONCERN OVER YEAR 2000 REMAINS LOW IN SURVEYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the days winding down until the year 2000, each new survey
or poll seems to add to the evidence that Americans are confident
computer glitches will not have much impact on their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The National Federation of Independent Businesses, the leading
trade association for small companies, reported recently that many
members who had said last spring that they would take steps to
prepare for computer problems this fall had now decided not to
bother.
</P>
<P>
   And a survey for the National Association of Manufacturers found
that 93 percent of members expected the year 2000 to have almost no
impact on their companies and only 4 percent foresaw significant
disruptions of any part of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's news in this survey is what we're not seeing,'' said
Jerry Jasinowski, the manufacturing group's president, in
announcing the results last Friday. ``There's no last-minute panic
and little stockpiling of inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers' sample was small _ just 100 of its 14,000
members _ but the economist who did the survey, Edward Yardeni of
Deutsche Bank, said the results were in line with answers to the
same questions by a much larger group of similar companies just two
weeks earlier. (The data from these surveys, and prior samplings,
is at www.peoplepolls.com). The levels of concern rise only when
certain sectors, like health care, are isolated, Yardeni said.
</P>
<P>
   The air of normalcy is being reinforced by surveys that are
actually thinly disguised advertising. Blockbuster Video recently
reported that more than 22 percent of those it polled planned to
celebrate the arrival of Year 2000 by renting a movie and staying
home. London International Group, maker of Durex condoms, reported
that among 16- to 21-year-olds around the world nearly half intend
_ or at least hope _ that the big night include activities
requiring its products.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to a challenging climate for many Year 2000
entrepreneurs, particularly those who anticipated that disruptions
and public concern would be in full swing by now.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the book world. ``The Millennium Bug'' by Michael
Hyatt, probably the best seller so far among Year 2000 books, is
hanging strong, relatively speaking, in the 820 spot on Amazon's
hardcover sales list. But ``Time Bomb 2000'' the one-time
hot-seller by Edward Yourdon, a well-known software expert, and his
daughter, Jennifer, was down to 12,322 overall in the rankings. And
``Crisis Investing for the Year 2000'' by L. Jay Kuo and Edward M.
Dua, was languishing at 86,808.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jan Nickerson, who claims to have created the only
Year 2000 board game, has just started a two-for-one sale ($34
including shipping at www.Y2KConnections.com).
</P>
<P>
   Those trying to sell their wares are increasingly competing with
others who make many of the same points more succinctly for free.
The Utne Reader recently began offering free copies of its Y2K
Citizen's Action Guide to any group that wants at least 50 (contact
mitra(AT)utne.com). ``Awakening: the Upside of Y2K,'' a collection
of essays on community and personal preparedness edited by Judy
Laddon, Larry Shook and Tom Atlee, costs $7 at Amazon.com; but Ms.
Laddon will give 50 or more copies free to anyone who pays shipping
costs (JGLaddon(AT)aol.com).
</P>
<P>
   And last week, Global Action Plan, a nonprofit environmental
group in Woodstock, N.Y., announced plans to distribute 125,000
preparedness brochures to community groups in 16 states, all
financed by the Nathan Cummings Foundation. (The brochure can be
downloaded free at www.GlobalActionPlan.org).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-12-12-99 1828EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
