<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-REPORT14-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Before hitting the Web for toys, check the ratings 
By Mark Clothier  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We're thick into the holidays. By now, you've seen the
commercials. You've read the magazine and newspaper ads. Most of us
have been deluged with ads about companies wanting to sell you
things from their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   It's called e-commerce because Web shopping doesn't sound too
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   But which companies are worth your time and money?
</P>
<P>
   Gomez Advisors, an online industry consultant based in
Massachusetts, ranks Web shopping sites by how easy they are to
use, how secure customers feel, how much the products cost and what
resources are available from the Web site. The results are
available at Gomez's Web site, www.gomez.com.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez ranks the sites depending on the type of shopper as well.
For toy shoppers, Gomez considers those shopping for a gift, for an
educational toy, a trendy toy or a bargain toy.
</P>
<P>
   The top five toy-buying sites, as far as overall rankings were
concerned, were www.etoys.com, www
</P>
<P>
   .amazon.com, www.kbkids
</P>
<P>
   .com, www.smarterkids
</P>
<P>
   .com and www.zanybrainy
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   For those looking for the best price on toys, www
</P>
<P>
   .kbkids.com, www.etoys.com, www.servicemerchandise.com,
www.amazon.com and www
</P>
<P>
   .acetoys.com ranked highest.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez also ranks Web shopping sites for a variety of things,
including clothes, books, music, sporting goods, videos, cars,
computers, furniture, groceries and mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   OUT OF LOVE?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the boom is beginning to bust. Or maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Early results of a study by a sociology professor at London's
Brunel University found that American teens don't seem to be as
interested in the Web as they once did.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, presented at Britain's Westminster Media Forum
earlier this month, found that the number of former teen Web users
outnumbered current teen Web regulars.
</P>
<P>
   The professor, Steve Woolgar, attributed the early findings to
``boredom'' with the fad, according to an article on
www.techweb.com, an online technology magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But another London industry analyst, Fletcher Research, studied
the Internet habits of Britain's teens. Fletcher's most recent
British Internet User Monitor survey asked 50,000 Internet users.
The study found that those under the age of 18 made up 5 percent of
Britain's population, but 9 percent of Britain's online population.
</P>
<P>
   SITE HONORED
</P>
<P>
   An Atlanta Web site developer won a Webby for building the best
cultural Web site. The site, www.tsinoy.com, is geared toward
people with Chinese-Filipino heritage. Tsinoy.com was one of more
than 1,000 entries.
</P>
<P>
   Dux Raymond Sy works for Innovative-e.com. The Atlanta-based
company develops Web sites for companies that do business in the
domestic and Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   Tsinoy.com offers news, information and links to Tsinoys, people
of Chinese and Filipino heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
