<HEADLINE>
CALIF. FIRM TO INVEST $1 BILLION, MAINLY IN E-COMMERCE STARTUPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By RONALD ROSENBERG   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andersen Consulting, which has helped fund more than two-dozen
Internet companies, announced an ambitious program Monday to invest
$1 billion over the next five years, primarily in
business-to-business electronic-commerce startups.
</P>
<P>
   Called Andersen Consulting Ventures and based in Palo Alto,
Calif., the new unit will receive $500 million from Andersen
Consulting and $500 million from some yet-to-be-named investment
banks and venture capital firms, said Jackson L. Wilson, who will
head the venture firm. He previously was managing partner for
global markets at Andersen Consulting, one of the largest
information technology and management consulting firms.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson previously invested $40 million in startups, and the $1
billion in new funding is expected to catapult Andersen to third
place among venture capital firm, behind Accel Partners, also in
Palo Alto, and Kleiner Perkins Caulfield &AMP; Byers of Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   In his new role, Wilson will forge relationships with venture
capital firms, investment banks, and other e-commerce providers in
North America, Europe, and Asia, regions in which the creation of
e-commerce ventures and dot-com companies is accelerating. The
focus, he said, will be on launching on-line ventures that bring
buyers and sellers together to create marketplaces in such areas as
plastics, global chemicals, and computer products.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new venture money will also go to Andersen
Consulting employees who want to start e-commerce businesses,
rather than continue as consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this bold investment initiative, we are sending a strong
message to our clients, alliance partners, and our employees that
Andersen Consulting intends to lead in the new eEconomy,'' said a
statement released by Joe W. Forehand, managing partner and chief
executive of Andersen Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   To differentiate itself from venture capital companies, Andersen
Consulting Ventures plans to offer a combination of cash and
consulting expertise and provide consultants to help startup
companies, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to bring something different to the party,'' said
Wilson, 52, who plans to open a Northeast office in either New York
or Boston next year.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the venture unit plans to invest between $5 million
and $25 million in each startup for equity stakes of 2 percent to
51 percent. Wilson said he also envisions investing in incubator
businesses, which house and nurture startups, but he declined to be
more specific.
</P>
<P>
   He said one of the early companies Andersen Consulting invested
in was ShopLink.com of Westwood, Mass., which provides on-line
grocery shopping with weekly deliveries in more than 70
Massachusetts communities. It competes against Streamline.com, also
in Westwood; HomeRuns of Newton, a unit of supermarket chain
Hannaford Bros.; and PeaPod, based in Chicago, which is working
locally with Stop &AMP; Shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got pulled into the ShopLink deal at an early stage, and it
is very promising,'' said Wilson. So far, it is the company's only
New England venture and one of its last business-to-consumer deals,
he said.
</P>
<P>
