<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-VOTING15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL ONLINE VOTING OVERCOME SNAGS TO ACHIEVE ITS PROMISE?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By ANDREW J. GLASS  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For an idea whose time has yet to come, Internet
voting is drawing lots of attention.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by Dell Computer Corp. revealed that nearly 80
percent of current World Wide Web users _ more than 100 million
Americans _ would like the chance to vote on line.
</P>
<P>
   If the ballot box does find its way into cyberspace, some
experts believe, it could help reverse slumping voter
participation, which is especially prevalent among computer-savvy
young people.
</P>
<P>
   But staging a pick 'n' click election ``is not like most other
applications on the Internet,'' California Secretary of State Bill
Jones warned at a briefing here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said a forthcoming California task force study on Internet
voting will call for a four-stage process.
</P>
<P>
   In stage one, he suggested, Internet voting would take place at
the voter's wired-up traditional polling place. As mouse clicks
replace punch cards, ballots could be tabulated more rapidly. But
the thorny problem of online identity _ being able to prove you are
who you say you are _ would not arise.
</P>
<P>
   Stage two would expand the process to any local polling place,
including schools and libraries with fast Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commuters who went to work before the polls open could vote
during their lunch break,'' said Jim Adler, a former rocket
scientist who serves as chief executive officer of VoteHere.net,
one of several startup companies in an expanding field.
</P>
<P>
   During the next step, people could vote from kiosks located in
conveniently located malls and other urban centers. But Adler and
Jones both emphasized that these voters would be required to obtain
their Internet ballots through much the same paper-based
authentication process that today governs mail-in absentee ballots.
</P>
<P>
   A final and somewhat distant goal is remote voting at any time
and from any place with Internet access, including TV sets in the
home equipped with digital two-way set-top boxes. Before that
happens, election officials and computer experts must devise
totally foolproof ways of dealing with possible fraud and potential
hackers who could mount crippling virus attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet holds out the promise of allowing us to build in
integration of voting with voter education and information about
candidates that we never had before,'' said Larry Sabato, a
political science professor at University of Virginia who has
successfully used VoteHere's software in mock elections for his
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think Internet voting is coming? Yes, I do,'' said Thomas
Ferguson, the Connecticut-based chairman of the National
Association of State Election Directors. ``But first there have to
be answers to some of the unanswered questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Pending legislation would direct President Clinton to initiate a
broad federal study of Internet voting issues that could provide
some of them.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's chief sponsor, Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr., D-Ill., seeks
ways of implementing voting via cyberspace without furthering the
``digital divide'' _ the access gap between rich and poor, whites
and minorities, urban and rural residents.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing the legislation, Jackson said voting on line,
``presents a fantastic opportunity to reverse a 40-year decline in
national voter turnout. American families increasingly find it
difficult to take time from their busy work schedules, child care
and community activities to vote. ... The Internet could make
voting easier, more convenient and extremely efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the trail-blazing California study, which is due
out later this month, recent signs of interest include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A pilot program run by the Defense Department and at least
five states that will allow a small number of military personnel
stationed overseas to vote on line in next November's presidential
contest.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Arizona, as many as 50,000 Democrats are gearing up to vote
on line from their homes and offices in the party's March
presidential primary. To do so, they must first register with party
officials and obtain a secure digital code that verifies their
identity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Next month, VoteHere.net will host a straw poll for some 3,500
registered Alaska Republicans who live in a Texas-sized remote
region that is accessible at that time of year only by snowmobile
and dog sled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to talk about all the benefits involved,'' said
Adler, who has set up January Alaska vote. ``But this has to be
totally redundant and totally safe. It's not like Internet polling
or even (corporate) proxy voting, both of which have been around
for some time. With Internet voting, you can't have any mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
