<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DISABLED18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SIGNS BILL EXTENDING INSURANCE FOR WORKING DISABLED
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a memorial to the nation's most disabled
president as a backdrop, President Clinton signed a bill Friday
designed to help the disabled return to work by preserving their
federal health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we say, with a simple but clear voice, no one should
have to choose between taking a job and having health care,''
Clinton said, standing before a large statue of President Franklin
D. Roosevelt sitting in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation reorients our policy by saying health care
ought to be a tool to getting a job, earning a salary, paying taxes
and living up to one's God-given potential. You don't have to worry
about losing Medicare or Medicaid any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Roosevelt kept his paralysis from polio largely
hidden _ a blanket obscures the wheelchair in the FDR statue _
Clinton said encouraging the disabled to work will benefit all
Americans by boosting the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No country, however rich, can afford the waste of its human
resources,'' Clinton said, quoting Roosevelt. ``That is ever more
true as we cross the threshold into the new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, which overwhelmingly passed both houses of Congress,
requires states over the next four years to provide severely
disabled workers a ``ticket'' that allows them to obtain
rehabilitation, employment and other support services, either from
a government agency or private provider.
</P>
<P>
   It also extends by four and a half years _ to a total of eight
and a half years _ Medicare coverage of disabled workers who return
to work.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted the bill also would benefit workers suffering from
early stages of debilitating diseases such as Parkinson's disease
and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, also known as Lou Gehrig's
disease, by creating a $250 million demonstration project allowing
them to buy into the federal-state Medicaid program.
</P>
<P>
   Such workers now face the agonizing choice of leaving their job,
which often does not provide insurance coverage for such illnesses,
in order to qualify for government assistance.
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, said the
new law ``will help people with disabilities pass through the doors
of opportunity and return to self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government should be tearing down barriers to work, not
building them up,'' Archer said. ``We are our brothers' and
sisters' keepers, and I can think of nothing more important than
providing support to help individuals to reach their utmost
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Labor Committee Chairman James Jeffords, R-Vt., who with
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., escorted Clinton to to podium,
also referred to the FDR Memorial setting, noting that ``what
President Roosevelt felt obliged to keep private can now be
celebrated in public.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
