<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIJORING GETS LAZY DOGS INTO SHAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Besides Lucy Studds, Rufus Whittemore, Oban O'Conner, Lady Jane
Gammons, and very few others, modern dogs have essentially gone
stupid because they don't have enough to do. Nothing really to
occupy the mind or stimulate growth.
</P>
<P>
   They're also out of shape, for the most part, and we're not just
talking about fraternity dogs fed on pizza scraps and stale beer.
</P>
<P>
   No, these are modern dogs, most of whom are underemployed and
given to all kinds of undignified foolishness with slippers,
pillows, and tennis balls. Especially in winter, dogs need chores
to keep them fit.
</P>
<P>
   As it just so happens, there is a growing outdoor winter sport
to alleviate this canine crisis. The sport is skijoring, which is
practiced widely in Europe, especially the Nordic countries.
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients include: snow, one to four dogs, harness and
leash, and a rider on cross-country skis. Then, mush, you huskies!
</P>
<P>
   Actually, any sort of dog will do, said Richard Dale-Mesaros
who, with wife Lydia, is promoting skijoring as just one option in
what he calls ``dog-powered sports.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we're in the business of providing equipment and
information to people doing any kind of active dog-powered sport,
be it skijoring or being pulled on rollerblades, mountain bikes, or
(snow) scooters,'' Dale-Mesaros said.
</P>
<P>
   Dale-Mesaros agrees most average dogs can use the kind of
activity skijoring provides. It also teaches people how to train
their dogs. In one case, he said, Lydia e-mailed instructions to
two women on how to train their Labrador retrievers to pull them on
mountain bikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They train them by putting a bunch of biscuits down one end of
a dirt road, and then let them take off, flying down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Some obvious problems arise when skijorers expect to practice
their sport at cross-country ski areas. The fact is, dogs and
cross-country do not blend well, and many areas ban dogs from the
trails.
</P>
<P>
   But not all. Some 14 New England areas allow dogs and skijoring
_ which in Europe is also done behind reindeer and horses. In
March, Waterville Valley will host the first skijoring World Cup
event ever in this country, and Dale-Mesaros believes this will put
the sport on the map.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the states, dog-powered sports are growing because there's
very little cost. About $80 for the gear, including the skijoring
belt, tug lines, and harness. Skis and dogs sold separately.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can start on the road to skijoring, said Dale-Mesaros, by
walking and running with dogs in the woods and teaching the
commands at forks in the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your dog can be sitting around on the porch all summer, and
you shouldn't expect him to drag you 10 miles without having a
heart attack. It's good to do some walking and running with your
dogs first to get them in shape. `Gee' and `haw' are the left and
right commands, `on by' means keep on going, and `whoa' usually
falls on deaf ears,'' said Dale-Mesaros.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need Alaskan malmutes, though they are the standard
sled-pullers in the north country. But any sturdy dog that can pull
the weight of a human can be a skijorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about Labs and German shepherds and
retrievers,'' he said, ``is that they're very easy to train. Some
of the old mushers would tie their lead dog to a post and bring the
head from side to side saying `gee' and `haw.' But it's a lot more
dog-friendly if you can just go out and walk with them, giving them
commands when they get to a fork in the trail. When they make the
correct choice, you give them loads of praise and positive
reinforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, canine and human athletes compete on a World Cup
circuit all winter. The March 3/4 event at Waterville will be the
largest ever on the continent, with the entire tour here competing
for World Cup points.
</P>
<P>
   The course is a 7K groomed trail through the White Mountain
National Forest. The event has already attracted TV coverage, and
Dale-Mesaros expects a mix of dog lovers, cross-country lovers, and
lots of curiosity seekers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of dog-powered sports is not yet mainstream with
the American public,'' says Dale-Mesaros. ``Give it another six
months and it probably will be.''
</P>
<P>
   One important tip for beginners to remember: ``Don't run over
your dog. It will slow down the whole learning process.'' And give
the dogs time to learn the commands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really cool when they do respond to the commands,'' he
said, adding that flying through the woods on a mountain bike and
having his Alaskan malmutes respond at a fork in the road makes
dog-powered sport the experience it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so excited about this,'' he said. ``This is the sport we
have a passion for. We love our dogs and we love doing stuff
outdoors with them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(The Dale-Mesaroses have a Web site link at www.xski.org, or call
(603) 536-3864 for information.)
</P>
</TEXT>
