<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNING ISSUES IN HIS THOUGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picked-up pieces while worrying about global warming and Tebucky
Jones starting at cornerback . . .
</P>
<P>
   --As for Rae ``Mind-if-we-check-the-trunk, ma'am?'' Carruth,
what is there to say other than, ``Where's the Mystic River Bridge
when we really need it?''
</P>
<P>
   --When Sports Illustrated gathered the greats of the sports
world at Madison Square Garden for its all-century TV show, the mag
listed the top six NBA players and did not include Bill Russell.
Wilt Chamberlain, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Michael Jordan, Larry Bird,
Magic Johnson, and Oscar Robertson made the cut. Preposterous. Any
top-six list has to have the man who won 11 championships in 13
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   --I don't know about you, but I'm having trouble buying Cameron
Diaz as an NFL owner in ``Any Given Sunday.'' She looks nothing at
all like Marge Schott.
</P>
<P>
   --Why do the Red Sox worry so much about season ticket- holders
scalping or reselling tickets when the Sox sell tickets to ticket
agencies? According to Sox flak Kevin Shea, ``The reason we go
after unlicensed sellers is that we're trying to protect our fans
from getting gouged when they buy tickets for our games.'' Some of
us might contend that the agencies are the ones doing the gouging.
</P>
<P>
   --Anybody else wonder about team morale when Lawyer Milloy
refers to Drew Bledsoe as ``Big Money.''
</P>
<P>
   --Wonder if Jacksonville running back James Stewart watches
``It's a Wonderful Life,'' this time every year?
</P>
<P>
   --If Carl Everett can just be as good as Ellis Burks, that'll be
good enough to make the Red Sox lineup a lot better in 2000.
Everett's domestic situation raises a flag, however. It's news when
a millionaire athlete loses custody of his daughter because of
child abuse charges. Wil Cordero and Christian Peter were run out
of this town because of off-field activities, and Everett would do
well to explain the touchy situation and put it behind him.
</P>
<P>
   --Speaking of Cordero _ who looked 20 pounds heavier when the
Sox played Cleveland in October _ the Pirates rewarded him with a
three-year, $9 million contract. I think he said he's always wanted
to play in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   --Sean McDonough not getting renewed by CBS is a joke.
</P>
<P>
   --Ken Griffey Jr. gets high marks for squashing a deal to the
Mets. He said he hates New York and backed it up with his actions.
However, it's tough to buy the ``Junior just wants to be closer to
his family in Orlando'' spin put forth by Griffey and the Mariners.
Anybody making $100 million can afford to move his family to
Seattle. Why can't Griff and the Mariners just admit that he
doesn't like the franchise or the new ballpark?
</P>
<P>
   --Nice to see that President Clinton wants baseball to forgive
Pete Rose. Pete and Bill are a good pair: two guys who believe that
a lie becomes truth if you repeat it enough times.
</P>
<P>
   _Tebucky ``Give Him The Damn Ball'' Jones says, ``My style and
his (Ty Law's) are different.'' Echoing the thoughts of Patriot
Nation, Globe desk whiz Scott Thurston says, ``Yeah, we know. Law
can cover guys. Tebucky can't.''
</P>
<P>
   --Rick Pitino snapping at TV's Bob Halloran was mildy
reminiscent of the Bill Parcells era.
</P>
<P>
   --The Globe's Page 1, in-dept interview with the inimitable Bob
Kraft almost had me crying Monday. Kraft dropped these whoppers on
our intrepid Meg Vaillancourt: ``When we got such a vote of support
from hard-working (Foxborough) people who were willing to come out
on a rainy night . . . it felt like it was my family saying
`Welcome home.' '' . . . and, ``I hope somehow we can try to make
it up to the good people of Connecticut and to the political
leaders down there who unfortunately took the heat for it.''
</P>
<P>
   --Keep an eye on Houston Rocket Cuttino Mobley, a former URI
player and one of the few NBA rising stars who puts on a show worth
NBA prices.
</P>
<P>
   --The New Jersey Devils play at the New Garden on the first
night of the next century. The Devils are coached by the greatest
high school hockey player (Needham) in Massachusetts history,
Robbie Ftorek, and their assistant coach, Viacheslav Fetisov, was a
member of the 1980 Soviet Union Olympic team that lost to Mike
Eruzione and Co. in Lake Placid. They've also got a 19-year-old
rookie, Scott Gomez, who is the first player of Hispanic lineage
(his dad's from Mexico, his mom's Columbian, and he grew up in
Anchorage) in NHL history.
</P>
<P>
   --Tough year for both author and subject of ``The Girl Who Loved
Tom Gordon,'' by Stephen King. The horror writer looks as if he'll
be back before Flash.
</P>
<P>
   --What will we all do when we don't have Pete Carroll to kick
around anymore?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
