<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBERT'S RETURN NO SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dick Ebersol is one of the most powerful men in television
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Smart and charming, the president of NBC Sports would have us
believe that the reappointment of Marv Albert as lead NBA
play-by-play announcer was an act of graciousness on the part of
Bob Costas, the guy who replaced Albert after his little legal
problem.
</P>
<P>
   You remember the sordid tale of biting and garter belts, the
claims of innocence everywhere except inside the Virginia
courthouse where Albert pleaded guilty. All of that is behind
Albert these days, and Ebersol, to his credit, always said Albert
had a home at NBC as long as he was on watch.
</P>
<P>
   So it was written; so it was done.
</P>
<P>
   The Albert rehabilitation started three years ago when the
Madison Square Garden cable network hired him to call Knicks games.
Turner Sports put him on its payroll shortly after that, and NBC
followed suit. Albert resumes his lead NBA position next season.
</P>
<P>
   Albert is one of the boys, and his return was predictable. But
the real reason Albert is back is not that Costas was gracious but
that Costas just wasn't that good as a basketball announcer.
</P>
<P>
   Costas concedes that he wasn't as good as Albert, but that
didn't stop him from taking the job given him on a platter by
Ebersol. At the time, Greg Gumbel was the number two play-by-play
guy at NBC. Gumbel quit soon after and became CBS's top
play-by-play guy for NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol is very smooth. Whether NBA receives high ratings with
Albert next fall remains to be seen. But as it is now, the NBA is
losing viewers, and Albert alone won't reverse the trend.
</P>
<P>
   Costas certainly couldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   Costas is sure to excel on his new assignment on HBO, which
announced that a new show with him as host will premiere in 15
months. According to Costas, the show will be a sports version of
``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross Greenburg, senior vice president of HBO Sports, said the
show will fit with HBO's other programming, such as ``Real Sports
with Bryant Gumbel'' and some award-winning documentaries. ``Let's
be realistic,'' Greenburg told reporters. ``We don't have $800
million laying around to acquire a live sports property. With the
exception of our premier boxing events, we are not a live-sports
network. We know who we are and we have carved our niche by being
reflective journalists. Costas is an extension of our philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Costas has been at NBC for 20 years and has wanted to do such a
show for at least the last five. He would like the show to delve
beyond the surface of stories such as the ongoing one about Rae
Carruth, the Carolina Panthers wide receiver charged in the murder
of his girlfriend. ``We would want to talk not just about the
specifics of the case but also question what sort of person is
welcomed to college sports programs and what, if any, safeguards
there should be to prevent such a tragedy,'' Costas said.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Costas took a swipe at NFL pregame shows. ``I
understand that those shows are there to set the table for the
day's games,'' Costas said. ``But to me, it's staggering that those
programs can be on air for hundreds of hours and never address the
largest issue _ franchise extortion and related stadium issues.
When I did the pregame show for NBC, I was champing at the bit to
do those kinds of stories.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If not Carroll, who?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS football analyst Gus Johnson poses a good question: If the
Patriots get rid of coach Pete Carroll at the end of the season,
who will replace him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to fire a head coach,'' said Johnson, who will
work with Brent Jones and Beasley Reece on Sunday's Patriots-Eagles
telecast. ``You can't tell me that Bill Cowher is any less of a
good coach because his (Steelers) team has struggled this year.
Pete Carroll is a young, enthusiastic coach who inherited a Super
Bowl team coached by a legend. He has made the playoffs the last
two years. Give the guy a break. If they fire Carroll, who will
replace him? There's not that many Super Bowl-winning coaches out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson believes that Carroll has been successful in his three
years and, while it has underachieved, his team remains one of the
more competitive in the NFL. ``My point is this: If you run Carroll
out of town, what coach is out there to replace him?'' said
Johnson. ``All the names that have been floated have strengths and
weaknesses. None have actually won a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to remember: The coach doesn't play. These
athletes are grown millionaires that have to execute on the field.
A coach can only do so much.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
