<HEADLINE>
`STUART LITTLE' COMES UP SHORT ON CHARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
STUART LITTLE 
Directed by: Rob Minkoff 
Screenplay by: M. Night Shyamalan and Greg Booker, based on E.B.
White's novel 
Starring: Geena Davis, Hugh Laurie, Jonathan Lipnicki, Jeffrey
Jones, Connie Ray, Allyce Beasley, Brian Doyle-Murray, Estelle
Getty, Harold Gould, Patrick O'Brien, Julia Sweeney, Dabney
Coleman, with the voices of Michael J. Fox, Nathan Lane, Chazz
Palminteri, Steve Zahn, Jim Doughan, David Alan Greer, Bruno Kirby,
Jennifer Tilly and Stan Freberg 
Running time: 92 minutes 
Rated: PG (brief language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The impetus to see ``Stuart Little'' will come largely from
parents who fondly remember the E. B. White classic about the mouse
who refuses to think small. There are, after all, only so many
times kids can sit through ``Toy Story 2,'' and here's an
acceptable alternative. But whether they'll come away from this
adequate but hardly magical retelling of the story about the can-do
mouse and match their parents' enthusiasm is questionable. In its
visual style and production design, especially the Little family's
ancestral digs, tucked in between two Fifth Avenue high-rises, the
film is designed to evoke a certain nostalgia for the genteel
patrician Manhattan world to which The New Yorker (and White's
writing) were aimed.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers have taken a few liberties with the story, right
from the start, when Stuart is adopted, not born, into the Little
household, which would have been even more difficult to explain
than the film's fanciful adoption procedures. Geena Davis brings
warmth and aplomb to the role of Mrs. Little, and Hugh Laurie
embodies Mr. Little with the button-eyed good cheer of a
traditional up-market greeting card. Jonathan Lipnicki, as the boy
who must learn to accept Stuart as a brother, goes through his
paces engagingly enough. But any retelling of ``Stuart Little''
must rise or fall on its mouse. This one rises, but only so far,
even though it allows sufficient weight for the story's message
about the qualities that sustain families.
</P>
<P>
   This Stuart was hatched from a computer, and is the product of
visual effects that didn't exist as recently as five years ago.
He's three inches of cuteness, and the voice of Michael J. Fox does
a lot to win us over, but we're never altogether nudged into
believing that we're watching anything but a sophisticated toy. As
impressive as the technological Stuart may be, I was more impressed
with the performances that the filmmakers, aided by a band of cat
wranglers, got out of the 23 cats playing the eight feline roles in
the film. Most of the cats are of course hostile toward Stuart. In
their eyes, he's lunch, but with attitude. Not that their menacing
ways stop the spunky little guy, but Nathan Lane's surly Noo
Yawk-accented house cat, a white Persian Chinchilla named Snowbell,
almost steals the film anyway. The new ``Stuart Little'' is OK, but
it's never so charming that you forget you're watching a
manufactured object.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
