<SLUG> BC-FBN-COACHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACHES IN THE LINE OF FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of the 101 head coaches in the NFL since 1980 (not including
interims), only eight have been fired after winning seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The situations have been quite different and some of the
dismissals are filed under the ``You-can't-fire-me-I-quit''
heading, but the two most clear-cut firings were done by the
Patriots, when general Patrick Sullivan fired Ron Meyer after a 5-3
start to the 1984 season, and by the Raiders, who fired Art Shell
following a 9-7 season in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The most bizarre firing was of John Mackovic in Kansas City
following the 1986 season, in which he led the Chiefs to a 10-6
record and into the playoffs for the first time in 15 years. Yet he
was gone when a player revolt supposedly occurred, and the Chiefs
promoted special teams coach Frank Gansz.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Ryan was also gone after the Philadelphia Eagles went 10-6
in 1990, but the firing came after he had lost his third straight
playoff game, which owner Norman Braman could no longer bear.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots coach Pete Carroll could join this select group.
</P>
<P>
   Bum Phillips, who was relieved of his duties in 1980 by the
Houston Oilers after having posted an 11-5 record and a
third-straight playoff berth, received a multiyear contract
proposal from Oiler owner Bud Adams at the time, but it wasn't
enough for Phillips, who turned it down and was replaced afterward.
He wound up taking the head coaching job at New Orleans in 1981,
and a year later was also named the GM.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Houston, Jerry Glanville was replaced following the 1989
season when his 9-7 team was eliminated from the playoffs.
Glanville claims he didn't want to enter the '90 season in the
final year of his contract, got permission to speak to Atlanta, and
coached that team from 1990-93 before being fired following a 6-10
season. Others say Glanville was fired in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Colts coach Ted Marchibroda finished 9-7 and lost to Pittsburgh
in the AFC Championship Game in 1995, but only after he asked for a
two-year contract extension while the Colts sent a message with a
one-year offer, which Marchibroda rejected. The Colts turned to
Lindy Infante, and Marchibroda took the head job with the Baltimore
Ravens in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Leeman Bennett's Atlanta Falcons finished 5-4 in
strike-shortened 1982 and lost a playoff game to Minnesota. He was
replaced by Dan Henning.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Schottenheimer walked away, he insists, from Art Modell
and the Cleveland Browns following a 10-6 season in 1988 after the
Browns lost to the Oilers in the playoffs. Schottenheimer refused
to fire some of his coaching staff and took a chance he'd find a
new job. He didn't have to wait long, as the Kansas City Chiefs
came calling.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer is certainly the only coach fired with a winning record
during a season. He had finished 8-8 in 1983 and was going along
fine until he decided to fire defensive coordinator Rod Rust after
a 44-24 pummeling by the Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at the league meetings that week and we received a
call from `Moose' Hoffman, who was our public relations man at the
time, and he said, `Ron just fired Rod Rust,' '' recalled Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got on the phone with Ron immediately and I said, `What are
you doing?' This came out of the blue. He had never discussed it
with the management or the ownership. Coordinators have always made
good money and so we were on the hook for it. So we told Ron he
couldn't do it. He said, `If you don't like it, fire me.' And so we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said Meyer had a ``credibility problem among the
players'' and he questioned, ``Is this guy capable of leading 45-50
people?'' He gave the job to Raymond Berry, whom he dismissed after
the 1989 season when Berry refused to hire a defensive coordinator.
Berry wanted to take on the duties of head coach, offensive
coordinator, and defensive coordinator. ``We felt at that point,
Raymond needed some help,'' said Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Several coaches have seen their last days after 8-8 seasons,
including Dan Reeves in 1992 with Denver, Bruce Coslet with the
Jets in '93, and Bobby Ross with the Chargers in '96 after a slow
downward trek from a Super Bowl appearance in '94.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Erickson lost his job in Seattle last season after an 8-8
mark and a 31-33 record. Bart Starr was 8-8 in '83 when his Packer
tenure ended with a 53-77 record. Bud Grant's first retirement came
after an 8-8 season in '83; he returned to finish 7-9 in '85 before
calling it quits in Minnesota. His successor, Jerry Burns, who was
55-46 during his tenure (1986-91), was fired after an 8-8 season.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, there are many different factors each coach
ultimately faces on judgment day. Either he didn't make the
playoffs, or he kept losing in the playoffs, or the team had tuned
him out.
</P>
<P>
   Shell was 56-41 from 1989-94, but owner Al Davis grew impatient
with his coach, who had made a most unfortunate comment about Jeff
Hostetler, calling him ``just another white quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Some liken Ross's situation to Carroll's, but the difference is
Ross took the Chargers to the Super Bowl, while Carroll inherited a
team that already had been there.
</P>
<P>
   There's a whole category of legendary coaches who left after
winning seasons following disputes with their ownership. Don Shula
``retired'' after '95 with a 9-7 record, George Seifert was gone
from the 49ers after a 12-4 year, Parcells left New England after
an 11-5 season and a Super Bowl appearance, Jimmy Johnson walked
away from the Cowboys after winning a Super Bowl in 1993, and Mike
Holmgren left the Packers after an 11-5 season and two Super Bowl
rings.
</P>
<P>
   With rumors circulating about Carroll, Glanville offered this
advice: ``It doesn't matter what everybody else says. It matters
what one person says, and that is Bob Kraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan was asked assess the management team in Foxborough.
Asked if there were grounds for firing Carroll, he said,
``Absolutely not. The stability of a management team is so
important. The life of a player is four years, no matter how you
look at it. You're going to have some good stretches and some
not-so-good stretches. For Carroll to have made the playoffs his
first two years and be over .500 now, that's pretty successful. I
don't care what market you're in.''
</P>
<P>
   He also defends vice president of player personnel Bobby Grier's
``poor drafts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody brings up the good players he picked,'' said Sullivan.
``Nobody brings up that Robert Edwards was one of his picks and he
had an unfortunate accident. One of the biggest mistakes I made was
not hiring Bobby in the position he's in a long time ago. He should
have been my choice.'' Sullivan instead hired Joe Mendes.
</P>
<P>
   Acutely aware of the hostile environment when a team doesn't
perform up to expectations, Sullivan said, ``If I were to criticize
my own performance, I was too reactive to that type of thing. The
Patriots now have a strong enough following where they can take a
long-term view. They'll have to ask themselves who can they bring
in here that will do a better job than Pete Carroll? The answer to
that question is guys like Parcells, Holmgren, maybe Seifert, who
are already working.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
