<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IPO PUTS ENTREPRENEURS ON STAGE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're back (again).
</P>
<P>
   John Donovan, charismatic and controversial technology lecturer
to the corporate elite, and his wealthy entrepreneurial protege,
Sundar Subramaniam, are knee-deep in a new Cambridge consulting
company with an initial public stock offering priced and primed for
its first day of trading Friday.
</P>
<P>
   C-Bridge Internet Solutions is led by a senior management team
chock full of former Oracle Corp. executives, including the
consulting firm's highly regarded new chief executive, Joseph
Bellini.
</P>
<P>
   But a handful of offshore trusts and entities benefitting
Subramaniam, his relatives, and Donovan's relatives control a
majority of the C-Bridge stock.
</P>
<P>
   Subramaniam was the company's chief executive until May, and
C-Bridge documents say a ``substantial majority'' of the company's
business engagements were generated by sales leads from seminars
featuring Donovan and a company that counts him as an employee.
</P>
<P>
   Underwriters priced C-Bridge stock at $16 per share, which
valued the entire company at $276 million. It clearly marks another
public-stock fortune built for the investment vehicles connected by
Donovan and Subramaniam.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan, a former MIT professor and prolific author, has
attracted ardent supporters and critics in his life as an
entrepreneur. But it is on the seminar circuit where a big-picture
technology vision created his biggest following.
</P>
<P>
   Subramaniam, who was recruited by Donovan straight out of
Brandeis University in the late 1980s, is just coming off another
investment home run. His personal stake in International
Integration Inc., widely known as ``I-Cube,'' was worth about $310
million when the company he helped develop was sold to Razorfish
Inc. last month.
</P>
<P>
   International Integration Inc. was working in an area similar to
C-Bridge's business, selling consulting services, help with
electronic business, and ``transformation services.'' Unlike at
other young businesses Subramaniam helped build, Donovan appeared
to have no role at International Integration.
</P>
<P>
   But two previous public ventures, both with Donovan close at
hand, were disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Open Environment Corp. of Cambridge, Mass., a software company,
went public at $15 per share in 1995 and was sold to Borland
International for $4 a share less than a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Their next effort, OneWave Inc., went public in 1996 at $16 per
share and plunged to below $3 in less than a year. A venture firm
later bought a majority interest in the company, now called Primix
Solutions Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Public shareholders got clobbered in both stocks, but Donovan
and Subramaniam cushioned their own declines by selling shares into
the public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case at C-Bridge, an IPO that involves no inside
sellers. Three of the big offshore trusts that own stock have
signed lockups that prohibit the sale of shares for periods ranging
from one year to three years.
</P>
<P>
   C-Bridge works out of the same building in Cambridge where many
Donovan start-ups began. Like other companies that grew up there,
C-Bridge trades in part on Donovan's high-tech following and
corporate backers, particularly Hewlett Packard Co.
</P>
<P>
   C-Bridge also has corporate muscle from Oracle behind it.
Besides the group of management alums, C-Bridge counts Oracle
president Raymond J. Lane as a director.
</P>
<P>
   Smack in the middle of one of the Internet's hottest growth
industries, C-Bridge boasts a roster of impressive clients and
fast-growing though modest-size revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The company has done business with companies that include
include US West, General Motors, SteelCase, Caterpillar, Liz
Claiborne, and Cardinal Health Care, according to public documents.
</P>
<P>
   But the booming e-business consulting industry is also drawing
heavyweight competition. By C-Bridge's own description, it
sometimes faces off against the likes of Scient Corp. and Viant
Corp. when it comes to Internet services, Sapient Inc. and Anderson
Consulting on systems integration, and Bain and McKinsey for
management consulting services.
</P>
<P>
   C-Bridge may well get off to a hot start as a public stock. When
underwriters priced the offering at $16 per share, they jumped over
the original estimate range of $12 to $14 each.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
