<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRANSPORTATION, HOUSING TOP CONCERNS IN BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
 SF-HOUSING   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RYAN KIM  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The skyrocketing cost of home ownership made
housing the second most important concern for residents in the San
Francisco Bay Area, according to a survey conducted for the Bay
Area Council.
</P>
<P>
   As it has for years, transportation remained the top concern in
the region, listed by 38 percent of respondents, down from 40
percent last year. The poll, which has been released by the council
every year since 1980, also included new statistics on Internet and
computer use in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve percent of the respondents listed housing as the biggest
problem facing the Bay Area, the highest number this decade. Sunne
Wright McPeak, president and chief executive of the Bay Area
Council, which is backed by businesses in the region, said housing
has not kept pace with the tremendous job growth of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Housing has emerged as the second Achilles' heel in the Bay
Area,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The poll looked at the housing situation and found many
residents were discouraged by the cost of homes. Eighty-six percent
of those surveyed said housing costs had gotten worse in the past
year and 81 percent agreed there is a shortage of affordable
housing in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The random survey of 607 residents of the Bay Area was conducted
by telephone by the Field Research Corp. Oct. 20 to Nov. 3. The
poll has a margin of error is 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Many respondents said they want to see more housing growth, just
not always in their own neighborhood. Forty-eight percent of those
polled said they did not want new housing in their own community.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a true `not-in-my-back-yard' sentiment that hasn't
changed since 1994,'' McPeak said.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration with the region's transportation network and highway
system was still far and away the leading concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is uniform throughout the region,'' McPeak said. ``It's
true in every one of the nine counties.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite growing frustration with transportation and housing,
residents remained upbeat about the future of the region.
Seventy-three percent of the respondents said it was possible for
the Bay Area to grow economically while at the same time improving
the quality of life here.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the poll looked at how pervasive the
Internet and computers have become in the region. The poll found 79
percent of residents regularly use a computer, with 64 percent of
them using them at home. San Francisco led the region in computer
use with 82 percent of its residents using a computer, either at
work or at home.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that 66 percent regularly access the Internet,
well above the national average of 50 percent, McPeak said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We truly have a digital bay and it's not just Multimedia Gulch
or Silicon Valley or pockets of Internet use,'' she said. ``It's
pretty evenly spread out.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of the Internet and computers, however, was not uniform
across economic lines. For example, of people making less than
$40,000 a year, 65 percent of them used a computer regularly.
Conversely, 86 percent of those making between $40,000 and $79,000
used a computer.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also found that residents with less education were less
likely to use computers and go on the Internet. Forty percent of
respondents with a high school degree or less use the Internet,
while 78 percent of college graduates go on line.
</P>
<P>
   With a healthy economy and low unemployment, only 3 percent of
those surveyed rated it the top problem. Fifty-two percent of
people said their personal finances were better than last year. The
economy was the top concern for residents in 1992 and 1993, at the
height of the region's recession.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
