<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV19-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTOR PICKED A POOR TIME TO TRY BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 19, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. In September I received an inheritance of $100,000. I am 79.
I went to our savings and loan, intending to put it in a CD. The
lady I talked with asked if I would prefer a tax-free municipal
bond fund. I ended up putting the entire amount in a Franklin
California Tax-Free Income fund account. The price was $7.56 per
share at the time, and I paid a $4,000 sales charge. I realize that
it was my own fault, but I was not familiar with mutual funds. The
price is now $6.80 per share. My question is, at my age should I
continue to leave the money there or take it out and take the loss?
I do take out the interest each month. Will this rise in my
lifetime? What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   M.T., Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, you certainly picked a poor time to get into the bond
market, and an equally poor place to do your investing. Based on an
unscientific survey over nearly a decade of reading letters from
often-troubled fund investors, Ive found that the chances of a
person buying a mutual fund that they don't understand is greatly
enhanced if they buy their funds through a bank. In your case, its
probably not that the investment is inappropriate for you, but that
the risks inherent in the fund should have been explained in
sufficient detail to insure that you understood them.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the fund you bought is an excellent one,
and although it has had a bad year, the odds are excellent that it
will recover. Basically, bond funds of all sorts lose principal
value when interest rates rise, or when the market sentiment is
that they are likely to rise. Inversely, when rates fall or when
people think rates are likely to fall, the value of shares in bond
funds rises. Usually, this effect becomes sharper the longer the
duration of the funds holdings. When there is a portfolio of
long-term bonds such as your fund holds, the effect of rate changes
will be greater than for funds holding a shorter-duration
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the interest rate increases of 1999 -- and the
fears that more are in the short-term pipeline -- has been that
this fund has produced a year-to-date loss of 3.53 percent as this
is written. Bond funds usually have about two tough years in every
decade, and for the nineties the bad years have been 1994 and 1999.
But good bond funds tend to make up the lost ground in the other
years. Thus Franklin California Tax-Free Income fund boasts a
five-year record of average annual total returns of 6.25 percent,
and a 10-year record of 6.48 percent average annual returns. This
is good enough to win it the top five-star rating from Morningstar
Mutual Funds, which credits it with above-average performance and
low risk relative to its peer funds.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, remember why you bought the fund -- to get a steady
tax-free income stream each month. This, as youve seen, continues
despite the fluctuations in the principal value.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion is to stick with the fund, which, if the patterns
of the past prevail in the future, will recover the lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   One final caveat: if you decide to make any further investments,
make sure you fully understand what youre buying before you make
the move. This time you bought a good fund at a bad time. Under
other circumstances, you might not have been so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband is 55 and earns $63,000 a year. I am 53 earn
$53,000. Our home is paid for and worth approximately $95,000. We
have no children living at home and no outstanding debt. We have
$170,000 in mutual fund and common stock investments through our
local bank; two years ago when we made the initial investment, we
were told to expect our money to triple in 10 years if all went
well. My husband has $44,855 in a 401(k) account from a previous
employer, and has a new 401(k) account just begun with his new
employer, to which he contributes 15 percent of his salary and the
company matches on a sliding scale up to 6 percent. I have a 403(b)
account worth $6,100 to which I contribute 22 percent of my
earnings. We also have $4,000 in IRAs. Can we expect to triple our
money in 10 years as the financial counselor at our bank has
stated? If we continue to invest as noted, at approximately what
age can we expect to retire? The officer at the bank suggest we
diversify our holdings by adding a fund that invests in small
companies.
</P>
<P>
   J.M., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A. If you continue saving at the current rate and if you achieve
average portfolio returns of 10 percent, you would have $892,007 in
ten years when your husband turns 65. That calculation is based on
6 percent employer contributions to your husbands 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   That may sound like a pretty tidy pile, but if you invested the
whole accumulation in fixed-income securities to provide an income
stream, earning an average 6.5 percent yield, it would amount to
$57,980 a year. Worse, if inflation averages 3.5 percent over that
period, that money would have the buying power of about $41,000 in
today's money. Not an overwhelming prospect, no. The situation
might be made rosier with Social Security benefits, and the
accumulation would be larger if you increased retirement savings
proportionately with any raises you get. But theres no question
that you would not be in a great position.
</P>
<P>
   If you increased your savings level so that both of you fully
funded IRAs each year, the accumulation would be $958,681, using
the same assumptions. Better, but still far from perfect. You may
want to consider delaying retirement until you reach age 65, or
until 12 years from now. At that point, again using the same
assumptions, you would have $1,133,995 if you saved at current
levels, or $1,223,458 if you funded both IRAs each year.
</P>
<P>
   That highest figure might produce an income stream of $79,524,
equivalent to about $52,500 in today's money, making the same
inflation assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   Is your banks financial counselors projection realistic? Well,
to triple your money over the course of a decade requires average
annual returns of 11.61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thats not far off the historical average returns for the stock
market, but given the overperformance of the market in recent years
(which I believe will be balanced by a period of underperformance)
I am more comfortable with lower projections. I typically use a 10
percent estimate for projecting the long-term growth of a stock
portfolio. But in the bankers favor, without going into detail
about your portfolio holdings, I absolutely agree that you would
likely do well if you diversified by putting about 20 percent of
the current balance into a good small-cap stock fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is your opinion of Massachusetts Investors Trust, class
C? I've been in this fund for about 16 months. I've been in this
for about 16 months. I bought it at $19.24 per share, and in that
time it has gone up $1.20 per share. At the same time I bought
Massachusetts Investors Growth Stock fund, class C, which is up
from $13.74 per share to $18.79. I am concerned that Massachusetts
Investors Trust has not performed well at all during a record stock
market runup. I know its all full of blue chips, so whats up?
</P>
<P>
   R.I., Malden, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, although both funds concentrate on large-cap stocks,
these funds are fishing in pretty different waters. Massachusetts
Investors, like most value-oriented funds, has been underperforming
the market pretty consistently for the past few years, but it has a
very good long-term record. Massachusetts Growth Stock fund, on the
other hand, buys growth-oriented stocks, putting its portfolio in
the market sector which has been the major element pushing the
broad averages to their recent highs, most particularly high-tech
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Should you sell Massachusetts Investors Trust and concentrate in
Massachusetts Growth Company? I wouldnt do it. The stock markets
are notoriously fickle, and today's darling is likely to be
tomorrow's goat, and vice versa. Moreover, with its value-oriented
portfolio, Massachusetts Investors is certainly better positioned
to weather a sour market.
</P>
<P>
   So my suggestion is to do precisely what you are doing --
diversifying into the two ends of the large-cap spectrum,
calculating that although they will not move in tandem, in the long
run each will have its day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
