u s BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      12-17 1513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLY EARNS HIGH-FIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was just a regular-season game between a pair of Philadelphia
schools, Villanova and Temple.
</P>
<P>
   It was no big deal on the national stage. But Wednesday night's
game was signficiant in Philadelphia, because it was symbolic.
Villanova was back in the Big Five family, after agreeing last
spring to resume playing a round-robin schedule of games against
its fellow city schools, Pennsylvania, St. Joseph's, Temple, and
LaSalle.
</P>
<P>
   If you are age 50 or older and a college basketball fan, surely
you remember the tradition of the Big Five, which once made
Philadelphia as hot a college basketball spot as any place in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Five schools playing each other in front of sellout crowds in
the cozy, if not always friendly, confines of the Palestra, vying
for the unofficial city championship each year while also going
about their business in their respective leagues.
</P>
<P>
   It was that way for decades. But times changed. Priorities
became different and Villanova, according to the consensus, decided
it was no longer in its best interests to continue. So the Wildcats
began playing only selective games against the other four
Philadelphia schools, not a round robin, and Big Five basketball
withered on the vine.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to last spring. Villanova found itself with two
fewer Big East games (16, rather than 18) on its dance card. The
Wildcats agreed to resume the round robin.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball unity in Philadelphia?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. ``What happened happened,'' said St. Joe's coach Phil
Martelli earlier this week. ``It was a sign of the times. Now it's
different. And I'm happy it's back. The Big Five didn't belong to
any of us, it was bigger than all of us, and I hope the tradition
of the past can be rekindled. The basketball community in
Philadelphia is whole again, and I think that's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we had here in the past was the essence of college
basketball. It was almost like a clash of brothers. Before the game
and after the game, you would love your brother, but during the 40
minutes of the game, you hated him. This city is full of basketball
fans. Each school has some dormant basketball fans who lost
interest over the years. Hopefully those fans would come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Having said all that, let's move the scene a few hundred miles
north. To Boston College. Harvard. Boston University. Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   Why not a three-game round robin in Boston each year, a revival
of the old Commonwealth Classic?
</P>
<P>
   A BU-BC game would certainly have more flavor and more interest
than St. Francis at BC, which was played in the Conte Morgue on
Saturday night before 3,000 fans, 2,950 of whom did not appear to
be BC students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be in favor it it,'' said BU coach Dennis Wolff. ``I
think it would be great for basketball in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We would certainly go for it,'' said Harvard coach Frank
Sullivan, whose team played all three other schools last season but
doesn't have BC on the schedule this season. ``It would be the
right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The stumbling block, obviously, is BC, which would appear to
have the most to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Athletic director Gene DeFilippo, who came to BC from Villanova
and is very familiar with the tradition of the Big Five, at least
said he is interested in exploring the possibility. ``But you have
to understand it's different than in Philadelphia,'' he said. ``In
Philly, you are dealing with 40 years of great tradition, with a
deep foundation and history.''
</P>
<P>
   So when will the Eagles be scheduling BU, Northeastern, and
Harvard? ``I'm not sure we want to do that at this time,'' said
DeFillippo, ``but it is something to consider in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The down side for BC is obvious. A loss to BU, Northeastern, or
Harvard (which did happen last season) would look bad for a Big
East team. However, the Eagles and their conference are strong
enough to overcome a few speed bumps.
</P>
<P>
   And we're not talking about taking a trip to Cameron Indoor
Stadium. We're talking about getting in a bus and going across
town.
</P>
<P>
   BC's nonconference schedule this season has included games
against Holy Cross, Vermont, and St. Francis. Are those opponents
more attractive than BU, Harvard, and Northeastern?
</P>
<P>
   If college basketball is ever going to establish itself in
Boston, an annual round robin between the city schools makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky blues
</P>
<P>
   Things are getting ugly at Kentucky, where the Wildcats have
dropped out of the Top 25 and are only a .500 team.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the first two questions asked of Kentucky coach Tubby
Smith on his radio show last week:
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we starting a point guard who wasn't ranked in the top
500 prospects in the country in his senior year in high school?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we playing this Joe B. Hall style of ball?''
</P>
<P>
   The most damning part of the first question, of course, was that
the point guard in question happens to be Smith's son, Saul.
</P>
<P>
   No question the Wildcats are struggling. Through their first
five games, the Wildcats were averaging 60.2 points, the lowest
scoring average for a Kentucky team in its first five games in 55
years. A loss to cross-state rival Louisville Saturday night would
put the 'Cats below .500 _ and turn things even uglier in Lexington
for Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Full-court press
</P>
<P>
   If you look up the term ``hoop junkie'' in the dictionary, you
are likely to find a picture of Jim O'Connell, the Associated
Press's highly respected national college basketball writer. The
season is not yet a month old and O'Connell has already covered 27
games. But next week might test even O'Connell's skills. He is
covering not one but two tournaments in Puerto Rico _ on the same
days. ``No problem,'' said O'Connell. ``The games are spaced out
enough and it's only 20 minutes between the two arenas, so I can do
it with no problem. Just as long as there's a Steak and Shake
around, I'll be fine.'' . . . The first month of the season has
established a pecking order of Top 10 teams. Ahead of the pack, by
a comfortable margin, is Cincinnati, with Connecticut, Arizona,
Michigan State, and Duke in the next grouping . . . Ohio State
continues to struggle to meet the expectations of last year's
surprising Final Four appearance. The bottom line is that the
Buckeyes are not as good as most people thought; they will be hard
pressed in almost every Big Ten game they play . . . Early
candidate for upset of year: Indiana State's victory the other day
over Indiana in the Indiana Classic, traditionally an IU block
party each year. The loss was the Hoosiers' first in the 26-year
history of the event . . . Tennessee has gotten off to a quick
start, largely because of the solid play of sophomore Vincent
Yarborough, who is averaging nearly 16 points a game and making 46
percent of his 3-point shots . . . Another hot team is Creighton,
which was picked near the bottom of the Missouri Valley Conference
but is unbeaten with victories over Iowa and Nebraska . . .
Remember the hype when Jerry Tarkanian returned to Fresno State?
Now the Bulldogs are just another sub-.500 team, and no one seems
to care what Tark is or isn't doing . . . San Diego State has
established a strategy under first-year coach Steve Fisher: Win
with 3-point shots. But it hasn't quite worked out that way: In the
Atzecs' first three games, they threw up 44 three-point shots and
made just five. However, help may be on the way next year. San
Diego State has signed Chris Walton, reportedly the best of Bill's
offspring. Walton turned down a scholarship offer from UCLA, which
has to be a first among the Waltons . . . Rick Majerus is not a
happy camper at Utah, where he has been grousing about more than
the room service menu at the hotel where he lives. Injuries are
part of the problem, but Majerus is also sniping at the media,
which could mean there is an underlying cause to Majerus's
unhappinesss . . . At Nevada-Las Vegas, Bill Bayno has the Runnin'
Rebels off to a fast start, with five wins in their first six
games. But the real news is that Bayno, who used to have a high
profile off the court, has toned down his act and become more of a
homebody, preferring staying at home to the nightlife that
characterized his first four years in Vegas . . . Oklahoma coach
Kelvin Sampson noted the $6 billion contract CBS signed with the
NCAA for rights to the basketball tournament and asks a pointed
question: ``Why can't some of that go back to the
student-athletes?'' . . . Bad week for the Rush brothers. Earlier
in the week, Jaron Rush of UCLA was suspended for possible NCAA
violations, and then, at Missouri, his brother Kareem was declared
ineligible for a possible NCAA violation . . . Dayton has turned
some heads with its 8-0 start, the best for the Flyers in 34 years,
with five of the wins coming against 1999 NCAA tournament teams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material for this column was gathered through personal interviews
and from wire service and Internet reports.)
</P>
