<HEADLINE>
GILL BECOMES A HIT ON THE BLUE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Size does matter _ in preventing goals.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when that size comes in the form of 6-foot-7,
240-pound Bruins defenseman Hal Gill.
</P>
<P>
   And knowing that it's important to get better as the years go
on, the burly skater has added even more physical play to his game
in the last year or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to get better as the years go on,'' said Gill, in his
third year in the National Hockey League. ``You try to add
dimensions to your game, by adding different things, by playing
harder, by playing more aggressively, but the bottom line is you
have to be at your best not to give away any goals.''
</P>
<P>
   It is what the Bruins do best in coach Pat Burns's system.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Man uses his size effectively. It doesn't matter whether
he's putting a fierce hit on an opponent, or battling in a corner,
Gill likes to put his licks on the other team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to be big in the corners and get in the way a lot,
with some of the guys in this league trying to make little moves in
trying to catch you off your feet,'' Gill said. ``You've got to
keep a good center and get in the way as much as you can by using
your stick side, taking away the angle, and forcing them in the
corner.''
</P>
<P>
   With his added physicality, Gill tries to finish guys harder on
the glass. ``That comes with confidence. Once you realize who you
can hit, some guys you have to ride them out instead of taking them
hard to the glass. Some guys you can go up and be aggressive on
them. You've got to learn when to do it and when not to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Gill provides the big hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big hits are there when you can get it, but you don't want
to sacrifice your body position,'' Gill said. ``You don't want to
take yourself out of the play to make the big hit. The most
important thing is to eliminate the player from the play, and
that's what you try to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The big hits, however, aren't what Gill's size is all about.
``It's more with his reach and his strength along the boards and to
make it tough for people to go around him and with people getting
to the net,'' said Ray Bourque, Gill's defensive partner. ``Hal's
plenty strong and he's plenty big and he takes up a lot of room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest compliment Hal has going for him is when some top
guys in the league come in, they don't like going against him, they
don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill and Bourque have been paired for 2 1/2 years now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great; he knows what to do with the puck all the time,''
Gill said. ``They read on him a lot of times. There's so much
pressure on him, so I can make the play up or if I pass it over, he
always makes the right play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we work well together, we know who's going on the puck
and who's going to stay in front of the net. Whatever the situation
is. After 2 1/2 years together, you learn what to do and when to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to Gill's contributions offensively, he
chuckles. ``I'm not asked about my offense that much; it's not
really my job,'' he said. ``I try to help out when I can, but, for
the most part, my job is to play defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to score goals and get assists, but on a team,
you have goal scorers and you have role players and I consider
myself a role player,'' said Gill, who has 4 points (three goals)
in 31 games, with a goal and an assist against the Rangers Nov. 18
in a 5-3 Bruins win.
</P>
<P>
   Gill had 10 points (three goals) last season in 80 games, and he
contributed 6 points (two goals) in his first season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to move the puck up and get it in their end,'' he said.
``If I get a chance to take a shot, I try to use that as much as I
can, but otherwise, I try to keep it in their zone and get it up to
the forwards and let them do the work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
