<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REAL MEANING OF ACHIEVEMENT TEST FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something has to give on high-stakes tests. Demanding that
students pass rigorous standardized tests with substandard
educations is unfair, if not illegal. We also know that the answer
does not lie in a wholesale abandonment of tests. Too many children
cannot spell, count, or call upon enough common knowledge to thrive
in a surging economy and a civil society. Life is one long test.
Our children need to know how to pass it.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, 2003 is the year that students must pass the
MCAS tests in order to graduate from high school. Other states have
similar deadlines. There is nothing wrong with that. Most people,
even highly motivated ones, work better with deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   But the only people facing the deadline, the only ones who would
be burned at the stake of high stakes, are the students. It would
be different if the clock were also ticking and the straw were also
smoking at the feet of state and city officials.
</P>
<P>
   So arrogant state officials want standardized tests? Fine. They
want to block failing students from graduating? Fine. But first let
us see them work to attain the standard of quality education for
everyone. Let us see them held accountable if they fail the test of
providing equitable resources.
</P>
<P>
   Accountability for equalizing resources is so easy to measure it
should be a condition of employment. I suggest three such
conditions. And if governors and state education officials cannot
meet them by 2003, they should all resign.
</P>
<P>
   The three conditions are:
</P>
<P>
   --Quality teachers. Studies show huge disparities in teacher
quality. Nationally, 25 percent of math and science teachers did
not major or minor in those subjects. In low-income schools, the
percentage of such teachers soars to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The latest study, released this month by the Center for the
Future of Teaching and Learning, found that California public
schools finishing in the bottom 25 percent of third-grade reading
tests had five times more underqualified teachers than schools that
finished in the top 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The study said that schools with higher percentages of
underqualified teachers were ``dysfunctional. These schools are
simply unable to increase student performance without dramatic
support to help them improve.''
</P>
<P>
   --Course offerings. This has been documented dramatically in
Massachusetts. Latino and African-American 10th-graders are between
2 1/2 and three times more likely to be enrolled in lower-level
math than white students. White students were between two and 2 1/2
times more likely than African-American and Latino 10th-graders to
be enrolled in grade-level science.
</P>
<P>
   While the paucity of higher-level courses disproportionately
hits Latinos and African-Americans, huge amounts of white and Asian
students are also being failed by the state. Nearly half of white
students _ 46 percent _ and 42 percent of Asian students are not in
grade-level science. Less than half of white and Asian students are
in higher level math.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cohen, assistant secretary of elementary and secondary
education at the US Department of Education, which is concerned
that the MCAS may be discriminatory, said, ``It's not good testing
policy, not good school policy.''
</P>
<P>
   --Class size. We need some caution here. California, which is
undergoing a massive class-size reduction campaign but also has a
major shortage of quality teachers and poor distribution of them,
is finding that lower class sizes work only with quality teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that the quality is there, smaller classes seem to
result in better scores, particularly in reading. Minneapolis
reported this fall that smaller classes sizes led to a 45 percent
rise in passing rates in eighth-grade, basic-skills reading tests
and a 17 percent rise in passing rates for math. Minneapolis says
that 79.4 percent of students who were in small classes for seven
years passed the basic skills tests, compared with 53.5 percent of
students with only one to three years of small classes.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``The Black-White Test Score Gap,'' Harvard University
professor Ronald Ferguson wrote: ``It is probably correct that
having fewer pupils per class can improve learning outcomes and
reduce racial disparities. There is no consensus on how small
classes should be, but few experts who think that class size
matters would condone a pupil-to-teacher ratio much above 20.''
</P>
<P>
   There has not been a consensus or will to fix the schools, but
with a clock ticking and the straw smoking at their feet, state
officials might find a second wind. They want the kids in at the
bottom in Boston, Lawrence, Springfield, and Holyoke to measure up
to the cozy towns at the top, Harvard, Wellesley, Weston, and
Lexington? Fine. But first let them deliver quality from top to
bottom in teachers, courses, and smaller classes.
</P>
<P>
   If they do not do this by 2003, then the MCAS and other such
exams are a scandal. Tying children to the stake of high-stakes
tests without a fair chance to pass them is abandonment and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and educators who are guilty of such abuse should be
given two choices: either see their careers burned at the stake or
take the MCAS themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
