<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1967 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MILL-FIRE-SUIT-ART-BO     12-17 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILL-FIRE-SUIT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALDEN MILLS OWNER STUNG BY NEGLIGENCE CLAIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos with MILL-FIRE-SUIT are being sent to NYTNS
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE BUTTERFIELD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ In the years since a huge fire destroyed Malden
Mills, owner Aaron Feuerstein has faced hundreds of crises in his
drive to rebuild the famed New England textile company.
</P>
<P>
   But few have been as unexpected or potentially ugly as the one
he faces today: a charge in a claim filed last Friday by 13 of his
workers that the injuries they suffered in the 1995 fire were at
least partly caused by negligence at the mill.
</P>
<P>
   Mill officials, insisting they have long supported full
compensation for the workers, call the negligence charge baseless
and see it as little more than legal maneuvering. But it has
clearly stunned Feuerstein, who has made fairness to workers a
cornerstone of his efforts at the mill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just shocked out of my wits,'' Feuerstein said during an
interview this week. ``I feel dreadful. Our hearts have gone out to
these victims. How could they do this? They're like members of my
own family.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, at least some of the 13 _ four of whom have returned to
the mill to help Feuerstein rebuild _ appear equally conflicted.
``I really like Aaron,'' one of them agreed Thursday, asking not to
be identified. ``I respect what he has done. He's done a noble
thing. I feel very bad he's going through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Feuerstein, 74, has drawn national attention for his liberal
worker policies. He paid all 3,000 of his employees full salaries
for months after the fire, and refused to rebuild in labor-cheap
regions in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the injured workers were seen as partners with
Feuerstein in lawsuits both had filed against companies that
supplied the mill with products linked to the cause of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   All of that changed last Friday, when the workers reached a
separate settlement with those companies for a reported $18
million. Hours later _ and with time running out on any further
action _ the 13 workers filed a new workers' compensation claim
charging Malden Mills itself with ``reckless conduct,'' and with
knowingly allowing dangerous conditions to exist in the mill's
so-called flock division, which is no longer in operation.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the workers said they had to file the claim,
including the charge of negligence, with the state Department of
Industrial Accidents by midnight last Friday or face losing the
right to seek additional compensation altogether because a
four-year statute of limitations was expiring. The fire occurred on
Dec. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers expect a quick settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Mill officials, who said they did not learn of the workers'
claim until this week, were caught by surprise. ``I know Aaron is
totally pro these injured workers,'' said Jeff Bowman, one of the
mill's executives.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman said the mill has spent $3 million beyond what was
provided by normal state compensation to ensure that all medical
and related bills were paid, and he indicated the mill was prepared
to do more.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the company will fight any special claim of
negligence, insisting that the claim had ``no basis in reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Autieri, the lawyer for eight of the 13 workers, said
the claim was filed only after efforts to reach a settlement on
further payments had failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have a very strong case,'' Autieri said.
</P>
<P>
   If workers win the claim _ which will be heard administratively
by the industrial accidents department _ they will be entitled to
double workers' compensation payments. They must not only show that
Malden Mills was negligent in its operation of the flocking
operation where the fire occurred, but also that the mill operated
with reckless disregard for the safety of its employees.
</P>
<P>
   No other state or federal agency has made a similar finding.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration _ the
principal agency charged with investigating labor conditions at the
time of the fire _ concluded that Malden Mills did not violate
safety and health standards. In a later report, the state fire
marshal's office was more critical of the mill, but did not blame
it for the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Both agencies found that the ``most probable'' cause of the fire
was the explosion of dust-like nylon fibers created in the making
of flock upholstry. The nylon fibers _ supplied by other companies
_ were not supposed to pose a flash-fire threat.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 workers were working on two textile lines in the mill's
former Monomac Building when the fibers ignited, gravely injuring
eight of them. Some still face years of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the fire, the flock upholstery operation was the
most difficult, and clearly the most hazardous, of the mill. In the
year following the fire, Feuerstein spent nearly $50 million trying
to rebuild the operation as a clean and modern one. He eventually
abandoned the effort to concentrate on expanding the mill's
signature business, Polartec manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the nearly $500 million mill complex on the
Lawrence-Metheun line is recognized as one of the safest and most
technologically advanced textile manufacturing facilities in the
country. It was also recently honored by the US Energy Department
as the most energy efficient.
</P>
<P>
   But if the road back for the mill has been long and, at times
rocky, it has been even more difficult for the 13 workers,
according to their lawyer, Autieri.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is suggesting that Aaron Feuerstein didn't do all that
he did after the fire,'' Autieri said. The new claim, he insists,
deals only with the mill at the time of the fire, and the injuries
suffered by the workers. Seven of the 13 workers are permanently
disabled, he said, with some still undergoing skin grafts and other
procedures to reduce scarring.
</P>
<P>
   Mill officials insist they remain sympathetic and support the
injured workers receiving all the help and care they require. For
years after the fire, Feuerstein's daughter, Joyce, was charged
with personally working with the victims and their families.
Charging the mill with reckless disregard for the workers' health,
they add, is both untrue and unfair.
</P>
<P>
   To Feuerstein, it is more than unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I like. I hate it,'' he said of the
negligence claim. ``The reason I hate it is that Malden Mills
stands for being sensitive to the human equation and having
compassion. And if we're guilty of willful or neglectful action _
or anything of that nature _ then everything I have tried to
represent for a lifetime is in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horrible thing,'' he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
