<HEADLINE>
CONFERENCE REUNITES WOMEN SEEKING PEACE IN WAR-TORN REGIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mary Montague helped stanch the wounds of her fellow
Catholics gunned down in the streets of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   Sumaya Naser walked in front of Israeli soldiers firing rubber
bullets at rock-throwing Palestinians to protect children caught in
the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Emilia Salamanca helped stage anti-violence protests in
Colombia, despite the near anarchy there that often leaves the
outspoken in unmarked graves.
</P>
<P>
   The three women came to Boston this week to confer with more
than 100 other women from similarly embattled countries spanning
five continents.
</P>
<P>
   Women struggling to stop the bloodshed in war-torn territories
such as Kashmir, Nagorno-Karabakh, and Cyprus came to compare
strategies on halting violence, rebuilding ravaged societies and to
organize a common front against the mainly male-led conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   They also came to voice their views to officials in the Clinton
administration, the European Union and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many women don't have political power,'' said Swanee Hunt,
director of the Women and Public Policy Program at Harvard's John
F. Kennedy School of Government, who organized this week's
conference called ``Women Waging Peace.'' ``What we're doing is
trying to figure out where the rich resource of women can have some
leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   While most women throughout the world lack the political pull to
change their governments' policies, many have acted when confronted
by tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers in Argentina marched against the country's military
junta to protest the disappearance of their sons during the
so-called ``dirty war'' in the late 1970s. Russian women earlier
this decade risked being killed by their own nation's bombs to find
their sons and pull them from the fighting in Chechnya. Serbian
women likewise helped end NATO's onslaught against Yugoslavia by
demanding their sons return from marauding in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the women at this week's conference has a story to tell
about rising up against authority.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Montague worked as a nurse for eight years, riding
ambulances and delivering dying youths to morgues during the peak
of Northern Ireland's bitter conflict. She spent many years
protesting British rule there. Now, she's a community worker in
Belfast and is considering a run for Northern Ireland's new
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter much what someone's religion or nationality
is, we all bleed and feel pain in the same way,'' she said.
``What's important is that we work together to stop the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Lerman and Marta Eugenia Segura were chatting about the
conflicts in their countries over dinner one night during the past
week.
</P>
<P>
   Lerman, an Israeli peace activist, and Eugenia Segura, a
consultant to development organizations in Colombia, decided they
would work together to stop any Israeli arms sales to any of the
various combatants in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our connection is a good example of how you build coalitions
across countries,'' Lerman said. ``I told her, `Whenever you hear
about the presence of Israelis, let me know. We will publicize this
and we can protest it.' Whenever they have any kind of information,
we will try to start a big campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 109 women return to their corners of the globe this
weekend, Harvard plans to stay in touch. The Kennedy school has set
up a Web site where the women will be able to post ideas and
consult professors.
</P>
<P>
   Later on, there will be additional conferences and Swanee, a
former US ambassador to Austria, said she expects the women to
draft a platform and pressure governments around the world to
improve their human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the women are trying to lay the foundation of
what could be a broad international women's movement, Swanee said.
They hope their efforts will reverse a deadly trend that has left
noncombatants, mainly women, children and the elderly, increasingly
the victims of the world's bloody conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   That may be possible, they say, if women gain more influence and
are elected to positions where they can effect change. Until then,
however, the women said they will organize and speak out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call to your attention the role of women, not just as
victims and survivors, bus as pioneers and leaders of peace
initiatives,'' a statement concluding the conference says. ``They
are seeds of hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
