<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUG &AMP; SUN CAN'T REPEL SUN-BUG SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mitchell Swartz has three more university degrees than most
people. He has a master's and doctorate from MIT in electrical
engineering and an MD from Harvard Medical School. But that doesn't
mean he's smart.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, according to a lawsuit he has filed in federal court
here, Swartz made a very silly mistake. He and three business
partners turned over their research for a so-called ``dual
protection,'' combination sunblock and bug repellent to the
pharmaceutical company Plough Inc., because one of their mothers
was a close friend of founder Abraham Plough. Swartz's colleague
Robert Berlin has testified that he discussed the product, called
Sun-Bug, with Plough executives on numerous occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to 1997, when, Berlin recounts, ``we were
astonished to find that the exact same product was on the shelf at
our local pharmacy.'' In fact, without informing anyone on Swartz's
team, Schering-Plough had launched a dual-protection sunscreen cum
bug repellent called . . . Bug &AMP; Sun. Great minds think alike!
</P>
<P>
   Swartz, who is acting as his own lawyer, filed a broad, 12-count
complaint against Schering-Plough this spring. It is quite
amateurish, alleging RICO (Racketeering Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations) violations and civil rights claims against the New
Jersey-based health care giant. For ``breech of contract'' (sic),
Swartz asks for $13 million in damages; for gross negligence and
willful misconduct, $367 million.
</P>
<P>
   Laughable? Well, Schering-Plough isn't laughing. When it moved
to dismiss the case this summer, Judge William Young upheld
Swartz's breach of contract claim. Plough promptly switched law
firms, dropping Fitzhugh &AMP; Associates and hiring Bingham Dana LLP,
which had the consequent effect of dumping Judge Young. As a former
Bingham partner, he recused himself, and the case has been assigned
to Judge Nancy Gertner. (Bingham Dana also represents the Globe.)
In one filing, Swartz accuses Plough of ``judge-shopping,'' and
notes that he has so far had to square off against five different
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Bingham Dana's chief litigation partner, John Curtin, wishes he
had an effective Swartz repellent to rid himself of this litigious
gnat. ``Mr. Swartz is very bright, and he can spin a lot of tales,
and that's what this suit is about,'' Curtin says. ``We have all
this history in our files, and we haven't found any record'' of
Swartz's Sun-Bug research.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time to go
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Stone, president of the Federation of American
Scientists, will be leaving his post June 30. ``He maintains it's
because of age,'' says a fellow FAS member; Stone will turn 65 next
year. But the word is that Stone is actually leaving because of
negative fallout from l'affaire Morrison _ Stone's very public
accusation that his mentor and FAS colleague, Philip Morrison of
MIT, spied for the Russians during the Cold War. Princeton
physicist Frank von Himmel commented that ``it would be surprising
if this distressing episode did not play a role in firming up
Stone's decision to step down.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone, who has defended his father, the crusading journalist I.
F. Stone against accusations that he was a KGB Cold War
``contact,'' fingered Morrison in a book and subsequent newspaper
article last spring. Morrison denied the charges, and the FAS
issued a statement ``fully crediting'' Morrison's denials. In an
interview, Stone declined to talk about Morrison. He said he was
``ecstatic'' about his life change. He is leaving to head up an
organization devoted to public diplomacy, called Catalytic
Diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   The FAS was orginally the Association of Los Alamos Scientists
(ALAS), a group mainly comprised of physicists worried about the
destructive potential of the atomic arms race. The FAS may reorient
its interests away from arms control, judging by the short list of
candidates for Stone's job. Only one _ Bruce Blair of the Brookings
Institution _ has the conventional FAS background. The other two
candidates, the Department of Energy's Allan Hoffman, and Henry
Kelly, currently on the White House staff, both have expertise in
global energy issues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
