<HEADER>
A1975 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BROTHERS-REUNITE-BOS &LR;      12-17 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROTHERS-REUNITE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEWS PHOTO TOUCHES A FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ To newspaper readers, it was a touching Associated
Press photograph of a homeless man, wrapped in a blanket and
shaking hands with Mayor Thomas M. Menino. But for one Uxbridge
man, it was the key that led to a reunion with his missing brother.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, Brian Goodwin, 52, received a call from
his sister-in-law asking him to check out a photograph in the
Telegram &AMP; Gazette of Worcester. The man in the picture was his
long-lost brother, Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no mistake _ the name, the age, the face,'' said Brian
Goodwin during a telephone interview Thursday. ``We all kind of
chuckled and said, `Damn.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his mother's death in 1986, Scott Goodwin, 49,
left the family's Ashland home and never returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Thanksgiving we would say, `Oh, Scott is going to call,
and we will pick him up in Framingham,' but the call never came,''
Brian said.
</P>
<P>
   As the years passed, the family assumed that their brother, the
second oldest of five children, had either moved to California to
pursue his dream of becoming a drummer or died on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   It was at about 11 p.m. Monday when AP photographer Elise
Amendola and a reporter spotted Scott outside a doughnut shop. They
were assigned to follow the mayor during the city's annual homeless
census.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Scott) was the first or second person we ecountered in the
storefront alley in Downtown Crossing,'' Amendola said. ``He was
under his blanket reading a book. All of his stuff was piled around
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor asked Scott, who was reading a book of science
fiction, if he wanted shelter, but he refused, saying shelters were
unsafe, recalled Amendola.
</P>
<P>
   Scott would be the focus of a subsequent AP article on
homelessness, but Amendola never expected to hear from him again.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, AP reporter Robin Estrin answered a phone call
from Brian Goodwin, who wanted to know where the photograph of his
brother was taken, so he could locate him.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Estrin and Amendola led Brian to the Washington
Street area where his brother was sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   Scott wasn't there, but Amendola recalled that the homeless man
sold newspapers for The Boston Globe. As they moved toward Boston
Common, Brian asked a man wearing a Globe jacket if he knew his
brother; the man directed the three to Scott's newsstand at North
Station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got a newspaper for your brother?'' asked Brian after spotting
his younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott looked blank. It has been 12 years,'' said Amendola.
``Brian takes off his baseball cap and says, `It's your brother,'
and slowly he recognizes him and stands up and they hug.''
</P>
<P>
   In a few minutes, the two men try to catch up with all the
missing years: Scott said he'd been meaning to call, but somehow
life got in the way. The family scholar, Scott dropped out of the
University of Massachustts at Amherst, used drugs, and moved to a
commune in Cambridge, according to the AP.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Scott lost his apartment and has been homeless ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on the National Honor Society in Ashland High School,''
recalled Brian. ``He was always real studious. We thought, `He's
got it made, always able to breeze through everthing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Scott fulfilled his dream of moving from Ashland to
Boston. He worked odd jobs and returned home for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never tried to lecture him, but just let him be himself,''
Brian said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Scott returned to the family's Ashland home but left
after an argument with his father. Months grew into years of
absence.
</P>
<P>
   Brian told his younger brother that their father died in April.
Scott said he had stopped using drugs years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the reunion, the two brothers looked at several
rooming houses in the Beacon Hill area. ``He won't go into a
shelter. He said it's more dangerous than on the streets '' said
Brian, who is married with three adult children. He offered his
brother a place in his home, but Scott refused, explaining that he
had a job to do.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Brian bought his brother dinner and gave him money.
They expect to unite with another sibling Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not expecting him to work at Microsoft,'' Brian said. ``If
he wants to sell Globes until he is 80 years old, that's fine with
me _ as along as he is happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
