<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINFUL QUESTIONS IN WORCESTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Worcester firefighters pay a final salute to their six fallen
comrades, one chapter of this hellish tragedy draws to a painful
close. There are more to come.
</P>
<P>
   The personal pain of family and friends will, of course,
continue without end. But one piece of the tragedy that will run a
very specific course is the criminal case against Thomas Levesque,
37, and Julie Barnes, 19. They allegedly knocked over a candle
during an argument inside the Worcester Cold Storage &AMP; Warehouse
Co. building and left without reporting the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Does it diminish the self-sacrifice and heroism of the dead
firefighters to question the involuntary manslaughter charges
brought against Levesque and Barnes? I don't think so, but others
may. I will ask it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Globe published a photograph of Linda McGuirk,
the widow of Worcester firefighter Joseph T. McGuirk, with her
young children, Emily and Everett. Their faces break your heart.
Beneath their glazed, solemn gazes was a photograph of Barnes.
Waiflike in baggy jeans and chains around her ankles, she also
looked numb, obviously for different reasons: She is 19, three
months pregnant, and, according to a court psychologist, competent
to stand trial on six counts of involuntary manslaughter in
connection with the Dec. 3 fire.
</P>
<P>
   According to a story published in the Worcester Telegram &AMP;
Gazette, Barnes had the troubled childhood you would expect from
such a lost-looking soul. She and a sister spent their early
childhood with their mother, but by 1985 the state Department of
Social Services stepped in after reports of sexual abuse and
neglect. She had no friends and would wait on the back steps for a
next-door neighbor to get home from work. For a time she lived with
her father, a Worcester cabdriver, in a bedroom decorated with
Barbie dolls. Described as slow, she never graduated from high
school.
</P>
<P>
   She left home at 18 and ended up in a relationship with
Levesque, who had previously dated her aunt. Levesque, who has a
record of violent assaults on women, is still undergoing
psychiatric evaluation at Bridgewater State Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A troubled life does not give anyone license to commit a crime.
Still, the heartbreak of six deaths and 17 fatherless children does
not necessarily add up to a manslaughter conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes and Levesque apparently started a fire but did not intend
to kill anyone. The legal question turns on whether they engaged in
reckless conduct that a reasonable person might conclude could lead
to the death of another person. Not surprisingly, the nuances are
subject to legal argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to say they should be responsible for the fire.
But to charge them with responsibility for the deaths? It's a
little bit much,'' says defense lawyer Harvey Silverglate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some prosecutors believe they have a duty and a right to
charge the most serious offense the facts will bear. However,
responsible prosecutors have the view that they have a professional
obligation to charge the highest, most serious offense that 12 out
of 12 jurors would convict on.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer R. Robert Popeo says manslaughter charges are
technically correct but might not have been brought if prosecutors
had ``the luxury of time to be able to look at it with detached
reflection.'' Adds Popeo: ``What we see now are two homeless people
who knocked over a candle, couldn't put it out, and took off. If
that's all there was, it's a very hard case of involuntary
manslaughter.''
</P>
<P>
   But Popeo stresses that other factors, as they become known,
begin to weigh in: How much did Barnes and Levesque know about the
extent of the fire when they left the warehouse? How foreseeable
was it for them to think people would be killed in what they knew
to be an abandoned building? Is the ``reasonable man'' standard
really applicable in this case, given the intellectual capabilities
of the defendants?
</P>
<P>
   There are painful questions for other people as well.
</P>
<P>
   City officials knew that homeless people stayed in the building.
Why did they allow the practice to continue for so long? What is
the responsibility of the building's owner? The vacant 82-year-old
warehouse lacked fireproofing, automatic sprinklers, and fire and
smoke alarms, according to the Telegram &AMP; Gazette. It was awaiting
renovation into a biomedical park. In the interim, it was a
firetrap and, ultimately, a death trap.
</P>
<P>
   The questions haunt, as do all the faces from Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
