<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BICENTENNIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MALE FANTASTY WITH ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
BICENTENNIAL MAN 
Directed by: Chris Columbus 
Screenplay by: Nicholas Kazan (based on Isaac Asimov's short story
and Asimov's and Robert Silverberg's novel, ``The Positronic
Man'') 
Starring: Robin Williams, Sam Neill, Embeth Davidtz, Oliver Platt,
Wendy Crewson, Hallie Kate Eisenberg, Stephen Root, Lynne Thigpen,
Bradley Whitford, Kiersten Warren 
Running time: 132 minutes 
Rated: PG (language and some sexual content) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bicentennial Man'' is the kind of movie that makes you wish
Robin Williams would say enough with the touchy-feely stuff
already. Still, it seems only fair to add that the fans who liked
him in ``Mrs. Doubtfire'' and ``Patch Adams'' will like him, here,
too, as a sensitive robot. At least if it plays pretty shamelessly
to the sensitive and sentimental side of his persona, it's also
darker than the cute robotic kids' movie it at first may seem.
Basically, Williams plays a robot with soul. Brains, too, and not
for a moment is ``Bicentannial Man'' out of touch with a long line
of beauty-and-the-beast movies in which somebody outside the human
race teaches a human being, usually a pretty girl, what humanity is
all about.
</P>
<P>
   Does this sound a tad cynical? If so, it's because Williams'
robot winds up falling in love with the granddaughter of the little
girl whose family originally bought him, thinking they were
purchasing little more than a glorified household appliance. But
not this robot. Beneath his plastic and metal exterior, he's not
just smart, but full of feeling, and the feelings only get deeper.
His feelings for a member of the third generation of the family
he's connected to seem a little uncomfortably akin to an old man's
Viagra fantasy, but Williams' persona _ and the way the story is
set up _ make it all palatable, if only just.
</P>
<P>
   Right off, the robot named Andrew announces holographically that
he's been programmed never to harm any human. Many, many years and
a few reprogrammings later, when he's looking into the eyes of a
woman who's the better part of a century younger with a wish to do
more than just serve her, this ground rule yanks the scene back
from any sort of
King-Kong-clutching-Fay-Wray-atop-the-Empire-State-Building danger.
Still, while we're used to older male stars getting much younger
female stars, this is a bit of a stretch. What helps is that Andrew
has really worked his way up the scale of demands very slowly and
very reasonably. It starts with him getting his own bank account
when he puts his skills to work and makes money manufacturing
exquisitely crafted clocks.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, he's gotta be free, and, hey, this is America,
right? When he does get his freedom, Andrew the robot never gets
manic and clangs his heels together. He even looks a little sad
about it, and assures his ``family'' that he'll always be close by.
Here the film veers into some rich irony. Because Andrew is made of
high-grade alloys, he's virtually ageless, given regular
servicings. But because he's an American man who acquires some
disposable income, he puts it into approving his appearance,
draping enough artificial skin and hair over his steely exoskeleton
to make him look like Robin Williams. And not just any Robin
Williams, but Robin Williams just back from a health spa.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ``Bicentannial Man'' puts a very agreeable and even
disarming face on its understandable but not so lovely male
fantasy. Few actors apart from Williams could bring it off. Of
course, part of the reason he's able to is that the robot is
expressionless, which means Williams is able to underplay a lot. So
what he wants never seems assaultive. This encourages us to
sympathize with his essential isolation, even if the film is a
little remiss in pointing out that loneliness is often the price of
freedom. Still, I found it very tempting to just go along with the
prettiness and the mellowspeak that are the medium of exchange in
``Bicentennial Man.'' Williams makes us feel there's enough good
will behind it to really preclude anyone hating it. Still, I wish
the film had found the courage to really grapple with the
conundrums accompanying the advent of artificial intelligence and
not just play them out on the level of how the sweet, brilliant
dork is going to get the girl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
