u e BC-MOVIE-ANNA-BOS &LR;      12-17 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ANNA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RICH, ROYAL `ANNA AND THE KING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ANNA AND THE KING 
Directed by: Andy Tennant 
Screenplay by: Steve Meerson &AMP; Peter Krikes (based on Anna
Leonowens' diaries) 
Starring: Jodie Foster, Chow Yun-Fat, Bai Ling, Tom Felton, Syed
Alwi, Randall Duk Kim, Keith Chin 
Running time: 160 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (some intense violent sequences) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Anna and the King'' is a lot more than ``The King and I''
minus Rodgers' and Hammerstein's music. It's a broader, wider,
deeper, fuller canvas. A big, handsome throwback to star-powered
historical costume movies, it relies on the charisma of Jodie
Foster and Chow Yun-Fat and a screenful of spectacular production
values to carry it past its inevitable political incorrectness.
While there's more than a little sensitivity training between the
new ``Anna and the King'' and the macho ``King and I'' of Yul
Brunner, both proceed from the same source, the diaries of Anna
Leonowens, a British schoolteacher who journeyed from India to what
was then called Siam and taught the 70-odd children and several
concubines of Siam's King Mongkut in the 1860s.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the film retains an Anglo-centric point of view that
contributed to its being deemed unwelcome in Thailand (filming took
place in Malaysia). That the real Anna Leonowens was a remarkable
woman is beyond dispute. That the proud king was willing to take
many a cue from her (except in public) remains debatable. And only
in Hollywood, not Siam, could she all but save the Siamese royal
family. But she almost certainly reinforced the progressive outlook
that led to the king having sent for her. He realized he would have
to bring his country into the modern world, propgate scientific and
linguistic studies, and thread his way carefully through the
diplomatic waters if he was to avoid being colonized.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just star power that the two leads bring to the table.
Not since Holly Hunter in ``The Piano'' have we seen so
strong-willed a Victorian woman on a movie screen as Foster is.
Foster is never going to do unintelligent work. Here she generates
sympathy by letting us see Anna's brave bluffing when she stands up
to the king and demands to be treated with respect (of course, this
being a romantic fantasy, he respects her). We also believe in the
feelings she and the king develop for one another. Their imapct is
all the greater for the restraint each must show, given their more
than slightly melancholy mutual acknowledment that their feelings
must be kept under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   Anna, as it happens, keeps her feelings rather too completely
under wraps. She's at least partly in denial about her husband's
death. And her high-mindedness sometimes comes off as mere
high-handedness. Although she's a liberalizing force, and rightly
maintains her position with unfaltering rectitude, she's also, one
feels, a bit narrow in her perspective, not as open to newness as
the king. He's a lot more receptive to Western thought than she is
to Asian viewpoints, which she almost automatically regards as
benighted, a view not entirely free of colonial arrogance. What she
does contribute in abundance, though, is character. She's not just
headstrong. She's strong, period, even if her liberal ideas could
just as readily be applied to Victorian England as to Siam.
</P>
<P>
   If she were any less powerful, in fact, the film would be stolen
away by Chow. What he contributes in prodigious amounts is warmth
and vision and shrewdness. He's too intelligent to indulge in macho
posturing. In fact, he's admirable in his realistic awareness of
how fragile his rule really is, and how possible it would be to
find himself overthrown. We can believe he spent part of his youth
in a Buddhist monastery. His eyes convey more feeling than his
position permits him to say. Even when turns Anna down for
political or other reasons, his eyes tell us he wishes he could
find a way to do what she asks. The one thing he doesn't have to
take lessons from Anna in is dignity. In short, Chow does a superb
job of convincing us that he's a wise king as well as a good one,
and more sophisticated than Anna in the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the smartest decision made by director Andy Tennant was
to not twist the film out of shape by trying to avoid being
old-fashioned. ``Anna and the King'' is nothing but old-fashioned,
but it's old-fashioned in a glorious way. The Malaysian locales
serve splendidly for Siam, with its emphasis on gold and pointy
decor. The other performances are fine, too, especially those of
Bai Ling as the beleaguered Tuptim, resisting her fate as a
concubine, and 12-year-old Keith Chin, as the number one prince
whose searching eyes carry forward his father's faraway look. The
film also avoids stereotypes of Asian exoticism based on a
patronizing view of it as a toy culture. Still, it's eye-filling
when it has to be. ``Anna and the King'' is as enlightned and as
appealing a telling of this tale as we're likely to get.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1422EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1985 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-DEAD-BOS &LR;      12-17 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DEAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ROADS' RECAPTURES DEAD'S LIVE SOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the end of the Grateful Dead in 1995, one fact has become
abundantly clear: It's not easy to be a good jam band. While
Phish's improvisation has a buoyant elasticity, and some of the
Dead offshoot bands _ particularly the various incarnations of Phil
&AMP; Friends _ have risen well above the nostalgia factory, none of
the keepers of the flame have a fire that burns quite as brightly
as the Dead's, at its hottest moments. The rock 'n' roll
conversation of Jerry Garcia, Phil Lesh, Bob Weir, and Bill
Kreutzmann is one of those inventions that started off as an
accident but ended up as something inevitable, unique, and quite
impossible to imitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Many Roads (1965-1995),'' a new five-CD boxed set, is an
ambitiously edited attempt to chronicle the growth of this
ever-changing musical conversation. It's the sort of project _ an
aural biography of jamming _ that could only be done on the
Grateful Dead, and it comes closer to capturing the band than any
of the ``greatest'' Dead collections like ``What a Long Strange
Trip It's Been.'' It's a rough-hewn but carefully thought out
collage, mostly comprised of concert recordings reaching from the
short-lived ``You Don't Have to Ask'' at the Fillmore in 1966 to
the elegiac ``So Many Roads'' at the Dead's final concert in 1995.
These live selections _ some of them snippets of longer pieces _
are interspersed with unreleased studio material, notably
early-1990s songs like ``Eternity'' and ``Days Between'' that had
yet to be included on an album when Garcia died.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pre-1980 live cuts are extraordinary, if not
definitive. Each one bookmarks a different stage in the band's
early musical development, from the full-frontal acid playing of
the late 1960s to the cosmic space journeying of the early 1970s.
On ``The Same Thing'' jamming from 1967, you can hear Garcia segue
from traditional blues riffs into the fiercely modern enterprise
that he will later perfect. Surprisingly, the Dead's most famous
jam vehicle, ``Dark Star,'' is represented by a speedy 1968 version
that only hints at the open-ended exploration the song will later
inspire. But it flows into an interestingly primitive ``China Cat
Sunflower'' and then into a scorching ``Eleven'' that fairly drips
with the night's energy. The ``Watkins Glen Soundcheck Jam'' from
1973 reveals a band that has fully fleshed out its own jazz-rock
sound, with a final third that is so uplifting it should be named
``Happy Jam.'' And one of the boxed set's peaks is a 1974
improvisation that plows through ``Spanish Jam'' and into ``U.S.
Blues'' on the ballast of Phil Lesh's ferocious bass lines. It's
the Dead in fifth gear, in the last months of its most inspired
era.
</P>
<P>
   Like the band, the boxed set loses some of its magic as it
reaches into the 1980s. Or at least, the magic changes, with a
shift in keyboardists, with the 1977 return of second drummer
Mickey Hart (who had left in 1971), with the unwieldy expansion of
the Dead's audience, and with the very beginnings of the malaise
that would haunt Garcia until his death. Gone are the ragtime riffs
and bright tinklings of Keith Godchaux, replaced by the synthetic
arena-rock intonations of Brent Mydland. An ``Estimated Prophet''
from 1979 gives us Mydland at his best, as his solos build
seamlessly into some classic Garcia, but the inclusion of a pair of
Mydland-sung tunes from the 1980s is unfortunate. So is an
unremarkable ``Scarlet Begonias _ Fire on the Mountain'' from 1990,
included to feature Garcia toying with MIDI technology. The
strongest jams from the Mydland era are an eerie, self-enclosed
``Playing in the Band'' and a gorgeously twisted ``Bird Song'' that
has the Dead diving headlong into fusion madness with Branford
Marsalis.
</P>
<P>
   The boxed set's most poignant moments are on its 1990s disc,
which could double as the Dead's final album of new material. As
music, these pieces aren't amazing; as Dead history, they are
essential. The most engaging latter-day song is ``Liberty,'' which
is well represented with a live version from 1994. And a
fascinating fly-on-the-wall rehearsal cut has Garcia drawing his
bandmates into an impromptu version of the Irish folk tune
``Whiskey in the Jar.'' The disc and the entire set ends with
Garcia singing his ailing heart out on his last-ever ``So Many
Roads,'' a song that calls to mind Dylan's ``Knockin' on Heaven's
Door.'' A month later, he was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Many Roads (1965-1995)'' summarizes three decades of Dead
as much as any five-disc set possibly can. Yes, it's too bad the
producers fade in and out of jams, a technique that Deadheads
continue to debate on the Internet. But it was an unhappy necessity
when faced with a band whose most intensely synchronized moments
were often in the middle of aimless noodling, or worse. With
cutting and pasting, we are able to hear small, telling gems that
might have fallen into the void, like the piercing ``Beautiful
Jam'' from 1971, or Garcia's fluttering 1990 foray with Bruce
Hornsby, ``Jam Out of Foolish Heart.'' And anyway, the truest
portrait of Dead music is coming out bit by bit, with the archival
releases known as ``Dick's Picks'' (of which there are 15 so far).
They are where the spaciest and spookiest and most sparkling
versions of ``Dark Star'' can live and breathe, and that's where
Deadheads can continue to mine for the gold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1424EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1986 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-CIDER-BOS &LR;      12-17 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CIDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DENSE, RICH `CIDER HOUSE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE CIDER HOUSE RULES 
Directed by: Lasse Hallstrom 
Screenplay by: John Irving, based on his novel 
Starring: Tobey Maguire, Charlize Theron, Delroy Lindo, Paul Rudd,
Michael Caine, Jane Alexander, Kathy Baker, Kieran Culkin, Kate
Nelligan, Heavy D, K. Todd Friedman, Paz de la Huerta, Erykah Badu 
Running time: 131 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (mature thematic elements, sexuality, nudity,
substance abuse and some violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rules'' is the best film to date of a John
Irving novel. The author, who does not lightly bestow his
imprimatur, would have only himself to blame if it weren't. He
wrote its screenplay. As he himself says, he could telescope it
with a license unavailable to other writers. Irving clinches it by
appearing at the start and finish of the film as the stationmaster
of a Maine town. Although he has no lines, he emits the vibe of a
man who enjoys the opportunity he has afforded himself to scowl
disapprovingly, secure in the knowledge that his frowns are likely
to be the only ones that coalesce around ``The Cider House Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all of Irving's tales, this one, which unfolds in the
1940s, is densely packed, and it confronts some bleak New England
realities. At its heart is the surrogate son-surrogate father
relationship between Tobey Maguire's orphan named Homer and Michael
Caine's kindly orphanage doctor. He takes the boy under his wing
and turns him into a junior colleague who helps care for his fellow
orphans and abandoned babies. The orphanage scenes were shot at the
Northampton State Hospital and at Ventfort, one of those
millionaire's houses in the Berkshires, referred to in a piquant
piece of reverse ostentation as cottages.
</P>
<P>
   The very architecture, and the spaces in it, add to the vibe of
a film that asks, among other things, what is to be done with
unwanted children, especially the ones who aren't so fortunate as
to live under the loving care of the caring staff run by the caring
doc, who bolsters their little egos by addressing them at bedtime
as princes of New England, without the smallest speck of irony. The
closest to controversy the film comes is in the doc's emphatic
pro-choice beliefs. He performs illegal abortions on the grounds
that many of the pregnant women who come to him would die at the
hands of backstreet abortionists in a time when abortion is a
criminal offense.
</P>
<P>
   Homer, protege though he may be, disagrees with the
large-hearted doc's abortion policy on philosophical grounds and
won't assist in the operations. Otherwise, we're convinced the bond
between them is deep and loving. This is due to the exceptional
performances of Maguire and Caine, and the ability of Swedish
director Lasse Hallstrom to infuse with gentleness and lyricism the
harshest of environments. At first, it's a little disconcerting to
hear Caine speak in an American accent, but it isn't long before he
drapes the doc's profound compassion over us and enchants us with
his matter-of-fact saintliness.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire has made the transition from teen roles to young-man
roles without missing a beat. Unlike many actors, he's not afraid
of quiet, and he's not afraid to hold back. This comes at no cost
to our belief in his sensitivity, and, in this case, essential
goodness. His open face tells us, as Homer moves out into the
world, that while there's a lot he doesn't know, he wants to know
it, and that even though he treads softly, he's an eager pupil. In
short, Homer is a blank page but hardly a blank person when he
disappoints the doc by not immediately slipping into a role as the
doc's successor. Instead, he goes off to see the world when he's
offered a lift by a GI who had brought his girlfriend to the doc
for an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Homer isn't taken that far down the road in miles (by the most
remarkable of coincidences Maguire plays another young man taking a
different kind of journey in the Civil War drama, ``Ride With the
Devil,'' also opening Friday). Nevertheless, he winds up a world
away from the orphanage. He's given a job on the apple farm
belonging to the departing GI's mother and yes, Homer does indeed
eat from the tree of knowledge, if you were wondering about the
symbolism. Homer, in fact, learns more than he counted on. Some of
it he learns from Southern migrant workers headed by a proud Delroy
Lindo, who has a grown daughter played by Erykah Badu, in a strong
debut. The title comes from a list of dos and don'ts nailed on a
wall of the workers' bunkhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Rules, of course, are one of the things Homer has to figure out,
including which are to be broken and which are not, and what's to
be done if they are. Complicating matters is that Homer has eyes
for his benefactor's girlfriend, a lobsterman's daughter played by
Charlize Theron with a disarming down-to-earth quality to go with
her sexiness. Homer's grappling with moral choices is classic
coming-of-age stuff, and the film handles it beautifully. ``The
Cider House Rules'' is Hallstrom in his ``My Life As a Dog'' and
``What's Eating Gilbert Grape?'' mode. Given a choice between
overplaying and underplaying, it always underplays, which is part
of its charm. Certainly, it's filled with vivid characters and
action. Beneath its modesty of gesture, it's one of the year's
richest, most humane films.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1425EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
