<HEADER>
A1987 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-BOX-BOS &LR;      12-17 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINKING INSIDE THE BOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new standard for boxed sets was notched up by Bruce
Springsteen, whose four-CD ``Tracks'' redefined the genre last
year. His box contained all previously unreleased songs or
alternate takes _ many of which had fans salivating. This year's
boxed crop is less enticing and less adventurous, though not
without a few hearty recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best new releases come from outside the rock 'n'
roll field _ notably, boxes by Stevie Wonder and Sammy Davis Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, it's a mixed bag, weighted down by the hit-and-miss
quality of new sets by the Doobie Brothers, Linda Ronstadt, and
Harry Chapin. Clearly, some of these don't generate the excitement
of previous, higher-profile sets by the likes of Bob Dylan, Led
Zeppelin, Eric Clapton, Tom Petty, and, of course, Springsteen.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, this season will be remembered for the granddaddy of
boxed sets _ a 26-CD Sony Records retrospective (``Soundtrack for a
Century'') that retails for a gaudy $300 and is so weighty you
virtually need a wheelbarrow to lug it around. This is truly a gift
for the music lover who has everything.
</P>
<P>
   Let us proceed to specifics:
</P>
<P>
   Sony Music 100 Years: ``Soundtrack for a Century.'' We kid you
not about the heft of this thing. It's the ultimate vanity project
by Sony Records _ spanning 547 songs from 479 of its artists dating
all the way back to 1889 when the label was known as the Columbia
Phonograph Co. The set includes double CDs representing every genre
from country to world music (which can be purchased as two-CD sets
apart from the box). The breadth is mind-boggling. The country set
runs from Fiddlin' John Carson's ``Little Old Log Cabin in the
Lane'' in 1923 to the Dixie Chicks' ``Wide Open Spaces'' in 1997.
And what other box contains tracks by Al Jolson, the Dorsey
Brothers, and Pearl Jam? Too many artists are restricted to a
single song, but it's a fascinating compilation nonetheless. And it
comes with a 308-page book filled with essays about the development
of music and technology. You can spend a lot of time with this box,
which has 40 hours of music alone.
</P>
<P>
   Stevie Wonder, ``At the Close of a Century,'' Motown. The appeal
of a good boxed set is that it forces us to reexamine an artist.
Sometimes that's painful if the artist doesn't have enough material
to fill a quality box (see the following reviews of the Doobies and
Chapin), but it's a joy in the case of Wonder. His growth from
being a precocious 12-year-old scoring a hit with ``Fingertips Pts
1 &AMP; 2,'' to a groundbreaking fusionist mixing funk, psychedelia,
and spirituality is astonishing. He also got the best out of such
guests as the Jackson 5, Minnie Riperton, Paul Anka (!), and pedal
steel ace Sneaky Pete Kleinow from the Flying Burrito Brothers.
Occasionally, Wonder played every instrument on his songs, and his
attempts to embrace outside styles such as Latin music were way
ahead of his time. Sadly, the box lacks previously unissued tunes
or alternate takes but still merits high marks.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Davis Jr., ``Yes I Can! The Sammy Davis Jr. Story,''
Warner Archives/Rhino. Davis wasn't called Mr. Entertainment for
nothing. The son of a vaudeville dancer, Davis was touring by age 8
_ one memorable show had him opening at Boston's Plymouth Theatre
for Bill ``Bojangles'' Robinson _ and his ability as a song
interpreter is captured skillfully on this box. Although often
viewed as a campy singer, Davis had a more thoughtful way than he's
given credit for with show tunes and jazz standards. He ranged
easily from the songbooks of George and Ira Gershwin to Johnny
Mercer and Rodgers and Hart. Enjoyable collaborations are found
with Frank Sinatra and Count Basie (in a track produced by Quincy
Jones), but the central figure is Sammy and his sheer,
finger-snapping joy with life. His positive attitude was contagious
_ as revealed in one of these four CDs that deals only with live
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ronstadt, ``Box Set,'' Elektra. Ronstadt has had an
eclectic career, but this box goes overboard in trumpeting that
eclecticism. The problem is not that she's recorded everything from
country to classical in her career. It's the sequencing of the
songs. Instead of going chronologically, the box uses reverse
chronology (the first song is a John Hiatt cover, ``When We Ran,''
from 1998), which immediately shakes up the listener. So does the
too-clever sequencing of her cover of Neil Young's ``After the Gold
Rush,'' followed by a duet with Frank Sinatra (``Moonlight in
Vermont''), then a Mexican song, ``El Camino.'' Sorry, it doesn't
work. And there are many other examples. It would have been better
to divide the four CDs into distinct genres. However, the last CD,
``Rarities,'' is interesting and has three songs she did for Randy
Newman's opera, ``Faust,'' along with a live track with bluegrass
group the Seldom Scene.
</P>
<P>
   Doobie Brothers, ``Long Train Runnin','' Warner Archives/Rhino.
The Doobies have had some great hits from their guitar-centered,
hippie-mongering '70s era (``China Grove'' and ``Black Water'' jump
out), as well as their more polished late '70s and early '80s
period when Michael McDonald took over on keyboards and sang ``What
A Fool Believes.'' But each era saw plenty of filler _ and too much
of it is on this box. Also problematic is a fourth CD of
``Abandoned Tracks _ Demos and Roughs.'' Rough is the operative
word, because many tracks should have stayed abandoned. The only
discoveries are a couple of Patrick Simmons' Leo Kottke-like guitar
instrumentals. The Bay Area Doobies would have been better served
to tighten up this box into two or three CDs, not four.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Chapin, ``Story of a Life,'' Elektra/Rhino. Chapin was a
folk-pop troubadour who will be forever known for his
irony-drenched hits, ``Taxi'' (about driving a cab and picking up a
former girlfriend) and ``Cat's in the Cradle,'' a bittersweet tale
about a father who ignores his son, then is ignored by the son when
the latter reaches adulthood. But Chapin did not have enough
high-end songs to merit a box. Some tunes sound hopelessly hammy
(such as ``30,000 Pounds of Bananas'') and overproduced. Chapin
wrote some strong story-songs, but he was still a work in progress
when he died in a car accident in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Marley, ``Songs of Freedom,'' Tuff Gong. This is a new
reissue (with new packaging) of a Marley box that originally came
out in 1992. It's worth mentioning again, because it's a landmark
box that doesn't settle for the familiar recordings of his hits
(from ``I Shot the Sheriff'' to ``No Woman, No Cry''), but instead
includes some live versions and some 12-inch mixes. Jamaican
singer/prophet Marley still sounds vital, right up to a taping of
his eloquent ``Redemption Song,'' recorded in his final concert in
Pittsburgh. ``Emancipate yourself from mental slavery,'' he says in
classic Marley style.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1426EST &QL; 
