<HEADER>
A1990 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ARTS-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      12-17 1677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT'S (KIDS') ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What would Christmas be without parents bemoaning the mindless
drift of their children's entertainment? And who could blame them,
what with the endless procession of Beanie Babies, Teletubbies,
Barneys, Mutant Turtles, and whoever those mystical morons were
from the last ``Star Wars'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   Well, bah me no humbugs, but suddenly the kids' stuff is all
right. More than all right, in fact; children's entertainment seems
awash in a sea of faddish creativity. Of the three humongous fads
of the day only the religious right and the politically correct
left could be upset by the three Harry Potter books or the second
``Toy Story'' movie. Pokemon is perhaps a horse, or whatever those
creatures are, of another color, but even this phenomenon _ the
collecting, not the animation _ has something to say for it. Not
only is each of the three of them instructive on its own level, but
recalls the joys of the fads from childhoods past _ or at least one
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HARRY POTTER
</P>
<P>
   The aforementioned muggles of the right and left _ who have more
in common with each other than they like to think _ are up in arms
that Harry Potter enchants children with tales of sorcery and
witchcraft. The key word, though, is ``enchant.'' With children so
seduced by television and computers, the sight of a child with his
or her head buried in any book other than ``How to Poison Your
Parents'' ought to elicit tears of joy.
</P>
<P>
   When the writer is as good as J. K. Rowling, parents should be
doubly encouraged. It is annoying that a publisher called
Scholastic would see fit to Americanize many references, even
changing the title of the first book from ``Philosopher's Stone''
to ``Sorcerer's Stone'' _ apparently philosphy is beyond Americans
_ but a trip to Amazon.com.UK can fix that. (It is amazingly easy
and relatively inexpensive to order the British books over the
Internet.)
</P>
<P>
   But Harry Potter is a charmer even in American English. You know
you're in the hands of a master storyteller who knows how to cozy
up to a kid from the opening paragraph: ``Mr. and Mrs. Dursley, of
number four, Privet Drive, were proud to say that they were
perfectly normal, thank you very much. They were the last people
you'd expect to be involved in anything strange or mysterious,
because they just didn't hold with such nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Cinderella's stepmother and stepsisters, Mr. and Mrs.
Dursley and their son find themselves saddled with their nephew,
Harry, whom they treat like dirt. Harry, however, has magic in his
genes and is whisked away into a world of wizardry and
transmogrified animals. Empowerment and self-esteem, indeed. Some
parents would rather those things be learned in more down-to-earth
forms like noncompetitive athletics (talk about fantasy worlds),
but magical landscapes have always been a part of children's
literature, from ``The Wonderful Wizard of Oz'' to ``The
NeverEnding Story'' and if the goal is to get children to read,
then even a good pagan like Harry is on the side of the angels this
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   My angel was a legendary teacher at Boston Latin School named
Joseph McNamara, who delighted in upending the rote-learning apple
cart so prevalent at that school in the 1960s when I was lucky
enough to have him as an English teacher. His reading list, which
was voluntary, shunned Shakespeare and Dickens and instead
suggested Bram Stoker's ``Dracula,'' Arthur Conan Doyle's Sherlock
Holmes mysteries, and H. Rider Haggard's adventures. (Latin School
was an all-boys school at the time. A Falstaffian figure like Joe
McNamara might not have survived in a coeducational institution,
which in itself is a great reason for keeping adolescent boys and
girls separate but equal.)
</P>
<P>
   Students who didn't know that a book could be read for pleasure
would be chowing down eight books a month, only partly because that
raised your grade 10 points. McNamara knew that if you hooked a kid
on Stoker he would graduate to Poe and then to Hawthorne. Entrance
him with the science fiction of A. E. Van Vogt and you open a door
onto the disciplines of science and fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of his former students are losing sleep reading
Dostoevski these days, but I wouldn't be surprised if almost every
one of them who takes a look at a child spellbound by Harry
Potter's days at Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry has a
special wistfulness for Joe Mac's classes at Boston Latin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POKEMON
</P>
<P>
   Ash, the boy hero of ``Pokemon,'' leads a similarly enchanted
life, and devotees of the cards/video game/TV show/movie can also
find portals into, pardon the jargon, self-esteem and empowerment.
It is considerably harder, though, for adults to get excited about
whatever virtues it has, given its less literate and confusing (to
adults) story line and its awful animation. Perhaps, though, that's
part of the allure, that children have this special world of
communication that keeps parents out of the clubhouse. It's the
consumerism and addictiveness (``Gotta catch them all'') that
disturbs some parents, although Peggy Charren, the former head of
Action for Children's Television, tells of other parents who spend
their own money trying to buy rare cards for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Still, collecting cards seems to be a joyful part of childhood,
short of one of the little tykes getting your credit card number
and searching the Internet for some of those rare cards. (The
Internet, itself, is one of the ways that children can understand
this world and delight in its nooks and crannies in ways that give
them a special power over their parents.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a special power in having something your friends
don't have, which may not be a trait you want to foster in a child,
but probably isn't a sign that he or she will go psycho either. My
friends and I were obsessed with the cards based on the ``Davy
Crockett'' movies in the 1950s and I still can't suppress the glee
when I discovered that the cards were being released in Nantasket
before Boston and so I'd come back from weekends at the summer
rental being the cock of the walk with my complete sets (the orange
and the green series) of Davy Crockett cards.
</P>
<P>
   Charren isn't crazy about some elements of the Pokemon
phenomenon, like the creature with the fiery tale that might
inspire to light up one of their little toys. But Pokemon elicits
sympathetic thoughts from Charren as well, even in the way that
children derive status from them. ``I can relate the trading cards
personally to a game I played in the streets of New York.'' Charren
would pitch playing cards with drawings or paintings, everything
from comic strips to Thomas Gainsborough's ``The Blue Boy,'' in the
same way that children do with baseball cards. She was as adept at
that as she would later become at judging children's entertainment,
and wound up with the most valuable set around. ``One of the most
horrible things that ever happened to me,'' she says with a laugh
as well as a lament, ``was one day I came home from school and I
couldn't find them. My mother incinerated them. She thought I was
becoming obsessed. And I was the winner! I was the big cheese!''
</P>
<P>
   She does add, though, that these collections were valuable only
to the children who owned them and that the economics behind the
card companies' manipulativeness with Pokemon is ``nauseating.'' In
addition to children having to roam the Internet for rare cards,
you have to go to the movie four times to get the complete set of
``Pokemon'' cards that they give children with tickets. ``Some
kids, it has been witnessed, buy tickets to the movie and go home
after getting the cards. That's very manipulative. It's another
example of the corporate culture making their profits on the back
of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOY STORY 2
</P>
<P>
   We can all find antecedents for Harry Potter and Pokemon, but
were there any movies as smart as the two ``Toy Story'' films from
Pixar and Disney? One might compare the anime of ``Princess
Mononoke'' to Disney's experiments with ``Fantasia,'' but there was
nothing like the mix of word and image in the '50s that there is in
``Toy Story 2.'' One can cavil, and probably should, at the
merchandising of the ``Toy'' toys, which the movie itself has some
fun with, but it's hard to be angry with a movie that so lovingly
and brilliantly captures the relationship between children and
their toys.
</P>
<P>
   It is the nature of the world we live in that obsolescence
travels at the speed of light, for Woody the cowboy toy as well as
cinematic technique. ``Toy Story 2'' puts its considerable heart on
the side of slowing down and appreciating everything for what it
is. Woody and Buzz Lightyear, the astronaut toy, becoming friends
instead of rivals in the first ``Toy Story'' is a great lesson in
finding common ground for children as well as questioning the modes
and mores of a disposable society.
</P>
<P>
   But we're getting too serious. ``Toy Story 2,'' like the Harry
Potter books, is most of all an ode to the powers of the
imagination, which takes on all the more power because it makes
such a fanciful world so credible. (It's Tom Hanks's most
believable role in years.) Perhaps we should say fanciful worlds,
because there are more worlds within worlds here than in ``Being
John Malkovich.'' The magic of ``Toy Story 2'' is in the blending
of the lives of the animated _ or pixilated _ people with the lives
of the toy people, toy creatures, and the merchandise created from
them, all the while adhering to the ``reality'' that directors John
Lasseter and Lee Unkrich have created. Thus a prospector from an
old ``Howdy Doody''-like show is trapped inside a box because it
was never opened.
</P>
<P>
   No children's entertainment is without its risks, though. If you
see the film, you might not let your kids get rid of any of their
toy clutter even if they want to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
