<HEADLINE>
J. GEILS BANDS TOGETHER FOR FIREFIGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent fire that claimed the lives of six Worcester
firefighters has hit home with the reunited J. Geils Band. The
Boston group took a break from rehearsals the other night to
discuss doing something for the families left behind by the
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got friends who are firemen,'' Geils singer Peter Wolf
recalls thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a Geils decision to play a benefit for the
families on Dec. 29 at the Orpheum. Tickets go on sale Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed like a pertinent thing to do. It makes sense,
and it reminds me of a lot of the things that the Geils Band used
to do,'' says Wolf. ``I know the whole band feels good about this _
and it strengthens the sense of our reunion.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the last Geils gig before the group's long breakup was
a charity show at the Worcester Centrum in 1982 to benefit the Toys
for Tots campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That was back in the days when the Geils Band was a fixture at
New Year's Eve shows in the area _ playing at either the Boston
Garden, the Centrum, or the Providence Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it for 12-13 years straight,'' Wolf recalls.
</P>
<P>
   The band isn't playing a local New Year's gig this year because
the city of Detroit (the second most popular city for Geils)
grabbed it first. ``It would have been great to be in Boston, but
people in Detroit made the offer early on,'' Wolf says of the
group's commitment to play the Palace in Auburn Hills that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit asked early, but it's still nice that we can play in
Boston during holiday week,'' Wolf says of the Orpheum benefit.
Which raises the question: What about future Geils shows? Will the
reunion continue into next year?
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be no more shows or we could decide to do a bunch
more,'' says Wolf. ``We want this to be a labor of love and not
laborious.'' No long-term commitments have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf has gone back to making a solo record (no Geils album has
been agreed upon, though Wolf is sure some label would be
interested), while guitarist J. Geils and harpist Magic Dick have
gone back to their band, Bluestime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it's going right now is healthy. It allows people to
continue what they're doing,'' says Wolf. ``And we'll see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sister Kate resurfaces _ Kate Taylor, unlike her brothers James
and Livingston, has performed only sporadically through the years,
while focusing on the upbringing of her three daughters. She has,
however, just released a new single _ a compelling version of
``Auld Lang Syne'' with James on harmony _ that she's selling
through her Web site, http://www.katetaylor.com, as a holiday gift,
with some proceeds going to charity. The song is a prelude to a new
CD, ``Beautiful Road,'' due in early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were thinking of a song to do last New Year's Eve at the
Old Whaling Church,'' Taylor says, referring to the Edgartown
church near her Martha's Vineyard home. ``And `Auld Lang Syne' came
up. No one knew what the lyrics were, so we got them from a
librarian on the island.'' Taylor's husband, Charlie Witham, then
adapted them from the original, written by Robert Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``James came over to dinner last winter and we played it for
him. And when he got off the road in June, he came into the studio
and sang the harmony vocal,'' says Taylor, referring to Sonic
Brothers studio on the Vineyard _ in the basement of a building
where Kate actually lived in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The single likewise features bassist Tony Garner (who coproduced
the record and is Bob Dylan's tour bassist) and violinist Mindy
Jostyn, who has worked with Carly Simon and Billy Joel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James on the Hall of Fame: Although he's never been principally
known as a rocker, James Taylor just won induction into the Rock
and Roll Hall of Fame (the ceremony is March 6 in Manhattan). ``I
was thrilled to even be considered, let alone selected,'' Taylor
says in a statement, before joking: ``I'm honored, especially
considering the other nominees. It's incredible. I demand a
recount.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Songs of the century: ``You've Lost that Lovin' Feelin','' a hit
for the Righteous Brothers, is the most played song of the century,
according to BMI, the performing rights group. BMI tallies the
number of performances on US radio and TV _ and the song has passed
the 8 million mark. It was written by Barry Mann, Phil Spector, and
Cynthia Weil. Following it, with 7 million performances, are
``Never My Love,'' ``Yesterday,'' and ``Stand By Me.'' Rounding out
the Top 10, with 6 million performances, are ``Can't Take My Eyes
Off of You,'' ``(Sittin' On) the Dock of the Bay,'' ``Mrs.
Robinson,'' ``Baby I Need Your Loving,'' ``Rhythm of the Rain,''
and ``Georgia On My Mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
