<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MOMA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUXTAPOSITION, WIT INVIGORATE `MODERNISM' SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ Art museums haven't escaped the end-of-century urge
to take things apart and sum them up. Most of the resulting shows
exhaust you with good intentions, grand ambitions, murky thinking
and too many things.
 &HT;    The Museum of Modern Art _ which has been explaining its subject
since its founding in 1929, sometimes in a rather high-handed
fashion and not usually with a lot of wit _ has come up with a
delightful turn of the century show. Three shows, actually:
``People,'' ``Places,'' and ``Things,'' the game-show categories
sometimes stretched by the addition of abstraction. The umbrella
for the three, which had staggered openings but are now all up and
running, is ``ModernStarts,'' which is itself part of ``MoMA2000.''
(You knew the millennium had to figure into this somehow.) A series
of shows examining the 20th century through the prism of the
Modern's gigantic collections, ``MoMA2000'' is supposed to prepare
museum-goers for expanded thinking about art, to go along with the
museum's expanded real estate, a vast addition being designed by
Yoshio Taniguchi and scheduled for completion in 2004.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, ``ModernStarts'' examines the idea of ``modernism,''
but discards the strict linear canon MoMA had always espoused,
instead cavorting freely among styles, media, and categories. It
works. The curators _ John Elderfield, Peter Reed, Mary Chan, and
Maria Carmen Gonzalez _ have the finest eyes in the business for
what looks good next to what, what objects spark each other.
They've focused on art from around 1880-1920, but were none too
fussy about the dates: They added earlier and later works when
appropriate, and monumental contemporary ones to introduce the
show's themes.
 &HT;    ``People,'' for instance, opens with a vast 1975 Sol LeWitt wall
drawing of white arcs on a black wall. Abstract, yes, but the
context encourages you to read the composition as a ballet reduced
to its essence, even as the ultimate distillation of one of the
masterworks in the galleries beyond, Matisse's 1909 ``Dance.''
Another abstraction, a red stripe painting by Barnett Newman, acts
as backdrop for Maillol's gargantuan allegorical female figure,
``The River,'' which tumbles forward into space like a waterfall.
Both are heroic; the Newman stresses the verticality of the
masculine; the Maillol, the horizontality of the feminine. Not
particularly PC, this contrast, but it's clear.
 &HT;    France looms large in ``People'' and its companion shows,
largest in ``Places,'' where, in certain galleries, French
landscape almost blots out any other country's contributions. MoMA
championed the School of Paris from the start. While the museum has
broadened its outlook, Paris is still an overwhelming presence,
with Rodin, Matisse, and Picasso among the heavyweights of the
``People'' section. The themes here reach beyond what you'd expect
_ the move toward the fragmentation and abstraction of the figure _
to include ideas like posture as composition, using, as example,
the way Matisse's blocky bronze ``Backs'' virtually merge with
their slablike backgrounds.
 &HT;    A room exploring the body language of despair juxtaposes
Steichen's ``Pussy Willow'' photograph with Schiele's ``Nude with
Violet Stockings'': In both, the figure's face is obscured, which
makes the crouched-over posture all the more prominent. The
curators highlight artists who exploited the figure to make
compositions that were daring for their day, like the Degas pastel
``At The Milliner's,'' a picture that zooms from left to right and
doesn't include the viewer at all. The milliner is intent on the
client; the client, on her image in a mirror we're not privy to
see.
 &HT;    A section on actors, dancers, and bathers _ people who exist to
be looked at _ juxtaposes a 1921 Steichen photograph, ``Wind, Fire,
Therese Duncan'' _ with Jules Cheret's 1893 poster
``Folies-Bergere, La Loie Fuller.'' In each, the dancer is consumed
by a costume that seems almost to go up in flames. (Fuller
experimented with radium to light herself up.) The amorphous nature
of the image symbolizes the freedom of the modern dance that
developed at the turn of the century.
 &HT;    One of the most telling juxtapositions of ``People'' is a c.
1885 Cezanne ``Bather'' next to Rineke Dukstra's 1993 Chromogenic
<TEXT>
color print, ``Odessa, Ukraine. 4 August 1993.'' Both depict a lone
male figure in swim trunks, silhouetted against a low horizon line.
The heroic bulk of the Cezanne suggests timelessness, eternity;
Dukstra's boy, by contrast, looks frail and very much of the
moment.
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maria Fernanda Cardoso's stunning 1992 ``Cementerio _ Vertical
Garden,'' a 112-foot-wide expanse of artificial flowers that spring
directly from the wall, parallel to the floor, opens ``Places'' in
suitably disorienting fashion. The massive bunches of fake white
lilies suggest a cemetery, an interpretation reinforced by faint
pencilled arches on the wall behind them: They look like rows of
tombstones. The topsy-turvy effect of Cardoso's piece jibes with
the entrance to the galleries, one of Hector Guimard's famous
turn-of-the-century Paris Metro gates, iron liquified into whiplash
curves, jack-in-the-pulpit lighting fixtures and irregular
typography. Like Cardoso's artificial flowers, Guimard's garden of
a gate is an example of modern means and materials mimicking
nature.
</P>
<P>
   Examples of artists' rejection of modern industrialization
follows in the very next room, though. The ambiguity about
``progress'' is epitomized in the rugged woodcuts Gauguin made
after fleeing to Tahiti and Munch's depictions of lonely souls
staring out at a black sea or dense pine forest. Photographs of a
train careening around a cliff, the building of the Panama Canal,
the Eiffel Tower going up, document nature disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   The airplane freed man from earth and freed artists from the
traditional horizon line. In World War I, RAF pilots on
reconnaissance missions were taught to identify landscapes as
``Cubist'' or ``Futurist.'' Aerial views have much in common with
the disconnect of modern painting. In the MoMA show, Malevich's
1915 ``Suprematist Composition: Airplane Flying,'' which at first
glance looks completely non-representational, is paired with
Jacques-Henri Lartigue's 1909 photograph of a glider, to emphasize
that the Malevich isn't abstract at all.
</P>
<P>
   The hyperactivity of Futurism butts up against the eerie
stillness of Surrealism in a section devoted to views of an urban
Europe shattered by the Great War. Matisse's ``View of Notre Dame''
hangs next to Mondrian's ``Church Facade'': In both, the church
towers are barely legible, surrounded and defined by networks of
black lines, a break-up of space that has nothing to do with the
horizon line of open land. A map of Paris locates the studios of
the astonishing number of important artists working there early in
the century. The proximity of their workplaces belies the notion of
the artist working in isolation _ and confirms what MoMA has
preached all along about Parisian preeminence of the period.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Things'' is the most fun of all three parts of
``ModernStarts,'' and here the curators had the most leeway. While
they couldn't include real people or places in the other sections,
they could and did incorporate real chairs, tables, and toast racks
in this one, along with painted representations of same. A witty
lineup of still-life paintings by Klee, Gauguin, Matisse, and Miro
illustrates the 20th century willingness to ignore gravity and
perspective and tilt the tabletop until it's parallel to the
picture plane, the better to show what's on the table. A few real
tables from the same era, including an oval one by Charles Rennie
Mackintosh, keep you grounded.
</P>
<P>
   In a section on guitars the curators had a field day with this
curvaceous instrument that resembles the female form and symbolizes
the Bohemian life as well. For Picasso and Gris, the guitar also
evoked their native Spain. Guitars depicted in works in the MoMA
show have been dismantled and reassembled, in two dimensions and
three. Artists experimented with how little of a guitar they could
show and still have it be unmistakable. Picasso's 1912-13 sheet
metal and wire ``Guitar,'' for instance, is crudely cut, ragged and
unplayable, but resolute in its identity.
</P>
<P>
   A case devoted to objects as subjects holds things that look
like other things, including Tiffany glass and Grueby faience, both
plantlike, and a Christopher Dresser watering can so sleek it looks
like abstract sculpture. There are function-thwarted objects
including Man Ray's ``Cadeau,'' a flatiron spiked with 13 tacks
that would snag any fabric the iron encountered; and Meret
Oppenheim's iconic fur-covered teacup. And there's Umberto
Boccioni's even more iconic ``Development of a Bottle in Space,'' a
fractured, twirling bronze that looks as if it's spun right out of
a still-life painting of the period in its determination to become
3-D.
</P>
<P>
   Trans-Atlantic affinities emerge. Frank Lloyd Wright's strict
but colorful geometry is teamed with Mondrian's; Gaudi's ability to
make iron look fluid and organic is likened to Louis Sullivan's. It
took the Gothic style centuries to spread across Europe; it took
Art Nouveau no time at all to cover two continents. Technology is
as much a determinant in ``Things'' as advances in communication.
The perfection of bentwood in the 19th century, for instance, made
possible chairs that spiralled and curled.
</P>
<P>
   Big, brash, c. 1910 posters by Lucian Bernhard and others
advertise cigarettes, lightbulbs, and toothpaste by placing single
examples against vividly colored grounds. They anticipate Pop by
half a century. A section on the word as object demonstrates how
words were incorporated into Cubist and Dada pictures, and how
typography was freed from neat horizontal rows and uniform scale.
The basis for Jenny Holzer's blinking truisms of the late 1970s was
in place decades earlier. What's most eye-opening and eye-popping
about ``Things'' is how much of modern art was fully present by
1920.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1431EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
