<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PORTABLE E-MAIL DEVICES IDEAL FOR ROAD WARRIORS 
</HEADLINE>
 E-MAIL-HNS   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT BEER  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Get itchy when you think about all that unread
e-mail piling up back at the office? Do you lie awake nights
wondering about how many recruiters have left you digital siren
songs? Can't wait to open all those hilarious forwarded e-mail
jokes?
</P>
<P>
   You ship has just pulled in.
</P>
<P>
   Electronics giant Motorola and Research in Motion, a New
York-based wireless data company, are pushing two nifty, but
imperfect, devices that will let e-mail addicts get their fix just
about anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Both devices _ Motorola's PageWriter 2000X and RIM's Blackberry
_ are pager-like devices with tiny keyboards that send and receive
e-mail messages via radio signal. They also include some simple but
useful software that keeps track of a user's calendar, phone
messages, memos and other personal information.
</P>
<P>
   For someone who has to keep up with e-mail, these are viable
solutions. But with the advent of other wireless technologies, such
as the connected personal digital assistants like the Palm VII and
the increasing e-mail capabilities of cell phones, the pager e-mail
devices seem to be headed for a niche market. And it's too bad,
because both the PageWriter and the Blackberry are, for lack of a
better word, pretty nifty.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackberry resembles a pager with a slight weight problem.
It sports a tiny keyboard that, at first, seems daunting, but
actually is quite functional. You can't write a novel on this
thing, but for a simple e-mail response, it works just fine. The
device fits in a cradle that attaches to a PC's serial port. It can
trade phone numbers and other data with such popular personal
information managers as Outlook and ACT.
</P>
<P>
   As a stand-alone organizer, the Blackberry actually rivals the
Palm and other electronic gizmos for ease of use. A scroll button
on the upper right lets you easily navigate through the various
functions and up and down lists. And the keyboard is actually more
accurate and faster than the scribble input of a Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up the Blackberry is a bit daunting. You have to first
determine whether your PC is using Microsoft Exchange Server
software. Most do, but some don't, and you should be careful to
check this out before you invest in a Blackberry. After installing
the software, you then have to leave your PC on in order to get
your messages shunted to the Blackberry.
</P>
<P>
   But once you go through all that, you will find that the
Blackberry makes a great companion. It notifies you via a tone or
vibration of arriving messages. You can shut the device off while
in a theater or on an airplane, and the service will send along
e-mails that have piled up while you were off the air.
</P>
<P>
   But not all e-mail can be forwarded. You can't send attachments,
and the Blackberry device is not designed to deal with lengthy
messages. Users can set up filters to send only messages with
specific subjects or read messages only from particular people.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's slightly beefier PageWriter 2000X could be considered
the deluxe version of the Blackberry. The screen is brighter and
larger; navigation is through an easy-to-use four-direction
``NavDisc.'' The keyboard, slightly larger than the Blackberry,
lights up. And instead of a replaceable AA battery, the PageWriter
sports a rechargeable power pack that fuels up from a desktop
cradle. Like the Blackberry, the PageWriter includes all the usual
personal information organizing software, and it will synch with
the usual desktop PC organizing titles.
</P>
<P>
   The Motorola requires you to have a separate e-mail account that
uses a pretty arcane naming scheme. You also have to add separate
software to your company's servers to forward e-mail to the
PageWriter.
</P>
<P>
   Blackberry at a glance:
</P>
<P>
   Research in Motion, Limited
</P>
<P>
   www.blackberry.net
</P>
<P>
   $400 for the device. $40 for monthly e-mail forwarding service.
</P>
<P>
   Requires: PC with at least an Intel 486 powered chip, available
serial port, Windows 95, 98 or NT with 16 MB RAM. Microsoft
Exchange Client, Microsoft Outlook 97 or 98 Workgroup installation
with access to an e-mail account on an MS Exchange Server 4.0 or
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola PageWriter 2000X at a glance:
</P>
<P>
   Motorola Inc.
</P>
<P>
   www.motorola.com
</P>
<P>
   $400 for the device. Monthly service start at $25 per month.
</P>
<P>
   Requires: PC with Windows 95, 98 or NT. Server software required
for forwarding other e-mail. SkyTel paging service. Other carriers
are slated to offer PageWriter services.
</P>
</TEXT>
