<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Dec. 18:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNET &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ A divided Security Council is to
vote on a major new Iraq resolution covering arms inspections and
conditions for lifting sanctions. France, in a break with the U.S.
and Britain, says it will abstain. Russian and China will also
abstain. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Dateline to kum) _ Developments in the Russian
campaign in Chechnya. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Two days ahead of parliamentary
elections, former Prime Minister Primakov announces that he is
running for president in June. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   G8-MEETING (Berlin) _ Secretary of State Albright and the other
G-8 foreign ministers meet, call for Chechnya cease-fire,
reflecting how the group is increasingly back to being the G-7 plus
Russia. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-SLAVE-LABOR (Berlin) _ The Nazi slave labor compensation
case is finally settled as lawyers and Germany agree on a $5.2
billion fund. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-U.S. (Paris) _ Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, on a visit
to Tokyo, said that the United States should be ``discreet'' in
exercising its global power. His criticisms follow remarks made by
President Jacques Chirac in an interview this week. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DISABLED (Washington) _ At the Roosevelt Memorial,
President Clinton signs into law a bill that continues medical
insurance for disabled people who obtain jobs. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   EPA-AIR-POLLUTION (Washington) _ The EPA, acting at the request
of Northeastern states, says it wants specific Midwestern factories
closed because of air pollution violations. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
