Smith, is giving one of her kidneys to one of her eighth-grade
students. The surgery will be next week.
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-DRUGS (Undated) _ After declining for two years, the use
of marijuana and other illicit drugs by American adolescents
leveled off in 1999, according to an annual study. By Christopher
S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   CUBANS-DETAIN (St. Martinville, La.) _ Developments in the Cuban
detainee hostage situation at the Louisiana jail. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-DEBATE (Nashua, N.H.) _ Bill Bradley and Al Gore debate. By
Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-CATHOLICS (New York) _ As Cardinal John O'Connor prepares to
step down, a New York Times poll finds that Roman Catholics in the
New York Archdiocese say they want the next archbishop to be more
concerned about issues humanitarian than political, that helping
the poor is the most important challenge facing the archdiocese and
that the church could be much more in touch with its members. By
Diana Jean Schemo. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TOBACCO-TAX (Albany) _ Gov. George Pataki and Democrats have
brokered a health care deal that would result in coverage for 1
million uninsured New Yorkers and cost smokers 55 cents more a
pack. By Raymond Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-ATTACK (New York) _ Developments in the attack
on a painting at the Brooklyn Museum; the suspect is arraigned. By
Alan Feuer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MONSANTO-PHARMACIA (Undated) _ Folo on reports that Monsanto and
Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn are in merger talks.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-COKE (Undated) _ The Italian Antitrust Authority has fined
the Italian units of Coca-Cola $16.1 million for ``serious
violations'' in abusing its power in that country's soft drinks
market. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York ) _ Stocks surge into record territory in early
trading on the last ``triple witching'' session of the year. By 2:
30 p.m., the Dow was up 111 points, the S&AMP;P 500 up 9 points and the
Nasdaq composite index up 63 points. Treasury prices were little
changed, with the yield on the long bond at 6.40 percent. European
markets were higher: London i up 1.24 percent and Frankfurt up 0.30
percent. The Nikkei closed down 0.09 percent; the Hang Seng, up
2.67 percent. The dollar was at 103.04 yen; the euro is at $1.021.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-STOCKS (Sao Paulo) _ A look at the 100 percent rise in
Brazil's stock market this year and what is fueling it. A major
reason is the Internet fever driving stocks higher in many parts of
the world. But in Brazil, the quest for Internet plays is
benefiting some traditional businesses like banks and supermarkets.
By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
