   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-PEACE (Boston) _ One hundred women from embattled
territories and countries such as Cyprus, Kashmir and Sudan attend
a Harvard conference called ``Women Waging Peace.'' They compare
strategies on overcoming violence. By David Abel. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   ICELAND-ELVES (Hafnarfjordur, Iceland) _ Iceland is overrun with
elves, gnomes, trolls, light-fairies, lovelings and hidden people.
Just ask anayone. By Colin Nickerson. 1350 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-KENNEDY (Boston) _ Never again, Ted Kennedy aides say,
will the senior senator allow himself to be caught off-guard by a
challenger. So, Kennedy is getting fit (politically), stockpiling
more cash than ever, and making sure his campaign machine is
cranked. By Frank Phillips. 670 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIT-Y2K (Cambridge, Mass.) _ If anyone should be ready for Y2K,
it should be MIT, the most technically savvy university in the
universe. For a while, the school was in high panic, planning to
shut down elevators. Plans have been scaled back, although it still
intends to ask everyone to have their computers off when we cross
the ``millennium boundary'' at midnight on Dec. 31. By Peter Howe.
1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   BROTHERS-REUNITE (Boston) _ One builds homes for a living. The
other has no home. This is a story of two brothers, a dozen years
of separation, a life on the streets and a fraternal reunion. By
Tatsha Robertson. 750 words.
</P>
