<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of Mon., Dec. 20, 1999,
and anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New York
Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KEEP THAT SPRAY &LR;  _ Farmers may need to douse their fields with
yet more pesticides to get the best out of genetically modified
plants. Novartis of Switzerland has filed patents covering the use
of pesticides on genetically modified crops. Scientists realized
that a wide spectrum of insect pests were attacking its modified Bt
maize. By Andy Coghlan and Barry Fox. (Slugged:
BC-GENETICALLY-ENGINEERED-CROPS-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   SKIP THE WARM-UP &LR;  _ Stretching before you exercise in a bid to
prevent injuries is a waste of time. After monitoring army
recruits, Australian researchers advised the army that it should
consign the stretching tradition to the scrap heap. Page 23 by
Julia Hinde. (Slugged: BC-DARWINIAN-EVOLUTION-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   THERE MAY BE A WAY TO AVOID THE TRAUMA OF THE WRONG CANCER
TREATMENT &LR;  _ Making tumor cells look like miniature comets could
save people with bladder cancer from the trauma of unnecessary
surgery or radiotherapy. Researchers in Ulster and Leicester have
developed a quick test that can predict the response of bladder
cancer cells and help decide which is the best therapy. (Slugged:
BC-CANCER-TREATMENT-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   LOOK BEFORE YOU EAT &LR;  _ A see-through refrigerator lets you see
its contents without wasting energy. A Swedish inventor has
designed a fridge with a two-way mirror door that can be a normal
mirror when the fridge light is off, becoming transparent when the
fridge light is switched on. By Barry Fox. (Slugged:
BC-JAPANESE-PATENTS-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
