<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV19-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN OF THE CENTURY: JOHN ROCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 19, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could spend every waking hour between Christmas and New
Year's in family conclaves debating who did the most good in the
century just ending.
</P>
<P>
   Start by striking out all the despots _ the Hitlers, Lenins,
Stalins, and Maos. But spend five minutes kicking the topic around
after the Christmas bird is plucked clean, and there'll be a raft
of interesting or daffy nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton's nominee is Franklin D. Roosevelt, the president
who kept spirits up during the Great Depression and the worst war
the world has seen. Winston Churchill, the Greatest Briton, is
another, though I think that even had he not emerged, or had fallen
prey at 25 to a Boer bullet on one of his hell-for-leather gallops
across the veldt, somehow Britan would have prevailed over Nazi
Germany and the Axis.
</P>
<P>
   Ghandi? Martin Luther King Jr.? JFK? Mother Teresa? Thomas
Edison? Henry Ford? The scientists who gave us polio vaccine,
penicillin, television, computers? A musically inclined friend
swears by John Lennon. An artist tells me Picasso. Your own
short-list might be totally different.
</P>
<P>
   Without pre-empting Time magazine, which seems to have a
stranglehold on the concept, my nominee for Man of the Century is a
tall (6 foot one-and-a-half), slim, pipe-smoking gent of quiet and
courtly manner, Massachusetts born and bred, as it happens, a
Bostonian to the core, who at his death in 1984 had done more good
for more people, by my rough calculation, than anyone I can name.
</P>
<P>
   His name? Dr. John Rock.
</P>
<P>
   He did not invent, but he did help develop, popularize, improve,
expand, and defend the birth control pill. Using natural hormones
in a timely fashion, the pill brought into common usage by Rock and
his many collaborators and colleagues changed life in remarkable
ways, not only for females of child-bearing age, but for the men
who cared for them, or tried to keep them down. Despite the
opposition of Roman Catholic prelates, women around the world,
including over 80 percent of Catholic women, embraced the pill as a
godsend, if not a pope-send.
</P>
<P>
   Women work today, outside the home, in numbers not dreamed of
when Rock took himself to Harvard College and Harvard Medical
School. Only 40 years before Rock was born in 1890, half of all
American women were illiterate. Twenty years before his birth, six
out of 10 working women were domestic servants. When he turned 10,
women held three out of four clerical jobs in the United States,
thanks to the invention of the typewriter. At the turn of this
century, only 4 percent of married white women worked outside the
home.
</P>
<P>
   Each time there was a war, women's rights took a lurch forward.
During World War I, most women cooked, cleaned, or washed, in a
work week that typically extended to 72 hours. But by World War II,
one shipyard worker out of eight was female, and an astonishing 40
percent of aircraft assembly workers were women. But the war did
not change as much as did that little pill. Life expectancy for
American women was 51 in 1900, and it is 80 today.
</P>
<P>
   The pill helped prolong women's lives by giving them better-paid
and physically easier work, and reducing the strain imposed by
successive childbirths. Nothing has done as much to reduce the
dependence of women upon men as the pill that freed them from
unwanted pregnancy. And it is worth remarking that the man who did
most to advance the pill's acceptance was a happily married father
of five, a descendant of Irish famine immigrants, who presided over
his merry brood in a French manor-style home in West Roxbury,
spending his working life trying to help Boston women have babies
when they wanted them.
</P>
<P>
   He had a first-rate high school education at Boston's High
School of Commerce. Musically inclined and theatrical, very close
to his twin sister, Nell, he was a devout Catholic who grew up in a
happy household with loving parents. ``They got along beautifully
together,'' he said of his parents.
</P>
<P>
   But he discovered firsthand the negative impact on family life
of unwanted pregnancies when he won an essay contest in high
school, and the prize was a trip to Latin America. As a payroll
clerk for United Fruit, he saw the destitution and dismay of the
impossibly large families of the peasants who picked bananas. As a
doctor in Boston, he saw how the poorer women were kept in grinding
poverty by relentless childbearing.
</P>
<P>
   Rock's remarkable life is detailed in the 1982 biography ``The
Pill, John Rock and the Church'' by Loretta McLaughlin, my retired
Globe colleague. When he died two years later, she wrote in a Globe
editorial that Rock paid a severe personal price for his battle
against misplaced prudery. Yet it was ``with dignity and a feeling
for humanity'' that he managed to nudge medicine toward a more
enlightened attitude toward human reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   The year John Rock was born, the world's population stood at 1.5
billion. Today, it is 6 billion, and one person out of five lives
on the equivalent of less than a dollar a day. But there might have
been many millions more clinging to the shrinking surface of
Lifeboat Earth had not Rock's little pill come into popular use.
</P>
<P>
   After writing his own book, ``The Time Has Come; a Catholic
Doctor's Proposals to End the Battle Over Birth Control,'' Rock
traveled the globe, warning that unrestrained population growth
threatened the welfare of humanity by pitching mankind into
life-or-death struggles for food, water, and cropland. His faith,
like his name, was unshakable. He recognized, like Freud, the
centrality of sexual congress in maintaining a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   He made it possible for women to have a life, as well as a sex
life, and in doing so, made life so much richer and more rewarding
for their menfolk as well. So, I ask you: who did more, for more
people, this century, than this man Rock?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
