</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV19-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEX IS THE `STATE OF THE ART' FOR INTERIOR WALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 19, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am having all my interior walls painted. Is it best to use
oil or latex?
</P>
<P>
   CAROL GOLDMAN, Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The state of the art is to apply two coats of latex or
acrylic, or latex-acrylic, (water-based) wall paint, flat or
eggshell, which is neither flat nor shiny. And, it is best to do
this. Generally no primer is needed on plaster, plasterboard, or
skimcoat walls, but it is a good idea to sand the walls lightly and
to wash really dirty walls. Otherwise they need a wiping down with
a dry cloth to remove dust and surface dirt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I put away my crystal salt and pepper shakers last Christmas
and did not remove the salt and pepper. When I got them out this
season, the pepper was not a problem. It cleaned out nicely. But
between the tarnish and salt I cannot get the sterling silver top
off the salt shaker. I shook the salt out but the top is still
stuck on. I soaked it in hot water to no avail. Can you offer any
help?
</P>
<P>
   MARY ELLEN McLAUGHLIN, in Cyberspace
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's try. Salt is soluble in water, so it's a matter of
getting the water into the space between cover and glass. Soak the
shaker in water overnight or longer. Then try twisting off the cap.
First, tap it with the flat side of a knife to possibly break the
bond. To get a better grip, use a thin rubber pad designed for that
purpose. Another twister-offer is a small tool, I think it's called
a Gilhooley, but I couldn't find it in the dictionary. They give a
very good grip without damaging the cap, although you want to grasp
the cap where it grips the glass, not above it. If that fails, soak
it some more in water. No additives needed. Finally, if all else
fails, try squirting a bit of WD-40 into the space (space? very
little space) between cap and glass. Something's gotta give!
</P>
<P>
   In the future, use the shaker and pepperer all year long.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My split-entry house was built in the 1960s. The bedrooms are
over a two-car garage, and they are cold. If I put in new garage
doors that have no windows and are insulated, will it solve the
problem?
</P>
<P>
   TOM FOLAN, from Out There
</P>
<P>
   A. Insulated doors on your garage will make no difference in
keeping the bedrooms warmer. Don't waste your money. In a '60s
house, the garage ceiling is probably insulated, but you can check
to see if it is. Drill a hole in the ceiling to check. It is
probably a cement-type concrete on wire lath to make it fire
resistant. Or, check the ceiling space between garage and basement.
If there is any insulation in there, it should be full; that is,
the entire ceiling cavity should be full. If there is none, you can
have cellulose blown in. If there is plenty of insulation, then
your heating system is slightly undersized and is not getting to
the far bedrooms, which are probably the farthest away from the
boiler. You can try insulating any heating pipes that you can see
in the garage or basement. This will keep the water hot until it
reaches the baseboard heaters.
</P>
<P>
   Or, live with the cool bedrooms; they should be cool, especially
for sleeping. Kids can handle the cool; tell them to put another
sweater on. A last resort is to upgrade the heating system to a
bigger one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you recommend for hot water radiators? Is it
necessary to paint with a high-heat-resistant (hhr) paint? Is an
enclosure or cover OK?
</P>
<P>
   PETER LYME, Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The best paint is an oil-based primer and oil-based spray
enamel. Apply the primer with a brush, but for the finish, use an
aerosol can of enamel; Krylon makes a good spray enamel; expensive
but very serviceable. The darker the color, the better the heat
transfer. Do not use the old-fashioned silver or bronze paint; it
reduces the efficiency of the radiators by about 10 percent. There
is no need for an hrr paint; hot water radiators do not get that
hot. But they do get hot enough to turn latex paint brown; that is
why uou should use oil paints. An enclosure or cover will make the
radiator more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Red candle wax dripped on a newly-finished floor. I took off
the wax with a credit card, but how can I remove the red dye that
remains? Goof-Off did not work.
</P>
<P>
   HELENE DUNLAP, Chestnut Hill, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. That red dye is probably still a bit of wax, so try this:
Place brown paper (a grocery bag, cut to one layer, will do nicely)
on the stain and run a warm to hot iron over it. You will see the
paper discolor; move the paper and repeat.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, it may be that it is only the dye, and it
is on the very top of the finish. So, spread a bit of toothpaste
(not gel) on the stain and rub with your fingers, with the grain.
Or, wet the stain with any kind of oil, sprinkle a bit of
rottenstone (sold in paint and hardware stores) on the oil, then
rub. There is enough abrasive material in the toothpaste (Colgate
is best for this purpose) and the rottenstone to take off the very
top of the finish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
