<HEADER>
A2023 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a DUMB-SUSPECTS-HNS &LR;      12-17 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ROBBERY SUSPECTS MAKE POLICE WORK EASY 
</HEADLINE>
 DUMB-SUSPECTS-HNS   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The police are calling these robbery suspects
dumb, dumber and dumbest.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys sure made our work easier,'' said Lt. Bruce
Marovich, head of the San Francisco police robbery detail. ``These
guys don't think. They just do it _ impulse and go. I don't know if
they have half a brain between them.''
</P>
<P>
   Marovich was referring to the seven suspects in more than 60
robberies and holdups in San Francisco in the past month. The
crimes they are suspected of committing include bank robberies,
store stickups, street muggings and assaults.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the police said, a suspect was arrested after his
accomplice blurted out his name during a robbery of his former
workplace. A second suspect in that case turned himself in after an
investigator used the oldest line in law enforcement: ``We know
everything, you might as well confess.''
</P>
<P>
   In another case, the suspects were arrested after they used
cellular phones the police said they had stolen to call their
girlfriends. Finally, a robber caught Wednesday had the wit to hail
a cab in broad daylight outside the bank he had just robbed.
</P>
<P>
   The first case involved a guy who is accused of robbing his
former employer, a video arcade at Pier 39. The police said Audie
Branagan, 26, tried to rob the Namco Land video arcade on Nov. 21
with another man. Both men wore ski masks. The police said Branagan
tried to conceal his voice so his co-workers would not recognize
him. But his accomplice messed up, Marovich said, and blurted,
``Audie'' during the crime. The robbers then allegedly tried to
strangle the manager because she was a witness. She feigned
unconsciousness, and the robbers fled with the loot, officers said.
</P>
<P>
   It took officers 10 days to find Branagan, who was arrested Dec.
1 when his car ran out of gas after leading the California Highway
Patrol on a high-speed chase.
</P>
<P>
   Branagan told investigators that he only knew that his
accomplice's name was ``Bryan,'' police Inspector Dan Gardner said.
Gardner tried a pager number he found on Branagan's cellular phone.
A man promptly returned the call, reaching Gardner at the Hall of
Justice, Marovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner told him, ``We know all about you, Bryan. You better
turn yourself in.'' The caller quickly hung up. But a minute later
Branagan's cellular phone rang and Gardner answered. Without
realizing that he was talking to the police inspector, the caller
said, ``Audie, the cops know everything. What should we do?''
according to Marovich
</P>
<P>
   Gardner replied: ``I'm the police officer you just spoke to. We
know everything. It would better for you if you just came on in
here on your own.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, 18-year-old Bryan Houston of San Francisco
walked into the Hall of Justice and turned himself in for the Pier
39 robbery, Marovich said. Prior to that, the police had no idea
about his identity and no proof he committed the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like playing poker,'' said Marovich, between hearty
laughs. ``You tell everyone you've got a full house when you really
have a pair of deuces.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days before the arrests of Houston and Branagan, officers
arrested the so-called ``Give It Up'' bandits. Because both
suspects were 17 at the time of the crimes were committed, the
police did not identify the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   They are suspected of 20 muggings in on four different nights in
November. One would wait behind the wheel of a pickup truck while
the other would do the mugging, the police said. Marovich said the
mugger pistol-whipped some of his victims before demanding money.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would just hear footsteps and, bam, this guy would hit
the victim and knock them down,'' Marovich said. ``He beat up
people, especially males, when he didn't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The break came, police said, when the two teens took a cellular
phone that they promptly used to call their respective girlfriends
and other buddies, Marovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors Robert Totah and Bob McMillan traced the calls over
the Thanksgiving weekend and arrested the pair when they returned
to the city from visiting relatives for the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on Wednesday officers arrested a man they believe is a
bank robber dubbed the ``Blonde Bandit.'' Blaine Lippincott, 29,
was taken into custody about 10 minutes after he allegedly passed a
note demanding money to a bank teller at a Washington Mutual bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``He walked outside and got in a cab,'' Marovich said. ``The
teller watched him and got the taxi number: Yellow cab number 999.
Pretty easy for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
