<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TRADE-PACTS18-COX     12-17 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-PACTS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRADE ACCORDS LOST IN FEDERAL BUREAUCRACY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a time when exports have been a key factor in
the U.S. economy and a central theme of the Clinton administration,
the government is having trouble keeping track of its trade
agreements with other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. General Accounting Office, after searching federal
archives, concluded that the records were so incomplete that it
could not tell how many trade pacts the United States now has.
</P>
<P>
   The poor record-keeping hinders the enforcement of the accords,
the GAO warned in a report released this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fully securing the benefits of trade liberalization depends,
in part, on the ability of both private businesses and the public
to quickly and easily access the terms and conditions of the
numerous trade agreements,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that in some cases Congress is not notified of
agreements, as required by law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lack of information on the terms and conditions of these
agreements could impede Congress' oversight efforts to determine
whether trade agreements are being fully implemented,'' the GAO
said.
</P>
<P>
   Trade agreements are the chief means for opening markets and
reducing tariffs for U.S. goods and services abroad. The job of
negotiating them is divided among several federal agencies,
including the U.S. Trade Representative's office and the State and
Commerce departments, each of which keeps its own listing.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, identified 441 trade
accords between 1984 and 1998. But the study added that the actual
total was ``uncertain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Officials at key agencies were unable to provide a definitive
count,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it said some of the information made public about the
pacts has included ``factual errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a draft of the report, the Commerce Department
late last month announced it had begun a periodic review of its
database to add missing agreements and remove obsolete ones.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the House Ways and Means Committee, Greg Crist,
said Friday that the GAO findings ``should serve as a wake-up call,
as we move into next year, to have a detailed account of these
negotiations'' for overseeing trade issues. But he added that the
poor record-keeping was not seen as a cause for major concern by
the committee, which asked for the GAO study.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. exports, which have increased about 70 percent to almost
$700 billion a year since 1990, have been a driving force in the
current economy. However, imports are rising even faster, leading
to a record trade deficit of $25.9 billion for the United States
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
