<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-HOSTAGES (St. Martinville, La.) _ Eight years have passed
since the last desperate cry from Cubans held indefinitely in U.S.
detention facilities as undesirables. But the message, this time
from a handful of Cubans holding hostages in a small parish jail,
is much the same _ they want release from immigration limbo, that
without a shift in U.S.-Cuban relations, they may never escape. By
AMANDO VILLAFRANCA.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-SHUTTLE (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ NASA prepares the shuttle
Discovery for a mission that entails a long-delayed rendezvous to
repair the Hubble telescope. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE-2000 (Nashua, N.H.) _ After trading barbs over such
issues as health care and campaign financing, Vice President Al
Gore and former Senate Bill Bradley go face-to-face tonight for the
first time in seven weeks. By BENNETT ROTH. (The 90-minute debate
begins at 7:30 p.m. EST.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ One of the Holy Grails of personal
computing
</P>
<P>
   has long been voice recognition. Its proponents believe that
it's better to talk to your computer than use that ancient
instrument of torture known as the keyboard. But, hey, don't throw
away that keyboard just yet. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader asks, ``In your ... story
on specifications for shopping for a new computer you mentioned
that buyers should look for a microprocessor that has at least 256
kilobytes of cache. But then you also recommended Intel's Celeron
processor for some buyers, and it only has 128 kb of cache. Does
this mean you advise against a Celeron because it only has 128?''
Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BARLOW-COLUMN (Houston) _ Would you like to go to work without
going to work? Currently, more than 21 million Americans do just
that, although some only part time. We're talking telecommuting.
Using the telephone and a personal computer to work from home. By
JIM BARLOW.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ What it's like to be suddenly
disabled: A Houston man lost his voice in a heart operation and
found that people at work treated him differently. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (`a'' category)
</P>
