<SLUG> BC-TV-MARLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-STAR CAST REMEMBERS MARLEY IN TNT TRIBUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All-star tributes are often awkward affairs, filled with erratic
performances and cocky stars trying to get their faces on TV
because their managers thought it was a good idea. Do they love the
artist being paid tribute? That doesn't always matter, as long as
there's a potential for ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, such is not the case with TNT's ``One Love: Bob
Marley All-Star Tribute,'' a moving tribute in which a high-end
cast of talent _ Lauryn Hill, Tracy Chapman, Jimmy Cliff, Queen
Latifah, Erykah Badu, and others _ recognizes the soul of Marley's
landmark reggae and conveys that passion to the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   In short, no dilettantes allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Not that all the performances on Sunday's two-hour Marley
tribute (airing on TNT at 8 p.m.) are keepers. There are a few
flops, such as Chrissie Hynde's way-too-understated version of
``Waiting in Vain.''
</P>
<P>
   But most stars who ventured to an outdoor stage in Jamaica's
Oracabessa Bay for the taping two weeks ago provide exquisite
versions of Marley's still-relevant blend of social protest tunes,
tender love songs, and spiritual anthems.
</P>
<P>
   On a stage flanked by photos of Marley (who died of cancer in
1981), the stars display their reverence, but also their
interpretative skills, while backed by remnants of Marley's band,
the Wailers, and backup singers, the I-Threes (including his widow,
Rita). Rain starts to fall on the audience, but doesn't dampen
spirits onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Grammy queen Lauryn Hill intones a stirring ``Turn Your Lights
Down Low,'' as husband Rohan Marley (one of Bob's seven children)
spins around her at the end. Reggae pioneer Cliff fixates with
party favorite ``Jammin' '' before Badu brilliantly jazzifies ``No
More Trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The best efforts, though, come from Chapman and Queen Latifah.
The former drops her vaunted shyness and energizes ``Three Little
Birds'' (with its famed ``don't worry about a thing'' chorus), and
Latifah stomps around in bare feet, singing rivetingly about the
``hypocrites and parasites'' in Marley's ``Who the Cap Fits.'' If
there's one lesson from this tribute, it's that Chapman and Latifah
should do a reggae album _ or, better yet, do one together.
</P>
<P>
   Other affecting performances come from Ben Harper (``Get Up,
Stand Up''), Chris Robinson of the Black Crowes (``Kinky Reggae''),
Darius Rucker of Hootie and the Blowfish (an admirable ``War,''
with the great line, ``until the color of a man's skin is of no
more significance than the color of his eyes, then I've got to say
`war' ''), and reggae great Toots Hibbert (``Lively up Yourself'').
</P>
<P>
   The night ends with Ziggy Marley and the Melody Makers firing
through ``Could You Be Loved,'' followed by an ensemble finale of
``One Love.'' No wonder there will also be a concert album and home
video released next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
