<HEADER>
A2053 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-17 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHERS: COMING TO A FOREST NEAR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is slinky, stealthy, handsome, and mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   With equal parts dexterity and daring, it regularly dines on
porcupine and raccoon. An elusive predator, it sees but is rarely
seen, though it can be counted in the thousands. Still, it is large
enough that those who do catch a quick glimpse often mistake it for
a mountain lion.
</P>
<P>
   And, as its population rebounds from being wiped out in this
state at the turn of the century, there will be more sightings.
</P>
<P>
   According to director Matt Laing at the New England Wildlife
Center, one was brought to the clinic two years ago with a broken
leg, after having been hit by a car.
</P>
<P>
   Tom French, assistant director in the Massachusetts Division of
Fisheries and Wildlife, says he saw one in his own neighborhood
near Sturbridge, Mass., and knows of a family, in a suburb north of
Boston that found its black Lab barking at one that was growling
atop the rabbit hutch, pet bunny firmly held in its jaws.
</P>
<P>
   Who is this mystery animal? The fisher, one of North America's
most intriguing predators. The beefy cousin to the marten.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad we don't get to see them more often because they
are beautiful. Martes pennanti is described as a magnificent member
of the weasel family, with a long, slim body and a bushy tail. The
fisher has a thick rich dark chocolate-to-almost-black coat. It's
leonine air has led to the nickname the ``black cat.'' And though
it does get mistaken for a mountain lion, it weighs considerably
less _ only 10 to at most 25 pounds. It's more fox than Simba size.
</P>
<P>
   Still, fishers are impressive. Using strong, thick,
semi-retractile claws, they will rip up the trunk of a small tree
in pursuit of a squirrel and barrel back down, head first. National
Geographic's dusty old ``Wild Animals of North America'' gushes
over their athleticism: ``for their size, by far the swiftest and
most deadly of all forest carnivores . . . able to make astonishing
leaps from tree to tree . . . It is fearless and savage . . . And
worthy of all due respect from antagonists several times its
size.'' But the book, published in 1918, sadly notes that the
animal was fast disappearing from its southern boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   French confirms they are multiplying here as we head into the
next century, with family farms sharply decreasing and woodland _
fisher habitat _ returning.
</P>
<P>
   And though fishers, like coyotes, may snatch a house cat once in
a while, they are not prone to ``mischief,'' according to the old
book and current biologists. For the most part, they don't want to
be near us. (Who can blame them?)
</P>
<P>
   Todd Fuller, professor of wildlife ecology in the Department of
Natural Resources Conservation at the University of
Massachusetts-Amherst, is a fisher intimate. He and a student
worked on a three-year study of the animals, in the north central
area of the state, including the Quabbin Reservoir area.
</P>
<P>
   He found fishers to be fearless opportunists who eat everything
from raccoons to blueberries and apples, though squirrels make up
the biggest part of their diets. (No, you can't have a fisher as a
pet.)
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows why they are called fishers _ they don't eat
much fish. It probably has more to do with a funny translation than
hunting behavior.
</P>
<P>
   And that behavior impresses Fuller. The low-slung carnivores
will come up under a porcupine to get at the quill-less belly in
order to dispatch it. They then basically turn the prey item inside
out, leaving that troublesome hide behind like a child's coat
tossed on the floor. They can do all that, French reports, without
falling victim to a single spine.
</P>
<P>
   He says the fisher is ``a single-minded, cantankerous hunter.''
Fuller can describe the fisher in three words: ``Smart. Adaptable.
Tough.'' Yet he was amazed that during the study, when confronted
by a human hand in their tree hollow dens, mother fishers would
never bite.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Laing, of the New England Wildlife Center, recalls the one
fisher who was successfully treated. It took six weeks for the
aggressive, furious animal's leg to mend. This little fisher never
grew fond of his caretakers and thrashed and growled whenever they
approached.
</P>
<P>
   It's always a happy moment when an animal is returned to the
wild. But in this case, Laing reports, there was extra cheer to see
him go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
