<HEADLINE>
SURFING FOR SANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   'Twas the week before Christmas, when all through the house,
</P>
<P>
   The sole sound you could hear was the click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   New Web sites were accessed in haste but with care,
</P>
<P>
   In hopes that Yule cyber stuff could be found there.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there were hundreds upon hundreds of Christmas
sites, including our 20 favorites, if you'd like to try some
holiday surfing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --How Christmas Works (howstuffworks.com/christmas.htm) _
Answers the pressing questions of the season. Who is this Santa
Claus person? What is it about these fruitcakes? Why are there
oversize socks on your mantel?
</P>
<P>
   --Planet Christmas (planetchristmas.com) _ Dedicated to a home
in Franklin, Tenn., that has 143,268 miniature lights, 6.4 miles of
wire, and 540 computer-controlled lights.
</P>
<P>
   --Dean Clean's Tacky Christmas Light Page
(www.tackychristmas.com) _ Guide to Yuletide tackiness from
California to Florida as seen through the eyes of Mr. Clean, a
resident of Virginia Beach, Va. Includes a certain home in
Franklin, Tenn. Also includes hate mail.
</P>
<P>
   --Les's Christmas Magic: (www.qni.com/lesherm/frames.htm) _ Do
you hear what I hear? More than 100 MIDI files of Christmas songs,
from ``Away in a Manger'' to a karaoke version of ``Grandma Got Run
Over by a Reindeer.''
</P>
<P>
   --Christmas Movies (www.auburn.edu/vestmon/christmasmovie.html)
_ Who says higher education is useless? This Auburn University site
has links to data on more than 125 Christmas movies, including
seven versions of ``A Christmas Carol'' and all five parts of
``Silent Night, Deadly Night.''
</P>
<P>
   --The 12 Days of Christmas Cost Factor (www.pncbank.com/12days/)
_ PNC Bank Corp. calculates the cost, with inflation since 1997, of
purchasing the 12 gifts of the ``Twelve Days of Christmas.'' You'll
wish you'd invested in drummers drumming.
</P>
<P>
   --Santa Claus . . . Ever Wonder? (scifi.com/xmas/) _ This site
includes several conspiracy theories involving Old Saint Nick.
Communist conspiracy? Extraterrestrial intervention? Time travel?
You be the judge.
</P>
<P>
   --Old Jim's Santa Page
(prime-fe2.lvcablemodem.com/oldjim/Chris1.html) _ An odd but
likable series of animated cartoon pages accompanied by music and
created on a homemade computer by 64-year-old James Robertson of
Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   --The Physics of Santa (www.saintnick.org/html/physics.html) _
Q: How does Santa Claus visit 91.8 million households in 31 hours,
covering 73.5 million miles while carrying a payload of 353,430
tons. A: Quickly. It's all explained herein.
</P>
<P>
   --Santa Panic (zoetek.com/entrance/santa/) _ Arcade Christmas: a
low-tech game in which Santa tries to recover his lost head while
avoiding the Easter Egg Hitmen.
</P>
<P>
   --Ultimate Christmas Site
(members.tripod.com/newyearseve/index.html) _ Now in its fourth
year, a potpourri of music, games, and jokes (Why does Santa have
three gardens? So he can ho-ho-ho) created by an Internet design
firm in England.
</P>
<P>
   --Merry Christmas in Many Languages
(spots.ab.ca/ice/jennifer/xmas/language.html) _ Eighty-nine ways to
say ``Merry Christmas and a Happy New Year.'' Vesele Vianoce i na
zdravie v novom roku everyone!
</P>
<P>
   --A Religious Christmas (execpc.com/tmuth/stjohn/xmas) _ Yes,
there's still religion in Christmas, even on the Net. Scripture,
music, arts, and essays all the way from St. John's Lutheran Church
in Brookfield, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   --Reindeer Liberation Front (www.penddraig.co.uk/rlf/ _ Home of
freedom fighters dedicated to the liberation of reindeer from the
oppressive yoke of Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   --Yes, Virgina, There Is a Santa Claus
(barricksinsurance.com/virginia.html) _ Text of the famous 1897
editorial from the New York Sun, written by veteran editor Francis
P. Church, replying to 8-year-old Virginia O'Hanlon. Church's
answer still holds.
</P>
<P>
   --``The Messiah''
(charlene.cyber-crew.com/holidays/messiah.html) _ Music and text of
George Frederic Handel's ``Hallelujah Chorus,'' composed in 1741.
Sing along with your PC.
</P>
<P>
   --Santa Claus Village (claus.com) _ Heavily sponsored site for
kids. Check your naughty or nice rating. Track Santa's journey on
Christmas Eve. Send e-mail to Santa. (We sent him a note two days
ago asking for a 1955 Ford Thunderbird for Christmas and he hasn't
replied.)
</P>
<P>
   --Technical Night Before Christmas
(webpages.marshall.edu/hartwel1/humor/MISC/TECHNICAL
NIGHTBEFORECHRISTMAS.HTML) _ A scientific translation of the poem,
beginning with `` 'Twas the nocturnal segment of the diurnal period
preceding the annual Yuletide celebration. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   --The Grinch Movie Quiz (inkweb.com/grinch/) _ Twenty-three
questions about the classic cartoon. Where does the Grinch live?
How many times does the Grinch get stuck in the chimney? What was
the last thing the Grinch took? Answers via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   --North Pole Weather
(weather.com/holidays/northpole/northpole.html) _ The Weather
Channel's report from up above, which you may want to check on
Christmas Eve. When we looked Friday, conditions were ``cool'':
temperature -17F, wind chill -27F.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
