<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Dec. 19, and thereafter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CATALOG-SHOPPING (New York) _ Catalogs are supposed to be the
answer to our holiday shopping needs. But they turned out to be the
paper equivalent of shops I call close-but-no-cigar stores, where
everything is sort of nice but you don't really want to buy
anything. As it turns out, the most useful catalog I received this
season was from Eddie Bauer Home. I rolled it up and used it to
kill a water bug the size of a Volkswagen. By Frank DeCaro. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEASONAL-PARTY-ANXIETY (New York) _ This year, Millennial Eve
has cranked the Seasonal Party Anxiety (SPA) dial up to 11. It's as
if anyone not popping magnums of Cristal with the right people
(Hillary! Puffy!) and at the coolest place (St. Bart's! Bali!) will
be branded a loser. By Rick Marin.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STORE-SPRITZERS (New York) _ There are other ways emerging to
sell perfume other than using human spritzers. This has, after all,
been called the first big e-Christmas, and Sephora, the
trend-setting French beauty store, where perfumes are arranged
alphabetically for customers to sample on their own, has just
opened its United States flagship with much fanfare in Manhattan.
The success of either or both of these retail channels could
eventually mean an end to spritzers. By Lauren Goldstein. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-PLASTIC-SURGEON (New York) _ Presents wrapped? Check.
Holiday cards sent out? Check. Waistline reduced to fit into dress
for New Year's Eve? Oops. Don't worry, it's not too late. So say
some New York plastic surgeons, who report that they are working
double time this month to help patients look their millennium best.
By Monique P. Yazigi. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-HAPPNER (New York) _ ``Excuse me while I slip into
something a bit more flame-retardant,'' said Ben Heppner, the
Canadian tenor who concluded his role as Tristan in the
Metropolitan Opera's sold-out ``Tristan und Isolde'' with
Saturday's broadcast performance. Speaking to fans at the Canadian
Consulate in Midtown Manhattan on Wednesday night, Heppner was
quoting his own joke from other Wagner operas he has performed
around the world, many of which utilize smoke or fire.
Flame-retardant or otherwise, Heppner, 43, has become a superhero
in operatic circles. By Jeremy Eichler. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Nature has more shades of green than a
super-size box of crayons, for which gardeners ought to be properly
grateful. The blossoms may be what we most covet, but it's the
foliage we most look at _ especially in shady areas, where blooming
plants are hard to come by. By Cass Peterson. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
