A2063 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-POLICE-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      12-17 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLICE ACCUSED OF MURDER TO GET TRIAL OUT OF BRONX 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MELISSA GRACE  
 &HT;     c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A state appeals court has ruled that the trial of
four white police officers accused of murdering a West African
immigrant be moved to Albany, finding that media coverage had made
it impossible to pick an impartial jury in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Coming just three weeks before the trial in the slaying of
Amadou Diallo was set to begin, the rare change-of-venue ruling on
Thursday was hailed by defense attorneys and condemned by
prosecutors and civil rights leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It also left judges in Albany contemplating the possibility they
would preside over one of the most sensational cases of alleged
police brutality in recent history.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we need is a fair jury,'' said Steven Brounstein, the
Queens-based defense attorney representing Officer Kenneth Boss.
</P>
<P>
   Brounstein and three other defense attorneys petitioned an
appeals court in Manhattan in November requesting the change.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 4, Diallo, 22, was unarmed and standing in the vestibule
of his Bronx apartment building when the four officers opened fire
on him, hitting him with 19 of 41 shots. Officers in New York
City's Street Crime Unit had been looking for a rapist-murderer in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   The officers _ Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Richard Murphy and
Boss _ were indicted on second-degree murder counts in March. Each
has pleaded not guilty, saying the shooting was justified. If
convicted, each faces a prison term of 25 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   Bronx District Attorney Robert Johnson, whose office opposed the
move, is considering an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still reviewing the decision,'' said Steven Reed,
Johnson's spokesman. ``We don't know if we can appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed declined to comment further on the case. Johnson's office
will prosecute the case whether it is held in the Bronx or Albany.
</P>
<P>
   In its 11-page decision, the Appellate Division of state Supreme
Court, First Department, said massive media coverage of the event
and demonstrations that followed justified moving the trial, and
sought to relocate it to a county similar to the Bronx. It selected
Albany because it said the county is urban and demographically
diverse _ and because it is closer to New York City than the other
counties that fit that description, Erie, Monroe and Onondaga.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, defense attorneys had argued to have the case
moved because it ``has long been the conventional wisdom among the
legal community in the Bronx that jurors harbor an existing
prejudice against police officers.''
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, juries are largely seen as conservative and willing
to accept the testimony of the police over others. Also, in Albany,
where the African-American population is about 8 percent, the jury
pool is more heavily white than in the Bronx, where blacks make up
42 percent of the residents. Diallo was black, and the officers
accused of shooting him are white.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys had asked the court to move the trial to
Westchester County, which adjoins Bronx County. But the court said
that ``within reasonable limits,'' the community selected must
reflect the community in which the event occurred, and found Albany
more suitable.
</P>
<P>
   The decision took some legal observers by surprise and outraged
the Diallo family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect the rules but it is not fair,'' Katiadou Diallo,
Amadou's mother, told a news conference in Manhattan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trial should take place in the Bronx. ... No family should
suffer the way we have suffered, no family should cry the way we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Diallo's death sparked massive demonstrations and reignited a
debate about racism in the city's police force. More than 1,000
people, including high ranking state officials, were arrested in
the demonstrations, led by the Rev. Al Sharpton. More
demonstrations were expected outside the Bronx courthouse at the
start of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the protesters are likely to converge on Albany, with
perhaps busloads of protesters, and supporters, commuting to
upstate New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
