<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2064 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-SEASONAL-PARTY-ANXIET     12-17 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEASONAL-PARTY-ANXIETY-$ADV19-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY PARTIES SEND SOCIAL ANXIETY SOARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 19)  
(lh) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's time to be bitter _ at least for those of us
prone to the pain of not being invited to swanky Christmas parties
and epic bacchanals ringing in the new year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All parties are held against someone,'' is a line I once heard
attributed to Oscar Wilde. And for sufferers of what might be
called Seasonal Party Anxiety (SPA), December is the cruelest
month.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Millennial Eve has cranked the SPA dial up to 11.
It's as if anyone not popping magnums of Cristal with the right
people (Hillary! Puffy!) and at the coolest place (St. Bart's!
Bali!) will be branded a loser. Posterity's patsy.
</P>
<P>
   The list of Christmas parties passing me by grows longer every
day. And for New Year's Eve, I have been asked nowhere. News of one
Eve event to which I was not invited, a modest affair on the
mid-outer rim of my social circle, induced a flashback to my dark
days as a free-lance writer.
</P>
<P>
   Crazed with cabin fever in my fifth-floor walkup, I felt every
social slight during the holiday season. Hunched over my Powerbook,
I'd fantasize about life in offices. There, I reasoned, amid all
those fancy cubicles and free copy machines, careers were being
made, expense accounts forged, flirtations consummated. I jumped at
every office Christmas bash that came my way and stewed over every
one that didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Was I _ am I _ alone in this madness? Not entirely, it seems.
Diagnosticians of the New York psyche know well the issues of this
notoriously depressed time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Josephson, a psychologist with a private practice on
the Upper East Side, said he has been encountering a lot of
``perfectionistic expectations'' for New Year's Eve. ``I've heard
it a lot,'' he said. ``People are feeling that everyone else is
having a good time, and they will be very self-critical if they're
not invited to this affair or that affair.''
</P>
<P>
   As Dr. Paul Michael Ramirez, a neuropsychologist with a practice
in Westchester County, put it: ``This is a milestone in the history
of the civilization. Imagine sitting at home hearing parties going
on around you. Just thinking about it makes me depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, few people suffering from SPA are willing to admit to
it, at least on the record. They want to maintain a front of
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   But one New York film critic, who asked not to be identified to
preserve his image, confessed to pangs of night-life envy around
this time of year. ``You hear about Christmas parties or you read
about them in the paper, and it always makes one feel worse about
one's life in New York,'' he said. ``It gives me a stab of
self-doubt, like, `Oh, why wasn't I there?''' A fashion publicist
who also requested anonymity has a different beef: reciprocity, or
lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   ``After organizing so many parties, it's always kind of a smack
in the face not to be invited,'' he said. ``I'm so careful about
making sure I get all the right people. I guess I'm not all the
right people.''
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Harper's Bazaar published a list of the right
people from the New York whirl, the ones who are ``Invited
Everywhere.'' I wondered if members of the genetically and
financially advantaged classes might occasionally be stricken with
SPA. If so, then the rest of us commoners need not feel so bad.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the Bazaar list was Serena Altschul, the MTV News
presenter, who grew up on Fifth Avenue. ``I got a stack of
invitations and promptly RSVP'd no to all of them,'' Ms. Altschul
said. Those envelopes included offers to join in the VIP
festivities hosted by Puff Daddy and the Artist Formerly Known as
Prince. ``My problem is usually the inverse: parties I go to that I
wish I hadn't,'' Ms. Altschul said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   True socialites are unlikely to confess to social anxiety, even
if they do feel its sting.
</P>
<P>
   But Ahn Duong, an artist and exotic beauty in high demand, was
willing to acknowledge a chink in her fabulous armor. ``How can you
find the perfect party for the millennium?'' she said. ``That's a
lot of pressure.'' Not so much that she wasn't able to arrive at
the perfect solution: spending New Year's on a yacht off Mustique
and visiting her parents in Paris. Anyway, she added, ``if I really
want to, I can always get invited.''
</P>
<P>
   George Plimpton has been a mainstay of the beau monde for many
decades. Ostracism is for him a distant memory. ``You read about
parties in the papers and think, `Why wasn't I there?''' he said.
``I'm getting over that.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For social alpinists, certain pro-active techniques can increase
the invitation odds. Kristina Stewart, the editor of Quest, says
that many of her readers are not above waging pre-emptive
Christmas-card campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get a card right after Thanksgiving, you know the
person wants to go to your party,'' Ms. Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   But of course, the truly confident don't care. David Koch, the
billionaire known for playing gregarious host at lavish blowouts at
his various houses, is for the first time in 10 years not giving
his annual New Year's Eve party in Aspen, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, people have been calling me up with this sense of
desperation, wondering if I'm having a party and whether they're
invited,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koch and his wife, Julia, have not yet been asked to anyone
else's big New Year's Eve bash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm letting it be known that we are available to be invited
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
