<SLUG> BC-CATALOG-SHOPPING-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF SALES HELP THAT IS HELPFUL, I TURNED TO CYPERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Calif.)   (For release Sunday, Dec. 19)  
(DW) 
 By FRANK DeCARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are 169 catalogs in a box in my foyer and
another 43 in the standing rack in my bathroom. There are still
more mixed in with the hundreds of magazines and newspapers stacked
3 feet high in my living room and bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   We do not call my apartment Collier's Condo for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   They've been arriving at an average rate of four a day since
Oct. 13, when I received 11, threw them in the box with the six I'd
gotten the day before that, and started taking notes. I had always
gotten a lot of catalogs, but this was ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   The first batch included catalogs from San Francisco Music Box
and Gift Co.; Garnet Hill, which bills itself as the Original
Natural Fibers Catalog, and Levenger _ ``Tools for Serious
Readers.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly they have the wrong guy, I thought. I am scared of music
boxes, wear Performance Fleece for day exclusively, and the last
book I actually finished was one I had written, and that was
technically proofreading. But they kept coming. Even one called
Plow and Hearth: Products for Country Living, although I have
neither and my idea of country living is a Hickory Farms cheese
log.
</P>
<P>
   Catalogs like these were supposed to be the answer to our
holiday shopping needs. But they turned out to be the paper
equivalent of shops I call close-but-no-cigar stores, where
everything is sort of nice but you don't really want to buy
anything. As it turns out, the most useful catalog I received this
season was from Eddie Bauer Home. I rolled it up and used it to
kill a water bug the size of a Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   Now I wonder if e-commerce will be any more useful in the long
run. Right now, of course, it's all anyone is talking about. Like
so many other people this holiday season, I spent money on the
Internet. I sent out-of-state chums books from amazon.com. Using a
Web search service that led me to an Oregon bookstore, I found
leftover copies of an out-of-print 1995 book about food fads that I
adore.
</P>
<P>
   I bought black chinos in my size from gap.com. I ordered cookie
cutters from a Web site I read about in Family Circle in my
dentist's waiting room. When no one at the F.A.O. Schwarz stores in
Manhattan and Short Hills, N.J., could find me ``At Home for the
Holidays'' _ a new limited edition magenta-and-lavender hostess
outfit for my Gene doll _ I ordered one from a collectibles
superstore. And I got a 10 percent discount for ordering online.
</P>
<P>
   It arrived from Monroe, Mich., four days later.
</P>
<P>
   With speed and value like that _ not to mention not having to
ask a teen-ager for pants in my waist size _ Internet companies are
making good on the promise that catalogs once held. Like their
paper predecessors, they are geared toward the so-called cash-rich,
time-poor professional. They're re-introducing courtesy back into
the retail experience. Now you click, you type, they wrap, they
send, and then you get a little note saying it's all been taken
care of. That's all any of us want from retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Try getting that from a human being, however. Lately, every time
I speak to a salesperson or catalog operator, I understand the need
for rage management clinics. At a tiny Flatiron district store
specializing in tabletop items, bric-a-brac and novelties, I paid
for my items and asked the clerk to wrap them up. He handed me
colored tissue paper and said I had to wrap them myself, even
though I was on my way to the party at which they were to be
bestowed. I thought, of course, why would you wrap these presents
for your customers? You're only a gift store!
</P>
<P>
   This frustration is all too common nowadays. In a time of
prosperity, when retailers don't have to scramble for your buck,
most of us feel stranded by sales help.
</P>
<P>
   In leaner times, as recently as the early 1990s, service was
being pushed as the top priority of retailers everywhere. Sales
clerks would do a lot for you. Today you can forget that at all but
the toniest retailers.
</P>
<P>
   At any store approaching the mainstream pocketbook, no one seems
to know the answer to anything. An exception: At Restoration
Hardware recently, I asked, ``How many rings does a shower curtain
need?'' Two salesgirls answered ``Twelve!'' in unison. I could have
kissed them both.
</P>
<P>
   In my shopping travels, this is by far the exception. Most of us
have been trained to avoid sales help, whether it's at the
supermarket or a trendy boutique. We know we're not going to get
the help we need, so why disrupt their conversation. This lack of
service is the chief reason we're being drawn into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The pleasure of Internet shopping is not just the smoothness of
the transaction or the vast selection. It's the joy of buying
something without having to talk to a woman whose nail tips are
longer than her attention span or a man whose disposition is about
as steely as his abs.
</P>
<P>
   Now only cyberretailers remember your tastes, sending you an
e-mail that says, ``If you bought the Elvis Costello-Burt Bachrach
CD, you might like this jazz reinterpretation from Bill Frisell.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers have proven they can build beautiful stores _ the new
Terrance Conran Shop at 59th Street and First Avenue beneath the
Queensboro Bridge, for instance, is exquisite. Now if they could
just fill them with sales help who are equally impressive, people
who know the merchandise better than the best shoppers do, we could
all be happy. When they do, I'll throw out my catalogs and put down
my mouse, but not a minute before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
