<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OOPS! INTEL CELERON CACHE WAS OVERSTATED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: In your Dec. 3 story on specifications for shopping for a new
computer you mentioned that buyers should look for a microprocessor
that has at least 256 kilobytes of cache. But then you also
recommended Intel's Celeron processor for some buyers, and it only
has 128 kb of cache. Does this mean you advise against a Celeron
because it only has 128?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oops! Mea culpa. I blew it.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to juggle the various kinds of chips that are out
there _ and users really do have quite a choice _ I got some
specifications crossed.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Celerons have 128 kb of cache, and that's fine for the kind
of users in the first two categories _ novice and basic
home/business users. The Celeron is an excellent bargain _
essentially a Pentium II with less cache. Most users will not
notice the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There's a text file on my computer that I would like to
change, but I am not allowed to change it. When I try, I get told
that this is a ``read-only'' file. What can I do to change it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The way a file is stored on your hard drive is known as its
``attributes.'' A read-only file is one that you can't write to
and, in some cases, you may not be able to delete it.
</P>
<P>
   In bad old MS-DOS days, you had to issue an arcane string of
characters in your command line to change a file's attributes. But
with Windows 95/98, you can do it with the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Find the file you want to change and right-click on it. Choose
``Properties'' from the menu that appears.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of the resulting box, you'll see a series of check
boxes, and one of them will be Read-Only. Uncheck it to be able to
change the file.
</P>
<P>
   You also can change the attributes of all the files in a folder.
Right-click on a folder and choose Properties. If all the files in
the folder are read-only, you'll see the plain,
black-check-on-white-background checkbox you saw in the single
file. But if only some are read-only, the background in the box
will be gray. Click on it until the box is cleared.
</P>
<P>
   What are some of the other checkboxes you see there? The
``Archive'' box allows programs such as backup software to grab
files that are frequently changed. ``Hidden'' is self-explanatory _
it will hide files when you open the folder, but only if your
Folder Options are set up to hide hidden files. ``System'' is to
indicate a file is an important part of the operating system _
don't mess with it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I updated the video drivers for the first time on a new
computer. I watched the process and could see the installer put the
drivers in the windowssystem folder. But when I look in my AOL
download folder, I see the drivers are in there! Are they in both
places? Do I need to leave them or can I delete them?
</P>
<P>
   A: When you download an update package like this, it's often
comprised of a cluster of files that first must be unpacked, then
installed. What you're seeing in the AOL download folder are the
unpacked files.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, a well-written install program will clean up after
itself and delete the files it unpacked. Not all do this. In fact,
some packages merely unpack the files, then leave it to you to
start the installation routine by finding and clicking on a Setup
program.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have the files installed, you should be able to delete
them. Be sure to inspect any instruction or ``read-me'' files
before you do.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been told to use Windows Update to keep Windows 98
files up to date, but I keep getting a message wanting me to
approve downloading something from Microsoft before I continue.
What is this?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a component that automates the process of seeing what's
already installed as part of Windows 98, downloading the patch and
installing it. Don't worry, it's a good thing. Without it, you have
to download these patches and install them manually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
