<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME GO TO WORK BY STAYING HOME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM BARLOW 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Would you like to go to work without going to work?
</P>
<P>
   Currently, more than 21 million Americans do just that, although
some only part time.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking telecommuting. Using the telephone and a personal
computer to work from home.
</P>
<P>
   That 21 million number is up from just 4 million in 1990. The
best guess is that 51 million telecommuters will be out there in
2030.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are from the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics.
However, keep in mind they include everyone who does some work from
home every week, not just full-timers.
</P>
<P>
   Another estimate, from the American Internet User Survey, said
the number of corporate employees who spent at least part of their
time working from home increased from 10.5 million in 1997 to 11.4
million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A third study, by International Data Corp. said currently 23.8
million home offices are used by telecommuters and entrepreneurs,
up from 8.7 million in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the exact figures, all the surveys agree that
telecommuting is growing. A recent survey by the Society of Human
Resource management found that 28 percent of companies are now
letting their employees telecommute, up from 19.5 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ABSENTEEISM CUT IN HALF &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's driving the growth?
</P>
<P>
   _ First there's the plunging cost of equipping home offices. In
1984, the kind of computer needed for business cost $3,995. In
1997, that was down to $999. That's an 83 percent drop in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Or look at cellular phones. When first introduced in 1984, they
had a retail price of between $3,995 and $4,395. Today, you can
pick one up for $120. And it's digital, giving much better service
than the old analog phones.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the number of mobile phone subscribers grew from 11
million worldwide in 1990 to nearly 400 million today.
</P>
<P>
   _ Second is the fact telecommuting is good business. It reduces
absenteeism and improves productivity, says Krishna Kundu of the
Employment Policy Foundation in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Studies by the Gartner Group, a global information technology
consultant, found telecommuting improves productivity by 10 to 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity gains come primarily from two areas. Telecommuters
have more energy. On average, Americans take 22 minutes to
physically commute to work each day. If you are working from home,
you don't have that energy-sapping drive.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommuters also face fewer distractions. The person at the
next desk isn't going to be telling your about his vacation or
showing you the latest pictures of the grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   Having the opportunity to work at home cuts absenteeism in half,
according to a study by the International Telework Council
Association &AMP; Council in October of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that telecommuters could spend a couple of hours
taking care of a family emergency, which would normally keep them
out of the office, than use a home office to get the work done.
</P>
<P>
   _ Third, there's the fact that telecommuting helps business to
hold on to good employees.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Wirthlin Worldwide Survey found that 78 percent of
telecommuters described themselves as ``very committed'' to their
company, vs. only 53 percent of those who went to the office each
day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THERE ARE SOME DOWNSIDES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not every job is suitable to telecommuting. It's most
often used for knowledge workers who use a computer to do their
work.
</P>
<P>
   One downside for the company is the lack of face-to-face
meetings with all employees to keep everyone working together.
Companies that successfully use telecommuting find their managers
have to spend additional time on the phone or talking by e-mail
with those who work at home.
</P>
<P>
   You also lose interaction between employees _ those informal
contacts where conversation leads to problem solving.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of speculation that telecommuting will wind up
solving traffic congestion and air pollution problems by
eliminating most commuting.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Burgess, president of the Denver-based Center for the New
West, says it won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is growing evidence that teleworkers travel more than
those who commute,'' he says. They go shopping, take their kids to
soccer practice and take more-frequent, but shorter vacations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travel is here to stay,'' Burgess believes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
