<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-CROSSINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS MOVES TO EASE STATE BORDER INSPECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With an eye on traffic congestion at
international crossings, the Texas Transportation Commission has
approved the development of eight centralized state inspection
stations at five cities on the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth of commercial truck traffic along the border points
to the need to build these state inspection stations sooner rather
than later,'' commission Chairman David Laney said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But state Sen. Eliot Shapleigh, author of a state law calling
for one-stop state and federal border inspections, voiced
skepticism about the state's move without including federal
agencies, what he called a ``two-stop shop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope someone at TxDOT (the Texas Department of
Transportation) can explain to us on the border how this makes
border commerce more efficient. In Europe, that truck on the
Autobahn barely stops between France and Germany. Are we heading in
the right direction in Texas when we build into the system
essentially two stops?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shapleigh, D-El Paso, said state policy must reduce crossing
times and separate commercial functions from enforcement of drug
and immigration laws.
</P>
<P>
   Laney said the commission supports the one-stop goal but does
not want to wait for the federal government to make a move.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure to act is heightened by the possibility that the border
could be opened wide to Mexican truck traffic under provisions of
the North American Free Trade Agreement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be caught flat-footed,'' he said. ``This
leaves us total flexibility to move to one-stop or two-stop, but it
keeps the thing on track and moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's action authorizes environmental studies, route and
design plans, public involvement, field surveying and acquisition
of rights-of-way. The cost of rights-of-way acquisition is
estimated at $8.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Additional commission action would be needed to start
construction, which could begin as early as 2001. Construction
costs are estimated at $76.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The state stations are to be near international bridges in
Brownsville (Los Tomates and Los Indios), Eagle Pass (Bridge II),
El Paso (Bridge of the Americas and Ysleta-Zaragoza), Laredo
(Bridge IV and Colombia-Solidarity) and Pharr (Pharr-Reynosa).
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the secretary of state's office and Texas
Department of Public Safety said the stations would allow for
faster inspection of a greater number of trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The facilities also would allow for the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission to check for hazardous waste, the Texas
Department of Agriculture to monitor agricultural products, and the
comptroller's office to check fuel permits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1713EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
