<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2094 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-E-COMMERCE18-COX     12-17 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EARLY SIGNS POINT TO BREAKOUT YEAR FOR E-COMMERCE
 &HT;    680&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saturday is likely to be the biggest day in retail
history, with millions of Christmas shoppers spending record
amounts everywhere from small shops on Main Street to glitzy stores
in malls.
</P>
<P>
   But for most online merchants, who typically need a few days to
pick, pack and ship goods, the sales peak passed earlier this week.
Now the cyber-companies must prove they can deliver boxes in the
real world by Dec. 24.
</P>
<P>
   And it appears there are plenty of packages to move.
</P>
<P>
   Based on conversations with electronic merchants, ``we expect
sales to exceed our estimate of $8 billion,'' said Evie Black
Dykema, an e-commerce analyst for Forrester Research Inc., based in
Cambridge, Mass. Last year, holiday sales amounted to $3.5 billion
for online companies, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some extremely optimistic analysts believe sales may even reach
$18 billion. Dykema said accurate figures will not be available
until well into January, when companies finish adding up sales and
subtracting returned merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   But odds are good that online sales soared, considering the
near-jubilant mood of consumers. This fall, the National Retail
Federation, a trade group, had predicted overall holiday sales
would rise about 6 percent from last year. But consumer confidence
is so high that an increase of 7 percent may be more likely,
exceeding projected sales of $183 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While conventional wisdom holds that the Friday after
Thanksgiving is the busiest shopping day of the year, retailers
have found that the Saturday before Christmas is the real whopper.
With the weather expected to be calm over most of the country,
merchants hope to smash one-day sales records.
</P>
<P>
   Those consumers who still want to shop on line do have options,
but not as many as a week ago. ``The fact is, many products are
running out,'' Dykema said, which means e-merchants won't have time
to restock and deliver by Dec. 24. In addition, getting a gift
delivered by Christmas Eve is now likely to require the use of more
expensive express services, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone in cyberspace is closing down the holiday
season yet. For example, America Online, based in suburban
Washington, has compiled a ``Last Minute Gifts'' catalog that
allows procrastinators to choose items guaranteed for pre-Christmas
delivery. Others, such as Toysmart.com, in Waltham, Mass., are
allowing customers to order without any extra delivery charges
until Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts ordered by then will be under the tree Christmas morning,
``barring any acts of God or snowstorms in New England,'' said
company spokesman Paul Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   To allow customers to order so late, Toysmart.com must keep
warehouse staffing levels high. Chris Larivee, a 25-year-old gift
wrapper, said the packing frenzy has workers almost giddy. ``It's
definitely a fun environment,'' he said. ``We're working two shifts
now, with up to 20 wrappers'' per shift.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have started moving their marketing focus to
electronic gift certificates, which can be ordered and delivered
via e-mail, even on Christmas morning.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to make Dec. 25 deadlines will be immense because
of the ferocious competition in cyberspace, according to Irwin
Barkan, chairman of e-Buyersguide.com, an online research firm in
Burlington, Mass. Young companies cannot afford to infuriate
customers. ``If the gift is not there by Wednesday, people are
going to flip out'' and take their business elsewhere next year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the winnowing has begun. Barkan said about 70 percent
of all online shoppers did business through the top 25 sites. Most
of the problems that consumers reported this December, such as Web
site slowdowns, server errors and delivery failures, involved the
smaller, less experienced companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those underperforming companies may not get a second chance next
year. ``There will definitely be a shakeout'' in early 2000,
analyst Dykema said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been a free-for-all,'' with companies spending
vast sums on advertising to attract companies, she said. In
January, accountants will determine whether that spending resulted
in respectable sales. If not, companies will disappear quickly,
leaving only those with strong reputations and brand recognition.
As the herd of e-retailers thins, ``there will be more structure in
the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the number of online merchants may shrink next year,
spending is likely to grow sharply. That's because millions of
Americans are still learning about computer-based shopping, AOL
spokeswoman Julie Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week, 6 million consumers made a purchase for the
first time through AOL, she said. That's more than double the 2.4
million first-time shoppers that AOL attracted during the
comparable week of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people are shopping online'' with each passing
year, she said. As the ranks of competitors shrink, overall service
may improve. ``The thing that differentiate the winners from the
losers will be service,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1718EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2095 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-STORE-SPRITZERS-$ADV1     12-17 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORE-SPRITZERS-$ADV19-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUERRILLAS IN THE MIST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By LAUREN GOLDSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tom Crutchfield stands, on a hectic pre-Christmas
Friday afternoon, as he has for most of the last 15 years, on the
Bloomingdale's main floor. Today he's saying, ``Ferragamo?
Ferragamo?'' to passersby. Two years ago it was, ``Tiffany?
Tiffany?'' And before that, ``Giorgio Beverly Hills?''
</P>
<P>
   Formerly a cruise director, Crutchfield, 49, is bemused, rather
than annoyed, by the throbbing dance music coming from the nearby
MAC counter. He doesn't mind that a dancer in a midriff-bearing top
and a micro-miniskirt is distracting potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   And after a decade and a half of this, he is accustomed to the
throngs of stony-faced consumers who don't bother to look up at him
as they fight their way to the center of the store.
</P>
<P>
   He stands, focused and calm and, yes, happy, in his official
black Bloomingdale's blazer, bottle and blotter cards in hand,
repeating his mantra: ``Ferragamo? Ferragamo?''
</P>
<P>
   When customers stop, it's more often to ask, ``Where are the
pants?'' or ``Where's the exit?'' than, ``Does it come with a
gift?'' With the patience of a man used to constant rejection, he
offers directions and then, again, asks, ``Would you care to try
...'' More often than not, they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Crutchfield estimates that of the 400 people he may speak to on
a given day, only a dozen or so will actually buy.
</P>
<P>
   There are other ways of selling perfume. This has, after all,
been called the first big e-Christmas, and Sephora, the
trend-setting French beauty store, where perfumes are arranged
alphabetically for customers to sample on their own, has just
opened its U.S. flagship with much fanfare in Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   The success of either or both of these retail channels could
eventually mean an end to spritzers like Crutchfield. Are he and
his kind part of a doomed breed?
</P>
<P>
   During these peak preholiday days, there are some 150 spritzers
working the main floor of Bloomingdale's. Finely tuned recording
equipment could separate out more than 100 brand names being
chanted over the din of shoppers streaming in from Lexington Avenue
and 59th Street _ Shalimar, CK, Givenchy, DKNY, Angel. There are 30
more spritzers working heavy traffic areas throughout the store's
nine selling floors _ Bulgari, Contradiction, Emporio, Cartier.
</P>
<P>
   But just blocks away, at Sephora, there are no spritzers, no
ladies in lab coats. ``It's an easy selling environment,'' said
Betsy Olum, the vice president for marketing at Sephora. ``It's not
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not be aggressive, but spritzers and department stores
are finding it to be the scariest development in beauty retailing
to come along in years. Sephora is ``going to give the department
stores a real battle for the young consumer,'' said Laurie Palma,
the vice president for fragrance marketing at Chanel.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year there will be 50 Sephora stores
throughout the country. Eventually there will be some 200 in urban
centers and suburban malls, all priding themselves on a hands-off
policy that frees customers from high-pressure sales.
</P>
<P>
   And for customers who really can't stand human interaction,
there's yet another option: the Internet. New beauty sites are
emerging nearly as quickly as new fragrances: Beauty.com, Eve.com,
Beautyjungle.com., Toofaced.com. The most recent cosmetics survey
by the NPD Group, a market researcher company, found that less than
1 percent of beauty sales were made online, but that was back in
June. Like makers of almost every kind of consumer product, perfume
marketers are watching the Internet closely.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than predict the demise of spritzers, cosmetics
companies insist that they are what will help department stores
hold their own against self-service upstarts like Sephora or the
Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a customer is really in a rush, they'll probably buy
online,'' Ms. Palma said. ``If they're in a store, they want the
show. They'll be more receptive to service, because that's what
they want. That's what they're there for.''
</P>
<P>
   Camille McDonald, the president of Givenchy Perfumes, said
because her company does not have the marketing budget of, say, a
Calvin Klein, it puts more emphasis than most on spritzers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``As stores strip counter space and salespeople, the only
informed service is provided by our ladies,'' she said. ``We will
never abandon them as our No. 1 spend.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one has yet figured out how to give an online
customer a sample spritz of a perfume. One site, Gloss.com, is
attempting to overcome this barrier through heavy doses of
product-sample mailings and an online quiz that asks customers to
identify their favorite fruit and favorite season as a means to
pinpoint fragrances that they might like.
</P>
<P>
   Deanna Kangas, a founder of Gloss.com, acknowledges that even
though shoppers frequently grouse about ambush spritzing, the
technique is successful. ``When you walk up and spray someone, it's
offensive,'' she said, ``but you do get bigger sales numbers with
consultants.''
</P>
<P>
   Crutchfield isn't really worried: ``A lot of the things you can
get at Bloomingdale's, you can get at other stores. What is going
to make the difference is the way we treat our guests,'' he said of
his customers. Ten days after he makes a sale, he calls his
customers to see ``how the fragrance is working,'' he said. Thirty
days, he calls again. Just to check in.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety days, another call _ this one asking if there's anything
else they need. ``I have people who have been shopping with me for
15 years,'' Crutchfield said. And, as if on cue, one of his
longtime customers appeared to get his opinion about which tie she
should buy for her dentist. She took the blue one _ and a $75
Tiffany gift set he was offering.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Crutchfield nor most of the other perfume sales
representatives at Bloomingdale's actually work for the store, even
though they all wear Bloomingdale name tags. Not the ones spritzing
customers, not the ones ringing up sales, not the ones giving
directions to confused shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomingdale's requires that each cosmetic company staff its own
counter and pay for its own displays. Crutchfield, for instance,
works for Fragrances Exclusive Inc., a division of Chanel that
distributes Ferragamo, Bulgari and Tiffany perfumes. He is the
manager for the Ferragamo brand, and as such he selects the scores
of free-lancers who make $15 to $18 an hour spritzing from the FEI
``outposts'' throughout the store _ plus bonus incentives, often in
cash.
</P>
<P>
   What does it take to be a successful spritzer? Aside from good
aim and a high tolerance for (per)fumes, the most valuable asset is
simply an ability to put others at ease. Aminata Ndiaye, currently
stationed outside the Ralph Lauren boutique, started working at
Bloomingdale's 10 years ago to earn money for graduate school. Put
in the basement and told to sell $300 her first day, Ms. Ndiaye
cleared four times that amount and became a store legend.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for the secret of her success, Ms. Ndiaye, 35, said, ``A
lot of people in New York, they need someone to talk to.'' Early
last week, she recalled, a customer stopped outside her station and
declared: ``It's Hanukkah, and I don't have any presents, and my
husband is going to ditch me if I come home without gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in Bloomingdale's,'' Ms. Ndiaye said she replied.
``There's plenty to choose from.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ndiaye and the customer left the sales floor to have a
cigarette together, and Ms. Ndiaye heard all about the woman's
husband and children. When the customer came back to Ms. Ndiaye's
station, she spent $1,500 on perfumes for her family.
</P>
<P>
   Try making that sale on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1719EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-E-COMMERCE18-COX     12-17 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EARLY SIGNS POINT TO BREAKOUT YEAR FOR E-COMMERCE
 &HT;    680&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
