</P>
<P>
   But not everyone in cyberspace is closing down the holiday
season yet. For example, America Online, based in suburban
Washington, has compiled a ``Last Minute Gifts'' catalog that
allows procrastinators to choose items guaranteed for pre-Christmas
delivery. Others, such as Toysmart.com, in Waltham, Mass., are
allowing customers to order without any extra delivery charges
until Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts ordered by then will be under the tree Christmas morning,
``barring any acts of God or snowstorms in New England,'' said
company spokesman Paul Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   To allow customers to order so late, Toysmart.com must keep
warehouse staffing levels high. Chris Larivee, a 25-year-old gift
wrapper, said the packing frenzy has workers almost giddy. ``It's
definitely a fun environment,'' he said. ``We're working two shifts
now, with up to 20 wrappers'' per shift.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have started moving their marketing focus to
electronic gift certificates, which can be ordered and delivered
via e-mail, even on Christmas morning.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to make Dec. 25 deadlines will be immense because
of the ferocious competition in cyberspace, according to Irwin
Barkan, chairman of e-Buyersguide.com, an online research firm in
Burlington, Mass. Young companies cannot afford to infuriate
customers. ``If the gift is not there by Wednesday, people are
going to flip out'' and take their business elsewhere next year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the winnowing has begun. Barkan said about 70 percent
of all online shoppers did business through the top 25 sites. Most
of the problems that consumers reported this December, such as Web
site slowdowns, server errors and delivery failures, involved the
smaller, less experienced companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those underperforming companies may not get a second chance next
year. ``There will definitely be a shakeout'' in early 2000,
analyst Dykema said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been a free-for-all,'' with companies spending
vast sums on advertising to attract companies, she said. In
January, accountants will determine whether that spending resulted
in respectable sales. If not, companies will disappear quickly,
leaving only those with strong reputations and brand recognition.
As the herd of e-retailers thins, ``there will be more structure in
the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the number of online merchants may shrink next year,
spending is likely to grow sharply. That's because millions of
Americans are still learning about computer-based shopping, AOL
spokeswoman Julie Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week, 6 million consumers made a purchase for the
first time through AOL, she said. That's more than double the 2.4
million first-time shoppers that AOL attracted during the
comparable week of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people are shopping online'' with each passing
year, she said. As the ranks of competitors shrink, overall service
may improve. ``The thing that differentiate the winners from the
losers will be service,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
