<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2098 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-HOLIDAY-PLASTIC-SURGE     12-17 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-PLASTIC-SURGERY-$ADV19-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOLIDAY RUSH TO SCHEDULE PLASTIC SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 19)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Presents wrapped? Check. Holiday cards sent out? Check.
Waistline reduced to fit into dress for New Year's Eve? Oops.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, it's not too late. At least, so say some New York
plastic surgeons, who report that they are working double time this
month to help patients look their millennium best.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons are getting desperate phone calls like the one Dr.
Lloyd Hoffman, a chief of plastic surgery at New York Presbyterian
Hospital, received the other day from a woman, 35, who suddenly
realized she couldn't squeeze into the ball gown she planned to
wear to a New Year's Eve party.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted her abdomen suctioned to fit the tight waistline,''
said Hoffman, who has scheduled the procedure for this week.
</P>
<P>
   Another patient, 24, actually brought a dark red dress with a
drop waist and a flare skirt to Dr. Helen Colen's Park Avenue
office. Why? To show the doctor where it didn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had to have the liposuction done in her hips immediately
because she HAD to wear that dress on New Year's Eve,'' said Dr.
Colen, who performed the work last week.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that you could roll a bowling ball through the
surgical suites of plastic surgeons in December without hitting a
soul. But on the eve of the millennium, thanks to a new generation
of quick procedures, new treatments that speed healing and patients
who want to jump-start their New Year's resolutions, doctors in New
York say they are heavily booked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one woman who pleaded with me to have surgery on Sunday,
so she could look her best for the New Year,'' said Dr. Carroll
Lesesne, a plastic surgeon in private practice, who was looking
drowsy at a Park Avenue holiday party last Monday, after working
many hours the day before. He had performed a facelift, eyelid work
and a nose-tip modification on the woman. While he would not reveal
the price, other than to say it was ``somewhere over $15,000'' he
related that his patient was so eager that she promised to make it
well worth his efforts. ``She did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dolores Laun, a data-entry clerk from the Bronx, who was waiting
in Dr. Thomas Romo's office on Fifth Avenue last Thursday, said her
decision to have plastic surgery was ``spur of the moment.'' She
said: ``I wanted to look great for the year 2000. I have a lot of
friends, and I like to go out, and I'm having a big party New
Year's Eve.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Laun, 52, who works part-time in Romo's office, had an
endoscopic brow lift (a procedure done through small incisions in
the scalp), fat pads removed from her lower eyelids and a chin
implant. While the first two procedures took two weeks to heal, the
latter, performed in November, took three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look like I'm 35,'' Ms. Laun said. ``I'm ready for the
millenium.'' The cost to be ready: $12,000, part of which she is
working off in the doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   No figures exist for plastic surgery performed each month, but
in recent years quick fixes like Botox injections and minor
liposuction have become the most popular cosmetic procedures
nationwide. In 1998, chemical peels of the face were the most oft
performed procedure, followed by collagen injections, with
liposuction No. 4 and Botox No. 6, according to the American
Society for Aesthetic Plastic Surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Fritz Barton, the society's president, understands the rush
for year-end self-improvement. ``People become more
appearance-conscious when they have important events occurring,''
he said. ``It's part of getting prepared to look good in a
particular time in your life. Just like wanting something new to
wear.''
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned against impulsiveness and unrealistic
expectations. ``You can't just do a procedure the day before and
look great the next day,'' he said. ``Most procedures need at least
two weeks to heal and sometimes three or four.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some patients clearly have come to view a visit to the
plastic surgeon as similar to an appointment with the hairdresser,
and some doctors seem to encourage them. ``You can walk in the
door, have Botox injections all over your face, have your driver
waiting and be on the plane in an hour,'' said Dr. Alan Matarasso,
a Park Avenue plastic surgeon, adding that he has never been busier
in the month of December before. In addition to Botox and collagen
injections _ so that wrinkles will not appear in holiday and
society-page pictures _ his patients are seeking quickie eyelid
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyelids heal faster than any other procedure on the body,''
Matarasso said. ``You can have an operation on Thursday and maybe
with a little cover-up go out on a Saturday night.'' But Joan Kron,
who has been both a patient of cosmetic eye surgery and is the
author of ``Lift: Wanting, Fearing, and Having a Facelift''
(Viking, 1998), called Matarasso's time frame ``overly
optimistic.'' Sometimes, she said, the healing can take three to
four weeks. ``You can't always predict the bruising,'' Ms. Kron
said. ``Sometimes it's a function of your biology, the thickness or
thinness of your skin, whether you had an aspirin on that day.''
</P>
<P>
   For women with visions of low-cut dresses in their heads,
doctors reported that they are performing breast lifts
(repositioning the breast for a more youthful look) and
ever-popular breast implants. While a lift takes about one to two
weeks to heal, according to Matarasso, implants can allow a patient
to ``come in on Monday and by the weekend you won't be at the gym,
but you'll be going out.'' (That is, if you avoid painful
swelling).
</P>
<P>
   Some plastic surgeons are uneasy with people viewing surgery as
the answer to a fashion emergency. Dr. Bryan Forley, who is in
private practice on Fifth Avenue and is the resident plastic
surgeon at the new Soho Integrative Health Center, said he
discourages patients seeking liposuction just before a St. Bart's
vacation or a big night out.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than having plastic surgery to fit into a ball gown, he
said, he would encourage patients ``to make a New Year's resolution
that will help them to maintain the ability to fit into that ball
gown next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise advice, perhaps. But Ms. Kron said this year, in
particular, it is likely to be ignored. ``There'll be a lot of
people in dark glasses and tight girdles on New Year's Eve,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
