<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ELECTRONICS-STORES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONICS STORES CITED IN CRACKDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ City officials are moving to shut down two
electronics stores in midtown Manhattan and fine 15 others
throughout New York, accusing them of illegal business practices
like mispricing stock, overcharging credit cards and lying about
the quality of merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The citations follow a six-month investigation in which consumer
affairs agents visited the stores posing as customers. The
investigation came after a long history of complaints from
customers, and particularly foreign tourists in the cases of
Photokina Limited and Audio Photo International, the two midtown
stores. Most of the other 15 shops are charged with selling
refurbished goods as new merchandise, a crime that has become a
major problem among electronics retailers, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many people, part of a tour of New York is taking
advantage of the fantastic shopping opportunities,'' said Jules
Polonetsky, the commissioner of the Department of Consumer Affairs.
``Unfortunately, these stores were turning the holiday shopping
experience to holiday horror for many visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Audio Photo, for example, tourists from England,
Norway and Germany complained to the consumer affairs department
that they had been tricked into signing credit card receipts for
more than twice the agreed-upon prices. An Irish visitor complained
that he had been sold a video camera that did not work in his
country after being told the opposite. And a Belgian sightseer told
the agency that while buying a laptop computer and portable CD
player, he was charged about three times the manufacturer's
suggested retail price, which was never posted.
</P>
<P>
   New York electronics retailers are required by law to post the
suggested retail price for goods that are being sold for more than
that amount. Stores also must mark all electronics items with the
sale price, which some of the cited retailers failed to do,
Polonetsky said. In some cases, he added, stores charged customers
for accessories like batteries that manufacturers package free with
the merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Both Photokina and Audio Photo are threatened with losing their
licenses because of a long history of breaking consumer-protection
laws, officials said. Since 1991, both have been cited by the
Consumer Affairs Department for multiple violations. In 1997, the
agency fined Audio Photo more than $15,000 and Photokina more than
$7,000, and both signed agreements saying they would comply with
consumer laws.
</P>
<P>
   But since 1998, the department has received about 35 complaints
from tourists shopping at the two stores, officials said. The
stores, whose president is listed on license applications with the
department as Eli Zarif, are scheduled for a consumer-affairs
hearing on Jan. 24. They could have their licenses revoked and be
fined up to $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they would also seek to bar the store owners from
applying for future consumer licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do this to us every year with no reason,'' said Richard
Zibi, an Audio Photo manager, referring to the charges. ``Listen,
you cannot please every customer. A few people get upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Zibi said the store had received eight customer complaints this
year and had responded to all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Photokina did not return calls asking for comment.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 electronics stores are licensed by the Department of
Consumer Affairs, which received about 800 complaints against
electronic retailers last year. The other 15 stores charged in the
investigation have been issued more than 400 violations. Last
month, Palace Electronics, a well-known Brooklyn retailer found
guilty of several violations, was forced to shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stores give a very black eye to New York's shopping
reputation for many many tourists,'' Polonetsky said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
