<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING TO HEART OF MAN'S DISABILITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Most of us don't know what it's like to be disabled.
Jim Kollaer didn't either _ until he lost his voice after
undergoing heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   That would be bad enough for most of us, but Kollaer makes his
living by communicating. He is president and chief executive
officer of the Greater Houston Partnership, the city's biggest
business association, and as part of his job he negotiates,
persuades and lobbies. He is a leader, and leaders generally need
to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Kollaer had to listen from the sidelines as his
subordinates or volunteers from the board made presentations and
speeches for him.
</P>
<P>
   He no longer could interject comments or reroute the discussion
to a new direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``My talent is being able to think on my feet and communicate
those thoughts,'' Kollaer said recently over lunch. ``I couldn't
tell jokes, I couldn't make snide remarks, and it was hard to tell
someone you love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing that power to speak also caused Kollaer to lose some of
his power. He started getting left out of the loop when the only
way he could contribute was to listen, nod his head, wave his hand
or bang his fist on the table.
</P>
<P>
   A voice seems so matter-of-fact _ people just assume everyone
has one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HEART SURGERY STARTS PROBLEM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kollaer's voice problems began after he had a heart operation in
April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, he couldn't speak for three weeks, but his voice
returned and Kollaer chalked up the temporary loss to the swelling
of his vocal cords during the eight-hour operation.
</P>
<P>
   But seven months later, Kollaer lost his voice again when he
came down with a cold.
</P>
<P>
   And this time it didn't appear to be temporary.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that one of Kollaer's vocal cords was nicked
during the heart surgery and was no longer working.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a year, Kollaer couldn't talk above a whisper. And
there were periods when he couldn't speak at all.
</P>
<P>
   He did the best to cope by carrying around a child's Magna
Doodle with him to scribble notes and handing people cards that
explained he couldn't speak. But Kollaer wasn't ready for the
reactions he encountered.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes people whispered back, he said. Other times, people
assumed he couldn't hear so they'd shout at him.
</P>
<P>
   Or they just ignored him, assuming that if he couldn't speak, he
couldn't hear either. When Kollaer revealed to a car salesman that
he couldn't speak, the salesman spoke only to Kollaer's 15-year-old
son, Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``He acted like I wasn't even there,'' Kollaer said.
</P>
<P>
   It was also getting difficult to keep working as the head of the
Partnership. Board members never said anything directly. But when
you go to so many board meetings and you can't make the
presentation, you can feel it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The situation came to a head when Kollaer tried to eke out a
speech at a Houston luncheon in the fall and could hardly croak out
a few words.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Kollaer thought he could control it _ that if he
just got closer to the microphone, people could hear him. But after
the disastrous Houston 100 speech, Kollaer told his team that was
his last. He gave himself to the end of the year to get his voice
back.
</P>
<P>
   He also began to consider his life and what he had been missing.
Slowly, Kollaer uncovered a whole new side of himself and began to
take time to write in his journal, paint and go to art museums.
</P>
<P>
   He also started thinking about other career options that didn't
require a voice. He used to be in real estate, but that was out
because talking is too important in cutting deals. For a while he
considered returning to work as an architect.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe he could become a writer. ``I thought if Stephen
Hawking could find a way to communicate, I could too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GOOD COMES FROM MISFORTUNE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before he got too far along in a career change, Kollaer got his
voice back. It returned as quickly as it disappeared when he woke
up Nov. 3 with the ability to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Medically, the explanation is that an ulcer on one of the vocal
cords finally cleared up and the working vocal cord picked up the
slack. Or it may be otherworldly.
</P>
<P>
   Kollaer has become more spiritural as a result of what happened.
</P>
<P>
   During lunch he pulled a card out of his pocket that said: ``I
found I had less and less to say until finally I became silent and
began to listen. I discovered in the silence the voice of God.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
