<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2114 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-RAGE19-COX     12-17 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAGE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rage reconsidered: Message and muscle
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 19.
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1993, when the band got a career-launching break touring with
Lollapalooza, Rage Against the Machine came off as an outfit of
callow hell-raisers. With its crunchy rhythms and searing electric
guitar, the band had no problem getting the mostly under-25 crowd
bounding up and down all over the dirt field in suburban New
Jersey, where I first saw Rage, but there was also something really
silly about the group.
</P>
<P>
   Vocalist Zack de la Rocha, dreadlocks flapping like Bob Marley's
as he threw his spindly frame to and fro like a leaping dolphin,
went on a long tirade about concert T-shirts and his record company
and how everyone needed to rage along with him about grievances
that seemed petty and ephemeral. Guess the man was holding him
down, but the really great rock bands that have made agit-prop and
revolutionary rhetoric part of their game plan _ think of the Clash
in the late 1970s or the Minutemen in the mid-1980s _ never got
hung up on the small stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Rage is on tour with a new album, its third and
best, called ``The Battle of Los Angeles.'' The group already
weathered the battle of Woodstock '99, where its constituency raged
against the automatic teller machines, and where it found itself at
a specific point in the contemporary rock continuum. While white,
rap and funk-influenced acts like the Beastie Boys and the Red Hot
Chili Peppers have made varying (and varyingly sincere) efforts to
achieve and preach a reformed bad boy enlightenment, the artists
Spin magazine recently denounced as ``rap-rock mooks'' _ Fred Durst
of Limp Bizkit is taking most of the heat _ have taken over the
charts, promoting old-school misogyny and the bratty thrills of a
self-involved adolescent response to the usual frustrations. Rock
'n' roll!
</P>
<P>
   Musically, at least, Rage is a major influence on this school,
which has, at times, been as innovative in expanding the frontiers
of mainstream rock (deconstructing sonic conventions with weird
noise, basically) as it's been retrograde in reclaiming the inner
caveman. But, as the group showed during its recent performance at
Atlanta's Philips Arena, that's where the comparisons end.
Guitarist Tom Morello suggests they occupy nose-bleed seats in the
arena built by the MC5, Marley and Public Enemy _ three very
different performers for whom social protest was a common
touchstone _ yet, Rage is clearly coming into its own. Morello
commands a fierce economy on his instrument, slung high on his
chest as if he were Wes Montgomery, while seeming to be two
musicians at once: He gets all the gonzo noise-bursts that hip-hop
DJs and art-rock dudes like the guys in Sonic Youth specialize in,
while conjuring the ghosts of every great '60s power trio that ever
existed. Mostly, the Jimi Hendrix Experience and Cream. Not
slavishly, either, but in the way a pianist might think of
Thelonious Monk or Bill Evans while playing his own thing. When it
works, it's titanic and primal and stunningly confounding. At last,
a technician with heart.
</P>
<P>
   Propelled by a rhythm section as limber as it is muscular, de la
Rocha has become a vastly more effective rapper. He still dolphins
like crazy around the stage _ you'd think he invented Flubber _ but
lyrically he's more grounded. Tracks such as ``Testify'' and
``Guerrilla Radio'' dig deeper than bumper-sticker sentiment,
reaching for a more complicated play of rhymes and images while
targeting the devils we know (the media, multinational
corporations, guns vs. butter) and stepping up the insurgent
message. Despite de la Rocha's very cool self-defense advisory to
the women in the mosh pit on the arena's general admission floor,
it's rousingly masculine music. The message can easily be swallowed
by the medium, though the energy it unleashes in the crowd is
thrilling. Rage fans dance like it's high-impact aerobics: fists
pumping and swirling, bodies bounding in place, hips locked into a
groove. None of that twirly dervish business you see at Dave
Matthews concerts, which are anesthesia by comparison. Hate to drop
a tired buzz word, but, yeah, it's empowering. And it's only one
part of another continuum, which includes socially conscious
entertainers like Atlanta's Indigo Girls and Nashville's Steve
Earle and Bruce Springsteen (whose ``The Ghost of Tom Joad'' was
taken by Rage and exploded into a million tiny bits) and Ani
DiFranco _ people who actually try to say something in their songs,
rather than angling for a gossip column glamour shot with the Dalai
Lama.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to like the songs. You don't have to like the
message. But when those two things meet successfully, you have to
listen. As a wise man once said, when the ship is sinking you've
got to go overboard. Bands like Rage Against the Machine are
leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
