<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2115 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WALTONS-CD19-COX     12-17 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALTONS-CD19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV's Walton clan `Together Again' in Christmas reunion album
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 19.
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If anyone were to ask me where I would most like to spend
Christmas this year, the answer would be simple: at the Waltons.'
</P>
<P>
   Since 1971, when the made-for-TV movie ``The Homecoming'' first
aired on CBS, the fictitious Blue Ridge Mountain family with all
those double names has become the essence of what Christmas is
supposed to be, at least if you grew up in the rural South: strings
of popcorn, red blooms on a Christmas cactus, cracking black
walnuts, trudging deep into the woods to pick out a tree, placing a
bird's nest on its branches. For millions of fans, the frame house
with its sit-a-spell porch and long family dinner table stirs deep
holiday longings, a place where gritty reality _ job stress, broken
families _ dissolves into fantasies of sipping hot chocolate with
Grandma and swapping homemade gifts.
</P>
<P>
   This year, fans can get even closer to Walton's Mountain, thanks
to country songwriter Bruce Burch. A Gainesville native who now
heads EMI's publishing division in Nashville, Burch brought the
whole cast together for a reunion recording called ``A Walton's
Christmas: Together Again.'' It features 19 tracks of Christmas
song standards, warm-fuzzy recitations and chitchat among the
actors, right down to the mandatory bedtime mantra, ``Good night,
'Liv. ... Good night, John. ... Good night, Grandma. ... Good
night, Erin. ... Good night, Ben.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect anything polished. The music is a folksy blend of
sentiment and song that captures the clannish camaraderie of the
show, from John-Boy (Richard Thomas) reading ``The Night Before
Christmas'' to group sing-alongs that sound kind of like the sweet
rawness of the old ``Hee Haw'' Gospel Quartet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is true to the spirit of the characters on the
show,'' explains Jon Walmsley, who played the gangly Jason Walton
and who produced the album and recruited his co-stars for the
project. ``The idea is an evening at the Waltons' at Christmastime
with everyone swapping stories. ... We did the cast vocals in L.A.,
and it turned into a big, festive party atmosphere. We're such good
friends that everyone went along with it enthusiastically.''
</P>
<P>
   As the only musician in the cast, Walmsley provides most of the
vocals and plays guitar. He co-wrote five original songs and gave
the album a bluegrass-country feel on such familiar tunes as
``Christmas Time's a Comin','' ``Sleigh Ride'' and ``Have Yourself
a Merry Little Christmas.'' In his soothing Virginia dialect,
familiar narrator and ``Waltons'' creator Earl Hamner Jr. reads an
original holiday piece written specifically for the record. Jerry
Goldsmith's infectious ``Walton's Theme'' has been redone as a
fiddle tune. There's even a song about ``Mama's Applesauce Cake,''
and the liner notes include the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   The album is dedicated to Will Geer (Grandpa), who died in 1978,
and Ellen Corby (Grandma), who died in April while her younger
co-stars were recording the album.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Walton ``kids'' are middle-aged now, but Burch
believes their fictitious family endures because ``they may be the
last of that kind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In this day and time, there's just not much family
entertainment,'' he says. ``Families today are `The Simpsons' or
`Married ... With Children.' `The Waltons' was the last show that
actually dealt with the traditional family. Think about what's
going on here at the millennium. Look at all the broken families,
Columbine. People may never get back to those traditional values in
reality, but in spirit they would like to.''
</P>
<P>
   More things Walton
</P>
<P>
   If watching ``The Homecoming'' or popping ``A Walton's
Christmas'' into the CD player don't have you smelling Papa's
Recipe, check out these other routes to Walton's Mountain:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Walton's Mountain Museum: The real John-Boy, writer
Hamner, grew up in the tiny mountain hamlet of Schuyler, Va. The
family home is still there. (Hamner's brother James, aka Jim-Bob,
lives there.) Across the street, the community's elementary school
has been converted into a Waltons museum. Curators have
reconstructed sets from the show, including the family's 1930s-era
living room and John-Boy's bedroom with writing desk. You can buy
souvenirs, such as T-shirts, videotapes and pages from original
scripts, in the Ike Godsey Store and Gift Shop. Located on Va. 617
between Charlottesville and Lynchburg, the museum is open 10 a.m.-4
p.m. daily from the first Saturday in March through the last Sunday
in November. Admission: $5 adults, $4 senior citizens, children
under 12 free. For information, call 804-831-2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Web site: In the early 1990s, Ralph Griffin, 57, recovered
from a heart attack by watching reruns of ``The Waltons'' every
night. He says he became fascinated with the show, archiving every
episode ``because I grew up in a home like that, a simplistic life
that I identified with.'' Griffin eventually created a detailed
Waltons Web site at www.the-waltons.com. It includes descriptions
of every episode, a complete list of guest stars and characters,
fan club information, biographies of all cast members, pictures of
the real Hamner family, theme music, sound clips from shows, a
Waltons chat room and a calendar of Waltons-related events.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The documentary: ``The Waltons Legacy'' is a one-hour 1997
video that looks at the history of the Schuyler area, the Hamner
family and ``The Waltons'' television series. Originally produced
by WVPT public television in Harrisonburg, Va., it's available for
$24.95. To order, call 540-434-5391.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Waltons cruise: ``Waltons'' cast members often travel with
fans as part of vacation packages. The most recent outing was a
$500 excursion to the Bahamas with Mary McDonough (Erin), Judy
Norton (Mary Ellen), Walmsley (Jason) and Eric Scott (Ben). You can
find future events posted at www.the-waltons.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The television series: Reruns air on The Nashville Network at
1 and 7 p.m. Mondays-Thursdays and 1 p.m. Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Homecoming'' video: May be ordered through
www.amazon.com for $9.98. Amazon also offers several episodes of
the television series.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Walton's Christmas: Together Again'': The CD may also be
ordered through www.amazon.com for $12.99.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
