<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2116 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGION-ENDTIMES19-C     12-17 1692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-ENDTIMES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With 2000 just around the corner, predictions about the end
times abound
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yellow type, outlined in red, screams from the cover of the
supermarket tabloid the Weekly World News: ``ARE WE ON THE EVE OF
JUDGEMENT DAY?''
</P>
<P>
   Below it is a warning that the prophecies detailed within
(alongside articles about a refrigerator exorcism and a chihuahua
who survived being flushed down the toilet) may be ``terrifying.''
The sensational supermarket publication is one in a plethora of
media, from National Public Radio to Newsweek, devoting time and
space to end times in the waning days of the 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   As Christians mark the season of Advent leading up to a
celebration of what they believe was the incarnation of the
messiah, some are anticipating Jesus' imminent return to Earth. A
1997 Associated Press poll showed that nearly one of every four
Christian adults _ some 26.5 million Americans _ expect Jesus to
come back during their lifetimes. Almost 40 percent say he will
arrive by the end of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas story is replete with pictures of a sweet baby in
a manger. In contrast, the Second Coming is usually seen in terms
of spectacular images of devastation.
</P>
<P>
   The impending change in the calendar has pumped up the volume on
predictions. The public is gobbling them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our readers, as most people, are very concerned about what's
going to happen with the new millennium,'' said Susan Jimison,
managing editor of the 400,000-circulation Weekly World News.
``We're sending them every story on that that we come across.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimison's company is not the only publisher that has found
profit in feeding the end-time frenzy. As time until 2000 dwindles,
the volumes stack up. The megahit novels in the ``Left Behind''
series by Family Life seminar founder Tim LaHaye and Christian
author Jerry Jenkins have sold roughly 9 million copies and leapt
from Christian best-seller lists to those of The New York Times,
USA Today and The Wall Street Journal. Christian publisher Tyndale
House has extended the series from three to seven to 12 volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Why are human beings so fascinated with the ultimate finale?
</P>
<P>
   For people who think the culture is hellbound, the dissolution
of the present world order is appealing, said Ted Daniels, editor
of ``A Doomsday Reader'' (New York University Press, 1999, 256
pages, $18.95), which explores apocalyptic writings from Marx to
Aum Shinri Kyo, the Japanese sect charged with 1995 poison gas
attacks on Tokyo subways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the core issue here is that the millennium promises
salvation and it promises it right here and now,'' said Daniels.
``All the corruption and sin that's in the world is going to be
swept away and replaced by a perfect order.''
</P>
<P>
   There's the added tension that, since World War II, people have
lived with the existence of weapons that could destroy the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Louvin Brothers, a 1940s country duo, were sure the
apocalypse would come in the form of an A-bomb. They sang, in
toe-tapping rhythm: ``Are you ready for the great atomic power?
Will you rise and meet your Savior in the air? Will you shout or
will you cry, when the fire rains from on high?''
</P>
<P>
   People living with the potential of annihilation like to think
they can know the future and therefore feel less helpless, said
Tina Pippin, associate professor of religious studies at Agnes
Scott College. ``There's a need to control, to be in the inside
group,'' she said. ``You've got this insurance, this heavenly,
glorious future with God.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Pippin's fall classes was called ``Apocalypse and
Revolution.'' Students watched the films ``The Omega Code'' and
``End of Days.'' They listened to R.E.M.'s ``It's the End of the
World As We Know It'' and the long version of Madonna's ``Justify
My Love,'' which quotes from the Book of Revelation. They made
journals and wrote poetry. One student even produced her own
supermarket tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   They've joked about the commercialism they've seen in end-times
products, such as the literal ``Keys to the Kingdom,'' but there
has also been a serious side, said Pippin, ``like the possibility
of trains carrying nuclear waste going in front of the campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Good vs. evil
</P>
<P>
   The study of the end in religion has its own name _ eschatology
_ taken from the Greek root meaning ``last.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the majority of people in the United States are Christian,
most end-time scenarios in this country are derived from the
Christian Bible, especially the Book of Revelation.
</P>
<P>
   In general, many Christians believe: The world will undergo a
battle between good and evil (Christ and Antichrist), often called
Armageddon. Humankind will endure terrible turmoil known as the
``tribulation.'' Jesus will return, as the Apostles' Creed says,
``to judge the quick and the dead.'' There will be 1,000 years of
peace. And finally _ God's perfect reign.
</P>
<P>
   Christians pray for this eventuality in the Lord's Prayer or the
Our Father when they say, ``Thy kingdom come.''
</P>
<P>
   But the nature and sequence of events _ whether Jesus will come
before or after the time of trouble, and whether they are literal
or figurative _ are matters of great debate.
</P>
<P>
   Some Christians, including broadcaster Pat Robertson, say the
faithful will have to endure the troubles leading up to Christ's
reign; others believe the church will be ``raptured'' or
miraculously taken into heaven before the times of difficulty.
Hence the bumper stickers: ``In case of the Rapture, this vehicle
will be unoccupied'' and ``Beam Me Up, Jesus.'' One New York
insurance company even promises to pay off the life insurance
policies of Christians who are raptured.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus is quoted in Matthew 24:36 as saying not even he knows
when he will return, but some of his followers pore over Scriptures
looking for clues. True believers hear the hoofbeats of approaching
apocalypse in news reports of earthquakes, hurricanes and school
shootings, diseases such as AIDS and Ebola, modern developments
such as credit cards and automatic teller machines, and
international alliances such as the European Union and World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the chaos that would result from massive computer
failure on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In the high-tech 1990s, street-corner prophets have traded in
their sandwich boards for sites on the World Wide Web. There they
catalog their evidence _ from plagues of locusts in Uzbekistan to
legalized euthanasia in the Netherlands. ``It means Jesus is about
to return, folks!'' TV preacher and prognosticator Jack Van Impe
recently proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions not new
</P>
<P>
   The predictions are nothing new. Ignatius, bishop of Antioch,
who died about 110, is reported to have said, ``The last times are
upon us.'' The king of recent date-setters is probably Hal Lindsey,
whose 1970 best seller ``The Late Great Planet Earth'' _ which went
through more than 100 printings _ predicted that God would put the
period at the end of the present world order in 1988 after
rapturing the faithful in 1981. An ``updated'' version says Jesus
is coming in 2007.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite end of the spectrum from the date-setters are
the people such as Gary DeMar of Atlanta, author of ``Last Days
Madness'' (American Vision, 4th edition 1999, 455 pages, $19.95),
who argue that the events of Revelation took place centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   DeMar is president of American Vision, a Reconstructionist
Christian organization that seeks to bring about a kingdom of God
right here in the United States _ by making the Bible its primary
charter and modeling a legal system on the Old Testament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Book of Revelation is not talking about our time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than looking at the Bible and interpreting current
events, people are looking at current events and forcing them into
the Bible,'' said Richard Abanes, a California Southern Baptist
whose most recent book is called ``End-Time Visions'' (Broadman &AMP;
Holman, 1998, 424 pages, $9.99).
</P>
<P>
   Many other Christians, drawing a line between anticipation and
prediction, caution against date-setting but conclude that the end
is, indeed, nigh.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ed Hindson, a Southern Baptist minister who lives in
Tucker, has been a student of eschatology since he was a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   Hindson, whose newest book is ``Earth's Final Hour'' (Harvest
House, 1999, 207 pages, $9.99), says, ``It's hard to read the Bible
and then turn around and read the newspaper without seeing some
parallel there.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes Jesus wants Christians to watch for him to
return, but to keep serving until he does. ``Genuine Christianity
has to live in tension between the fact that Jesus could come at
any moment and the possibility that he may not come in your
lifetime,'' he said. ``You keep your eye on the sky and your feet
on the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, Catholics and so-called mainline Protestants
de-emphasize the end times. Although some conservative Catholics
see apocalyptic significance in the changes in the church since the
second Vatican Council, most don't read Revelation in an attempt to
match up its descriptions with current events, said Mark Jordan, a
Catholic scholar in the religion department at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of all the hoopla, many Christians struggle daily
to live out the message of their faith without forecasting the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central message is that God is trustworthy whatever the
suffering, whatever the turmoil,'' said Don Saliers, professor of
theology and worship at Emory University's Candler School of
Theology.
</P>
<P>
   As the world awaits another Christmas, Saliers said, ``something
is alive now in history that makes us hopeful and makes us work for
justice and makes us want people to be healing and makes us want to
dry the tears and have no more Kosovo, no more Columbine.''
</P>
<P>
   For Christians, that something is faith, he said. ``We think
about the Second Coming only because we're so confident in the
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
