<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2117 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX     12-17 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PLACE DOESN'T AGREE WITH OLD FRIEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: My little computer was running fine before I
packed it up and moved to a new city. It stayed in my closet for
about three months before I found the time to set it up again. When
I plugged everything in, it screamed, ``Operating system not
found.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Un-Smooth Operator
</P>
<P>
   DEAR UN: Well, how would you feel if somebody ignored you for
three months at a time? Sure, my ex-girlfriend never seemed to
mind. At least I think she didn't, but I haven't seen her for a
while, and she's not returning my calls.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all that time in the closet was the last straw for the
computer. Stored in an unusual position, the drive platters might
warp, especially if they were exposed to temperature extremes.
Maybe excess dust got into the drive or the spindle lubricant
turned into sludge.
</P>
<P>
   Pop the cover, blow the dust away, and try listening to your
computer for a change. Does it sound like it used to? Does the
drive activity light come on? You really have nothing left to lose,
so turn off the PC and give the drive a sharp smack on the side.
Sometimes that frees anything that's gummed up. It feels good, too.
But don't let my therapist hear that.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe your problem runs deeper than simply ignoring your PC. I
don't think it handled the move very well, but you can't really
blame it: Moving was your idea.
</P>
<P>
   I hope you realize how fragile your computer is and that
bouncing around in the back of a moving truck is no life for a
delicate piece of machinery. It's entirely possible that the hard
drive suffered physical damage.
</P>
<P>
   Most drives retract their recording heads when you power them
down, but a good jolt might send one of them clanging into the disk
surface.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's next? I'd probably end the relationship at this
point: Reformat the drive and install Windows again. If there is
drive damage, though, it's not going to get any better. Some things
just can't be fixed. But, don't worry. There are plenty of other
drives in the computer store. I'm sure you'll find the one meant
just for you.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I take issue with the blanket statement that
simply reading an e-mail is safe. It has recently been shown that
reading or previewing an e-mail may cause a problem. There is a
patch on the Microsoft site, but it is just a matter of time before
virus writers are able to work around the patch. While the greatest
risk comes from opening attachments, sadly, it is no longer true
that reading e-mail is 100 percent safe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inoculated
</P>
<P>
   DEAR INOC: Nothing is safe as long as there is one doofus out
there who thinks he knows how to mess with your life. How long
before it's not even safe to get out of bed, much less do anything
productive on your computer?
</P>
<P>
   The viruses you're talking about are ``Trojan horses'' that
exploit the preview panes in some e-mail programs. The same kind of
hidden code that makes Web pages dance and sing can launch
destructive programs once they're activated by just previewing a
message.
</P>
<P>
   All we can do is keep informed about the latest viruses and
remedies at places like Symantec (www.symantec.com/avcenter/) or
McAfee (www.mcafee.com). That means checking every day, not
periodically. Remember, those dysfunctional dweebs have nothing
better to do. It's not like they have dates to the prom or
anything.
</P>
<P>
   (Warning: The preceding column may have been infected with the
Bombay2K virus, which employs clever masking badinage to deliver
its deadly payload of vitriol. The virus' author, Dr. Emilio
Bombay, can be reached at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com
(snail-mail: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101). Fax: (817) 390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael
Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
