</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2118 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WHITNEY-ARTISTS19-COX     12-17 3392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITNEY-ARTISTS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meet the four Atlanta artists selected for America's most
prestigious exhibit
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 16.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every two years, the Whitney Museum of American Art in New York
stages its great bazaar, the Whitney Biennial. The largest _ and
certainly the most raucous _ survey of contemporary art in the
country has a unique mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biennial is a hybrid of objective selection and passionate
advocacy,'' says Whitney Museum director Maxwell Anderson. ``It's
different from so many contemporary exhibitions in which the theme
is the key. It's not about ... a curator's vision. This is about
artists and their work.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the show have charged that it is also about
favoritism and politics. But, whatever its faults, the biennial is
hugely influential. Inclusion can potentially make an artist's
career. Not surprisingly, landing on the list is like making Phi
Beta Kappa and All-American at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the ultimate validation of all my years of work as an
artist,'' says Ruth Leitman.
</P>
<P>
   Leitman, a filmmaker, is one of four Atlanta artists, all under
the age of 40, selected for the 2000 biennial. Robin Bernat, a
video and book artist, painter Kojo Griffin and photographer Chris
Verene also are among the 97 participants.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that only about four Georgia artists total have ever
been in any biennial, the number alone is news. And good news for
the community at large. As Nexus Gallery director Teresa Bramlette
says, ``It puts us on the radar screen.''
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from past practice, the first biennial of the new
century, which runs March 23-June 4, was assembled by a team of six
regionally based curators. The curators tried to counter the
perceived New York bias by seeking out artists outside the inside
track, making studio visits nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Biennial curator Valerie Cassel came to Atlanta in August with a
list compiled by local critic Rebecca Dimling Cochran and High
Museum of Art curator Carrie Przybilla. Only one of the four
Atlanta artists selected, Verene, was on that list.
</P>
<P>
   Cassel happened to see Griffin's work while visiting Verene's
gallery, Vaknin Schwartz. Whitney director Anderson passed along
Bernat's videos to the curators for consideration. And Linda
Dubler, High Museum curator of media arts, was one of several who
recommended Leitman.
</P>
<P>
   But how is not the key. Being there is. Even those like
Pryzbilla, who calls the biennial ``more interesting than
important,'' says, ``There is no other forum like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Kojo Griffin's paintings are seductively pretty. The characters
_ patchwork dolls, people with animal heads _ look like something
out of a children's book. The roles they play are ambiguous. But
the mood isn't. Beyond their surface appeal, these images are
disturbing and sordid. They speak of abuse, suicide, impending
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paint the moment before or the moment after something has
happened,'' says the artist, 28, sitting in the bare West End
warehouse that serves as his home and studio. ``I paint things
people don't like to talk about and deal with. I know I'm not going
to change the world, but I want to show people that they aren't
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was attracted to the subtle and intricate manner in which he
deals with complex issues,'' says curator Todd Smith of the Mint
Museum of Art in Charlotte, who exhibited Griffin's work in ``New
Frontiers,'' a series about young artists. ``And he does it with
such dexterity for one so early in his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin's career began seven years ago, with the birth of his
older son, Zion. The lanky Virginia native was in school, dabbling
in graffiti and doing small graphic design projects to make ends
meet, when the weight of his new responsibility hit him. In mulling
his future, Griffin, who had come to Atlanta in 1989 to attend
Morehouse College, toyed with pursuing psychology, his major.
Instead he decided to take advantage of the gift he had never
appreciated and become an artist.
</P>
<P>
   Making art was always a private comfort zone. Griffin, who is
single, grew up in two Boston-area communities _ Brookline, where
he lived with his mother and sister, and Roxbury, where his father
lived.
</P>
<P>
   Tall and overweight as a child and saddled with an unusual name,
he didn't feel like he belonged anywhere. ``I love it now,'' he
says of his name, which he describes as an African word meaning
``unconquerable.'' ``But then I wished my name was Sam or Steven or
Joshua, like everyone else. I felt very isolated. Art was always my
refuge. I drew a lot and read comics.''
</P>
<P>
   Not belonging to one group permitted him to engage in many. For
instance, Griffin could absorb traditional aesthetics in classes
and field trips to the Boston Museum of Fine Arts and get involved
with hip-hop in high school. He could make graffiti and still study
the I Ching and the cabala, a mystical Jewish philosophy. (He drew
Kether, the name of his 3-year-old son, from the cabala.) These
systems of knowledge find their way into paintings in abstracted
diagrams that overlay the figurative elements.
</P>
<P>
   The ambiguity of the characters in his paintings is a way of
keeping the paintings as open-ended as possible. By foregoing
specifics of race and gender, he hopes to make a pre-emptive strike
against those who might key their interpretation to the fact that
he is black. By making the action equivocal, Griffin thinks he
allows people to project their own experience into the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to communicate. That's why I make art,'' says the
artist, who teaches classes for the Fulton County Arts Council and
the city of Atlanta's Bureau of Cultural Affairs. ``The painting is
not the be-all and end-all. I care about craft, but it's more
important to have a dialogue with the viewer. That's art to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He has matured surprisingly quickly, and his career has mirrored
that trajectory. In the five years since his work began appearing
in local group exhibitions, he has joined the stable of the Vaknin
Schwartz gallery. He has had the solo show at Charlotte's Mint
Museum and will have another at the Kemper Museum of Contemporary
Art in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest leap of all will be seeing his paintings on the
walls of the Whitney Museum of American Art in New York. Still,
Griffin, who is one of the biennial's youngest participants, is
taking a cautious approach to his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity,'' he says, ``but no guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   ROBIN BERNAT
</P>
<P>
   Robin Bernat can confirm what we're told about the joy of
giving.
</P>
<P>
   After Maxwell Anderson, director of New York's Whitney Museum of
American Art, spoke here in June at a benefit for Art Papers, a
local art journal for which she is a board member, Bernat sent him
copies of her art videos and poetry books as thank you presents.
</P>
<P>
   Five months later, the Whitney told Bernat that she was on the
short list for its prestigious biennial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in enormous shock,'' recalls the 34-year-old artist. ``I
didn't even know I was being considered. I had sent them a personal
gift, not a submission.''
</P>
<P>
   She will be represented in the biennial by one of her videos,
aptly titled ``Effortless.''
</P>
<P>
   In the piece, the word signifies an unattainable goal. In a
voice-over of one of her poems, Bernat expresses grief over her
father's murder 20 years ago and describes the social unease that
has plagued her since. The video features a salamander, which
adapts easily to changing environments, and symbolizes the
effortlessness for which she longs. Images such as the slow,
rhythmic arc of a lawn sprinkler and long pans of country roads
establish an appropriate mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robin gets at the subtle nuance of feeling in her videos,''
says critic Jerry Cullum. ``She captures what it feels like to be
an often frustrated and defeated romantic.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernat spent her Louisiana childhood immersed in arts. She wrote
poetry. Her father loved opera and dance. Her great-grandparents'
home in Monroe houses the town art museum, and she visited museums
everywhere she traveled. But Bernat couldn't imagine being an
artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was seeing the masters,'' she says. ``I knew I couldn't do
that. It wasn't until I went to art school that I understood it's
an incremental process.''
</P>
<P>
   She majored in political philosophy at the University of Georgia
but became interested in art history her senior year. After
dropping out of graduate school at Emory University, she applied to
Atlanta publishing houses for a job, including Nexus Press, which
she thought was a typical book-publishing establishment.
</P>
<P>
   That was a pivotal move. The press, a part of Nexus Contemporary
Art Center, is a renowned facility devoted to nurturing visual
artists who use the book format creatively and to publishing their
work. She went for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the artists' books, it was like lightning struck,''
she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   In the medium, she found a way to meld her passion for words and
images. During this crash course in book arts, she made one book,
``Evidence of Living,'' which is shaped like a ``cootie catcher,''
a child's game.
</P>
<P>
   The internship not only opened up a new world but also propelled
her to art school. After earning her bachelor of fine arts at the
Atlanta College of Art in 1992, Bernat started Circle B Press in a
studio on Means Street. She has published six books of her poetry
and images under its imprint and one collaborative piece with her
writing group.
</P>
<P>
   Bernat, who teaches part time, made her first video in 1996.
``Video was a natural progression of combining narrative and
images,'' she explains. ``I needed them to be animated.''
</P>
<P>
   The videos _ she directs, narrates and performs in them _ almost
always start with her autobiographical poems. They are usually
presented as installations. ``Effortless'' was shown on three
custom-made maple monitors and three benches, along with a box of
talismanic souvenirs _ a ladybug, a leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Bernat often works in the serene Buckhead condominium she shares
with cats Pasha and Mama. A laptop and a set of sharpened colored
pencils sit on the desk of her book-lined study. When she gets
stuck creatively, she buys flowers and makes arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   She was hosting an Art Papers meeting in her home when she got
The Call. Bernat remembers asking the Whitney staffer if she could
tell her mother. She also remembers jumping up and down. A lot. The
euphoria has hardly worn off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very validating experience,'' she says. ``I always
believed in myself. I felt my art was authentic to me, but I never
thought anyone else got it.''
</P>
<P>
   RUTH LEITMAN
</P>
<P>
   Alma Thorpe, a blowsy mound of a woman in her 60s given to
wearing big hair bows and quoting the Bible, appears to be a
harmless Southern eccentric. Her daughter Margie knows better _ and
so do we, after seeing Ruth Leitman's searing documentary about
their destructive relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alma,'' which caps a triumphant stint on the film festival
circuit with its selection for the 2000 Whitney Biennial, is a
complex, compelling and perversely humorous story, creatively told.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is set up like a mystery,'' says the artist, 37,
sipping coffee in Cabbagetown's Carroll Street Bakery near her home
and studio. ``It's like unpeeling an onion.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when you get to the central family revelation _ an
accusation of incest _ another mystery remains. Why, after you've
learned how a disturbed mother has damaged her daughter, can you
still like the ``villain''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ruth humanizes the characters so much that I had a hard time
dealing with Alma,'' says Linda Dubler, curator of media arts at
the High Museum of Art. ``I should have been horrified, but she's
viewed with such compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely Leitman's intention: ``I wanted people to like Alma
and Jim (Alma's husband), to see them as victims of their own
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Maysles, the pioneering documentary filmmaker of ``Grey
Gardens'' and ``Gimme Shelter'' fame, was impressed with ``Alma.''
``You don't often see a documentary with a motivation out of love.
... Few people go beyond the technology,'' he says. ``To do that
you have to be empathetic. You're not a fly on the wall; you are
engaged.''
</P>
<P>
   As ``Alma'' co-producer Nancy Segler observes, ``Ruth respec subjects. They understand, appreciate and respond.'' That's why
Margie Thorpe chose to bring her story to Leitman.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not condescending,'' Thorpe says. ``That was really
important as to who I was going to trust.''
</P>
<P>
   For an artist interested in ambivalence, this family was a
perfect subject. ``What completely intrigued me the minute I
started this project was that beyond all these difficulties, there
was love and understanding,'' Leitman says. ``Under all the
dysfunction, there was forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Leitman, a native of suburban Philadelphia, weaves together past
and present by way of photos and mementos, and she presents the
imagery more like a feature film than a report. The camera travels
lovingly through Alma's West End home, crammed with broken
furniture, religious paraphernalia and piles of papers and frosted
with grime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of Alma as a poor Norma Desmond,'' the artist
explains, referring to the faded silent screen star in the 1950
film ``Sunset Boulevard.'' ``Her house was in beautiful decay. If
you open her cabinets, all this stuff _ recipes, religious writings
_ taped to the doors is eaten by roaches. It looks like lace.''
</P>
<P>
   She developed an eye for detail during her career as a
photographer. Leitman, who graduated from the University of the
Arts in Philadelphia, moved to Atlanta in 1984. She made her living
photographing rock musicians for magazines and record companies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, she co-founded a group called Photograffiti, which
provided this fan of Robert Frank, Gary Winogrand and Diane Arbus
with an outlet for her interest in street photography and social
issues. The group enlarged their photos into posters and stuck them
on buildings in the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, about the time she married guitarist Steve
Dixon, Leitman started making the transition to filmmaking. She
returned north to film her first documentary, ``Wildwood,'' about
the girls of a New Jersey beach town, completed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I identified more with the gentile working-class girls in
Wildwood, N.J., than with (peers) of my Jewish middle-class
upbringing,'' she says. ``I was always interested in people who
were afforded less but had the strength and confidence to make
their way in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Making ``Alma'' required great determination. Staying with the
brutal subject matter was only one challenge. Raising funds over
the four years of filming was just as difficult. But her resolve
was truly put to the test when she had a stillborn child during the
sixth month of her pregnancy, just as she was starting the editing
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only took two weeks off,'' she recalls. ``Nancy (the
co-producer) had to scrape me off the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily, she and Dixon are now the doting parents of 1
1/2-year-old Ella, conceived, says the artist, on the day that her
first daughter was to have been born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm making an epic film of Ella,'' she says. ``I asked Steve
the other day, `Do you think spending $100 a week on film
processing is excessive?'''
</P>
<P>
   She is also involved in a number of other projects. Among them,
Leitman is editing a film on a group of developmentally disabled
adults and trying her hand at writing a feature film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be like Louis Malle,'' she says. ``He made
documentaries and films. Each project was very different.''
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS VERENE
</P>
<P>
   These days it's hard to know what time zone Chris Verene is in,
let alone what city. When the Atlanta artist is not abroad planning
exhibitions of his photography in the Netherlands, France and
Greece, he is splitting time between New York and Georgia's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Even when he's stateside, he's going in many directions. He
might be finalizing the publication of an untitled book of
photographs. He might be playing wild-man drums with one of his
bands. He might not even be Chris Verene, but rather Cheri Nevers,
a cross-dressing ``it girl'' posing for repugnant cheesecake photos
or standing behind the camera at the Self-Esteem Studio Salon, a
part-performance, part-photo studio.
</P>
<P>
   Although Verene, 30, sees his art and music as interconnected,
he doesn't even try to link his various, uh, bodies of photography.
As the artist asserted in a telephone conversation from Amsterdam,
``Cheri Nevers needs a separate interview.''
</P>
<P>
   He does know _ and makes something out of _ family ties. His
paternal roots are in the prairie railroad community of Galesburg,
Ill., which has produced three generations of Verenes. He spent
holidays and summers there as a child, and he has devoted the
better part of 13 years creating a loving photographic portrait of
the town that is as quirkily American as ketchup on mac-n-cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Photography curator Tom Southall has purchased two of the
Galesburg photos for the High Museum of Art's collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was immediately struck, when I first arrived a year ago,
with how he uses the style of documentary photography without being
hung up oer it is fact,'' he says. ``He creates characters
not unlike Faulkner and Yoknapatawpha County. Finally a
photographer is using the freedom a novelist has felt all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he started the series, Verene spent five or six months out
of the year there. ``Photography is a slow process of watching and
waiting,'' he says. ``I could be there for a month and come home
with no pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Home'' is where the darkroom is: Atlanta. He moved here at 11
when his father, a philosophy professor, began teaching at Emory
University. His father and mother, an anthropologist, now run the
Institute for Vico Studies at Emory, which brings together Italian
Renaissance philosophy and the writings of James Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   Verene started taking pictures when he was 16 or 17. ``It was a
curiosity,'' he recalls. ``By the time I was 18, I was really
devoted to it.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to Emory and took photography classes at Georgia State
University, where he earned a master's. Atlanta artist Ruth
Leitman, a fellow biennial participant, remembers when Verene first
brought his photos to the Atlanta Photography Gallery in the early
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hunched over, with big glasses _ the ultimate geek, but
he had a really interesting vision,'' recalls Leitman, who gave
Verene his first one-man show in her Cabbagetown studio.
</P>
<P>
   Verene, who plays drums, also became involved with the music
scene and community of artists in Cabbagetown, where he has lived
for eight years, next door to Leitman and her family. From 1994 to
1997, he played with the Rock-a-Teens. They recorded on Daemon
Records, the label owned by Indigo Girl Amy Ray, and he even played
drums on the Indigo Girls' ``Shed Your Skin.'' His duo, Bach on a
Hook, which plays electrified Bach partitas, is about to release a
CD. He also
</P>
<P>
   has a heavy-metal band, Fight Evil With Evil.
</P>
<P>
   Two points of crossover: His photos have appeared on seven album
covers, and Elton John and Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid of LaFace Records
have his prints in their collections.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his success, Verene, who is a full-time artist, is not
blase about his inclusion in the Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like it's not true,'' says the artist, who has never
been to a biennial. ``I'm very excited; it's what everybody talks
about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney will be showing photos from his Camera Club series.
In this sly and inventive study, Verene focuses on the voyeuristic
nature of photography by taking pictures of amateur snappers as
they shoot photos of young women in pinup poses.
</P>
<P>
   He's watching the men watching the women. We're watching Verene
watch them. We're also watching a career take wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting a painful amount of positive attention,''
Southall says. ``It could go to one's head, knock one off his path.
But he's unusually self-directed and clear in his personal
motivations. Chris has a real chance to be a great photographer.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
