<HEADER>
A2119 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CRACKER-AUTHOR19-COX     12-17 2542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRACKER-AUTHOR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Georgia writer chronicles a life and a landscape in
'Ecology of a Cracker Childhood'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 19.
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAXLEY, Ga. The 10-acre junkyard where writer Janisse Ray spent
her early years sprawls alongside U.S. 1, its secrets screened from
passing traffic by trees, muscadine vines, dog fennel and ragweed.
Once Ray's parents kept sheep to crop the underbrush, but the sheep
are gone and the junkyard, like Ray, is all grown up.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, 37, is a successful writer, environmental activist and
mother. But the junkyard was once her universe. Along with her
parents, a sister and two brothers, she lived an isolated South
Georgia life cramped by poverty, mental illness and strict
fundamentalist beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Not allowed to see movies, newspapers or television, to take
part in Christmas or Easter celebrations, or even to socialize with
classmates outside of school, the Ray youngsters found their fun in
their father's junkyard. They paddled around its leaf-spattered
pond on rafts made of gas tanks ripped from old cars. They imagined
driving to exotic places in vehicles that would never ride the road
again. They soared above the junk in chinaberry and red maple
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Ray even believed that she and her siblings were found in the
junkyard as newborns, because that was the creation story their
parents told them.
</P>
<P>
   Ray left rural Appling County years ago in search of a wider
world. That she found the forest in spite of the trees is evident
in her first book of prose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ecology of a Cracker Childhood,'' published in late October by
Milkweed Editions and already in its second printing, interweaves
the story of Ray's unusual childhood with chapters about the
natural history of the once-vast longleaf pine forests that
blanketed the coastal plain from Virginia to Florida to west of the
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Both are stories of pain and loss. Both offer hope of healing.
</P>
<P>
   Now working on a book about rural communities, Ray has returned
to Appling County to live, at least for a time, in the heart pine
farmhouse her grandparents built 80 years ago. She is involved in
the fight against strip mining near the Okefenokee Swamp. She's
helping to establish a riverkeeper group for the giant Altamaha,
which borders Appling County to the north.
</P>
<P>
   She is also trying to reconcile more personal issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be back in my homeland, with all the pain and
weirdness that surrounds it,'' Ray said, sitting by the fireplace
that provides the only heat for her borrowed house. ``I wanted to
work things out with my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ecology of a Cracker Childhood'' contains unsparing
descriptions of the pain her father's mental illness and rigid
religious beliefs caused her as a child.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 6, she watched as Franklin Delano Ray, now 62, held
his arms up, called out, ``I'm coming, Lord,'' and then stepped
through a window, ``cracking the pane like thin ice on a pond,
snapping strips of white-painted frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Another day, he locked his wife, Lee Ada, and children into a
back bedroom with a 6-foot chest freezer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That day, he wanted us to be quiet, and we were,'' Ray writes.
``We sat where he told us to sit. Each of us obeyed him perfectly
and immediately, watching wide-eyed as Daddy ranted in what I now
know to be mania.''
</P>
<P>
   When the children begged for food, Frank Ray at first refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toward evening, he permitted Mama to reach into the freezer
with her eyes closed and choose one thing for us to eat. `Honey,
you know we can't eat raw food out of that freezer. Let me go cook
us some supper,' (Lee Ada) protested. `One thing,' he said. ``No
more no less. I'll hold the lid for you. You have to close your
eyes. That's the way God says to feed the children. One thing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ray counters those harsh memories with accounts of her father's
abundant love for his family, his inventive genius with scraps
salvaged from the junkyard, his insistence that the children learn
to think and value knowledge. She describes his tender efforts to
save a wild green-backed heron hit by a car and an endangered
gopher tortoise captured and spray-painted gold and silver by a
roadside fruit seller.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Ray still lives on the junkyard property with Lee Ada, in
the two-story red brick house the family built to replace the
smaller home where Janisse Ray grew up. He admitted that his
daughter's book ``jarred me around a little bit'' when he read it
in draft form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did my best not to make my mind up until I finished it,'' he
said. ``I backed up and tried to look at it objectively. I decided
overall that it was a great book and worthy to be published and go
out.''
</P>
<P>
   His pride in his daughter is evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's always been smart, and she didn't just get that way
yesterday,'' he said, telling how Ray was her high school's STAR
student, graduated fourth in her class, wrote prize-winning poetry
and put out the school newspaper almost single-handedly.
</P>
<P>
   He has become an enthusiastic salesman of her books, hauling
boxes of them to libraries in Ludowici and Nahunta when she is
doing readings in small towns nearby. He tells people that his
daughter's book is ``the best book I ever read besides the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Ray's relatives agree. Some are angry with her for
writing so openly about the family, especially the mental illness
that has plagued it for generations.
</P>
<P>
   A cousin in Florida recently left an angry message on her
answering machine. ``If we're all crazy in that book then you're
crazy as hell, too,'' a woman's strident voice said. ``I don't
appreciate what you done.''
</P>
<P>
   Another cousin called Ray's Minnesota publisher with similar
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is,'' Ray said, ``everything I wrote is the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Appling County residents have been more accepting. Members of
Spring Branch Baptist Church invited Ray to take her grandmother's
place there after she came back home.
</P>
<P>
   Although she doesn't attend church, she appreciated the
invitation. ``That was a tender and warm welcome,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that life in the rural community revolves around church
does limit her social options, Ray said, though she keeps in close
touch with far-flung friends around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here think that because there's beer at the bottom of
my refrigerator, I'm going to hell. And you cannot talk about the
joy or terror of your life, and other real things.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving home, Ray got a degree in English and creative
writing from Florida State University, living near Tallahassee in a
two-room shanty she built with friends. There, she joined forces
with experts who taught her botany and astronomy. She learned about
organic gardening, beekeeping and drying fruit. She wrote poetry,
joined the Audubon Society and wrote articles for wildlife
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   She also conceived her son, Silas, now 11. A granny midwife
delivered him at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was part of my lifestyle to have him at home _ part of my
culture,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Four months later, with baby Silas balanced on her hip, Ray
married his father, a marquetry artist named Breeze VerDant, at the
county courthouse. ``I didn't want to get married, and it was a
mistake,'' she said. The marriage lasted less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Divorced and needing work, she took a job teaching English in
Colombia. Terrified of that country's armed guerrillas and by
stories of stolen children, Ray stayed six months before fleeing
back to the Florida shanty. Her newly acquired Spanish-language
skills helped her land a job with the state. Then she began a
``serious search'' for the direction of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I wanted to combine the two things I loved the most:
environmental activism and writing.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 she went back to college, earning a master's degree in
environmental studies and English from the University of Montana.
One summer during graduate school, while Silas was visiting his
father in Vermont, she wrote the draft of her book. It took two
more years to finish it.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty of blending family history and natural history
frustrated her. At the suggestion of her editor at Milkweed, Ray
eventually organized the book by alternating chapters of childhood
memories with chapters about longleaf pines.
</P>
<P>
   Ray has become a passionate spokeswoman for the stately trees,
which once covered more than half of the 156 million acres in their
Southeastern range. By 1930, only a few thousand acres _ less than
1 percent _ of old-growth longleaf pines remained. The trees were
lost to agriculture, to development and to paper and timber
companies, which favor faster-growing varieties of pine. Today,
regimented ranks of loblolly and slash pine have turned much of the
rural South into a landscape as monotonous as the moon's.
</P>
<P>
   With the pines went the wiregrass that blanketed the ground
beneath them. Trees and grass had supported a huge and diverse
community: red-cockaded woodpeckers, indigo snakes, gopher
tortoises and hundreds of other plants and animals, many now rare
or endangered. Ray is eloquent in her descriptions of the old
forests:
</P>
<P>
   ``In a longleaf forest, miles of trees forever fade into a
brilliant salmon sunset and reappear the next dawn as a battalion
marching out of fog. The tip of each needle carries a single drop
of silver. The trees are so well spaced that their limbs seldom
touch and sunlight streams between and within them. Below their
flattened branches, grasses arch their tall, richly dun heads of
seeds, and orchids and lilies paint the ground orange and scarlet.
Purple liatris gestures across the landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   She also describes the voices of the trees:
</P>
<P>
   ``What thrills me most about longleaf forests is how the pine
trees sing. The horizontal limbs of flattened crowns hold the wind
as if they are vessels, singing bowls, and air stirs in them like a
whistling kettle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray urges Southerners to fight for restoration of the longleaf
habitat. ``We want more than 1 percent natural stands of longleaf.
We know a pine plantation is not a forest and the wholesale
conversion to monocultures is unacceptable to us,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Hermann, a research scientist specializing in plant and
fire ecology at Tall Timbers Research Station near Tallahassee,
said Ray paints an accurate picture of old longleaf forests. The
station, one of six such independent, nonprofit research
organizations in the country, owns or manages more than 6,000 acres
in North Florida and South Georgia that embrace one of the largest
surviving stands of longleaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a frequent situation that someone who writes prose
also has an understanding of the natural setting,'' Hermann said.
``She saw early on that nature is not just something to be enjoyed
but to be understood.''
</P>
<P>
   The connection came naturally for Ray, who remembers spending
much of her childhood outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think something in me from the very start loved nature,''
she said, showing visitors around the old farmstead where she
lives. Her uncle, who owns the property on a yellow dirt road near
Baxley, lives in a trailer a few hundred steps away. Nearby are an
old corncrib, a ramshackle log woodshed, the boiler where the
family made cane syrup and the well where they drew water. Beyond
are fields, empty this time of year, where Ray's relatives will
plant cotton, corn or soybeans come spring. There are a handful of
longleaf pines, which sing Ray and Silas to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people live close to the land here,'' Ray said, gazing
across the rustic property with love and pride. ``That's part of
this culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Collier, Appalachian regional representative for the Sierra
Club, said environmentalists are beginning to discover Ray's book.
Collier said he believes Ray's message is one of redemption, both
from the pain of her early life and her sense of loss over the
ravaging of her homeland's native forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's saying, `Don't give up on the landscape. It was once
beautiful and can be again.' She's also saying that her childhood
might have been rough at times, but there's a lot of richness
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray isn't sure her future, or her son's, lies in Appling County,
where many residents don't finish high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard for Silas to find friends here, hard to find
kids raised the way he has been, to have a voice in everything,''
she said. ``He's been really lonely. He says, `Here, there is no
imagination.'''
</P>
<P>
   And while her parents love Silas and keep him while she travels,
their philosophy of child rearing sometimes clashes with hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was invited to go to a Pokemon movie with his friend, Caleb
... and my folks wouldn't let him go,'' Ray said. ``I called home
from a pay phone in Savannah and he was so sad, crying on the
phone. It just epitomized how it was when I was a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray wound up crying herself, helplessly beating her fists on the
seat of her car.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my only fear for Silas,'' she said. ``That what
happened to me doesn't happen to him. The isolation, the
misinformation.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she fears that rural communities such as
Baxley will vanish as more and more people like her move away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-thirds of us live in cities now. I feel like somebody has
to stay and inhabit the ghost towns, to combat the ignorance and
racism.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, she's content to finish her next book, fight for
environmental causes and spend time with her family.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent autumn afternoon, Ray and her father took a walk
together through the junkyard, each enjoying it in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   The place has an exotic beauty, especially when drifts of dark
red pine straw and golden hardwood leaves carpet the ground and
soften the ragged edges of rust and rot. Amber sunlight plays
across half a century's worth of rusting cars and car parts, bales
of bottles and jagged glass, broken household goods, rotting
furniture, crumbling plastic and mutilated tools and toys.
</P>
<P>
   Although Frank Ray is no longer active in the junk business, he
knows every twisting path and tumbled pile. He points out the
rusted 1939 Packard with the Shriner emblem on the door, the
resting place of the old grits mill and the rust-brown truck he
drove 40 years ago, hauling scrap iron to Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   As he chronicles the story of each item, his daughter pauses to
identify the voices of birds gossiping from the bushes and to
admire a clump of pitcher plants. She stops by a young tree pushing
up through the junk toward light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy, look, it's a longleaf pine,'' she says, sliding her
hand over slender needles like someone stroking a pet cat.
</P>
<P>
   Her father examines the tree. ``No, I don't believe it is,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   The two look at each other, both smart and strong-willed, their
beliefs clashing. Then they walk on, leaving the issue of the
tree's identity unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken a long time, but Janisse Ray and her father are
learning to walk away from differences. Their love for each other
compels them to search, even in a junkyard, for the sweetness of
common ground.
</P>
<P>
   Jingle Davis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
