</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, December 18,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds. Adds: TRADE-DEFICIT, CLINTON-DISABLED,
AFFIRMATIVE-CONNERLY, BUSH
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TRAVEL _ JERUSALEM _ A review of what's going on at the
millennium sites. At Armageddon, the place where the battle to end
all battles is supposed to occur, the Israelis have fixed up the
park that is there. At the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, where
orthodox Christians believe Christ was crucified, the five
bickering denominations in charge are trying to agree on where to
place an exit door _ the first change in the church in years. In
Bethlehem, the Palestinians have rebuilt the plaza and torn down
the ugly old British jail next to the church. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/MIDEAST-AGENTS _ JERUSALEM _ It took the millennium to make it
happen, but for the first time Israelis and Palestinians have
formed a travel agency together. They hope to cash in on a boom of
tourists. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., Dec. 16, in (i) International and (t) Travel
categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-MILLENNIUM _ MEXICO CITY _ Mexicans are ringing in the
new millenium with the same cultural clashes and contradictions
they've lived with for 500 years. They are invited to attend their
local Catholic church for a night of prayer and devotion to Jesus
Christ, born 2000 years ago in a land the original Mexicans didn't
even know existed until the 1500s. Or _ among other bashes _ they
can rock and roll at the hulking Teotihuacan pyramids near Mexico
City and commune with their indigenous roots. Developing. (Ferriss,
Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   w/MEXICO-Y2K _ WASHINGTON _ Mexico is one of America's closest
trading partners and its immediate neighbor. Because of tight
trading links, Mexico is nearly on par with the United States and
Canada, in terms of Y2K readiness. The coordination of Y2K efforts
among Canada, Mexico and the US helps show how much NAFTA has knit
the three countries together into one big market. (Geewax, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thursday, Dec. 16, in (i) International, (l)
Lifestyle and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-DEBATE _ Coverage of Al Gore-Bill Bradley faceoff on ABC's
Nightline. Will have access to early taping of the show in
Manchester. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As he officially files for the
presidential election in Texas, Gov. George W. Bush sits down with
the American-Statesman to discuss the campaign so far. (Herman,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-POLLS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Candidates in the 2000 election
will face increasingly skeptical voters who are growing less
tolerant of attack ads and dishonesty on the campaign trail, a
research group with ties to Ohio said Thursday. In a nation-wide
poll done in early November, the Institute for Global Ethics found
nearly 60 percent of those polled think all or most candidates
``twist the truth'' while campaigning. Almost 40 percent said most
candidates lie. The latest figures come from a group that used Ohio
and Washington as pilot states in 1998 to begin its Project on
Campaign Conduct. (Montgomery, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-FACTS _ WASHINGTON _ At a time when the U.S. trade deficit
has hit an all-time high, the U.S. government has lost track of its
trade agreements with foreign nations. In a new report, the General
Accounting Office says it was unable to determine how many pacts
exist because of sloppy bookkeeping. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DISABLED _ WASHINGTON _ With a memorial to the nation's
most disabled president as a backdrop, President Clinton signed a
bill Friday designed to help the disabled return to work by
preserving their federal health coverage. (Lipman, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-DRUGS _ WASHINGTON _ Health and Human Services Secretary
Donna Shalala and National Drug Control Policy Director Barry
McCaffrey announce the results of the 25th annual ''Monitoring the
Future'' study on illicit drug use among teens. The survey has
tracked 12th graders' illicit drug use and attitudes towards drugs
since 1975. (Schultz, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE _ WASHINGTON _ Friday is widely seen as the climax of
the Internet holiday shopping season _ the last day when shoppers
can hope to receive Christmas purchases by standard shipping, and
the first day that analysts can guage how successful e-tailing has
been this year. (Geewax, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   NEWT-DIVORCE _ Newt and Marianne Gingrich are to file the terms
of their divorce. (Stanford, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-CONNERLY _ WEST PALM BEACH _ Ward Connerly, the
California businessman who's pushing a constitutional amendment to
eliminate affirmative action programs in Florida, speaks to a group
of business leaders. Opponents of Connerly's petition drive protest
before his speech. (Palm Beach Post)
</P>
