<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2129 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV19-B     12-17 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV19-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DISTANT MIRROR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 19, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In August 1903, a 14-year-old girl burned down a barn in
Poughkeepsie, NY. Nobody died, but the fire caught the attention of
an editorial writer at the The New York Evening Journal who blamed
the fire on the fact that the child craved a little excitement
because she had been raised in . . . an orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   If the girl were returned to her institution for her crimes, the
editorialist wrote, ``She will go back to a scheme of life which is
largely the cause of her disordered cravings, a kind of life that
ruins with its dull routine hundreds of thousands of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a big asylum, no matter how good the intention of the
management, or how kind the attendants, the lives of the
unfortunate children are dull beyond belief. Everything is routine,
commonplace, dead-level monotony. They all sleep in uniform little
beds side by side, they get up, go to bed, eat, walk _ do
everything in one monotonous routine. And worst of all nothing is
left to their own initiative, their imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   The moral? According to the editorialist, nothing to do but to
abolish the orphanage and build some other, kinder, gentler system.
Such as? Such as the system that even then rapidly was evolving
into the program of federal assistance to mothers and their
children that eventually came to be known as Aid to Families with
Dependent Children (AFDC) or, in the political argot of the '90s,
Welfare As We Know It.
</P>
<P>
   That story is from ``Building the Invisible Orphanage: A
Prehistory of the American Welfare System,'' by Matthew A. Crenson,
a professor of political science at the Johns Hopkins University. I
consulted the book after reading stories about the blaze in
Worcester that killed six firefighters who had gone into an
abandoned warehouse to look for homeless people -- and about the
argument between two homeless people that led to the fire in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Homelessness is an issue in New York City, too. Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani has ordered police to begin arresting street persons who
decline to go to a shelter or a hospital. His city has the nation's
largest, but far from only workfare program; fully 10 percent of
those on its welfare rolls are now performing low-skill city jobs.
Indeed, ever since President Clinton signed the welfare act in 1996
handing most of the responsibility for welfare programs back to the
states, it has been clear that things changed -- if not exactly
how.
</P>
<P>
   The virtue of Crenson's book is that it is a close examination
of the sea change that brought the welfare system into existence in
the first place. It is, in the historian Barbara Tuchman's phrase,
``a distant mirror'' of the present day. ``This is not the first
time Americans have scrapped a system of public assistance long in
use for another largely untried,'' writes Crenson. Impoverished
children always have been a part of the landscape; it was tensions
and disappointments associated with the orphanage system that gave
rise to the modern welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   Orphanages expanded rapidly in the decades after the Civil War
to accommodate large numbers of street children in the increasingly
populous and newly industrializing Northern cities. Gradually they
undertook to rescue poor children from almshouses and slums as
well. Most were private, sectarian institutions. A vigorous
competition set in among Protestant denominations and the Roman
Catholic Church over the proper tending of young souls.
</P>
<P>
   Child care was an expensive business, however, and by the 1870s,
the states were paying substantial subsidies to many orphanages.
With courts and county poorhouses making referrals, regulation by
the state became a necessity, and state supervision of religious
stewardship produced a constant rub. The organizational superiority
of the Catholic Church gave its essentially private system a
significant edge.
</P>
<P>
   Orphanages were developing bad reputations, however, for
stifling the good and furthering the bad. As in prisons, protecting
the innocent was possible, but even more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Crenson shows, the state sought ways of
implementing what we today call ``de-institutionalization.'' Almost
alone among the states, Massachusetts relied entirely on ``placing
out'' _ paying foster families to take in homeless children. But
that was expensive, too, and had perils of its own. So reformers
settled on the idea of ``mothers' pensions'' as the best solution
to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   It was risky putting cash in the hands of indigent mothers in
order to enable them to keep their children, but ``for the sake of
innocent children, welfare policy should accommodate the failings
of their parents'' _ or so the argument went, Crenson writes. Not
only was the ``invisible orphanage'' cheaper _ today we would call
the orphanage ``virtual'' _ but it appealed to both Catholics and
Protestants as well. Thirty years and the Great Depression were
required before the federal government accepted responsibility for
the program from the pioneering states.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it was the magnitude of American charity _ not just the
underdevelopment of the American state _ that helped delay the
emergence of a comprehensive welfare system, Crenson says. Others,
notably Harvard sociologist Theda Skocpol, have argued that
feminist activism was the galvanizing force. That analaysis pays
too little attention to the role of the churches, Crenson says, and
as a result fails to explain why welfare ``never moved far from
considerations of sin, redemption and salvation.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenson is rather bleak in his views about the policy that is at
the heart of the 1966 welfare act _ Congress' decision to back away
from the grand conception of social policy ratified in the 1930s in
favor of a period of decentralized social experimentation. To my
ear the news is fairly reassuring. Most of it comes from Jason
DeParle, an extraordinary reporter for the New York Times Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   There is an awful lot of misery out there, as he makes clear.
And backing away from one system before another is devised may make
it worse for a time. We've undertaken to re-work our main safety
net at a time when the economy is booming. It will go harder than
usual on the poor if and when things turn sour.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is hard not to be intrigued by the manner in which
several states have begun to to rewrite the web of expectations
loosely known as ``the social contract.'' Wisconsin in particular
has used its block grants _ lump-sum payments on a per capita basis
from the Federal government _ to ``construct a safety net not
around a check but around a job,'' DeParle writes. And a universal
work (itals)requirement(unitals) can easily be seen as a universal
(itals)right(unitals) to work. So in the end the main effect of
welfare reform in a post-industrial society may be to establish the
states as employers of last resort.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of an alternating cycle between centralization and
pluralism in American politics has been a fact of life at least
since Henry Adams first enunciated it more than a century ago in
his ``History of the United States During the Administrations of
Jefferson and Madison.'' Maybe something of what was lost with the
orphanage can be reclaimed. What I wish this holiday season is that
there was a little less dot.com and a little more examination of
the issues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
