<HEADER>
A2130 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-DALLAS-SPELLMAN-H     12-17 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DALLAS-SPELLMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FAITH IN GOD HELPS COWBOY FIND REBIRTH ON THE FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM ORSBORN  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Seven months ago, Alonzo Spellman sat on the
edge of his bed one night and wondered how life became so painful.
</P>
<P>
   ```It was like, `Man, what's next?''' said Spellman, remembering
what he calls the lowest point of his life.
</P>
<P>
   It was at that moment that everything became brighter, his
worries faded and his road to recovery began.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when God walked into my life and said, `I'm what's
next, because you don't have a what's next.' Everything else
changed from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it did. Instead of making headlines for being involved in
one bizarre incident after another, the former first-round draft
pick starts at defensive tackle for the Dallas Cowboys and is
playing some of the best football of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done a tremendous job of turning things around in his
life,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said, ``and we are the
beneficiaries of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the Cowboys who are benefiting from Spellman's
rejuvenation. Texas advocates for mental health believe his
well-documented struggles with bipolar disorder will help others
who suffer from manic depression understand they can lead
productive lives.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Mental Health Association, bipolar
disorder is a mental illness that involves episodes of serious
mania and depression. At least 2 million Americans suffer from
bipolar disorder, which some researchers believe is caused by a
biochemical imbalance.
</P>
<P>
   ``His story is a survivor's story, a story of triumph and
hope,`` said Ray Kenny, president of the Mental Health Association
of Greater San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a story of faith and the power of prayer, two things
Spellman believes were the tools that helped him rebuild his life.
</P>
<P>
   Happiness was all Spellman knew after the Chicago Bears drafted
him with the 22nd overall pick in 1992. Blessed with a
muscle-bound, 6-foot-4, 290-pound body, he appeared to be well on
his way to an outstanding career in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   But he made a wrong turn in his spiritual life when he left Ohio
State after his junior season. Instead of staying connected to his
family and church, he drifted away from his emotional anchors and
adopted a lifestyle that included fathering three children out of
wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming up, the only thing I focused on in my life was my
family and Christ,'' said the native of Mount Holly, N.J. ``That's
the reason I made it out of the ghetto and became a first-round
pick. But then after I had my success _ first-round pick, big
contract _ I stepped away and started thinking it was more about me
than it was about (God), and he had to chop me back down.''
</P>
<P>
   Spellman, who recorded 31 sacks for Chicago between 1992 and
1997, missed nine games in 1997 with a shoulder injury. The Bears
eventually suspended him for three contests when he refused to
undergo arthroscopic surgery. After an angry confrontation with
then-Bears coach Dave Wannstedt, Spellman told the team he was
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a series of bizarre incidents in the spring
and summer of 1998 that may have been caused by bipolar disorder
and that most certainly put his life in danger.
</P>
<P>
   In March, he found himself in a standoff with a police SWAT unit
after he barricaded himself in the home of his publicist. He was in
the house for eight hours before former Bears linebacker Mike
Singletary talked him out.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Spellman kicked open the door of his hospital room
and was later found walking the frozen streets of Chicago without a
shirt or shoes.
</P>
<P>
   In April, his 16-month marriage ended in divorce. In June, the
Bears cut him with two years left on his contract. That same month,
he was arrested and charged on a felony weapons count in Michigan
and received a face full of pepper spray from the police in an
altercation at a Detroit hotel
</P>
<P>
   In July, he was evicted from his suburban Chicago home. Two
months later, the police found him asleep in his car as it raced
down the fast lane of an interstate highway.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, as his nightmare year drew to a close, Spellman asked
God for relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prayed every day for God to give me an answer, to talk to
me, to help me, some how, some way,'' said Spellman, 28.
</P>
<P>
   Help from a higher power finally arrived this past May while he
sat alone in the bedroom of his Chicago home.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did next was cry,'' he said. ``I fell on my knees and
started praying.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he felt like a great weight had been lifted from his
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a feeling you can't really explain,'' he said. ``I just
couldn't stop the tears from coming out of my eyes. It's a very
releasing feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   s he prayed daily, good things started to happen, he said. He
renewed his relationship with his mother, Dorothy Spellman _ she
has the ``faith of a giant,'' he says _ and got a phone call from
Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys cornerback, himself a born-again Christian, decided
to reach out to Spellman after seeing him interviewed on
television. Always on the lookout for peers he can aid spiritually,
Sanders believed that, deep down, Spellman wasn't a bad person.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between a guy causing problems and a guy
with problems,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Spellman: ``If it wasn't for Deion, I probably wouldn't be
here in Dallas. He's got all my respect. He's not just a Hall of
Famer. He's an incredible person. He had a huge impact on my
comfort level when I came here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After establishing a relationship with Spellman, Sanders told
Cowboys owner Jerry Jones about his new friend. In need of
defensive-line help, Jones immediately began doing his homework on
Spellman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry established a very good relationship with Alonzo's
mom,'' said former Cowboys running back Calvin Hill, who works as a
consultant for the team's Player Assistance and Development
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a saying that good fruit falls off good trees, and I
think Jerry knew what kind of stock Alonzo came from. Jerry
deserves all the credit for Alonzo coming here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones had Hill and other club officials learn all they could
about bipolar disorder and develop a program to help Spellman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got everything answered that we wanted answered, it
didn't take me 30 seconds to make up my mind,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones finally signed Spellman on July 29 to a one-year deal
worth the veteran minimum of $400,000. The contract also includes
incentives worth $450,000.
</P>
<P>
   Playing like a man who has a new lease on life, Spellman has
recorded 39 tackles, five sacks, one forced fumble, one fumble
recovery and a team-high 18 quarterback pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really helped our team tremendously,'' said Gailey, who
believes Spellman should receive consideration for a Pro Bowl
berth.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman credits God for his stellar play.
</P>
<P>
   ``My spirit is reborn in Christ, and that's why my game is
reborn,'' he said. ``If I wouldn't have come back to Christ and
been really committed to him, I wouldn't be able to do the things
I'm doing now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
