<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BUCKLEY-FIRING-LINE-2     12-17 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCKLEY-FIRING-LINE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 33 YEARS, A FAREWELL TO BUCKLEY'S `FIRING LINE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even many of the guests who turned out at the Museum
of Broadcasting on Tuesday to pay tribute to William F. Buckley Jr.
on the occasion of the taping of the final broadcast of ``Firing
Line,'' his weekly program, might be forgiven for being surprised
that it was still on the air.
</P>
<P>
   After 33 years, ``Firing Line,'' the longest-running program in
television history with the same host, had long since lost its
buzz, having been supplanted by many other programs in which
outspoken conservative commentators hold forth. But to chroniclers
of Buckley's life and the conservative movement, ``Firing Line''
was the first and the most important in widely establishing
conservatism as a serious intellectual movement in America
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the program played a critical role in Buckley's signal
achievement: almost singlehandedly ``dekooking'' a conservative
movement widely identified in the 1950s and '60s with
isolationists, protectionists and bigots and catapulting it into
the mainstream of U.S. politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was opposing the hegemony of liberalism on the outside
looking in,'' said George H. Nash, the historian and author of
``The Conservative Intellectual Movement in America Since 1945''
(Intercollegiate Studies Institute, 1996). ``What `Firing Line'
represents is the opening of the door from the outside to the
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   After the landslide defeat of Barry Goldwater, the movement's
standard-bearer, in the 1964 presidential campaign, prominent
liberals like John Kenneth Galbraith declared that conservatism had
no place in U.S. politics.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley, now 74, was already well known as the defiant author of
``God and Man at Yale,'' the founder of the conservative weekly
National Review and an insurgent New York City mayoral candidate
when ``Firing Line'' first went on the air in April 1966. But the
program quickly took his celebrity to a new level, transforming him
into a cultural icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buckley became best known not as a writer or speaker but as a
television performer,'' wrote John B. Judis in his 1988 biography,
``William F. Buckley: Patron Saint of the Conservatives.''
``Television was the medium through which he projected his own
views and personality onto the canvas of the '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Firing Line'' is also seen as having blazed the trail for the
current wave of pugilistic punditry on television. The idea for a
weekly program in which Buckley would debate a liberal opponent for
an hour was first proposed by an executive at RKO, which owned
WOR-TV in New York. Buckley jumped at the chance to present his
conservative views to a wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot that had been said by National Review that
needed to be said face to face to its critics,'' Buckley recalled
in an interview on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning, Buckley, who was a skilled debater from his
student days at Yale, set out to eviscerate his opponents. Judis
wrote that Neal Freeman, Buckley's personal assistant at the time,
modeled the program after the Friday night fights that were then
nationally televised.
</P>
<P>
   The guest on the first ``Firing Line'' was Norman Thomas, the
Socialist and perennial presidential candidate who was 81 and
losing his eyesight. ``When you argue with a man who is old and
blind, you are pretty tough,'' said Warren Steibel, producer and
director of ``Firing Line'' since its early days. But, he added,
``it made good theater.''
</P>
<P>
   And good television. Buckley drove liberal viewers around the
bend by defending Sen. Joseph McCarthy, tarring his guests as
Communists and questioning such liberal orthodoxy as universal
voting rights in the South. With his tousled hair, blue eyes that
tended to bulge like an exotic lizard's, portentous vocabulary and
halting patrician speech, he quickly established himself as the
face of a new kind of conservatism: intelligent, urbane, witty,
cutting.
</P>
<P>
   By today's standards of political discourse it is hard to
imagine what ``Firing Line'' was like in the late 1960s and early
'70s, Judis said. ``Those shows were an extension of politics,'' he
said. ``They would not just comment on this spectator sport of
politics we have now. They were part of the political debate. That
is why ``Firing Line'' was interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckley was ripe for parody. Like the sportscaster Howard
Cosell, he became a man many viewers detested but could not stop
watching. ``I think you are finally going to displace me as the
most hated man in America,'' novelist Norman Mailer wrote to
Buckley after ``Firing Line'' took off. ``And of course the
position is bearable only if one is No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few years, Buckley mellowed, becoming more generous to
his guests while losing little of his passion. (Judis wrote that
Buckley was so nasty that the program had trouble attracting guests
after its first year but Buckley and Steibel have denied this.) As
a result, his image began to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``He added a kind of charisma and sexiness to conservatism that
had never been there before,'' said Sam Tanenhaus, a contributing
editor at Vanity Fair who is preparing a biography of Buckley.
Young women flocked to him after his public appearances. The
feminist Germaine Greer flirted with him on camera. A 1973 study in
Psychology Today found that many women fantasized about Buckley
during intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firing Line'' became a necessary stop for the leading liberal
figures of the era. Muhammad Ali, Allen Ginsberg, Jesse Jackson,
William M. Kunstler and Murray Kempton, among others, all made
appearances. Buckley was helped by the fact that he counts liberals
like Galbraith and Ira Glasser, executive director of the American
Civil Liberties Union, among his closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By putting Buckley alongside liberal celebrities, his
conservative views were given equal weight at a time when few
people took conservatives seriously and there were many fewer
outlets on television than there are today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody said I am going to apostatize as a result of seeing
`Firing Line,''' Buckley said, using one of his trademark $5 words.
``The challenge of conservatives in those years was not to convert
others to our point of view but to convince them that conservative
views weren't held by savages.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Firing Line'' retained its clout throughout the 1970s but its
influence, as well as that of National Review and Buckley's
syndicated column, began to wane after Ronald Reagan was elected
president in 1980. While Reagan called Buckley, his longtime ally,
``the most influential journalist and intellectual in our era,''
his victory occurred alongside the ascendance of a new generation
of conservative pundits like the columnist George Will.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley said that there was no particular pressure on him to
discontinue ``Firing Line,'' which was cut back to a half-hour from
an hour in the mid-1980s. But since the program had to end
sometime, he said, it might as well be at the end of the
millennium. He said he planned to continue writing his column and
books. The last ``Firing Line,'' which is the second installment of
a two-part retrospective, will be distributed to 294 PBS stations
on Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   It seems unlikely that any conservative commentator will soon
reproduce the influence that Buckley and ``Firing Line'' had at
their peak. ``He had tremendous intelligence and wit,'' Judis said
of Buckley. ``That is a quality that is not necessarily valued now
on television. It takes time to debate someone. You don't do it in
a minute while the viewer goes from channel to channel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
