u a BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT     12-17 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Dec. 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Temperatures plummeted to minus 10 degrees Fahrenheit on Friday
morning at International Falls, Minn., as an Arctic air mass
continued to numb the upper Midwest. Saturday, the Arctic air will
retreat north into Canada as its high pressure center shifts east
and gives way to a low pressure system approaching from Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   South of this ``Alberta Clipper,'' a disturbance, which Friday
came ashore in the Pacific Northwest, will produce snow in the
northern Rockies early Saturday morning. Snow will taper to snow
showers as the disturbance moves eastward.
</P>
<P>
   In its wake, winds averaging 20 mph to 30 mph _ with gusts to 40
mph or more _ will develop east of the mountains in Montana and
Wyoming. Ahead of the disturbance, winds from the west-northwest
could exceed 40 mph across eastern Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a fresh Arctic air mass amassing in western Canada
will invade the high plains Saturday night across eastern Montana,
northeast Wyoming and the western Dakotas, accompanied by gusty,
frigid winds from the northwest. Winds gusts of more than 30 mph
are likely, adding a bitter bite to the already frigid air.
</P>
<P>
   A wet disturbance, which Friday moved over portions of Oklahoma
and the southern Plains will produce broken areas of cool rain
across parts of the central Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   A chilly Canadian high pressure system will build into the
Northeast on Saturday. On its southern flank, a swath of low clouds
will cover northern parts of the Middle Atlantic states, although
very little, if any, precipitation will fall from these clouds.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SIBERIAN INVASION
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, temperatures dipped below minus 50 degrees
Fahrenheit at the Russian town of Vitim along the southern fringes
of Siberia as an infamously frigid Siberian high, with a central
barometric pressure of 31.33 inches of mercury, settled over the
region. In winter, Siberia lays claim to breeding the northern
hemisphere's coldest air masses. When winds blow across the North
Pole, frigid air masses born in Siberia invade North America. Next
week, a ``cross-polar flow'' of Siberian air will aim at the
northeastern quadrant of the nation, setting the stage for a bitter
Christmas Eve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
