<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2138 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     12-17 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SANTA DEBATE GROWS NASTY
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Monday, Dec. 20)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year, around this time, people divide into two camps:
Those who subscribe to the magic ``reindeer-dust'' theory and those 
flying-reindeer/fat-Santa/gifts-for-all-the-good-little-boys-and-gir
ls who believe that a 353,430-ton payload traveling at 650 miles
per second through the atmosphere would absorb approximately 14.3
quintillion joules of energy, per second, per reindeer, turning the
whole festive, holiday wad into a flaming charcoal briquette in
something like four-thousandths of a second.
</P>
<P>
   The two camps, needless to say, do not get along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disbeliever!'' hiss the magic-dusters to the
charcoal-briquetters.
</P>
<P>
   ``English major!'' retort the briquetters.
</P>
<P>
   The passion with which both sides defend their viewpoints
reminds one of the evolution/creationism debate, only with caribou
instead of monkeys. (School boards don't have to deal with the
controversy since the subject is Christmas-related and therefore
off-limits. However, free birth-control for flying reindeer can be
obtained in some school clinics, with or without a note from a
parent.)
</P>
<P>
   Politicians are either reluctant to take a side in the debate
for fear of losing votes or else simply ``don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the editor, Dan Quayle said he believes
``raindear'' are destroying family values because in every cartoon
and comic book he's ever seen, Rudolph isn't wearing any clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Caught off-guard in an ``ambush'' interview by Don Imus, George
W. Bush confused Santa Claus with the prime minister of India.
</P>
<P>
   Adroitly side-stepping the locomotion question altogether, Al
Gore said he is a ``friend'' of all endangered species, including
flying reindeer, and would be proud to pose with some as long as
Bill Clinton's not in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   A visibly angry John McCain said he was tortured by flying
reindeer in a Hanoi prisoner-of-war camp and proceeded to punch the
interviewer in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, most, if not all, of the serious discussion on
this topic takes place between the magic-dusters and
charcoal-briquetters themselves. The debate has been going on for
many years with little or no new ground being plowed. The
briquetters, many of whom have crew-cuts and wear Drew Carey-style
eyeglasses, challenge their rivals to produce ``a single gram'' of
magic reindeer-dust. (Not surprisingly, the briquetters are big
fans of the metric system.) When they are feeling especially mean,
they compare magic reindeer-dust to trickle-down economics and
Nixon's ``secret plan'' to get us out of Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The magic-dusters, who lean more toward the Jewel look (a look
that works much better for women than it does for men, by the way),
counter that magic reindeer-dust is not something you can scoop out
of a wooden bin in a health-food store like so much St. John's wort
or ginko biloba. It is produced exclusively by Santa Claus, only on
Christmas Eve, and only in sufficient quantities to sprinkle on the
heads of the eight tiny reindeer so that they can fly invisibly at
the speed of light, or slightly faster, depending on wind
conditions and how many boys and girls have been good that year. It
is not available commercially, and even if it were, it would not
allow you to fly because it would be out of date.(The magic-dusters
concede that it might be useful in treating mild cases of anxiety
or constipation, but prefer to stick to the main issue.)
</P>
<P>
   But the most persuasive argument the magic-dusters have going
for them is this: If Santa and his sleigh and his reindeer and his
toys and goodies for all the good little boys and girls of the
world were reduced to a flaming charcoal briquette by atmospheric
friction, then how is it that the presents get delivered year after
year after year?
</P>
<P>
   The briquetters, who might have said NASA before the crash of
the second Mars probe, are still searching for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
