<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET2-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (Adds China-Macao and Russia-Candidates)  
 For Release SATURDAY AMs, December 18, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-COUNCIL (London) _ The final piece of the institutional
jigsaw puzzle at the heart of the Good Friday Agreement of 1998
falls into place as Tony Blair and Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern,
convene the first meeting of the council that will oversee areas of
mutual interest on the islands of Britain and Ireland. By Kevin
Cullen. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MACAO (Macao) _ The last vestige of Europe's colonial era
in Asia comes to an end as China regains control this weekend of
the Portuguese territory of Macao. In Macao, almost everyone is
happy about it, even the Portuguese. By Indira A.R. Lakshmanan.
1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   UN-IRAQ (New York) _ The UN Security Council, ending months of
contentious negotiations, adopts a resolution that could send
weapons inspectors back to Iraq and ease Gulf War sanctions if it
cooperates with a new UN disarmament agency. By Joe Lauria Jr. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CANDIDATES (Moscow) _ The list of candidates running in
