<HEADER>
A2144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AMERICAN-LUCK-2TAKES-     12-17 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-LUCK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CULTURE OF BOTH LUCK AND PLUCK 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.J., Pa.)  (Eds: 1st three grafs should be set in italics.) 
(DW) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I know what you're thinking. Did he fire six shots or only
five? Well, to tell you the truth, in all the excitement, I kind of
lost track myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Dirty Harry, scowling, a last bite of hot dog still tucked into
his cheek, holds a long-barreled revolver on a wounded robber,
prostrate on the sidewalk, whose own gun is just inches from his
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, seeing as how this is a .44 magnum, the most powerful
handgun in the world, I guess you've got to ask yourself one
question: Do I feel lucky? Well, do you, punk?''
</P>
<P>
   There it is, in a nutshell, in Don Siegel's 1971 Clint Eastwood
thriller. The forces of moral order playing a cruel game of chance
with an antisocial representative of the culture of luck. That
fault line runs through the heart of American history, says Jackson
Lears, a historian at Rutgers University who is writing a cultural
history of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I believe that we have this dominant culture, a
culture of control, which emphasizes technical mastery over one's
fate through systematic achievement and personal moral
responsibility, whose view of luck is that you make your own
luck,'' said Lears, best known for ``Fables of Abundance,'' his
1994 cultural history of advertising, and ``No Place of Grace,''
his 1981 history of anti-modernist criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where we get our ideals of the self-made man and a lot
of our success mythology. Yet even Horatio Alger realized that luck
is as important as pluck. Look back at these classic tales of
American success, and you will find that the key event in every
young hero's rise to respectability is a fortuitous event that is
beyond his control, the intervention of a wealthy benefactor at a
crucial moment or saving an innocent heiress from Bowery toughs.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as two threads that run through American history _
two ways of seeing the world _ and that America, as we understand
it, is impossible without the continuous interplay between them. On
one side there is the scrupulous ant, on the other the
devil-may-care grasshopper; or, speaking in a more American idiom,
the risk-taking cattlemen of the wide open range versus the
fence-building farmers. While the ants, the dominant culture, see
the world as a place that rewards the prepared and the
hard-working, the grasshoppers see it also as a place governed by
sheer dumb luck, where something like grace and magic can play as
large a role in individual destiny as keeping your nose to the
grindstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common practice of wishing someone good luck is not a
matter of suggesting that they are incompetent,'' wrote Nicholas
Rescher, a philosophy professor at the University of Pittsburgh, in
``Luck: The Brilliant Randomness of Everyday Life,'' published in
1995, ``but rather reflects our realization that competence alone
is not enough to secure success in a chancy world _ that there is
always the prospect that even the best possible effort may not meet
with the success it deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Though many of the same themes are played out in other cultures,
it is particularly strong in American culture, Lears says. ``I'm
pretty committed to the idea that we have certain unifying themes
that we can characterize as constitutive of American culture,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Luck seems to be one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis de Tocqueville understood this. ``What you find in his
work and a lot of other commentators on early American economic
history is the fascination with risk, the sheer excitement of it,
the fascination with intense experience as an end in itself,''
Lears said. ``We have a culture that can both celebrate and deny
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Main Street sings America's song, but so does Las Vegas
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   If someone strikes it rich, if he gets that promotion, if the
horse or the stock he picks carries the day, then it is simply his
just reward for the hard work and preparation that he put into it.
But there is also that American soft spot for the person who goes
over the far mountain into the wild unknown, who buys a lottery
ticket even though he knows that it's a sucker bet, who bungee
jumps off a cliff and is willing to put everything on the line,
well beyond reason, for the downright thrill of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning is a big thing in our culture _ a fist in the air, an
archetype, the late-20th-century American gesture,'' wrote
Frederick and Steven Barthelme in ``Double Down,'' their recent
memoir about how they squandered their inheritance in Gulf Coast
casinos. ``Winning is everything, many have said. In that word
there is a magic release from the weight of all those nagging, dull
concerns you're accustomed to carrying.''
</P>
<P>
   A magic release.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the culture of chance, the recognition that there are
in fact important forces beyond our control that shape our
destinies and that this is a powerful countercorrective that runs
against the dominant mythology of the self-made man,'' Lears said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Auster, in his 1990 novel, ``The Music of Chance,'' has one
of his characters describe it in a slightly different way. ``It's
as though God has singled us out from other men,'' says the
character, a rich gambler, explaining a long winning streak. ``He's
showered us with good fortune and lifted us to heights of
happiness. I know this might sound presumptuous to you, but at
times I feel that we've become immortal.''
</P>
<P>
   All through American history there is celebration of
risk-takers, from the pioneers to the day-traders, existing side by
side with the proponents of hard work and making money the
old-fashioned way. What is particularly interesting, Lears says, is
that while there has been ebb and flow in the relative strengths of
these opposing worldviews over the centuries, the champions of luck
have been resurgent lately, as shown by the explosive growth in
gambling, the risk-embracing entrepreneurial ethos championed by
Ronald Reagan and the recent day-trading phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Fabian, a cultural historian whose 1990 book ``Card Sharps
and Bucket Shops: Gambling in 19th-Century America,'' has just been
rereleased in paperback, agrees that the gambling boom is mirrored
in such enthusiasms as day-trading. ``You can't think of these
attitudes on luck and gambling as divorced from other attitudes
toward economics and culture,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What is interesting in the current risk boom, Ms. Fabian said,
is that it involves a much wider swath of the community. ``It used
to be that gambling was an activity for the very rich and the very
poor,'' she said. ``But now it is reaching a much larger segment of
the population, into the middle class.''
(MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   As Lears looked more closely at this culture of luck, the more
he was able to see American history as a kind of battle between
these two opposing worldviews. Before the 1820s, he said, the
culture of chance was ascendant, with popular philosophers of the
time talking about Fortuna, the old Roman goddess of luck, and
about the mutability of fate and unpredictability of life.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1820s, with the rise of evangelical Protestantism, the
culture of control asserted itself, crusading against gambling and
promoting moral and business principles. During and immediately
after the Civil War, when it became painfully clear how large a
role chance played in who lived and who died, there was a
resurgence in interest in luck, but by the turn of the century,
with monopolists trying to control chance in the economy and social
reformers trying to mute its effect in the ghettos, the culture of
control was again ascendant.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s and '30s, gamblers were either objects of menace,
as in James Cagney movies, or faintly ridiculous, as they were in
Damon Runyon stories. ``Those guys in the Runyon stories inhabit a
specific universe that exemplifies the culture of chance,'' Lears
said. ``Everybody talks in the present tense, there is an ethos of
not hoarding, of reckless generosity, of no thought for the
morrow.'' Efforts were made in these years to harness chance, both
in business (the rise of market research) and in science. This
cultural mood persisted into the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Job security is a reality for much of the population in that
period,'' Lears said. ``My favorite example of the mind-set of the
period is the slogan that Roy Rogers always had at the end of his
television program: `Be brave, but don't take chances.' That sort
of self-canceling advice epitomized the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in the mid-1960s, with the institution of the first state
lottery and, 10 years later, the expansion of gambling to Atlantic
City, N.J., and then elsewhere, that the culture of chance began
its current rise. Suddenly, gangsters in ``The Godfather'' were
equated with businessmen and a risk-loving,
get-rich-while-you're-young ethos supplanted the stodgy old coots
in their smoke-filled clubs.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s and into the '90s, job security was no longer the
norm. Fear and uncertainty entered the marketplace and the American
home, and the difference between speculation and investment got
murkier and murkier. ``One of the phrases that strikes me as
particularly revealing in marking the re-emergence of the culture
of chance is the whole idea of the contingent labor force,'' Lears
said. Once again people became interested in finding ways to
understand and perhaps even govern chance. ``Even chaos theorists
are interested in locating patterns in the chaos,'' Lears said.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the battle lines sometimes got harder to
determine.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Dirty Harry,'' the prostrate robber declines to reach for
his gun and Harry pulls the trigger with a smirk. Click. An empty
chamber. Then, at the end of the movie, another criminal finds
himself in the same position. ``Do you feel lucky, punk?'' This one
grabs for his gun and Harry pulls the trigger. Blam! One dead
criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Harry knew each time whether there was a bullet in the
chamber. Maybe the culture of control won the day over the culture
of chance through perseverance, hard work and determination.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe he was just lucky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
