<HEADLINE>
$5.2 BILLION COMPENSATION PLAN APPROVED FOR NAZI-ERA WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ American and German officials formally agreed Friday on
a $5.2 billion plan to compensate surviving slave workers and other
victims of the Nazi era.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to heal old wounds as well as resolve several
class-action suits against German companies, President Johannes Rau
punctuated the financial agreement with a moving apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pay tribute to all those who were subjected to slave and
forced labor under German rule, and, in the name of Germany, beg
forgiveness,'' Rau said. ``Their suffering will not be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement covers far more than former forced workers. It is,
in effect, a catchall agreement to settle all remaining disputes
and suits that involve the Nazi era.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement covers claims over ``Aryanization'' programs under
which German Jews were forced to sell their properties and their
businesses at low prices, often to the profit of German banks. It
also includes unpaid insurance claims owed by German insurers, and
it includes virtually all miscellaneous abuses such as those
stemming from medical experiments in concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the agreement is what amounts to a legal guarantee by
the U.S. government that it will oppose future suits against German
companies that involve the Nazi past.
</P>
<P>
   But even as negotiators hailed the agreement, reached after
nearly a year of bruising talks, officials braced for new and
potentially nasty fights over distributing the money.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult and emotional issue is how to allocate the
money between slave workers, who were kept in concentration camps
and usually worked to their deaths, and forced laborers, who worked
against their will but received at least some pay and better
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   American officials estimate that 240,000 former slave workers
are alive, about half Jewish. Estimates of the number of forced
laborers range from 700,000 to 1.5 million, although some lawyers
say the total may be 2.3 million. Those survivors are scattered
across Central Europe and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Most negotiators agree in principle that slave workers should
receive more compensation. But there are major differences over how
much more. American officials are worried about conflicts between
American Jewish groups, who have played a pivotal political role
but represent a small minority of the victims, and groups that
represent forced workers, who are overwhelmingly non-Jewish, in
Poland, the Czech Republic, Belarus, Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be very difficult and extremely emotional,'' predicted
Stuart Eizenstat, the U.S. deputy treasury secretary who mediated
on behalf of groups that demanded compensation from Germany. He
said survivors would not start receiving money for about a year.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.5 billion settlement that Swiss banks reached two years
ago over claims that stemmed from plundered gold and from dormant
bank accounts that belonged to Jewish Holocaust victims prompted
bitter battles among Jewish groups, class-action lawyers and other
groups involved in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Another uncertainty, though probably not a big problem, is where
the money will come from. In principle, the German government and
German industry will each contribute 5 billion marks, for a total
of $5.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But 70 companies have thus far pledged to contribute, and their
commitments fall well short of 5 billion marks. ``There is still a
big gap, but I feel confident we can fill it,'' said Manfred Gentz,
chief financial officer of DaimlerChrysler and leader of the
industry group.
</P>
<P>
   Gentz said the German subsidiary of General Motors, Adam Opel,
has in principle pledged to give money to the fund. The German unit
of Ford, Ford Werke, is expected to join, as well.
</P>
<P>
   In an executive agreement between the United States and Germany,
the American government will pledge itself to oppose suits. In case
of a Holocaust-related suit, Washington will file a standing
statement to urge the court to reject it.
</P>
<P>
   The statement will argue that the new fund should be the
``exclusive'' remedy for all Holocaust claims and that any new
suits would be against American interests.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether that will protect German companies
from litigation, given that American class-action suits have proven
to be formidable bargaining tools.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it is clear that German companies and the German
government, which has already paid out 60 billion marks, in
reparations since the end of World War II, are determined to make
this 10 billion marks their last payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten billion marks is a final amount,'' said Otto Lambsdorff,
the lead negotiator for German industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
