r l BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     12-17 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAGUAR XKR: MORE POWER, MORE FUN, MORE MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. Chambers Williams III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   More power, more performance and more fun. More money, too.
</P>
<P>
   That sums up the 2000 Jaguar XKR, a new, speedier version of the
XK8 that was introduced in 1997. As Jag's flagship model, the XKR
carries a base price of $76,800 for the coupe and $81,800 for the
convertible, which we tested for this report.
</P>
<P>
   The extra power comes from supercharging the 4.0-liter AJ-V-8
engine in the XK8, raising the horsepower to 370 from 290, and the
torque to 387 foot-pounds from 284.
</P>
<P>
   I thought the XK8's 290 horsepower was plenty _ until I mashed
the accelerator on the XKR for the first time, and got a rush
somewhat like the feel of the Concorde supersonic jetliner speeding
down the runway on takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Recognition of that supreme acceleration isn't limited to
adults. My 2-year-old granddaughter, Savanna, riding shotgun in her
safety seat, giggled out loud each time I briskly accelerated the
XKR. Already, she understands driving excitement; it must be in the
genes.
</P>
<P>
   With a specially modified Mercedes-Benz five-speed automatic
transmission, the XKR convertible goes from zero to 60 mph in 5.3
seconds (5.2 seconds for the coupe), making it the
fastest-accelerating Jaguar on the market. It's also one of the
fastest cars on the market.
</P>
<P>
   The XKR's appearance is distinguished from the XK8 by its
wire-mesh grille, functional hood louvers, deck-lid spoiler and
18-inch alloy wheels that come with Z-rated Pirelli tires.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, this car is gorgeous. The lines flow much more
smoothly than those of the XJ series, in effect giving the car a
more modernistic look. Still, the car is clearly a Jaguar, and that
was a primary goal in creating the XK series' design.
</P>
<P>
   I can't tell you this is the most practical car in the world.
The designers won out over the engineers, which makes the car look
better than it would have if the engineers had been allowed to give
it more head room, better outward visibility and a functional rear
seat.
</P>
<P>
   The XKR is hard to get into and out of, thanks in part to the
low roof line. Sitting in the driver's seat, the top of my head was
brushing the canvas roof _ an annoyance that is forgotten during
the brisk acceleration mentioned above.
</P>
<P>
   Handling is typically Jaguar. This is a rather big, heavy car to
be called a sports car, so it's not as nimble as some pure sports
cars. But for its size, the XKR's road-hugging abilities are
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The handling characteristics are aided by Jaguar's Computer
Active Technology Suspension, standard on the XKR. This system
provides automatic two-stage damping to ensure superior handling,
ride comfort and driver control. Cornering is further assisted by
the Servotronic II steering system, which varies the amount of
power-steering assist depending on the speed. At medium to high
speeds, this system reduces power-steering assist to keep the wheel
firmer.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-spoke alloy wheels were designed to aid performance, too.
They are 8 inches wide at the front of the car and 9 inches wide at
the rear. The Pirelli P Zero tires _ 245/45 at the front and 255/45
at the rear _ were specifically designed for the XKR to optimize
steering response and high-speed stability, Jaguar says.
</P>
<P>
   The twin hood louvers are used to help control the car at high
speeds. Midway between the nose and the windshield, the louvers
create a low-pressure zone to help draw air through the radiator,
as well as reducing aerodynamic lift in the front end. The small
spoiler lip on the edge of the trunk works in concert with the
louvers to balance the car for high-speed stability.
</P>
<P>
   Visibility from the driver's seat is limited by the narrow
windows, and with the top down, it's hard to see clearly to the
rear. We didn't get to drive with the top down very much, however,
because it was just too cold the week we had the XKR.
</P>
<P>
   The premium AM/FM/cassette stereo with trunk-mounted
compact-disc changer was a welcome feature. It's an outstanding
system worthy of a vehicle in this price range.
</P>
<P>
   The power controls for the driver's seat are rather hard to
reach. They are on the lower front edge of the side of the seat.
You really need to have the door open to work the controls
efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Once you are planted inside, the front bucket seats are rather
comfy. The rear seat is just for looks _ there is no leg room. You
could put a dog back there, but not much else. The trunk of the
convertible is rather small _ 9.5 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   Amenities abound, as you would imagine. Connolly leather seats
and burl walnut interior trim are standard, along with traction
control; heated seats; headlight washers/wipers; rain-sensing
windshield wipers; automatic headlights; power windows and door
locks; and remote-control locking/unlocking.
</P>
<P>
   Only one option is offered: a Global Positioning System-based
navigation system, with moving map mounted in the center of the
dash. This $2,400 system was included on our test car. There was
one serious problem with it, however: The screen is way too bright
at night _ so bright I had to turn it off. A similar system offered
in Lexus vehicles has a night setting that tones it down; without
that, the Jag system is more a nuisance than a help at night. There
was a setting on the Jag system for night driving, but it did not
lower the brightness.
</P>
<P>
   Total price of our test vehicle was $84,200.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 16 miles per gallon in the city and
22 on the highway for the convertible; 16 city/23 highway for the
coupe. The tank holds 19.9 gallons, and unleaded premium gasoline
is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE:
</P>
<P>
   2000 Jaguar XKR convertible
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Premium, midsize, two-door, supercharged V-8
powered, rear-drive, high- performance convertible.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: New for 2000 (in the United States; it has been on
sale in Europe for two years), the XKR is Jag's new flagship
vehicle. It comes in coupe and convertible versions, with more
power than any other Jaguar, great roadhandling and gorgeous
styling.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: Hard to get into and out of, head room and outward
visibility are limited, high price tag.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Mercedes-Benz SL.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 16 mpg city/22 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE: $81,800.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE AS TESTED: $84,200.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A-minus.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his e-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
