<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, Dec. 18 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ A divided Security Council voted
Friday to create a new arms inspection system for Iraq with the
promise to President Saddam Hussein that sanctions against his
country could be suspended within a year and eventually lifted if
he cooperates. The vote was 11 in favor and 4 abstentions. At the
decisive moment, France broke ranks with the United States and the
European Union and abstained along with Russia, China and Malaysia,
which holds a non-permanent Security Council seat. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   EPA-AIR-POLLUTION (Washington) _ The Environmental Protection
Administration on Friday ordered 392 plants in a dozen states,
mostly electric generating stations, to cut in half emissions that
drift with prevailing winds and create smog along the Eastern
seaboard. The federal regulators acted at the request of New York,
Connecticut, Massachusetts and Pennsylvania, which said they needed
help to meet national smog standards. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TOBACCO-TAX (Albany, N.Y.) _ Gov. George Pataki and
legislative leaders from both parties agreed Friday to raise the
state's cigarette tax by 55 cents a pack in an ambitious effort to
provide health care coverage for as many as one million uninsured
New Yorkers. By Raymond Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTING-SETTLE (New York) _ Ernst &AMP; Young, the world's third
largest accounting firm, agreed Friday to pay $335 million to
settle a suit contending that it certified financial statements
that fraudulently inflated the earnings and profits of Cendant
Corp., the big franchiser that operates Ramada and Avis. The
settlement was by far the largest ever by an accounting firm
accused of improper practices. And although Ernst &AMP; Young said that
it had been duped itself and had done nothing wrong, accounting
experts said it was a sad day for the accounting profession and
that perhaps new procedures were needed. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-ARREST (Seattle) _ U.S. Customs agents arrested a man
crossing the Canadian border into the United States with 200 pounds
of powerful explosives and timing devices, a government source said
Friday. The man, who carried Canadian identification papers with
two different names, tried to outrun the agents Tuesday after they
found two garbage bags full of white powder in his rented car,
investigators said. (Summary from wires) By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-SUBURBS (Mexico City) _ A new class of commuters has
emerged in Mexico. A half-century after Americans began to abandon
cities for suburbs, thousands of Mexicans are for the first time
making a similar choice, fleeing the pollution and clamor of Mexico
City in search of quiet homes, well-clipped lawns and safer streets
in cities and towns hours away from the capital. By Sam Dillon.
