<HEADER>
A2149 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NITEOUT-HEPPNER-$ADV1     12-17 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-HEPPNER-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH BEN HEPPNER TACKLING TRISTAN, LOVING BUGS BUNNY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)   (For release Sunday, Dec. 19.)  
(DW) 
 By JEREMY EICHLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Excuse me while I slip into something a bit more
flame-retardant,'' said Ben Heppner, the Canadian tenor who
concluded his role as Tristan in the Metropolitan Opera's sold-out
``Tristan und Isolde'' with Saturday's broadcast performance.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to fans at the Canadian Consulate in Manhattan on
Wednesday night, Heppner was quoting his own joke from other Wagner
operas he has performed around the world, many of which utilize
smoke or fire.
</P>
<P>
   Flame-retardant or otherwise, Heppner, 43, has become a
superhero in operatic circles. The role of Tristan is regarded as
the most punishing vocal part in the tenor repertory, and until
Heppner and his Isolde (the soprano Jane Eaglen) stepped up, the
Met had not produced the work in almost 16 years. Wagner fans, a
group not known for tepid opinions, greeted this production a bit
like die-hard football fans might greet a Super Bowl Sunday _ one
that had been delayed for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for being you!'' one man exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   A towering figure whose physique is proportional to his voice,
Heppner arrived in an elegant dark suit, a vest with lapels and
black leather pointed boots. Seventy-five guests _ a mixture of
proud Canadians and reverential Wagnerians _ whooped and applauded.
Nonetheless, the tenor looked exhausted; his performance the night
before began at 7 p.m. and ended after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am experiencing a good bit of Wagner lag,'' he confessed.
``It's like jet lag, except it's in German.''
</P>
<P>
   As the night wore on, Heppner seemed buoyed by the admirers
around him. The question among these fans was not whether one had
seen the new production, but whether one had made it to all seven
performances so far. (Several had.) One man said he had purchased a
new stereo system to record the international radio broadcast of
the final matinee, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these people know more about me than my children do,''
Heppner said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Heppner was whisked off with the Canadian consul general,
Michael Phillips, to Phillips' private residence on Park Avenue for
a dinner in Heppner's honor. In attendance were other Canadian
dignitaries, as well as officials from the Wagner Society of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Seated at a table resplendent with silver candlesticks,
variegated holly and mimosa plants, Heppner polished off six
courses that included chanterelle mushroom ravioli in tomato butter
and grilled sirloin of lamb with sunchoke and potato puree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have to watch what you eat?'' asked Ellen Wright, a
member of the Canadian delegation to the United Nations and the
wife of the deputy consul general, Dwayne Wright. ``Apparently
not,'' Heppner said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   There was chat around the table about Heppner's humble origins
in northern British Columbia and his love of limited-edition
acetate cells from the Warner Brothers cartoons of Bugs Bunny
singing opera. ``Kill the wabbit, kill the wabbit,'' Heppner sang
under his breath.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wright requested a real song, but Heppner demurred, saying,
``All my resources have been spent on Tristan.'' He added that he
would not even speak the next day in preparation for Saturday's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Before slipping off, however, he surprised Ms. Wright by placing
his hands on her shoulders and singing for her the opening of a
love aria from Benjamin Britten's ``Peter Grimes.'' Ms. Wright
bubbled with excitement: ``He sang to me! Did everyone hear? He
sang to me!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
