u p BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     12-17 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN DEMS STILL GO THEIR OWN WAY IN CONGRESS  
 SOUTHERN HOSTILITY TOWARD GAYS IN THE MILITARY  
 RHETORIC ON TOBACCO  
 GODFATHER OF SOUL LIKES STROM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: The South)  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Conservative Southern Democrats are fewer in
number, but they still manage to make their presence felt in
Congress by bucking the party line.
</P>
<P>
   A new analysis by Congressional Quarterly found that a handful
of Dixie Dems in both the House and Senate were among the most
likely to balk at the party's position on any number of issues.
John Breaux of Louisiana, for example, was the most rebellious
Democrat in the Senate, breaking with Democrats on 25 percent of
key votes, while his Louisiana colleague Mary Landrieu was third
with a 19 percent rating.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Democrat Virgil Goode of Virginia voted against
his party's position an astonishing 78 percent of the time to take
the rebel award. Other Southern Democrats who regularly broke ranks
included Reps. Bud Cramer of Alabama, who opposed his party on 47
percent of the votes; Chris John of Louisiana, also 47 percent; and
Mike McIntyre of North Carolina, 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the more conservative nature of their constituencies,
white Southern Democrats have historically tormented their party's
congressional leadership through their fractiousness. When
Democrats ran Congress, members of the party's Southern wing often
sided with minority Republicans to bottle up initiatives they
didn't like. Even with the GOP in charge, Southern independence is
having an impact.
</P>
<P>
   CQ's review found that the Blue Dog Coalition, a caucus that
includes many moderate and conservative Democrats from the South,
tipped the outcome on a handful of votes by siding with Republicans
_ including high-profile proposals on gun control and arts funding.
If a majority of the 30-member coalition had instead sided with
Democrats, the outcome would have been reversed.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine predicted that the feisty group could become even
more influential _ and pose a headache for Democratic leaders _ if
the party manages to win back the House in next year's election.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T ASK, DON'T TELL
</P>
<P>
   Democratic presidential candidates Al Gore and Bill Bradley,
battling for primary election voters, are advocating allowing
homosexuals to serve openly in the military, branding the
administration's existing policy a failure as evidenced by the
beating death of a gay soldier.
</P>
<P>
   While the position could have its appeal in the primary for the
two men, it could cost them later, particularly in the South. Many
in the region, which prides itself on military tradition and a
network of installations, reacted with open hostility to President
Clinton when he proposed ending a ban on gays serving within days
of assuming office in 1993. The fact that Clinton's record on the
draft was murky did not help matters.
</P>
<P>
   Southern lawmakers, including former Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia,
led the effort to try to retain the ban on gays though Nunn
eventually compromised. The unfolding campaign could show whether
sentiments have changed with the passage of time and the fact that
it is not Clinton advocating the change.
</P>
<P>
   WITH FRIENDS LIKE THESE ...
</P>
<P>
   Looking to exploit a sympathetic political constituency, both
anti-tobacco advocates and cigarette manufacturers claim to be
looking out for the best interests of tobacco farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The rhetoric has heated up with a new report that details how
U.S. cigarette manufacturers have sharply curtailed their use of
home-grown tobacco over the past few decades, relying more on
foreign leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Myers, incoming president of the Campaign for
Tobacco-Free Kids, said cigarette manufacturers invoke the plight
of farmers when they want to score some political points on Capitol
Hill, but at other times they focus on their bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cigarette manufacturers like to paint a picture of the
tobacco industry as one big happy family,'' Myers said. ``This
picture is a 20-year-old myth.'' The American Cancer Society and
the American Heart Association also sponsored the report.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarette executives quibble with some details of the report,
but they concede that the move has been toward more foreign
tobacco. Mark Smith, a spokesman for Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco
Corp., said that his company has made a commitment to reverse that
trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in this together for the tobacco farmers,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   HE FEELS GOOD
</P>
<P>
   Long popular in his home state, Sen. Strom Thurmond, the
97-year-old Republican from South Carolina, has apparently found
new fans in the world of rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   In the millennium issue of Rolling Stone magazine, singer James
Brown, the godfather of soul, cited Thurmond as one of his heroes,
along with John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the young whippersnappers get out of line, whether
Democrat or Republican, an old man can walk up and say, `Wait a
minute, son, it goes this way.' And that's great for our country.
He's like a grandfather to me,'' Brown said of Thurmond. ``He's all
of our grandfathers.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
