u i BC-MACAU-CHINA-ART-NYT &LR;      12-17 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACAU-CHINA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH MACAU ALMOST IN HAND, CHINA LOOKS TO TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ When China's leaders in Beijing look south at Macau,
which returns to Chinese sovereignty Sunday night, they do not see
a tiny island rife with casinos and bedeviled by crime.
</P>
<P>
   They see glorious destiny. They see the end of foreign
oppression. And, most importantly, they see a cause for hope that
the mainland will eventually annex Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Once Macau returns, ``the great endeavor of reunifying China
will take a big step forward,'' President Jiang Zemin said last
week. ``Under these circumstances, the task of resolving the Taiwan
issue'' will ``appear increasingly urgent.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the Chinese are going all-out this week to mark the
hand-over of Macau to China, after more nearly 450 years of
colonial rule by Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Although a new millennium arrives in less than two weeks, the
digital countdown clock that now graces Tiananmen Square marks the
seconds to Macau's return. This weekend, there will be a gala on
the square for 30,000 guests featuring fireworks and dragon dances.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, newspapers here are documenting in excruciating
detail the preparations of cities, old folks clubs and religious
groups. They have lovingly described the 600 potted lotuses donated
to Macau by the nearby Chinese city of Zhuhai, and the 12-foot-long
commemorative picture made using 14,000 pieces of fish bone by a
retiree in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese attach great importance to the return of Macau,
primarily for symbolic and political reasons,'' said Jia Qingguo,
an international relations professor at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging Macau's chronic problem with crime, a
byproduct of the gambling that forms the base of its economy, he
said: ``To Chinese, these are practical issues that will be dealt
with between the Chinese government and the new special
administrative region of Macau. The far larger issue is that of
Chinese reunification and that has tremendous symbolic and
emotional value.''
</P>
<P>
   For centuries before the Communists took power in 1949, bits and
piece of China were taken over by Western nations and Japan, a
legacy that still rankles the Chinese. The return of tiny Macau is
viewed as proof of China's rejuvenated status in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that China is once again powerful,'' said a retired
railway conductor surnamed Liu who was out buying vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government clearly hopes that sentiments like these
will boost its popularity at a time of great economic uncertainty.
Still, it is linkage between the Macau hand-over and an eventual
reunification with Taiwan that has consumed China's leaders in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan, a Japanese colony from 1895 to 1945, became the seat of
the Chinese Nationalists after they lost the civil war to the
Communists in 1949 and is still considered a renegade province by
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   With the return of Macau assured, many leaders see Taiwan as the
missing piece of the China puzzle. And they hope that by applying
the ``One Country _Two Systems'' formula of relative autonomy to
Macau, as they have to Hong Kong since its return in 1997, they
will somehow convince Taiwan that reunification is workable.
</P>
<P>
   To help gin up popular enthusiasm, the government has declared a
holiday on Monday and state television will broadcast live from
Macau for the 48 hours surrounding the hand-over. But it is unclear
if the media blitz is having the desired effect.
</P>
<P>
   Many state companies have scheduled events, although in the
spirit of modern China, some are celebrating the return to the
Motherland and the arrival Father Christmas at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'm happy because Macau is China's territory and
it's coming back,'' said Fu Xiaozhen, a fashionably dressed
26-year-old. ``My company is having a joint `return of Macau' and
Christmas party, since it's more convenient that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
