A2153 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TIMBER-STOCK18-COX     12-17 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMBER-STOCK18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wall Street still positive on stock of Timber Co.
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like seedlings in a pine forest, the stock price of
Georgia-Pacific's timber unit may take awhile to grow.
</P>
<P>
   While Timber Co. (ticker TGP) is up 21 percent from a 52-week
low of $19.87 1/2 low in February, the stock is down 75 cents from
its first day of trading two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts said the pulp and paper giant made the right
move in giving Timber Co. its own ticker symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timber Co. is going to be winner year-in and year-out with
cash flow,'' said Joshua Zaret, a timber analyst with Warburg
Dillon Read. ``Management has achieved everything they set out to
do. This is a stock that will come into its own when the (pulp and
paper) market gets a little more volatile and riskier,'' Zaret
said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific Chairman and Chief Executive Pete Correll
created a separate stock for the timber business to unlock the
market value hidden in 5 million acres of forest land _ most of it
pine trees in the Southeast. Unlike the cyclical swings of
Georgia-Pacific's main lines of business _ pulp, paper and building
products _ timber prices generally march upward.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to the current upswing in the paper side of the
business, timber is getting the short end of the stick on Wall
Street, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus is that paper earnings are going to rise fairly
dramatically over the next two years, while wood probably peaked
earlier this year,'' said Zaret. ``Most people are going to play
paper today instead of timber.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Georgia-Pacific Group shares are up 63 percent this
year. The stock closed Friday at $47.62 1/2, up 87 1/2 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific's creation of the letter stock raised some
eyebrows when it was first announced in 1997. Typically used to
ease acquisitions or ward off unwanted takeovers, letter stocks are
not common. By making the timber operations a separate unit with
control over its own profitability, Georgia-Pacific reasoned that
the two stocks would each trade at a higher price than if they
remained together.
</P>
<P>
   Timber Co. is also known as a tracking stock _ tied to part of a
parent company's operations and not a spinoff or independent
company.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the share price doesn't reflect Timber Co.'s
profitability. The company has consistently beat analysts'
estimates. Through the third quarter, Timber Co. reported profit of
$195 million, up 51 percent from the year-ago period. It's expected
to earn about $2.11 a share for the year, according to an average
of analysts' estimates by IBES.
</P>
<P>
   Given the company's performance and the price-per-acre in recent
timberland sales, some analysts have pegged the real value of
Timber Co.'s stock at $30 to $35 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value is there, but the market isn't recognizing it, and
that's masking some of the Timber Co.'s benefits,'' said analyst
Chip Dillon of Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts contend that owning timberland is a good investment
over the long run. While the stock may be undervalued, investors
are getting compensated with steady dividends, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Through dividends and share repurchases, Timber Co. says it has
as returned $399 million to shareholders in the past seven
quarters. The company has repurchased nearly 11 million shares, or
12 percent of its outstanding stock, since it started trading
separately.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1848EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2158 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MEXICO-SUBURBS-ART-NY     12-17 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SUBURBS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO CITY'S SUBURBS ARE GROWING RAPIDLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Cuernavaca, a city of gardens and golfers south of
Mexico City, is still dark at 5:30 a.m. when Mario Betancourt, an
executive with Pemex, the government oil company, crawls from bed
and noses his car into a line of other commuters heading toward
jobs in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuautla, another city south of the capital, Roberto Aguilar
boards a bus for his own two-hour trip to his Mexico City job
varnishing antique furniture.
</P>
<P>
   And at the same hour far to the north, in the city of Pachuca on
the other side of the vast capital, Javier Chavez, a computer
specialist, is beginning his daily drive to work at a Mexico City
cellular phone company.
</P>
<P>
   A new class of commuters has emerged in Mexico. A half-century
after Americans began to abandon cities for suburbs, thousands of
Mexicans are for the first time making a similar choice, fleeing
the pollution and clamor of Mexico City in search of quiet houses,
well-clipped lawns and safer streets in cities and towns hours
away.
</P>
<P>
   The commuters are bringing broad changes to the face of the
countryside for 100 miles on all sides of the capital. Land prices
throughout the suburban region are rising fast, and the few patches
of farm or forest land that remain near major highways are quickly
being bulldozed for strip malls and housing developments.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the commuters appear to be fueling economic
growth in dozens of towns and cities. Schools, hospitals and other
services in some suburban towns are being improved to meet
middle-class standards.
</P>
<P>
   The daily commute here offers more daunting challenges than
those faced by most straphangers and car-poolers in the United
States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic jams are horrendous. And the cost of parking, gasoline
and roadway tolls, which are among the highest in the world, can
drive the price of the daily commute by car to above $20 a day. As
a result, many professionals prefer to travel by bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very Mexican-style suburbanization process,'' said
Reina Corona Cuapio, an urbanologist at the National Autonomous
University who has conducted a survey that aims to provide the
first preliminary profile of Mexico's burgeoning commuter class.
``It's taking place with almost no governmental planning, and the
costs for commuters in time, money and inconvenience are high.''
</P>
<P>
   North of the border, commuters have been polled, profiled and
analyzed ever since the U.S. Census Bureau first included questions
about ``place of work and journey to work'' in the 1950 census. The
1990 census showed that 24 percent of all Americans now commute to
jobs in a county other than the one they live in.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Mexican commuters have never been systematically
counted, mainly because they have emerged in large numbers only
recently. Ms. Corona's survey counted commuters traveling from
Cuautla, 65 miles southeast of Mexico City, and she hopes to count
commuters in the entire metropolitan area in broader studies later.
</P>
<P>
   Based on calculations including revenues from highway tolls, she
estimated that as many as 500,000 people may be traveling each day
between the capital and six surrounding states. Probably a third of
them are workers commuting to jobs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even cities as far away as San Juan del Rio, 102 miles north of
the capital, are being suburbanized, demonstrating Mexican workers'
tremendous patience for grueling daily travel.
</P>
<P>
   Aguilar, the furniture restorer, who is 67, spent one recent
month journeying by bus, subway and taxi to a job in a city far
north of Mexico City, 180 miles from his home in Cuautla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd leave home at 5 a.m. and get back at 11 p.m.'' Aguilar
said. ``But I didn't want to turn down the job.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of this century, Mexico City has been a powerful
magnet, attracting millions of peasants to its industries in one of
the world's most extraordinary farm-to-factory migrations. The
population of the Federal District, Mexico City's formal name,
quintupled between 1940 and 1980, to 8.8 million from 1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   But early in this decade, experts studying Mexico's 1990 census
detected a startling reversal. For the first time, the city's
population declined in the 1980s, by about 600,000.
</P>
<P>
   The figures showed a corresponding growth in many mid-size
Mexican cities, leading some demographers to conclude that the
tremendous forces of centralization that governed Mexico for more
than a century had come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recently the process by which population has been
concentrating in Mexico City has been turned around,'' concluded a
1995 essay in the population journal Demos. Because of crime,
pollution and the high cost of living, ``the city is now expelling
rather than receiving migrants,'' the study said.
</P>
<P>
   But further study showed that many smaller cities like
Cuernavaca, Cuautla, Pachuca and Toluca that were showing rapid
growth were simply being transformed into suburbs of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the metropolitan boundaries of all settlements
around the capital, from Cuautla in the south to Queretaro, 142
miles north of the capital, are expected to merge, creating one
giant megalopolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toward the middle of the 21st century, this megalopolis will
concentrate approximately 50 million people,'' Gustavo Garza, a
demographer at the Colegio de Mexico, wrote in a recent essay. That
will require Mexican commuters to be even more long-suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the wasted time and the long distances drive me to
desperation,'' said Betancourt, who moved his family to Cuernavaca
because his wife came down with a respiratory disease in Mexico
City, which has serious pollution problems. ``But you've just got
to be patient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
