u f BC-SOUTHERNCOMPANY18-COX     12-17 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERNCOMPANY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern blames jellyfish in Philippines blackout
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Forget about Y2K. Southern Co. is blaming a jellyfish
attack for gumming up the works at its new $1.4 billion Philippine
power plant and triggering a major blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Half the nation was plunged into darkness for several hours Dec.
10 when Southern's Sual Power Station shut down while thousands of
jellyfish were extracted from its cooling system.
</P>
<P>
   Many local politicians, however, are ridiculing what one called
a ``fishy'' explanation for the blackout and demanding an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't gel,'' Sen. Juan Flavier was quoted as saying
in response to Southern's explanation. Sen. Francisco Tatad called
it an ``explanation that nobody understands,'' the Philippine Star
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Southern insists there is no squishiness to its fish story.
Philippine President Joseph Estrada, his energy secretary and the
state-run National Power Corp. have backed the jellyfish scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Southern opened the 1,200-megawatt plant 130 miles north of
Manila only two months ago and uses water from the South China Sea
to cool the coal-fired generators.
</P>
<P>
   David Mould, a spokesman for Southern Energy Inc., the
subsidiary that operates the plant, said an ``enormous
concentration'' of jellyfish crippled the plant when they were
sucked into a water treatment unit. A lack of cooling automatically
shut down the plant, which in turn triggered a ``cascading effect''
that knocked other power plants off line as well.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting blackout affected up to 40 million of the
archipelago nation's population of 73 million, according to
National Power, which purchases electricity from the Sual plant.
Most of the island of Luzon, including parts of metropolitan
Manila, were affected.
</P>
<P>
   Mould said power was completely restored within seven hours as
the other plants resumed operations. It took 14 hours to clean out
the jellyfish from one of the two generating units at Sual and
restore operations. The second unit was brought back Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty dump trucks full of the umbrella-shaped creatures were
removed from the cooling systems of the two coal-fired Sual units
following the incident, Mould said. ``We had to pull them out by
hand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As if the jellyfish were not enough, an earthquake measuring 6.8
on the Richter scale struck the same area Sunday. Mould said that
one marine biologist had speculated that the cnidarians may have
been fleeing the earthquake when they converged on Sual 24 hours
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Rodolfo Biazon, head of the Philippine Senate Defense
Committee, was quoted by the South China Morning Post as saying the
jellyfish affair had national security implications. Southern
should have anticipated the problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the incident, Southern has installed barriers at the plant
to prevent another jellyfish invasion and anticipates no further
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Southern opened the Sual plant with much fanfare in October
after more than two years of construction. The company inherited
the project when it acquired a Hong Kong-based independent power
company in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The plant is described as state-of-the-art and is the newest and
largest in the Philippines, which for years has been plagued by
power blackouts and brownouts.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have said it will add $100 million to Southern's
profits during the first full year of operations in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
