<SLUG> BC-FBC-HERITAGE-PREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heritage Bowl, Jags go way back
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern University will seek its third consecutive
Heritage Bowl victory when it takes on Hampton University at the
Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players are really excited to be here. We start making
plans to be in Atlanta in the spring time,'' Southern linebacker
Channing Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the sixth appearance in the 9-year-old bowl for
Southern (11-1), which comes to town a week after defeating Jackson
State in Birmingham to capture its third consecutive SWAC title.
Just as was the case a year ago, when they defeated Bethune-Cookman
28-2, the Jaguars will be facing an opponent that finished third
its conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the SWAC, they must win their championship to
make it to Atlanta. We had to throw a few games to get here,'' said
Hampton coach Joe Taylor, whose team finished third in the MEAC
behind Division 1-AA playoff participants North Carolina A&AMP;T and
Florida A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (7-4), from a league that has I-AA playoff options, will
be competing in the Heritage Bowl for the first time. In the
previous two postseasons, the Pirates represented the MEAC in the
playoff as that conference's champion.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars have a chance to win a 12th game for the first time
in the school's history. But Southern will have to win the rematch.
Southern knocked off Jackson State in the regular season, before
last weekend's victory over JSU in the SWAC championship battle. In
early October, the Jaguars posted a 21-6 victory over Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing (a rematch) does is give the team that lost the
incentive to prove to people they can beat the other team,''
Southern coach Pete Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
