<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rams are eady for Tuskegee
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There was a time when Kermit Blount didn't want his
team to face one coached by Rick Comegy.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Blount welcomes that challenge in the Pioneer Bowl at
the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Blount will coach Winston-Salem State against Tuskegee's Golden
Tigers in the third annual event. The Rams are the CIAA champions
with a 7-0 conference record, a far cry from seven years ago, when
Blount inherited a struggling program and Comegy, then coaching at
NAIA power Central State of Ohio, called in search of a game.
Blount turned him down.
</P>
<P>
   Winston-Salem State features an offense led by 1,000-yard rusher
Terrie Newkirk, but most of the team's success has been credited to
a defense that was allowing 7.7 points per game before a
season-ending 25-23 loss to Grambling.
</P>
<P>
   Blount's team will try to cut down the production of tailback
Michael Scott, the SIAC's leading rusher, and quarterback Aaron
James of Jesup, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen (Scott) on film and he's a pretty good back. But
what we plan to do is what we've done all season: Shut them down,''
Winston-Salem cornerback Deryl Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Scott appears to be the central figure for Tuskegee,
Comegy thinks James may be the key for the Golden Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaron is going to have to keep his composure, make the right
reads and come up with some big plays if we're going be
successful,'' Comegy said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuskegee defeated Livingstone 23-9 in last year's Pioneer Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
