<SLUG> BC-FBC-QUINCYCARTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quincy Carter is staying a Bulldog
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Stating that ``money isn't everything'' and that
he had goals left to accomplish at Georgia, quarterback Quincy
Carter will pass on the opportunity to become an NFL first-round
draft pick in order to return for his junior season with the
Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who said he had been ``50-50'' about turning pro, made
the announcement Friday at a news conference on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It basically boiled down to me being a competitor and wanting
to accomplish everything I wanted to accomplish in life,'' said
Carter, who was accompanied by his mother, Sherry Carter-Embree.
``Money is not the only thing in life and I realize that. I also
had to think about my college education, coming back to school and
getting a degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter completed 57 percent of his passes for 2,713 yards, 17
touchdowns and six interceptions this season. The Bulldogs finished
7-4 and will play Purdue (7-4) in the Outback Bowl on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia failed to beat Tennessee, Florida and Georgia Tech
for the second year in a row and Carter has yet to achieve his
stated goal of leading the Bulldogs to the SEC championship and
contending for a national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream is to play in the NFL but, at the same time, you have
to think about the things you want to accomplish,'' Carter said.
``Winning an SEC championship and winning a national championship
are goals of mine and of this football team. I didn't feel like I
accomplished enough to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter consulted with coach Jim Donnan and with his family on
his NFL prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have been a first-round pick,'' said Donnan, who said
he polled NFL general managers and coaches. ``Where he would go
would pretty much be based on each team's needs. But middle to late
first round is what we got from most people we talked to.''
</P>
<P>
   refer to Dez White story and Kelly Campbell stories
</P>
