A2167 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-MCNAIR-COX     12-17 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCNAIR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Titans don't plan any changes at QB
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE - The Titans, after three consecutive 8-8 seasons, are
10-3 and clinch their first playoff berth in six years by beating
the Falcons on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But that success hasn't tempered the quarterback controversy
that is brewing in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Steve McNair, the team's first-round draft pick in 1995, hasn't
thrown a touchdown pass in six games. He threw seven interceptions
during that same stretch.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who missed five games after undergoing surgery on Sept.
19 to repair a ruptured disc in his back, has a passer rating of
66.1. His rating is second-worst among AFC quarterbacks with at
least 187 pass attempts, leading only Pittsburgh's Kordell Stewart,
who was benched.
</P>
<P>
   Many Titans fans are calling for coach Jeff Fisher to replace
McNair with veteran Neil O'Donnell, who had a 4-1 record during
McNair's six-week absence. O'Donnell threw for 1,209 yards and
eight touchdowns in five starts.
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher insists there isn't a controversy, at least not among
his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the big topic around here and around the league now:
Why don't you make a change?,'' Fisher said. ``Well, Steve is 6-2
as a starter. He's 5-2 since coming back from a very significant,
serious injury. He's doing the things that we need to do to win
games.''
</P>
<P>
   And Fisher doesn't seem ready to make a change anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of other quarterbacks that have ratings much
higher than Steve that are playing on teams that don't have half as
many wins as we do,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we're finding ways to win games. He's made
plays the last four weeks that very few quarterbacks could make and
those go unnoticed. It's the lack of touchdown passes that has
become issue. Steve has been our guy since we traded (Falcons
quarterback) Chris Chandler away and there's no question about
that. We have no intention of making a change.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair, 6 feet 2, 225 pounds, has been bothered by a bad case of
turf toe on his left foot. He also has a badly sprained ankle on
the same foot. McNair wore a stabilizing boot until Wednesday, but
he says he'll play against the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the foot that I plant with at the end of my throw, so you
can't get that much pressure on it and it's kind of hard being
accurate,'' McNair said. ``It makes you throw a little off the mark
when you can't plant and push down.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who had to overcome doubts that he could make the jump
from tiny Alcorn State to the NFL, seems unphased by the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has their opinion, but you can't pay attention to
that,'' he said. ``This team is focused on just winning and we're
not trying to make a (quarterback) change right now. ... We're in a
position right now we haven't been in a long time. We're not happy
with the passing game. We know things have to shape up if we want
to win games in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
