<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-ITALY18-COX     12-17 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-ITALY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke receives fine in Italian antitrust case
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola received more bad news from Europe on Friday
when Italian antitrust regulators fined the company $16.1 million
for abusing its dominant market position to exclude Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it will appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the ruling ... is inconsistent with Italian
and European competition laws and with commercial practices widely
accepted in Italy, as well as in other parts of Europe and around
the world,'' Enrico Nardulli, chairman of the Coca-Cola Bevande
Italia bottling company, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's antitrust authority said Coca-Cola and its Italian
bottlers worked together to try to eliminate Pepsi from the market
by offering discounts and other financial incentives to retailers
and wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   The authority also said Coca-Cola's Italian subsidiary offered
discounts to big distributors in exchange for display space or for
reducing the display space of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola controls about 46 percent of the carbonated soft drink
market in Italy, compared with 6 percent for Pepsi, according to
Beverage Digest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision preserves fair competition and consumer choice
in Italy,'' said Pepsico spokesman Jeff Brown. ``We hope this
decision puts an end to Coke's effort to restrain competition and
bully retailers.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola denied it bullied anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the time of the alleged anticompetitive practices,
retail pricing was stable or declined, Virgin cola entered the
Italian market, and Pepsi's market share grew,'' said Robert
Baskin, a Coca-Cola spokesman in Atlanta. ``That's a competitive
marketplace and demonstrates that we follow the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's decision stems from an investigation started in 1998
after complaints were filed by Pepsico and the Esselunga
supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based beverage giant faces similar investigations in
other European nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the $16 million is a material financial
matter,'' said analyst Marc Cohen of Goldman Sachs. ``But I think
this obviously is an embarrassing incident for the company and
raises questions about what might develop from other European
investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also said he thinks the company's new president, Douglas
Daft, will give priority to dealing with such matters. The
Coca-Cola board has said Daft will be named chairman and chief
executive officer in April, when M. Douglas Ivester retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Avoiding incidents like this is part of bringing back a more
positive and diplomatic image to the company,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The $16.1 million fine amounts to 3 percent of Coca-Cola's
revenue in Italy. The company could have been fined as much as $80
million, or 10 percent of its Italian revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the company has stumbled in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's planned acquisition of the Orangina brand in France
was rejected by antitrust regulators there. And its purchase of
Cadbury Schweppes brands outside the United States was consummated
only after Coca-Cola eliminated 22 European nations from the deal
because of antitrust concerns by the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's shares rose $1.25 on Wall Steet, losing at $59.75.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
