<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2174 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELL18-COX     12-17 0280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell expands to Tennessee
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp. on Friday said it will
broaden its operations in Nashville, Tenn., with a sales office and
notebook PC plant, while a company executive voiced frustration
about the pace of road construction in Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion will raise Dell's work force in Tennessee to 3,000
by the middle of next summer, up from about 2,200 now, according to
the company.
</P>
<P>
   The Nashville operations represent Dell's first U.S. expansion
outside of Central Texas. When executives announced in April that
Dell would move manufacturing of its Dimension line of desktop
computers _ which is aimed at consumers and small businesses _ to
Tennessee, they cited strategic reasons as well as their concerns
that Dell is getting too big for Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Strategically, Nashville is closer to major hubs of carriers
such as United Parcel Service, which is in Louisville, Ky. That
shortens the time it takes to ship PCs to some areas of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   By adding the manufacturing plant for its Inspiron line of
notebook computers and a sales operation in Nashville, Dell is
creating an East Coast center for its home and small business
division.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has said it may be getting too big for Central
Texas. A consultant's study for Dell earlier this year estimated
that the computer maker accounted for half the direct and indirect
job growth in the region last year. Indirect jobs are those created
by demand for goods and services by employees and vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
