<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NILSSON-OPERA-ART-870     12-17 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NILSSON-OPERA-ART-870(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ISOLDE LEGEND RETURNS, TRIUMPHANT AND UNTRAMMELED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saturday afternoon's performance of ``Tristan und
Isolde'' at the Metropolitan Opera, the last of the season, with
the acclaimed new duo of Wagner opera, Ben Heppner and Jane Eaglen,
in the title roles, will also commemorate an illustrious night in
the history of the company, indeed, a milestone in the annals of
20th-century opera: exactly 40 years ago Saturday, Birgit Nilsson
made her Met debut in the role of Isolde.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Nilsson, who is 81, will be in attendance, sitting in a
first-tier box as the guest of the Met's general manager, Joseph
Volpe. No official announcement of her presence will be made from
the stage before the performance. But count on opera fans to spot
her when she takes her seat and greet her with an ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Her debut, of course, occurred at the old opera house. Few Met
debuts have matched it in excitement and importance. The next day,
Howard Taubman's review in The New York Times made the front page,
accompanied by a close-up photo of the Swedish soprano smiling
during the tumultuous reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Birgit Nilsson filled the Metropolitan Opera House last night
with the glory of the finest Isolde since the unforgettable days of
Kirsten Flagstad two decades ago,'' Taubman wrote. ``With a voice
of extraordinary size, suppleness and brilliance, she dominated the
stage and the performance.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Nilsson was reminded recently during an interview in
her hotel room near Lincoln Center that this rave review was
accorded a place on The Times' front page, she replied, ``Ja, and
on the front page of The Herald Tribune too!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nilsson has had some health problems lately and walks with
some difficulty but for the most part seems remarkably fit and
hardy. She has been spending most of her downtime during retirement
on the farm in rural Sweden where she was born and reared, although
as a young woman she hated farm work and couldn't wait to leave the
place. Her crusty father was disappointed that his only child was a
girl and could not comprehend why she wanted to pursue a quixotic
career as a singer rather than assume her place as a farmer's wife.
</P>
<P>
   But spending time in the country must be salutary now, for Ms.
Nilsson has plenty of energy. Over the last five days she has been
conducting master classes with singers from the Met's Lindemann
Young Artist Development Program. The sessions have been closed to
the public, but an invitation-only audience was permitted to
observe Ms. Nilsson at work.
</P>
<P>
   Her last appearance at the Met was as the Dyer's Wife in a
now-legendary performance of Strauss' ``Frau Ohne Schatten'' in the
fall of 1981, though she did sing once more from the stage during
the gargantuan gala concert in honor of James Levine's 25th
anniversary at the Met in 1996. After paying tribute to Levine, Ms.
Nilsson offered what she called a traditional ``Viking salute,''
which turned out to be Brunnhilde's famous salutation of
``Hojotoho! Hojotoho!,'' topped off with a couple of high Bs and
high Cs that dramatic sopranos half her age would have coveted.
</P>
<P>
   Though Heppner and Ms. Eaglen are being paired in the minds of
Wagner fans as the Tristan and Isolde of the future, Ms. Nilsson
never really had a comparable partner. The closest was the German
tenor Wolfgang Windgassen, who died in 1974. Of the 209
performances of the opera she sang in her career, Windgassen was
her Tristan in more than 100 of them, Ms. Nilsson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a fine colleague and artist,'' she said. ``He had
style. He didn't overact. His voice was lyric; it was a small
voice. But the sound was beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The tenor Jon Vickers, with his heroic sound, came closest to
matching her, though he was an elusive Tristan. During the 1960s
Vickers repeatedly promised to take on the role for her, but kept
withdrawing. Finally he made good. His debut as Tristan came in
Buenos Aires in 1971, with Ms. Nilsson as his grateful Isolde.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him at the time that I waited and waited for my Tristan
for 14 years,'' Ms. Nilsson said, ``as long as Jacob waited for
Rachel in the Bible.'' They sang it together only once at the Met,
another legendary performance, on Jan. 30, 1974. ``Maybe he was
uncomfortable with me,'' Ms. Nilsson said, somewhat wistfully. ``I
don't know.'' She also cited the American tenor Jess Thomas. ``He
was an excellent Tristan, good-looking, wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course she also heard and sang with Tristans who were not so
good, purportedly great Wagnerian tenors who ``belted out the
role,'' she said. ``They shouted, they wobbled. The voice was so
spread out you couldn't decide within four notes which one they
were trying to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   For all her acclaim in the German dramatic repertory, Ms.
Nilsson never let herself get trapped by it. She assiduously kept
performing Italian roles as well. ``This was the only way to
survive,'' she said. ``When I sang too much Wagner, the voice got
dark, without shine, and heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nilsson once told Levine that it was essential for her to
keep Mozart in her repertory, even though she knew that she was
probably few people's ideal of a Mozart singer. ``I have not been
good to Mozart,'' she said at the time, ``but Mozart has been very
good to me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In her master classes Ms. Nilsson repeatedly emphasized the
importance of supporting the voice from the abdomen and letting the
sound emerge without tension through the throat and what she calls
``the mask,'' meaning the head and face. This basic technique is
not well understood by the public. Human beings are born with
proper vocal technique, as anyone knows who has heard the crying of
an infant fill an entire house. But people lose that natural
ability to project sound and soon begin to speak and sing through
our throats. Voice teachers have to break those habits and get
young adults singing naturally, with proper abdominal support.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Nilsson's master class on Wednesday afternoon at the
Met's intimate List Hall, the first singer was a 25-year-old tenor,
Charles Castronovo, who recently made his Met debut as Beppe in
``Cavalleria Rusticana.'' When he announced his name to the
audience, Ms. Nilsson jumped in, already critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one understood you,'' she said. ``Say your name clearly.
Maybe somebody is sitting here with a contract.'' She proved to be
as quick with one-liners as David Letterman. When Castronovo was
about to sing ``Dies Bildnis ist bezaubernd schoen'' from Mozart's
``Zauberfloete,'' a renowned lyric tenor aria, Ms. Nilsson said
with mock distress: ``No score for me? I never sang that aria
before.'' Then, with savvy timing, she added, almost under her
breath, ``I was sick that day.''
</P>
<P>
   After Castronovo's performance, Ms. Nilsson told the audience
that the young man, with whom she had worked earlier in the week,
was a very talented tenor with an appealing voice and solid
musicianship, but that, as with many younger singers in her
experience, his sound was produced too much from the throat,
without sufficient abdominal support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mask,'' she said, putting her hands on her face, ``is like
our resonance room, our violin case, our piano case. Let the sound
come through it, but support the sound.'' As Castronovo sang a
particular phrase, Ms. Nilsson said that he was concentrating too
much sound on an upbeat note that leaps to a higher note. ``Your
upbeat is killing the high note,'' she said, suggesting that the
lower note should provide a lift to the higher one, ``like a diving
board.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point she approached the strapping young man and, in a
gesture of comfort, placed her hand around his upper arm. ``Oh, you
have big muscles,'' she said, turning to the audience and winking
as the tenor blushed. ``I thought he was so skinny.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, when Marjorie Elinor Dix, a soprano, sang the aria
``Elsa's Dream'' from Wagner's ``Lohengrin,'' Ms. Nilsson needed no
score. She was able to correct pitches exactly and shape phrases
from memory. As before, she emphasized the importance of supporting
the voice and praised Ms. Dix for the increased radiance of her
sound in the upper register when she sang with freedom, from ``deep
down,'' as Ms. Nilsson put it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nilsson had nothing but praise for the performance of ``Il
mio tesoro,'' Don Ottavio's aria from Mozart's ``Don Giovanni,'' as
sung by the tenor Eric Cutler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I would have heard it as good when I sang Donna Anna,''
she said. ``It's very vigorous, which is right. You don't want to
sound like a Mrs. Donna Anna.'' She cautioned the tenor about his
slight tendency to sing sharp but added that, on balance, it was
better to be a little sharp than flat. She too had a tendency to go
slightly sharp, she said, though in fact her unerring sense of
pitch was routinely cited by critics during her career. ``Maybe
singing sharp a bit is Swedish,'' she said. ``Jussi Bjorling, you
know, was also sometimes sharp a little.''
</P>
<P>
   After the class Ms. Nilsson remained to greet well-wishers. Some
people had brought her recordings for her to autograph, though Ms.
Nilsson asserted that she seldom listened to them herself. During
the 1960s and early '70s, when she made most of her recordings, the
technology was not advanced enough to capture her enormous voice
well, she said. Many critics agree that recordings of the Nilsson
voice do not suggest how glorious it was when heard live. Still,
her discography is extensive and monumentally important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she said, it's nice that something is left, ja?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
