<HEADLINE>
COUNCIL MEETS ON BRITISH-IRISH PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The final piece of the institutional jigsaw puzzle at
the heart of the Good Friday Agreement of 1998 fell into place
Friday with the first-ever meeting of the council that will oversee
areas of mutual interest on the islands of Britain and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Opening what they said was a new era in better relations between
their two nations, British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish
counterpart, Bertie Ahern, convened the British-Irish Council,
which includes representatives from the newly-empowered local
assemblies of Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland, as well as
officials from the British islands of Jersey, Guernsey, and the
Isle of Man.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years, relations between the Irish and British
governments, which were of necessity dominated by the issue of
Northern Ireland, were conducted in a bipolar framework, between
Dublin and London,'' said Ahern. ``We were in the habit,
inaccurately but revealingly, of thinking in terms of Anglo-Irish
relations. This terminology is no longer adequate for the complex
reality which I see represented here at this table.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair agreed, saying, ``We are setting the seal on a truly
unique relationship for the future, between the Republic of
Ireland, Northern Ireland, and the rest of these islands.''
</P>
<P>
   After presiding over the formal opening of the council at
Lancaster House, Blair and Ahern had to make only a brief journey
around St. James Park to 10 Downing Street for the first meeting of
the two governments under the terms set forth in a Anglo-Irish
treaty signed two weeks ago in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   The British-Irish Council, which will hold summits twice a year,
was the idea of David Trimble, the Ulster Unionist leader and first
minister of the Northern Ireland Assembly. It is meant to provide a
balance to the North-South Ministerial Council that will oversee
six areas of cross-border mutual interest, such as agriculture, in
the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Irish nationalists in Northern Ireland consider the
cross-border institutions essential to acknowledging their
Irishness, unionists in Northern Ireland see the British-Irish
Council as underpinning their sense of being British.
</P>
<P>
   The council overseeing the cross-border institutions met for the
first time Monday in Armagh, the city in Northern Ireland that is
the seat for both the Roman Catholic and Anglican churches in
Ireland. Ahern led members of his Cabinet to that meeting, then
flew Friday for London to complete the formalization of the three
strands of relationships between the north and south of Ireland,
the islands of Britain and Ireland, and the governments in Dublin
and London.
</P>
<P>
   With Friday's meeting, the key constitutional elements of the
Good Friday Agreement of 1998 have been implemented _ the
power-sharing government in Northern Ireland, the cross-border
institutions giving Dublin a direct role in affairs in Northern
Ireland, and now the council that formalizes links between the two
neighboring islands. The Good Friday agreement, fashioned under the
mediation of former US senator George Mitchell, a Democrat from
Maine, produced a political settlement designed to end years of
sectarian violence in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   So much has happened in the last few weeks that another
milestone passed Friday with little fanfare. When Blair shook hands
with Bairbre de Brun, the Sinn Fein official in charge of health in
Northern Ireland, it marked the first time a British prime minister
had shaken hands in public with someone from Sinn Fein, the
political allies of the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the optimism on both sides of the Irish Sea, the
political progress could still be shattered in two months. Trimble
got his party to drop its refusal to form a power-sharing
government with members of Sinn Fein before the IRA began
disarming, but he says he and his party will withdraw and collapse
the Northern Ireland assembly if the IRA does not begin to disarm
by February.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, however, those who gathered here, except for Trimble,
were content to remark on the historic importance of the day and
the last two weeks. Trimble, speaking to reporters with Seamus
Mallon, the Catholic nationalist who is the first deputy minister
of the Northern Ireland Assembly, said he was hesitant to proclaim
Friday as historic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not quite there yet,'' Trimble said, but he added that
the moment may not be far off.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon quickly interjected, ``You'll know that moment because
he's promised he'll buy a drink.''
</P>
<P>
   That Trimble, Mallon, and the assembled dignitaries all laughed
underscored how much progress has been made in the last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
