<HEADER>
A2179 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WINE-CHAT-ONLINE-NYTR     12-17 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-CHAT-ONLINE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT COMES TO WINE ONLINE, IT'S YAK-YAK-YAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TIM FISH   
 WineToday.com   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes it seems that people like talking about wine even more
than drinking it.
</P>
<P>
   We yak around the dinner table past midnight. Every clerk in a
wine shop gets an ear-chewing. If we corner a winemaker _ the poor
devil _ we're in heaven. We form cliques and clubs and gather at
large tastings, chatty herds, wine glasses in hand.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Ah yes, the Internet, the epic clatter of keyboards heard 'round
the world. It makes your wrists swell just thinking about it. And a
good number of those people are chatting about wine, whether it's
in private e-mails, in chat rooms or on bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   Wine, of course, has been a topic on the Net since the stone age
of alt.food.wine, but now the worldwide wine community is hanging
out on the Net as never before.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the facelessness. Wine talk can so easily be
pretentious and intimidating. Online you can write what you would
never say. Let's face it, the wine world can be stuffy, and the
Internet pops that balloon right away.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps it's a matter of geography. Wine lovers are spread
thin around the globe _ there aren't many towns that can fill an
arena with enophiles _ so the Internet is a natural town hall.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most popular boards, particularly with wine lovers in
the United States, are the Wine Lovers' Discussion Group
(www.wine-lovers-page.com/forum/general) and West Coast Wine
Network (www.westcoastwine.net/wwwboard1.html). The wine board at
America Online isn't nearly as active as it used to be, but it
offers a few insights.
</P>
<P>
   For the big picture, you need to turn to Robin Garr, whose Wine
Lovers' Page was one of the first independent wine Web sites.
Before he launched the site as the ``Wine Bargain Page'' in 1993,
he put in time running the wine board at CompuServe.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are passionate about a subject enjoy finding other
people who feel the same way, and I don't think that applies only
to wine,'' Garr said.
</P>
<P>
   Wine lovers are certainly a passionate bunch, and the Internet
allows them a forum they might not get otherwise. The same guy who
complains about the line at the ATM will post a 10-page thesis on
the 1995 Barolos. With footnotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few of us are content with merely enjoying the occasional
glass of wine Most of us delve more deeply into the subject,'' Mark
Levesque, who's a regular on Garr's board, wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua du Lac, who participates on the West Coast board from his
home in Sacramento, Calif., would agree. ``I find it harder to
enjoy wine without evaluating it. Which isn't to say I don't enjoy
it. It's just that it's hard for me to put anything across my
palate _ even if it's a $7 bottle served at a wedding _ without
considering what I like and dislike about it. I guess that means
I've shifted from being a drinker to a taster.''
</P>
<P>
   It's this kind of passion that many wine fans crave and often
can't find without the Net. Matthew Cooper, a regular on the West
Coast board, said: ``I live in Lexington, Ky., an area not known
for its love of wine, so it is difficult to find others with the
same passion. The board is like having a wine club/tasting group
with 10,000 members.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, the wine boards are a substitute for the traditional
wine press. You can find like-minded drinkers, and when it comes to
new wines, the boards are often weeks ahead of the magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information is more current than any other source,''
Gordon Drake said of the West Coast board. ``By the time I got my
Wine Spectator, the Constant mailing list was closed. Not so for
Flowers, Pride, Jones Family, La Sirena and Showket, all of which
were posted on this site.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you get,'' Levesque added, ``is unvarnished opinion, not
glossy marketing-speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are challenges. Without a face behind the words,
intentions can easily be misread. ``Humor is very difficult, and
tone is very hard to gauge,'' Cole Kendall of Washington, D.C.,
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main challenge is keeping things civil,'' Craig of
Montreal wrote. ``There's always a danger of being misunderstood or
of someone taking offense when none was intended.''
</P>
<P>
   For many participants, the board goes beyond wine chitchat. What
keeps them dialing in is a sense of community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us have also made friends for life,'' Paul, a regular
on the AOL board, wrote. Three years ago, for example, Paul was
having an online argument about the 1981 La Mission Haut Brion. ``I
told him he was nuts and if he was ever on Long Island (N.Y.) that
I would open one up for him. We quickly discovered that we both
live in Syosset and have been great friends ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   One regular on the West Coast board added, ``When my father died
I received messages from dozens of people I'd never met, messages
that helped me deal with the loss in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the hankering for wine goes beyond the Net and most
of the boards have what they call ``off-lines:'' tastings and
dinners at cities around the country. Often the wines served are
treasures from the wine cellar.
</P>
<P>
   ``People,'' Kendall said, ``are incredibly generous with their
wine and friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stuart Yaniger of Napa, Calif., put it best. And it sort of
fits the whole tone of what I'm writing about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my first off-line,'' Yaniger wrote. ``It was at
Ridge Vineyards. We were supposed to meet in the picnic area. My
wife asked me what the participants looked like. I responded,
`12-point Letter Gothic.'''
</P>
<P>
   (Winetoday.com is a daily Internet wine publication of The New
York Times Co. The Web address is http://www.winetoday.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
