<HEADLINE>
EDWIN HOBSON III, 84 CEO OF MANUFACTURING FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Ohio)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A funeral will be held Saturday for Edwin Lafayette Hobson III,
chief executive officer of Abanaki Corp., a manufacturer of oil
skimming equipment used in pollution control.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hobson died Wednesday in a one-car accident in Rye, N.H.,
where he lived, as he traveled to the airport on his weekly commute
to Chagrin Falls, Ohio, where his firm is based. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hobson was born in Richmond, Va. He graduated from
Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   He was an engineer for Bakelite Corp. before serving in the Army
during World War II. While at the Quartermaster General's Office,
he was a co-inventor of plastic body armor and was instrumental in
the development of plastic helmet liners and other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   From 1946 to 1967, Mr. Hobson was associated with Monsanto Corp.
He also cofounded Aladdin Synergistics Inc. in Nashville before
becoming president of Abanaki Corp. in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves eight daughters, Jane E. of Vancouver, Wash., Anne
Marie of Kittery, Maine, Susan of Seattle, Mary of Richmond, Maine,
Martha of Kenmore, Wash., Margaret of Charlottesville, Va.,
Catherine of Seattle, and Paula M. of Concord, Mass.; three sons,
Edwin L. Jr. of Middlesex, Vt., John A. of Falmouth, Maine, and
Mark L. of Chagrin Falls, Ohio; three siblings, R. Archer Hobson of
Stanton, Va., Graham Black of Miami, and Richard Hobson of
Alexandria, Va.; and 18 grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral will be at 1:30 p.m. in St. John Episcopal Church in
Portsmouth, N.H.
</P>
</TEXT>
