<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2183 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-VPHISTORY19-COX     12-17 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VPHISTORY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds. EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, DEC. 19
 &HT;    History a postive and a nagative for Bradley
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During a television interview this fall, Democrat
Bill Bradley was confronted with the weight of history: no sitting
vice president, his interviewer asserted, had ever been defeated
for his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Not true, Bradley responded. Vice President George Clinton lost
to James Madison to succeed President Jefferson _ in 1808. A far
better historical precedent, Bradley said, was the fact that George
Bush was the first vice president to win the presidency in 150
years.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, trying to wrest the nomination from Vice President
Gore, was both right and wrong. Bush was the first vice president
to be elected president since Martin Van Buren did it in 1836. But
history is dotted with other examples of vice presidents who
coveted the presidency but failed to win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Alben Barkley, who served under President Truman
and had the affectionate nickname ``Veep,'' sought the Democratic
nomination in 1952 but watched it go to Adlai E. Stevenson. Charles
Fairbanks, vice president to President Theodore Roosevelt, saw the
nomination go to William H. Taft, who was subsequently elected
president, after Roosevelt worked against Fairbanks.
</P>
<P>
   Only 14 of the nation's 44 vice presidents, excluding Gore, have
become president, and eight of those reached the office when their
president died in office.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no election in America's history is comparable to the
present. The job of vice president, the party nominating process,
even the method of electing presidents has changed radically since
John Adams became the nation's first vice president under President
George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1804, members of the electoral college were required to
vote for two men, one of whom could not be from their home state.
The top vote getter became president and the second place finisher
became the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The system was changed in time for the 1804 elections after the
electoral college vote of 1800 produced a tie between Jefferson and
Aaron Burr, forcing Congress to engage in a protracted round of
balloting that ultimately made Jefferson the winner and Burr the
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's fate in 1808 was typical of what could happen to a
vice president. Although Clinton, a revolutionary war hero and
former governor of New York, wanted to succeed Jefferson, Jefferson
held his aging vice president in low regard and wanted his friend
and secretary of state James Madison to become the fifth president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's consolation prize was to become vice president again
under Madison. He created a small constitutional crisis when he
declined to either acknowledge or refuse the vice presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really thought he was running for president at that point
and the caucus renominated him for vice president,'' says Don
Ritchie, the Senate Historian, co-author of ``Vice Presidents of
the United States 1789-1993.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidents didn't have any say in selecting their running mates,
who were generally chosen because of which state they represented,
or because of which ideological wing of the party they came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were usually thrust on the ticket to balance it,''
Ritchie said. ``You often got situations where the president and
the vice president were just passing acquaintances.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also wasn't considered a part of the
executive branch. He served as the president of the Senate and was
regarded as a part of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   President Woodrow Wilson was the first president to even invite
his vice president to attend cabinet meetings, and even then the
vice president wasn't an active participant.
</P>
<P>
   Until President Franklin Roosevelt, presidential candidates or
their running mates didn't attend the nominating conventions, let
alone engage in much campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a mind set in the 19th century and early 20th
century that the man shouldn't seek the office,'' Ritchie said.
``The office should seek the man. So a lot of people who really
were candidates never officially declared themselves as candidates.
They just waited for the party to come to them and ask them to
serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the party often never came calling, so the vice
president was left to simply suffer the fate of someone like
Barkley, who was passed over when Truman decided not to seek
re-election in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Since Barkley, vice presidents have been more successful in
winning their party's nomination, but fared poorly in winning the
White House on their first try.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon became the Republican nominee in 1960 after
serving as Eisenhower's vice president, but didn't become president
until the election of 1968. Hubert Humphrey, President Johnson's
vice president, won the Democratic nomination in 1968 but went no
farther.
</P>
<P>
   Bush broke the record in 1988, succeeding President Reagan. But
Bush suffered in 1992 when he became viewed as not simply a
four-year president, but part of a 12-year administration.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, who dropped his presidential
bid earlier in the fall, joins the list of vice presidents who
haven't been able to convert the number two job into a trip to the
Oval office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your stuck with whatever the record is of your president,''
said Ritchie. ``And usually there is a fair amount of
dissatisfaction with the president, especially after eight years.
The parties do tend to alternate. People get tired and they want to
try something new. And they forget what they disliked about the
party the last time they were in office.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
