<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2184 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV19-NY     12-17 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THIS PARTY ENDS, MORE WILL FEEL THE PAIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the excitement of the approaching millennium, it is
understandable that a different anniversary has been largely
ignored. December was the month, in 1996, when Alan Greenspan made
his famous warning about ``irrational exuberance.''
</P>
<P>
   He was uncertain then whether stock prices had become ``unduly
escalated.'' But three years later and 4,800 points higher on the
Dow Jones industrial average, doubt is gone. The market is clearly
exuberant and irrational.
</P>
<P>
   That might not be so terrible if this were 1987 or the
mid-1970s, when bubbles burst and stock prices took famous plunges.
Fewer shareholders counted so much on their paper wealth in those
days, and fewer executives relied so heavily on a rising market to
sustain their entrepreneurial spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the selloff that now seems inevitable will do only passing
damage. But the odds of getting off easily this time are fading.
The national economy and the market have become too intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every optimistic forecast about the economy is based on the
premise that stock prices will either go up or change very
little,'' said Henry Kaufman, the Wall Street economist. ``Not
since World War II have we been so dependent on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists count the ways. Some items on the list are already
well known, the most familiar being the ``wealth effect'': rising
stock prices encourage consumers to spend more and borrow more,
activities that almost certainly will come to a halt, shrinking the
economy, if the Dow Jones average falls by 30 percent or so and
stays down for at least six months.
</P>
<P>
   Even people who don't own stock hear all the glad tidings on the
evening news. They see in the rising market a signal that the
economy is OK and that their jobs are safe, noted Edward McKelvey,
senior economist at Goldman, Sachs. So they, too, spend beyond
their incomes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Market selloff would throw the effect into reverse. The spenders
would pull way back. Companies would, too, in response. Job growth
would halt; the unemployment rate would rise and incomes would
fall. But debt would not, and everyone _ companies and households _
would pull back more in the scramble to pay debts and restore
savings that evaporated in the market decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``A selloff would bring us the first stock-market-induced
recession since before the Second World War,'' said Stephen S.
Roach, chief economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he does not surrender optimism. Although he anticipates a
selloff, he does not forecast a recession. When the downfall comes,
Roach and many others will count on Greenspan's Federal Reserve to
lower interest rates quickly enough and to take other steps to
prevent the anticipated chain reaction of belt-tightening from
happening.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for damage, however, is spreading in small and
perhaps uncontrollable ways. Many corporations, for example, no
longer have to add cash to their employee pension funds. Because
the funds have invested in a rising stock market, they are fully
funded.
</P>
<P>
   As long as stocks keep their value, the corporate money that
would have been needed for pension contributions augments profits
instead, or is invested in new products and equipment, activities
that keep the economy humming. If the stock market falls sharply,
that money would again have to be channeled into the pension funds
to keep them whole.
</P>
<P>
   Grants from foundations would also decline after a selloff, and
they finance thousands of projects and considerable research and
employment. Grants are geared to a foundation's wealth, and
foundations invest heavily in stocks. Grant money has risen in step
with the market. A selloff would produce a reversal of this trend.
</P>
<P>
   On a different level, corporate mergers, particularly those in
which one company pays for another with stock, would become more
difficult. ``We have a sense in this booming stock market that
there is no deal we cannot do,'' said Peter L. Bernstein, an
economist and author.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there is the spreading use of stock options
as pay in place of cash, a practice that is marching down the
hierarchy to lower ranks of workers. A market fall that lasted for
a while would render many of those options worthless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, a lot of people will be angry,'' said Dean Baker,
co-director of the Center for Economic and Policy Research in
Washington, ``and some will try to get paid retroactively in
cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are all the flourishing Internet companies. They
float new stock and watch it soar in value even as many companies
fail to make a profit. The market wealth covers the shortfall. Or
it makes possible borrowing and expansion in pursuit of success in
a new technology that is vibrant and promising.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it? Is it the technology that kindles the entrepreneurial
spirit in the Internet billionaires, or is it the stock market?
</P>
<P>
   Probably both. But we must wait for the market selloff to get a
more sober fix on the lasting changes wrought by the Internet, the
star technology in the much-proclaimed new economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1915EST &QL; 
