<SLUG> BC-UN-IRAQ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PLAN WOULD ALLOW UN INSPECTORS BACK IN IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Security Council adopted a plan Friday that could
allow UN weapons inspectors to return to Iraq for the first time in
a year. The plan also would suspend economic sanctions on Baghdad
if it cooperates with the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution passed with four abstentions, by China, Russia,
France, and Malaysia, leading some diplomats to fear the council
sent smixed signals to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   France said the resolution was too ambiguous and could lead to a
new crisis with Baghdad. Russia also said the resolution made it
unclear what Iraq had to do. China said the lack of consensus made
the resolution unenforceable.
</P>
<P>
   But US diplomats played down the abstentions. ``This was adopted
with 11 votes and the four who abstained all said they would be
dedicated to get Iraq to cooperate with it,'' said Peter Burleigh,
deputy US representative to the United Nations. ``The ball is back
in Iraq's court. They have to deliver to get sanctions suspended.''
</P>
<P>
   Baghdad insisted it would reject the resolution because it does
not immediately lift all economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The council offered Iraq a complicated formula that would lift
restrictions on oil exports immediately and suspend import and
export sanctions after certain disarmament goals are achieved. It
dangles before Baghdad the prospect of lifting the cap on its oil
exports under the UN oil-for-food program, although the United
Nations still would control profits.
</P>
<P>
   Under the oil-for-food deal, Iraq has been permitted the past
three years to export only $5.2 billion in petroleum for renewable
six-month periods, with the proceeds going into a UN escrow
account.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations then buys food and humanitarian supplies for
Iraqis who have been hurt by nine years of UN sanctions imposed
after Baghdad's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi diplomats say they prefer the existing cap on oil exports
because it provides them some measure of relief without accepting
new weapons monitors. Iraq also would have to pay for the monitors
out of the escrow account.
</P>
<P>
   A European diplomat said that allowing Iraq to sell unlimited
oil would remove the criticism that the West was insensitive to
Iraqi suffering.
</P>
<P>
   The former inspection team, known as UNSCOM, fled Iraq last
December just before the United States and Britain launched
airstrikes designed to force President Saddam Hussein to cooperate
with inspections. Iraq has barred the return of the monitors ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   The monitors had been searching for Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, including chemical, biological, and long-range missile
programs. Iraq also has stopped cooperating with the International
Atomic Energy Agency, which is charged with uncovering Baghdad's
nuclear weapons project.
</P>
<P>
   This has led to fears in some Western capitals that Iraq may
again be pursuing the bomb. That is why Washington and London in
particular deem it urgent to return a UN team.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Baghdad needs the inspectors because sanctions
cannot be permanently lifted until they declare Iraq free of
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The reconstituted inspection team, to be known as the UN
Monitoring, Verification and Inspection Commission, or UNMOVIC,
would not get into Iraq for several months, if Iraq agreed to
accept them, UN officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The council has given UN Secretary General Kofi Annan 30 days to
appoint an executive chairman for UNMOVIC, who would then have 45
days to come up with an organizational plan. After he had hired new
staff, which could take months, UNMOVIC would attempt to enter
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   If Baghdad let inspectors return, the monitors would have 60
days to present to the council its plan of operation, including the
remaining disarmament it believed Iraq had to complete.
</P>
<P>
   If Iraq cooperates with the inspectors' plan for 120 days the
council would suspend import and export sanctions for renewable
120-day periods, allowing the United States or Britain to slap the
sanctions back on Baghdad if it misbehaved.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution retains the legal language necessary to allow
military action if necessary. However, British diplomats stressed
that Friday's resolution is not a pretext to use force against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Iraq does not meet the standards for the suspension of
sanctions, then the sanctions will continue,'' said Jeremy
Greenstock, Britain's UN envoy. ``The use of force is not a way to
deal with Iraq on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The council worked eight months on Friday's resolution, with
several holdups in the past two weeks, mostly because of Russian
objections.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been Baghdad's closest friend on the council. Moscow
is motivated in part by more than $7 billion in Soviet-era debt
owed to it by Iraq, mostly for arms sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1916EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
