<SLUG> BC-CMGI-AKAMAI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI ANNOUNCES ALTAVISTA IPO, FUND-RAISING PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet company CMGI Inc. chose the day of its annual
shareholders meeting to announce the long-awaited public offering
of stock in its AltaVista Internet search service.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
CMGI said it would try to raise as much as $300 million in the
initial public offering. CMGI bought AltaVista, one of the most
popular search services on the Internet, for $2.3 billion earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, CMGI filed a separate notice of intent to raise $1
billion through sales of stocks and bonds, with the money to be
spent on general corporate purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements came hours after the close of the shareholders
meeting, where CMGI CEO David Wetherell revealed that his firm is
considering an IPO of its (at)Ventures venture capital fund, which
invests in Internet startups. Wetherell didn't reveal when such a
stock offering would be made, but said it would be ``sooner rather
than later.''
</P>
<P>
   A public sale of (at)Ventures stock would likely be one of the
most popular of the new year, considering the extraordinary
performance of CMGI's shares. CMGI stock traded at 28 5/8 at the
start of the year, and closed Friday at 211-13/16 on the Nasdaq
stock exchange. The Andover company announced Thursday it would
split its stock 2 for 1 on Jan. 11, its second split in a year.
Delighted shareholders at the meeting frequently applauded
Wetherell, with one investor begging him to take good care of his
health.
</P>
<P>
   But any Wetherell fitness program will not include slowing down.
He announced more deals at the meeting, including a nuts-and-bolts
alliance with Akamai Technologies of Cambridge, Mass. CMGI will
speed up the distribution of data from its Web-based companies by
pumping it through through Akamai's worldwide data network. Users
of CMGI's AltaVista search service and NaviSite Web site hosting
service could see improved performance as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Also, CMGI will leverage its recent deal with Pacific Century
CyberWorks, a Hong Kong satellite communications company, to
distribute Internet data in Asia. CMGI aims to improve the
performance of Asian Internet services by transmitting data from
space directly to local data caches run by Akamai.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders also got a preview of iCast, a free software
download for multimedia entertainment. The software plays audio and
video files over the Internet, as well as CD recordings on the
user's own computer.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition, iCast automatically identifies the CD being
played, and links the listener to CMGI-operated Web sites
containing information on the artist and links to other Internet
users with similar tastes in music. The iCast software also
features chat rooms where people can communicate while listening to
a favorite Internet radio station.
</P>
<P>
   However, CMGI CEO David Wetherell said that one of his company's
least glamorous investments _ Engage Technologies _ is at the heart
of its entire business strategy. Engage uses cookies _ small bits
of data attached to the browsers of Internet users _ to follow
people through the Internet, collecting detailed data on their
Web-surfing habits. This information is then used to precisely
target them with advertisements tailored to the user's tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think someday this will be the most valuable database in the
world,'' Wetherell said, predicting that leading Web advertisers
will demand the kind of targeted marketing that Engage can provide.
Wetherell described how the millions of visitors to other CMGI
Internet sites will constantly feed new data to the Engage
database. In turn, that new data will be used to display targeted
advertising to the Web site's visitors, with advertisers paying
handsomely for the privilege.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1920EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2190 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HARVARD-INVESTMENT-BO     12-17 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-INVESTMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD MONEY MANAGERS BRING IN LESS BACON, LOWER PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvard University's elite money managers are punishing
themelves.
</P>
<P>
   Top executives at the institution's investment arm are taking
home lower pay this year, due to leaner returns in their mega
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   In the lucrative investing world, ``less'' can be relative. The
Harvard managers, who run the university's $14 billion endowment,
are still among the best paid in the business. Their paychecks
declined nowhere near as much as their investment returns, whose
leaner shape Harvard has blamed on outside, non-staff money
managers, an inability to place more cash in venture capital funds,
and tough benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Management's new top earner, Philip Dubuque, will take
home $9.5 million in salary and bonus for the fiscal year ended in
June, just under the $10.2 million last year's lead earner,
Jonathon Jacobson, garnered. Jacobson left the firm last year to
start a private investment fund.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, the firm's top five money managers, president, and
dozens of other employees will take home $41.3 million this year,
compared with $45.4 million last year. The slimmer bounty, most of
which goes to the top guns, is still about 50 percent above 1997's
payout and four times 1996 levels.
</P>
<P>
   The pay packages are closely watched by the secretive investment
industry and by some university critics, who dislike the fact that
Harvard money managers earn more than a tenured professor. Most of
the compensation comes from bonuses, which are tied to performance
over time.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most money management companies, Harvard Management is
required to disclose compensation in routine tax filings because it
is technically a nonprofit. Harvard, whose endowment is the largest
of its kind, defends the pay packages as suitable for professional
investors who have earned the university billions of dollars. It
says hiring more outside companies to oversee the endowment would
cost far more.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Harvard Management reported a total return of 12.2
percent for fiscal 1999. That figure, far below the firm's
benchmark of 18.9 percent, was a drop from year-ago levels of 20.5
percent. Harvard Management president Jack Meyer said in a
September letter to university contributors that the
underperformance was due to unnamed, outside money managers the
firm uses to manage part of its portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Still, over the long term, the portfolio has done well, gaining
20.1 percent over five years, just over its goal of 19.1 percent.
The median for that period for large institutional funds, which
include university endowments, was 16.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard places some of its money in the hands of two former
Harvard Management professionals, Jacobson and Tim Peterson, a
high-yield manager who left in September to form his own company,
Regiment Capital. A Harvard Management spokeswoman declined to name
other outside managers. The university farms out about one third of
its endowment portfolio to other firms.
</P>
<P>
   Within Harvard Management, David Mittelman, who manages
fixed-income, saw his pay package fall to $8.9 million from $9.8
million last year. Phillip Gross, equities, fell to $8.7 million
from $9.7 million. Robert Atchison, equities, slipped to $7.3
million from $7.9 million. And Jeffrey Larson, foreign equity, took
home $1.6 million. He didn't make the top five last year.
</P>
<P>
   President Jack Meyer earned $1.6 million, down from $1.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are well paid relative to the market,'' said Joel
Millonzi, an executive compensation specialist in New York. He said
top mutual fund managers at giant funds can make anywhere from $5
million on up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 1922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
