<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'ALLESANDRO CRITICAL OF IOC REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their No. 1 critic was not impressed with the ``reforms''
announced by the International Olympic Committee this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key questions still have not been answered,'' said David
D'Alessandro of John Hancock, a major Olympic sponsor. ``Where is
the money coming from, and where does it go? (The IOC has) never
released a full, comprehensive financial report, and until they do,
all of this talk of reform is just talk.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro was the first one to speak out against the IOC
after the scandal surrounding the Salt Lake City bidding came to
light. He was one of the first to call for reform, but when it came
this week, he wasn't pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping for more, and I hope more will be done once (Juan
Antonio) Samaranch leaves at the end of next year,'' said
D'Alessandro. ``But that will depend on the person who takes his
place. If that person doesn't push for some meaningful reforms,
then nothing will happen in the long run. (The IOC) said they were
going to be more democratic in the way they do business. But when
you look at what happened, they are going to continue to elect
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people presently on the board vote to keep each other on
the board, and have grandfathered themselves into their positions
until they are 80 years old. They tried to make it look good by
adding some new members, but those members will have just four-year
or eight-year terms. Some of the people on the board now are only
in their 40s, so they can stay on the committee for 30 years or
more, and they will continue to manipulate the process the way they
have been doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this is not ``reform'' at all, but just a spin
to keep the heat down. Between 2000, 2002, and 2004, when the
Olympics are held in Australia, Salt Lake City (Winter), and
Greece, the IOC will take in $5 billion. Where does it come from?
Where does it go? If the US government is sincere about Olympic
reform, they'd keep the IOC on the hot seat until they provided all
of the answers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is one NFL team's character report on Rae Carruth, who now
faces first-degree murder charges in North Carolina, when he was
coming out of Colorado:
</P>
<P>
   ``A solid citizen from a single-parent home. Very supportive
mother. Father was a Navy Seal. Has extended family. Conscientious
student. Will graduate on time. Confident but not cocky. Works
hard. Very respectful person. Good self-motivation. Double major in
English and Education. Likes to write. Overall grade 8 (on scale of
10).'' Carruth took the Wonderlic Test twice, scoring 21 and 24,
which is well above average and high for someone playing the wide
receiver position.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He has Boston stamped all over him, but no one will be rooting
harder for the Eagles than Jeffrey Lurie when they play the
Patriots in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie, 48, remembers seeing the first Patriots game when he was
just a kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Gino (Cappelletti) kicking a field goal, but the
star of the game was Gene Mingo of the Broncos,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie grew up in Newton, then attended Buckingham, Browne &AMP;
Nichols, Clark (bachelor's degree), Boston University (master's),
and Brandeis (doctorate). But despite all of the education, his
first love was sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent many a night sleeping out on Causeway Street waiting
to buy obstructed-view seats to see Orr and Esposito play for the
Bruins; or Havlicek and Cowens with the Celtics,'' Lurie said.
``Those are some of the greatest memories of my life. They are
still with me today. I think the sports figure I admired most was
Red Auerbach. He was a model for me. He didn't always make the easy
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason Lurie will be rooting for the Eagles? He owns them.
``I wanted to buy the Patriots, and I almost did. I thought I had a
deal to buy the team with James Orthwein (who preceeded Bob Kraft),
but I couldn't close on it. I'm happy here in Philadelphia. I like
the people. In the long run, I think we are going to be good, and
this will be a good investment for me. I'm happy that this is what
I decided to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one could have been more disappointed than Patriots running
back Terry Allen when he got stopped on the 1-yard line last week
against the Colts. Allen needs two more touchdowns to get 10 and a
$250,000 incentive bonus. Allen took a shot when he signed for
short money, the minimum $400,000 for a veteran, at the start of
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Allen reached his first incentive last week, topping 700 yards
rushing, which kicked in a $250,000 bonus. If he gets 1,000 yards
(he has 713) by the end of the season, he'll get another $250,000.
For every two touchdowns he scores the rest of the way, another
$250,000 will be added.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, Allen got a potential big break last week when
teammate Kevin Faulk broke his ankle. Faulk and Allen were sharing
time, so now Allen will be forced to carry most of the load, giving
him a better chance at reaching his incentives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NHL owners are ``going down the road'' toward allowing their
players to perform in the 2002 Winter Games, but it isn't a done
deal yet. The owners want some assurance from NBC, which will
handle the telecast, that their games will get some prime-time
treatment. In Nagano, with CBS doing the broadcast, men's hockey
was not featured. Question: If the NHL players are allowed to play,
will the three stiffs who trashed some rooms in Nagano but still
haven't had the courage to step forward and accept the blame be
allowed to play for the US team? . . . Antoine Walker, who has his
hands on the ball as much as any Celtic, averages one assist every
17 minutes, or two a game. Adrian Griffin leads the team in
rebounding, even though he's just 6 feet 5 inches. Rick Pitino
should have a rule that Walker is forbidden to take a shot above
the foul line. At least when he misses in the paint, he has a
chance to get fouled . . . Of all the players who participated in
the fabulous Ryder Cup tournament at Brookline, only two sent
thank-you notes for the treatment they recieved at the club. Mark
O'Meara and Payne Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As long as the Bruins play their current system, they will never
score enough to be consistent winners. You can't score goals in the
NHL when your players' first thought is to get back and defend.
Somewhere along the line, Pat Burns has to turn them loose to see
what they can do in the offensive zone, or else this team isn't
going anywhere . . . At the recent major league baseball meetings,
it was revealed in an owners' financial report that only eight
teams in the league made money. The Red Sox were credited with a
profit of $5 million because they reached the American League
Championship Series vs. the Yankees, but in reality, the team broke
even because it never received the more than $5 million it was owed
by its local television broadcaster. The Sox will file a lawsuit to
try to recoup some of that money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Through 203 games this year, NFL officials have reviewed 157
plays with the help of instant replay. Forty-seven plays have been
reversed. The biggest flap of the season came last Monday night in
the Broncos-Jaguars game in Denver. Broncos QB Brian Griese was hit
trying to pass. Referee Gerry Austin, standing 15 feet away, ruled
an incomplete pass. Jacksonville had recovered the ball thinking it
was a fumble, and when Tom Coughlin asked for a replay, Austin
reversed his own call, making it a fumble. However, he gave the
ball back to Denver, saying he blew the whistle (thinking
originally it was an incomplete pass) when the ball hit the ground.
Well, Al Michaels and Boomer Esiason, broadcasting the game for
ABC, hit the roof and stayed on Austin's back all night. They
couldn't seem to get it through their heads that once Austin
reversed himself, the ball was a fumble, and not an incomplete
pass. And the rule is, once the whistle blows, which it did when
the ball hit the ground, the ball goes to the team that last had
possession. That was Denver. The Jacksonville player did not touch
the ball until after the whistle. Austin, after blowing the first
call, made the absolute right decision after that, and then was
villified.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a very moving passage in Wally Carew's book ``Men of
Spirit, Men of Sports'' involving former Boston College basketball
coach Jim O'Brien. For the first time, O'Brien tells what happened
inside his family when his wife, Christine, died suddenly of a
heart attack in their home, leaving behind Jim, and daughters Erin
and Amy. ``Christine and I kissed each other and told each other
how much we loved one another each day. My girls and I do the same
thing. It's very important. People need to say it. People need to
hear it, too. Every single day. I don't know how to tell you this,
but for five months after Christine's death, a light bulb in one of
the bathrooms was on the verge of blowing. It flickered on and off.
We didn't change it. It was her. Christine was there. It was her
way of telling us that she was with God, and she was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most sought Red Sox farmhands in trade talks at the league
meetings were third baseman Wilton Veras, first baseman Dernell
Stenson, and catcher Steve Lomasney. The Sox let every team know
that John Valentin was available, and there was no interest . . .
Both the coaches and players admit the Patriots' major problem all
year on defense has been getting the other team off the field on
third down. Why, then, have the Patriots brought Ted Johnson back
to play middle linebacker, when Johnson does not play third-down
passing situations? A year ago, they let Drew Bledsoe play with a
broken finger and he went out for the year when he reinjured it.
Last week, they let Ty Law play with a broken thumb, and he's out
for the year after he reinjured it. There is no reason to put Ted
Johnson back on the field until he is 100 percent healthy, and his
injured biceps doesn't need a brace to protect it . . . Bruce
Sundlun made this space in the past as the Rhode Island governor
who almost got Bob Kraft to move the team to Providence. Sundlun,
no longer in office and closing in on 80 years of age, recently got
married for the fifth time, which led top hoop writer Bill Reynolds
to offer in his Providence Journal column: ``There is no truth to
the rumor that Sundlun is honeymooning in Viagra Falls.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
