<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Dec. 18 and thereafter. For questions about stories, contact the
Daily News, (818) 713-3705.
</P>
<P>
   SNOW-GIFT (LOS ANGELES) _ He is an ice man with a warm heart.
Pete De Granis of Union Ice Co. was listening to the radio when he
heard a suburban Los Angeles woman call and say she wanted to
surprise her sick mother with snow on their lawn. But how to do it,
she girl wanted to know. De Granis decided to do it for free,
blowing about five tons of snow on her front yard, a service that
would normally cost upwards of $600. By Harrison Sheppard (Will
move on the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-GIFTS (LOS ANGELES) _ Chocolate apples. Wooden apples.
Silver apples and real apples. By the end of the day Friday,
teachers will have a load of apples, Christmas gifts from their
students. But they also get an unusual and sometimes creative
variety of presents. One boy brought his teacher a bag of his
mother's used lipstick. By David Baker (Will move on the ``n''
California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   MERCY-PLEA (LOS ANGELES) _ ``For Artiom to be in jail would not
ease my sadness at all, and also my son wouldn't want Artiom to be
jailed,'' wrote the mother of a 17-year-old Hoover High School in
Glendale student fatally gunned down off campus last year by Artoim
Badalyan, who was to be sentenced this week. Prosecutors are
seeking a 6-year sentence for Badalyan, 19, who pleaded no contest
to involuntary manslaughter in the accidental death of his friend.
But the victim's mother is pleading with the judge to free
Badalyan, writing a moving letter in Armenian and English. By Donna
Huffaker (Will move on the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news
wires.)
</P>
</TEXT>
