<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMAKOV ANNOUNCES BID FOR PRESIDENCY AS PARLIAMENTARY ELECTIONS
NEAR  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Shortly before Russians, spread across nine time zones,
vote for a new parliament, Yevgeny Primakov, the former prime
minister and leader of an anti-Kremlin electoral bloc, announced
Friday that he would be a candidate for the presidency in the
election scheduled for June.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, 70, previously said he would not decide on a bid for
Russia's top job until after the parliamentary elections on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But in the final hours of a bitter and ugly campaign, he told an
audience of Moscow university students that he had sped up his
decision to take a stand against the ``lawlessness'' pervading the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``After much thought and after receiving thousands of letters
and telegrams, I have decided without further delay to announce
today that I shall take part in the presidential race,'' said
Primakov, whose re-entry into national politics last summer ignited
a full-scale counteroffensive by Kremlin political strategists.
</P>
<P>
   Some political analysts seized on Primakov's announcement as a
last-minute maneuver designed to galvanize supporters for his
Fatherland-All Russia political bloc, which has been slipping in
the polls, falling behind both the Communist party and a newly
concocted pro-Kremlin alliance, nicknamed Medved, or Bear. Official
election results are expected to be reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the vote Sunday is for 450 seats in the parliament's
lower house, the Duma, these elections are widely seen as a trial
run for the more critical presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, 26 parties and electoral blocs are competing for
half of the Duma seats, with the other half to be filled by
candidates, running on their own or with party affiliations, in 225
individual districts.
</P>
<P>
   As the parliamentary campaign wound down, the Kremlin's current
occupant, President Boris Yeltsin, now in the final months of his
second term, remained above the fray, while his designated heir,
Prime Minister Vladimir Putin _ now seen as a favorite in the
summer presidential race _ went on national television Friday night
urging voters to get out and vote.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov countered in a television interview Friday evening by
warning viewers to beware of Kremlin-orchestrated provocations,
which he said would be designed to keep voters away from the polls,
particularly in Moscow and St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the heightened nervousness that has accompanied
this election season, he also warned his own supporters not to
engage in any last-minute illegal campaigning that would give
authorities an excuse to penalize his political alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, who last August topped the polls as Russia's most
trusted and respected political leader, has been battered by a
barrage of negative publicity that has dominated campaign coverage
on two major television channels controlled by the Kremlin and its
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Another target has been his main political ally, Moscow Mayor
Yuri Luzhkov, who is running both for parliament and for
re-election in Russia's largest city.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov, once a potential presidential contender himself, said
Friday that he backed Primakov's decision, praising the former
prime minister as ``a wise and predictable leader.''
</P>
<P>
   When the two men joined forces last summer, their Fatherland-All
Russia alliance looked set to capitalize on popular disillusion
with the Yeltsin presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before rebel guerrillas from Chechnya launched an
attack on a neighboring region, setting in a motion a popular war
that has changed Russia's political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The war has boosted the popularity of Putin and reset the
national political mood. According to Russian opinion polls, many
Russian voters have switched their allegiance from Primakov, seen
as a sage statesman-like figure, to Putin, 46, a former KGB officer
who is perceived as a decisive and energetic defender of Russian
interests.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Primakov has been clearly stunned by the vehemence of the media
attacks that have portrayed him as old, feeble and too close to the
Communists, who are the core of the anti-Yeltsin opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In recent statements, both Primakov and Luzhkov have gingerly
begun to question the Kremlin's handling of the Chechen war, even
as they reiterate their support for crushing the Chechen
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Grigori Yavlinsky, leader of Yabloko, a liberal opposition party
that has been bitterly criticized for its more moderate stance on
the war, said Friday night that the outcome of the Chechen campaign
could determine Russia's future political stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very feeble political construction,'' he said
Friday. A failure in Chechnya ``would lead to a collapse of the
entire construction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
