<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE GEORGE, DIABETES UNDER CONTROL, MAY SEE MORE FIELD TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ At halftime, he'll have to check his blood
sugar to make sure it's in control. If not, he will have a shot of
insulin.
</P>
<P>
   Tony George, a diabetic, has had to go through this procedure
for the last eight years, since he was first diagnosed with Type II
diabetes. George, a third-round pick from the University of
Florida, will likely be playing a little more than usual and may
even be the starting free safety against Philadelphia Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to test it at halftime,'' said George. ``I take it
during pregame meal and it keeps me going and regulated throughout
the game. I let my trainers know if my sugar's too high or too low,
or if I have a headache. When you've had it for eight years, you
can tell what you can do and what you can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   We saw a glimpse of George in the fourth quarter of a 20-15 loss
to the Indianapolis Colts last Sunday after Chris Carter went down
with a hamstring pull. Carter made one excellent play in the game,
knocking down a Peyton Manning pass intended for Marvin Harrison at
the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who replaced Willie Clay, was given the job without ever
having started a game in the NFL. A third-round pick out of Texas,
he had made the roster, coincidentally, following a big final
exhibition game against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Now, George has a chance to make his mark. Some feel it's been
long overdue. While Carter hasn't played poorly, he hasn't made big
plays, either.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots held back on George because they didn't believe he
knew the defense well enough. The rookies named him their de facto
representative in camp because he is so well-spoken. At Florida,
George was regarded as a hard hitter. He hasn't had many
opportunities to show that except on special teams, where he's made
nine tackles, second-highest on the team to Larry Whigham and Marty
Moore.
</P>
<P>
   George has been wondering for some time when he'd finally get
his chance, to the point where the Patriots had fielded phone calls
from George's agent.
</P>
<P>
   George is grateful he finally has a chance to play a game he has
played every year of his life at 100 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been hard at all,'' said George. ``I was making
plays on special teams. It's an unfortunate incident with Chris,
and when something happens like that, another trooper has to go in.
That's my duty right now. I have a veteran defensive line and
linebackers, and Lawyer (Milloy) back there, who can show me how
it's done. They have all of that knowledge, so I just have to
follow them and do what I'm supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very exciting to play against a team like Philadelphia or
any team in the NFL,'' said George, who has decent speed for a free
safety (4.5 40). ``I guess it's an opportunity. I'm just gonna do
what the coaches ask me to do. I'm grateful for whatever I get. I'm
not going to do too much or too little.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what ``style'' he can bring to the field, he said, ``I'm
going to leave it to y'all to see what kind of style I bring. I'm
not sure what I'm able to do or what I can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   He said watching on the sideline has been quite an education.
``You have to do those mental reps on the sideline, where you put
yourself in someone else's place and visualize yourself making the
play,'' said George. ``You're able to see the mistakes that are
made and how you come back from them. I've learned so much from
Chris and Lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to this point, the most excitement he's had in the NFL was
proposing to his girlfriend in the lobby of a hotel, down on one
knee, before the Patriots' last loss to the Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   With diamond ring in hand, his girlfriend said yes and George
promptly kissed her as the families roared with approval.
</P>
<P>
   George would like to hear that roar from his coaches Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
