<HEADLINE>
POWER PLANTS TOLD TO CUT POLLUTION TO SPARE EASTERN STATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The head of the US Environmental Protection Agency ordered 392
power plants and industrial facilities from New York to Ohio to
sharply reduce air pollution Friday, granting an unprecedented
request from officials in four eastern states that claim the
emissions worsen their smog problem.
</P>
<P>
   EPA Administrator Carol Browner's ruling _ the first time the
agency has cracked down on pollution in one state on behalf of
another _ is expected to reduce releases of smog-causing nitrogen
oxide by 510,000 tons a year in 12 states, much of which would
otherwise drift on the wind to the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   But owners of the targeted facilities immediately promised to
challenge the EPA directive, expected to cost them $950 million a
year by 2003 when it is fully effective. Lawsuits from Midwestern
and Southern utilities and states have already stalled two related
EPA initiatives to cut smog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's action is an important first for air quality in this
country. We are providing public health protection for Americans
who live hundreds of miles away from significant sources of
pollution,'' said Browner in a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the facilities, many of them coal-burning power plants
equipped with towering stacks to spread emissions over a large
area, are not violating federal law. However, the owners haven't
installed state-of-the-art pollution controls, resulting in
pollution levels several times higher than similar plants in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Massachusetts, who petitioned EPA for help with
out-of-state pollution along with Connecticut, Pennsylvania and New
York, were jubilant. At least 25 percent of the nitrogen oxide in
Massachusetts air comes from outside New England, they said,
suggesting that the EPA order could actually reduce the number of
smoggy days from this summer's 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's ruling ranks in its impact with the surgeon general's
original finding that smoking is hazardous to your health,'' said
Attorney General Tom Reilly, who is taking the lead among
Northeastern states in defending EPA's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Added Massachusetts Environmental Affairs Secretary Robert
Durand, ``EPA is forcing some of the filthiest Midwestern power
plants to clean up so that we will no longer breathe their
secondhand smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Flannery, legal counsel to the Midwest Ozone Group
that represents many of the targeted facilities, said he was
disappointed by the EPA action. He argued that there is no
scientific proof that nitrogen oxide from West Virginia can reach
Massachusetts, as Massachusetts argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting these kinds of controls in place is going to leave the
air quality in Massachusetts, for example, essentially unchanged,''
said Flannery. ``What Ms. Browner has done here is put a
one-size-fits-all control strategy in place'' when the Northeast
would benefit most from a cleanup of facilities within the region.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA ruling is the latest twist in a tense tug-of-war that
long has pitted Northeastern states against the Midwest and South.
Because the prevailing winds flow from west to east, air pollution
in Ohio can be carried to Maine, bringing acid rain and other
problems in their wake.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Connecticut suffers some of the worst smog in the
country in large measure because of pollution from New York City,
New Jersey and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   But the EPA has run into a legal brick wall in attempting to
control far-flung smog sources. In May, the US Court of Appeals in
Washington rejected plans for a tougher national standard for
ozone, a key ingredient in smog that causes lung tissue to stiffen,
calling the EPA action ``an unconstitutional delegation of power.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also stayed Browner's plan to require power plants and
industrial boilers in 22 states to slash nitrogen oxide levels, on
the grounds that it, too, exceeded EPA authority. The court is
expected to make a decision on whether the plan can proceed early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   With both proposals stalled, Browner turned to the state
requests for relief as a back-up strategy, carefully weeding out
requests that would be vulnerable to appeal. For intance, the EPA
rejected petitions from Maine, New Hampshire, Vermont and Rhode
Island because smog levels in those states were not high enough.
</P>
<P>
   But the EPA agreed with Massachusetts' claim that 24 named
facilities in West Virginia aggravate smog here and ordered them to
cut nitrogen oxide releases by 76 percent. EPA called for a 50
percent cut in releases from more than 250 facilities in 12 states
whose emissions reach Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Browner conceded that Friday's ruling reduced nitrogen oxide by
less than half as much as she had hoped under the broader proposal
stayed by the court. However, she said the agency is still
considering petitions for help from three other states and
Washington, D.C. that could eliminate another 150,000 tons of
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Frank O'Donnell, the executive director of the Clean Air Trust,
a Washington environmental group, called the EPA action ``an
important start while the court cases are being resolved,'' noting
that the cleanup is good for the polluting facilities' home states,
too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
