<SLUG> BC-DISABILITY-INSURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SIGNS DISABILITY INSURANCE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Summoning the spirit of Franklin Delano Roosevelt,
President Clinton Friday signed a bill that allows people with
disabilities to go to work without losing their federal health
insurance, saying the legislation would restore the ``dignity of
work'' to the disabled and add new taxpayers to the rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of the Roosevelt memorial, Clinton said the
former president, who relied on a wheelchair but mostly kept it
hidden from public view, had disproved the notion that ``being
disabled meant being unable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, in the spirit of his leadership, in the wake of his
accomplishments, we move further along on our nation's marvelous
journey of equal opportunity for all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which costs $500 million over five years, was
widely lauded by advocates for the disabled. It includes $150
million in grants to states to make it possible for people with
disabilities to hold a job without losing their Medicare or
Medicaid coverage. Disabled people whose earnings or assets are
above federal income limits will be able to buy health insurance
through Medicaid, and Medicare coverage will be extended to four
years for those in the disability insurance system who return to
work. The disabled also will be provided a ``ticket'' that can be
used to purchase services from government or private rehabilitation
programs to help them enter the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should have to choose between taking a job and having
health care,'' Clinton said. He said the bill recognizes that
``work is at the heart of the American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The president hailed the measure as the ``most significant
advancement'' for the disabled since President George Bush signed
the Americans with Disabilities Act into law in 1990. The sponsors
of the Work Incentives Improvement Act included Senators Edward M.
Kennedy and James M. Jeffords, a Republican from Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Vachon, a 32-year-old quadriplegic from Somersworth, N.H.,
called the signing of the new law ``a great day for us.'' In a
telephone interview, he said, ``People in our society are pretty
much judged by what they do. This will allow us to be able to go to
work, earn a living, pay taxes, become productive members of
society rather than people who kind of live off society. This gives
people with a disability a sense of self-worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna P. McNamee, 40, who is stricken with brittle bone disease,
came from her home outside of Cleveland in Willoughby, Ohio, to
attend the signing ceremony. She called the new law ``a dream come
true.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``The door is unlocked, it's open, and a whole new
world lies beyond it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
