<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MACAO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACAO TO QUIETLY RETURN TO CHINESE ORBIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACAO _ At the stroke of midnight Sunday a small European
country that once ruled territories across the globe will
relinquish to China the southern port city of Macao _ the first
European colony in Asia, and now the last.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal will return to China the last bit of land that it ceded
to foreign powers during the era of European empire building, and
at the same moment, draw the curtain on 450 years of Western
expansion in the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   It is a proud, historic moment for China, one the leadership is
trumpeting to boost nationalistic pride and to send a message of
unity to restive provinces such as Tibet and Xinjiang, where
separatism runs high. A digital countdown clock towers over
Tiananmen Square thousands of miles north in Beijing, where a giant
television screen will broadcast the handover live, while a crowd
expected to total 30,000 people celebrates in the square _ 12 times
the number who will attend the ceremony in Macao.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the 1997 British handover of the nearby but far
wealthier port of Hong Kong _ which was broadcast worldwide and
commemorated with parties as far away as Helsinki _ Macao's return
is getting little attention.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, the handover of this tiny outpost has more symbolic
value than economic or strategic significance. But it is in many
ways a bigger deal for China, which is overcoming old humiliations,
and for Portugal, which is regaining dignity lost in ugly exits
from its African colonies, than it is for Macao itself.
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades, this odd mix of a quaint, cobblestoned
tourist town and a tawdry casino haven has enjoyed easy border
crossings and good relations with the mainland, leaving most locals
blase about the coming change. In contrast to worries that clouded
the handover in Hong Kong, Macao's people seem unconcerned that
they might lose freedoms under communist sovereignty. Many even
expect life to be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Macao handover will be a non-event, just a party. For
locals, it's not the end of anything or the beginning of anything,
because there's a sense of continuity,'' said Luis Quintaneiro,
director of the Institute of European Studies in Macao. In the last
two months, outgoing Portuguese Governor Vasco Joachim Rocha Viera
and incoming Beijing-appointed Chief Executive Edmund Ho, a local
banker, ``have done everything together except sleeping,'' he
quipped.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Macao 2 1/2 years after Hong Kong also feeds a
drumbeat of inevitability for Beijing. China will likely turn up
the pressure now on the last missing piece of its historical
empire: the island of Taiwan, where Nationalist Chinese retreated
after losing a civil war to the Communists in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ``Macao is just a snack between the two main courses of Hong
Kong and Taiwan,'' one European observer said drily. ``It will be
used as propaganda in the mainland, and as a warning to Taiwan to
get in line _ because they are next.''
</P>
<P>
   At least for now, though, Beijing's spotlight is on this tiny
outcropping on the western edge of the Pearl River Delta in
southeastern China. Settled by Portuguese sailors in 1557, Macao
became the key Far East entrepot along the trade routes that made
Portugal rich. It was eclipsed 300 years later by Hong Kong, 38
miles away, which had a deeper port that could accommodate larger
ships.
</P>
<P>
   Macao then declined into a sleepy, neglected backwater that the
poet W.H. Auden dismissed as ``a weed from Catholic Europe'' where
``nothing serious can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Its economy was finally resuscitated a few decades ago by
legalized gambling and light manufacturing. Today, most of the
factories have migrated to China, where labor costs are lower and
taxes can be nil.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal tried twice before to give Macao back _ once following
destabilizing riots in 1966, and again when Lisbon rid itself of
other colonies in 1975. Both times China declined, and it was only
after diplomatic relations were established in 1979 that
negotiations over Macao began.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 50,000 people cross the border daily between Macao and
mainland China _ many to work or simply to shop for groceries,
which are cheaper in China. On holidays, that number can swell to
100,000 _ equivalent to one-fifth of Macao's tiny population.
</P>
<P>
   The crossing point resembles a bustling commuter bus station
more than a fortified border; people stream in and out all day
long, and buses return them back to the center of Macao within
minutes. There's no barbed wire, and just a few guards.
</P>
<P>
   A pastel yellow colonial archway with a Portuguese inscription
separates Macao from China, but aside from the hustling vendors,
the less fashionable clothes, and more garbage, things are not very
different on the Chinese side.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lai, 18, an unemployed Macao resident, returned Friday
evening from the Chinese side after an hour-long trip to deliver a
new telephone to relatives. Asked about the handover, Lai said he
had given it little thought, since he, and everyone he knows,
already spends so much time in China.
</P>
<P>
   His only concerns were very down-to-earth _ nothing to do with
the questions of civil rights and political freedoms that swirled
around Hong Kong: ``I assume it'll be just like Hong Kong, where
you can still bet at horse races and go dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Ferreira Wu, 59, was the first Macao businessman to set
up a knitting factory in China five years after the mainland's
economic reforms began in 1979. Today, the self-made millionaire
has 90 percent of his business in China, and harbors nothing but
enthusiasm for the handover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese people understand each other's way of thinking,'' said
Wu. ``Under the Portguese, there are barriers to business created
by language and bureaucracy. . . Everything's conducted in
Portuguese in this administration, and most people have no idea
what's going on, no affinity with the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in Hong Kong, where the mass media and pro-democracy
politicians drew international attention to their worries over
human rights, Macao does not have a critical press nor a strong
opposition. There is just one pro-democracy politician in the
legislature, and few outside pressure groups.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Ng, the legislator, accepts as inevitable that the new
administration will limit certain rights, as has happened in Hong
Kong. ``The government is controlled by Portugal now. Later it will
be controlled by Edmund Ho _ and of course he will obey Beijing,''
Ng said resignedly.
</P>
<P>
   China ``doesn't have to put a hand on Macao, because Macao is
already under control,'' added Herbert Yee, a political science
professor at Hong Kong Baptist University. Macao society is already
pro-China, he said, especially since the 1966 riots.
</P>
<P>
   Locals have several theories as to why Macao feels closer to
China than Hong Kong ever did. One is that because Macao's
residents are largely from rural China and have a lower standard of
living than Hong Kong's, they may be concerned mostly about
livelihood issues. ``Hong Kong's urban professionals were afraid of
losing their professional freedoms and rights. In Macao, people are
more concerned with the basics,'' Wu said.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory is that thanks to centuries of Portuguese
influence and the slow pace of life here, Macao's people are simply
more relaxed than Hong Kong's British-educated notoriously
stressed-out masses, and will take change in stride.
</P>
<P>
   A third factor is that Macao's people are socially conservative,
Yee said, and expect that China will crack down on rising crime and
vice.
</P>
<P>
   As factories have migrated north, tourism became Macao's main
industry, bringing in 40 percent of Macao's revenue. But in recent
years, turf wars between crime syndicates linked to casinos and
prostitution have culminated in gangland killings that tarnished
Macao's reputation, and scared off tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Ng Gok-hung, 50, a jewelry shop employee, echoed the views of
many here. ``As far as I can see, it's good that Macao is going
back to China. Macao is tucked in next to China anyway, and without
China, we wouldn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tourist city, so security is really important,'' he
added, pointing at the uniformed guard at the door. ``We all think
it should be a lot safer under the Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Editorial Assistant Joyce Hor-chung Lau assisted in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
