<HEADER>
A2240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-ART-NY     12-17 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRIA TALKS BREED HOPE: LEBANESE REFRAIN FROM REVENGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Every day this week, the war in southern
Lebanon wore on as usual, with mortars, rockets and air attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps more noteworthy is what did not happen, especially
after a barrage by Israeli-backed troops injured 20 Lebanese
schoolchildren on Thursday. The usual quid pro quo would be a
strike into Israel by Lebanese guerrillas. But with Syria and
Israel holding peace talks in Washington, the guerrillas held back.
</P>
<P>
   The reason appears to be that Syria is determined to keep hopes
for peace alive. Syria controls the guerrillas' access to weapons,
and followers of the war say they have no doubt that Syria has made
clear to the fighters that this is time to hold back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some basic guidelines, and one of them is, `Don't
get the Syrians in trouble,''' said Timor Goksel, a senior adviser
to the U. N. peacekeeping force here, which has tried and failed to
keep peace in Lebanon since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lebanon more than anywhere else remains the crossroads
that could derail the quest for a broader peace. And expressing
relief that Thursday's attacks had not been followed by an ugly
spiral, experts caution that the atmosphere remains extremely
tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we dodge a bullet every day,'' said one analyst in
Beirut, who out of concern for the delicacy of the situation and
the peace talks would speak only on condition that he not be
identified further.
</P>
<P>
   For years the militias, which are run by Hezbollah, the Party of
God, have served as Syrian proxies, launching attacks that have
shown Israel the price of occupying Arab land, even while Syria's
own border with Israel along the Golan Heights remains quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Iran is Hezbollah's main patron and arms supplier, but the
weapon pass through Damascus, and Syria has the hand on the spigot.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while Syria has great influence here, it does not exert
direct control over Hezbollah, and the two do not share interests.
</P>
<P>
   What worries many people is that Hezbollah, which aspires to a
greater political role in Lebanon, may prove more interested in
showcasing itself as the vanguard of Lebanese resistance than in
respecting Syrian orders.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, Thursday's test seems to suggest that the
guerrillas recognize that this would be the wrong time for
defiance. Hezbollah's secretary-general, Hassan Nasrallah, told
dinner guests Thursday that his group would ``settle for a warning
to the Zionists,'' even while arguing that the wounding of the
schoolchildren would justify rocket raids into northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The show of restraint brought sighs of relief in Israel Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Along the northern border, citizens emerged from bomb shelters.
Foreign Minister David Levy, who took part in the talks with Syria
in Washington, said the message he heard there was that Damascus
would ``fight against anyone who would try to break up the talks.''
</P>
<P>
   Syria has long tried to have things two ways in Lebanon: By
allowing Hezbollah to operate freely, it has put pressure on
Israel. But Syria has also set ground rules for Hezbollah that most
of the time have confined the war in southern Lebanon to clashes in
the narrow, rocky swath occupied by Israel since 1978 _ what Israel
calls its security zone.
</P>
<P>
   There have been exceptions, most recently in June, when an
Israeli attack in response to crossborder raids by Hezbollah killed
22 Lebanese civilians and knocked out power to much of Beirut. Many
people here feared that the shelling of the schoolyard Thursday by
the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army might set off a similar
spiral.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, all sides seem to have acted with caution
for fear of spoiling what feels to many like a historic moment,
with Syria and Israel back at the bargaining table for the first
time in nearly four years.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the shelling, Israel had apologized for what it
said was a mistake by its Lebanese counterparts. And in Washington
the president's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said in a
television interview: ``We certainly urged Syria to use its
influence to bring about restraint from Hezbollah.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Israel and Syria held face-to-face talks, between
1993 and 1996, southern Lebanon served as a kind of sideshow where
Syria would sometimes seek to put pressure on Israel by authorizing
Hezbollah to increase the level of violence, including crossborder
rocket attacks. But an Israeli military offensive in Lebanon in
1996, with 18 days of air and artillery strikes, indicated that
Israel would no longer accept such a pressure campaign, and Syria
seems hesitant to try to influence the current talks in the same
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon was not represented at this week's talks. Its
representatives are expected to join sometime after the
negotiations resume on Jan. 3, but the country's foreign policy is
controlled by Syria, which maintains 30,000 troops here, meaning
that Lebanon's future is largely in Syrian hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
