<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2246 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV19-NYT &LR;      12-17 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEM ON SURVEYS, STUDIES AND NEW PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Real Thing &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead of properties, there are old-time soda bottles and
nostalgic ads. Instead of houses, there are six-packs. The big
money is in vending machines, not hotels.
</P>
<P>
   It's Coca-Cola Monopoly, a custom version of the familiar board
game with brand imagery everywhere, from the playing pieces (a Coke
truck, a bottle cap) to the board and the play money. It is
available in some stores and is officially for anyone 8 and over.
</P>
<P>
   But several experts wondered whether the game was smart public
relations for a company that is fighting antitrust accusations on
two continents, was fined $16 million in Italy last week over its
competitive tactics and runs into hostile regulators with almost
any acquisition it tries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did they come out with a (italics)Monopoly(end italics)
game?'' mused Emanuel Goldman, a global consumer-products analyst
for Merrill Lynch who is more of a Scrabble buff himself. ``What's
wrong with Rummi-Kub? Or Boggle?''
</P>
<P>
   A Coca-Cola spokesman, Bob Bertini, said the game, part of the
company's licensing program, was ``really intended to be an
enjoyable, fun board game that's played by millions of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi shareholders may not find the game's inherent
scorched-earth mentality all that amusing. ``The point is to
bankrupt the other players,'' said Lee Weisenthal of the United
States Monopoly Association. ``You start off theoretically even. In
time, those that are most successful drive out those that are
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola is the first soft-drink company to get its own version
of Monopoly, which is also available in theme editions for cities,
colleges, NASA, Nascar racing, Corvette cars, Harley-Davidson
motorcycles and others. USAopoly, the California company that makes
many special editions under license from Hasbro, says Coke's is one
of its better sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brochstein, the executive editor of The Licensing Letter,
said the game, which he does not expect to see on sale in the
European Union, was all about marketing. Though its overall
quarterly profits have declined for two years, Coca-Cola is one of
the top-earning American companies in licensing revenue, according
to Brochstein _ much of it from old ads and other nostalgia items
like those depicted in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be honest, who would collect modern Coca-Cola logos?''
he said. ``The classic imagery is what carries it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertini said Coca-Cola had no other board-game plans. But one
industry expert had a thought. ``Next year, if results improve,''
said John D. Sicher, editor of Beverage Digest, ``they could try
Candyland.''
</P>
<P>
   _Constance L. Hays
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
