<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMES-WORCESTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES CO. TO REDUCE WORK FORCE IN WORCESTER BY 30 JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Employees of the Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette learned Friday
that The New York Times Co. plans to reduce the T&AMP;G's work &UR;  &LR; force
by 30 jobs through a voluntary separation program that will get
under way when it takes control of the paper next month.
</P>
<P>
   The Worcester, Mass. paper employs about 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Co., which also owns The Boston Globe, announced in
October its plan to buy the T&AMP;G for $295 million from Chronicle
Publishing Co. of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   When the sale is completed, expected in early January, T&AMP;G
publisher Bruce Bennett will report to Globe publisher Richard H.
Gilman, in Gilman's role as a member of the senior management team
of The Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   When the T&AMP;G deal was announced, the Times Co. said the Globe
and the T&AMP;G would pursue a ``clustering strategy.'' Because the two
papers publish in neighboring markets, there is a potential for
gaining efficiencies by collaborating on some operations and by
offering national advertisers one-stop shopping for reaching a
large audience of readers in eastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Times Co.'s announcement in October, this
clustering strategy can yield results without affecting either the
Globe's or the T&AMP;G's individual identities or structures.
</P>
<P>
   A review of the T&AMP;G's operations convinced the Times Co. that
the T&AMP;G can maintain its quality with a smaller staff, Gilman wrote
in a memo; the decision to cut 30 jobs at the T&AMP;G ``is being taken
to streamline operations, increase efficiencies, and eliminate
positions that are considered redundant.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Pope, a leader in the Worcester unit of the Providence
Newspaper Guild, said most T&AMP;G staffers were still studying the the
voluntary separation offer put forward by the Times Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're mulling it over,'' Pope said. ``It's murky enough and
not specific enough for most people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, the T&AMP;G staff mobilized to cover a fire
that killed six Worcester firefighters, and the timing of Friday's
announcement, coming just before Christmas and just after the fire,
angered some in the newsroom, said chairwoman Kathleen A. Shaw of
the T&AMP;G's unit of the newspaper guild.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people feel let down and disheartened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   T&AMP;G staffers who resign under the voluntary separation program
may qualify for ``extra considerations,'' said Peter Horstmann, the
T&AMP;G's director of human resources, who declined to use the word
``buyout'' to describe the Times Co. offer.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman expressed the hope Friday that 30 job cuts could be
achieved through T&AMP;G staffers opting to take the voluntary
separation package. ``Involuntary reductions'' would come ``only as
a last resort,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman said that there are no plans to take similar action at
the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 2016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
