<SLUG> BC-G8-MEETING-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUSTRIALIZED NATIONS CONDEMN RUSSIA'S ACTIONS IN CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The world's biggest industrial countries, meeting with
Russia in the Group of 8, on Friday issued another condemnation of
Moscow's actions in Chechnya and called for an immediate cease-fire
there.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright warned that Russia was
becoming increasingly isolated in the international community,
threatening its larger relationships.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright also stressed the importance of relations with
Russia for the United States, and none of the foreign ministers
even suggested suspending Russia from the group, to which it had
originally been invited by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there any serious discussion about imposing economic or
other sanctions on Moscow, which gave no indication of changing its
policy or fierce tactics toward the Chechens two days before
parliamentary elections in Russia on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As Russian forces continued to bomb Grozny, the Chechen capital,
and to prevent an estimated 45,000 civilians trapped there from
seeking safety, the Russian Foreign Minister, Igor Ivanov,
responded soothingly to the Western criticism, saying, ``On some
issues our opinions coincide, on others they diverge, but what's
important is that this issue should not lead to us growing apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov insisted that ``I never felt isolated from my colleagues
in the Group of 8,'' causing Albright to respond that Ivanov
himself was treated with respect but that Russia's behavior in
Chechnya ``creates problems in the ways it deals with its
partners.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think has been evident at this meeting, frankly, is
that the Russians, through their actions, are self-isolating from
the rest of the international community,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   European and U.S. officials said the host Germans, including
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer, were particularly concerned that
the meeting not concentrate on criticism of Russia, so there would
be no important breach with Moscow, but focus instead on the theme
of preventive diplomacy to stop future wars, a key issue for
Fischer's Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that the French were particularly outspoken
in the meetings about the need to take action to show Moscow that
its partners were serious about their criticism, and that the
British, too, were taking a harder line.
</P>
<P>
   But even the harder-line European idea of ``no sanctions but no
aid'' to Moscow creates problems for Washington, senior U.S.
officials said, since cutting or even suspending aid to Moscow
would be a sanction. In any event, most U.S. aid is directed to
Russian civilians, regions and nongovernmental organizations, not
to the central government, unlike most European foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   Officials acknowledged that the timing of this meeting, so close
to the Russian elections, was awkward, and left Moscow little room
to compromise. The battle against the Chechens has been very
popular among ordinary Russians, and some Western governments fear
that strong Western action now would only backfire and help
anti-Western politicians and parties, like the Communists of
Gennadi A. Zyuganov. Moscow in the meantime seems to be trying to
conquer Grozny by Sunday, a senior U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow responded to similar criticism by NATO foreign ministers
in Brussels earlier this week by complaining of interference in
internal affairs and raising the example of NATO's bombing of
Yugoslavia in the Kosovo conflict this year. ``Another splash of
crocodile tears in Brussels about `human rights' simply amazes us
by its cynicism,'' Ivanov's Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Ivanov kept his cool. ``We are not talking of criticism of
one party by another,'' he said. ``The situation is complicated,
and there are no simple solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ivanov did not want to appear at a joint news conference
with the other foreign ministers, to avoid sitting through public
criticism. Instead, each foreign minister had separate news
conferences or briefings, while Fischer read a ``chairman's
statement'' _ since member Russia would not agree to a joint
statement _ calling for an immediate cease-fire and serious
political negotiations with responsible Chechen leaders to end the
war, as Moscow has already promised but done little to bring about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight against terrorists cannot be won by indiscriminate
war against cities and the whole population,'' said the statement,
approved by the seven other members. ``The war poses a serious
threat to partnership and cooperation between Russia and all of
us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But having allowed the chairman of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe, Knut Vollebaek, to visit the region,
Moscow is now expected to allow a few monitors from the security
organization to watch the borders with Chechnya and Georgia _ ``a
sop,'' a senior European official acknowledged, ``to their need and
our need to show that something happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright also met here with leaders of the democratic opposition
to President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, on a day when a key
Serbian opposition coalition finally called a halt to its dwindling
and now farcical daily rallies against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, with European Union representatives, is intended to
boost the opposition, and Washington is increasing its aid _ from
$12 million to $25 million _ to independent media, the opposition
and nongovernmental organizations. But Albright rejected the
opposition's united call for the lifting of sanctions against
Belgrade and its government, including bans on regular oil
importation and flights to Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
