r t BC-KARTCHNERCAVE-1000(2T     12-17 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KARTCHNERCAVE-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEEP SECRET: ENVIRONMENT OF NEWLY OPENED CAVERNS ZEALOUSLY GUARDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENSON, Ariz. _ The park ranger at the front of our pack beckons
us to step, single-file, inside the long, narrow vault; the ranger
at the back closes a heavy steel door. It slams tightly shut,
vacuum-packing the 20 of us inside. Slowly, we feel the humidity
hit, like a miniature cloud seeping over our bodies, rising inch by
inch from the ground up. The air is warmer and clammier than the
desert air outside. It smells like a swim team's locker room.
</P>
<P>
   We are preparing to go where few _ relatively speaking _ have
gone before: Kartchner Caverns State Park, the most prominent U.S.
cave to open in a generation. Our mid-November tour is taking place
just a week after the cave officially began accepting paying
tourists Nov. 12. Even counting the park officials, construction
workers and media members who've already been here, the number of
previous visitors is only in the low thousands.
</P>
<P>
   And especially compared with other public caves, often used as
homes or hideouts by American Indians or early settlers or even
outlaws before being opened to masses of camera-wielding tourists,
this is truly virgin territory. Located an hour's drive southeast
of Tucson, Kartchner Caverns apparently was untouched by humans
until it was discovered by two amateur cavers in 1974; it was seen
by only a handful of carefully chosen people for a decade after
that. The adventurers who found the caverns kept them a closely
guarded secret until they were sure the rare formations inside
could be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, unlike many caves, Kartchner Caverns is still
``alive.'' Left undisturbed, the colorful and fragile formations
that have developed over millions of years beneath the Arizona
desert will continue to grow. Mishandled, the formations could stop
growing or even be broken off, and the complicated ecosystem of
minuscule cave dwellers could be irrevocably altered.
</P>
<P>
   That's why access to the cave has been so strictly controlled;
visitors who touch a formation won't just be thrown out, they could
be subject to criminal prosecution. And it's why the development of
the cave, from first human footfall to first official tourist, took
more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, it seems absurd that they were able to keep it
secret for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Recipient of much admiring press coverage (a multiday report on
National Public Radio, a cover story in USA Today, among others),
the cave is already being termed a huge success. More than 50,000
tour reservations have been booked, and reservations are largely
sold out into March.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that is due to its geological importance; experts have
called Kartchner Caverns one of the 10 most important caves in the
world in terms of mineral deposits, and it is the only one in the
United States open to visitors. The limestone cave's three major
rooms, each bigger than a football field, contain large versions of
common formations such as columns, stalagmites and stalactites, and
more unusual developments such as ``bacon,'' ``turnip welts,''
``fried eggs,'' ``cave popcorn,'' and ``cave pearls'' _ all of
which look exactly like their names.
</P>
<P>
   And part is due to the irresistible back story, already taking
on a mythological bent. Randy Tufts and Gary Tenen were in their
early 20s when they burrowed into a sinkhole and emerged, after
much muddy crawling, into a vast underground wonderland. Struck by
the beauty, size and rarity of the formations, and sure they'd
stumbled onto a once-in-a-lifetime find, they named it Xanadu and
began covert explorations.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that the cave might be vandalized, and thus ruined, by
other explorers, they kept the secret for two years before finally
informing the Kartchner family, who owned the property over the
cave. The family also recognized the importance of the find, and
they agreed to keep the secret until it could be determined how
best to preserve it. So protective were the caves' defenders that
they blindfolded the first few government officials to tour the
cave so that they couldn't find it on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1988, the Arizona State Parks Board acquired the
cave and began the process of developing it for tourists. Board
members had the benefits of learning from the mistakes made at
caves discovered much earlier, but it was still a slow and
difficult process.
</P>
<P>
   The interior of the cave hovers at 68 degrees year-round, with
99 percent humidity _ a stark contrast to the dry, hot desert
outside. It is precisely those conditions that allowed the
formations to develop and that had to be maintained.
</P>
<P>
   The cave's designers came up with a series of compression
chambers, misters and monitoring stations to keep the cave as
pristine as possible. Then, keeping as much as possible to the
paths made by the original explorers, trails were built by hand
without the use of heavy equipment, often with the help of
volunteers carrying out buckets of rock one or two at a time.
Sometimes only inches of progress were made in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Modifications were added as they went along; for instance, the
cave's walkways are washed each night, to rid them of stray
clothing fibers or hair unwittingly deposited by visitors. Misters
run intermittently , to compensate for the moisture carried out on
guests' clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Construction went more slowly and cost more money than
anticipated; $28 million has been spent so far, and they're not
finished. The opening was postponed from November 1997, mostly
because tunnel construction took about 16 months longer than
anticipated, but finally, tours began this November.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   What has been built is not the typical herd-'em-in tourist
attraction that so many U.S. caves have become.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations are strongly recommended; on my visit, several
groups without them were turned away. Visitors are urged to arrive
at least an hour before their scheduled hour-long tour, in order to
examine the exhibits on cave formations at the visitor's center and
watch a short video on the cave's development.
</P>
<P>
   Tour groups, which are limited to 20 members _ 16 reserved and
four walk-ups _ are driven to the cave's entrance in electric
trams. Rules are strictly enforced: no flash photos, no
videotaping, no gum, no littering, no strollers or backpacks. Each
tour is led by two park rangers, one of whom stays in front and the
other who brings up the rear, and they keep a close eye on
tourists. Kind of like a Nature's Secret Service, they magically
rearrange themselves to contain visitors so that nobody has a
chance to surreptitiously finger a stalactite. (They are serious
about this. A temporary worker who intentionally broke off a piece
of crystal during construction was fired, then charged with a
misdemeanor; he was fined the cost of the repair and given two
years' probation.)
</P>
<P>
   The mood on my tour is more school field trip than vacation
outing; even though rangers John Hawkins and Peter Polley are
pleasant and chatty, they take their jobs seriously. When we arrive
at the cave's entrance, guarded by a volunteer, we slowly file into
the first of two airlocked compartments.
</P>
<P>
   After several firm warnings to touch nothing, even by accident,
Hawkins opens another steel door and we enter a second compression
chamber, filled with air that's even more humid than that of the
first. Finally, a third steel door is opened, and we step into the
actual cave.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the caverns' three major rooms are now open. Though the
scientific importance of the cave's deposits may be lost on the
average visitor, the visuals are impressive. It's hard to believe
it's all just rocks. The butterscotch drapery looks like beeswax;
pieces of the wall shimmer like they were sprinkled with diamond
chips; the impossibly skinny ``soda straw'' formations are so
fragile they look like they'd break if you brushed against them.
</P>
<P>
   The first room on the tour is called the Rotunda Room; its most
memorable feature is the mud flats, where what looks like a deep
sea of mud is topped with an expansive ceiling of stalactites
reaching almost to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Next, we're led into the larger, more dramatic Throne Room. This
is home to the cave's largest formation, the grandiose Kubla Khan.
A massive 58-foot-tall rock column, it looks like a forced-together
melange of frozen drips and molten, oozing mud, kind of like a
backdrop from a Sid and Marty Kroft Saturday-morning show.
</P>
<P>
   The tour ends with a meditative light-and-music show at Kubla
Khan, which we watch sitting on concrete benches built on a rock
outcropping where the two young explorers used to sit and
contemplate their find. If the show is a little New Age meets Las
Vegas, it's still beautiful to watch the lights flicker against the
shimmering rocks and awe-inspiring to consider what it must have
felt like to be the first humans to come across this.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows for sure what the long-term effects will be, on
either the cave or the surrounding area.
</P>
<P>
   The closest town, Benson, has been bracing itself for a tourism
bonanza, but its offerings remain fairly basic and unsophisticated:
chain motels, fast-food outlets, a few family-owned restaurants and
souvenir shops. Many visitors will probably stay instead an hour's
drive away in Tucson, with its superior lodging, restaurants and
cultural attractions, but tourism officials expect that more
upscale dining and lodging, such as small bed-and-breakfasts, will
sprout near the cave.
</P>
<P>
   As for the cave, it will continue to develop as well. Excavation
and construction continues on a third area, the aptly named Big
Room, which is nearly double the size of the Throne Room. The Big
Room is expected to open for tours within a few years, though an
exact date has not been set. The remaining large feature, the
250-foot-long Subway Tunnel that links the Throne and Rotunda rooms
with the Big Room, will probably never open to the public because
it is too narrow and muddy and unsuited to a large number of
visitors. In addition, too much human contact could easily damage
it environmentally.
</P>
<P>
   That, in fact, is the overriding unanswered question about the
whole underground system. Park officials have begun a 10-year study
of the effects of tourism, based on an estimated 200,000 visitors
per year. What they do with the cave _ open it to more visitors,
limit it to fewer, or, more remotely, shut it down completely _
hinges on that.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
