<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF VALUES IN LAGGARD SMALL CAPS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Questions may be italicized)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's something to chew on: For almost all of this year, the
yield on the Russell 2000 index of small stocks, now 1.43 percent,
has been higher than that for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index of
mostly large-cap stocks, currently 1.19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500, of course, isn't what it used to be _ since 1988,
nearly 300 of its components have changed. Still, these are most of
the country's biggest, most established companies, many of which
pay dividends. Small companies often aren't expected to pay
dividends; they are expected to grow, and faster than their larger
cousins.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, that hasn't been happening either, and investors
have long since gotten the message. Unless something miraculous
happens in the next two weeks, 1999 will be the sixth consecutive
year that the Russell 2000 has underperformed the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the worm is finally about to turn. John H. Laporte, lead
portfolio manager of T. Rowe Price New Horizons _ one of the
nation's oldest small-cap funds _ certainly hopes so. Last week, he
took some time to talk about the sector's prospects. Here are
excerpts from the conversation: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What will it take to get small-cap stocks moving? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. To me, the really critical factor is an improvement in
relative earnings growth. Historically, the sweet spot of the
economic cycle has been when small companies do exceedingly well.
That has not happened this time around, and I don't know why it
hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   If small companies can deliver the earnings, investors are going
to buy them. And I see no fundamental reason why small companies
will be permanently disadvantaged in terms of earnings growth. It
doesn't make sense that in the aggregate, small companies will grow
their earnings several percentage points below big companies.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five or six years, the market cycle has challenged
the long-held tenet that small caps outperform over the long term.
But what you need to keep in mind is that small caps have
historically traded in long cycles of five to seven years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some argue that large companies have adopted many of the
mannerisms of small ones, enhancing their ability to outperform.
Does that train of thought have merit? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There is some validity to some of those arguments. One of the
reasons large companies are doing better is that they got religion
in the 1990s, and it became voguish to cut costs. Since large
companies had more fat to be cut, that has helped large companies
in general.
</P>
<P>
   Small companies have also suffered because the cost of capital
has done nothing but get more expensive relative to large caps. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. And yet there is a story within the story this year. Haven't
small technology stocks done much better than the average small-cap
stock? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Even in the small-cap world, technology stocks in general
have done very, very well. There are some small-cap growth funds
that have more than 50 percent of their money invested in
technology and the Internet and are up over 100 percent this year.
We are more diversified than that and have done OK _ through Dec.
14, we were up just over 17 percent. But it really depends what
your benchmark is. My average technology stock is up 50 percent to
75 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The other area that has done well is biotechnology. Outside of
those two areas, everything else has shown only a nominal gain. You
could make a case that small-cap tech stocks are cheaper than
large-cap tech stocks. You can also say they are expensive, really
expensive, relative to other small-cap stocks. A year ago, I could
have generalized by saying that all small-cap stocks were cheap. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you see this mania for technology and Internet stocks
continuing? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Over the next few months the trend will continue. But I don't
expect it to go on indefinitely, because the valuation disparity is
so wide. You are seeing a record number of smaller companies being
bought out by bigger ones this year, in part because large caps see
value there. I think there is a floor being created where the
corporate world is going to step in and say, ``Hey, this is
ridiculous; I can buy cheaper than I can make.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Would you care to share some names of stocks that look
compelling right now? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Omnicare, an institutional pharmacy provider, is one. They
have a great growth record, but have suffered this year because of
problems in the nursing home industry. The stock has been
slaughtered. At the moment, it is selling at about 10 times what I
think it will earn next year.
</P>
<P>
   In technology, the stock I like is Sipex, an analog
semiconductor company. Their earnings are down sharply this year
due to a problem with an outside supplier. We think they will do
much better next year. The stock is currently selling at less than
20 times earnings. I don't know many technology companies you can
say that about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
