<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Adviser to the Stars Moves to a Court Setting &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you missed Dana Giacchetto's first 15 minutes of fame, stay
tuned. This controversial young financial adviser _ his clients
until recently included Leonardo DiCaprio, Matt Damon, Ben Affleck
and Cameron Diaz _ is fighting a spate of nasty publicity by suing
his estranged business partners.
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine and the Los Angeles Times recently reported that
clients were deserting Giacchetto (pronounced ju-CHET-oh), but
Giacchetto says those reports actually caused the exodus.
</P>
<P>
   His lawsuit accuses a business partner, Jeffrey A. Sachs, of
slandering him by falsely telling many people, including one of
DiCaprio's advisers, that Giacchetto's firm, the Cassandra Group in
New York, was in trouble. Sachs, a New York political and business
consultant, said that ``there has been no defamation and no
untruths.''
</P>
<P>
   In his suit, Giacchetto further contends that Sachs and Samuel
S. Holdsworth, a former magazine publisher, unfairly pushed him out
of a venture capital fund that they organized in November 1998 with
an affiliate of Chase Manhattan Bank. Holdsworth expressed sympathy
``for someone who was once a very great friend, who is now
desperate enough to employ these sorts of tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   A subdued Giacchetto acknowledged that 17 clients _ including
the young stars _ have left his firm, but said he still managed
$141 million for 290 others. ``I understand why clients would not
want their name associated with this bad publicity, but I believe
many will come back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _Diana B. Henriques &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let Others Do the Spadework &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two leading financiers are getting deep into gardening without
getting dirt under their presumably well-trimmed fingernails. Lord
Rothschild and Henry Kravis, longtime friends, are paying $1.2
million for 9 percent of a gardening Web site, Crocus.co.uk, a
gardening site yet to go online.
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild acknowledged that he knew little about gardening or
the Internet. ``I can't pretend to be a gardener, but I try,'' he
said, adding that, in using the Internet, ``I have to get help
constantly.'' Rothschild's son, James, _ ``fanatically keen on the
Internet,'' his dad says _ has advised him on investing in this
site and others.
</P>
<P>
   _ANDREW ROSS SORKIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Counting Down the Megahertz &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most exclusive New Year's Eve celebrations may be in
the Silicon Valley command centers that are set up to monitor
customers' computers. Many top executives plan to be present.
``I'll be sipping champagne with our employees who will be working
in our Palo Alto command center,'' said Carly Fiorina,
Hewlett-Packard's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   While Hewlett-Packard has agreed to let reporters watch, other
companies are being more reserved and less festive. On the other
side of the valley, in Santa Clara, Calif., John Chambers, chief
executive of Cisco Systems, plans to oversee a center that will be
closed to the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it won't be a party atmosphere,'' said a Cisco
spokesman, John Earnhart. ``We have no idea what is going to happen
in Asia and Eastern Europe, but hopefully it will be a very boring
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the valley's generals plan to linger in war rooms.
While Sun Microsystems will be on full alert, Scott McNealy, the
chief executive, might not be. As Elizabeth McNichols, a
spokeswoman, explained, ``I think he'll be at home.''
</P>
<P>
   _John Markoff &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No Takers Yet for `Dream Job' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Roth's two-year search for a director of development for
his Vornado Realty Trust, the big Manhattan commercial landlord, in
recent weeks included none other than John E. Zuccotti, an eminence
grise of New York real estate. Zuccotti did not appreciate the
call, according to a close friend. No mere hired hand, Zuccotti,
the former deputy mayor, is chairman of Brookfield Financial
Properties, which owns almost as much Manhattan property. ``They
were so naive'' to even think they could hire him, this person
said.
</P>
<P>
   At least two other candidates have rebuffed overtures. And
Bernard Mendik, ostensibly co-chairman of Vornado, left a year ago
rather than continue playing third fiddle to Roth and endure his
barbed wit.
</P>
<P>
   Vornado plans to announce an, er, winner early next year. ``This
is absolutely everybody's dream job as a developer,'' said Jane
Lyons, a partner at Rhodes Associates, hired 82 days ago, she said
on Friday, for the search. ``But you've got to have the
professional weight and experience to sit at the table with
Steve.''
</P>
<P>
   _Charles V. Bagli
</P>
</TEXT>
