<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBANS-DETAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 CUBAN INMATES GIVE UP; 6 CONTINUE STANDOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. MARTINVILLE, La. _ Two of the eight Cuban detainees holding
hostages inside a parish jail here surrendered to the authorities
late Thursday night while a hostage came out at about the same
time, the sheriff said Friday. Though negotiations to end the
five-day standoff continued, there was no indication that it was
drawing to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long, slow process,'' the sheriff, Charles S. Fuselier
of St. Martin Parish, said of negotiations with the six remaining
Cuban inmates who are seeking an end to their indefinite
confinement.
</P>
<P>
   The six inmates continued to hold the warden, Todd Louvierre,
and a deputy, Jolie Sonnier, in the warden's office along with six
female prisoners, Fuselier said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Another deputy, Brandon N. Boudreaux, who had been held since
the uprising began on Monday, came out of the jail late Thursday
and was described as being in good condition. Fuselier would not
comment on reports that Boudreaux had escaped. Three female inmates
also came out at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the jail, 35 Cuban detainees who are not part of the
uprising were still behind bars, along with 26 other inmates, the
sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Mathews III, a special agent with the FBI who is part of
the negotiating team, said the authorities have regained control of
most of the jail, with the exception of the warden's office where
the hostages and captors were confined. The detainees had been in
control of the jail's command post and the building's electronic
locks, but apparently gave up that room.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans, all of whom were part of the Mariel boatlift in 1980
when 125,000 Cubans arrived in the United States, had finished
serving time for crimes committed in the United States and would
normally be deported if they were citizens of most other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Cuban government has refused to take them back, the
inmates are being held under a 1996 federal law prohibiting the
immigration agency from releasing noncitizens who are considered
threats to society.
</P>
<P>
   The six had been convicted in the United States of various
crimes, including homicide, rape, burglary, robbery and drug sales,
according to records released by the Immigration and Naturalization
Service.
</P>
<P>
   They are among 2,400 Cuban detainees held mostly in small-town
jails around the country, whose continued detention has drawn
protests from human-rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mike Foster, who visited the jail Friday, said Louisiana
was growing weary of the difficulty in housing Cuban detainees.
Louisiana has nearly 1,000 Cubans in local jails, many of whom had
been in the nearby Oakdale detention facility before they rioted in
1987 and were then dispersed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more of this, the less the people will want to take
them,'' Foster said.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours before the deputy and the two Cubans came out, the
jail's public address system crackled with the voices of the warden
and Ms. Sonnier.
</P>
<P>
   In what appeared to be a prerecorded statement, the warden said
the federal government had misled the public about the nature of
the Cubans' detention, and Ms. Sonnier had asked for a helicopter
to take the prisoners to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Fuselier and FBI officials would not discuss the statements or
whether they might have been coerced, although the sheriff seemed
to indicate he did not take them seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an opinion of what took place, but I would rather
reserve that,'' the sheriff said.
</P>
</TEXT>
