<HEADER>
A2274 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV19-N     12-17 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Fraction at a Time &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bull market hasn't trickled down to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that many stocks trade for a couple of hundred
dollars or more a share, so buying a round lot of 100 shares can be
prohibitively expensive for many people. Then there are brokerage
commissions, the costs of putting together a diversified portfolio
of 10 or 12 stocks, and the minimums _ sometimes $20,000 or more _
that discount brokerage firms may require for opening an account.
</P>
<P>
   A new online service, Buyandhold.com of New York City,
drastically lowers the barriers to entry for small-fry investors,
allowing individuals to open accounts for as little as $20 and to
buy fractional shares of stock _ say, one-quarter of a share of
CMGI for about $53.
</P>
<P>
   The fee to buy or sell shares is $2.99 a transaction, regardless
of the dollar amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity for everybody and everyone to
participate on Wall Street,'' said Peter E. Breen, chief executive
of Buyandhold.com, which began operations last month. ``This is the
feel-good service of Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   A possible downside: The low transaction cost stems from the
fact that buy-and-sell orders are executed just twice a day, once
in the morning and once in the afternoon, when an investor offer to
sell, say, one-fifth of a share of Microsoft stock, for $23.05, is
pooled with like trades of other investors. So investors won't know
in advance the exact prices of stocks they trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are an aggregator of transactions,'' said Breen, 35.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the target audience of Buyandhold.com is participants in
direct purchase plans, sometimes called dividend reinvestment
programs, or DRIPs, that let investors buy shares directly from a
company. Buyandhold.com will simplify such investors' paperwork by
providing them with an online account that shows their average cost
and other data.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, Buyandhold.com had attracted 3,000 accounts,
Breen said.
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Teitelbaum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Active Managers Win Again &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the last quarter of the millennium winds to a close, it looks
as if investors who placed their bets with the active fund managers
have again outperformed those who chose to simply track the
Standard and Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lipper Inc., the research firm, the average United
States diversified equity fund, a proxy for actively managed stock
funds, returned 12.7 percent from Sept. 30 through Thursday, versus
10.8 percent for the average S&AMP;P 500 index fund.
</P>
<P>
   Unless something upsets the markets in the next two weeks, this
will be the third quarter in a row in which active stock fund
managers beat the index. ``The mutual fund managers really earned
their fees this year,'' said Edward S. Rosenbaum, director of
research at Lipper.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the active managers' outperformance was their voracious
appetite for technology stocks _ the market's golden sector. ``As
growth stock managers, they jumped in with both feet,'' Rosenbaum
said, adding that the sizzling market for new issues had also
helped active managers' relative performance, because index funds
generally don't buy such offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 25 largest funds, the Janus 20 was named by Lipper as
the best performer in the quarter through Thursday, returning 30.7
percent, followed by Janus Worldwide, 29.9 percent, and Fidelity
Growth, 29 percent. The biggest fund, Fidelity Magellan, beat the
second-largest, Vanguard 500 Index, 12 percent to 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Teitelbaum
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
