<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2278 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-WITH-EHLERS-AR     12-17 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-EHLERS-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH HERBERT E. EHLERS AND DAVID G. SHELL: HERITAGE
CAPITAL APPRECIATION FUND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of Heritage Capital Appreciation is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, Herbert E. Ehlers and David G. Shell sound as if they
would rather be venture capitalists than money managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a capitalist society like America, wealth is created
through long-term ownership of growing businesses,'' said Ehlers,
co-lead portfolio manager with Shell of the $287.1 million Heritage
Capital Appreciation fund in Tampa, Fla. ``We talk about buying
businesses, not shares of stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Their approach has produced a record that _ although it may pale
next to a venture capitalist's payoff _ is more than respectable.
The fund has returned 36.4 percent a year, on average, for the
three years through Dec. 10, compared with 20.7 percent for its
peer group of large blend funds and 25.7 percent for the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago
financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Ehlers, 60, and Shell, 37, work with five other portfolio
managers in running more than $15 billion for Goldman Sachs Asset
Management. The other investments include separate accounts and
three other mutual funds. The largest fund is the $3.10 billion
Goldman Sachs Capital Growth, which uses the same strategy as
Heritage but is more diversified and has a shorter record. (Goldman
bought Ehler's firm, Liberty Investment Management, in 1997.)
</P>
<P>
   When picking stocks, generally of high-quality American growth
companies with market capitalizations of more than $1 billion, the
managers consider myriad factors, focusing on three:
</P>
<P>
   _ Strong business franchises. Shell said they looked for
companies with strong brand names or patented products, or for
businesses that make key components for other companies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Management strength. Specifically, they examine how top
executives allocate a company's capital. ``It's important that cash
be deployed wisely to continue growing the business,'' Shell said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Long-term growth prospects. The managers ignore companies'
earnings in favor of cash flow, for which they like to see growth
of 12 percent to 15 percent a year. They also look for a similar
growth rate in what they call a company's intrinsic worth _ ``what
a rational and knowledgeable business operator would pay to own the
business,'' Shell said.
</P>
<P>
   They tend to steer clear of slow-growing and cyclical companies
like utilities, commodity chemical and transportation concerns.
Some keys to long-term growth, Ehlers said, are long product life
cycles, strong competitive advantages and favorable demographics.
</P>
<P>
   Ehlers and Shell are also fond of companies with pricing power
over their goods or services. But the managers won't pay too much
for their stocks: They look to buy those that trade at a discount
of at least 20 percent to intrinsic worth.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, they see value among companies in the media business.
</P>
<P>
   They recently added to their position in Liberty Media, a
tracking stock of AT&AMP;T. Liberty owns stakes in Sprint PCS, Time
Warner, Discovery Communications, and USA Networks, among other
cable programming and communications stocks. Shell said Liberty
management allocated its capital particularly well.
</P>
<P>
   The fund managers originally bought shares in 1993 at $3 each.
Earnings are not particularly meaningful in the programming
business, but the value of the business is growing at an annual
rate of 20 percent to 30 percent, Shell said. The stock closed on
Friday at $49.4375, and he estimates that it intrinsic worth is
between $55 and $60.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite is CBS, which is expected to complete its
merger with Viacom in the first half of next year. CBS, of course,
has a strong brand, and Ehlers called its chairman, Mel Karmazin,
``the best leader in the broadcast business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehlers said radio in particular was benefiting from the growth
of the Internet, because Internet companies use radio advertising
to build their brand names. And CBS's cash flow is growing at more
than 20 percent a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The managers began buying CBS shares in early 1998 at $30; the
stock closed on Friday at $59.8125. Ehlers put the company's
intrinsic net worth at $65 to $70 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The managers also like Time Warner, whose media reach includes
the Warner Brothers studio, cable networks like CNN and HBO and
magazines ranging from Time to InStyle to Mutual Funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The backbone for its strong business franchise,'' Ehlers said,
``is its library of entertainment copyrights, which is the largest
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has substantial recurring revenue streams from its
cable and magazine businesses and generates reasonable amounts of
free cash flow, he said. Demographics are in the company's favor,
too: The aging population has more time for entertainment-related
activities, Ehlers said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock has experienced weakness this year. Last
month, Jessica Reif Cohen, a Merrill Lynch analyst, published a
report expressing concern about Time Warner's music business. The
stock, which closed on Friday at $66.125, is down 16 percent from
its high of $78.625 in April.
</P>
<P>
   That does not faze the two managers. ``We believe the underlying
fundamentals of the company are very strong and we're still very
bullish,'' Shell said.
</P>
<P>
   They first bought the stock in 1990 at about $12; Ehlers puts
the intrinsic worth at $100 a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 2045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2280 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-DELL-COMPUTERS     12-17 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DELL-COMPUTERS-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOWER GROWTH AT DELL HAS LEFT A SOUR TASTE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of stock chart is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Dell Computer a value stock for the new economy? Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, many people on Wall Street called Dell a niche
player, one whose growth would sputter once it saturated the base
of customers who want to buy a personal computer through a
toll-free phone number.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Dell sales running at $27 billion a year,
investors are not calling it that anymore. But there is still much
doubt about the sustainability of Dell's growth, which is one
reason that its stock has languished all year.
</P>
<P>
   Dell shares, a mainstay of the 1990s bull market, took a
pounding in February, when some analysts predicted that the
company's revenue growth would slow. And it turned out the rate had
declined, to 38 percent for the quarter ending Jan. 31, from 56
percent, on average, over the previous two years. It has since
recovered a bit, to 41 percent in the most recent quarter, ended
Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The message to investors, however, was clear: No one should
expect a company of Dell's size to keep growing at 50 percent
indefinitely. And shareholders have not forgiven the slip. Dell
shares, now at $45.5625, are 17 percent below their 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
   Even with that decline, it is difficult to find anybody who
questions Dell's strategy or faults its execution. Many people
believe that the company could be the world's largest maker of PCs
within the next year or two, as it continues to take market share
away from Compaq Computer and IBM. It has been the No. 1 supplier
of PCs in the United States for the last two quarters. And with the
start this month of WebPC, a PC geared to the retail consumer, Dell
is finally attacking the home market.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's direct-sales model is well-known: The company builds each
PC to order and sells it directly to consumers, by telephone, the
Web or, for big corporate customers, through a field sales force.
There is little money tied up in inventory and no dealer markups,
allowing it to undercut rivals on price.
</P>
<P>
   By keeping the barest of component inventories itself, Dell
minimizes working capital and maximizes return on that capital. It
has a negative cash conversion cycle, meaning that it is paid for
finished goods before it pays suppliers for parts.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, Compaq and Hewlett-Packard have taken steps to mimic Dell's
business model and have made some headway at trimming inventories
and costs. But they cannot duplicate Dell's model without cutting
off their dealers, which they fear to do.
</P>
<P>
   All of this leads some investors to say that Dell stock simply
doesn't deserve the punishment it has suffered. ``We're starting to
believe that the assumptions people have made about revenue growth
slowing down could be wrong,'' said Randy Befumo, an analyst with
the Legg Mason Value Trust, a $14 billion mutual fund and a
longtime Dell shareholder. ``It's not that they increase revenue
growth, because the law of large numbers does eventually apply, but
most likely they can sustain the current growth rate much longer
than people expect.'' About 4.6 percent of the fund is invested in
Dell shares.
</P>
<P>
   Befumo said that he believed the growth of the Internet would
spur sales of servers and other PC-related products, and that Dell
would have many chances to gain market share in these categories
and overseas. ``The market will consolidate around the most
efficient player, and that's Dell,'' he said. ``There's no reason
Dell can't have 50 percent market share.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell has a 15 percent share in the United States and 7 percent
overseas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Wolf, an analyst with Warburg Dillon Read, said Dell
shares had underperformed for reasons divorced from fundamentals.
``Momentum investors pulled out of the name,'' he said, referring
to Dell stock. ``They were very big in the name prior to the
February announcement, but once that momentum is broken for any
reason, they jump ship. The reality is, except for a little blip in
the October quarter due to memory pricing, which I ignore, they
have delivered every quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said that Dell's competitive advantage over IBM and Compaq
appeared to be widening, and that the company was exploiting the
Internet more effectively than other PC makers, not only to sell
its products but also to maintain relationships with customers. He
noted that Dell's price-to-earnings multiple for next year was
under 45, just slightly above its earnings growth rate of about 40
percent, while many technology stocks trade for two or three times
growth.
</P>
<P>
   If Dell's stock-price appreciation matched his expected earnings
growth rate of 40 percent in 2000, shares would hit $63.7875 in the
next 12 months. ``Last week, I lifted it to my No. 1 pick for
2000,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   It is still possible, however, to admire Dell's model but not
the stock. Andrew Neff of Bear Stearns rates Dell ``attractive,'' a
level below ``buy.'' ``Dell uses the Internet, but they don't run
the Internet the way Sun does,'' Neff said, referring to Sun
Microsystems. ``Sun sells to the core of the Internet. There's a
higher focus on companies that own technology, whereas Dell's
competitive advantage has a lot to do with supply chain leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Kunstler at J.P. Morgan is also waiting for a reason to
lift his rating on Dell from ``market perform.'' He said Dell had
lifted expectations by describing the slowdown for the January
quarter as a one-time event, though it has since become apparent
that it was not. ``The opportunity for them to really exceed
numbers on revenues or earnings is not what it used to be,'' he
said. ``It's not that the business model has become deficient. It
has not. But there's little perceived potential for upside
surprises.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
