<HEADLINE>
TORRENTIAL RAINS LEAVE MORE THAN 100 DEAD AND TENS OF THOUSANDS
HOMELESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ More than 130 people have been killed and
hundreds are missing and presumed dead after three days of
torrential rains that caused mudslides and flooding here and
elsewhere along the Caribbean coast.
</P>
<P>
   The toll is expected to rise as emergency teams begin to shift
from removing stranded survivors to recovering corpses buried under
avalanches of mud. Some 120,000 people have moved from their homes
to makeshift shelters operated by the military and civil defense
groups, and an additional 36,000 are estimated homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst natural catastrophe to hit Venezuela in 50
years,'' President Hugo Chavez said in a somber television address
to the nation on Thursday night. Addressing reporters Friday,
Chavez, a former army colonel who has been visiting disaster zones
dressed in military fatigues, said that although it was too early
to fear that ``thousands are dead, and let's hope it does not come
to that,'' the destruction had been extensive.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez has declared a state of emergency here in the capital and
in nine northern states. In those hard-hit areas, many towns and
neighborhoods remained without electricity, telephone service and
drinking water Friday, and some were being inundated by the rivers
of mud and rock that have come crashing down mountainsides.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster is attributed to La Nina, the meteorological
phenomenon that has caused unusually rainy and cool weather
throughout South America in recent months, particularly in the
Andean region. A series of rain storms and floods in neighboring
Colombia has caused even more widespread death, damage and
destruction than here, and forecasts are for the siege of bad
weather to continue for several days.
</P>
<P>
   The most seriously damaged areas are precarious hillside
settlements known as ranchos, where thousands of shacks have been
destroyed and thousands of families uprooted. Since Wednesday, when
Venezuelans went to the polls to approve a new constitution favored
by Chavez, dramatic images of poor, shocked and tearful slum
dwellers hauling what remained of their personal belongings down to
flat land have dominated television coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But numerous affluent neighborhoods, luxury apartment buildings
and even parts of the downtown area of the capital have also been
severely affected, with streets blocked by garbage and tree limbs
and overturned cars that have been swept away by flash floods.
Torrents of mud and sewage flowed into three subway stations in the
Parque Central area, and the city closed its extensive subway
system.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster has also led to the suspension of all air service
at the main international and national airports, including American
and Continental Airline flights between Caracas and Miami, New York
and Houston. With the road between Caracas and Simon Bolivar
International Airport in La Guaira severed at several points, an
estimated 3,000 passengers and airline employees have been stranded
at the main terminal, some since Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the collapse of other transportation links as well,
the government has urged people to remain at home and not to try to
go to work, even though many workers were due to have been paid at
midmonth. As a result, most businesses, stores, banks and
government offices closed Friday for the third day in a row,
leaving many families short of money, food and water.
</P>
<P>
   In some neighborhoods, shuttered or damaged stores were looted
by residents who said they had no provisions. The police and the
military were quickly dispatched to restore order. At the port of
La Guaira, on the other side of a mountain range from the capital,
desperate survivors swarmed over cargo containers of food and other
supplies that had broken open after having been tossed about by the
surging waters.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from that area, a favorite of Caraquenos and foreign
tourists because of its beautiful beaches, Defense Minister Gen.
Raul Salazar predicted that it would take ``between six and seven
years to return the zone to its previous condition.'' Government
officials and insurance executives predicted that damage to public
works and private property would eventually amount to more than $1
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
