<HEADER>
A2285 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-ACCOUNTING-SETTLE-(TR     12-17 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTING-SETTLE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTING FIRM AGREES TO PAY $335 MILLION IN CENDANT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young agreed Friday to pay $335 million to settle
charges that it failed in its responsibilities when it certified
financial statements that fraudulently inflated the earnings of
Cendant Corp., which operates Ramada Inn hotels and Avis Car rental
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was by far the largest ever by an accounting firm
accused of improper practices by shareholders, although Ernst &AMP;
Young paid more than $400 million in 1992 in penalties and fines to
settle the claims of federal agencies in connection with the
savings and loan crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Ernst &AMP; Young said in a statement that it had been
duped itself in the Cendant case and had done nothing wrong,
accounting experts said it was a sad day for the profession and
that perhaps new procedures were needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The auditors are supposed to be smart enough that they don't
get duped,'' said Howard Schilit, the president of the Center for
Financial Research and Analysis, an accounting watchdog
organization in Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the auditors of this particular company are completely
exonerated,'' he added, ``you have to look at the auditing
procedures in general and say there is something very wrong with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts said that Ernst &AMP; Young's failure to detect the
fraud may have been a consequence of cost-cutting which has led big
accounting companies to rely more heavily on younger, less
experienced auditors. Ernst &AMP; Young is the world's third-largest
accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``To maintain the profit margin, they send in young,
inexperienced people to do a lot of the work,'' said Arthur Bowman,
the editor of Bowman's Accounting Report, an independent monthly
newsletter. ``And then they rely on their experienced staff to
review the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young said the settlement was not ``an admission of any
wrongdoing,'' adding: ``It is simply a recognition that in the
litigious environment in which we operate today settlements are an
unfortunate reality and sometimes the only realistic option.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the American Institute of Certified Public
Accountants, which sets auditing standards, said they had begun
working on tightened procedures for detecting fraud before the
Cendant case became public, and had put new guidelines into effect
in 1998. At present, they said, several academic teams are
evaluating the effectiveness of the anti-fraud measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to be in front of the curve and not to react to
any given case,'' said Arleen Thomas, the vice president at the
institute in charge of professional standards and services.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, the shareholders, led by the pension funds of
New York state, New York City and California, reached a $2.8
billion settlement with Cendant in the same fraud. The shareholders
said that the fraud took place over three years at CUC
International, an online telephone and shopping services company,
which combined with HFS Inc. in late 1997 to form Cendant Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant's share price rose from 22 5/8 to 24 3/8 at 4 p.m.
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young's costs could rise even higher as the result of a
suit by Cendant accusing the auditors of malpractice and breach of
contract. But Ernst &AMP; Young has countersued, saying that ``both CUC
management and subsequently Cendant management'' provided the
accountants with ``information they knew was false.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the U.S. attorney's office in Newark, N.J., is
conducting a criminal investigation into the case, which includes
allegations that executives no longer with Cendant sold shares
before the accounting fraud was publicly disclosed. The Securities
and Exchange Commission is also investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young said it had ``substantial insurance coverage''
that would limit the personal strain on the firm's more than 6,000
partners, including about 2,300 in the United States. The firm
would not discuss its insurance coverage further.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   An insurance broker who has worked out such professional
liability coverage with major corporations for more than 20 years,
said that Ernst &AMP; Young might recover as much as 75 percent of the
settlement claims from perhaps a dozen or more insurers sharing the
policy. Other insurers said it was likely that the companies
providing the insurance would investigate to make sure that the
fraud had not resulted from intentional or criminal acts by the
accountants.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On April 16, 1998, less than four months after its formation in
the merger, Cendant announced that accounting irregularities had
been discovered in CUC units, jolting the market and reducing
Cendant's overall value by $14.4 billion, as shares plunged to $19
from $35. In August, Cendant, with headquarters in Parsippany,
N.J., reported that more than $640 million in profits reported over
the previous three years had been fictional. The inflated profits
helped drive up the share price of CUC International, making the
company more attractive to potential acquirers and benefiting
shareholders, including company executives.
</P>
<P>
   In suits that were consolidated in U.S. District Court in
Newark, the pension funds said that in certifying three annual
reports, seven quarterly reports and as many as twenty federal
registration statements, Ernst &AMP; Young ``knowingly or recklessly
misrepresented'' that its audits of CUC International were
conducted according to proper auditing standards. The pension funds
also contended that Ernst &AMP; Young failed to review quarterly
reporting packages of major CUC International subsidiaries, failed
to require sufficient backup documentation for substantial merger
reserves, and failed to review CUC International's general ledgers
and journal entry adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernst &AMP; Young failed to perform their watchdog function and
Cendant shareholders paid the price,'' said H. Carl McCall, the New
York state comptroller and the sole trustee of the New York State
Common Retirement Fund. The fund lost $26.5 million when Cendant's
share price plumeted, said Theresa Bourgeois, a spokesman for
McCall, adding that the New York City pension fund lost $35.9
million and the California Public Employees Retirement System lost
$26.9 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McCall's office and several accounting experts said that in the
highest previous settlement of a class-action suit by shareholders
against an accounting firm, Arthur Young, a predecessor of Ernst &AMP;
Young, agreed to pay $63 million to shareholders of Lincoln Savings
&AMP; Loan in 1992, as part of a settlement of $270 million. Another
accounting firm, Arthur Andersen, paid $22.85 million in the same
case, McCall's office said. Shareholders charged that they were led
to believe that they had put their money in government-insured
savings investments, which turned out to be securities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Arthur Young merged with Ernst &AMP; Whinney to form Ernst
&AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman, who maintains an accounting industry database, said that
two years after Ernst &AMP; Young paid record federal fines and
penalities in 1992, another firm, Deloite &AMP; Touche, paid $312
million in fines and penalties to settle similar federal claims
arising from the savings and loan crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
