<HEADER>
A2286 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-GEMSTONES-$ADV19-     12-17 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-GEMSTONES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMOND BUYERS WONDER: IS IT REAL OR TREATED? AND DOES IT MATTER?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BARBARA WHITAKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While nearly all colored gemstones are heated or otherwise
treated to improve their color, diamonds have long been sold in
their pure state, enhanced only by the cutter's art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diamond more or less maintained a unique sanctity for
centuries,'' said William E. Boyajian, president of the Gemological
Institute of America, an industry educational and research group.
</P>
<P>
   But no longer. These days, a diamond may have been irradiated to
improve its color or drilled with a laser to remove flaws. And in
March, General Electric announced a process, virtually impossible
to detect, that applies high temperature and pressure to make
diamonds whiter. Among the test markets is Borsheim's Fine Jewelry
and Gifts in Omaha, owned by Warren E. Buffett's Berkshire
Hathaway.
</P>
<P>
   Such new technologies can make shopping for diamond jewelry even
more challenging. Experts advise buyers to demand a guarantee that
a stone has not been altered or a written explanation if it has.
Treated diamonds are usually worth less than diamonds that come by
their good looks naturally, but more than diamonds that are
seriously flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Several major retailers _ including Fortunoff, Tiffany and the
chains owned by the Zale Corp. _ said they did not sell altered
diamonds. Some, however, have provided more prominent disclosures
in recent years about when other gems have been treated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all colored gems on the retail market go through some
treatments, experts say. But, they add, an untreated natural
gemstone would most likely be worth more. Even at those jewelers
that have full disclosure policies, there is no guarantee that the
disclosure is made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because a retailer has trained their people doesn't mean
their people are communicating it at the counter,'' said Antoinette
L. Matlins, the author of several consumer guides including
``Jewelry and Gems: The Buyer's Guide'' (Gemstone Press, 1998).
``Nor does it mean they understood it to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Zale, which operates more than 1,300 stores under the names
Zales, Gordon's and Bailey, Banks &AMP; Biddle, says it began
disclosing colored gem treatments in its catalogs about two years
ago. Susan Lanigan, general counsel for Zale, said the company
trained its employees to discuss these treatments and printed
disclosures on receipts. But she said employees might not always
inform consumers directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to tell you that every sales associate does it,'' she
said, ``but I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission offers limited protections. Its
rules generally require that treated gemstones be identified when
the treatment is not permanent or if the gem requires special care,
said Laura J. DeMartino, a staff lawyer. Industry groups have asked
the FTC to require that laser drilling of diamonds or any other
treatment that affects a gem's value be disclosed. The commission
is expected to respond early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Even an expert might not be able to distinguish a GE diamond.
``The amazing thing about this treatment is that it's not
detectable by the major laboratories,'' said Martin Rapaport, a
diamond broker and publisher of Rapaport Diamond Report, a monthly
magazine that covers the gem industry.
</P>
<P>
   GE and its partner, Lazare Kaplan, a major diamond distributor,
say they make sure that stones are properly marked, described and
sold. They are engraved with a minute identification mark visible
with a jeweler's loupe. They are being test-marketed as Monarch
diamonds _ alluding to the butterfly's metamorphosis _ in only five
stores, where merchants are instructed to describe and document
their enhancement.
</P>
<P>
   Borsheim's has about 30 for sale, as loose diamonds. The store
also sells diamonds that have been drilled with lasers or whose
fractures, or minute cracks, have been filled with diamond-like
substances.
</P>
<P>
   Susan M. Jacques, Borsheim's chief executive and a member of the
Gemological Institute of America board, said store employees tell
customers how the diamonds have been treated, provide explanatory
brochures and give certificates describing the stones' quality and
treatments when they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   GE says its diamonds, which it expects to account for $30
million of the nation's $10 billion diamond wholesale market next
year, sell in a range from 15 percent less than a similar,
unaltered diamond to just as much.
</P>
<P>
   Elly Rosen, who runs Appraisal Information Services in Brooklyn,
N.Y., estimated that a diamond drilled with lasers is worth 10
percent to 20 percent less than an unaltered diamond of similar
appearance. A diamond whose fractures have been filled is worth 25
percent to 30 percent less, he said. Fillings have to be disclosed,
because they are not permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers themselves might not even know which of their diamonds
or colored gems have been treated, or how. ``The biggest problems
are those merchants _ I'm not even going to refer to them as
jewelers _ who don't know all this stuff and don't care,'' Rosen
said. ``They might as well be selling bananas.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Matlins suggested that consumers protect themselves by
asking about the factors that affect the quality and value of any
gem: color, cut, clarity and weight. They should also ask
specifically if the stone has been treated in any way. If the
answer is no, it should be stated in writing on the invoice. If the
answer is yes, the procedures should be spelled out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to diamonds, she said, a shopper should ask
specifically about laser drilling, fracture filling and GE's new
process.
</P>
<P>
   To verify that the gem and the jeweler's description match, a
buyer should take the purchase and the invoice to an independent
appraiser certified by groups like the American Society of
Appraisers, the American Gem Society or the Accredited Gemologists
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the FTC guidelines the onus is on the consumer,'' Ms.
Matlins said. ``The bottom line is that the consumer today has to
know more than the salesperson to protect themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
