<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END-OF-DAY SELLOFF ENDS DOW'S FLIRTATION WITH NEW HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to correct spelling to 'Qualcomm' sted `Qualcom' in 10th
graf.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dow Jones industrial average, powered by a jump
in General Electric after it announced a 3-for-1 stock split,
flirted with a new high Friday but then gave up the gains in a
selloff at the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon, the Dow was up 138 points to 11,383,
surpassing its record close of 11,326.04 on Aug. 25. But the
average plummeted at the end of the day and wound up inching only
12.54 points higher, to 11,257.43.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq index, which was up as much as 81
points at Friday's opening, also slumped in the afternoon. But it
still rose 38 points, or 1.02 percent, to 3,753.06, its 10th new
high since Thanksgiving. The Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stock
rose 2.25 points, to 1,421.03, just 12.27 points from the record of
1,433.30 it reached on Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   There was no news to trigger the selloff late Friday. Analysts
said they did not think the selling was a result of the expiration
of the futures contracts and options on stock indexes and the
options on individual stocks, which is known as triple witching.
That did contribute, however, to a day of record trading volume on
the New York Stock Exchange as 1.35 billion shares changed hands.
For the month so far, trading volume is averaging more than 1
billion shares a day.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Galvin, the chief investment officer at Donaldson, Lufkin
&AMP; Jenrette, said the selloff could reflect the ``wrestling match''
going on between investors who have made huge gains this year and
are selling now to protect them, and the buying from money managers
who are trying to dress up their portfolios by buying the
better-performing stocks of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The performance came as interest rates surged to their highest
level in more than two years. For the week, the Dow and the S&AMP;P
rose less than a third of a percentage point, while the Nasdaq
leapt 3.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Because the economy continues to grow briskly despite three rate
increases by the Federal Reserve this year, more and more analysts
are now predicting that the Federal Reserve will raise its
short-term interest rate target a quarter of a percentage point in
February and another quarter of a point before summer.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the fact that the Nasdaq set its 54th record of the
year and the Dow and the S&AMP;P are near records, the stock market's
performance _ outside of technology stocks _ is still sluggish and
many stocks have been left out.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Dow first crossed 11,000 on May 7, it has risen only 2
percent, which means that almost all of its 22.6 percent gain for
the year came by early May. For the S&AMP;P 500 index, which is more
heavily weighted with tech stocks than the Dow, the rise since May
7 has been 5.7 percent. But still, most of its 15.6 percent gain
for the year came by May.
</P>
<P>
   In the same period, the Nasdaq index is up 50 percent, led by
Qualcomm, Oracle, Sun Microsystems, Yahoo and Cisco Systems. For
the year, the index is up 71.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Looked at another way, almost 58 percent of the 500 stocks in
the S&AMP;P 500 index are down 20 percent or more from their 52-week
highs, according to Salomon Smith Barney. Sixty-six percent of the
stocks on the New York Stock Exchange are down 20 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   And this may indicate that the sharp rise in interest rates this
year, which has pushed the yield on the 30-year bond up almost one
and a half percentage points to as high as 6.39 percent, is having
some impact. In this higher rate environment investors are favoring
big-name growth companies and the tech and Internet stocks that
have done so well all year.
</P>
<P>
   In late trading in the bond market Friday, the yield on the
30-year bond slipped a little to 6.37 percent from 6.39 percent on
Thursday. The price, which moves in the opposite direction, rose
5/32, to 96 22/32.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of GE, which also announced a dividend increase, rose 4
1/2, to 151 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Investors expressed little enthusiasm Friday for a possible
merger between drug giants Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn and Monsanto. Reports
surfaced that the two companies were discussing a deal, but that
was not enough to spark a rally in either stock. Shares of Monsanto
increased a meager 3.4 percent, or $1.375, to close at $41.75.
Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn's stock tumbled 6.3 percent, or $3, to close at
$50.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging by what happened Friday, Monsanto is not likely to go
at a premium,'' said Tom Brakel, an analyst with Mehta Partners.
``And if they do this deal, Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn still has to figure
out what to do with Monsanto's agricultural division.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
