<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BIRMINGHAM-MAYOR-NYT &LR;      12-17 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRMINGHAM-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL REBEL IN BIRMINGHAM FINDS HE'S OUT ALTHOUGH IN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ For years, Bernard Kincaid was the wrench in
the political machine that controlled Alabama's largest city, the
outsider who railed at the vast powers of its 20-year mayor,
Richard Arrington, and tried to assemble a bi-racial coalition of
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Then last month, the city's voters _ wearied by five terms of
one-man rule and angry at fiscal carelessness that slopped over
into scandal _ elected Kincaid as mayor. He defeated Arrington's
handpicked successor.
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid, who had been a City Council member for two years,
demanded resignations, ordered audits and promised a new day in
Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   It did not take long, however, for Kincaid to become a victim of
the same fears and hostilities that propelled him into office, a
legacy of the divisive tenure of his predecessor and the city's
polarized racial history.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of his victory, he began clashing with a City
Council that was as suspicious of his intentions as he had been of
Arrington's. Last week, in a vote similar to actions he had long
advocated, Kincaid was stripped of much of his power by a unanimous
City Council, which forbid him to execute contracts larger than
$10,000 without the Council's approval.
</P>
<P>
   Political rebellion often seems to come at a price in the cities
of the Deep South, where clouds of racial suspicion hover over so
many voting booths. When Arrington swept away years of often
oppressive all-white rule to become the city's first black mayor in
1979, he and his allies felt little need to reach out to the white
residents who began deserting the city by the tens of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid is also black, but his challenge to that coalition has
earned him the lasting bitterness of most Council members. Even his
allies want to ensure that no future mayor ever has as much power
as Arrington had.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens when a machine dies,'' said Natalie
Davis, a political scientist at Birmingham Southern College. ``When
all the power is inside the African-American community, you're
going to have black-against-black competition. And now all those
voters who never got contracts, who watched everything from
unethical behavior to outright stealing, are going to turn every
Council meeting into a weekly slugfest.''
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid is fighting back, threatening to sue the Council and
laying plans for a citywide referendum to regain his power to
approve contracts. But he says he is resigned to spending nearly
half of his term in a virtual stalemate with the Council, delaying
his hopes for improving the city's schools and transit system, at
least until the Council members are up for re-election in 2001. He
considers that a small price to pay for dislodging a political
movement that had lost its vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will probably cripple my administration for the next 22
months, but then those individuals on the Council will stand for
election,'' he said in an interview. ``And the public will be left
to judge if they like my brand of leadership or theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid, 54, is a former administrator at the University of
Alabama at Birmingham who earned a doctorate in education
administration and a law degree. A coal miner's son who attended
Miles College just outside Birmingham, he knew and admired
Arrington when the former mayor taught zoology there. He says he
welcomed Arrington's early efforts to integrate the city's work
force and end the tension between the police and black residents.
</P>
<P>
   But like many critics of Arrington, white and black, Kincaid
grew disenchanted with the insularity of the Arrington
administration and the all-black political coalition from which it
drew strength, the Jefferson County Citizens Coalition. There were
constant investigations into cronyism and kickbacks, and two
convictions of mayoral allies on fraud charges. Arrington even
timed his retirement in July to allow William Bell, the Council
president, to serve as interim mayor until the election.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell could not overcome the weight of his patron's many
years in power, despite raising 10 times as much campaign money as
Kincaid's $120,000. In the campaign, a councilman allied with
Kincaid disclosed that the Arrington administration had paid
$891,000 to buy a three-acre parcel from a friend of Arrington in
1994, as the site for a housing project. When the Council approved
the sale in a rubber-stamp action, it had been told the city was
buying 30 acres.
</P>
<P>
   The city eventually sold the land for a $700,000 loss, giving
Kincaid a resonant campaign issue. Associates of Bell and Arrington
were also shown to have been paid millions for promoting a plan to
sell the city's water system, which the voters rejected last year.
On Nov. 2, Kincaid, once the most distant of long shots, defeated
Bell with 51 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably couldn't have won without those things happening,''
Kincaid said. ``It turned out the mayor's plan to install Bell
backfired, because these things came out while he was sitting in
that seat. They just enveloped him like a blooming flower, and all
of a sudden he didn't look so mayoral.''
</P>
<P>
   The rift between the factions only deepened after the election.
Arrington waited three weeks before sending a terse note of
congratulations to his successor. Bell, who has served on the
Council for 20 years, retained his seat, and joined four other
Arrington allies on the nine-member Council to begin limiting the
new mayor's power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony of that simply can't go unmentioned,'' said an
editorial in The Birmingham News, which had endorsed Bell. ``Here
are five people who rubber-stamped everything Mayor Arrington ever
wanted with the gusto of a mad postal clerk, and now they want to
put a leash on Kincaid in the name of accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   The paradox can also be inverted, because Kincaid was one of the
loudest proponents of greater oversight of mayoral contracts when
he sat on the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six weeks ago, he would have led the charge for this,'' said
Dr. Jimmy Blake, a white Council member who supported Kincaid.
``That's because we had a king for mayor all those years. I'm not
the least bit interested in having another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid did not help matters when he hired as a top legal aide a
lawyer who had been disbarred and convicted of forgery. But he
remains convinced that his real enemy is the bitterness of the
city's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that this is the nadir of Arrington's coalition,''
he said. ``But those walls between us were erected pretty heavily
during the two years I was on the Council. Now, I don't know how
they're going to be lowered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
