<SLUG> BC-BOMB-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN STOPPED AT U.S.-CANADA BORDER, SUSPECTED OF TRANSPORTING BOMB
MATERIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Canada)  (Eds.: A 1stLd is scheduled to move by 9:45 p.m. ET) 
(js) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK with TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A man who brought a car with a trunk full of
explosives on a ferry from Canada, and then led customs officials
on a foot chase through the streets of a Washington port town, was
arrested by federal authorities. They said Friday that his target,
his motives and his background remain a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who had more than 150 pounds of bomb-making chemicals
and detonator components in the car, was detained Tuesday just
after driving off a ferry from Victoria, British Columbia, in Port
Angeles, Wash. He had a reservation for a downtown Seattle motel
Tuesday night, and also had reserved tickets to fly Wednesday from
Seattle to New York and to connect from there to a London-bound
flight, federal authorities said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and the CIA are investigating the incident, a government
official said Friday. How and when the man planned to use the
materials in his car are just two of the numerous questions
surrounding the incident. Although, as one government official said
Friday: ``There's nothing mysterious at all about what was in that
car. It was stuff for a bomb, a powerful bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said the man's actions, use of fake
Canadian identification papers and background fueled suspicions
that he could be part of an international terrorist network.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they believe the man is Algerian, is 28 years
old and that his name is Ahmed Ressam. They say he arrived in Los
Angeles on Feb. 7 on a flight from Seoul, South Korea, and that he
was next seen in Vancouver, British Columbia, in October. They said
his passport, which listed his name as Benni Noris and gave his age
as 28, was false. The officials also believe that both of the
Canadian driver's licenses, bearing his picture, that he was
carrying were falsely obtained. One was under the name of Benni
Antoine Noris
</P>
<P>
   The suspect was carrying maps of Washington, Oregon and
California in the car with him, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers federal prosecutors indicated that he would be
charged, under the name of Ahmed Ressam, with illegally
transporting explosive material into the country and making false
statements on his customs forms.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest comes after a recent State Department warning that it
had received ``credible information'' about plans for terrorist
attacks against U.S. citizens around the time of the Jan. 1
millennium celebration. The department's ``worldwide terrorism
warning'' advised Americans to stay away from ``large gatherings
and celebrations'' throughout the world for the rest of this year,
but it did not specify any groups planning attacks or state where
such attacks might occur.
</P>
<P>
   Two federal officials in Washington said Friday that the CIA had
been called in on the case. One of them said the intelligence
service was asked to join the case because of suspicions that the
man may be tied to terrorists.
</P>
</TEXT>
