<SLUG> BC-BOMB-PLOT-POWER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEIZED CHEMICALS POWERFUL ENOUGH TO `TAKE OUT A BUILDING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The urea powder and liquid nitroglycerine seized in a
rental car in Port Angeles, Wash., Tuesday night are powerful
enough to destroy a mid-sized office building, according to a
military explosives expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going definitely to take a building out with this
stuff,'' said the expert, who reviewed the chemical properties of
the material seized by U.S. Customs officials. ``You could
devastate an office building.''
</P>
<P>
   The expert, who agreed to discuss the incident only on grounds
of anonymity, said a bomb made of the seized materials would have
the equivalent blast power of 100 pounds of TNT.
</P>
<P>
   Customs inspectors found 118 pounds of urea powder, about 16
ounces of nitroglycerine in two glass jars, and four small black
boxes containing circuit boards, watches and nine-volt batteries in
the wheel well of a car trying to enter the United States on a
ferry from Victoria, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary tests conducted at the Washington State Patrol
Laboratory in Tacoma confirmed that the material, when combined
with a detonator, would produce ``a large explosive device,''
according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Ressam, 33, was in federal custody Friday night, facing
explosive and immigration charges. He is an Algerian wanted in
Canada who intended to stay in the United States only a day, then
fly to London.
</P>
<P>
   Urea is a fine white powder used to manufacture explosives and
fertilizer. It has similar properties to ammonium nitrate, another
fertilizer ingredient that can easily be made into a high
explosive, the expert said.
</P>
<P>
   The expert expressed relief that the liquid nitroglyerin seized
by border agents was apparently well stabilized, apparently with
sawdust. ``Liquid nitro is pretty nasty _ it's twice as sensitive
as the explosive in a blasting cap,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The liquid nitroglycerine _ a powerful explosive in its own
right _ would normally be used for the initial detonation that
would in turn trigger the detonation of the urea powder, the expert
said. Detonating the nitroglycerine would merely require a small
blasting cap fired by a battery-driven igniter, the expert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five pounds of that stuff could take a car apart,'' the expert
said of the mixture.
</P>
<P>
   The terrorist bomb that blew up under the New York World Trade
Center on Feb. 26, 1993 _ killing six people and injuring more than
1,000 _ was made with 1,200 pounds of urea nitrate combined with
fuel oil.
</P>
<P>
   Bombs used to destroy two U.S. embassies in East Africa last
year were made of ammonium nitrate common to fertilizers, as was
the 1995 bomb that blew up the federal building in Oklahoma City.,
Okla., killing 168.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 2115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
