<SLUG> BC-NY-TOBACCO-TAX- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK STATE RAISING CIGARETTE TAX 55 TO FINANCE HEALTH CARE FOR
POOR
</HEADLINE>
 ART- 830(2TAKES)-NYT   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki and legislative leaders from
both major parties agreed Friday to raise the state's cigarette tax
by 55 cents a pack in an ambitious effort to provide health care
coverage for as many as one million uninsured New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and leaders of the Legislature also decided to renew a
financial program that pays hospitals about 1.3 billion a year to
train new doctors and treat poor people who show up in emergency
rooms with no way of paying their medical bills. The program had
been set to expire at the end of the year, threatening the state's
health care system with financial uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to expand coverage for the uninsured is expected to
cost the state about $750 million over the next 3 1-2 years. It
would be financed with revenue from the higher cigarette tax, as
well as a share of the $450 million a year that the state is to
receive from the settlement of the national lawsuit against tobacco
companies. The plan would also be paid for with about $300 million
in new federal health care funds.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement represents one of the most ambitious investments
in health care by the state in recent memory. It also concludes a
series of tense talks between Pataki, a Republican, and the
Democratic speaker of the Assembly, Sheldon Silver, over how to
finance the state's multibillion-dollar health care industry and
provide coverage for the growing number of medically uninsured New
Yorkers, who now number more than 3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would bring New York's tobacco tax to $1.11 a pack, the
highest of any state, and represents the first significant defeat
here for the tobacco industry since 1993. The industry has long
been one of the most powerful interest groups in state politics,
but recent disclosures about its extravagant spending on gifts for
lawmakers and other lobbying expenditures have weakened its
position. Some lawmakers acknowledge that they hope to use the
higher tax to rebuff charges that they are too close to the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations were largely orchestrated by Dennis Rivera, the
influential head of 1199, the National Health and Human Service
Employees Union, which represents 150,000 health care workers in
the state. Rivera had threatened to use his group's political clout
and financial resources to mount a fierce media campaign against
Pataki and his Republican allies in the Legislature if they moved
to reduce state financing for hospitals or refused to expand
medical coverage for the uninsured. He enlisted the support of not
only Democrats but Republicans as well, primarily Joseph Bruno, the
State Senate majority leader. Bruno shared the governor's concerns
over the state's rising health care costs, but also did not want to
pick a fight with labor unions over the issue. with an important
election year approaching.
</P>
<P>
   Before the deal was reached, the negotiations had stalled over
the question of how to structure the new insurance program.
Democrats had proposed modeling it after the Medicaid program, with
the state providing coverage directly to the uninsured using
federal and state funds. But Pataki was concerned that such an
approach would encourage employers to stop offering their workers
medical insurance and instead let the state and federal governments
provide it. He wanted to offer financial incentives for private
employers to expand coverage for workers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the two sides agreed on a compromise that attempts
to accomplish both of their goals over the next 3 1-2years. The
agreement calls for providing free insurance to families earning up
to 150 percent of the federal poverty line _ meaning that a family
of four with an annual income of $25,000 or less could receive
coverage without paying premiums. The program would cost nearly
$600 million in state and federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for providing $219 million in state subsidies to
small businesses to help them provide medical coverage to their
employees. The money would be given to businesses with up to 50
employees. The agreement also sets aside $150 million to help
individuals buy their own medical coverage from private insurance
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he expected as many as 500,000 uninsured New Yorkers
to apply for medical coverage over the next 3 1-2 years as a result
of the new health care initiative. ``I am confident that with this
program, we are going to have the best health care in the country,
possibly the world,'' the governor said during an afternoon news
conference at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also includes a major concession to Pataki: it keeps a
lid on the state's fast-growing Medicaid costs. Pataki has proposed
cuts in Medicaid spending in the past, only to be rebuffed by his
Democratic rivals nearly every year. But the deal announced Friday
would reauthorize a series of Medicaid cuts that are due to expire
on April 1. Those cuts total $1 billion a year in federal, state
and local financing for the Medicaid program, and the deal would
extend them for three years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
