<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: END OF AN ERA IN SOUTH BEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an attempt to put the outgoing century in perspective, we
have been bombarded by lists and rankings: the most powerful, the
most influential, the best. But the moment that provides the
greatest symmetry of this sports century unfolded Friday in South
Bend, Ind., when the NC AA placed Notre Dame on probation for two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame on probation. Who would have guessed? Certainly not
Grantland Rice, the legendary sportswriter of the first half of
this century. Rice's account of the 1924 Notre Dame-Army game
contains one of the classic leads in sports journalism: ``Outlined
against a blue-gray October sky, the Four Horsemen rode again. In
dramatic lore they are known as Famine, Pestilence, Destruction and
Death. These are only aliases. Their real names are Stuhldreher,
Miller, Crowley and Layden.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus Notre Dame football, now with its Four Horsemen, went from
popular to legendary. Of all the college sports teams in the 20th
century, Notre Dame became the most significant; the Fighting Irish
invented big-time college sports. Now the century ends with them on
probation.
</P>
<P>
   The penalties themselves were less than a slap on the wrist. The
sanctions will not bar Notre Dame from bowl games and will not
affect the school's exclusive television contract with NBC. The
program loses one scholarship _ out of 85 _ for each year of
probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notre Dame has all these walk-ons who are offered athletic
scholarships at other schools,'' said Murray Sperber, a professor
of English and American Studies at Indiana University. ``They
watched the movie `Rudy' one too many times and they hope to make
the Notre Dame roster, so these sanctions are not going to hurt
them remotely. I think they're embarrassed by the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperber has written three books about intercollegiate athletics.
In 1990 he published ``College Sports Inc.: The Athletic Department
vs. the University'' (Henry Holt). Five years later he wrote
``Shake Down the Thunder: The Creation of Notre Dame Football''
(Henry Holt, 1995).
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me understand them more,'' he said. ``People on the
outside have lots of myths about Notre Dame. A lot of people think
it's this huge school because they play Michigan, but its a very
small school. They think of the people there as being very
arrogant, whereas I found them to be very polite and professional.
I came to appreciate them in a professional sense, and I became
friendly with one or two people there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never be a Notre Dame fan,' he added. ``I went to Purdue,
after all. But it made me understand them more. I'll say this:
Athletes there get a better education than at a lot of other
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still believe somehow in the student-athletes thing, and
I think they are trying harder to do it and as a result they are
not able to compete in recruiting with Florida State.''
</P>
<P>
   Sperber, who at his core is a cynic, has nonetheless been
seduced by the aura and legend of Notre Dame football and has
failed to distinguish the university from the football program. In
a football sense, how different is Notre Dame from Florida State?
</P>
<P>
   The story of Notre Dame football _ indeed, of all the great
college football programs _ is largely the story of image and
imagery _ and stones left unturned.
</P>
<P>
   The Notre Dame violations stem from the activity of a a
bookkeeper turned booster who embezzled more than $1.2 million from
a former employer and used some of the money to lavish gifts and
trips on at least a dozen Notre Dame players.
</P>
<P>
   The bookkeeper, Kimberly Dunbar, was convicted of embezzlement
in September 1998 and was sentenced to four years in prison. She
was released in October after serving one year.
</P>
<P>
   Sperber conceded, ``You could say the Notre Dame coaches could
have been more into their players' lives.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials reacted as much to the tarnish caused by the
event as they did to the actual event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a good day for Notre Dame,'' the Rev. Edward
Malloy, the school's president, said. ``We are embarrassed by these
incidents, troubled that they occurred and have taken action to
avoid such problems in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   There probably won't be another invention like Notre Dame
football in the future, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot imagine any college team in the 21st century
representing what the Notre Dame Fighting Irish did in this
century,'' Sperber said.
</P>
<P>
   Unless another Grantland Rice dreams one up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
