<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE WORRIES THAT U.S. MAY BECOME A BULLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Prime Minister Lionel Jospin of France, on a visit to
Tokyo, said Friday that the United States should be ``discreet'' in
exercising its global power.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin, a Socialist, also made veiled criticisms of the United
States in a speech in Tokyo on Thursday that were more pointed than
remarks made by President Jacques Chirac, a Gaullist conservative,
in an interview this week.
</P>
<P>
   Both leaders chided Congress for sharply cutting the $370
million the Clinton administration had asked for to ease the debts
of 41 poor countries, mostly in Africa, as President Clinton and
other leaders agreed at a summit meeting in Germany this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resistance of the American Congress on this point is
worrisome,'' Jospin told his audience in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac said: ``Congress has recently made the participation of
the World Bank more difficult. It's hard to tell why. It's not a
very large amount of money, and we can settle it without the World
Bank, or more precisely the World Bank will find the funds
elsewhere. So why did Congress do this?''
</P>
<P>
   Jospin also seemed to blame U.S. negotiators for the collapse of
the opening of a new round of world trade talks in Seattle early
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain countries that chose to give priority to their
domestic policy goals came with an intransigent attitude and
refused to enter into real negotiations,'' he said. ``That should
reinforce our determination to counter any temptation to return to
unilateralism.''
</P>
<P>
   In French political discourse, ``unilateralism'' is a uniquely
American sin.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin said France, which will hold the rotating presidency of
the European Union in the second half of next year, wanted to hold
a high-level meeting of member countries in the World Trade
Organization to draw lessons from Seattle and make it ``more
effective, more open and more democratic.''
</P>
<P>
   He also took a dig at the United States for failing to pay all
its dues to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``All member states should fulfill their financial
obligations,'' he said. ``France and Japan do that completely and
unconditionally. A responsible attitude by all contributor nations
would encourage the necessary reforms of the organization,
including the Security Council.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 2130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
