<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2308 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-HEDGEFUNDS-ART-$ADV19     12-17 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUNDS-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELSEWHERE, 1999 IS SHAPING UP AS A BANNER YEAR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: See related article: TIGER-HEDGEFUNDS)  
(ART ADV: Graphic of how hedge funds fared this year is being sent
to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tiger Management's woes notwithstanding, many hedge funds have
been posting their highest returns in years, buoyed by soaring
international markets and what some managers say may be the best
environment for stock-picking since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Top-performing funds include those specializing in technology
stocks, the Pacific Rim, Latin America and emerging markets in
general. Over all, an index of hedge funds tracked by Hennessee
Hedge Fund Advisory has gained 23.17 percent this year through
November, putting it on a pace to beat the S&AMP;P 500 _ which rose
14.3 percent through November _ by the widest margin in six years.
</P>
<P>
   The results are a stunning reversal from last year, when many
hedge funds _ battered by the Russian debt default, bad bets on the
Japanese yen and fallout from the near-collapse of Long-Term
Capital Management _ trailed the S&AMP;P by wide margins.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie McCabe, chief executive of Blackstone Alternative Asset
Management, which oversees $1.5 billion in hedge-fund assets, said
some of the managers with the best performance are those investing
in European stocks, or selling them short.
</P>
<P>
   Profits on the short side have come much more easily in Europe,
she said, as national economies continue to integrate and
industries that had enjoyed the fruits of protectionism falter
against new competition.
</P>
<P>
   Among technology fund managers, the best performers are those
who have switched nimbly among different parts of the industry,
like software and hard drives. ``There were a huge number of sector
rotations this year,'' Ms. McCabe said.
</P>
<P>
   Laggards this year include so-called macro funds _ which use
currency and interest-rate bets to profit from global trends _ and
some that specialize in value stocks, which typically trade at
lower price-to-earnings ratios.
</P>
<P>
   George Soros' Quantum fund, which like Tiger is one of the
biggest hedge funds, fared poorly for much of this year. But it
soared last month on the strength of its technology holdings,
giving it a 14.6 percent gain for the year through Dec. 15, people
at the firm said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
