   &QL; 
 &UR; ASKJEEVES  &LR; _ Two scientists at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology are suing Ask Jeeves, a company that lets Web surfers
use everyday English to conduct Web searches, for patent
infringement. By Kelly Zito
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 2135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2311 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ASKJEEVES-ASKJEEVES_S     12-17 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASKJEEVES-ASKJEEVES </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Ask Jeeves Sued Over Patents  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Two scientists at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology are
suing Ask Jeeves, a company that lets Web surfers use everyday
English to conduct Web searches, for patent infringement.
<P>
   Emeryville's Ask Jeeves, which operates the popular Ask.com
site, violates two U.S. patents issued in 1994 and 1995, according
to artificial intelligence researchers Patrick Winston and Boris
Katz.
</P>
<P>
   The patents concern methods for retrieving stored text and
database material using so-called ``natural-language'' searches
such as ``What city is nicknamed `The Big Apple?''' or ``Where can
I find MP3 players?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically we have two patents and we filed a suit for patent
infringement,'' Katz said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Katz wouldn't elaborate on the details of the suit, but
according to his Web page, for the past several years he has been
developing the ``START natural language system that allows the user
to access various types of information using English.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz is a research scientist at MIT's Artificial Intelligence
Laboratory. Winston is the Ford professor of Artificial
Intelligence and Computer Science at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Ask Jeeves said the company hadn't yet &LR;   &LR; been
served with official notice of the suit but said it is ``without
merit'' and the company plans to aggressively defend itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they describe in their patents is fundamentally different
from what we do,'' said company spokeswoman Heather Staples.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, filed yesterday in federal court in Boston, seeks
an injunction prohibiting Ask Jeeves from ``making, using or
selling the Internet search products provided under AskJeeves.com,
Ask.com and Ajkids.com,'' according to a statement from Katz and
Winston.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also seeks to prevent Ask Jeeves from licensing its
search software to other companies and asks for treble damages for
``willful infringement'' of the two patents.
</P>
<P>
   Along with operating the Ask.com site, Ask Jeeves provides its
search technology to sites for companies like Nike, Microsoft and
Williams-Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   At www.marthastewart.com, for instance, the technology allows
brides-to-be to ask plain English questions like ``How much should
I pay for my wedding?'' and receive instant answers.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time this year publicly traded Ask Jeeves has
been sued.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Mountain View's IPLearn LLC filed a suit in federal
court in Oakland, also alleging patent infringement. Ask Jeeves
denied it violated a patent held by that company. That case is
still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jeeves stock fell $7.36 yesterday, closing at $118.50.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
