u a BC-EPA-AIR-POLLUTION-ART     12-17 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-AIR-POLLUTION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA ORDERS POWER PLANTS TO CUT EMISSIONS TO REDUCE SMOG IN EAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: V.Va., Ohio, N.C., Pa., Md., Va., Mich., N.J., Ky., Del.
N.Y., Ind.)  (Eds: 2nd take is scheduled to be filed by 10 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Environmental Protection Agency on Friday
ordered 392 plants in a dozen states, mostly electric generating
stations, to cut in half emissions of chemicals that drift with
winds and add to smog along the Eastern seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   The federal regulators acted at the request of New York,
Connecticut, Massachusetts and Pennsylvania, which said they needed
help to meet national smog standards.
</P>
<P>
   The plants are in 12 states, as far west as Indiana and as far
south as North Carolina. Agency officials said they might soon
issue similar orders for plants in Illinois. Most of the plants
meet existing federal limits on the chemicals, nitrogen oxides, and
are in areas that do not exceed smog standards.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 states are West Virginia, Ohio, North Carolina,
Pennsylvania, Maryland, Virginia, Michigan, New Jersey, Kentucky,
Delaware, New York and Indiana. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The states that requested the action are among a group on the
East Coast that had already agreed among themselves to impose the
stricter standard on nitrogen oxide emissions within their borders.
The areas that would for the first time be forced to take action
under Friday's order are in the South and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   The areas covered by the action must reduce emissions by a total
of about half a million tons a year, all in the summer smog season,
the federal regulators said. The EPA said that compliance would
cost companies, which include Ford, General Motors, Dow Chemical
and most power providers in Ohio, West Virginia and Pennsylvania,
about $950 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in several industries, though, said Friday that they
were not sure what compliance would cost. Many executives and state
officials from areas covered by the order denounced it, saying that
they already met strict standards, that Eastern smog was little
affected by Midwestern emissions and that the EPA would ultimately
be rebuffed by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's track record in court has been poor in the last few
months. In May, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia Circuit barred the agency from enforcing a stricter
standard on smog levels, one calculated over an eight-hour period
instead of the current one-hour. In a separate decision, it blocked
the EPA from requiring the states to order a new round of
reductions in nitrogen oxide emissions from sources within their
borders.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Browner said Friday in a conference call with reporters,
``Our commitment is to solve the long-distance ozone-transport
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get there, one way or the other,'' she said.
``We are going to get there. We are going to get people clean
air.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 2143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
