A2315 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AFFIRMATIVE-CONNERLY1     12-17 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVE-CONNERLY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Battle lines firm in affirmative action fight
 &HT;    By Stephen Kiehl
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Ward Connerly brought his
anti-affirmative action campaign to West Palm Beach on Friday,
sending a message to Gov. Jeb Bush: You cannot stop me, no matter
how many roadblocks you put in my way.
</P>
<P>
   The latest delay, at the state Supreme Court, could make it
impossible for Connerly to put his racial preferences referendum to
voters next fall. Last week, the Californian put his petition drive
on hold until the court rules, which may not be until next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly and his supporters said Friday they had slowed but not
stopped their drive, and they will continue to gather signatures to
be in a position to get their measure on the ballot if the court
rules in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intention of backing off,'' Connerly told 340 people
at the Sheraton West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly's Florida Civil Rights Initiative has gathered more
than 50,000 signatures and needs to get another 385,000 by Aug. 8
to get on the ballot. The initiative has been opposed by both
Democratic and Republican lawmakers, but polls show it would win
easy approval from voters.
</P>
<P>
   In his talk, hosted by the Forum Club of the Palm Beaches,
Connerly mixed praise with criticism of Bush's One Florida plan,
designed to derail Connerly. He also blasted the state's
complicated method for getting a referendum on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, about 25 protesters from the National Organization
for Women waved signs _ ``Ward Off Connerly,'' said one _ and
passed out pro-affirmative action literature to people attending
the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, accustomed to hostile opposition, jokingly said that
he appreciated the welcome brigade but didn't understand the
one-fingered salute.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the hotel, the reception was warmer, with bursts of
applause throughout the speech, but Connerly still faced angry
questions from small-business owners and politicians, including
Palm Beach County Commission Chairwoman Maude Ford Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are zero programs in place, nothing is going to
happen'' to help minority contractors, Lee said. Connerly responded
that preferences based on race ignore discrimination against other
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe racism is gone,'' Connerly said. ``There's all
forms of discrimination. Nobody has a monopoly on discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of California's Board of Regents, Connerly was
instrumental in putting measures before California and Washington
voters that ended affirmative action in those states. He made
Florida his next battleground, he said, because of its size and his
desire to make race preferences an issue in the 2000 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   To those who say he should stay out of Florida's business,
Connerly offered no apologies, saying, ``55 percent of my taxes go
to government agencies, some of which are in Florida, and that
entitles me to go anyplace and share my views.''
</P>
<P>
   Connerly said Bush's One Florida plan is a good effort but it
doesn't go far enough. The plan ends racial preference in state
contracting and university admissions, but guarantees the top 20
percent of students at every public high school entry to a state
university.
</P>
<P>
   While ending explicit racial preferences, the Bush plan allows
colleges to look at race-correlated factors _ such as the economic
status and hometowns of applicants _ when admitting students.
Connerly said that distinction is really no distinction at all.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly also said the ``Talented 20'' guarantee will lower the
quality of students who get into college, hurting the reputation of
state universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is not in the top tier of academic institutions, yet
you want to be,'' Connerly told the editorial board of The Palm
Beach Post. ``I don't know how you can get there by admitting the
top 20 percent of all high school students.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bush responded that the governor believes his
plan will eventually improve the caliber of college students
because of the plan's provisions for improving high schools.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly was unequivocal in his call for a colorblind society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black people have to give up the past,'' he said. ``Slavery is
gone _ it's history. ... Our destiny is to get beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
