   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- BUCKLEY-FIRING-LINE-B&AMP;W
-- To chroniclers of William F. Buckley's life and the conservative
movement, ``Firing Line'' was the first and the most important in
widely establishing conservatism as a serious intellectual movement
in America. The show's influence, as well as that of National
Review and Buckley's syndicated column, began to wane after Ronald
Reagan was elected president in 1980. (Teresa Zabala/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) SPERLING, Manitoba - Dec. 17, 1999 -- CANADA-FARMS-2 --
Manitoba farmer Ron Hiebert sifts through some of his wheat which
is stored in a bin on his farm. ``Twenty five years ago, there were
25 families on this land - now there is only one.'' Free market
policies such as slashing farm subsidies, allowing inefficient
farmers to fail, and promoting productive techniques for the
survivors, have radically transformed the human landscape here.
(Kevin Moloney/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) LEWISBURG, Pa. -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC.
19 -- WEIS-SUPERMARKETS-3-B&AMP;W -- President Gerald Ford, left, Janet
C. Weis and husband Sigfried Weis, right, at the Weis residence in
Lewisburg, Pa., after the president spent the evening in their home
in 1978. In the last few years, profits have been stagnant for Weis
Markets Inc., and the Weises are now locked in an intense fight for
control of the company that made them one of the wealthiest
families in the United States. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- NILSSON-OPERA -- Birgit
Nilsson, 81, advising tenor Charles Castronovo to support the voice
from the abdomen and let the sound emerge without tension during a
master class in List Hall at the Metropolitan Opera House on
Wednesday. Exactly 40 years ago Saturday, Birgit Nilsson made her
Met debut in the role of Isolde in ``Tristan und Isolde.'' (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A -- John H. Laporte, lead portfolio manager of T.
Rowe Price New Horizons - one of the nation's oldest small-cap
funds. ``Historically, the sweet spot of the economic cycle has
been when small companies do exceedingly well,'' he says. ``That
has not happened this time around, and I don't know why.'' (The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
ABOUT-CARS-LANDROVER -- Land Rover Discovery Series II not only
takes punishment, it seems to enjoy it. The thing bobs, weaves,
digs in and keeps going. This is what driving an SUV should be all
about: fun. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) ATLANTA -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
WHITNEY-ARTISTS-2-COX -- Photographer Chris Verene, in Little's
Grocery in Atlanta, is one of four Atlanta artists, all under the
age of 40, selected for the 2000 Whitney Museum Biennial.
``Photography is a slow process of watching and waiting,'' he says.
(Louie Favorite/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ATLANTA -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
WHITNEY-ARTISTS-1-COX -- Ruth Leitman in her Atlanta studio. Ms.
Leitman, a filmmaker, is one of four Atlanta artists, all under the
age of 40, selected for the 2000 Whitney Museum Biennial. ``It is
the ultimate validation of all my years of work as an artist,'' she
says. (David Tulis/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BAXLEY, Ga. -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19
-- CRACKER-AUTHOR-2-COX -- Author Janisse Ray walking behind her
father, Franklin Delano Ray, in his junkyard in Baxley on Friday.
Her recent book, ``Ecology of a Cracker Childhood'', contains
unsparing descriptions of the pain her father's mental illness and
rigid religious beliefs caused her as a child. (Louie
Favorite/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BAXLEY, Ga. -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19
-- CRACKER-AUTHOR-1-COX -- Author Janisse Ray in her Baxley home
Friday. Her recent book, ``Ecology of a Cracker Childhood,''
interweaves the story of Ms. Ray's unusual childhood with chapters
about the natural history of the once-vast longleaf pine forests
that blanketed the coastal plain from Virginia to Florida to west
of the Mississippi. (Louie Favorite/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
RELIGION-ENDTIMES-COX -- As Christians mark the season of Advent
leading up to a celebration of what they believe was the
incarnation of the messiah, some are anticipating Jesus' imminent
return to Earth. A 1997 Associated Press poll showed that nearly
one of every four Christian adults - some 26.5 million Americans -
expect Jesus to come back during their lifetimes. Almost 40 percent
say he will arrive by the end of the 21st century. (Walter
Cumming/Cox Newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SPERLING, Manitoba - Dec. 17, 1999 -- CANADA-FARMS --
Manitoba wheat farmer Ron Hiebert on his wheat farm. ``Twenty five
years ago, there were 25 families on this land - now there is only
one.'' Free market policies such as slashing farm subsidies,
allowing inefficient farmers to fail, and promoting productive
techniques for the survivors, have radically transformed the human
landscape here. (Kevin Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SELINSGROVE, Pa. -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC.
19 -- WEIS-SUPERMARKETS-2-B&AMP;W -- The first Weis business was a
general store located in Selinsgrove in the early 1900s. By owning
their own trucks and warehouses, keeping out labor unions and
refusing to take on debt, the Weises created the most profitable
grocery company in the country, with margins four or five times
those of their competitors. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
WEIS-SUPERMARKETS-1-B&AMP;W -- Sigfried Weis, the father of Harry and
Sigmund Weis, first sold goods from a cart during the 1800s. In the
1920s, with the Weis' stores in Sunbury, Pa., thriving, Harry and
Sigmund decided to build neighboring houses on choice land in the
small Susquehanna Valley city. Over the decades, the Weises
transformed their small markets into a modern supermarket chain.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
STORE-SPRITZERS -- Tom Crutchfield has worked Bloomingdale's main
floor for most of the last 15 years. Formerly a cruise director,
Crutchfield, 49, is one of 150 spritzers hawking more than 100
brand names in the store. Such old-world sales techniques could be
endangered by the emergence of perfume-selling chains and online
venues - making this the scariest development in beauty retailing
to come along in years. (Elizabeth Lippman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) TROY, N.Y. -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
BIZ-SOFTWARE-EMPLOY -- Michael D. Marvin, chairman of MapInfo, at
company headquarters in Troy. Marvin, 54, is so much the spiritual
mentor of the informal Capital Region software circle that the
other chiefs often call themselves the Marvinettes. ``These were
21-year-old boys,'' he says. ``They needed an adult, and I loved
the challenge of proving a high-tech company could make it in
Troy.'' (David Jennings/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
HOLIDAY-PLASTIC-SURGERY -- Dr. Thomas Romo attending to Dolores
Laun, a 52-year-old data-entry clerk (in Romo's office) who, on the
``spur of the moment'' had an endoscopic brow lift, fat pads
removed from her lower eyelids and a chin implant. ``I wanted to
look great for the year 2000. I have a lot of friends and I like to
go out and I'm having a big party New Year's Eve.'' (Carol
Halebian/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Dec. 17, 1999 - FUNDRAISING HUANG -- John
Huang, seated center, who was Clinton's chief money-raiser for the
Asian-American community, testifies for a third day about
controversial donations to the Democratic Party before the House
Government Reform Committee on Friday. The hearings have been
sparsely attended by audience members as wells as members of the
committee. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK - Dec. 17, 1999 -- NY-BRICK-ATTACK -- Sharon
Barrett and her husband Arlen, parents of Nicole Barrett, announce
their daughter's release from Bellevue Hospital on Friday. Nicole
Barrett suffered a critical head injury when a man threw a brick at
her head on 42nd street. Ms. Barrett is making a solid recovery
from brain trauma following the broad daylight attack last month.
She will undergo intensive rehabilitation while living with her
parents in Athens, Texas, and hopes to move back to New York as
soon as she is well, said her mother. (Aaron Lee Fineman/the New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK - Dec. 17, 1999 -- BROOKLYN-ART-ATTACK -- Dennis
Heiner, 72, at a police precinct after his arrest on Thursday
night. Heiner allegedly threw white latex paint on the
controversial painitng of the Virgin Mary at the Brooklyn Museum
earlier Thursday. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED - Dec. 17, 1999 -- NY-CATHOLICS -- Cardinal John
O'Connor outside St. Patrick's Cathedral on St. Patrick's Day in
1992. Credit: As O'Connor prepares to step down, a New York Times
poll finds that Roman Catholics in the New York Archdiocese say
they want the next archbishop to be more concerned about issues
humanitarian than political, that helping the poor is the most
important challenge facing the archdiocese and that the church
could be much more in touch with its members. (Steve Berman/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WOODBURY, Conn. -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC.
19 -- CAR-SMART-LANDROVER -- A just-detailed Land Rover gets dirty.
All Land Rover dealers schedule ``outings'' - as often as four
times a year - in an attempt to bond with their outdoorsy
clientele. (Roger W. Strong/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
TIGER-HEDGEFUNDS -- Julian H. Robertson Jr., 66, has made many
changes recently at Tiger Management but says he remains committed
to a philosophy of value investing. ``We decided primarily to
return to what brought us to the party,'' Robertson says, referring
to plain old stock-picking. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON - Dec. 17, 1999 - CLINTON-DISABLED --
President Clinton leans over to hug Donna McNamee of Willoughby,
Ohio, who suffers from brittle bone disease after sighning into law
a bill that allows millions of disabled Americans to keep their
government-funded health coverage when they take a job. The
ceremony took place on Friday at the memorial to President Franklin
Delano Roosevelt. From left behind the president is Sen. Ted
Kennedy, D-Mass., Wesley Vinner of Riverdale, Md., Sen. Jim
Jeffords, R-Vt., Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y. (background), Secretary of
Labor Alexis Herman and Justin Dart, right, a disabled rights
advocate. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ABOARD THE USS JOHN F. KENNEDY - Dec. 17, 1999 -
CARRIER-CONCERT -- Robby Takac, left, and John Rzeznik, of the
``Goo Goo Dolls,'' interact with their audience aboard the U.S.
Navy aircraft carrier USS John F. Kennedy, Thursday. The band
performed a concert for the crew while the ship sailed in the
Persian Gulf in support of Operation Southern Watch. The operation
enforces the U.N. -imposed ``No-fly'' zone over southern Iraq.
(Christopher Moore, U.S. Navy/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
