<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 12/17/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Phot
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- NY-CATHOLICS -- Cardinal
John O'Connor. A strong majority of Catholics polled in the New
York region said things were going well or excellently for the
church in America. As Catholics do nationally, though, they favor
modernizing and opening up the church, by allowing priests to
marry, ordaining women as priests and granting lay people a greater
say in naming bishops. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) PASSAIC, N.J. -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- NJ-PRINCETON-GUNS --
Angela Gibson, the schoolmistress at Collegiate Academy, says that
some study guides the school had been using show ``no respect for
rules and order.'' Stating that one such book, the Princeton Review
study guide, which contains oddly insensitive language and
passages, is ``not a reflection of the beliefs of Random House
Random House or its Princeton Review publishing program,'' company
officials stopped shipment of the guide Friday. (Norman Y. Lono/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- GORE-LAUTENBERG -- Sen.
Frank G. Lautenberg, a three-term Democrat from New Jersey,
announced Friday his endorsement of Vice President Al Gore for the
Democratic presidential nomination. ``The experience of Al Gore was
the deciding factor,'' he says. (Shana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- OBIT-TAPLEY-B&AMP;W -- Donald
Fraser Tapley, dean of the Columbia University College of
Physicians and Surgeons during 10 years of robust growth, died on
Thursday at Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center. He was 72 and
lived in Palisades and Hamden, N.Y. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- OBIT-HELSTOSKI-B&AMP;W
-- Rep. Henry Helstoski voting at the Sylvan School in Rutherford
in 1976. Helstoski, a former New Jersey congressman whose bright
career in government all but ended in 1976 when he was indicted -
but never tried or found guilty - on charges of accepting a bribe,
died Thursday at a hospice in Wayne, N.J. He was 75. (Frank C.
Dougherty/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) TRENTON, N.J. -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- NY-NASCAR -- Donald L.
Fauerbach, left, executive director of the New Jersey Conference of
Mayors, discussing Nascar prospects in Trenton with lobbyists.
Fauerbach says that the state that wins a speedway would have to
put in no more than the usual access roads and sewer lines,
something New Jersey has done for Atlantic City casinos. (Laura
Pedrick/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Dec. 17, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 19 --
HOLIDAY-PLASTIC-SURGERY-2 -- ``You can walk in the door, have Botox
injections all over your face, have your driver waiting and be on
the plane in an hour,'' says Dr. James Matarasso, a plastic
surgeon, shown giving a consultation in his Park Avenue office. On
the eve of the millennium, thanks to new, quicker procedures and
treatments that speed healing, doctors in New York say they are
heavily booked. (Carol Halebian/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) LOS ANGELES - Dec. 17, 1999 -- SUB-ELDERLY-EDUC-2 --
From left, Ed Bressler, Estelle Howard, Shirley Finn, Marjorie
Bierman and Don Palmer listen to Margery Gould, right, make a point
during a group discussion session at the Great Southern American
Literature study group at the Plato Society. The purity of the
intellectual exercise at Plato is rare to behold. It reflects an
explosion in the lifelong learning movement, as the first
generation to pursue higher education in big numbers has settled
into its Golden Years.(Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK - Dec. 17, 1999 -- BROOKLYN-ART-ATTACK-2 -- A
police officer, right, and a museum security agent guard the
painting ``Holy Virgin Mary'' by Chris Ofili on Friday at the
Brooklyn Museum.Dennis Heiner, 72, has been charged with trying to
deface the painting on Thursday after he allegedly threw white
latex paint on the controversial painitng. (Chang W. Lee/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) LOS ANGELES - Dec. 17, 1999 -- ELDERLY-EDUC -- Estelle
Howard looks through notes during in her Great Southern American
Literature study group at the Plato Society. At left is fellow
student Ed Bressler. The purity of the intellectual exercise at
Plato is rare to behold. It reflects an explosion in the lifelong
learning movement, as the first generation to pursue higher
education in big numbers has settled into its Golden Years.(Monica
Almeida/The New York Times)
