<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2323 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-TOBACCO-TAX-1STLD-     12-17 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOBACCO-TAX-1STLD-WRITETHRU- </SLUG>
 ART- 2NDTAKE-NYT  
 ALBANY , N.Y. : three years. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The additional tobacco tax is expected to raise about $400
million a year for the state. The last increase in the state's
cigarette tax came in 1993, when it climbed to 56 cents a pack,
from 39 cents. At the time, that was the highest rate in the
country, but 13 other states have since adopted higher rates. New
Jersey's cigarette tax is 80 cents a pack, Connecticut's is 50
cents and Pennsylvania's is 31 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The measure marks the first time that Pataki has championed a
major tax increase since taking office in 1995 on an aggressive
tax-cutting platform. The tax increase could help him deflect
criticism over the fact that Philip Morris, the tobacco giant,
helped pay for two trips that he and his family took to Hungary in
1995 and 1996, an issue that is now the subject of a state ethics
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The move was lauded by anti-tobacco groups, which have long
asserted that a higher tax would discourage people, particularly
teen-agers, from smoking and lead others to quit. ``The 55-cent
cigarette tax hike could move New York to the front of the pack
nationally in tackling the tobacco menace,'' said Blair Horner, the
legislative director for the New York Public Interest Research
Group, a staunch advocate of policies discouraging tobacco use.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure drew protests from the tobacco industry, where
executives have long opposed tax increases, saying they depress
sales perhaps more than any other tobacco restriction. The industry
also says that such a tax is regressive, hitting the poorest
consumers the hardest, and that it encourages the smuggling of
cigarettes from states with lower taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan McCormick, spokesman for Philip Morris USA, said: ``We
think that it's a bad idea for New York state. The state's coffers
are really full of money in terms of the budget surplus. At a time
when the state's budget is prospering, we think that it's unfair to
single out smokers to pay for increased spending.'' He added, ``At
the same time, there is the potential for a negative business
impact on retailers, especially those located in border areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations between Pataki and Democratic leaders focused
on another critical health care issue: a state law that adds $1.7
billion in surcharges to hospital bills to help finance a range of
services provided by hospitals, primarily training young doctors
and providing charity care for the poor. The law, known as the
Health Care Reform Act, is set to expire at the end of the year,
and Pataki and the Democrats have been divided over what changes,
if any, to make to it before renewing it.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's allies in the business sector had been urging him to
eliminate the surcharges altogether, contending that employers end
up paying most of them through higher insurance premiums for their
workers. But Pataki abandoned their cause after they failed to
respond to an expensive advertising campaign that 1199 unveiled in
recent weeks predicting chaos if the surcharges were not preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Before Pataki and Democratic leaders reached an agreement on
renewing the system of surcharges, the negotiations had stalled on
the key question of how much money the state should be providing to
help hospitals train young doctors and provide charity care to the
poor. The issue is of great importance in New York City, where
large numbers of teaching hospitals provide care in poor
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's aides had privately proposed cutting funds for graduate
medical education, saying that the state should not be spending
money to train medical students because they often end up
practicing medicine in other states. The Democrats, meanwhile,
called for increasing the amount of money the state funnels to
hospitals to help treat poor people.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Pataki and Democratic leaders agreed to cut
financing for graduate medical education by $50 million a year, to
$494 million from $544 million. The two sides also agreed to
increase financing for charity care by $100 million a year, to $838
million from $738 million. The leaders also agreed to preserve a
program that provides health insurance for 415,000 low-income
children. That program, called Child Health Plus, is financed
through the system of hospital surcharges at a cost of $200 million
a year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
