u a BC-N &LR; J &UR; -PRINCETON-ART-NY     12-17 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL RULE FOR VOCABULARY GUIDE: DON'T USE TONGUE-IN-CHEEK
VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
 J -PRINCETON-ART-NYT  (ART ADV: A photo NYT34 is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASSAIC, N.J. _ Ralph Briggs was helping his son Sean with his
seventh-grade vocabulary homework on Tuesday, when he asked the boy
to use the word ``cardinal'' in a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Sean replied: ``The cardinal rule in our school is that you
don't shoot the teachers. If you have to shoot a gun, shoot it at
another student or an administrator.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got very furious with my son,'' said Briggs, a deputy fire
chief in Hackensack. ``I said: `How can you say such a thing? You
know that's not right.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `That's what it says in our book.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sean had been quoting almost verbatim from ``Word Smart II,''
the Princeton Review study guide that he and his classmates had
been given at Collegiate Academy, a private school here, to prepare
for the preliminary College Board exams.
</P>
<P>
   Leafing through the guide, which aims to build vocabulary by
using words in sentences, Briggs found some other surprising uses
for words, like ``boorish'' (`` `Don't be boorish,' Sue admonished
Charles at the prom after he . . . crushed empty beer cans on his
head'') and ``byzantine'' (``Angela couldn't follow the novel's
byzantine plot, so she just read the dirty parts'') and
``inundated'' (``The 15-year-old was inundated with gifts after she
gave birth to octuplets'').
</P>
<P>
   Outraged by those and other passages, Briggs immediately
complained to school officials, who in turn complained to the
publisher of the books, Random House.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, in response, Random House officials decided to stop
shipment of the popular study guide and some other Princeton Review
guides, and said that they would review their other guides for what
they agreed was unsuitable material for students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deeply regret this very insensitive use of language,'' Lisa
Alpert, vice president and publisher at Random House, said in a
statement. ``It is certainly not a reflection of the beliefs of
Random House or its Princeton Review publishing program.''
</P>
<P>
   Collegiate Academy officials said that they had pulled two of
the guides _ ``Word Smart I'' as well as its successor _ from
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a conscious effort to denigrate all things that are
traditional and proper and family-oriented,'' said Angela Gibson,
schoolmistress at Collegiate. ``It shows no respect for rules and
order.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Applebaum, a spokesman for Random House, said the
Princeton Review books had a reputation for being more flippant
than other guides.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're beloved by students and some educators, professors and
administrators exactly for that _ their irreverence _ because they
speak to kids in a tongue-in-cheek, anti-authoritarian frame of
reference,'' he said. ``One would speculate that that was the frame
of mind of the authors, which maybe in 1992 was considered
amusing.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was quick to add that since then, events like school
shootings had lent a more sinister tone to sample sentences like
this one from ``Word Smart II'': ``The fraternal feeling among the
meeting participants disappeared when one of them stood up at
dinner and began firing a machine gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Applebaum said, ``Surely today, with all we've gone through in
this country, it's at the very least inappropriate and
insensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is the first time the company has had such
complaints about the guides, Applebaum said. ``Word Smart I'' was
first published in 1988 and revised in 1993. ``Word Smart II'' was
first published in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The series is mostly sold in bookstores to individual buyers,
most of whom are older than seventh-graders, he said. Some books
are sold to schools, although Applebaum said he did not know how
many. This year 16,000 copies of ``Word Smart II'' have been sold,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gibson said the Collegiate Academy, which has 150 students
from prekindergarten through 12th grade, sends 100 percent of its
students to college. To help them qualify for special programs for
gifted children at Johns Hopkins University, or Drew University,
she said, it begins preparing students as early as seventh grade to
take the College Board tests.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, Mrs. Gibson said, the school used other study
guides. This year, at the recommendation of an English teacher who
is no longer at the school, teachers began using ``Word Smart I''
and ``Word Smart II'' for students in seventh and eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gibson acknowledged that she had not read the entire books
herself after the teacher recommended them, but instead relied on
the reputation that Princeton Review had for publishing quality
study guides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We select our teachers very carefully, and we rely on their
judgment,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When Briggs came to her with complaints about ``Word Smart II,''
she took it home that night to read through it, and and then called
Random House to complain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
