A2342 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH18-COX     12-17 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush confident as campagin spins forward
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Days before he breaks for the holidays, Gov.
George W. Bush is a confident candidate who pleads immunity to the
charges leveled by what he demeaningly calls ``the chattering
class.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed by critics and pundits who doubt his mettle and
intellect, Bush said Friday he believes the GOP presidential
nomination very well could be his by the time Texans vote in their
primary March 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've got a lot of work to do,'' he said at a news
conference after filing his candidacy in the Texas primary. ``But I
like my chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before, at the kind of carefully choreographed event
that is a Bush campaign hallmark, he told supporters, ``I hope to
come back to you in March and say, `Mission accomplished.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush says all the politically correct things: ``It's a close
race, and I welcome it,'' he says of Arizona Sen. John McCain, a
worthy opponent in New Hampshire. But the campaign is taking a
glimpse beyond clinching the nomination. Tentative plans are being
considered for how to generate publicity in the months between
capturing the nomination and formally accepting it at the national
convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way to do that would be to take a trip,'' Bush said in a
Friday interview.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is looking toward a multination trip in the Western
Hemisphere to demonstrate his support for the North American Free
Trade Agreement and talk about building the hemisphere into a
trading bloc that could compete with the emerging European Union.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the candidate, who campaigns Monday in New
Hampshire before taking a holiday break through the end of the
year, is focused on Iowa, New Hampshire and South Carolina, the
states with early battles. In addition to fending off McCain, Steve
Forbes and three other GOP foes, Bush is under attack from critics
who say his performance in recent debates raises questions about
whether he is White House material.
</P>
<P>
   Without anger, but with unmistakable disdain, Bush says the
criticism doesn't matter and doesn't bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what happened in '94,'' he said, referring to his upset
win over Gov. Ann Richards and launching into a recitation of that
year's conventional wisdom about him. ``He's never done anything,
doesn't believe anything. Everything was given to him. Total
failure. Not very smart. Doesn't understand policy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same routine. It's just repeating itself. There have
been a series of these little hurdles. Can't get off the ground.
This campaign is going be a flop before it begins. Never says
anything. Doesn't have any policy. Won't be specific. Won't answer
questions. Won't do the talk shows. Refuses to debate. And I've
been through this before. I remember '88 when a great man was
labeled by the chattering class and the cartoonists (who said) he
checked his manhood into a blind trust, or wimp,'' he said,
referring to criticism of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``And someone says, `Well what are you going to do about it?'
and that's win. Guess who is not being affected by it? The voter,''
he said with the kind of confidence being interpreted as cocky by
some of the chattering class.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's confidence in his escalating battle with top challenger
McCain is based on the front-runner's belief that the voters want a
president with chief executive experience, which McCain lacks.
</P>
<P>
   The last U.S. senator elected directly to the White House was
John F. Kennedy in 1960. ``You're making my case,'' Bush told an
interviewer who recounted that fact.
</P>
<P>
   As he heads into the next phase of the campaign, Bush is
publicly showing more of the feistiness he often exhibits in
private.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, you know, `He's got an empty suit,''' Bush told
supporters, working to turn criticism of him into a shot at Al
Gore's recent haberdashery preferences. ``And I said, `At least
it's not an empty earth-tone suit.'''
</P>
<P>
   And although he's still fielding criticism for running a
cocooned campaign heavy on stump-speech sound bites, Bush is
showing an increasing ability to wander from script. He also has
shown an ability to talk his way into near-trouble and navigate
himself out.
</P>
<P>
   In a Thursday interview on CNN's ``Larry King Live,'' Bush made
a midcourse correction in an answer about trade sanctions against
Cuba. King suggested that the sanctions strike hardest at Cuba's
poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not their fault,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not their ... yes, a little bit their fault,'' Bush
said, adding moments later, ``I mean, in a sense that, you know, I
would hope they ... well, maybe not. Maybe, you're right. I
shouldn't say that. The Cuban regime is so repressive, and they've
got secret police policing everybody that it's awfully hard for
people to express their will. But we should not _ we should not
provide capital to a Fidel Castro government to keep them propped
up.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Friday news conference, Bush adroitly handled another
foreign policy question with a couple of potentially dicey answers.
The governor was asked what his law enforcement advisers tell him
about their confidence in Mexican law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   One possible answer, fraught with credibility problems, would be
full confidence in the Mexican police. Another possible answer
would be a full assault on the integrity of Mexican law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Bush talked his way to a middle, non-newsworthy ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is no question that there is a lot of concern
about justice in Mexico. I think President Zedillo shares that
concern,'' he said, adding that reforms are planned. ``They
recognized that there needs to be a substantial upgrading of the
law enforcement efforts in Mexico. And step one is to recognize
there is a problem. They've recognized there is a problem, and step
two is to put a plan in place to do so. I haven't been down to
Mexico since then, but I certainly hope the reforms they've
proposed are being implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
