<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2344 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-WEIS-SUPERMARKETS-ART     12-17 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEIS-SUPERMARKETS-ART-4TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STANDOFF AT THE CORNER STORE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ill., Conn., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic of Weis
family tree; Weis Markets stocks vs. industry index; operating
income is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNBURY, Pa. _ In the 1920s, with their corner stores thriving,
Harry and Sigmund Weis decided to build neighboring houses on
choice land in this small Susquehanna Valley city.
</P>
<P>
   The brick homes, one colonial and one Tudor, bordered the
riverbank and looked out to the gently sloping Appalachian
Mountains. The two brothers shared a garage; their young children _
a son and a daughter for each _ ran back and forth across the
driveway when they played in their front yards.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, the Weises transformed their small markets
into a modern supermarket chain. By owning their own trucks and
warehouses, keeping out labor unions and staunchly refusing to take
on debt, the brothers, and later their sons, created the most
profitable grocery company in the country, with margins four or
five times those of their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, the Weises became one of the wealthiest families in the
United States, slowly expanding their central Pennsylvania chain as
far as upstate New York and the Virginia suburbs of Washington _
and popping into the public eye only when they appeared on Forbes
magazine's annual list of the richest Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Harry's and Sigmund's father had bequeathed his corner
store to them, they handed the business down to their sons, Robert
and Sigfried Weis (pronounced ``wise''). Although Weis Markets Inc.
went public in 1965, the family kept control, retaining about
four-fifths of the shares. There was little intrigue and a lot of
profit.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few years, profits have been stagnant, and in
the last month, intrigue has inevitably developed. Like the
Binghams, the Hunts, the Kochs and so many business families before
them, the Weises are now locked in an intense fight for control of
the company that has given them their fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides of the family that were once divided by only a
driveway are now split over one of the central questions in today's
economy: Can a small company, even one with a long history of
success, prosper in an era of consolidation?
</P>
<P>
   That the debate is taking place at Weis, which has achieved
almost legendary status in its industry, illustrates just how
difficult it is for family businesses to survive from one
generation to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Sigmund's descendants, with one eye on the fast-expanding
Wal-Mart Stores and the other on grocery behemoths like Royal Ahold
N.V. that have arisen from the consolidation spree of the 1990s,
want to look into selling the company. Led by Janet L. Weis, 80,
the widow of Sigmund's son, Sigfried, they are mounting a proxy
fight for two additional board seats, which would give them four of
the seven.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Weis, her three daughters and their husbands, who own a 41
percent stake, see declining margins and a company stock that,
before the feud burst into the open, was worth less than it was in
1987. They worry that the company risks a long, slow decline if it
stays independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The handwriting is really on the wall,'' Mrs. Weis said. On
Friday, shares of the 200-store chain closed at $41.25, up 18
percent in the last three weeks amid investors' hopes for a sale.
</P>
<P>
   But Harry's family, which now runs the business after decades
behind the scenes, has no intention of surrendering to its cousins
or to its larger rivals. Led by Robert Weis, Harry's 80-year-old
son, they say the current competition is similar to earlier
threats, when better capitalized supermarkets entered but failed to
crack their mid-Atlantic markets. Weis Markets still has
above-average margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are reading the facts wrong,'' said Robert Weis, a
soft-spoken man who still has a full head of gray hair. Weis, who
with his three children and his sister, also owns a 41 percent
stake in the company worth $700 million. He had served as deputy to
Sigfried, Janet Weis' husband, for more than 30 years and took over
the chairman's slot in 1995. Sigfried's family no longer has anyone
in management, and Robert's family has offered to buy out its
cousins' share.
</P>
<P>
   The battle has many trappings of a takeover struggle. Sigmund's
and Sigfried's family has hired Salomon Smith Barney and Wachtel,
Lipton, Rosen &AMP; Katz, a New York law firm, to advise them on how to
lobby shareholders, oust the current board and put the company up
for sale. Harry's and Robert's family has retained Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter and Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison, another
Manhattan-based law firm.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute, meanwhile, has split the Susquehanna Valley, where
hospital wings, arts centers and major buildings at two
universities, Bucknell and Susquehanna, bear the Weis name. And it
has chilled friendships among the principal players, who used to
play golf together and still routinely eat lunch at the same
restaurant, though not the same table.
</P>
<P>
   But this is also a family feud with a twist. So far, it is
nearly bereft of nastiness. Neither side doubts the other's motive,
only their conclusion. Over the last month, Janet Weis and her
allies have publicly praised the way Robert Weis and his deputies
have managed the company, even as she seeks to oust him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone respects the job they're doing,'' said Joseph I.
Goldstein, Mrs. Weis' son-in-law and a member of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trade allegations, the two sides share a sense of
melancholy that they are locked in a public squabble likely to end
up humiliating one branch of the family.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first thought about this, it was sad,'' said Michael
Morris Apfelbaum, a lifelong family friend and, as a lawyer
overseeing some of the stock, the second dissident board member.
``But when you cut out the emotion from it, you have to realize
this is the way of capitalism. You have to be big to survive in the
economy today. That's just the way of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   At least it's what the debate is about.
</P>
<P>
   The Weises have been merchants in these parts since shortly
after the Civil War, when Sigfried Weis immigrated from Austria and
made his way to central Pennsylvania. To earn a living, he walked
from farmhouse to farmhouse in the lush fields of the Susquehanna
Valley _ less than 100 miles from where the Battle of Gettysburg
had raged just a few years before _ selling jewelry and other
goods.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he opened a general store in Selinsgrove, a town across
the river from here, and he married a local woman; they would have
two sons. When the boys grew up, Sigfried Weis hung up a sign: ``S.
Weis &AMP; Sons.''
</P>
<P>
   After his death in 1907, the sons _ Sigmund and Harry _ opened a
new store in Sunbury, the county seat, focused on groceries. It was
the start of a furious expansion that lasted nearly 30 years and
did not end until the Depression, when they had more than 100
outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a division of labor was emerging that would last for
almost a century. Sigmund, the more outgoing brother, was the
marketer who decided which national brands the stores should sell.
Harry, a lawyer, scouted real estate, picking where the next Weis
Pure Foods would go, family members say.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the shops enabled the brothers to build their
neighboring houses on Front Street, just a few blocks from
Sunbury's main square and their first store.
</P>
<P>
   The Depression, however, prompted shoppers to look for more
bargains and helped usher in the era of self-service supermarkets.
In 1937, Sigmund and Harry Weis started closing many of their
stores to create a smaller chain of larger stores.
</P>
<P>
   Weis Markets, which owned more of its stores and more of its
equipment than competitors did, thrived. It sold an unusually large
number of private-label products. And it fought bitterly to keep
unions from organizing its workers, many of whom were part-timers
without benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in a 1965 registration with the Securities and Exchange
Commission to take the company public, virtually the only problem
that the family noted was a yearlong strike by meat-department
employees starting in the summer of 1963. Five years later, the
company and a food workers' union fought all the way to the Supreme
Court in a landmark case over whether a shopping mall was a public
place where the union, covered by First Amendment speech
protection, could try to organize.
</P>
<P>
   (The union won in court, but Weis has defeated every effort to
organize the company's employees, including one by the Teamsters
this year.)
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1960s, the company achieved operating margins of more
than 8 percent. Weis was the envy of the grocery industry, where
margins of 2 percent or 3 percent were much more common. When Weis
Markets Inc. went public in 1965, the shares made their debut at
$21. Each side of the family was suddenly worth more than $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   By then, both Sigmund and Harry Weis had died, and their sons
were running the business. Sigfried _ Sigmund's son, named for the
family patriarch _ was four years older than Robert, and they had
followed similar paths. As children, both worked behind the counter
at some of the original Weis Pure Foods stores. Both served in the
Army. Both attended Yale.
</P>
<P>
   It was during college that Sigfried Weis met his future wife,
Janet. He was a freshman and she was a 15-year-old who lived in the
nearby town of Hamden, Conn. He did not win her over immediately.
``It was one of those back-and-forth things,'' she said this month
at her home, grinning between puffs on a thin cigarette.
Eventually, after they were married at the Carlyle Hotel in New
York, she followed him back to Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Sigfried became president of the company in 1961 without much
debate, family members say. He was older than Robert, who became
his deputy. Robert ran the company's finances and, like his father,
chose sites for new stores, and the two cousins remained in those
jobs for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   They had lunch together most days and lived in the same
neighborhood, separated only by an alley.
</P>
<P>
   But by all accounts, Sigfried and Robert Weis were not as close
as their daily proximity suggested. They were business partners,
not best friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were different, but we were friendly,'' Robert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just moved in different circles,'' Janet Weis said.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father, Sigfried was the more social of the two. He and
Janet belonged to the country-club crowd and gave their money to
large institutions, like a regional hospital. Robert and his wife,
Patricia, gave to the small hospital in Sunbury.
</P>
<P>
   Differences in the ages of the two couples' children pushed them
further apart. The three daughters of Sigfried and Janet were all
at least 10 years older than the two daughters and son of Robert
and Patricia. The next generation _ second cousins who shared a
last name and a fortune and grew up only yards away from each other
_ still do not know each other well. There was never a blow-up,
both sides say. The two families simply drifted apart.
</P>
<P>
   That estrangement, particularly in the context of the strong
stock market, is dangerous, said John Messervey, president of the
National Family Business Council, an Illinois consulting firm that,
among other things, runs retreats where wealthy families can get to
know one another better. Many families, Messervey said, ``are
scared they're never going to see a market this good again.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Weises in the 1970s and '80s, there seemed to be little
reason for worry. Operating margins never fell below 7 percent and,
as late as 1987, were above 9 percent. Weis Markets, a 1982
headline in Forbes magazine said, ``makes one-third of what Safeway
does _ on only 5 percent of Safeway's sales.'' The same year, the
grandsons of the Austrian peddler appeared on the magazine's list
of the 400 wealthiest Americans.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the year after the Weises fell off the Forbes list, a
squat, enormous distributor center began rising just off of
Interstate 99 in western Pennsylvania. When completed, it covered
more than 800,000 square feet, and it bore the corporate name that
strikes fear into virtually every other retailer in the country:
Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   There could be no doubt about the building's purpose. Like a
massing of troops at an enemy's border, its size was an
announcement that an unstoppable invasion was about to begin.
Wal-Mart was bringing supercenters, stores that sell everything
from milk and bananas to slacks and tires and are three times the
size of modern supermarkets, to Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Supercenters, the first of which opened in 1988, had already
transformed the $420 billion-a-year grocery business. To respond to
Wal-Mart's efficient distribution network and its money-saving
clout with suppliers, supermarket executives were rapidly
consolidating one of the few remaining large regional businesses in
the United States. Their aim was to cut costs and gain the kind of
power over manufacturers that Wal-Mart has.
</P>
<P>
   The five biggest chains now take in 40 cents of every dollar
that Americans spend at the supermarket, up from 20 cents in 1993,
according to the Food Institute, a trade group in Fair Lawn, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   For Weis Markets, the changes were coming at a bad time. It had
been facing tough competition from Giant Foods of Carlisle, Pa.,
which had expanded in the area during the late '80s and early '90s.
By 1996, Giant had actually overtaken Weis in central Pennsylvania
with an 18 percent market share, according to Food Trade News, a
publication that tracks grocery sales in the mid-Atlantic states.
At the same time, inflation was almost nonexistent, leaving grocers
little room to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
   Weis' legendary operating margins paid the price. From their
high of 9.2 percent in 1987, they fell to 5.5 percent in 1993 and
just 4.1 percent last year. Operating margins for the rest of the
industry are now 3 percent. The company posted net income of $83.7
million last year on $1.87 billion in sales, about $3 million less
than it earned in 1989 on $1.24 billion in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers _ along with the specter of Wal-Mart and the new
grocery giants _ are at the core of the argument of Sigfried Weis'
family. The chain still has many strengths, like its $400 million
in cash, its milk and ice cream plants and its brand's reputation.
But the company should act quickly, the family says, to determine
whether it should participate in the current consolidation wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies rise and fall, and we want to make sure this company
keeps rising,'' said Goldstein, a director who is a partner at
Kirkpatrick &AMP; Lockhart in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Robert Weis and the president of the company,
Norman Rich, say that is precisely what it has been doing for the
past few years. In 1995, when Robert took over from an ailing
Sigfried, the company began a capital investment push even more
aggressive than the one undertaken by Sigmund and Harry Weis in the
1920s. In the last four years, the company has spent $374 million
to build 35 large new markets and to remodel 51 others.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion has helped increase revenue by 7.5 percent through
the first three quarters of 1999. The company, meanwhile, has begun
working with a cooperative of smaller chains, cutting deals with
manufacturers similar to the discounts the bigger companies can
negotiate, Rich said.
</P>
<P>
   The proof of Weis' relative strength can be seen in its stock,
they added. From Jan. 1 to Nov. 29, just before the proxy fight
began, the company's stock fell only 8 percent versus 35 percent
for the Standard &AMP; Poor's supermarket industry index.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity, Harry Weis' descendants say, undercuts their
cousins' main point: that a small chain can no longer hold its own.
``Back in 1928, Safeway Stores came with the same story and tried
to buy our company,'' Robert Weis said last week, speaking softly
while sitting in the company's modest boardroom here.
``Fortunately, we said no.''
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon after Thanksgiving, however, the phone rang in the
office of Rich, Weis' president. A native of New York City whose
gregariousness stands in contrast to the Weis family's reserve,
Rich had joined Weis Markets in 1964 as a food scientist and
climbed up the ranks, reaching his current position in 1994, He
runs daily operations and reports to Robert Weis, the chairman.
(The company has never used the title of chief executive.)
</P>
<P>
   The phone call, Rich recalled, came from Apfelbaum, the
director, who said, ``Norm, can you come down to my office?''
Apfelbaum said it was an emergency. His father, Sidney Apfelbaum,
who oversees a trust that owns Weis stock, and Goldstein, Mrs.
Weis' son-in-law, were also there.
</P>
<P>
   Rich drove to the law offices of Apfelbaum, Apfelbaum &AMP;
Apfelbaum, in a converted house off the town square. The three men
waiting for him said they believed Weis Markets should seriously
investigate selling itself and that they wanted to install
directors who agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The proxy fight, and family feud, had begun.
</P>
<P>
   The decision had come slowly for the dissidents, over a series
of informal discussions among themselves and during the occasional
cocktail hours that Apfelbaum and Mrs. Weis have together at her
house, a four-bedroom Tudor on 14 acres across the Susquehanna
River from Sunbury.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Apfelbaum, whose father grew up playing pool with
Robert Weis on the third floor of his Front Street house, and
Goldstein, a former associate director of enforcement at the SEC,
decided they had to act.
</P>
<P>
   Sigfried's family has asked that the company hold a shareholder
vote by Feb. 7, citing company bylaws, on whether to replace the
board. Since each family controls 41 percent of the votes, the
resolution would need the approval of more than half of the 18
percent of investors who are not family members.
</P>
<P>
   Most outsiders consider the dissidents to be the favorites; in
recent years, shareholders have tended to choose whatever path is
most likely to bolster a stock price immediately. Salomon argues
that the company could fetch $45 to $55 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Charles M. LaLoggia, a Rochester fund manager who publishes an
investment newsletter, said he thinks the company would sell for at
least $45 a share and maybe up to $90, given its strong balance
sheet and recent valuations for other chains.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Investors would be unlikely to turn down a deal in that range.
``As far as the dissidents work for all the shareholders, they're
our guys,'' said Martin J. Whitman, who runs a $1.5 billion fund
that has owned Weis stock since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But a vote would probably be close. About three-fifths of the
independent investors, representing 11 percent of the company's
stock, are individuals, Rich said. They are more likely to focus on
the company's long record of paying strong dividends, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Rich and Robert Weis will also argue that the company would not
fetch a fair price now, because many potential suitors are trading
near 52-week lows. Albertson's and Kroger, for example, are busy
integrating the chains they have already bought, and their recent
earnings disappointments show they have a ways to go. ``A lot of
the retailers have got their hands full right now,'' said Mark
Husson, a supermarket analyst at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   For the company, the stakes are obviously high. But they seem
almost as high for the region and the two Weis families. The chain
employs 19,000 people, and its higher-paying, middle-management
jobs would be most vulnerable in a takeover. Those positions are
concentrated in central Pennsylvania, a coal and agricultural
region that has suffered economically over the last three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average person thinks this just can't be good,'' David L.
Persing, the mayor of Sunbury since 1989, said of the dispute. ``It
might be good for stockholders, but I don't think it will be good
for this area.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the Weises, or their allies on either side, are likely
to emerge from the fight worse off financially. But the dispute has
already had personal costs. It has effectively ended the friendship
of Apfelbaum and Rich, who still see each other at Tedd's Landing,
a local restaurant where both have lunch. Only last summer,
Apfelbaum said, the two men smoked cigars together at 4 a.m. at the
W Hotel on Lexington Avenue in Manhattan, just hours after Rich's
son had been married.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Weis, meanwhile, has chosen to spend part of her 81st year
fighting a public battle over the company her late husband ran for
35 years, a company she helped build by tasting samples of new
products and telling her husband which labels looked right. ``It's
been all of my life,'' Mrs. Weis said.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has been most difficult for Robert Weis, said people
who know him, though he is reluctant to discuss his personal
feelings. As he nears retirement and grooms his 32-year-old son,
Jonathan, to succeed him, the family of his longtime boss is trying
to depose him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's conditions in life change. Their needs change. Their
desires change,'' the older Weis said, explaining what he sees as
the reasons for the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess every time you have a partner, you have a problem,''
he added, ``maybe not with the partner, but with the next
generation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
