<HEADLINE>
TIGHT CURBS ORDERED ON USE OF NUCLEAR SECRETS IN SCIENTIST'S TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal magistrate has imposed tight restrictions
on the release of nuclear secrets in court in the case of a former
scientist at Los Alamos National Laboratory charged with
mishandling and copying classified materials.
</P>
<P>
   Don Svet, a U.S. magistrate in Albuquerque, N.M., ordered that
all classified information the defense seeks to introduce in the
case of the former Los Alamos scientist, Wen Ho Lee, must be
screened under the Classified Information Procedures Act of 1981
before it can become evidence. The law was enacted to prevent
defendants in national security cases from using the threat of
divulging secrets to force the government to drop its prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was arrested on Dec. 10 and charged in a 59-count indictment
with transferring vast amounts of nuclear data from a classified
computer system into an unsecure system, and then copying the
material onto portable computer tapes. Of the 10 tapes the
government says he made, seven are still missing.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has not been charged with giving the secret information to
an unauthorized person or to a foreign government, and has not been
charged with espionage.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Lee pleaded not guilty to the charges and was ordered
held until his trial.
</P>
<P>
   The magistrate's order calls for a court security officer to
review any documents submitted by the defense to determine whether
they are classified, and then to keep the information sealed.
Closed hearings can then be held to determine if the information
can be admitted as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The magistrate's ruling applies to pretrial hearings and
motions, and the judge assigned to the case, Chief Judge John
Conway of the U.S. District Court in Albuquerque, will rule later
on the use of classified materials in the trial itself.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before a federal grand jury indicted Lee, senior
officials in the Clinton administration met at the White House and
decided that the case should go forward, even if some material was
divulged.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials say that Lee, who worked in the X Division
at Los Alamos, which designs nuclear weapons, transferred and
copied a vast archive of nuclear secrets, including recently
updated computer codes about the most recent designs of nuclear
warheads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
