</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DEBATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN HEATS UP AS GORE, BRADLEY CLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ In the increasingly acrimonious Democratic
presidential contest, Al Gore and Bill Bradley clashed repeatedly
but politely Friday night over which of them would do more to
protect Medicare for senior citizens, provide quality health
insurance to more Americans and improve public education for more
children.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp exchanges occurred during a town hall meeting at
Daniel Webster College, sponsored by ABC's ``Nightline.'' About 300
New Hampshire voters attended and asked questions about terrorism,
school violence, space exploration, gay rights, health care and
education in the course of the spirited 90-minute session in which
both candidates demonstrated their easy mastery of policy detail _
and talent for offering very long answers to short questions.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the subject of health care where the candidates
differed most dramatically. The vice president, for example,
pressed Bradley to explain what he would do to protect Medicare as
the baby boom generation doubles the ranks of beneficiaries. And he
accused Bradley of serving up a plan that would leave too many
unprotected in New Hampshire and, because of its great cost, could
endanger the economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, on the other hand, said there is plenty of time to
resolve concerns about the future solvency of Medicare. The more
urgent question of the hour, he said, is how to help the 44 million
Americans who don't have health insurance obtain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've offered a plan to do that,'' Bradley said. ``The question
I would ask Al, the main difference between our programs - I do
provide access to affordable quality health care for all Americans.
My question to you is, who will you leave out?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, however, insisted that he is intent on reaching universal
health care for all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't leave out anyone,'' said Gore, who favors a
step-by-step health insurance expansion that begins by guaranteeing
coverage for all children.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over the health care coverage has been the main
source of discord between the two on the campaign trail, and it was
the topic the two would return to again and again Friday night. In
most cases, it was Gore who took the rhetorical fight to Bradley,
challenging him to defend his ideas. Even when the voter question
was about putting a man on Mars, the conversation wound around to
health care. Gore said it is more important to get to universal
health insurance on Earth, first.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has yet to tell us who he'd leave out,'' Bradley
interjected.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one,'' Gore shot back.
</P>
<P>
   On Medicare, Gore said he would set aside 15 percent of the
federal budget surplus to shore up the health insurance program,
while accusing Bradley of offering no plan to prepare for the
increased number of future seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill does not set aside a penny for it; he said we can save
that for later,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, however, cited his 18 years of work on the Senate
Finance Committee, saying he had prevented Medicare premiums from
going up on numerous occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should doubt my commitment to making sure Medicare is
solvent,'' Bradley said, noting that the program is expected to be
whole until 2017.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't doubt your commitment, I doubt your plan,'' Gore
replied, then continued with another of his common criticisms of
Bradley's plan:
</P>
<P>
   ``You cancel Medicaid and give people a $150 voucher to replace
it,'' Gore charged, contending that people in New Hampshire would
find no private health plans for such a low sum.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley _ and later his aides _ disputed the $150 figure, saying
there would other sources of insurance available. The senator also
noted that his prediction about the risks of offering detailed
plans had come true. ``I've said. . .it was going to be like
throwing raw meat in a cage of wolves and they were going to chew
it up, and, you know, that's what's happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The constant back-and-forthing over Medicare for seniors and
Bradley's health plan for other Americans Friday night represented
the Democrats' contest to date in miniature. For months, the
candidates have been focused almost all their rhetorical cross-fire
on this one subject.
</P>
<P>
   But the pair also battled over school vouchers Friday night,
with Gore accusing Bradley of not yet offering a comprehensive
education proposal in his campaign, and of voting for private
school vouchers while in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he has offered numerous education proposals,
including one for early childhood education, and he said he voted
for vouchers while in the Senate only as an experiment. ``I do not
believe vouchers are the answer to the problems of public
education,'' Bradley said, adding that he never supported taking
money away from public schools to fund private school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   The touched on a number of other topics during the course of the
forum, in many cases underscoring more basic areas of agreement
than differences. Both said they are strong supporters of equal
rights for gays and lesbians, though both opposed legalization of
gay marriage. Both advocated new forms of gun control, though
Bradley was more specific on the topic. Both said they wished the
media would be more responsible about broadcasting images of sex
and violence. And both, responding to Ted Koppel's opening
question, said they think their wives are terrific and would be
activist First Ladies.
</P>
<P>
   Both were also asked whether they thought it appropriate for the
Republican candidates, at their recent Iowa debate, to underscore
their personal belief in God and Jesus Christ. Both said they had
no problem with the assertions by the GOP candidates, though
Bradley said he had decided he would not respond to such inquiries
about a private beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley have been locked in a dead heat in New
Hampshire for weeks, with Bradley's rise in the polls flattening
out and Gore's effort seeming to regain its footing with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the two campaigns had taken markedly different
tacks as they sold themselves to the voters. Gore, for example, has
delivered harsh critiques of Bradley's proposals. Bradley, on the
other hand, has remained largely silent in the face of the
onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   At their first town hall meeting at Dartmouth College, Gore
slammed Bradley for spending too much money on his health care
proposal, contending he would use up the budget surplus without
protecting Medicare, the federal health insurance program for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley blandly disagreed, saying, ``We each have our own
experts. I dispute the cost figure Al has used.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that moment, Gore has pounded Bradley relentlessly on the
subject. ``He's a good man with a bad plan,'' Gore has said, and
said again Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   After quietly taking the abuse, Bradley finally responded last
Sunday in Florida. He said it was ``dismaying'' for one Democrat to
attack another on Social Security, Medicare and Medicaid, which are
``articles of faith'' for members of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Bradley campaign issued a 24-page packet called
``Just the facts,'' explaining his health care plan and responding
to each ``Gore attack.'' The campaign also released a comparison of
Gore and Bradley's health proposals from its own experts,
contending that Gore only covers 7 million Americans, compared to
Bradley, who would provide insurance for 30 million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been clear in the last couple weeks that he's starting to
get aggressive with his approach,'' said John Rauh, one of
Bradley's top backers in the state..
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bradley told WSMN radio Friday, ``There's no question
that I'm going to correct misrepresentations and we'll get the
contrasts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
