<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2351 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CATHOLICS-ART-800(     12-17 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CATHOLICS-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT ARCHBISHOP SHOULD KEEP HELPING POOR, CATHOLICS SAY IN POLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Box explaining polling methodology at end.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT35 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO with MARJORIE CONNELLY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Cardinal John O'Connor prepares to step down as
archbishop, Roman Catholics in his New York archdiocese are hoping
for a successor who will be more spiritual than political, a
compassionate leader who will tackle poverty and homelessness as
priorities of the church, a survey by The New York Times has found.
</P>
<P>
   A strong majority of Catholics polled in the New York region
said things were going well or excellently for the church in
America. As Catholics do nationally, though, they favor modernizing
and opening up the church by allowing priests to marry, ordaining
women as priests and granting lay people a greater say in naming
bishops.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of an economic boom, Catholics in the financial
capital of the world's richest country told pollsters in several
ways that they consider poverty and homelessness the most serious
problems the church should address.
</P>
<P>
   The survey offered a snapshot of feelings among the New York
archdiocese's 2.4 million Catholics at a pivotal moment in the life
of their church. Church officials expect O'Connor, the leader of
the church in New York for the last 15 years, to step down soon.
</P>
<P>
   Though the cardinal, following tradition, offered Pope John Paul
II his resignation upon turning 75, the pope did not accept it. But
next month, the cardinal will turn 80, automatically losing his
vote in the papal conclave. He has also been battling ill health
recently, after surgery last summer to remove a brain tumor. For
the last two Sundays, he has not said Mass at St. Patrick's
Cathedral and has not appeared in public.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to questions about the next archbishop, the poll
asked Catholics about the cardinal, whose voice has been a
prominent one on some of the most debated issues of the day. But
among New York Catholics, O'Connor seemed to carry a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   While 57 percent had a favorable view of him, and just 6 percent
had an outright unfavorable opinion, only a small percentage could
name the best, or worst, things he has done as archbishop.
Spiritually, they say they are more influenced by Pope John Paul II
and by their local priests than they are by the cardinal. Forty-two
percent said his stands on social and political issues had no
influence on them at all.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, religious experts said, appear to reflect the
ambiguity inherent in the position of archbishop itself that even
O'Connor's political visibility has been unable to overcome. A
spokesman for the archdiocese questioned the usefulness of the poll
and declined to comment on the results.
</P>
<P>
   The findings also demonstrate the increasing independence of
Catholics, a trend that most experts on the church say began with
the changes of the Second Vatican Council in the 1960s and has
deepened throughout Pope John Paul II's return to a stricter, more
hierarchical tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Though the cardinal leads the archdiocese _ through his public
stands, management of finances and assignment of priests _ his
influence is not always direct or obvious. To most churchgoers,
archbishops are more distant figures than their parish priests and
yet not as exalted as the pope. Thirty-two percent of New York
Catholics said their priests had ``a lot'' of effect on their
spiritual lives, while 39 percent said the same of the pope. Only
16 percent said the same of O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really listen to what the archbishop says,'' said
Abraham Blanco, 74, a retired butcher in the Bronx who was
reinterviewed after responding to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Blanco said he paid more mind to the pope, whom he said he
admires for his extensive visits throughout the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Awn, a professor of comparative religion at Columbia
University, said the cardinal's role is more ``as a father figure
and the unifying symbol of the church in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed that Catholics were evenly divided over whether
the choice of the next archbishop would make a difference in the
life of the church. Asked for the most important qualities that the
next archbishop should have, Catholics most frequently said that
the next cardinal should be compassionate and humane, should help
the poor and homeless, show strong leadership and not be overtly
political. In addition, 8 percent of those polled said they hoped
for somebody similar to O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 37 percent of Catholics who offered an opinion on
O'Connor's best qualities as archbishop, the largest percentages,
25 percent, noted his work helping the poor and unifying the
church.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the most important problems facing the church, 59
percent had definite opinions. The most common response was
poverty, followed by the shortage of priests, abortion, declining
membership, and failure to keep up with the times and connect with
people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   More than half of New York's Catholics thought lay people should
have a say in selecting the next archbishop. The selection is a
thoroughly secret matter, which draws in only select churchgoers
sworn to silence, followed by discussions among bishops that result
in nominations being passed to Rome under papal secrecy. The final
decision rests solely with the pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should have input, but the final decision should be
with the pope,'' said Jasmine Thompson, a job recruiter in
Manhattan who responded to the poll. She said she hoped the next
cardinal would prove ``open as you can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thompson added, ``I understand that you still have to
support and defend the position of the Catholic Church, but I think
that in some cases there is room for flexibility and compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   But another participant, Aloysius Manz, 71, of Montgomery, a
retired manager at IBM, disagreed. ``What you'd get is a popularity
contest,'' he said. ``A lot of the decisions a cardinal has to make
are going to be unpopular with people, Catholics and others, but
when it's right, it's right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joseph W. Koterski, a philosophy professor at Fordham
University, said the support for giving lay people more of a say in
selecting bishops reflected the American enthusiasm for democracy.
``What people do know is that our country works well in a
democratic process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In applying statistical methods to understand faith _ which can
be amorphous and changeable _ the Times survey revealed an
intriguing mix of contradictions among believers and nonbelievers.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 percent of those who identified themselves as
practicing Catholics, for example, nevertheless said they consider
the church as an institution to be out of touch with the needs of
Catholics today. But they gauged specific people, like their local
priests, deacons, the cardinal and the pope, as more aware of their
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, a majority of practicing Catholics said they
seldom or never consult their priests about personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one in four people who identified themselves as former
Catholics said nevertheless that the pope had some or a lot of
influence on their spiritual lives.
</P>
<P>
   Of all Catholics polled, only 2 percent consider the sacraments
the most important aspect of being a Catholic. Far more important,
they said, were faith, the church teachings and belief in Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Thomas J. Reese, a Jesuit, said the survey's findings
illustrate that faith is complex and that the decision to go to
church springs from the spiritual quest for meaning, not from
feelings about a specific clergyman or even a teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not surprising that people recognize our limitations,''
said Reese, the author of the 1989 book, ``Archbishop: Inside the
Power Structure of the American Catholic Church.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``What's remarkable is that people still come. They're
seeing something that's deeper than the human reality, or the
person in the sanctuary.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll found practicing Catholics were much more inclined to
be opposed to extramarital sex than to homosexuality: 68 percent
said a person ``who engages in homosexual relations'' could still
be a good Catholic, while only 42 percent said a person ``who is
having an affair outside of marriage'' could be one.
</P>
<P>
   Through these and other answers, New York Catholics appeared
more accepting of homosexuality than church leaders are, and some
found fault with the cardinal for taking a public stand on the
issue. Elizabeth Gray, 45, of Monroe, said she generally liked the
cardinal but disagreed with his condemnation of gays' marching in
the St. Patrick's Day Parade. ``It was like him telling the gays
they're never going to see God, that they don't have a chance to go
to heaven,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Catholics generally consider the views of O'Connor
and other church leaders to be more conservative than their own.
For example, 57 percent favor allowing priests to marry, 48 percent
say they favor letting gays be priests if they remain celibate and
61 percent favor ordaining women as priests.
</P>
<P>
   But the survey found that Hispanics, who account for 36 percent
of Catholics in the archdiocese, tend to be more conservative than
other Catholics. They were, however, less supportive of O'Connor,
largely because they felt they did not know him. While two-thirds
of all Catholics in the archdiocese had a favorable view of the
cardinal, less than half of the Hispanic Catholics did did.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL BOX)
</P>
<P>
   POLLING METHODOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   The latest New York Times Poll is based on telephone interviews
conducted from Nov. 29 to Dec. 5 with 1,615 adults who live in the
Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York. Interviews were conducted
in English or Spanish. The archdiocese comprises Manhattan, the
Bronx and Staten Island and the counties of Dutchess, Orange,
Putnam, Rockland, Sullivan, Ulster and Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   Of these respondents, 567 said their religious preference was
Catholic, 198 said they were former Catholics, and 853 said they
were non-Catholics. For analysis, the responses of Catholics,
former Catholics and non-Catholics were separated.
</P>
<P>
   The sample of telephone exchanges called was selected by a
computer from a complete list of exchanges in the 10 counties. The
exchanges were chosen so as to assure that each county was
represented in proportion to its number of active phone numbers.
For each exchange, the final four numerals were formed by random
digits, thus permitting access to both listed and unlisted numbers.
Within each household, one adult was designated by a random
procedure to be the respondent for the survey.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been weighted to take account of household size
and number of telephone lines into the residence and to adjust for
variations in the sample relating to geographic area, race,
Hispanic origin, sex, age and education.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, in 19 cases out of 20 the results based on such
samples will differ by no more than 2 percentage points in either
direction from what would have been obtained by seeking out all
adults living in the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   For smaller subgroups, the potential sampling error is larger.
For example, it is plus or minus 4 percentage points for Catholics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
