<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO CASE IS SENT TO ALBANY, WHERE JURIES ARE FRIENDLIER TO
POLICE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Bronx will never be confused with Albany
County, a place where cornfields and deer are more common sights
than body shops, and their differences could have a profound effect
on the Amadou Diallo shooting case, sent here by an appellate court
order on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The court dropped the case into a place where the jury pool is
overwhelmingly white and inclined to accept the police version of
events. Albany County's prosecutors have one of the highest
conviction rates in the state, but in criminal cases against police
officers, the defendants usually walk free.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few similarities is that the city of Albany is roiled
on occasion by racial resentment, often aimed at the police. But
even those passions are different in quality and in kind from
tensions in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The black community is concentrated in a handful of tumbledown
neighborhoods in this city of 94,000 people. The county's white
majority is largely middle-class, lives mostly in quiet suburbs and
small towns and is largely oblivious to the hostility in minority
communities.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Appellate Division of State Supreme Court
granted a change of venue to the four white New York City officers
charged with murdering Diallo, an unarmed African immigrant, on
Feb. 4 in the the Bronx. The defense contends the officers thought
Diallo was armed, and only shot in the belief that he was reaching
for a gun. In seeking to move the case, the lawyers argued that the
shooting's intense publicity would prevent a fair hearing in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, when police officers here have been accused of
misconduct, they have been acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a defense lawyer, I don't think I could pick a
better spot than Albany County to present a case'' like the Diallo
case, said Terence L. Kindlon, a lawyer who has tried several
lawsuits against the police here. In one high-profile case, two
white Albany officers were acquitted in March of beating a
handcuffed black college student, Jermaine Henderson, in a police
station garage. Critics accused the district attorney of sabotaging
the prosecution by refusing to grant immunity to the student for a
fight that had led to his arrest. The student did not testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been very few convictions at trial of police
officers in Albany County in my 30 years of practicing law,'' said
the special prosecutor, John E. Dorfman, a lawyer in private
practice. ``Quite honestly, I can only recall one.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Wiest, chief assistant district attorney, agreed with
Kindlon that this is a place where people trust authority, a marked
contrast to the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, state police, when they were chasing someone, would
try to catch them in Albany County, because they were so sure of
the conviction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In one recent case, an Albany detective charged with stealing
cocaine from a drug arrest was acquitted of most charges and the
jury deadlocked on the last count. That charge was later
plea-bargained to a misdemeanor, and the detective served no prison
time. But when officers have not been the defendants, convictions
have been easier. Year after year, Albany County has one of the
state's highest conviction rates and the Bronx has one of the
lowest, according to state data. Many black people here say they
are treated callously by the police, a view that was reinforced by
the Henderson case and by the tactics the police used last month in
searching for a black man accused of wounding two officers. A large
police contingent swept through the mostly black Arbor Hill
neighborhood, and there were allegations that they roughed up some
residents. The suspect remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   Local black residents still refer angrily to the death of Jessie
Davis, a schizophrenic black man who was shot by officers in his
apartment here in 1984. The officers said he had menaced them with
a knife and a large meat fork, but his family insisted that he was
unarmed. A grand jury declined to indict the officers.
</P>
<P>
   While people in Albany tended to respond hazily when asked
Friday about the Diallo case, black residents knew all about it.
``Most people of color know about Diallo because it's such an
injustice,'' said Gloria Reese, 54, the black owner of a hair salon
in Arbor Hill.
</P>
<P>
   White people were more detached about the case. ``I don't think
it affects people one way or the other,'' said Lon Palatsky, 36, a
white computer technician who works for the state. ``New York City
is like another state _ we're far removed from them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
