<HEADER>
A2356 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEMS-DEBATE18-COX     12-17 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley, Gore civil in meeting that highlights candidates'
differences
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore and rival Bill Bradley
steered the high road Friday in a town hall meeting here, drawing
more contrasts between themselves and the Republican presidential
candidates than each other.
</P>
<P>
   Both men outlined plans for an activist government that would
seek to tackle and solve some of the nation's biggest problems,
such as providing health insurance to the 44 million uninsured and
providing for the safety of children in school.
</P>
<P>
   The 90 minute exchange between Gore and Bradley before New
Hampshire voters contrasted sharply with the sometimes testy
rhetoric that has characterized their back and forth over the past
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Senator Bradley,'' Gore said. ``As Democrats, we do
have an awful lot in common. We've been friends, former colleagues.
I think he's a good man. I think he's a good man with some bad
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley offered no such glowing endorsement of Gore, but he also
steered clear of negative attacks. He said his presidency would
provide a ``different style'' of leadership, one that offered bold
positions on complex problems.
</P>
<P>
   The town hall took place at Daniel Webster College before an
audience of 200 New Hampshire voters. It was broadcast live in New
Hampshire and rebroadcast nationally on ABC News's ``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC anchor Ted Koppel moderated the event, which featured Gore
and Bradley seated on stools in the center of an auditorium and
surrounded by the audience on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   Both men appeared relaxed throughout the event, only the second
town hall meeting of the campaign. The two will meet again Sunday
on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' in more of a debate format.
</P>
<P>
   They remained mostly civil toward one another, but engaged in
about 10 minutes of what Koppel called ``squabbling'' over their
respective health care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore noted that he planned to devote 15 percent of the budget
surplus to Medicare, the government insurance program for the
elderly. He challenged Bradley to say how he would ensure the
program's solvency. Bradley, insisting Medicare was secure until
2017, challenged Gore to explain who he would ``leave out'' of his
health care plan.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's health care plan aims to cover 95 percent of the
uninsured, while Gore has proposed a more graduated approach that
focuses first on insuring poor children.
</P>
<P>
   They also clashed over education, with Gore referring several
times to his $115 billion plan to pump new federal money into
pre-school education, teacher salary increases and special
education. Gore called the plan ``revolutionary'' and accused
Bradley of failing to address education.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley responded by ticking off the investments he would make:
doubling the size of Head Start, providing incentives to attract
teachers to disadvantaged areas, and new money for child care
centers.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley and Gore also agreed on a wide range of issues.
</P>
<P>
   They supported placing more counselors in schools to deal with
teen violence, strong gun control and greater restraint from media
companies who broadcast violent and sexually explicit programs.
</P>
<P>
   They each declined to commit to a specific date when the United
States should seek to land an astronaut on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   They also agreed on enacting a patients bill of rights to put
doctors in charge of health care decisions. And each claimed he had
the experience to enact such legislation in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gore cited his 16 years in Congress and asserted that he had
``excellent relations'' with the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley cited his 18 years in the Senate and pointed to his
stewardship of the 1986 Tax Reform Act, which eliminated loopholes
and lowered rates, as proof that he could negotiate big legislation
through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the questions elicited strong differences between the
two men and the field of Republicans seeking the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question about Jesus Christ, Bradley asserted
that religion was a private matter and he had made a decision not
to discuss his religious views. Gore said he strongly supported the
separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The responses were in marked contrast to a similar question that
was posed of the Republican candidates at a forum in Iowa last
week, during which each affirmed his personal faith in Christ.
</P>
<P>
   The campus here in this southern New Hampshire town resembled a
giant campaign rally for both candidates. Legions of supporters for
the two men paraded around the grounds in frosty temperatures
chanting their candidate's name.
</P>
<P>
   As he has done at previous appearances with Bradley, Gore also
littered the grounds with Gore 2000 posters, even encouraging some
of the surrounding homes to put up flashing, white holiday lights
spelling out ``Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also attempted to generate some bad news for Bradley,
flying Sen. Frank Lautenberg (D-N.J.) in to watch the debate and
publicizing the senator's endorsement of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg, who served with Bradley 14 years, endorsed Gore
before Bradley became a candidate, but he said if he had known his
former colleague was going to jump in the race he still would have
endorsed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I frankly think Al Gore has experience that is unmatchable,''
Lautenberg said before the meeting began.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hauser, Bradley's spokesman, dismissed the endorsement as
``old news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another example of taking credit for something that's
already happened,'' Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also imported a few supporters, including former White
House special counsel Archibald Cox, who investigated Watergate,
and Harvard scholar Cornell West.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
