</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-HOSTAGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAIL STANDOFF A PRODUCT OF CUBAN DETAINEES' LEGAL LIMBO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. MARTINVILLE, La. _ Eight years have passed since the last
desperate cry from Cubans held indefinitely in U.S. detention
facilities as undesirables.
</P>
<P>
   But the message, this time from a handful of Cubans holding
hostages in a small parish jail, is much the same _ they want
release from an immigration limbo that without a shift in
U.S.-Cuban relations, they may never escape.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the pleas carried a seething urgency. In Oakdale, La.,
water jets could not check 1,000 Cubans who rioted, took 28
hostages and burned down four prison buildings. And the same year,
1,400 Cubans killed a guard at an Atlanta prison and took 89
hostages. In 1991, Cubans held 10 hostages in Talladega, Ala., and
pledged death or freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Cubans at Oakdale and Atlanta who were granted review
hearings by immigration officials, the Cubans at St. Martinville
have had their hearings and lost.
</P>
<P>
   Their fate is simple, because of crimes they have committed in
the United States. Either Cuba will take them back, which is
unlikely because no deportation agreement exists between the
countries, or they will remain behind bars, indefinitely, awaiting
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Their demand, since taking hostage two deputies and the warden
Monday, has been for freedom. They will go anywhere, they said.
</P>
<P>
   But overnight Thursday, two hostage-takers surrendered and one
deputy was released. By late Friday, other inmates in the jail and
all of the facility except the warden's office were back in police
control.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said six hostage-takers remained and were holding
Warden Todd Louvierre and Deputy Jolie Sonnier along with five
inmates, all women, in the warden's office. No injuries have been
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage-takers at St. Martinville are among 2,400 Cubans who
have lost their temporary residency status in the United States
because they were convicted of crimes. Of the 2,400, 1,750 were
among an estimated 125,000 Cubans who came to the United States in
the 1980 Mariel boat lift, the mass emigration from Cuba allowed by
President Fidel Castro that was found to include convicts and some
mental patients. Most of the Marielitos settled into their newfound
freedom without incident and joined American society. The same
cannot be said of the 2,400 Cubans still in detention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority probably have, for the most part, been
involved in criminal activity here in the United States almost
since they day they arrived, and because of that they're prohibited
from naturalization,'' said Russ Bergeron, U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the law these people are deportable,'' Bergeron said.
``This isn't some arbitrary decision made by the INS. The reason
they're not being deported is because Castro won't take them and no
one else will have them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said most of the current Cuban detainees were granted
humanitarian parole after their arrival and released from INS
custody. But their criminal convictions stripped them of their
legal residency status and ended their chances of becoming
naturalized citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of Cuban detainees have contended, however, that
keeping Cubans behind bars indefinitely is inhumane and deprives
them of their human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Leshaw, an Atlanta attorney credited with getting Cubans at
the Atlanta prison to accept a compromise that ended that standoff,
said incidents like those at St. Martinville continue to erupt
because of immigration laws that leave the government with only two
options in dealing with undesirable immigrants: deportation or
detention if deportation is not possible.
</P>
<P>
   He said many of the Cubans in jails have served their sentences
for their criminal convictions but remain in prison because the
government does not know what to do with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who are, for legal purposes, not here. And
because they are not here, they don't have any rights. That's the
course the government has followed,'' Leshaw said. ``That's the
flaw in the policy: (The INS says), `You don't have any rights;
that's just too bad.'''
</P>
<P>
   The end result, he said, is that the Cubans ``just kind of sit
indefinitely'' in prisons. And because the Cubans have no
constituency, they are left to languish in prison cells until they
take action to force the issue.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Cubans, out of frustration, take desperate measures.
Taking hostages is the only way they can get their cause heard.
</P>
<P>
   Leshaw described their state of mind this way, ``Can you skin
the hide of a man who has already been skinned?''
</P>
<P>
   But even Leshaw concedes the Cubans have little of hope being
released. In the 1980s, thousands of Cubans were being held
awaiting immigration hearings to determine their residency status.
The same cannot be said 20 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Every Cuban currently in jails has had his case reviewed. A
major point in reaching the compromise that resulted in the release
of the hostages at Oakdale and Atlanta was an assurance that every
Cuban in detention would receive a review hearing. Of the estimated
3,800 Cubans in detention in 1987, more than 2,000 were eventually
released.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, he said, all legal remedies for the remaining
Cubans have been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   The 1987 riots also changed the way the INS detained Cubans. The
1,000 Cubans held at Oakdale, out of necessity because of the fire,
were scattered to prisons elsewhere, as were the 1,400 at Atlanta.
In an effort to minimize security and safety problems, the INS no
longer holds Cuban detainees in large concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Mariel boat lift and before the 1987 riots, the United
States had succeeded in persuading Cuban President Fidel Castro to
take back 2,746 Cubans considered undesirable by the United States.
In 1985, after agreeing to take back 201 more Cubans, Castro
withdrew from the agreement as a protest of Radio Marti, a U.S.
government-supported radio station with anti-Castro programming.
Castro later agreed to accept 2,500 Cuban detainees, which led to
the 1987 riots.
</P>
<P>
   Since the boat lift, Bergeron said, the INS has released more
than 6,000 Mariel Cubans with criminal background. He said the INS
will release Cubans convicted of crimes in the United States if
they demonstrate that they will not pose a public threat if freed.
</P>
<P>
   He counters the argument that detainees are being denied their
human rights by saying that the victims of crimes also have rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advocacy without responsibility rings hollow,'' he said.
``Those who would call for the release of these people do not have
to face the next rape victim, look into her eyes and explain why
this person was released. We do.''
</P>
<P>
   After holding the parish jail warden and two guards hostage for
three days, the Cuban detainees requested that the media be part of
the negotiations and allowed their captives to speak to their
neighbors through a public address system.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of supporters recently started holding a vigil across
from the courthouse, but most in town just drive by slowly to crane
their necks at the commotion.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Melancon, 65, found himself sympathetic to the Cuban
cause, but with caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they ought give them back their freedom,'' he said as
he stood behind the storefront window of an auto parts and hardware
store. ``Not here, but somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
