<SLUG> BC-EDS-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-EDS EMPLOYEES ACCUSED OF FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Del., Mass., Texas)  (mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine former employees of Electronic Data Systems Corp. were
arrested Friday and charged with conspiring to defraud the states
of New York, Delaware and Massachusetts of $37.9 million in cash
and other assets that had been abandoned by customers of brokerage
houses.
</P>
<P>
   A complaint unsealed in Manhattan said the nine employees of the
Texas-based computer services and data processing company had
worked in a New York division of EDS that specialized in helping
clients recover money that had been turned over, or escheated, to
states as abandoned property.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, banks and brokerage firms must turn over the
assets of dormant accounts to states after a specified number of
years. If the owners are later identified and found, the money may
be reclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   In return for assisting companies in that process, the EDS unit,
called the Asset Research and Recovery division, received 30
percent of any recoveries that it made.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White said in the complaint filed in
U.S. District Court in Manhattan that from 1995 until early this
year, the chief of the asset recovery unit, Victor Lugo, and eight
other employees had submitted fraudulent claims on behalf of
brokerage houses that had hired EDS to recover such assets.
</P>
<P>
   For example, prosecutors said, EDS had obtained through bogus
filings $16 million that had been turned over to Delaware by
Kidder, Peabody &AMP; Co., a subsidiary of General Electric. EDS
received about 30 percent of the total, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the employees made fraudulent claims for $15
million on behalf of Cigna Investments Inc., the complaint said. To
date, New York has paid back about $3.8 million, with EDS receiving
about $1.1 million in fees. A spokesman for Cigna did not return a
call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Massachusetts, the complaint charged that the EDS
employees obtained $6.9 million through fraudulent means _ with
about 30 percent going to EDS _ on behalf of General Electric
Investment Corp., also a subsidiary of GE.
</P>
<P>
   A GE official said that the company was cooperating with the
authorities in both cases involving its units. All nine employees
have been fired or disciplined or have resigned, EDS said. James
Daley, EDS' chief financial officer, said in a phone interview that
EDS, which is based in Plano, Texas, had agreed to repay the money
that had been fraudulently obtained. ``The amounts in the aggregate
are not material to EDS' operations or financial position,'' the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint says that EDS detected the fraud after its
auditors uncovered a ``variety of unlawful conduct'' at Global
Financial Markets Group, an EDS office in New York of which the
assets recovery division is a part.
</P>
<P>
   The illegal conduct included expense account fraud, kickbacks
from vendors and accounting irregularities ``that enriched various
employees'' at the expense of EDS, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   Further investigation by EDS uncovered the fraud scheme, the
complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found it,'' Daley said. ``We turned it over.'' He said the
company's intention was ``to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaint accuses one of the defendants, Lugo, 54, of Coram,
N.Y., of directing the unit to ``create bogus documents and take
other improper steps to convince states that various escheated
funds belonged to clients of EDS when, in truth and in fact, the
funds did not.'' Lugo ``directed other EDS employees to cut
information from certain documents, paste it into other documents,
and photocopy the resulting documents to conceal the alterations,''
said the 11-page complaint, which was signed by an FBI agent,
Kathleen Diskin.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Lugo, James Sherwood, said that his client will
enter a not-guilty plea, and ``intends to contest the charges
vigorously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
