<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC PUZZLED AFTER POOR EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's 10 games into the season, but there's
probably less answers today than a month ago about the USC
basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   At least four weeks ago, USC earned a measure of respect by
playing hard in its loss to North Carolina at the Maui
Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   But after losing to Long Beach State 76-66 on Thursday night at
the Pyramid, the Trojans (5-5) seemed completely befuddled over
their performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we didn't want to win,'' USC coach Henry Bibby said.
``You think you can come in and just show up. I don't have any
excuses for this. It was incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Some USC players, notably starters Jeff Trepagnier and David
Bluthenthal, were bothered by the flu this week, but it was hardly
enough to explain the listless way the Trojans played in the second
half, when they shot 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed this game. We couldn't afford to lose this one,''
forward Sam Clancy said. ``We shouldn't have lost this one. They
just wanted it more than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more troubling than a single loss, the game demonstrated
how ineffective the Trojans are when one of their top players
struggles. Forward Brian Scalabrine, who averages nearly 17 points
per game, scored only four against Long Beach and fouled out after
27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   He also had six turnovers, and has a team-high 43 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole night he was in foul trouble and in and out of the
game,'' Clancy said. ``I think it threw him off his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem area is free throws. USC made 15 of 24 attempts
and was 11 of 19 in the second half. The Trojans are shooting just
63 percent on free throws this season.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Scalabrine contributing and its free-throw misery,
USC was only down 68-66 to the 49ers with 1:36 remaining. But the
Trojans failed to score the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a loss and you've got to evaluate why we didn't play,''
Bibby said. ``That's the difference. It's more what we did than
what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was also a setback for USC's bench, which Bibby almost
ignored. Center Kostas Charissis and point guards Rashad Jones and
Sandy Fletcher all played one minute. Only freshman shooting guard
Nate Hair, who replaced Scalabrine, saw significant minutes (13).
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Clancy had his fourth double-double of the year, with 19
points and 11 rebounds against Long Beach State. Bluthenthal had
career highs in minutes (40) and points (19) in the contest.
Trepagnier had three steals to move into third place on USC's
all-time steals list with 116.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 2227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
