A2363 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN     12-17 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA: OLD DEMONS TO BLUE DEMONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Add Gonzaga to an infamous list that includes
Kansas, Stanford, North Carolina and Duke _ teams that have
humiliated UCLA during the Steve Lavin tenure.
</P>
<P>
   While the Bruins haven't learned to consistently attack a zone
defense under Lavin, they have shown remarkable resiliency _ or
very short memories _ following embarrassing defeats.
</P>
<P>
   That's the challenge again today, when the Bruins face No. 19
DePaul at Pauley Pavilion a week after their pathetic performance
against Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to flush that loss and get ready for DePaul,''
forward Rico Hines said. ``Nobody has dwelled on it. That's a sign
of a mature team.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavin's approach this week was no different than after other bad
losses. Time and again, he urged the Bruins to keep perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them the season's a marathon, not a sprint,'' he said.
``I think it'd be a mistake to overreact to Gonzaga. I think it'd
be a mistake to suddenly think this is a terrible team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush update: His exams completed, suspended forward JaRon Rush
went home for the holidays Friday. He'll spend at least the next
week in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sooner he gets legal counsel and takes care of business,
the better for him,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Rush probably will return to practice following Christmas,
although an exact date has not been determined. School officials
said the move doesn't necessarily indicate Rush will be cleared of
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Athletic director) Pete (Dalis) thought it was a logical
process,'' UCLA media relations director Marc Dellins said. ``(Rush
would) take care of school, be home for Christmas, and when he
returns, they'd discuss the possibility of practicing again.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes update: Forward Matt Barnes, academically ineligible for
the fall quarter, must pass four classes for reinstatement. His
last exam was Friday, and grades have to be posted before he's
cleared. That could happen by tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten two grades, and they were good,'' Barnes said. ``I
talked to the (teaching assistant) of the test I took (Friday), and
she said she'd e-mail it by 1. I'm shooting to play. The teachers
are going out of their way to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins depart Sunday for a three-game tournament in Hawaii.
If the situation is resolved Monday, Barnes probably will hop a
plane and join the Bruins for their first game, Tuesday against
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Roster update: Desperate for big men, the Bruins have added
Brandon Brooks, a 6-foot-6, 225-pound freshman who's the starting
goalie on UCLA's NCAA championship water polo team. A Honolulu
native, he was Hawaii's Mr. Basketball last year.
</P>
<P>
   Starting center Dan Gadzuric practiced sparingly this week
because of the flu. He'll play today but probably won't be at full
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve forward Sean Farnham strained a ligament in his left
knee Tuesday. An MRI exam was negative, and he's expected to play.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve guard Ryan Bailey, who missed the Gonzaga game with
tendinitis in his foot, will play.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Earl Watson and forward Rico Hines were involved in a
minor car accident Thursday night. Neither was hurt seriously, and
they practiced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   DePaul update: The Blue Demons will have super sophomore forward
Lance Williams available today for the first time this season.
Williams, who averaged 14 points and eight rebounds last year,
broke his foot Oct. 17 but returned to practice this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned about his weight,'' DePaul coach Pat Kennedy
said. ``He's lost 8-10 pounds. But he may get some minutes against
UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire sale: UCLA will hold its bi-annual apparel sale today at 1
p.m. on the east side of Pauley Pavilion. Sweats, game uniforms and
practice jerseys are some of the items available on a first-come,
first-serve basis.
</P>
</TEXT>
