<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FB-KATY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Attention: Fort Worth Star Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   Katy happy for chance to play
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By BRIAN McTAGGART &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Katy will take the field today at the Astrodome, which should at
least provide the Tigers with some sort of moral victory heading
into the Class 5A Division II championship game.
</P>
<P>
   It was one year ago today the Tigers had their hearts ripped out
when they learned a little more than 24 hours before kickoff that
they would have to forfeit their spot in the Division I title game
for using an ineligible player.
</P>
<P>
   All season long, Katy players and coaches have talked about
nothing else except wanting a chance to redeem themselves with
another shot at a state championship. The Tigers (14-1) will get it
against upset-minded Garland (14-1) at 12:07 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about it a lot,'' Katy senior center Brian Mosley
said. ``What happened last year was real bad, but we wanted to get
back for those seniors from last year. But this is also for us,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland, which has won 14 in a row, including upsets of
perennial state powers Austin Westlake, Plano East and South Grand
Prairie the last three weeks, will be making its first state-title
game appearance since winning back-to-back titles in 1963-64.
</P>
<P>
   Katy, meanwhile, won the Division I state title in 1997 after
losing in the Division I final in 1994 and winning the Class A
championship in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel confident from the point that a bunch of us guys have
been here before and we know what to expect, and Garland really
hasn't,'' Tigers junior quarterback Jared Kaspar said.
</P>
<P>
   Led by tailback Keith Mills (36 catches, 616 yards) and fullback
Donte Hart (1,879 yards rushing, 31 touchdowns), the Owls have
relied on their wing-T running formation to average 373.8 yards and
35.1 points per game. Garland amasses 281.3 yards per game on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Hart has the Garland ISD record for rushing yards in a season,
breaking Bobby Boyd's 44-year-old record. He has 413 yards rushing
the last two weeks. Hart has almost as many touchdowns during the
playoffs (13) as he did in the regular season (18).
</P>
<P>
   ``They will go to him when they have to have him,'' Johnston
said. ``He's got some wheels and runs with great lean and uses his
shoulders well.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Owls have allowed 219.2 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt they're a solid outfit,'' Katy coach Mike
Johnston said. ``Watching them on video they remind me of the
Temple teams in the '70s. I've never seen a precision wing-T
offense like Temple with (coach) Bob McQueen. But Garland has a lot
of that same look.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston compared Garland's offensive line to Katy's massive
bunch from two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line up there creates a new line of scrimmage every time
the ball is snapped,'' he said. ``Our defensive front seven will
certainly get challenged. It's going to be a physical game. I think
you're going to see chin straps, snaps, buckles and jaw pads all
over the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers, who come in averaging 348.6 yards and 31.7 points
per game with their ball-control offense, have struggled in first
half in recent weeks due to nerves.
</P>
<P>
   But Katy has managed to shine in the second half, partly because
of a defense that has produced a plus-15 turnover ratio.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the determination of trying to erase last year's
bitter disappointment, the Tigers have other intangibles pointing
in their favor. This will be Katy's 16th playoff game in the last
three years and it will be in the Astrodome, where it has played
numerous times in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having them come to Houston is going to put them a little but
out of synch and hopefully these things will work to our
advantage,'' Johnston said. ``The way all these things have
evolved, I feel real good about our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   And a chance is all the Tigers wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited more than confident,'' said Katy senior safety
Robby McDaniel, who will start his 46th consecutive game. ``We've
waited so long for it to be our senior year. We've gone through all
the bumps and bruises and sweat and blood and tears. So we figure
it's our turn and we're going to give it all we've got.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
