<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Saturday, Dec. 18. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
EXPLOSIVES-ARIZ _ Federal agents searched a remote mining camp
southwest of Flagstaff on Friday, looking for clues to the theft of
nearly 1,000 pounds of explosives and questioning workers with
access to the locked area where the missing materials were stored.
Authorities said 750 pounds of fuel-soaked ammonium nitrate, 250
pounds of dynamite; 6,000 feet of detonation cord and about 20
blasting caps were stolen after 5 p.m. Monday from the 3 Wins
Mining Co. camp near the tiny community of Drake. The materials all
are commonly used in mining, authorities said, but they also can be
used to make a bomb. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GIRL-RESCUE _ When a thief drove off and then ditched a
sport-utility vehicle with Clarissa Quihuis still inside, destiny
called. And the 5-year-old answered. Clarissa picked up her
mother's cell phone when it rang and calmly gave detectives details
about where she was _ right down to the street numbers on nearby
houses. She also followed the advice to keep honking the horn,
which helped bring Friday's harrowing ride from Tempe to Phoenix to
a quick, happy end. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
GM-VERDICT _ A Maricopa County jury ordered General Motors to pay
$14.2 million to the family of a Scottsdale woman who was run over
when her GM pickup truck lurched into reverse. The jury found the
automobile giant negligent and said it should have warned drivers
of the potential transmission problem it reportedly knew about
since the late 1960s _ decades before Ruth Golonka, 67, was killed.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUPREMACIST _ A member of Gilbert's ``Devil Dogs'' White
supremacist gang had some powerful people standing up for him
before he was sentenced in the gang beating of strangers who were
taunted with shouts of ``White power.'' The town's former mayor
sent the judge a letter to vouch for Glenn Cribbin's character, and
a high school athletic director testified in an attempt to spare
his former wrestling star from jail. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
