<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2366 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-BOMB-ARREST-1STLD-WRI     12-17 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-ARREST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN STOPPED AT U.S.-CANADA BORDER, SUSPECTED OF TRANSPORTING BOMB
MATERIALS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Canada)   (SUBS lede to add attribution `officials said' and change
`explosives' to `bomb-making materials'; 4th graf to delete
`Canadian' and `papers'; 7th graf to add new 1st sentence
describing Ressam in court, add `carrying false identification' to
charges in 2nd sentence, and adds 2 new sentences on court
proceedings; adds 340 wds to end of original text with background
info.) 
(js) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK with TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A man who officials said brought a car with a trunk
full of bomb-making materials on a ferry from Canada, and then led
customs officials on a foot chase through the streets of a
Washington port town, was arrested by federal authorities, who said
Friday that his target, his motives and his background remained a
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who had more than 150 pounds of bomb-making chemicals
and detonator components in the car, was detained Tuesday just
after driving off a ferry from Victoria, British Columbia, in Port
Angeles, Wash. He had a reservation for a downtown Seattle motel
Tuesday night and also had reserved tickets to fly Wednesday from
Seattle to New York and to connect from there to a London-bound
flight, federal authorities said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and the CIA are investigating the incident, a government
official said Friday. How and when the man planned to use the
materials in his car are just two of the numerous questions
surrounding the incident. Although, as one government official said
Friday: ``There's nothing mysterious at all about what was in that
car. It was stuff for a bomb, a powerful bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said the man's actions, use of fake
identification and background fueled suspicions that he could be
part of an international terrorist network.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they believe the man is Algerian, is 28 years
old and that his name is Ahmed Ressam. They say he arrived in Los
Angeles on Feb. 7 on a flight from Seoul, South Korea, and that he
was next seen in Vancouver, British Columbia, in October. They said
his passport, which listed his name as Benni Noris and gave his age
as 28, was false. The officials also believe that both of the
Canadian driver's licenses, bearing his picture, that he was
carrying were falsely obtained. One was under the name of Benni
Antoine Noris
</P>
<P>
   The suspect was carrying maps of Washington, Oregon and
California in the car with him, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 4 p.m. Friday, a slight man with short black hair
dressed in a blue button-down shirt, black pants and jail booties
was led into a federal courtroom here. In court papers federal
prosecutors indicated that he would be charged, under the name of
Ahmed Ressam, with illegally transporting explosive material into
the country, making false statements on his customs forms and
carrying false indentification. A court interpreter spoke to him in
Arabic, and an arraignment was scheduled for Wednesday. Ressam, who
officials said also spoke French, did not speak, and the two public
defenders who appeared with him did not speak to reporters
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest comes after a recent State Department warning that it
had received ``credible information'' about plans for terrorist
attacks against U.S. citizens around the time of the Jan. 1
millennium celebration. The department's ``worldwide terrorism
warning'' advised Americans to stay away from ``large gatherings
and celebrations'' throughout the world for the rest of this year,
but it did not specify any groups planning attacks or state where
such attacks might occur.
</P>
<P>
   Two federal officials in Washington said Friday that the CIA had
been called in on the case. One of them said the intelligence
service was asked to join the case because of suspicions that the
man may be tied to terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The incident in Washington state began on Tuesday when the man
drove off the ferry from Victoria, said Pat Jones, a spokesman for
the Customs Service. An inspector started asking him routine
questions and, noting that he appeared very nervous, she soon asked
him to step out of the car.
</P>
<P>
   The man initially refused, Jones said, causing the inspector to
call for back-up. The man then got out of his car and ran away,
stopping in a brief and unsuccessful effort to commandeer a passing
car, then, a few blocks later, to hide under a truck. He was caught
about six blocks from the Port Angeles ferry terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Several plastic garbage bags containing more than 130 pounds of
two kinds of powder, later identified by the Washington state
police crime laboratory as urea and sulfate, as well as two jars of
a yellowish liquid found to be nitroglycerine, were found in the
trunk of the car, in the spare tire compartment.
</P>
<P>
   The car also contained four black boxes, each with a circuit
board connected to a Casio watch and a 9-volt battery, apparently
to be used as timing devices, a government official said.
</P>
<P>
   Urea and nitroglycerine were two of the main ingredients in the
bombing of the World Trade Center in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Urea is a chemical sold for melting ice and is used in
fertilizer. It takes more technical skill to make it into a bomb
than was employed by the two Americans who killed 168 people in
Oklahoma City in 1995 with a huge but crude bomb made of fuel oil
and fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   The World Trade Center bomb, organized by Islamic radicals, was
built with a main charge of urea nitrate _ a combination of 1,200
pounds of urea and about 105 gallons of nitric acid, a chemical
widely used in industrial etching _ and a booster made of
nitroglycerine.
</P>
<P>
   The motel where Ressam made a reservation is a few blocks from
the Seattle Center, a complex of public buildings, including the
Space Needle, that is to be the site of New Year's Eve
celebrations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
