r s BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     12-17 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING LINK FOR THE DALLAS STARS IS `YEAR-RAY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's funny how these things work out. Like with the case of a
local Big Four team, which just happens to be the one wearing shiny
new world championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   Such jewelry has become scarce around here, so the process of
elimination quickly identifies our subject matter as the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   There was a long list of prominent heroes involved in last
season's thrilling Stanley Cup capture. These names, of course,
would include Modano, Hull, Nieuwendyk, Belfour, Hatcher, Zubov,
Carbonneau, Keane, Langenbrunner, Matvichuk ... Big-time guys, one
and all. Big-time in North Texas. Big-time across the NHL
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't it interesting that as soon as things get upside-down
this season, that as the stars of the Stars try to overcome a
disease known as Cup-itis, the rallying cry currently centers on
one name and one name only.
</P>
<P>
   ``Year-ray.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When his injury happened,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said of winger
Jere Lehtinen's broken ankle, ``there was this total negative cloud
over our team. Everybody was running around, asking, ``What are we
gonna do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``But now his absence has gone the other way. The positive
impact has become what kind of big boost we'll have when Jere is
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Hitchcock is counting or anything, but when asked
exactly how long Lehtinen has been missing, he answered quickly _
``eight weeks today.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Lehtinen, the Stars have struggled with many of the
intangibles _ intensity, motivation, and the most disappointing,
work ethic. Not that Lehtinen would have solved all that, but a few
more goals from Jere's No. 1 linemates, Brett Hull and Mike Modano,
might have made things smoother in the first three months of the
NHL season.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Hull and particularly Modano, are different
players without Lehtinen's contributions. ``Different'' in a
negative way.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Lehtinen's presence has not exactly gone unnoticed in
the past. He is, after all, a two-time winner of the NHL's Selke
Trophy, which Stars announcer Daryl Reaugh believes is a much
higher standard than just best defensive forward in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of the top goalie,'' said Reaugh, himself a former NHL
goalie, ``the Selke winner is usually the overall best player.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up another point. Does Lehtinen's absence, combined
with the troubles of the Stars, allow us to once-and-for-all finger
the Stars' team MVP? And his name is ``Year-ray.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't just think Lehtinen is the best player on the Stars,''
Reaugh said. ``He's the best player in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   A very strong compliment, and one that Hitchcock hedges on.
``Comparisons like that are difficult, almost impossible,'' he
said. ``How does Jere stack up against a \RJaromir\S Jagr, for
instance? It's two totally different types of talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for our style of play as a team, meaning everything we
want to do at both ends of the ice, Jere is the perfect fit _ very,
very valuable. Jere is a sweeper on the ice ... he sweeps up our
mistakes, which prevents goals, and he sweeps up the other team's
mistakes, which creates goals.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there's also Modano, who has never
hesitated over the years to tell the world how much Lehtinen's
presence means to his game. But in Jere's absence, the media, the
fans, and even Hitchcock, are constantly telling Modano his game
has not been dominant.
</P>
<P>
   But give it a week, and will that change when a certain missing
piece returns? Hitchcock could have gambled on Lehtinen's ankle
being healed, and pushed his return to action for this current road
trip, which ends Thursday night in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But a week ago, there was a setback as pain in the right ankle
intensified when Lehtinen stepped up his workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I think it's important that we get it exactly right before
Jere comes back,'' said Hitchcock, who obviously wants that return
to be a team motivational tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been frustration for the players, for me, for the
fans, for everybody,'' Hitchcock said. ``But you can see it turning
back around now. We are not the best team in the National Hockey
League by any means, but we are a team on the improve.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, in a direct reference to Lehtinen, he added, ``We have
got it on the upswing again, and we also have a big horse coming
back. In the long run, I like our chances to be even better than we
were last season.''
</P>
<P>
   A tall order, no doubt. And even a doubtful opinion at the
moment. But the rallying cry is now, ``Year-ray.''
</P>
<P>
   Give it a week, and we'll see.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
