r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-INJURIES-     12-17 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-INJURIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' INJURY SITUATION IMPROVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ According to the NFL calender, the playoffs
don't start for another four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   However, the postseason urgency began in earnest last weekend
for the Cowboys (7-6), who are approaching all of their remaining
games as must-win affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The victory against the Philadelphia Eagles was just the first
round in the Cowboys' odyssey to reach the playoffs. Tomorrow's
clash with the New York Jets (5-8) at Texas Stadium is Round 2 of
four. If the Cowboys win their final three games, they are
guaranteed a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the Cowboys got a boost when running back Emmitt
Smith (strained groin), guard Larry Allen (sprained knee) and
center Mark Stepnoski (strained calf) were able to practice for the
first time this week.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said the status of all three players
will likely come down to game-day decisions, but said that he was
``very encouraged'' about their availability for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer took it a step further with Smith,
saying, ``He's done a little more every day,'' and ``Everything is
pointing toward him playing.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt that the presence of Smith, the NFL's third
all-time leading rusher, and two perennial Pro Bowl linemen in
Allen and Stepnoski are soothing.
</P>
<P>
   Also calming for the Cowboys during this pressure-filled time
are the comforts of home _ Texas Stadium, where they are unbeaten
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Darren Woodson said it's why the Cowboys head into the
Jets game confident of winning back-to-back games for the first
time since starting the season 3-0 and optimistic about their
chances of finish the season on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely feels good to have a couple of more home
games,'' Woodson said. ``We've played well here. It's actually been
like that for the past couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets game is the second of two in a row at home for the
Cowboys, whose 20-10 victory Sunday against the Eagles extended
their regular-season home winning streak to eight games, including
a 6-0 mark in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will play two of their final three at home. They
travel to New Orleans on Dec. 24 before concluding the regular
season at Texas Stadium against the Giants on Jan. 2. Their
victories at Texas Stadium this season have been by a combined
score of 164-57.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't even ask me what the difference is because I don't know
why we play so differently at home and on the road,'' Gailey said.
``I know at home, being with family and not traveling impacts the
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the Texas Stadium crowd, which has not traditionally
offered the Cowboys the same type of rowdy home-field advantage as
other venues across the league, has been a big key for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been more involved as of late,'' Gailey said. ``They
weren't as loud last year. That's a difference for us. It's almost
like they feel we need their help, whereas in the past the Cowboys
might have been so good that they just came to be entertained. They
are a part of it now. That's what I'm seeing and feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Cowboys know, considering their woeful 1-6 mark on the
road, is that their home prowess is the main reason they are still
in the playoff hunt. It's also what they are counting on to get
them over the hump on the road and ultimately into the playoffs.
The Cowboys are looking to go undefeated at home for the first time
since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson admits the Cowboys' contrasting play at home and on the
road parallels] their inconsistent play all season. He said the key
for the Cowboys is first beating the Jets. He then hopes the team
can take the confidence they gained from a two-game winning streak
into the Christmas Eve battle with the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about building momentum and gaining confidence,''
Woodson said. ``We feel good about the Jets game because it's at
home. If we can win this game and take that into New Orleans and
then come home and play at the season against the Giants. That's
what we've got to do. It all starts with winning.''
</P>
<P>
   At home. Briefly Deion Sanders continues to be slowed by
flu-like symptoms. However, he did practice yesterday and is slated
to play three positions against the Jets _ wide receiver,
cornerback and punt returner. Chan Gailey said he is thankful
Sanders didn't come down with the flu later in the week, because he
might not have been able to play against the Jets at all. Gailey
also remains fearful that more players might contract the illness
before tomorrow's game], considering that it has gone ``around the
locker room'' through several players in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys receiver Ernie Mills (strained quadriceps) has been
ruled out of Sunday's game. He will be replaced by former TCU
standout Jason Tucker, who will be making his second career start.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
