<HEADLINE>
AFTER NINTH DELAY, NASA TO TRY AGAIN WITH SHUTTLE LAUNCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Foul weather thwarted efforts to launch
the shuttle Discovery late Friday on a mission to repair the Hubble
Space Telescope, leaving NASA few opportunities to begin the
much-delayed flight before year's end.
</P>
<P>
   If Discovery does not lift off Saturday, or perhaps Sunday, the
mission to restore the telescope's pointing system will be reset
for mid-January. Forecasters promised only a slight improvement in
weather conditions for Saturday's attempt at 8:21 p.m. EST. NASA's
associate administrator for spaceflight, Joe Rothenberg, said late
Friday there was a possibility of a Sunday attempt, but no decision
had been made.
</P>
<P>
   Though the targeted liftoff date has shifted nine times during
the past two months, Friday's was the first in which astronauts
Curt Brown, Scott Kelly, Jean Francois Clervoy, Steve Smith, Mike
Foale, John Grunsfeld and Claude Nicollier had seated themselves in
Discovery's cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   The seven men have been largely sequestered in their quarters at
the Kennedy Space Center since Dec. 6.
</P>
<P>
   An overcast sky with steady rain and winds produced by a
sluggish cold front refused to clear before Friday's 46-minute
launch period expired.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency's desire to avoid a potential Y2K computer
problem is driving future launch options.
</P>
<P>
   NASA wants Discovery back on Earth by Dec. 28 so that it can
prepare computers at mission control facilities at the Johnson
Space Center in Houston and the Kennedy Space Center launch complex
in Florida for the New Year. As a precaution, it has also ruled out
flying over New Year's Eve to avoid a problem, though its experts
believe there is little likelihood of computer difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   With Friday's launch scrub, Discovery's flight was scaled back
from nine to eight days and the number of spacewalks from four to
three. Even with the abbreviated flight, Discovery's astronauts can
accomplish the mission's highest priority, replacement of the
telescope's six gyroscopes, and make other improvements, said Ron
Dittemore, NASA's shuttle program manager.
</P>
<P>
   One of the world's premier astronomical observatories, the space
telescope has been inactive since Nov. 13, when a fourth gyroscope
failed. A crucial component of the observatory's pointing system,
the gyroscopes enable the telescope to lock on to the celestial
targets selected by ground-based astronomers.
</P>
<P>
   NASA announced Discovery's visit to the space telescope in
March, shortly after the failure of a third gyroscope, leaving the
minimum number necessary for celestial observations. It hoped then
that the shuttle crew could reach the telescope in mid-October,
before a fourth malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   However, all shuttle flights were suspended after Columbia
experienced an electrical short moments after lifting off in late
July. The short was traced to damaged insulation on electrical
wiring in Columbia's fuselage.
</P>
<P>
   The incident prompted shuttle managers to order extensive
inspections and repairs of the wiring in Discovery, Endeavour and
Atlantis.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery completed the procedure first, but a succession of
other equipment problems accumulated to bump the targeted launch
date eight times, including Friday's first attempt to lift off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
