<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-MUSEUM-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN IS ARRAIGNED IN DEFACING OF PAINTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 72-year-old Manhattan man accused of smearing white
paint across a controversial painting of the Virgin Mary was
formally charged Friday and temporarily barred from the Brooklyn
Museum of Art, where the painting had ignited a cultural uproar in
September.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Dennis Heiner, was charged with criminal mischief,
making graffiti and possessing instruments of graffiti, the
Brooklyn district attorney's office said. He was released without
bail after an arraignment in the Brooklyn Criminal Court, where
Judge Lauren Bailey-Shifman ordered him to stay out of the museum
until at least his next court appearance, on Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   The three charges against Heiner were misdemeanors. The district
attorney's office said it could not charge him with a felony
because less than $1,500 in damage was done to the painting. Heiner
remained silent throughout his brief arraignment, where he was
represented by Henry Dechalis, a court-appointed lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday afternoon, the authorities said, Heiner slipped
behind a plexiglass shield in front of the painting, ``The Holy
Virgin Mary'' by Chris Ofili, and rubbed strokes of white latex
paint across the canvas. After the attack, museum conservators
removed the painting and cleaned it before the paint even dried _
within an hour. The restored canvas was returned to the gallery
Friday, and a rope on stanchions was placed in front of its
plexiglass shield as an added precaution, said Sally Williams, a
museum spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, adorned with elephant dung and pornographic
cutouts, had been singled out earlier this year as particularly
offensive by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who, along with the Catholic
League and others, protested the exhibition, ``Sensation.''
Giuliani sought to pull financing for the museum, but lost in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, in response to questions about whether he may have
instigated Heiner in some way, the mayor replied: ``I haven't said
anything for about a month or a month and a half. So that would be
a real stretch.'' He said Heiner should be prosecuted like anyone
else accused of such a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Heiner was described by his wife, Helena, in an interview on
Thursday as a Roman Catholic who opposed abortion and believed that
the painting was sacrilegious. In 1990, Heiner was charged with
obstructing governmental administration for protesting in front of
an abortion clinic in Westchester County, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Davitt, a spokesman for the Brooklyn district attorney's
office, said there was no indication that Heiner had any help in
the attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
