<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-POLLS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poll says most people think political candidates lie
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Candidates in the 2000 election will face
increasingly skeptical voters growing less tolerant of attack ads
and dishonesty on the campaign trail, says a research group with
ties to Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationwide poll done in early November, the Institute for
Global Ethics found nearly 60 percent of those polled think all or
most candidates ``twist the truth'' while campaigning. Almost 40
percent said most candidates lie.
</P>
<P>
   The latest figures come from a group that used Ohio and
Washington as pilot states in 1998 to begin its Project on Campaign
Conduct, in which polling was combined with an effort to get
candidates to agree to codes of conduct for their campaigns. The
institute ran that project in association with the Kettering
Foundation in Dayton, and the Ray C. Bliss Institute of Applied
Politics at Akron University.
</P>
<P>
   And while Brad Rourke, a vice president with the global ethics
institute, said there's nothing remarkable about a poll showing
voters distrust politicians, he said the new data is valuable
because of the background polling done in Ohio last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's new is there's been an intensification (of those
feelings) over the last 18 months that's really surprising in
scope,'' Rourke said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rourke said some questions asked in both polls showed more than
a 10-point change in results, which he said is significant even if
the first poll was conducted only in a state and the second poll
was done nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Rourke said that among Ohioians polled in 1998
only 40 percent believed some or all politicians ``twist the
truth'' while campaigning, compared with almost 60 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's of a scope that is notable,'' Rourke said.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitfield Ayers, a Republican pollster in Atlanta, said it's
``not valid'' to compare polling results when the samples are drawn
from different populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say something's going up or down when you're talking
about people from two different universes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ayers agreed generally with the point of Global Ethics
that voters have grown impatient with attack ads. But he's not
convinced there's evidence voters are especially concerned this
year as opposed to previous years.
</P>
<P>
   He said polls on voter attitudes about negative ads must be
carefully crafted because it's not easy to define ``negative.'' He
said that in the coming election, as always, voters will be
sensitive to the tone of campaign attacks and are less tolerant of
personal attacks than pointed criticism of an opponent's record.
And Ayers said it's as true as ever that too strident an attack can
do more harm to the candidate making the attack than the candidate
who is the target.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question they're tired of the negativism,'' Ayers
said of voters. ``But that doesn't mean that candidates are going
to stop comparisons of one another. So it depends on how you define
an attack ad.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
