<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TOBACCO-INDUSTRY-N     12-17 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOBACCO-INDUSTRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: THE POLITICS BEHIND A DECISION TO RAISE A TOBACCO
TAX
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-TOBACCO-TAX) 
(rk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The 55-cent-a-pack increase in New York state's
cigarette tax agreed to Friday by Gov. George Pataki and
legislative leaders is the latest in a series of heavy blows
against the tobacco companies, an industry that just a few years
ago seemed invulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring setback occurred in lawsuit settlements with
the states in 1998, for $246 billion over 25 years. But as
sentiment against tobacco has grown, there have been numerous other
defeats. In the last five years, the federal government and 19
states have increased their tobacco taxes.
</P>
<P>
   And this year, Philip Morris, the world's largest tobacco
company, and the New York state Legislature have been embarrassed
by disclosures that the company's chief lobbyist here violated
state law by failing to disclose meals and other gifts she bought
for dozens of legislators. Since then, lawmakers have sought ways
to cover themselves politically, helping to propel the tax
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit settlements and higher taxes increase the price of
cigarettes, driving down their use. The industry reports that sales
nationally have fallen 8 to 10 percent in the last year, as
cigarette prices have risen to keep pace with the cost of the legal
settlements and higher taxes.
</P>
<P>
   A 55-cent increase would put New York's cigarette tax at $1.11 a
pack, the highest in the nation, and lawmakers say the $500 million
a year in revenue would be used to help expand health insurance for
the poor. It would be the first significant anti-smoking measure
the state has adopted since the governor took office. For Pataki, a
Republican who has built his reputation on deep tax cuts, raising
the tobacco tax is a stark departure. He acknowledged that Friday's
deal was a hard switch for him to accept, but added, ``We're not
just raising revenue, we're also saving lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax increase is expected to be advantageous to the governor
in New York, leavening his conservative image, and tapping into the
popularity of anti-smoking efforts and deep concern about the
uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   But it puts him at odds with Republicans in Congress, who
soundly rejected President Clinton's plan for a 50-cent increase in
the federal tobacco tax. Pataki would like to be considered for his
party's vice presidential nomination next year, but he is viewed by
many national Republicans as too moderate.
</P>
<P>
   At home, the tax gives Pataki, like the legislators, a way of
demonstrating that he is not beholden to tobacco interests.
Democrats often accuse Republicans of being too cozy with the
tobacco industry, whose campaign contributions overwhelmingly go to
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Until this decade, politicians around the country, in both
parties, were largely unwilling to challenge the tobacco industry.
But after voters approved initiatives raising the tobacco taxes in
Arizona, California and Massachusetts, legislators began to follow
their lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians have found that if you're going to raise a tax,
this is the one to raise,'' said Russell Sciandra, director of the
Center for a Tobacco-Free New York. ``There's been a tremendous
shift in public opinion against the tobacco companies.''
</P>
<P>
   When New York raised its tax in 1993, to 56 cents a pack, it
became the highest cigarette tax in the country. Now, New York
ranks 16th. The highest is $1, in Alaska and Hawaii, while the
lowest are in tobacco-growing states of Virginia and Kentucky, 2.5
cents and 3 cents, respectively. New Jersey's tax is 80 cents, and
Connecticut's is 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The federal cigarette tax, now 24 cents, will rise to 34 cents
on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   A 55-cent tax increase would mean an 18 percent jump in the
retail price of cigarettes, now averaging $3 a pack in New York.
Anti-smoking groups say that would drive down cigarette sales to
the state's 3 million smokers by 7 percent. ``The decline would be
almost twice as large among teen-agers and the poor,'' said Ana
Marengo, an American Cancer Society spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the tax increase, Sciandra said, ``The number of
kids who start smoking will drop by 12 percent, more than 20,000
kids a year, and it will get more than 200,000 adults to quit.''
Lawmakers say they will also increase spending on efforts to combat
smoking, to $37 million a year from about $13 million now.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies agree that rising prices depress demand, and
they note that cigarette sales have been declining for years. For
that reason, they maintain, higher taxes are an unwise way for
states to raise money. ``You kind of have to question the
advisability of a long-term program with a revenue source that is
declining,'' said Brendan J. McCormick, a spokesman for Philip
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   The industry also argues that reducing cigarette use will
undermine the bonds that some governments, like New York City and
Nassau County, are selling, backed by the expected
tobacco-settlement money. That is because the settlements stipulate
that lower sales will mean smaller payments to the states.
</P>
<P>
   New York accounts for less than 7 percent of the national
cigarette market, so what happens here may not affect the
industry's bottom line very much. But tobacco companies worry that
anti-smoking sentiment has become a runaway train, with New York
poised to leap to the front.
</P>
<P>
   Sure signs of that fear were on display earlier this week, when
the Legislature met for a special session. There were no
tobacco-related bills on the agenda, but everyone knew the higher
tax was under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   When Assembly Democrats finished a six-hour private meeting
Wednesday around midnight, the only people waiting for them as they
left were reporters and tobacco lobbyists. And when the Senate held
its session Tuesday, there were just four lobbyists waiting outside
the chamber. One worked for the cancer society; the three others
worked for tobacco companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
