<HEADLINE>
FOR THE MILLENNIUM, A DIFFERENT DRAWING OF JESUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a way to celebrate the millennium, The National Catholic
Reporter, an independent weekly based in Kansas City, Mo., decided
earlier this year to sponsor a contest for a new artistic portrait
of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, said John L. Allen Jr., the newspaper's opinion
editor, was to put ``the focus back on Christ'' at a time when so
much news coverage about the year 2000 seemed to turn either on
apocalyptic anxiety (fear of a computer disaster) or on hedonism
(where to find the hottest New Year's Eve party).
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost seemed to have slipped off the radar screen, why we
were marking this date, 2,000 years since the birth of Christ,''
Allen said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Jesus 2000'' contest, brainchild of the newspaper's
editor, Michael Farrell, received international attention almost as
soon as it was announced. It drew 1,678 entries, from artists in 19
nations.
</P>
<P>
   This week The Reporter announced a winner, selected from among
10 finalists by the British art critic Sister Wendy Beckett. The
portrait is called ``Jesus of the People,'' and it shows a young,
dark-skinned man with subtly feminine facial features. He clutches
a robe around himself, and his head is surrounded by a halo.
</P>
<P>
   The painter, Janet McKenzie, an artist from northern Vermont, is
quoted by the newspaper as saying she used a female model, an
African-American woman, in order to incorporate women into this
image of Jesus. The paper also quotes Sister Beckett as saying she
thought the Jesus in the painting gazed back at viewers with an
``ineffable dignity, with sadness but with confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The portrait, the article about it and commentary by Sister
Beckett can all be found on the newspaper's Web site,
www.natcath.org.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said the paper had been receiving lots of comment about
Sister Beckett's choice. ``It is generating an enormous reaction,''
he said, ``both positive and negative'': While many people are
outraged at the untraditional approach the artist took, many others
feel deeply moved by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any new image of Jesus is going to generate controversy,''
Allen added.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to see more of the entries in the contest,
the newspaper will publish a special color supplement in its Dec.
24 issue, showing the 10 paintings chosen as finalists, along with
50 others, Allen said. The paintings selected for second, third and
fourth place are also displayed on the Web site. They are
strikingly different from the winner, and from one another.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether any of the paintings will be formally exhibited
somewhere, Allen said all that was still in the talking stage. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JEWS AND BAPTISTS STILL SPLIT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to arrange a meeting between the president of the
Southern Baptist Convention and officials of a major Jewish
organization, to discuss the organization's criticism of Southern
Baptist approaches to converting Jews, have collapsed after the two
sides disagreed about who should attend.
</P>
<P>
   Gedale B. Horowitz and Michael S. Miller, president and
executive vice president of the Jewish Community Relations Council
of New York, wanted a one-on-one meeting between Horowitz and the
Rev. Paige Patterson, the convention's president. But in a letter
sent to the council last week, Patterson said he took that stance
as a rejection of his proposal that a gathering also include the
heads of four Jewish seminaries and two representatives of
``Messianic Jewish'' groups that assert that one can be Jewish and
nonetheless believe in Jesus as the Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   ``With regret,'' Patterson wrote, ``I accept your refusal of our
offer, and there the matter ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson and the council had exchanged letters since September,
when officials of the Jewish organization complained that Southern
Baptists were embracing ``deceptive'' proselytizing practices by
supporting Messianic groups, some of which use Jewish ritual
objects like skullcaps and prayer shawls in their religious
services while also worshiping Jesus.
</P>
</TEXT>
