<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLLINS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collins in jail on new warrant
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Cecil Collins is back in jail.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Dolphins running back turned himself in at the Broward
County jail after authorities in Baton Rouge, La., issued an arrest
warrant, saying he had violated terms of a four-year probation in
that state when he was arrested in Davie early Thursday morning and
charged with two counts of burglary of an occupied dwelling.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, 23, is expected to remain in the Broward County jail
until a bond hearing Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Collins had been released Thursday on $10,000 bond after a
married couple accused him of climbing through their bedroom window
at about 5:30 a.m. Ronald and Tina Nolte also told police that
Collins had been annoying Tina, 28, for the past two months,
repeatedly asking her out.
</P>
<P>
   There is the possibility that stalking charges could be added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that _ and obviously we have to get all the
information from Florida _ but it sounds remarkably similar to the
crimes he committed here,'' Sue Bernie, the assistant district
attorney for East Baton Rouge, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie was the prosecuting attorney when Collins was arrested
twice in less than a month in 1998 and charged with breaking into
women's apartments. As part of a plea bargain, he plead guilty to
two misdemeanor counts of simple battery and two felony counts of
unauthorized entry of an inhabited dwelling. He was put on
four-year probation.
</P>
<P>
   After learning of the incident in Florida, Louisiana authorities
issued the warrant and gave Collins the choice of turning himself
in Louisiana or Broward County. He chose to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd rather have him here, able to assist us in analyzing all
of these allegations that have been made,'' said Fred Haddad,
Collins' attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney for the Noltes said their wish is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want him to get help,'' Jim Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins remains on the Dolphins' roster but he is suspended
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   After practice Friday, Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson was asked if
Collins' problems would prompt him to shy away from giving players
second chances.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson paused for a couple seconds, then snapped: ``Anything
about the San Diego game?''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins will try to snap a three-game losing streak Sunday
at Pro Player Stadium against the Chargers. And at least one
observer at Friday's practice doesn't think the chaos of the week
will affect the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Wyche, a CBS analyst who will be covering the game, was the
Cincinnati Bengals coach when running back Stanley Wilson was found
in a Plantation hotel room with drugs the night before Super Bowl
XXIII. Wilson was suspended. And although the Bengals lost the game
to the 49ers, Wyche doesn't think the off-the-field problems create
much of a distraction for the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a conversation in the locker room until they get
it all out and said one time, then it's over with,'' Wyche said
after watching the end of practice Friday. ``Teams are used to
turnover. It's like a war. They're used to guys getting shot around
them and new troops coming in. That's just what football is.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyche said he empathized with the Dolphins' staff and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough on everybody because you put your eggs in certain
baskets, and when they're not their you don't know how the next
group is going to perform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That next group will be fullback Stanley Pritchett. For the
second consecutive week, Pritchett will start at tailback.
</P>
<P>
   Last week against the Jets he started in place of the injured
J.J. Johnson and gained 68 yards on 19 carries.
</P>
<P>
