<HEADLINE>
ROOT FOR ST. LOUIS? IT'S A RAM TOUGH ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Brett Taylor, who wore Rams pajamas as a boy _
``when they were blue and white'' _ hasn't rooted for the team
since it abandoned Southern California and he isn't about to start
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they lose every game,'' the Ojai high school teacher
said with some bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   Sal Martinez, who slept in the glow of a Rams nightlight as a
kid, never stopped being a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tell me, `They moved away _ how can you root for them?'
'' said Martinez, owner of the memorabilia-filled Golden Ram Barber
Shop in the Orange County city of Westminster. ``I tell them, `If
your best friend moves away, do they stop being your friend?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The jilted lover. The loyal friend.
</P>
<P>
   They are the two sides of an issue that has tugged me in both
directions since the football heroes of my youth got good again
this season in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Is it OK to root for the Rams?
</P>
<P>
   Should a self-respecting Angeleno feel guilty for having a
twinge of nostalgia when the familiar gold horns show up on
magazine covers?
</P>
<P>
   Do the Rams deserve my support, after jilting their L.A. and
Anaheim fans?
</P>
<P>
   Do I deserve to enjoy their renewed success, after ignoring them
the past four years?
</P>
<P>
   These questions cannot be put off any longer.
</P>
<P>
   At 11-2, the Rams have assured a winning record (for the first
time in 10 years), clinched a division title (for the first time in
14 years) and can nail down home-field advantage throughout the NFC
postseason by beating the New York Giants on Sunday in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   They have the league's most productive offense.
</P>
<P>
   In Kurt Warner, Marshall Faulk and Isaac Bruce, they have the
No. 1 passer, No. 2 rusher and No. 3 receiver in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Darn it, they're !ital!good!off!.
</P>
<P>
   It's like tuning in the Miss America contest and there's your
ex-girlfriend in a tiara. Do you call to say congratulations?
</P>
<P>
   In the Rams' case, it's complicated.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so easy to ignore them if you grew up here, as I did in
the era of Roman Gabriel and the Fearsome Foursome, and Mom and Dad
gave you one of those blue-and-white Rams helmets for Christmas,
and you remember as if it was yesterday watching from your uncle's
20-yard-line Coliseum seats as Isiah Robertson intercepted a
Redskins pass to clinch a playoff win 25 years ago next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, rooting for the Rams means rooting for Georgia
Frontiere, the team owner who took St. Louis' money and new stadium
and tried to claim the 1995 move was ``forced upon'' her by
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, before Frontiere moved them to Missouri, the Rams
were here for 49 years, deeper in the Southland fabric than the
Dodgers, Angels, Lakers, Kings, Clippers or Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, rooting for the Rams means rooting for John Shaw,
the team president who recently said he didn't regret the move but
did regret ``that there is no pro football in Southern
California.'' (San Diego must love to hear that.)
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it's really the !ital!players!off! you root for, not
the front office.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, these aren't the players you rooted for in that
final season at Anaheim Stadium _ among the 1994 starters, only
cornerback Todd Lyght was still on the 1999 training-camp roster.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, that helmet is pretty cool.
</P>
<P>
   What's a lapsed Rams fan to do?
</P>
<P>
   Said Taylor, 33, a history and phys-ed teacher at Oak Grove High
in Ojai: ``I hate to see Georgia Frontiere make a dime. I hate John
Shaw. I feel like they ran the team into the ground. They made a
lot of bonehead moves and then turned around and blamed it on us.
It's too bad, because there are things to like. I love (head coach)
Dick Vermeil. I love Marshall Faulk.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Martinez, 37: ``My friends say, `They moved away, how can
you root for them?' I tell them the Rams are my whole childhood,
what can I do?'' Besides, Martinez thinks the St. Louis deal was
``too good to pass up.''
</P>
<P>
   It's funny. On my desk is a file bulging with letters from
Raiders fans pining for their team's return from Oakland. I've
never received a letter from a Rams fan. The two teams left town at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the difference is that Rams management was smart enough to
leave, while Raiders management might be dumb enough to come back.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the difference is that old Rams fans have a conscience,
while old Raiders fans fans have an attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Is it OK to root for the Rams?
</P>
<P>
   For me there's probably no going back after a couple of years
ago when, looking for a new pro football team, I bought a really
cool 49ers hat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
