<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-ROBERTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LAWYER'S LEGAL VICTORY GOES AGAINST AN OLD HAUNT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twenty thousand dollars. That was the price of a poll
of Bronx jurors that defense lawyers for the four officers charged
with second-degree murder in the killing of Amadou Diallo thought
they needed to support their motion for a change of venue.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lot of money for a defense team already facing hefty
legal costs, and it was a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   But two of the lawyers representing Officer Sean Carroll _
Burton B. Roberts and Bennett M. Epstein _ argued strenuously that
the poll was worth it. Roberts said Friday that he even found
someone _ whom he would not name _ to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burt and I saw it as really preventing a lynching,'' Epstein
said of the motion, which he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was done, and so was the motion, and on Thursday, the
costly tactic paid off. The state Supreme Court's Appellate
Division ruled that the trial should be moved to Albany. The court
agreed _ partly on the basis of the poll _ that passions about the
case made the selection of an impartial jury in New York City
impossible. The poll said, among other things, that 81 percent of
potential Bronx jurors believed there was ``no justification
possible'' for the police officers' firing 41 shots at Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   For Roberts, a former chief administrative justice of the Bronx,
and for Epstein, his former law clerk, it was a career-capping
moment. ``We came riding back from the sunset,'' Epstein joked.
</P>
<P>
   But for Roberts, the glory was built, to an extent, on
repudiating the place and the jurors he presided over as
administrative justice.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly three decades, Roberts had prowled the Bronx courts _
he was district attorney before his appointment to the bench _ and
he had defended its jurors against accusations that they were out
of step with the rest of the city.
</P>
<P>
   But this legal victory rested in part on the notion that the
Bronx is ``a place in which large numbers of people harbor an
inherent distrust or even hatred of the police,'' in the words of
the motion.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx borough president, Fernando Ferrer, who roundly
condemned the appellate court's decision, called Roberts' position
``a complete absurdity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I am loath to diminish former Judge Roberts,''
Ferrer added, ``but his previous statements spread on the public
record over a number of decades are at wide variance with his
present statements as defense counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Roberts denied there was any contradiction. ``I believe
strongly that if ever a case merited a change of venue, this case
certainly did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned the case of Larry Davis, who was acquitted by a
Bronx jury of the attempted murder of nine police officers in 1988.
He called that a ``strange verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts also said Bronx juries seemed to acquit more frequently
on gun and drug charges, which usually rely on police officers'
testimony, which suggests ``there is maybe a feeling against police
officers.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, that did not mean every police officer should be
entitled to a change of venue. The pretrial publicity in the Diallo
case was exceptional, he said. ``The whole city was infected with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, he said, ``you could question jurors _ you could
have peremptory challenges.'' But in this case, he said, the taint
was too great.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bronx,'' he added, ``should not be disenfranchised.''
</P>
<P>
   But the clamor that the appellate decision did just that
continued Friday. The Rev. Al Sharpton joined about 50 protesters
and the Diallo family in a protest outside the Bronx County
Courthouse, and the Diallo family also met with the Bronx district
attorney, Robert Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Reed, a spokesman for Johnson, said the district attorney
told the family that the court's decision appeared to be
unappealable, but that if a legal basis to appeal could be found,
the office would pursue it. Court officials still were unsure when
the trial would begin. It had been set to start Jan. 3 in the
Bronx. A judge in Albany must be selected and then given time to
become familiar with the case. Previous rulings in the case would
stand, but pending issues, like whether the prosecution should be
required to turn over reports of the expert witnesses it plans to
use, will be up to the new judge.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who withdrew as the lead attorney in the case last
month, said: ``I really commend the Appellate Division for the
wisdom and courage they displayed. I can't praise them enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
