<HEADLINE>
ADULATION, STATE TITLES GO TOGETHER IN STEPHENVILLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEPHENVILLE, Texas _ With the anxious energy of two fleas,
8-year-old Adrion Edwards and his friend, 8-year-old Chase Skiles,
argue about their favorite football players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanna be Cody Avalos,'' Edwards says. ``He's good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Brady Gunn,'' Skiles says. ``He hits really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Avalos and Gunn are two of the Stephenville High School football
players who walk amid this NFL-type adulation from children and
elderly citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In Stephenville, (pop. 15,450) a relaxed community located on
Texas 377 about 60 miles southwest of Fort Worth, Avalos and Gunn
are bigger than Deion Sanders or Major Applewhite.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid I always wanted to play for Stephenville;
it's a big deal,'' senior receiver Toby O'Neal said. ``It's cool to
get caught up in it here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here'' is a place that proves small-town America isn't
extinct. It's a place where everyone knows everyone, and children]
revere their Friday night football heroes as much as they do Santa
Claus.
</P>
<P>
   It's a town where the biggest buildings are the churches. A town
where the boys wear their hair short and the girls wear theirs big.
A town where teen-agers work in fast-food restaurants, cruise the
drag on weekends and super heroes are born on touchdowns, sacks and
game-winning kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Children and senior citizens alike will watch the Yellow Jackets
(15-0) play Port Neches-Groves (14-1) at 4 p.m. today at the
Astrodome in Houston for the Class 4A Division II state title.
Stephenville is going for its fourth title of the '90s and the
unofficial moniker ``Team of the Decade.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the town Odessa wanted to be in H.G. Bissinger's
best-selling book ``Friday Night Lights'', which chronicled] the
football fervor of Odessa Permian High School 10 years ago. Unlike
a town rife with economic and racial divisiveness, Stephenville
seems to be a true Texas football town.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband had a chance to take a job in Granbury, but we
turned it down,'' said Cindy Carrell, whose son, Chris, plays
football at Stephenville's middle school. ``One of the main reasons
we stayed here is because he wants to play football so badly for
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago, Carrell's husband probably would have taken
the job. You see, Stephenville has not always been mentioned as a
quintessential football community.
</P>
<P>
   There is a definite line in Stephenville's football lore. B.B.,
Before Briles and A.B., After Briles.
</P>
<P>
   Before coach Art Briles arrived in 1988, Yellow Jackets football
tradition wasn't worth much more than a home security system in
Stephenville. Before Briles, the Yellow Jackets hadn't made the
playoffs since 1952. Since, Stephenville is 135-29-2 with three
state titles, all in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hiring Art was the luckiest thing I've seen,'' said ex-state
senator Bob Glasco, a Stephenville attorney and big Yellow Jackets'
backer. ``Those kids would walk through a wall if Art told them to.
It's really gotten the community together; I see people who haven't
spoken to one another in 13 years sitting next to each other
shaking cans.''
</P>
<P>
   The shaking cans _ Yellow Jackets fans use propane cans filled
with ball bearings to make thunderous noise at games. It's all part
of Stephenville's tradition, along with a booster club, fans
following the team by the thousands to away games and waiting in
the stands for two hours for kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Booster-club membership has more than tripled and, Glasco said,
donations to the school's athletic department neared $200,000 last
season. The waiting list for season tickets for reserved seating is
a few years long.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to be more than fans and participate in the
program, there is always a role, regardless of age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the games since I was a kid with my little
cheerleading outfit on,'' senior] dance-team member Tori Turley
said. ``You start learning the dances when you're 6]. I know it's
crazy, but I always wanted to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the posturing Stephenville's citizens do, of all the
revenue and publicity for the town that is correlated with the
football team, there are moments when the hype exceeds any Texas
football stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to date this one football player whose idea of renting
a movie was to watch his game film,'' dance team member Ericka
Wheat said. ``And if you are out with a letter jacket on or people
know you are from Stephenville, the first thing you get asked about
is the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a few pockets of people who feel the hoopla
surrounding the team can be a bit much, most believe that the team
has been such a positive beacon that if _ heaven forbid _
Stephenville losses today, life goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're gonna win,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   If this is a true Texas football town, they probably will.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
