<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2478 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-BUSH-HUNGER-1STLEDE-T     12-17 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HUNGER-1STLEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS IF THERE WERE POCKETS OF HUNGER IN TEXAS, HE'D KNOW ABOUT
IT 
(CLARIFIES LEDE)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Gov. George W. Bush challenged on Friday a recent
federal report that said many Texans, including children, are going
to bed hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the report that children in Texas are going hungry.
Where?'' Bush said in an interview with the Star-Telegram. ``I want
to know the facts. I would like for the Department of Agriculture
to show us who. Where are they, and we'll respond.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No children are going to go hungry in this state,'' declared
Bush, whose ``leave no child behind'' slogan has become a theme of
his frontrunning presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll fix it and respond,'' he added. ``You'd think the
governor would have heard if there are pockets of hunger in
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-hunger activists and food pantry workers were startled at
Bush's statements, saying emergency food distribution has risen
sharply in Texas as soup kitchens strain to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm shocked he said that,'' said Sharon Hogan, executive
director of the Metroplex Food Bank in Fort Worth, which
distributes food to the needy and to food pantries. ``There are
massive amounts of people who go hungry. I could you give you story
after story.''
</P>
<P>
   On a bulletin board inside her office is a photo of a 7-year-old
boy who lost most of his teeth from malnutrition, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'll get to work at 6:30 a.m. and find people in the
parking lot waiting for food that we don't distribute until 1
p.m.,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The federal study that Bush challenged, a U.S. Department of
Agriculture report entitled ``Measuring Food Security in the United
States,'' says about 13 percent of Texas households were ``food
insecure,'' or unable to meet basic food needs at all times,
between 1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   About 5 percent of Texas households suffered from hunger during
the period, a rate surpassed only by Oregon. The study defines
hunger as insufficient food intake causing an uneasy or painful
sensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a new report saying there's hungry kids in Texas.
It's been true for years,'' said Celia Hagert, nutrition policy
analyst at the Center for Public Policy Priorities, an advocacy
group for low-income Texans. ``It's ludicrous to say there's no
hungry people in Texas. It's just ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the report was carefully conducted using a detailed
questionnaire. Bush, however, suggested that Texans who need food
assistance are already receiving it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got food banks,'' the Republican governor said. ``We've
got food stamps. You know there's a lot of people that are poor
people, but I'd like to know who's going hungry in the state of
Texas. That report just kind of flew out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Cocciarelli, director of the Texas Association of Second
Harvest Food Banks, a non-profit which distributes food to hunger
relief agencies, said a steady increase in demand for food aid
indicates there are hungry Texans, children and adults alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definitely hungry children in Texas,'' she said.
Distribution projections for 1999 show the organization will
distribute 120 million pounds of food to 19 Texas food banks, a 26
percent increase over 1996, when welfare reforms took effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're finding within the food banking industry is we are
not able to keep up with the increased demands on our member
agencies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Beth Malcolm, the state Democratic party chair, accused
Bush of living in a ``land of illusions'' and repeated criticism of
his 1995 veto of a unanimously passed bill that would have created
a volunteer Food Security Council to study the hunger problem and
help acquire hunger grant money.
</P>
<P>
   In his veto proclamation, Bush said he rejected the bill because
it was ``not in the state's best interest to create another
bureaucratic entity ... when a private organization could be more
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are children probably within a mile or two of his
Governor's Mansion that are hungry,'' Malcolm said. ``Every member
of the Legislature acknowledged that there were hungry people in
this state when they passed that hunger bill four years ago. Bush
refused to face reality then, and he's refusing to face reality
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his comments as he prepares for the GOP presidential
primaries, which begin next month. On Friday, surrounded by his
fellow Republican statewide elected officials, the governor filed
the paperwork to appear on the ballot in Texas on March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, in a news conference and, later, in an interview with
the Star-Telegram, Bush:
</P>
<P>
   Said that Texas, facing potentially drastic measures to clean up
its dirty air, was right to pull the plug in 1995 on a politically
unpopular tailpipe testing program. The state later had to pay the
contractor, Tejas Testing Technology, $140 million for canceling
the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so sure of your premise that the air would have been
cleaner if we had centralized testing in the Metroplex or Harris
County,'' Bush told a reporter. ``I think that was an assumption
that just wasn't valid.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Vice President Al Gore, potentially his White House rival,
is proposing to usurp the states' traditional role in overseeing
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Al Gore wants to do is to run for federal superintendent
of schools,'' Bush said. ``The state's role is to build buildings
and the state's role is to pay teachers more. The federal role, to
the extent that it's focusing on children, needs to demand for
results and standards and high accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush criticized Gore's proposal to provide universal pre-school,
saying the government already has a sufficient pre-school program _
Head Start, essentially a pre-school program for poor children:
``We've got a pre-school _ called Head Start,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Said that European demands to require labeling of U.S. beef
produced with hormones, or of genetically altered foods, reflects a
desire to ``smear U.S. products.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sense they want to run a propaganda campaign,'' he said.
``There needs to be scientific labels as to whether something is
safe or not. What I'm for is for there to be truth in advertising
that enables a product manufacturer to clearly state nothing in
this product is harmful to your health, for example.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Bechetta Jackson contributed to this report. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
