<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2481 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HERITAGE-ARREST18-COX     12-17 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERITAGE-ARREST18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Student arrested at Georgia high school for threats, injuring
officer
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith and S.A. Reid
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Teen-age emotions erupted Friday at Heritage High
School, ending with threats, pepper spray and an arrest.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-year old Heritage student was arrested at the school and
charged with battery, felony obstruction of a law enforcement
official, terroristic threats and interference with government
property.
</P>
<P>
   According to a police report, the arrest came after an angry
student said, ``I wish they had been killed in the shooting last
year and I may come up here and kill them myself.''
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to the May 20 incident when Anthony ``T.J.''
Solomon, who was a sophomore at the school, opened fire on
classmates, injuring six.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning's incident took place in a school office when the
girl, a junior, became upset and could not be calmed down, said
Rockdale County Sheriff's Department Lt. Mike Ransom.
</P>
<P>
   She hadn't wanted to be in a room with another student, and
emotions escalated.
</P>
<P>
   Ransom said the girl ``got out of control, injured a school
resource officer (Dave D'Loivo), with kicks and punches, damaged a
door and threatened bodily harm.''
</P>
<P>
   In the office she tore the hardware from a door and frame and
fought with school officials who called on the school resource
officer, said Sheriff's Department Corp. Jeff Baker.
</P>
<P>
   During the course of the incident, the girl was subdued with
pepper spray. She was treated at the scene and then transported to
Rockdale County Hospital before being taken to the Gwinnett County
Youth Detention Center. She later was released into the custody of
her parents.
</P>
<P>
   D'Loivo also was treated for his injuries at the hospital and
released.
</P>
<P>
   Rockdale County Schools spokeswoman Susan Paul Smith said she
did not know whether the student has been suspended from school or
whether charges had been brought against others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an ongoing investigation, and we do not have anything
else to say at this time,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The student's parents have retained a lawyer and have threatened
to sue school officials for using what they consider excessive
force.
</P>
<P>
   Her 24-year-old brother said she told him after her release that
there never was an altercation. The other student involved is
prepared to come forward to support her story, the brother said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his parents' lawyer advised them not to comment. He
described his sister as an average student who has sometimes gotten
in trouble at school for taking back to teachers but would never
make such a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
