<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WEBTV-GIFT-NYT &LR;      12-17 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBTV-GIFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HIGH-TECH HANUKKAH GIFT DRAWS UNEXPECTED GUESTS: DETECTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Samuel Posner opened the Hanukkah gift from his
son, the high-tech gizmo seemed like any other pricey new toy.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. The gift, which resembled a videocassette recorder,
contained top-secret technology designed by Microsoft Corp.,
potentially worth $1 million, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Posner, 68, a lawyer, said he learned this when detectives from
the city's Computer Investigative Unit showed up at his Manhattan
apartment on Thursday night, in hot pursuit of industrial
espionage.
</P>
<P>
   The astonished lawyer had not yet unpacked the device.
</P>
<P>
   How the item _ a cutting-edge version of a WebTV box, a device
that can make an ordinary television set capable of browsing the
World Wide Web _ got from Microsoft's office in Mountain View,
Calif., to Posner's apartment was being investigated by New York
and California detectives.
</P>
<P>
   While they had yet to make arrests, the Mountain View police
said they thought a Microsoft employee might have changed the
shipping labels in the mailroom, either inadvertently or in an
effort to steal the device.
</P>
<P>
   Posner was not pleased. ``If Microsoft felt that something
improper had taken place, they should have contacted us and said,
`Hey, Posner, we sent you something by mistake,''' he said,
``instead of having two detectives in plain clothes show up banging
on the door as if we were criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Posner's son, Scott, 34, who works for the Bank of New York and
also lives in Manhattan, declined to comment. A Microsoft
spokeswoman, Angela Yearta, said the company was grateful to the
police for helping to retrieve the box but had no comment on the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Posner's woes began in Mountain View, where Microsoft's WebTV
operation is based. There, the device was engineered as a prototype
with new features that would not be on the market for at least a
year, said Detective Ted Cappozziello of the Computer Investigative
Unit of the New York City police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the proprietary information and the new sophistication
of the equipment,'' he said, ``Microsoft valued it as being worth
$1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   The device was packaged and labeled for shipment to an engineer
at Microsoft's corporate headquarters in Redmond, Wash. But the
engineer became alarmed when he received only a partial shipment.
``He said, `I got the cord, but where is the box?''' Cappozziello
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft told the Mountain View police that the United Parcel
Service package had somehow been rerouted from Redmond to
Manhattan, to the home of Scott Posner.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Scott was out walking his dog, and his wife,
who is seven months pregnant and confined to bed, was on the phone
with her father-in-law, when she heard men banging on her door who
said they were police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said to her, `Don't open the door,''' recalled Samuel
Posner, who stayed on the phone while he and his daughter-in-law
tried to figure out what the detectives wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing seemed so suspect, especially when they
started talking about this million-dollar whatever,'' Samuel Posner
said. Once the detectives revealed the UPS tracking number that was
on the package, Posner agreed to turn over the box, and the
detectives went to his apartment 10 blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police, Scott Posner told them a friend at
Microsoft had sent him the WebTV box, which he received on Dec. 11,
and he had given it to his father as a Hanukkah present.
</P>
<P>
   As for Samuel Posner, he hopes, in this season of gift-giving,
that the next present will be less eventful, a merino wool scarf,
perhaps, or a Brooks Brothers tie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 2315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
