<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2484 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-DEBATE-2000-HNS &LR;      12-17 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY, GORE SPAR OVER HEALTH CARE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Democratic presidential contenders Al Gore and
Bill Bradley clashed over how to improve health care and education
during a debate Friday that also underscored their similarities on
school violence, foreign policy and gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   In their second televised debate Gore also made it clear he
disapproved of GOP presidential front-runner George W. Bush
invoking Jesus Christ in the last Republican debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the separation of church and state,'' the vice
president said.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute town hall meeting broadcast on ABC-TV's
``Nightline`` did not reveal much new about the candidates, who are
locked in a close race in this first primary state. But the
free-wheeling format _ the only rule was to remain seated _ allowed
them to actually debate their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bradley mounted a strong defense of his proposals, Gore
was more aggressive, telling the audience at Daniel Webster College
that his opponent ``is a good man with some bad plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has proposed gradually increasing health insurance for
more Americans, attacked Bradley for his ambitious plan, which the
vice president said would be so expensive that there would be no
money left to deal with looming financial problems of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his own plan would set aside 15 percent of the surplus
to deal with Medicare, while, ``Bill does not set aside one
penny.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said Bradley's plan to abolish Medicaid and instead
provide tax-supported vouchers to beneficiaries would not be
adequate to cover the poor and the disabled's medical needs.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley countered that his health plan would address the
problem of the uninsured better than Gore's incremental approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do provide access to affordable health care for all
Americans and his plan does not,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who will you leave out?'' the former senator asked Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't leave out anyone,'' Gore shot back. But the vice
president said that he didn't want to do anything that would stymie
economic growth. Although Gore said he would consider increasing
cigarette taxes to pay for health care, he said he would not raise
income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be talking about targeted tax cuts,'' he said.
Bradley has acknowledged that he might have to increase taxes to
pay for his plan.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley tried to rebut Gore's claim that he would not address
Medicare's problems by saying the health insurance program for the
elderly does not become insolvent until 2017 and that it was too
early to devise a solution.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley also sparred on the issue of education. The
vice president charged that his opponent had supported
private-school vouchers in the past and had not come up with a plan
to help the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he had laid out a comprehensive program to improve
education that included more money for preschool programs such as
Head Start. Although he acknowledged voting for vouchers in the
past, Bradley said ``I do not believe vouchers are the answers to
public education.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore took aim at Republicans when a member of the audience asked
about the GOP presidential candidates' religious discussion during
an Iowa debate Monday night. Asked what philosopher or thinker they
admired most, Bush and Gary Bauer cited Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that although he affirmed his faith, ``I always try to
do so in a way that communicates absolute respect not only for
people who worship in a different way but just as much respect for
those who do not believe in God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atheists have just as much a right to public discourse as any
set of people in any religious faith,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was less critical. Every politician, he said, had to
decide for himself how to handle questions about his religious
faith. As for himself, Bradley said ``I have decided that personal
faith is private, and I will not discuss it with the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the evening the Democrats also agreed on many
items, including the need for more gun control and media
self-policing to stop the sort of juvenile violence that occurred
at Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   Both men also said they would stress diplomacy to head off a
conflict between Taiwan and China. While supporting the space
program, Bradley said he ``wouldn't commit to a date certain for
exploration of Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore concurred. ``We have got to have a mission to planet Earth
to focus on our problems'' before what he called the inevitable
event of a human being landing on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Although both men affirmed their support for gay rights, they
did not endorse gay marriages
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't support gay marriages because I think it is matter of
religious sacrament as well as a legal state,'' said Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bradley endorsed ending the military's
``don't-ask, don't-tell policy'' and offering other legal
protections to gays, such as honoring domestic contracts between
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Although the debate was largely civil, Bradley had anticipated
his opponent would come out swinging. Earlier in the day, Bradley
warned he would respond in kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take an elbow without returning an elbow, and that's
what's going to happen,'' said the former professional basketball
player.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who toured a Manchester company that sells candles over
the Internet, refrained from criticizing his opponent right before
the debate. But the vice president's campaign gleefully touted the
endorsement of Sen. Frank Lautenberg, R-N.J.,who hails from
Bradley's home state and served with both Bradley and Gore in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley continues to trail the vice president by a wide margin
in national polls, but he is slightly ahead of Gore in New
Hampshire, according to a Washington Post/ABC poll published
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The poll had Bradley leading Gore 48 percent to 45 percent, with
Bradley garnering more support among men, independents, liberals
and those with higher incomes and more education. He also received
support from voters who have become disillusioned with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As Bradley toured a mall in southern New Hampshire earlier in
the day, a number of shoppers said they would vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just has a trustworthy face,'' said Sharon Lamoureux, 40,
of Pelham.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
