<SLUG> BC-GORE-LAUGENBERG-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUTENBERG MAKES PICK OFFICIAL: GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Sen. Frank Lautenberg, a three-term Democrat from
New Jersey, announced Friday his endorsement of Vice President Al
Gore over his state's favorite son, former Sen. Bill Bradley, for
the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg, who served alongside Bradley in the Senate for 14
years, flew here Friday afternoon to make the announcement to
reporters prior to a debate between Gore and Bradley at a college
here.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey senator, who will retire from Congress at the end
of next year, said he had made up his mind to support Gore a year
ago, when Bradley had not declared his intention to run. But he
said Friday that even if he had known Bradley was going to run, he
would have endorsed the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience of Al Gore was the deciding factor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign tried to play down the announcement, saying
that Lautenberg told people months ago that he was supporting Gore.
But the Gore campaign said it had not made a formal announcement of
the endorsement until Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   While the Gore camp touted the endorsement as an important coup
that would perhaps be embarrassing for Bradley, Lautenberg had many
kind words for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are men of integrity, both are honest men,'' Lautenberg
said of the rivals. ``You couldn't get me to say anything bad about
Bill Bradley.'' He added that if Bradley wins the nomination, he
will support him in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg's comments about Bradley are in contrast to those of
some other New Jersey Democrats, including Rep. Robert Menendez of
Union City, who have criticized Bradley for being aloof and
unhelpful to local politicians while a senator.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg was also known to occasionally clash with Bradley,
and many New Jersey Democrats say he privately resented Bradley's
celebrity when he was doing much of the work of delivering federal
funds for the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Lautenberg said Bradley had been helpful to him
during his early years in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   And he fondly recalled that Bradley had refused to appear at
Lautenberg's victory party in his first election, out of concern
that he would draw the limelight from Lautenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You've worked too hard for this,''' Lautenberg said.
``I was struck by that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
