<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUGGISH ROBITAILLE WILL SIMPLIFY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Kings managed fine when winger Luc Robitaille
was out with a broken foot, so it only made sense the offense would
pick up when he returned, and the wins would follow.
</P>
<P>
   That was seven games ago. And in that span Robitaille, a
consistent 40-goal scorer most of his career, has done little
offensively. Since returning Dec. 3, he has one goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've been not playing the way I want to play, so I
told (coach) Andy (Murray) that I intend to start playing a more
simple game, put things at the net and see what happens,''
Robitaille said. ``Sometimes when things don't go well you try to
push a little bit. That's all I'll do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about it. The last two games we didn't get a
lot of chances, but the games before that, we got a lot of chances,
but they didn't go in. We've gotten a lot of opportunities, but it
didn't go in, and when that happens you just have to go back to
basics and do the little things and the rest will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray contemplated switching lines against the Chicago
Blackhawks tonight, going so far as to have playmaker Bryan
Smolinski skate with Robitaille and Glen Murray in practice.
There's little doubt with the way Smolinski's passed the puck this
season, Robitaille would get scoring chances. But Murray, who
rarely juggles lines, said he would probably keep things intact
against the Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to give Luc the opportunity to show his 40-goal
form,'' Murray said. ``I think he needs to be around the net more.
I think he's handled the puck too much, and I think he shouldn't be
a puck-handler. He should be a puck finisher, and I think he
realizes that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest in Storr: They are calling it post-concussion syndrome, and
it will keep goalie Jamie Storr out of the lineup for a while.
Storr, blitzed in back-to-back games before being yanked on both
occasions, was placed on injured reserve. Marcel Cousineau was
added to the Kings roster again.
</P>
<P>
   While Storr suffers through the headaches and dizziness caused
from the hit in Montreal, Murray wonders whether he did the right
thing by playing Storr against New Jersey and the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really only after the New York game that we felt there
might be a problem, and then not until we got back (to Los Angeles)
did we know,'' said Murray, pointing out Storr was examined by
three doctors on the road trip. ``Jamie's a real competitor and
wants to be in there, so maybe he was overlooking the problems he
was having. I guess he really wanted to go out there and play well
for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at it after and say as a coach, `Did I play somebody
who wasn't healthy?' But you don't know. You ask the player. He's
the only one who could make that judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   From the point: Defenseman Garry Galley won't play tonight, the
remnants of a concussion he suffered at New Jersey. Galley was
slated to undergo an MRI and CAT scan Friday night. . . . Stephane
Fiset will start in goal for the Kings. . . . The Kings are hoping
injured center Jozef Stumpel will return for Wednesday's game in
San Jose.
</P>
</TEXT>
