<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: PAKISTAN, EAST TIMOR, BRITAIN, ITALY, SPAIN,
ARGENTINA, BOLIVIA, MEXICO, SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: BHUTTO NAMED IN MURDER CASE
</P>
<P>
   A murder case has been registered against former Prime Minister
Benazir Bhutto, who is accused by the Islamic fundamentalist
Jamaat-I-Islami Party of ordering the police to fire on its members
during a protest in June 1996. Five others were also named. A
police investigation is likely to last several months.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: SHARIF CASE ADVANCES
</P>
<P>
   The case against the ousted prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, took
an important step toward trial when prosecutors finally shared key
evidence with the defense, something that had held up the start of
the proceedings. Sharif is charged with hijacking, kidnapping and
attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   EAST TIMOR: MILLIONS DONATED
</P>
<P>
   Donor nations meeting in Tokyo pledged more than $520 million to
the reconstruction of East Timor, far more than the $300 million
the World Bank had sought to raise. About $370 million is earmarked
for reconstruction and the remainder for humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PROTESTANTS MEET
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair opened the first meeting of the
British-Irish Council, a body of public officials from England,
Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland set up by the Ulster peace
accord to reinforce Protestants' wish to remain British. On Monday
there was the first meeting of a counterbalancing council of
ministers from the governments of Ireland and Northern Ireland
created to reinforce Catholic wishes to increase ties with Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: JAN HUS APOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   John Paul II apologized for the ``cruel'' execution of Jan Hus,
a Czech religious reformer who was burned at the stake in 1415. The
apology was timed for the visit from the Czech president, Vaclav
Havel, who donated the Christmas tree outside St. Peter's that is
to be lighted Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: COMMUNISTS CHANGE LEADER
</P>
<P>
   Julio Anguita, 58, the head of the Communist-led United Left
coalition, underwent emergency triple-bypass surgery, and the
leadership of his group, Spain's third largest political force,
named Francisco Frutos to lead the ticket in parliamentary
elections due by next April.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: 2 PROTESTERS DIE
</P>
<P>
   A day after the federal government took control of the bankrupt
Corrientes provincial government, two people were killed and at
least 40 injured in clashes between protesting workers and the
police. State employees who have not been paid since April as well
as other protesters were manning a roadblock on a local bridge when
the police tried to remove them.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA: NATIONWIDE STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of public transport workers staged a nationwide
48-hour strike to protest a recent 4 percent rise in fuel prices.
Traffic was disrupted through most of the country, with the
business center of Santa Cruz, 500 miles east of La Paz, virtually
paralyzed for hours.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: FINANCIER EXTRADITION
</P>
<P>
   An Australian magistrate ruled that Carlos Cabal Peniche, a
former Mexican financier, can be extradited to Mexico to face
charges that he embezzled $300 million from his banks. Cabal
appealed the 200-page ruling, in which the magistrate said Cabal
had not proven that Mexico was persecuting him for political
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: LOCAL OVERHAUL
</P>
<P>
   Finalizing plans to overhaul local government, the national
government announced it would reduce the number of city councils
from 843 to 235 in an effort to accelerate service delivery to the
poor. Towns that have been unable to pay bills or provide basic
services such as running water, paved roads or garbage collection
will merge with better-off towns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
