<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MAXWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT W. MAXWELL, 78, U.N. POSTAL CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert W. Maxwell, a U.N. official who headed the organization's
post office in the late 1960s, died Nov. 30 at a nursing home in
Hanover, N.H. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   He died of throat cancer, said his daughter, Ann E. Maxwell of
Pawling, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell was chief of the U.N. Postal Administration in New York
from 1966 to 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Maxwell held administrative positions in places
including Lebanon, Rwanda, Ethiopia and Switzerland, where he was
executive officer of the Economic Commission for Europe.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the U.N. Postal Administration he operated a dude
ranch in Lake Luzerne, N.Y., and managed a condominium in New
Hampshire. He also served as the town treasurer of Auburn, Mass.,
before retiring in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   His first wife, Pirie, died in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his daughter, Ann, Maxwell is survived by a son, Duncan
Maxwell of Chesieres, Switzerland; a sister, Bette Keating of
Vashon, Wash.; and two stepdaughters, Andrea Bush Rowe of Toronto
and K. Kittridge White of Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
