<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN STRUCK BY BRICK LEAVES THE HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nicole Barrett, the woman who was struck with a brick
while walking in Midtown Manhattan last month, has had a remarkable
recovery thus far but will probably have permanent brain damage,
her family said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrett's parents, Sharon and Arlen, appeared briefly at
Bellevue Hospital to share the news of their daughter's discharge
Friday and to thank New Yorkers for their support during the
monthlong hospitalization. Mrs. Barrett said that while her
daughter's recovery had been excellent, she still suffered from her
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrett was nearly killed when a man slammed the back of her
head with a 6.5 pound paving stone on Nov. 16. Her mother said that
Ms. Barrett had severe headaches, as well as problems with speech
and decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the types of things that are going to take a while
to get back to normal,'' Mrs. Barrett said, adding that her
daughter would undergo therapy near their home in Athens, a small
city in East Texas. Moreover, she said, doctors had cautioned the
family that in many cases patients with neurological injuries as
serious as Ms. Barrett's did not recover completely. ``There's
always something that never returns to normal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Barretts were cheerful, saying the recovery to date
had been faster and more extensive than doctors had predicted. They
also said that the timing of the discharge was cause for joy, and
that they would be returning to a home with a ``lovely Christmas
tree and a lot of food in the freezer.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said, ``She couldn't be released at a better time than
Christmas time.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, who has been undergoing chemotherapy and recently had a
cancer operation, leaned on a cane as he spoke. He said he was
feeling well and thanked New Yorkers for the flowers, cards and
donations the family had received. ``We want to just tell everyone
that we are so grateful,'' he said. ``God bless everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The Barretts also said that their daughter, who lived in Queens
before the attack, planned to return to New York within a few
months, and that they had no misgivings about safety in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Paris Drake, 32, a panhandler and career petty criminal, has
been charged in the attack and is being held at Rikers Island.
After the attack, the city began a crackdown on the homeless that
was criticized by civil libertarians and others.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, when asked whether they had any opinions about how the
city had handled the attack, the Barretts withheld judgment. ``I
still prefer not to make comments on that,'' Mrs. Barrett said.
``You don't want a Texan involved in your politics here, or your
decisions for your citizens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 2337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991217.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-17 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SENECA-HOUSE-NYT &LR;      12-17 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENECA-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP BUYS HUNT HOUSE, WOMEN'S RIGHTS SHRINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ending seven months of uncertainty over the fate of a historic
property that was central to the movement for women's rights in the
United States, a nonprofit organization acquired the Hunt House in
Waterloo, N.Y., at auction Friday, pledging to restore it and
donate it to the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   In a spirited 40-minute telephone battle among five bidders, the
1829 house was sold for $231,000 _ $91,100 above last month's
asking price. The winner was the Trust for Public Land, a nonprofit
conservation organization.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say the three-story Federal-style house was the site
of a tea party in 1848 at which a group of women organized a
women's rights convention in nearby Seneca Falls. That convention
sparked the national mass movement that ultimately led to the 19th
Amendment, which gave women the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-room house, which had not been made available for sale
for 55 years, had been avidly sought by private buyers as well as
by public-spirited groups. The house was pictured recently in a Ken
Burns public-television documentary, ``Not for Ourselves Alone,''
about the women's rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were right up against our maximum bid,'' said Erik
Kulleseid, the New York state director of the Trust for Public
Land, ``and my concern was that someone would outbid us.'' He said
that 50 percent of the bid money came from the nonprofit National
Trust for Historic Preservation, which will work with the Park
Service in the restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a trophy house,'' said Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the
New York Democrat, ``and I was fearful that someone might buy it
just to have it. The house deserves this happy news, the Park
Service deserves it, and New Yorkers deserve it.'' Last August the
senator introduced legislation, which is still pending, authorizing
the Park Service to purchase the Hunt House.
</P>
<P>
   Josie Fernandez, Park Service superintendent of the Women's
Rights National Historical Park in Seneca Falls, which will manage
the Hunt property, said: ``This is a wonderful gift for the nation.
As soon as someone hands us a key, we'd like to welcome America to
its house.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5.7-acre park, which includes the site of the Seneca Falls
convention, the Elizabeth Cady Stanton House and other landmarks,
was created in 1980 to celebrate women's history.
</P>
<P>
   The auction, which began at $205,000, was conducted by Greg Peet
of Patchen Real Estate in Waterloo, representing the retired owners
of the Hunt House and its 2.5-acre property, Thomas H. and Joan K.
Olmstead, who put the house on the market in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the house is in good hands with the Trust for Public
Land,'' Mrs. Olmstead said Friday after the auction.
</P>
<P>
   The auction was set last Friday when a purchase contract for the
Hunt House could not be fulfilled by Mary Church, a technical
writer and editor for an environmental consulting firm in
Rochester, who had wanted to buy the house with her husband,
Stephen. The purchase was contingent on the sale of the Churches'
own home in Bloomfield, N.Y., and they were unable to complete the
deal. The Olmsteads were then free to accept competing offers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
