<HEADLINE>
ON DOCTOR'S ORDERS, THE BALL WILL DESCEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A New York City surgeon who has worked as a volunteer
in war-torn countries was chosen Friday to press the button that
will lower the ball in Times Square, ushering in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement ended speculation that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
might give the job of ``special guest'' to a 6-year-old boy who has
been the subject of a dispute between the United States and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeon selected for the honorary job, Dr. Mary Ann Hopkins,
36, who works at Bellevue Hospital Center and New York University
Medical Center, has volunteered since 1996 with Doctors Without
Borders, an international medical relief organization that won the
1999 Nobel Peace Prize, spending extended periods in Sri Lanka and
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference with Giuliani, Dr. Hopkins said she hoped
her selection by the Times Square Business Improvement District and
NYC 2000, a mayoral planning group, would encourage others to
``engage in volunteerism and humanitarianism on a local and global
scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Past special guests have included Oseola McCarty, the
Mississippi laundress who donated her life savings of $150,000 to
the University of Southern Mississippi, and Sang Lan, a teen-age
gymnast from China who was paralyzed in the 1998 Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the Dr. Hopkinses of the world who will help us pursue
peace and unity on our shaky, shrinking planet in the millennium
ahead,'' said Brendan Sexton, the business group's president, who
called her ``a true New York hero.''
</P>
<P>
   In picking Dr. Hopkins, Sexton's group and the mayor ended two
days of private discussions concerning Elian Gonzalez, the
6-year-old boy who was rescued at sea after his mother and
stepfather died, along with nine others, in an effort to reach
Florida from Cuba by boat. The boy's relatives in Florida and his
father in Cuba are seeking his custody, which has become an
international point of contention.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor had said on Thursday that the boy might be invited
from Florida to attend the celebration, and others said that the
mayor's aides had suggested selecting Elian as the special guest
who would push the all-important button.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Giuliani said all the efforts to bring the boy to
New York had been dropped. ``The suggestion was worthy,'' he said,
``but probably not a good one for the welfare of the boy. Involving
him in this celebration would probably have created a lot of
confusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
