<HEADER>
A2500 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-VERDICT-AZR &LR;      12-17 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERDICT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY AWARDED $14.2 MIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HEATHER ROMERO  
 and CHUCK HAWLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Maricopa County jury ordered General Motors to pay $14.2
million to the family of a Scottsdale woman who was run over when
her GM pickup truck lurched into reverse.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found the automobile giant negligent and said it should
have warned drivers of the potential transmission problem it
reportedly knew about since the late 1960s _ decades before Ruth
Golonka, 67, was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The award included $4.2 million in compensatory damages, with
$10 million in punitive damages. &UR; GM attorneys said they will appeal
the punitive award.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the southeast court complex in Mesa, Carol Chapman,
Golonka's daughter, spoke on behalf of the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if we can have a heightened awareness (of the
safety problems) and we can save another life, all this will be
worth it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict mirrors several across the nation against GM.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Supreme Court this year reduced an $8.5 million
verdict awarded to the family of a man killed after his truck
slipped into reverse on a hill and crushed him. The high court
eliminated the $4.5 million punitive award and halved the $4
million compensatory damages, based on the driver's partial fault.
</P>
<P>
   A Montana man was awarded $1.3 million in 1990 after his truck
slipped into reverse. He is now a quadriplegic. A California jury
awarded $1.2 million to a man seriously injured in a similar
accident in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Golonka's family attorney, Adam Studnicki, said his team has
documented at least 400 incidents, including 30 deaths, where the
transmission slipped from ``hydraulic neutral'' to reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Golonka was killed April 17, 1997, when she stopped to pick up
some wooden chairs that someone had thrown out. Her half-ton GMC
Sierra truck suddenly slipped into reverse and crushed her under
its wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Golonka's widower, Eugene Golonka, and five children hugged
their attorneys after the verdict on compensatory damages was read.
They will split the award.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded a total of $7 million in actual damages, but
that was cut because the jury found Golonka to be 40 percent to
blame.
</P>
<P>
   Golonka's attorneys also asked the jury to find GM guilty of
faulty product design, but the jury did not agree.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for both sides agreed that GM vehicles with automatic
transmissions can shift into powered reverse from the ``no-man's
land'' between park and reverse.
</P>
<P>
   However, GM attorneys argued that the accident wouldn't have
occurred if Golonka had secured the truck by not leaving the engine
running and putting the transmission in park. The second phase of
the trial involved the jury's award of punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Daniel A. Barker of Maricopa Superior Court told jurors
they should consider all the arguments and evidence from the trial
in their new deliberations, as well as GM's net worth, $17.5
billion. Studnicki had suggested that an appropriate punitive award
might be $175 million, 1 percent of GM's worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you punish a company with no conscience, no heart, no
soul?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   James R. Condo, who represented GM throughout the trial, said
the compensatory damages award of $4.2 million already sent a
``very clear message'' to the automaker and asked, ``Is it right at
this point to do more?'' Condo said General Motors will appeal the
punitive award because ``there was no record in this case that
would support a punitive award.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-17-99 2352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
