u a BC-BONFIRE-COLLAPSE-1STL     12-17 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-COLLAPSE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNING ABOUT DANGERS OF BONFIRE CAME MONTHS BEFORE COLLAPSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (REMOVES ``other injuries'' from 2nd graf) 
 (th) 
 By ROSS E. MILLOY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Seven months before the Nov. 18 bonfire
accident that killed 12 people and injured 27 others at Texas A&AMP;M
University, a university vice president warned in a memorandum that
``we are dangerously close to having a serious incident that
connects alcohol, residence halls and bonfire,'' according to
documents released here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   J. Malon Southerland, the vice president for student affairs,
had issued the warning to colleagues on March 9 in response to a
series of problems reported to his office involving the bonfire, a
90-year-old tradition here, including alcohol abuse and hazing.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation was just one of many contained in nearly 3,000
documents, e-mail memorandums and photographs related to the
accident that were released this week by Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred as about 75 students were building a
bonfire as a part of the festivities surrounding the annual
football game against the university's archrival, the University of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The documents are expected to be part of the investigation
initiated by Texas A&AMP;M's president, Dr. Ray Bowen.
</P>
<P>
   Among the material was a police report about the 1998 bonfire
indicating that university officers discovered 30 students,
including 20 students who were underage, with a 15-gallon keg of
beer on the bonfire site. One of the underage students was found
unconscious and vomiting and had to be taken to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the students killed on Nov. 18 were legally drunk,
according to autopsy reports, and another student's blood showed
traces of alcohol. Evidence taken from the scene included empty
beer bottles and cans, bottlecaps, and at least one can of beer.
</P>
<P>
   But a new laboratory test has raised some doubt about claims
that two students were drunk, said a justice of the peace, George
Boyett.
</P>
<P>
   Boyett said that samples of fluids from the two victims had been
sent back for retesting and that those tests had different results.
He said an inquiry was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Southerland was not available for comment Friday after officials
issued a statement saying ``the university is taking the position
that its personnel will refrain from commenting on any aspect of
the inquiry or on any of the multitude of documents it has placed
on file for public review.''
</P>
<P>
   Leo E. Linbeck Jr., a Houston executive who is serving as
chairman of a five-person panel investigating the accident for the
university, said Friday that he did not believe that student
drinking or horseplay caused the log pile to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any sense that alcohol played a part in the
accident,'' Linbeck said, ``and we've had no evidence yet to
suggest that it did.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the investigation would examine questions raised about
the structural design, and any behavior by students or others that
might have contributed to the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a massive job ahead of us, but if student drinking
was part of the problem, we'll indicate that in our report,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Linbeck, 65, a graduate of the University of Notre Dame,
compared the task of his commission to that of investigating the
crash of an airliner.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least with an air crash you know what the airplane looked
like and what it was supposed to do,'' Linbeck said. ``In this
case, we have to figure out what the design ambitions of the
bonfire were and whether or not it was built and performed to those
specifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Though university officials have a goal of March 31 for delivery
of the commission's report, Linbeck refused to be held to any
timetable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of aspects to this case, and we're going to
take all the time we need to come up with the answers,'' he said.
``We've already identified more than 70 key questions that need to
be answered, and we will answer them all before we're finished.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Dallas Morning News reported that the bonfire
was 4 feet higher than a 55-foot height limitation imposed in 1968
when a bonfire also collapsed, and that the final structure would
have risen higher than 70 feet when completed.
</P>
<P>
   Other reports have pointed out various violations of the
university's ``Bonfire Safety Handbook,'' including underclassmen
working in the upper reaches of the stack reserved for more
experienced participants.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An evaluation of the 1998 bonfire also contained in the
documents indicated that university officials had raised questions
about the safety procedures surrounding the bonfires. The
evaluation listed 34 injuries involving ax cuts, machete cuts,
abrasions, broken bones and multiple lacerations that required
hospital treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ben Welch, director of student activities at Texas A&AMP;M, was
the university official who received the police report on the 1998
bonfire. At the time of last month's accident, Welch was in the
midst of resolving hazing accusations surrounding this year's
bonfire activities.
</P>
<P>
   Two residence halls on campus, Crocker House and Walton House,
had been prohibited from participating in building the bonfire
because of complaints that their members had been involved in the
hazing of underclassmen.
</P>
<P>
   At least one bonfire ``yellowpot'' (a term for crew leaders on
the stack) was removed from his position on Nov. 10 and was
appealing his suspension at the time of the accident, according to
the documents.
</P>
<P>
   The documents gave no details about the type of hazing involved.
</P>
<P>
   Southerland's memo warning of potential problems involving the
bonfire and student drinking apparently prompted a meeting of
senior university staff on April 29.
</P>
<P>
   The official who called the meeting, Ron Sasser, director of
residence life for the university, summarized the discussions by
writing to his colleagues that ``these problems did not occur
overnight and will take time to significantly improve. Many
questions arose about whether they could ever be totally
resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote: ``It should be recognized that alcohol, bonfire,
traditions, hazing issues are very interwoven, in many cases are
difficult to seperate (sic). This again emphasizes the need for a
universitywide effort if the problems are to be resolved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
