<SLUG> BC-GIRL18-TMARTIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRACLE CALL ANSWERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HEATHER ROMERO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a thief drove off and then ditched a sport-utility vehicle
with Clarissa Quihuis still inside, destiny called.
</P>
<P>
   And the 5-year-old answered.
</P>
<P>
   Clarissa picked up her mother's cell phone when it rang and
calmly gave detectives details about where she was _ right down to
the street numbers on nearby houses. She also followed the advice
to keep honking the horn, which helped bring Friday's harrowing
ride from Tempe to Phoenix to a quick, happy end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would pass on to parents to educate their kids to be aware
of their surroundings and learn about a cell phone. That's probably
what saved her,'' father Roy Quihuis said as he held Clarissa,
still dressed in her pink-and-white pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud about that. She's my little girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal began about 6:30 a.m. when Lucia Quihuis left her
Suzuki Sidekick running, with Clarissa sleeping in the back, while
she ran inside a baby-sitter's Tempe home to take in the girl's
school clothes.
</P>
<P>
   When Quihuis returned to retrieve the child, both the vehicle
and the girl were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe that the suspect, who is still at large and
identified as 20-year-old Jesse Bernal, didn't realize a child was
in the back seat until he drove off. He ended up ditching the car
and the girl just five miles away, but police had no idea at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   A frantic search was already under way when the mother
remembered she had a cell phone in the car. On a hunch, detectives
dialed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily the phone was on and she was able to answer it,''
Tempe police Sgt. Mike Scannell said.
</P>
<P>
   They found a scared little girl who had enough composure to
answer simple questions like, ``What do you see?''
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters and patrol cars quickly began scouring the nearby
area for landmarks Clarissa described.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Clarissa honked the horn, attracting the
attention of a group of middle school students at a nearby bus
stop.
</P>
<P>
   David Meza, 13, at first thought Clarissa was just playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then we noticed she was crying, with a runny nose and
tears everywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meza, who had learned of the search for Clarissa from watching
the morning news, took the cell phone from her and called 911.
Another student wrapped her in his jacket until police arrived,
just an hour after the girl was reported missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't get her face, the way she looked when we found
her, out of my mind,'' Meza said.
</P>
<P>
   Clarissa had little to say when reporters questioned her later.
But police say she helped save herself from a situation that could
have been prevented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope parents out here take this and learn from it,''
Scannell said. ``Take care, because in a matter of seconds, a lot
can happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
